<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN FATALLY SHOOTS 7 AT CHURCH BEFORE KILLING HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
  
(Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page)  (rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A man with a semiautomatic handgun walked into a
Baptist church in Fort Worth early Wednesday evening and began
firing during a special service for teen-agers who had just stopped
singing hymns and had begun to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, local police officers arrived at the church and
the man turned the gun on himself, the police said. Six people
attending the church service were killed in addition to the gunman,
local authorities said. An eighth person died later at a hospital,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. David Ellis of the Fort Worth Police Department said three
teen-agers and three adults were shot to death inside the church in
the city's southwest corner. Ellis also said a pipe bomb exploded
on a balcony inside the church sanctuary after the 7 p.m. shooting.
The bomb squad was inspecting several suspicious packages found at
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's cartridges, shrapnel and empty cart boxes and blood
splattered all over the wall,'' Ellis was quoted by The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Acting Police Chief Ralph Mendoza described the
gunman as a white male in his 20s or 30s but offered no other
information. He said the man had fired a semiautomatic handgun, and
officers had found at least three spent ammunition clips on the
floor of the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised the shooting had occurred inside a
church, Fort Worth Fire Chief Larry McMillen responded, ``I'm at
the point where nothing surprises me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 8 p.m., police officers told reporters and
bystanders to get inside an elementary school across the street
from the church because of the explosives. A Fort Worth Fire
Department spokesman, Tony Rodriguez, said eight people had been
taken to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   A supervisor with the Fort Worth Police Department. S. Coe, said
officers evacuated the church, Wedgwood Baptist, and a bomb squad
swept the sanctuary for other explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Coe said the gunman arrived at the church shortly before 7 p.m.
and began firing. An estimated 150 teen-agers were attending the
weekly service for the annual ``See You at the Pole'' gathering,
where students affirm their faith and concern for the problems of
society by holding prayer time around their school's flagpole.
</P>
<P>
   A young man interviewed on CNN said the gunman paused at least
once to reload his gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw him keep shooting and reloading,'' said the man,
who was not identified. ``He'd empty it and then throw some more
bullets in there and he kept shooting. I seen him sit down, he kept
walking back and forth in the very back aisle, and he kept shooting
straight. I was at the side between the door and the window and he
looked like he looked at me, so I got down and he started
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Dickens, 14, told the Fort Worth newspaper, ``We had
just finished singing and we were praying when he came in,''
Dickens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was a joke,'' Dickens said. ``We were singing
and he told us to shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on MSNBC, a man who was in the church said that
``all of a sudden we heard some bang noises.'' He went on to say
that a man then ``kind of fell across the doorway and said he had
been shot.''
</P>
<P>
   A teen-ager interviewed on CNN said: ``We were on stage playing.
We heard pops. We thought they were toys or something. A guy
started screaming in the back of the auditorium. And we seen him
load his gun so we just dove and ran out the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Another youth who was in the church described the gunman as
looking like the Unabomer, add that at first he ``thought it was a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``See You at the Pole'' service is celebrated at churches
across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the day youth in America gather around the flagpole
at their school and pray for their school,'' said Mark Collins, a
Baptist minister in Houston. He said the practice started about
five years ago, he believes with a youth group in a small Texas
town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
