<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO AGBAYANI, METS COMPLETE SUCCESSFUL TRIP WITH WIN OVER
ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The New York Mets were sliding like a car with a driver
who had slammed on the brakes too hard, spinning toward a second
straight loss to the Colorado Rockies that would send them home
from this road trip with some unflattering skid marks.
</P>
<P>
   Their offense had looked sleepy in the final days of this trip,
as if the players were weary from playing 13 consecutive games.
Their starting pitching had buoyed them through their last two
series on the West Coast this season. But when that sputtered
Wednesday _ and then the bullpen stalled, too _ the Mets were
careening toward a disappointing end to what had been a successful
trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets needed saving as much as Benny Agbayani needed to
salvage his own season, and he came through Wednesday, in the Mets'
10-5 victory over Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani, a part-time outfielder, who had hit 10 homers in his
first 73 at-bats only to wait 160 more at-bats for his next one,
hit a two-run homer in the sixth inning to give the Mets a 5-4
lead. After the Rockies rallied to tie the score, and Darryl
Hamilton hit a pinch-hit triple to drive in Robin Ventura to give
the Mets a 6-5 lead, Agbayani hit a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   That provided the Mets with all the cushion needed by a shaky
John Franco (who loaded the bases in the eighth) and Armando
Benitez (who got out of that jam) until the offense finally
unleashed a week's worth of pent-up hits for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finished the punishing road trip at 5-2. They trailed
Atlanta by 1 1-2 games in the National League East but were still
three games ahead of Cincinnati in the wild-card race pending
results of Wednesday night's games.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the late-game flurry of hits that ballooned the lead,
the Mets seemed to drag toward home as if they had blown a tire.
Although they scored three runs in the first two innings, their
starting pitcher, Orel Hershiser, struggled early, too. He was
removed after allowing four runs on six hits and four walks in six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook came in to pitch the seventh, and Kurt Abbott hit a
double down the left-field line, which sent chalk flying in the air
and manager Bobby Valentine racing onto the field for a few minutes
of heated argument with the umpires. Cook got Larry Walker, the
league's leading hitter, to pop up on the first pitch, but then he
walked Todd Helton on a 3-1 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Turk Wendell (5-4) from the bullpen to face Vinny
Castilla. Castilla entered the game batting .212 against
right-handers _ as Wendell is. Castilla smacked a single to left
field that scored Abbott to tie the score at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   But then Agbayani stepped on the accelerator and steadied the
Mets again. He had had an extraordinary burst after the Mets
brought him up from Triple-A. But since June 25, the date of his
last home run, Agbayani needed 182 at-bats to get his next two.
</P>
<P>
   After he got his 12th in the sixth inning Wednesday, he struck
again. Ventura had walked and Hamilton _ a former Rockie, who
pinch-hit for Shawon Dunston _ slammed a triple to right field that
Walker dived for but missed. As the ball skittered to the wall,
Ventura scored to give the Mets the lead and Hamilton went to
third. Agbayani's sacrifice fly scored Hamilton to give the Mets a
7-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That the Mets needed Agbayani's infrequent burst of power is not
surprising. Starting pitching had all but dragged the Mets through
this road trip. Entering the game, except for Roger Cedeno and Mike
Piazza, the other six Mets everyday players were hitting .169 on
this trip. But Wednesday, the Mets got going quickly against
Colorado's Brian Bohanon, scoring three runs on a walk and three
doubles in the first two innings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockies got to Hershiser, too, and they led by 4-3 to
create the perfect scenario for Agbayani. His season began as a
fairy tale: the 30th-round draft pick who had toiled for six years
in the netherworld of the minor leagues. But Agbayani had been an
all-state wide receiver in high school in Hawaii, and he had become
a favorite of Valentine's when Valentine managed him at Triple-A
Norfolk in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
