r s BC-BOX-DE-LA-HOYA-TRINID     09-16 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DE-LA-HOYA-TRINIDAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTERS FOR DE LA HOYA, TRINIDAD TRADE PREFIGHT JABS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Hall of Fame promoters Bob Arum and Don King have
forged an uneasy truce for Saturday night's ``Fight of the
Millennium'' between undefeated welterweight champions Oscar De La
Hoya and Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   But the truce got trashed during the final prefight news
conference at the Paris Hotel yesterday. King _ who is Trinidad's
promoter _ challenged Arum _ who is De La Hoya's promoter _ to a
one-on-one $1 million bet on the outcome of the scheduled
12-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a treasure that many of you don't know about,'' King
said as he introduced Trinidad, the International Boxing Federation
champion from Cupey, Puerto Rico. ``This man is the greatest
fighter, pound-for-pound, in the world. I'm so exuberant about
\Rhim\S that I'm about to put up $1 million of my own money _ if
Bob Arum will accept it _ I will bet $1 million that he will win
this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   King's offer to Arum capped a series of long-winded
presentations by Team Trinidad, highlighted by victory predictions
delivered by the fighter, his father/trainer, Felix Trinidad Sr.,
and King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe!'' King bellowed after Trinidad concluded his
remarks with the promise of a victory and a party that will leave
Puerto Rico hung over until Y2K. ``That is why I want to bet $1
million. I believe I want to put my money where my mouth is. Yeah,
I want to stand up and be accounted for. It won't be long.''
</P>
<P>
   When a grinning King fired that salvo and sat down, Arum strode
to the podium and announced, ``Thank God we're finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I want to say something from the bottom of my heart. Don
King challenged me to a bet of $1 million. I think it's totally
inappropriate for promoters or managers to bet on fighters. In 35
years in this business, I have never, ever bet on a boxing match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don, don't you understand that in putting Felix in the ring
with Oscar De La Hoya you're risking a lot more than $1 million?''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, (31-0, 25 KOs), and the reigning World Boxing
Council champion from East Los Angeles, Calif., has been forced to
carry TVKO's pay-per-view promotion on two fronts. Trinidad (35-0,
30 KOs) does not speak much English, and he has been training in
virtual secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was insulting,'' Arum said after Trinidad and
his entourage exited the news conference. ``When he should be
talking to the press, he's out of here. These people have no
respect for anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don King is fiasco. But I don't blame King for this. It's the
fault of the Trinidad people. Who the hell do they think they are?
They haven't cooperated in the promotion. They don't talk to
writers. That's why nobody in this country knows who Felix Trinidad
is. But Oscar De La Hoya is going to teach them on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinidad is not going to be around to see the fifth round.
That's my prediction.'' Trinidad Sr. OKs judges Felix Trinidad Sr.
has put his stamp of approval on the officials assigned by Marc
Ratner, executive director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Halpern of Las Vegas will referee the bout at the sold-out
Mandalay Bay Events Center. The judges will be Jerry Roth of Las
Vegas, Glen Hamada of Tacoma, Wash., and Bob Logist of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this fight was signed, we were a bit worried about the
judges,'' said the elder Trinidad, whose remarks were translated by
Pepe Ramos. ``But I got to meet Marc Ratner, a very professional
and honest person.'' Last words ``All I can say about this fight is
that if it was a talking contest, we'd lose.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gil Clancy, associate trainer for WBC welterweight champion
Oscar De La Hoya
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
