<HEADLINE>
POLICE USE EMERGENCY PLAN DEVELOPED AFTER COLUMBINE SHOOTINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The call that would report what is believed
to be the worst mass killing in Fort Worth's history brought into
action a plan that Fort Worth police developed but never expected
to need.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 7 o'clock Wednesday night, they needed it.
</P>
<P>
   The calls to 911 reported that ``shots have been fired'' in a
church and that several people had been hit. One of the callers was
an off-duty Fort Worth police officer, so dispatchers knew they had
a legitimate report and sent several squad cars to the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire Department also was notified.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses had reported hearing an explosion in the church, so
the Fort Worth bomb squad was dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:30, members of the Fort Worth Tactical Unit arrived to
conduct a search of the grounds to ensure no other explosives or
suspects were in the church.
</P>
<P>
   The entire area was secured, with media and onlookers moved back
three blocks from the church for their own protection, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The department's homicide and major case units will conduct the
investigation into what happened.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, patrol officers lined survivors and witnesses in
the nearby school hallway to begin taking statements. That was
expected to last throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all police clerical personnel were called in to work,
to transcribe statements and other reports.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials were unchacteristically uncooperative with the
news media and declined to talk with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The department's plan for such events was refined and updated
after the killings at Columbine High School near Littleton, Colo.
Police also worked with the school district, taking aerial
photographs at school in case of a similiar occurance in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday night, the plan had never been used. And a plan
on paper never completely fits the situation, so there were a few
to-be-expected glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique situation,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, all appropriate police units _ homicide and
major case in particular _ are notified, as are the deputy chief
and Acting Chief Ralph Mendoza. City leaders also are notified, as
was Fort Worth School Supt. Thomas Tocco.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting is believed to be the worst in Fort Worth since
three children were killed at Les Jardins Apartments on the city's
south side.
</P>
<P>
   The children's mother, a Fort Worth police officer, and two
other adults were injured in the shootings, which occurred early on
a Sunday morning in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   John Wheat, who was said to have been enraged that he had been
accused of molesting one of the children, a 6-year-old girl, was
convicted and sentenced to death in the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
