<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COUNTDOWN-2000-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY WAY AHEAD OF ATLANTA'S OLYMPIC PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To some, the Atlanta Summer Olympic Games will be forever
remembered for their wandering buses, their velvet Elvises being
hawked on the city streets and, most soberingly, for the night the
bomb went off in Centennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, in other words, does not have a hard act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlanta was being strafed in newspapers around the world,
Sydney organizers were taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Knight, Australia's Minister of Olympics, told
reporters last week, ``No other Olympic city has completed their
sports facilities as early as Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   So let the countdown begin.
</P>
<P>
   One year from now, the athletes of the world will begin
competition at the Games of the 27th Olympiad. A record number of
events, 292, will take place in a record number of sports, 28, one
of which will ``not'' be ballroom dancing.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be, for the first time in an Olympics, the
triathlon, a test of endurance in swimming, cycling and running.
The spectacle of 100 goggles-clad triathletes, charging into the
Sydney Harbor from the steps of the city's famed Opera House,
should be one of the enduring images of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   A year before its Olympics, Atlanta was progressing like the
afternoon commute on Interstate 75. It wasn't ready, but it was
getting there. Centennial Olympic Park, nudged into the middle of
downtown, was still a canyon of bulldozers and red dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney's centerpiece Olympic Stadium, on the other hand, has
been open for seven months. A rugby match in the stadium recently
drew 107,042 spectators, with the local newspapers reporting that
trains and buses experienced only minimal delays.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Hollway, the head of the Sydney Organizing Committee for
the Olympic Games (SOCOG), has warned his people not to be too
overconfident, however.
</P>
<P>
   Hollway has designated Sept. 26 as Super Sunday, when the Sydney
logistical and technological systems will be tested to the max.
Simultaneous competitions will be held in field hockey, archery,
water polo _ 10 sports in all, from athletes representing 50
nations _ and results, both real and scripted, will be reported
from 21 Olympic venue sites.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, as Hollway and his crew learned, the results
gathering system melted down on Day One. Again, Sydney observed and
learned.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians had beaten stiff competition from Beijing,
Berlin and Manchester, England, to win the International Olympic
Committee's nod in September 1993. They did it with skillful
politicking, centered around an ecology theme.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney bid team produced a video for IOC members that
featured appearances by Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman. Both extolled
the environment-friendly aspects of the Sydney bid. Kidman remarked
how she would love to see the Games go to the city where she grew
up.
</P>
<P>
   What the video neglected to mention was that Homebush Bay, site
of the new Olympic Park, was once the home to a Union Carbide plant
and for years had been a dumping ground for toxic wastes. Fishing
on the bay was banned in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after they had won the Olympic bid, Sydney officials
suddenly stopped boasting about the bay's adjoining waters. SOCOG
spent $85 million to clean up the Olympic Park site, gathering 400
tons of old wastes and encasing them in a clay-and-dirt procedure
that was endorsed by the environmental activists at Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
   You still can't fish in Homebush Bay. But in 12 months, grassy
knolls and gleaming new sports facilities will greet an estimated
350,000 visitors daily at the Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   It has not all been a smooth ride, however. The Salt Lake City
Olympic scandal reached across the seas and touched Phil Coles,
once Australia's most influential IOC member. Coles was twice
censured by the IOC for accepting excessive favors from Salt Lake
bid officials and for distributing a ``secret dossier'' on IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity surrounding Coles and Salt Lake City has made it
difficult for SOCOG to meet its announced revenue projections of
$1.65 billion. News reports in Sydney have estimated that the
shortfall will be anywhere from $32 million to $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollway has promised there will be no mass sale of civic
sidewalk space, like visitors saw in vendor-cluttered Atlanta. One
of his first changes was to open some of the venue seating areas,
previously reserved for sponsors, and sell the seats to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the most conspicuous changes from Atlanta figures
to stem from the fact that the Sydney Olympics are backed by the
state government of New South Wales. Atlanta prided itself on being
funded privately, using corporate contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Hollway and SOCOG boldly have promised to bring home a $19.4
million surplus to the government when it's all over.
</P>
<P>
   Controversies have been relatively few in Sydney as the Games
draw nearer. A flap involving a marching band with ``too many
Americans'' for the opening ceremonies was resolved by adding
marchers from 20 more foreign countries. The Australian field
hockey coach complained that the turf was too bouncy; it will be
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   By the inevitable comparisons, the world is probably going to
love Sydney as host of the 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Let the countdown begin.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
