<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BIG-THREE     09-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BIG-THREE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' BIG THREE SHOW THEIR SENIOR SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If the Cowboys proved anything in five quarters
against Washington, they proved that the Big Three of Troy Aikman,
Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin haven't gone soft on emotion after
33 seasons, 485 games and several lifetimes together in Sunday's
game alone.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly four-hour marathon with a surprise ending that
included a franchise-tying 21-point, fourth-quarter comeback and a
spectacular Rocket launch in overtime, gave Chan Gailey a little of
everything, not to be confused with a little of everything that the
second-year Cowboys coach heard, or chose not to hear, on the
sideline during the course of the game.
</P>
<P>
   You might say that the seniority leaders haven't lost their
larynxes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was loud and clear about running the ball when Gailey had
other notions during the Cowboys' black-hole period, otherwise
known as the middle quarters. During those two quarters, both
scoreless for Dallas, Smith carried the ball only seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin felt competitively challenged _ OK, he was livid _ because
he was forced to watch most of the third quarter from the sideline
at Gailey's request. You know Chan's Plan by now: Rest Irvin. Keep
him fresh, both for at the end of games and at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who until now always has been blamed for either lacking
emotion or unloading ill-tempered emotion on some unsuspecting
receiver who made a ``faux pas'', used Sunday's game to create
actions that speak volumes. He had a career-high five touchdown
passes, plus three interceptions, 362 yards passing, and a
fourth-quarter/OT performance that may end up helping getting his
old buddy Norv Turner, the Redskins coach, fired sooner rather than
later.
</P>
<P>
   But first, mind-speakers first. Smith knows there has been much
discussion since Sunday about his telling Gailey, with the Cowboys
21 points behind, that the run was there against the Redskins, so
please don't abandon it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Smith had to say yesterday:
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just sat on our hands on the sideline and weren't
emotional about what was going on, people would have the perception
that we really didn't care. If we show emotion and speak up, people
say we're \Rdisgruntled\S. We're in a Catch-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those folks, I say sit on your behinds and just do what
you've been doing best, which is ``nothing''. Let us go and do our
job the best way we can. If you think you can do better, then come
out here and work with us for a week. Go through what we go
through. Be what we are. Do what we do. Then go on the field and
try sitting on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RPlayers have\S spent the whole off-season trying hard for
this particular moment. Now you get into the middle of a very
heated game, you're behind by 21, you've got to have emotion.
Emotion drives you to come back and push it into overtime ... and
pull it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I knew that if we stayed behind like that, the
running game would be totally abandoned. I was afraid of that
occurring, considering how well we were running the ball at the
time. Chan is the head coach. It got it under control. It all
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it did. The first touchdown of the comeback was a 1-yard
run on a toss play, with Smith following Daryl Johnston into the
end zone. Smith went on to rush for 31 yards in the fourth quarter
before it was turned over to the passing game in OT.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said the message Smith laid on Gailey's ears was nothing
compared with the message Smith's action delivered to the young
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at Emmitt and say to themselves, `After all he has
accomplished ... and he's doing that, let me get my butt in gear.'
That's good for our young guys to see from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, when a man speaks, people let the vocal part
override his actions. Emmitt spoke Sunday, but it was emotion
boiling up. This game still means this much to him. He wanted to
make a play. I don't see anything wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman keeps his emotions in check more than Irvin and Smith,
but then he's the one directing the offense, reading the defenses,
checking off at the line of scrimmage as he did on the second of
his two touchdown passes to tight end David LaFleur in the first 16
minutes of the game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   How does he feels about Irvin and Smith's being left out of the
mix any time in a game? Aikman had an opinion yesterday:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the positives are that these guys get rested a little
bit ... and the negatives are that they're not out there on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little biased in my response because I've played with
those guys in some big games. I know there are some new people
within the club who haven't been around and have not seen these
guys make big plays in big games. I have the luxury of being able
to reflect on those times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see them on the field all the time, but I know the
coaches have to make those decisions as to what they feel is best.
I think everyone involved has done a nice job of accepting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he simply didn't hear or notice Irvin sulking.
Conversely, Gailey accepted Smith's plea to run the ball against
the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gailey, ``I heard ``that''!''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can say the Cowboys' Big Three are afraid to lay out
their emotions, voice their opinions or put their convictions on
parade.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3963 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN     09-16 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEJA VU ALL OVER AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The parallels are striking.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years ago, two remarkable welterweights _ Sugar Ray
Leonard and Tommy Hearns _ met here in one of the most important
lower-weight fights of all time. One was a good looking,
charismatic Olympic gold medal winner, the other a tall, fearsome
knockout artist who seemed to be unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, it seems history will repeat itself _ only with the
names Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad on the marquee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost eerie in terms of their styles,'' boxing
television analyst Larry Merchant said.
</P>
<P>
   However, does Saturday's energy-packed matchup truly rival the
unforgettable 1981 bout or other bouts in an era graced with the
once-in-a-lifetime foursome of Leonard, Hearns, Roberto Duran and
Marvin Hagler?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in terms of its place in boxing history and the record
amount of money it will generate. De La Hoya and Trinidad are two
of the three-or-four best fighters in the world and will be paid
handsomely because of it.
</P>
<P>
   No, in terms of impact on the general public. Even the casual
sports fan was captivated by Leonard and Co. _ who built their
names on free television _ while only De La Hoya among today's lot
has managed to pierce the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, promoters have a great deal of work ahead if
they hope to create anything resembling the earlier era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can it happen again? I don't think so,'' Leonard said. ``I
don' think it has the potential. Boxing at one time had true
characters and personalities, marquee names.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can argue that Saturday's fight isn't on par with
Leonard-Hearns in terms of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier group came along at the perfect time, when the
heavyweight division was down. Muhammad Ali's career had just ended
and boxing fans at the time were hungry for new heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, America's darling after his Olympic success, had
already faced Duran twice _ including the famous ``no mas'' fight
in which Leonard avenged an earlier loss _ while the unbeaten
Hearns had built a Tyson-like reputation by stopping 30 of his 32
opponents. It was a mesmerizing backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Fans in those days couldn't have asked for more. Certainly, the
same can be said for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, both fighters have perfect records _ De La Hoya
31-0 with 25 knockouts, Trinidad 35-0, (30 KOs) _ and it's
difficult to imagine either losing a fight. With the heavyweight
division again in a slide, this is the best boxing has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, no two other fighters alive (with the
possible exception of Mike Tyson) could create such intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN magazine put it well in its calendar listing for Sept. 18:
``Last chance to see what boxing can be _ before Evander
(Holyfield) and Lennox (Lewis) remind you what it actually is.''
</P>
<P>
   This bout is unparalleled in terms of economics.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard and Hearns made huge paydays, particularly the time.
Leonard took home an estimated $11 million, Hearns $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, that's chump change compared to the amount of money
generated in the pay-per-view era. De La Hoya could make more than
$20 million when a percentage of pay-per-view buys are factored in,
Trinidad well over $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters Bob Arum and Don King and others involved in the
promotion won't be hurting, either. Organizers are expecting a
pay-per-view buy rate of at least a million, which would be
considerably more than the number of people who saw Leonard-Hearns
because that fight was televised primarily at closed-circuit
venues. It would also break the nonheavyweight record of 760,000
established in the De La Hoya-Pernell Whitaker fight of 1997, but
fall short of the estimated 2 million for Tyson-Holyfield II.
</P>
<P>
   At $50 a buy, that's an automatic $50 million. And that's not
counting closed-circuit or overseas profits, which promise to fill
the deep pockets of those involved with even more cash.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only area in which Saturday's bout seems to fall
short in comparison to Leonard's era is on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, as with De La Hoya today, was the key cog.
!ital!Millions watched him win his gold medal on ABC and he
continued to build his reputation on free TV. And he appealed to
all ethnic groups _ everyone followed his career.
</P>
<P>
   The others _ Hearns, Duran and Hagler _ never claimed quite that
kind of allegiance but were stars in their own right. Hearns had
that alluring big-punch appeal, Hagler was a complete, seemingly
immoveable force and Duran was a legend.
</P>
<P>
   And they all came along at the same time. They fought eight
times between them _ !ital!eight historic matchups in a span of
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the definition of of greatness is who you rub up
against in the ring. Each of those men made the others great,''
historian Bert Sugar said.
</P>
<P>
   And today?
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is the only star among a talented but relatively
anonymous group of fighters in and around the welterweight
division. And even !italhe is no Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing wasn't a featured Olympic event by the time De La Hoya
won America's only gold medal in 1992, although the Barcelona Games
certainly was a significant springboard.
</P>
<P>
   And while De La Hoya is signing more endorsement deals every
day, his reach seems to be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say he's tremendously popular in the Latino market but
not outside it. This is at least in part because his biggest fights
have been seen only by hardcore boxing fans willing to pay
exhorbitant pay-per-view fees while his less-important fights have
been televised on cable's HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond De La Hoya, there is a wasteland. While boxing fans and
those in the business are well aware of Trinidad and his talents,
few others knew who the Spanish-speaking Puerto Rican was before
this fight.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the others in the deep, talented group of today:
Ike Quartey, David Reid, Fernando Vargas and Shane Mosley. Again,
boxing people are aware of the ability of these fine young fighters
but Vargas might be best known among casual fans because of his
recent arrest for assault.
</P>
<P>
   Without De La Hoya in the mix, no one would care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free TV was such a huge vehicle,'' Leonard said. ``It was what
really catipulted me to stardom. Fathers, mothers, kids,
grandmothers, they all knew me from free TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the fight fans who follow boxing are concentrated on
pay-per-view. It's a different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there hope?
</P>
<P>
   This match will give boxing what it needs: A megafight worth
watching. The question is whether the powers that be will build on
the momenteum.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins, will De La Hoya give Trinidad a rematch or face Reid
or Vargas or Mosley? If Trinidad wins, will De La Hoya get
!ital!his rematch? And will Quartey, Reid and Vargas _ as well as
other top welerweights _ take the risk of fighting one another to
build interest in themselves and the sport?
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to create a series of meaningful bouts a la the
'80s. That's what this group and boxing needs to recapture the
interest of the mainstream sports fan who seems to have drifted
away.
</P>
<P>
   However, that doesn't mean we'll ever see the likes of
Leonard-Hearns-Duran-Hagler again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing ever really duplicates itself,'' Merchant said.
``Leonard was the one who made the series happen. And you had
Duran, who is considered one of the greatest fighters ever. Then
you had Hearns, a knockout sensation. And then they all grew into
Hagler's division (middleweight).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it all depends on De La Hoya, win or lose _ who he'll go
after, whether there will be rematch. He will have fought three
excellent fights in a row now (Quartey, Oba Carr and Trinidad). If
that's how he wants to conduct his career and does well in this
fight, then we could start to have something similar to the
(Leonard) era. It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But not likely. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STERLING SERIES &QL; 
The Hall of Fame foursome of Sugar Ray Leonard, Tommy Hearns,
Roberto Duran and Marvin Hagler fought eight fights between them. &QL; 
__ Leonard-Duran I: June 20, 1980, Montreal, welterweight, Duran
dec. Leonard slugs it out with a slugger and pays the price. &QL; 
__ Leonard-Duran II: Nov. 25, 1980, New Orleans, welterweight,
Leonard KO 8. Duran says ``no mas'' after Leonard makes a fool of
him for seven-plus rounds. &QL; 
__ Leonard-Hearns I: Sept 16, 1981, Las Vegas, welterweight,
Leonard KO 14. Leonard, down on all cards, rallies in one of
history's greatest fights. &QL; 
__ Duran-Hagler: Nov. 10, 1983, Las Vegas, middleweight, Hagler
dec. Duran gave Hagler a suprisingly tough time and was never hurt
but came up short. &QL; 
__ Duran-Hearns: June 15, 1984, Las Vegas, middleweight, Hearns KO
2. Hearns is the only fighter to take apart a still-near-his-prime
Duran. &QL; 
__ Hearns-Hagler: April 15, 1985, Las Vegas, middleweight, Hagler
KO 3. One of the most exciting _ albeit short _ brawls in history. &QL; 
__ Leonard-Hagler: April 6, 1987, Las Vegas, middleweight, Leonard
dec. Leonard returns from hiatus to shock the world in perhaps his
finest moment. &QL; 
__ Leonard-Hearns II: June 12, 1989, Las Vegas, middleweight, draw.
Hearns should've won a close decision in a fight that paled
compared to its predecessor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
