u f BC-INTERNET-TAXES-NYT &LR;      09-16 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL AGREES ON OVERHAUL OF INTERNET TAX-COLLECTING METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Resisting political pressure from congressional Republicans, a
high-powered panel of executives and politicians voted Wednesday to
push ahead to develop a system that would make it easy and
practical for Web-based businesses to collect state and local sales
taxes on Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, the Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce, is
not yet ready to recommend whether taxes be collected at all on the
Internet. But at the second meeting Wednesday, in New York, the
members appeared to agree that the current quiltwork of levies and
overlapping districts would need an overhaul before Internet
merchants could ever be expected to collect the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   They voted to ask the states, which stand to lose revenues if
their taxes are not applied to electronic commerce, to suggest ways
to simplify the collection in cyberspace of the myriad taxes levied
by more than 7,000 state and local governments in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proposing that we say to the states, `You solve this
problem,''' said Gov. Mike Leavitt of Utah. ``The whole question
is, can you technologically make a system like this work?''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was adopted over the initial objections of the
panel's chairman, Gov. James Gilmore of Virginia, and two tax
opponents on the 19-member commission.
</P>
<P>
   And it came just a day after House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas, and 34 colleagues sent the commission a letter expressing
concern that the panel was focusing too much attention on how to
tax the Net, rather than whether to tax it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Although the commission was appointed by Congress last year to
make recommendations on tax policies for the Digital Age, Armey
reminded members that ``only Congress can authorize one state to
compel sellers in another state to collect Internet taxes.'' The
letter described proposals to collect existing taxes as ``new
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea is not a popular one in Congress or among the
American people,'' Armey's letter warned members. ``You should also
know that there are many members that will oppose any new taxes on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt, a Republican, laid out his proposal after a morning of
testimony about whether sales taxes should be applied to Internet
commerce and whether the states could make their rates and
collection structures simple enough that even small companies could
accommodate the taxes without being unduly burdened.
</P>
<P>
   The panel hopes to hear proposals from the states and anyone
else who cares to offer a solution at its next meeting, in San
Francisco in December. Its report is due to Congress next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The commission adopted criteria that any Internet tax-collecting
scheme must follow. Topping the list is simplicity: The plans
should not call for any new taxes, they must remove excessive
burdens from the sellers, they must not compromise the privacy of
the buyer, they should acknowledge the sovereignty of states, they
should treat buyers in all states the same, and they should
eliminate multiple audits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
