<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY BITES FOR ABERCROMBIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After all those yards and all those points,
reality hit Cos Abercrombie, and it felt like a smack in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see that 71 up there, it made me mad,'' said Abercrombie,
Cal State Northridge's starting middle linebacker. ``We played one
of our worst games, one of our worst games ever.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't an understatement. CSUN's 71-14 loss last week at
Kansas hurt not only Abercrombie's pride, but it was what he called
``a reality check'' for him and for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie, the sophomore who had a team-leading 17 tackles
through two games last year before breaking his jaw, admitted he is
playing poorly. He had two tackles against the Jayhawks after
getting just one against Western Oregon in the Matadors' season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working harder than I did last year,'' he said. ``(But) I
think I need to step it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie expects his defensive teammates to follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just broke down,'' he said. ``Now we really see what we
need to work on. (Kansas) exploited all our weaknesses. We know we
have to work on our stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas wore down CSUN with 353 rushing yards, including 135 by
David Winbush. The Jayhawks also completed 19 of 25 passes for 284
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we felt (the Jayhawks) were so much better than
us,'' CSUN defensive line coach David Robinson said. ``Everybody
thinks we could have played better and we should have played
better.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN gets two weeks to think about the debacle in Kansas; the
Matadors have a bye this week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back in the mix: Sean Beard, the Matadors' starting noseguard
last year, got his first action of the season late in the second
half at Kansas. Beard hurt his right leg in mid-August and was
dropped to third on the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to climb back up the ladder,'' said Beard, a
senior who had two tackles Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bumps and bruises: Starting cornerback Chazz Moore sprained
his left ankle against Kansas and hasn't practiced this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kearin, CSUN's interim head coach, said Moore is being held
out only as a precaution and if the Matadors had a game this week,
Moore would be practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a senior, is expected to be ready to play the Matadors'
Big Sky Conference opener at Eastern Washington on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Backup defensive end Erik Gardner, who missed six games with
injuries last year, hurt his shoulder against Kansas and isn't
practicing. Ironically, Gardner's younger brother, Isaac, a
redshirt-freshman linebacker, returned to practice last week after
separating his shoulder last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
