<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-TV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING SCENES ON TV HIT TOO CLOSE TO HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Scenes of tragic shootings have become so
common on the television screen that local viewers who happened to
catch the indelible images of sobbing teens and swirling emergency
vehicle lights Wednesday figured it was another bloody episode in
another part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. It was here in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   This time CNN was patched into WFAA/Channel 8 instead of the ABC
affiliate looking for ways to localize a story that was far from
home.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't change, unfortunately, was the kind of
misinformation that tends to seep out when TV news organizations
are scrambling to get it first before getting it right. Both the
ABC affiliate and the CBS affiliate, Channel 11, were reporting
deaths before they were confirmed, and the number kept changing.
The information was being picked up by MSNBC and CNN and quickly
dispersed to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   With news crews trying to get as much information as fast as
they could, witnesses were rounded up, and drilled accordingly.
Most were willing, even eager, to share their stories on TV, to
share what tiny morsels of information they had on a gunmen who
walked into the church and started firing.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC affiliate was on the air by 7:30 p.m., shortly after the
shooting occurred, and the rest of the stations followed.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much to show in terms of video. Many of the
stations showed parents racing to find out what happened to their
children. The Fox affiliate, KDFW/Channel 4, relied on the same
footage: crying teenagers on the front lawn of the Wedgwood Baptist
Church. Viewers had to wait and sort it all out.
</P>
<P>
   All-news stations such as CNN relied heavily on local stations,
breaking in with fresh information as they got it, while trying to
cover another breaking story: Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, local news organizations had to play catch-up through
most of the event, scrambling to find eyewitnesses and piece
together information.
</P>
<P>
   All five local stations called in additional personnel to help
cover what would be the biggest breaking story since a blaze
engulfed the Branch Davidian compound outside Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Covering stories of this nature is, of course, where television
earns its stripes. Or falls on its face. Many of the witnesses had
little information to share, but that didn't keep reporters from
digging up something, anything.
</P>
<P>
   The young pony-tailed girl on the Fox affiliate, who looked no
more than 10, talked of actually seeing the gunmen ``take the gun
and kill himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man on the CBS affiliate, said, ``I didn't see
anything, but what I heard I never want to hear again.''
</P>
<P>
   Camera crews camped en masse outside John Peter Smith Hospital,
trying to dig up names and give viewers more information. In the
meantime, they were forced to run video of the melee outside the
church, sticking cameras in the faces of screaming teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   With the potential to cross the line between information and
exploitation, news executives said they were trying to be sensitive
and not bother people who wanted to keep their trauma private.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't keep the ABC affiliate's Angela Kocherga from
asking a teen-ager, ``Can you describe the shooter?''
</P>
<P>
   As time moved on, the news organizations went into analysis
mode, trying to ask ``why?'' The ABC affiliate interviewed Dr. John
Lehman of the Red Cross Mental Health team while the CBS
affiliate's Ginger Allen rounded up students outside John Peter
Smith. Local viewers can expect more of that in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that few things are as chilling as hearing a
TV anchor (Channel 8's Scott Sams) warn his audience that ``Some of
the following might be graphic...''
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Judd Rose summed it up well when he turned back to the
camera after having viewed footage from Channel 8. ``It just never
seems to end, does it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
