<HEADER>
A3973 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTINGS-WITNE     09-16 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTINGS-WITNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS RECALLS A NIGHT OF HORROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A band was playing and students were singing
songs of praise when Aaron Bray heard gunshots from the church
lobby behind him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, a shot was fired into the sanctuary through a glass window
in the door. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt something go by my arm. I don't know if it was glass or
the bullet,'' said Bray, 18, a senior at Crowley High School, who
was sitting in the center section of the fan-shaped church. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Bray said, the gunman entered the sanctuary from
the right rear corner and walked toward the students gathered up
front. He began firing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear him say anthing,'' Bray said two hours later at
an elementary school across the street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like a handgun. He wasn't firing fast enough for it
to be an automatic; maybe semiautomatic, but not automatic,'' Bray
said. ``He fired many, many times. My guess, at least 30.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bray dropped to the floor to seek cover and does not think the
gunman came near him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, I heard a big bang. At first I thought he was
close to me and shot. But I guess now that that's when the pipe
bomb went off,'' he said, referring to an explosion that occurred
near the front of the sanctuary. &QL; 
.MDBO/.MDNM/ Bray said shrapnel flew about the front half of the
sanctuary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A piece of it came down and hit me on the back of the neck,
but it didn't hurt,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bray described the shooting in almost surreal terms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We never knew if it was real or part of the show,'' Bray said.
``Some people up in the balcony were giggling, some even laughing.
There was no screaming.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Killmer, 17, another Crowley High School senior who was in
the sanctuary when the shooting began, spoke in similar terms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really knew it was for real until it was over and the
cops were running us out of there, and I saw blood on people's
clothes and some of the bodies and wounded people lying around,''
Killmer said. ``Then I saw the shooter slumped over a pew in the
back, dead. Then I knew it was for real. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so strange,'' he said. ``People were smiling, at least
at first, and laughing. It was hard to believe it was really
happening.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Killmer said he saw what he believes was the first shot fired
into the sanctuary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard some noise out in the hallway and turned around to
look back and I saw this guy with a gun through the window in the
doorway,'' he said. ``I saw the gun in his hand. I saw him shoot
through the glass and the glass fly. Then I remember looking at the
door and seeing the bullet hole in the glass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the last thing I saw until the cops came in and started
telling us to get out of there,'' said Killmer, who took cover on
the floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bray and Killmer estimated that the shooting lasted for between
two and three minutes, although both said that they felt their
sense of time had been distorted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that shot come through the glass in the door at the
back, I had about a million thoughts all at once,'' Killmer said.
``Everything seemed to be moving so slow. It seemed like he kept
shooting for a couple of minutes, maybe more. He kept shooting and
shooting. But maybe it wasn't that long; it just seemed like it,
sort of like the way you remember things in a car wreck taking a
lot longer to happen than they really did.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bray said, ``It was pretty long time. I'd guess two to three
minutes. He shot and shot and shot. And then the shooting stopped.
Then there were a couple of more shots, and it stopped again. Then
we heard one last shot; it was kind of a muffled shot. I guess
that's when he shot himself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A few seconds later, the police were in there with their guns
on him, yelling at us all to get out,'' Bray said. ``We got out
pretty quickly. I guess he shot himself because the police were
coming in, but I don't know for sure. I was on the floor.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
