<HEADLINE>
TAKING HIM ASIDE, DAD
 TEACHES SON THE JOY OF
 SAX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By DAVE WALKER 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  PHOENIX - A note to my son on the
occasion of his first band re hearsal:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud. Today you take the first little steps toward, maybe, Giant
Steps.
</P>
<P>
   Your new Leblanc saxophone looks beautiful and will someday
produce beautiful music _ if you keep your cork greased, take good
care of your reeds and mind your director.
</P>
<P>
   And practice a lot.
</P>
<P>
   You're my new favorite sax player, the latest in a long line of
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   As a jazz fan, I've studied a lot of great players. My
recollection may be a little fuzzy in places, but I think you can
learn a little from each of the masters discussed below.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Young, for example, kept his room very clean at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   Cannonball Adderley seldom com plained about homework.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Carter actually liked math word problems.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, Phil Woods frequently talked about topics other than
Poke mon and The Simpsons.
</P>
<P>
   James Carter never uses the words friggin' or freakin'.
</P>
<P>
   In his younger days, Lee Konitz brushed his teeth _ twice a day
_ without being told.
</P>
<P>
   The young Richie Cole didn't ask every single night if his
family was going out for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The young Wayne Shorter never audibly sighed when told that Mom
was cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Ornette Coleman never talked his grandma into letting him stay
up all night watching the Cartoon Net work.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Henderson takes the trash out before it overflows onto the
kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   Branford Marsalis tries all different kinds of foods.
</P>
<P>
   Maceo Parker uses soap every time he bathes. And, when the
subject of South Park comes up, he doesn't automatically begin
listing all of his friends who are allowed to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Clemons doesn't do ``chemistry experiments'' in the
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Redman doesn't get carried away on the Game Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Rollins' dad didn't have to tell him three times, every
time.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Webster had excellent telephone etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Fortune kept a very tidy school desk.
</P>
<P>
   He had a few character flaws, true, but Charlie Parker didn't
stand at the refrigerator with the door open.
</P>
<P>
   In noisy restaurants, little Art Pepper spoke clearly to
waitresses.
</P>
<P>
   John Coltrane loved miniature golf, GameWorks and Laser Quest,
too, but not every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   As a lad, Stan Getz was quite satisfied with his allowance, what
ever it was.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Gordon could be driven past a Circle K without mentioning
how good a Slurpee would taste right now.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Desmond understood the im portance of sun block.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Dolphy didn't enjoy telling and retelling the story about
how his dad graduated from college by literally begging for a D
from his ma rine-biology professor.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Brecker never leaves snack wrappers anywhere but in the
trash.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman Hawkins didn't repeatedly recall for his grandmother the
one afternoon he and his dad went to the corner bar to play darts.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny G, on the other hand, was kind of a rotten kid.  &LR; 4 Dave
Walker can be reached at (602) 444-8625 or at dave.walk er &LR; pni.com
via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
