<HEADER>
A3981 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ORPHANS-SPI &LR;      09-16 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORPHANS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANGEL OF SAIGON' REUNITED WITH ORPHANS SHE GAVE NEW LIVES TO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As children, they knew her as American Lady, Miss
Betty or, simply, the Angel of Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   As adults, they know her as a bridge to their past _ to the day
in April 1975 when they were airlifted from the An Lac Orphanage in
Saigon to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for the first time, three of the 219 airlifted met
Betty Tisdale _ the woman who fed them, changed them, brought them
toys and arranged for their escape from An Lac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming to see you, that has made the connection,'' Mary
Tripoli, 26, told Tisdale as they sat in the living room of
Tisdale's Queen Anne home in Seattle, poring over photographs and
newspaper clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work that you did not only impacted my life in big ways,
but others as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripoli hadn't considered meeting Tisdale until several weeks
ago, when an invitation arrived from the Greater Seattle Vietnamese
Association asking her to attend a banquet honoring Tisdale for her
work.
</P>
<P>
   Others flew in for Wednesday night's banquet, including Dinh
Dolan, 33, a chef from San Francisco, and Vikki Solviter-Wheeler,
26, a health care manager from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all raised in the same place, that's a big
connection,'' Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   The three gathered in Tisdale's living room Wednesday, telling
stories about their lives and asking Tisdale to fill in some of the
blanks.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, who was 9 when he left Saigon and was among the older
children, recalled the orphanage and asked about the well near the
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember growing up, playing with a lot of kids, sleeping
together in one room on the floor,'' said Dolan, who grew up on a
farm near Lock Haven, Pa. ``It seemed like everything happened very
fast. When I arrived in the U.S., it was totally a different world
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisdale looked the proud mother as three of her ``children,'' as
she called them, plied her with questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of felt that eventually you all would come home once in
a while,'' Tisdale told them during lunch. ``You need to know that
it was a loving place. You were well-loved.''
</P>
<P>
   The three always knew about Tisdale. They knew the story of how
they were brought to the United States and adopted by their
respective parents. They knew that Shirley Jones portrayed Tisdale
in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   How could they not know?
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers, even a newsletter from a diaper service,
featured their adoptions. Their parents told them stories,
encouraged them to look into their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan's mother clipped newspaper articles when he was young.
Tripoli's mother did, too. Solviter-Wheeler's mother tried for
years to encourage her to take a trip to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But none of them was ready to make contact with Tisdale until
later, when they were in their early 20s and 30s, when the question
of identity began to chip away at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about my background at all,'' said
Sloviter-Wheeler, who was adopted by a Jewish family. ``In my 20s,
I began to grapple with the whole identity issue. What are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she said, she didn't even consider herself Asian.
</P>
<P>
   In college, she took the first steps toward learning about her
past with a history paper on Operation Babylift, which allowed the
United States to bring babies from Vietnam on an emergency basis.
</P>
<P>
   Then she entered a contest last year sponsored by Life magazine
and named Tisdale as the person she most wanted to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no other way in which to come to terms with my
past,'' she said. ``I'd always known about Betty through the
movies. But it didn't mean anything. Shirley Jones was Betty
Tisdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloviter-Wheeler said she saw the movie, which was based on
Tisdale, and later bought a copy of it.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Tisdale over lunch Wednesday, she said to her: ``You
were like this movie star, this legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisdale first learned about An Lac after reading a book by Dr.
Tom Dooley, a Navy lieutenant known for his work establishing
clinics in Laos, Cambodia and Vietnam. She decided to see for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   What she saw, she never forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just changed my life completely,'' Tisdale said. ``I knew I
could never be the same girl I was before with the nice job, the
cocktail parties and nice clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   An Lac was founded by Madame Vu Thi Ngai. Tisdale returned to it
every winter afterward with toys, clothing and money. She raised
money by appealing to people's love of children.
</P>
<P>
   She resorted to cajoling, even harmless tricks, to do what she
could for the children.
</P>
<P>
   She once pretended to be a stewardess, wearing the uniform blue
skirt and white blouse, to fly to Vietnam for free.
</P>
<P>
   She sweet-talked military officials into allowing her to fill
vacant space on their airplanes with playpens, cribs, toys and
other things for the orphans.
</P>
<P>
   She even persuaded the mother of the secretary of the Army to
allow her to use the barracks at Fort Benning, Ga., to house the
children once she managed to get them out of Vietnam, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to cook or do anything, I just knew how to
raise money,'' said Tisdale, who worked as a private secretary to
the late Sen. Jacob Javits and later raised a family when she
wasn't raising money for An Lac.
</P>
<P>
   On April 5, 1975, as the North Vietnamese Communists advanced
toward Saigon, Tisdale got unusual permission from the South
Vietnamese government to get the children out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But they would not allow children 10 and older to leave.
</P>
<P>
   So Tisdale filled a C141 Starlifter cargo plane with 219
children, along with 38 children from other orphanages. She had to
leave 131 children behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were thrusting their children at me. `Take my baby,
take my baby,''' Tisdale remembered.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived in the U.S. Army base in Fort Benning after making
a stop in Los Angeles. The children spent the first night in an
abandoned kindergarten building and eventually found adoptive
families.
</P>
<P>
   Tisdale's aunt and uncle took her in and raised her in a
middle-class environment when her father died when she was 9 and
her mother became ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize it then but I realize now how important it
was for somebody to take a child in and raise them,'' Tisdale said.
``Maybe that was the beginning of what was inside me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
