<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-FASHION-II-2TAKES-     09-16 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-II-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 OVERSTAGED HILFIGER UPSTAGED BY IMPROVS  (rk) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everybody has heard of Tommy Hilfiger. But who has
heard of Miguel Adrover or Lola Faturoti? Or, for that matter,
anybody who doesn't have a colossal advertising budget, who stages
a fashion show in the dead of night in some broken-down theater on
the Lower East Side, with nothing for props except a plywood runway
and some dried marsh grass gathered from the side of the New Jersey
Turnpike?
</P>
<P>
   The mind boggles at the contrasts between the show Hilfiger
staged on Tuesday night at Madison Square Garden (in the adjacent
smaller theater but still the Garden) and the one Adrover put on an
hour later downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger had Bush, the British rock band, on the stage, while
the audience sat facing the runway, away from the band. The way the
stony-faced crowd ignored the boys in the band _ well, you would
have thought they were playing to a retirement home. The musicians
got so mad, or at least seemed to, that when the show was over and
everyone was going for the exits, the lead guitarist shouted,
``Thank you very much,'' except the ``thank'' came out as a swear
word.
</P>
<P>
   Adrover, on the other hand, had a lot of funky people, including
British designer Alexander McQueen, a friend of his, sitting around
on folding chairs drinking beer. The crowd was alive, and now and
then McQueen let out a wolf whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Adrover has a rich imagination. His collection, put together on
a shoestring budget, was based on the idea of a woman living in a
South American jungle, scraping together what she can find, and
then coming to New York, where a culture of brand names changes her
style. This might mean a miniskirt salvaged from a Louis Vuitton
bag, with the handles lapping at her sides, or a strapless cotton
dress smudged with paint and appliqued with scraps of newspaper,
like a littered wall of graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Although other designers, notably Xuly Bet, have made similar
conceptual statements, where Adrover excels is in his technique and
originality. It is hard to give clothes a sense of both history and
newness with red-and-white linen damask that looked as if it came
off a table in someone's home and a top shredded so finely
(probably with a razor blade) that it looked like strings of beads.
But Adrover did.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger's clothes, despite the fact that his cowboy boots were
inset with the words ``Tommy Rocks,'' seemed to have nothing in
common with the atmosphere he was trying to create. The clothes
were sanitized renditions of a rowdy Western theme _ flame-licked
leather pants, floral-yoke cowboy shirts, trophy belt buckles _
that tougher customers, like hogback Harley-Davidson riders, have
already blazed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pity that more people did not see Ms. Faturoti's gem of
a show, which drew a small crowd on Wednesday morning to Nobu, the
TriBeCa restaurant. She, too, has relied on the kindness of
strangers, mainly Nadja Swarovski, whose company produces crystals
for the fashion business, and Peter Arnell, the marketing
consultant, who donated money to produce her show. In all, it cost
about $60,000, the designer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Faturoti, who took a break from fashion for a few years,
gave deconstruction an elegant polish, overlaying deep blue
crocheted lace on a gold satin chemise, for instance, and splicing
vivid yellow damask into a black wool dress, leaving the ends of
the fabric bolt that say ``100 percent merino wool'' around the
hem. The show was smart, with surprising touches like a grill of
metallic ruffles over a satin back, and it ended with exquisite
colonial dresses, an ironic allusion to Ms. Faturoti's Nigerian
upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren is not a hard guy to figure out. Oh, he may have
his eccentric whimsies, like keeping a barber around (Howard
Hughes, one may recall, did the same), but he is not a complicated
ball of wax. On Wednesday, he proved that with a collection so
purely sexy that when the model Giselle came swinging down the
runway in navy polka-dot leather jeans and a matching bikini top,
one could almost swear the retail bosses in the front row were
lifted right out of their shoes. The grins!
</P>
<P>
   Well, all right. Lauren is one designer who knows how to work
within a narrow groove _ good old corn-fed American sexiness. Here
were slim gingham trousers in red or navy with stretch tops and
mules, hot pants in banker-gray glen plaid and pinstriped skirts
with girlishly ruffled hems, worn with untucked white shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren may wish he hadn't shown white eyelet leather, a trend
this week and already wearing thin. At least he didn't get too
wrapped up in it.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, you can imagine women wearing these clothes, which
can't be said of a lot of what goes down a runway. The look is
exactly like the clean, racy minimalism seen on fashion editors _
skinny pants, sexy heels. Except Lauren had the good sense to view
it as a woman from the Midwest might _ from a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The terrace of Lever House at Park Avenue and 53rd Street, would
have been a good place for Daryl Kerrigan to show on Tuesday if she
wasn't such an adorable sad sack. She is adorable in the sense that
she believes in putting clothes in a political context, and her
urban gear has made her a thorn, in the long tradition of Vivienne
Westwood and Rudi Gernreich.
</P>
<P>
   But it's difficult in the extreme to look up Park, with all that
blue glass and steel rising optimistically behind you, and imagine
women wearing nylon storm suits and ``OSHA orange'' tops. What are
they afraid of? Catching a cold at Barneys?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kerrigan's moody collection of blouson tops and asymmetrical
leather jeans, in black and murky botanical colors, was intended to
be a balm against the times: specifically, her program notes
stated, the ``threat of war, death, disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow!
</P>
<P>
   There were bright spots _ summery cotton dresses with zip-on,
zip-off ruffles, winged Princess Leia shoulders in the style of
Nicolas Guesquiere of Balenciaga, but where, in such a modern
setting, was the unclouded vision of Daryl K?
</P>
<P>
   If there was a clue to John Bartlett's show, with its
well-traveled theme of exotic mischief, it was in the signboard
backstage instructing the models to be guerrilla ballerinas and
sexy revolutionaries. They were also advised to ``be happy and
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a lot of designers have been down this road before,
mixing harem sensuality with European tailoring, Bartlett did it
with modern gusto. To black or golden-tan leather trousers laced up
the sides, he added filmy tops of plise chiffon or shirts flecked
with gold. There was a sense of things worn and borrowed, like
chocolate-brown leather jodhpurs and a slip dress of strips of
black, white and tan chiffon inspired by the prints of Sonia
Delaunay. The designer took those prints and rearranged them, in a
group of squares, say, on chiffon trousers, so that they became a
kind of memento, like scraps in a Peter Beard diary.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was also a breakthrough for Bartlett, who said
afterward that he had received a call this summer from Joan Kaner,
the fashion director of Neiman Marcus, advising him to be more a
proponent of the sensual than the frankly sexual. With strong,
wearable things like a white twill trench coat casually mixed with
golden chiffon trousers (and poppy-red shoes), he obviously took
her advice. A long line of retailers waited backstage to praise
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Bartlett said, grinning. ``It's, like, where's
the bride or the groom?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
