<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-16 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENDOR TAKES SWING AT D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - By this late in the season, Scott Fader should be
farther behind the Arizona Diamondbacks than the San Francisco
Giants. He shouldn't be in a pennant race. He shouldn't even be in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, here's Fader, standing up against the best the big boys
can throw at him and swinging for the fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to put me out of business, and now I want the
courts to tell them what they're doing is illegal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fader publishes an alternative program called Beat on Baseball,
which he sells before home games outside Bank One Ballpark for $1
each. Last year, the Dia mondbacks sold its ``official'' game pro
gram for $5.
</P>
<P>
   Fader whipped the home team, hitting 'em out of the park without
ever entering the ball yard.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the Diamondbacks reduced the price on their
larger, fancier (more costly to produce) program to $3 each, then
to $1 _ at least around the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I bought one at a retail store, it cost $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the Diamondbacks have kept Fader and his vendors
from selling Beat on Baseball on the plaza adjacent to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   SALES TAKE PLUNGE
</P>
<P>
   His sales dropped 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fader believes the Diamondbacks are trying to put him out of
business. Each time I've asked team President Rich Dozer about
that, however, he's denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to increase our cir culation,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   Fader doesn't buy it, and he doesn't be lieve a jury will,
either.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he sued the Diamondbacks in federal court, claiming
the team vio lated antitrust laws through what the law suit calls
``a predatory pricing scheme designed to lessen competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Fader also claims to have been slan dered by team
representatives who alleg edly referred to his publication as
``pornographic'' for carrying advertise ments from topless bars.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the lawsuit contends Fader should be able to sell Beat
on Baseball on the stadium plaza, which it says is public property.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Diamondbacks are in Cooperstown, N.Y., for
league meetings this week. I'm told they haven't yet seen the
lawsuit and, therefore, can't comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want any part of a court case,'' Fader says. `'But
this is really a matter of principle. And, luckily, I have the
resources to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't. OUT-OF-STATE REVENUE
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Fader should have gone broke months ago. He would
have, too, if he hadn't done what all successful base ball
franchises do _ he developed a farm team.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seattle Mariners moved into the new stadium earlier
this season, Fader and his vendors were outside selling a $1
program called The Seattle Slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done very well in Seattle,'' Fader says. ``And because
of that, I'm able to pursue our case here in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the lawsuit, Fader hopes to re cover the losses of the
past year, along with attorneys fees and punitive damages. Whether
any of that will happen is diffi cult to predict.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits aren't like baseball games. Since opening day in April,
the Diamond backs have slowly separated themselves from the rest of
their division by winning more games than the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the season winds down, fans are matching Diamondback
wins against rival losses, awaiting the point where a playoff spot
is guaranteed for the home team while the others are mathematically
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   That's the ``magic number'' baseball fans around Phoenix are
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit doesn't work that way.
</P>
<P>
   Several seasons can pass without it be ing resolved. And the
umpires (in black robes) can call the whole thing off at any time.
And victory isn't determined only by winning _ but by how much you
win.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is fine with Scott Fader.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't care which big gun the D-Backs hurl at him.
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as, in the end, the magic number is set by a jury.
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3991 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-16 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENDOR TAKES SWING AT D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - By this late in the season, Scott Fader should be
farther behind the Arizona Diamondbacks than the San Francisco
Giants. He shouldn't be in a pennant race. He shouldn't even be in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, here's Fader, standing up against the best the big boys
can throw at him and swinging for the fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to put me out of business, and now I want the
courts to tell them what they're doing is illegal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fader publishes an alternative program called Beat on Baseball,
which he sells before home games outside Bank One Ballpark for $1
each. Last year, the Dia mondbacks sold its ``official'' game pro
gram for $5.
</P>
<P>
   Fader whipped the home team, hitting 'em out of the park without
ever entering the ball yard.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the Diamondbacks reduced the price on their
larger, fancier (more costly to produce) program to $3 each, then
to $1 _ at least around the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I bought one at a retail store, it cost $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the Diamondbacks have kept Fader and his vendors
from selling Beat on Baseball on the plaza adjacent to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   SALES TAKE PLUNGE
</P>
<P>
   His sales dropped 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fader believes the Diamondbacks are trying to put him out of
business. Each time I've asked team President Rich Dozer about
that, however, he's denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to increase our cir culation,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   Fader doesn't buy it, and he doesn't be lieve a jury will,
either.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he sued the Diamondbacks in federal court, claiming
the team vio lated antitrust laws through what the law suit calls
``a predatory pricing scheme designed to lessen competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Fader also claims to have been slan dered by team
representatives who alleg edly referred to his publication as
``pornographic'' for carrying advertise ments from topless bars.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the lawsuit contends Fader should be able to sell Beat
on Baseball on the stadium plaza, which it says is public property.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Diamondbacks are in Cooperstown, N.Y., for
league meetings this week. I'm told they haven't yet seen the
lawsuit and, therefore, can't comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want any part of a court case,'' Fader says. `'But
this is really a matter of principle. And, luckily, I have the
resources to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't. OUT-OF-STATE REVENUE
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Fader should have gone broke months ago. He would
have, too, if he hadn't done what all successful base ball
franchises do _ he developed a farm team.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seattle Mariners moved into the new stadium earlier
this season, Fader and his vendors were outside selling a $1
program called The Seattle Slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done very well in Seattle,'' Fader says. ``And because
of that, I'm able to pursue our case here in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the lawsuit, Fader hopes to re cover the losses of the
past year, along with attorneys fees and punitive damages. Whether
any of that will happen is diffi cult to predict.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits aren't like baseball games. Since opening day in April,
the Diamond backs have slowly separated themselves from the rest of
their division by winning more games than the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the season winds down, fans are matching Diamondback
wins against rival losses, awaiting the point where a playoff spot
is guaranteed for the home team while the others are mathematically
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   That's the ``magic number'' baseball fans around Phoenix are
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit doesn't work that way.
</P>
<P>
   Several seasons can pass without it be ing resolved. And the
umpires (in black robes) can call the whole thing off at any time.
And victory isn't determined only by winning _ but by how much you
win.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is fine with Scott Fader.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't care which big gun the D-Backs hurl at him.
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as, in the end, the magic number is set by a jury.
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
