<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-ABORTION-VETO-KAN &LR;      09-16 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-VETO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI HOUSE VOTES TO OVERRIDE CARNAHAN'S VETO OF ABORTION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri House voted Wednesday to
override Gov. Mel Carnahan's veto of an anti-abortion bill, setting
up a decisive, high-stakes battle today in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 127-34 to override Carnahan's veto while rival
partisans watched from packed galleries. The tally was 18 votes
more than the 109 required for the two-thirds majority required by
the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill still need two-thirds approval in the Senate
_ 23 votes _ for the bill to take effect despite the governor's
veto. It passed 27-6 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Only six vetoes have been overridden in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the House vote, Sen. Ted House, a St. Charles
Democrat and Senate sponsor, predicted the Senate override attempt
would benefit from the lopsided House vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging that virtually no one bought the
arguments by the abortion industry,'' House said. ``I expect the
same result in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Senate debate will last hours or days is unclear,
because earlier Senate debate on the bill lasted 38 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides on the issue have a huge investment in the outcome of
the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters have invested several years on the issue and risk
losing momentum if they cannot override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Carnahan's gubernatorial prestige is on the
line. A defeat by a legislature controlled by his own party could
also be an issue in his U.S. Senate bid next year against
Republican incumbent John Ashcroft, an abortion opponent.
</P>
<P>
   While the House was debating the abortion bill and other
legislation, the Senate voted 24-8 to override the governor's veto
of a crime bill. The House declined to consider the issue, however,
and completed its work without voting to override any other vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the abortion measure say the bill would
criminalize a late-term abortion procedure that they describe as
``partial birth'' abortion by classifying it as infanticide. The
procedure would be a felony unless it was performed to save the
mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, who contends that the bill is unconstitutional and
would result in abortion clinics closing in Missouri, told
reporters he was disappointed by the House vote but planned to work
hard to prevail in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has said the bill would ban most abortions and could
provide a legal defense to anti-abortion violence.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has to persuade at least five senators who voted
for the bill in May to switch sides, a politically perilous move by
senators on such a closely watched issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have members to work with who think this is a bad
bill,'' he said. ``If I can convince them to vote the way they
think, I will be sustained.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House debate, Rep. Bill Luetkenhaus, a Josephville
Democrat and House sponsor, rebutted a variety of arguments put
forth by opponents of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Luetkenhaus noted that former Missouri Supreme Court Justices
John Bardgett and Chip Robertson wrote letters contradicting
assertions that the bill could provide a legal defense for
anti-abortion violence.
</P>
<P>
   He said officials of Cardinal Glennon Children's Hospital in St.
Louis disputed arguments that the bill would complicate efforts to
save premature infants, another contention made by Carnahan and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters overwhelmingly in this state want to ban partial
birth abortions,'' Luetkenhaus said. ``Let's listen to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vicky Hartzler, a Harrisonville Republican, took issue with
comments by opponents of the bill who said it represented
government intrusion into the lives of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's role is to protect its most vulnerable,''
Hartzler told the House. ``That is what we are doing today.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill said that they wanted to ban ``partial
birth'' abortions but that the Luetkenhaus bill was riddled with
flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carol Jean Mays, an Independence Democrat, said that she
had what she called a compromise bill to ban such abortions and
that Carnahan would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleading with all of you for a middle-of-the-road
philosophy,'' Mays said.
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents argued that the vetoed bill was designed to
overturn the 1973 decision that legalized abortions and that the
measure would trigger a costly court fight that ultimately would
result in the bill being struck down.
</P>
<P>
   Luetkenhaus said he welcomed getting the issue to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should proceed, do the override and then let the judges
decide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor told reporters that if the Senate sustained his
veto, he would call a special session to pass a new ban that would
allow the procedure to preserve the mother's health, not just her
life. Opponents of such a provision said it was too broad and would
be abused.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said that, despite the lopsided House tally, at one
point in recent days he was within half a dozen votes of getting
his veto sustained in the House. But when it became obvious that
the veto could not be sustained, lawmakers who considered switching
sides voted for the override instead, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The override was backed by all 76 Republicans in the House, as
well as 50 of Carnahan's fellow Democrats and one independent.
Thirty-four Democrats voted against the override. One Democrat
voted ``present,'' and one was absent.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote followed nearly three hours of debate amid heavy
Capitol security, in part because the issue attracted huge public
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill, many wearing red and wearing ``Ban the
Brutality'' stickers, rallied on the south side of the Capitol to
blast Carnahan, denounce the abortion industry and vow to make the
override attempt a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together we can move the mountains of injustice and evil,''
Sen. House told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Such comments won praise from supporters such as Mary Travis,
who was part of a church group from Harrisonville who attended the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is murdering infants,'' Travis said of
``partial birth'' abortions. ``It needs to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Gus Kolilis, chief of the Capitol police, estimated that the
rally in support of the override attracted about 2,000 people.
Organizers said they had nearly 5,000 people at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, about 100 abortion-rights supporters gathered
briefly on the north side of the Capitol to hear speeches about the
what they called dangers in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Boisseau, 79, said he came from the St. Louis suburb of
University City to let lawmakers know they were misinterpreting the
views of most Missourians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very extreme bill,'' Boisseau said. ``It would ban
all abortions. The director of Planned Parenthood told us this
morning that if this goes through, they won't schedule abortions
until the law is set aside, because they want to avoid
prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the debate at the Capitol was trouble-free, Jefferson
City public schools were dismissed after a bomb threat was made,
citing Carnahan's opposition to the abortion bill.
</P>
<P>
   By the constitution, the veto session is limited to 10 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
