r a BC-FARRIS-DETENTION-KAN &LR;      09-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARRIS-DETENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DETAINED SUSPECT WEEKS BEFORE WOMAN WAS KILLED, RECORDS
SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TRISHA L. HOWARD and JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City police had Michael L. Farris in jail last month for
a parking ticket days after he cut his electronic monitor and
jumped bond _ and weeks before he allegedly strangled a Kansas City
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities freed Farris because state probation officials had
not told them that Farris had jumped bond. Even though probation
officials knew within hours on Aug. 9 that Farris had cut his
monitor, they took nearly a month to seek an arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Without the warrant, police said, they had no way of knowing
that Farris was on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Circuit Judge John O'Malley, who oversees the
criminal docket, called the delay in the warrant request
``unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Had a judge known quickly, a warrant would have been issued, he
said, and Farris would have been behind bars when Sophia Szymczak
was strangled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just shouldn't have happened,'' said Leila Szymczak, the
victim's granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Probation and Parole, which oversees the
pretrial program, operates under the Missouri Department of
Corrections. Tim Kniest, a spokesman for the department, said this
week that an extensive internal review process delayed the warrant
request. Kniest added Wednesday that the delay was not normal.
</P>
<P>
   Farris' case has reverberated in the county courthouse and the
Missouri Capitol. Officials want changes in the way probation
officers track defendants.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Farris' home detention, he was supposed to wear an
electronic monitor so officials could keep track of him.
</P>
<P>
   Farris, 44, of Independence, was to leave home only to go to
work while he awaited trial on a charge of burglarizing Szymczak's
Kansas City home in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star reviewed court records and interviewed
police and court officials to reconstruct what happened:
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9 probation officials noticed Farris had cut off the
monitor. The next day they found he had left his Independence home
and quit work.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later Independence police responded to a call about a
man sleeping in a vehicle. It was Farris. An officer ran a computer
check and found Farris had a Kansas City warrant for an unpaid
parking ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Independence police notified Kansas City police, who took Farris
to a downtown detention center that day.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 13 Farris was taken to the City Jail, where he spent the
weekend. On Aug. 16 a city judge released Farris, according to
court records. Jail records show he was released Aug. 17;
authorities could not explain the discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   Through the entire process, authorities said they did not know
that Farris had jumped bond or that he was on home detention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't enter it (in the computer), we have no way of
knowing,'' said Russ Dykstra, a Kansas City police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   If Independence police had known, Officer Bill Pross said, they
certainly would have held Farris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking home detention strikes me as a jailbreak,'' Pross
said. ``He just didn't have to saw through the bars.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 3, Szymczak, 76, was killed. She was to have testified
against Farris at his burglary trial set for Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Arcaga, who shared a home with Szymczak, discovered her
body on the living room floor. He saw a man run out the back and
chased him more than a mile through afternoon traffic even after
the man had stabbed him.
</P>
<P>
   Police eventually arrested Farris. Prosecutors charged him with
first-degree murder and with assaulting Arcaga, and may seek the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, probation officials requested a warrant for Farris _
who was already in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The case has focused attention on the Board of Probation and
Parole. State Sen. Ronnie DePasco, a Kansas City Democrat, said he
would question the state probation chief about the Farris case.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections officials have started a new policy. They will
notify the court within three hours after a person cuts off a
monitor, he said. They are working with Jackson County officials on
other possible changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to solve this problem,'' Kniest said.
</P>
<P>
   Police want a change, too. The message to people on home
detention should be clear, Pross said: ``If you mess with this, you
will have your name put on a warrant so fast, you won't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said the case showed ``how
critical it is to get those warrants out as fast as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
