<HEADLINE>
`ACTION' IS RAUNCHY BUT
 HILARIOUS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  PHOENIX - If you don't get cable, it's
safe to say you've never seen anything like Fox's Action!, which
premieres tonight.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you do get cable, but only so you can watch the Disney
channel, it's safe to say you haven't seen anything like it,
either.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Do you want to?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is somewhat compli cated. If bleeped-out cursing (not
just ``damns'' and ``hells,'' but the big guns _ we're talking
about several uses of the F-word before the first commercial),
fairly graphic ban ter about the size of male sexual organs and
jokes about urinating in commissary food put you off your oats, the
answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be offended _ and by the way, some people
are, there's no question about it _ please don't watch,'' Doug
Herzog, the president for entertainment at Fox, told TV critics
this summer. ``Watch somebody else's network for that half-hour.
You know, we'd rather not field the phone calls and the e-mails and
the letters.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if hilarious, dead-on, ri otous Hollywood satire that
takes no prisoners appeals to you, then the answer is a resounding
yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to . . . remember that what we're trying to do is not
trying to make the most shocking show in television,'' said Chris
Thompson, who created Action! ``We're simply trying to make the
funniest show on television.''
</P>
<P>
   They've come mighty close.
</P>
<P>
   Action! concerns Peter Dragon, a producer of Hollywood action
films. His Christmas blockbuster, Slow Tor ture, is fizzling,
jeopardizing the chances of the sequel he so badly wants to make.
Naturally, he's started work on it before the first movie has even
opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``What title do you like better,'' Dragon asks an underling,
``Slow Torture 2: It Still Hurts or Slow Torture 2: Now It's
Unbearable?''
</P>
<P>
   Dragon picks up a prostitute on the way to Slow Torture's
premiere _ literally, his limo picks her up off the ground _ who
turns out to be the only person in town he can trust. Meanwhile, he
has bought the wrong script from the wrong writer, his ex-wife is a
beard for his gay boss and an agent is trying to pitch him an actor
so famous ``little children in Calcutta know his face,'' someone
more famous than Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair,'' Dragon says, ``Tom Hanks refuses to go that
extra mile and hack his wife to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Mohr, Tom Cruise's oily rival agent in Jerry Maguire, is
brilliant as Dragon; he's born to this kind of role. Illeana
Douglas is also good as the child-actor-turned-prostitute, Wendy
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every boy in America dreamed of being with Wendy Ward,'' a
Bruce-Willis-type action star says when he realizes who she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now that dream has almost come true,'' Dragon's security
man says.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, about that security man _ he answers the Hollywood trivia
ques tion, ``Is Buddy Hackett dead?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   The season will follow the progress of the movie Dragon makes
next (chosen by Ward from a stack of scripts left on his kitchen
table). Look for several celebrity cameos _ tonight's is Keanau
Reeves, who during the premiere receives a, um, how to put it,
special gift from Ward. It's neither Goobers nor Raisinettes.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson doesn't plan to water things down as the season goes on
_ if anything, look for him to push the edge even farther. But he
insists he's being realistic, not gratuitous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an advocate of the coarsen ing of the culture,'' he
said. ``I'm not an advocate of any of the behavior that's displayed
in this show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an observer of it. I am a chronicler of it. And I believe
that it can be made to be entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   If the first episode is any indication, he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at bill.goody
koontz &LR; pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
