<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FROM INDIA BIKING AROUND WORLD TO PROMOTE NONVIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIANXIANG YANG  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Mahatma Gandhi, Rajpal Singh embraces the credo of
nonviolence. And he's spreading that message around the world _ by
bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   After four years of preparation, Singh left his home in Jaipur,
India, on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   At every stop on his two-year journey, Singh talks about
nonviolence, the sharing of resources and peace.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, his wife and their 8-year-old daughter arrived Tuesday in
Kansas City. He was to speak at a coffeehouse Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Singh said people ``should seek
nonviolent approaches and influence their leaders to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, 41, a veteran cyclist, had made three long tours in his
own country before embarking on his around-the-globe trip.
</P>
<P>
   He pedaled alone in Bangladesh, Singapore and Indonesia. His
wife, Hamsavahini, and their daughter, Aditya, joined him in
Malaysia. The Singhs arrived in San Francisco on July 2 on a flight
from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   While in Kansas City, the Singhs are staying with Lynn and Chris
Cheatum. They serve as hosts for Servas, an international
cooperative system which promotes global understanding by opening
people's homes to travelers. The Singhs have stayed with Servas
hosts and in churches on their journey.
</P>
<P>
   Singh secured the sponsorship of some Indian companies for his
world trip. Companies and institutions also have paid for airline
flights. Apart from a few flat tires, which Singh fixed himself,
the cost of the trip has been small, Singh said.
</P>
<P>
   In Boulder, Colo., at a farmers market where Singh hung his
posters promoting peace and nonviolence, a man offered a tandem
bike for his Indian-made bike. The new bike afforded a more
comfortable ride for Aditya.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can people be so friendly?'' Singh asked.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded that people everywhere were basically kind.
</P>
<P>
   Aditya has just completed the third grade. During the journey,
her parents have been teaching her themselves. Hamsavahini Singh is
an assistant professor at an Indian university. Rajpal Singh works
for a city government.
</P>
<P>
   The Singhs will leave Kansas City on Friday. The next country
they plan to visit is South Africa, where ``we will trace the route
(along which) Gandhi led the march of demonstration against social
apartheid,'' Singh said.
</P>
<P>
   From South Africa, the Singhs will go to Portugal and tour
western and central Europe. Next June, Hamsavahini Singh and Aditya
will return to India. Singh will to keep pedaling through Poland,
Russia, Georgia, Azerbaijan, Armenia, Iran and Pakistan before
reuniting with his family in spring 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
