<SLUG> BC-GATES-GIFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES' TO ANNOUNCE $1 BILLION SCHOLARSHIP FUND FOR MINORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and his wife, Melinda, will
announce on Thursday that they are giving at least $1 billion to a
new scholarship fund to help minority students pay for college.
</P>
<P>
   The gift dwarfs previous giving by the 5-year-old Bill and
Melinda Gates Foundation and is only the second billion-dollar
bequest to a single cause. The first was a $1 billion gift from Ted
Turner to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Gates Foundation, which has assets of more
than $17 billion, refused to discuss the initiative on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But sources said the new minority scholarship program would
support a minimum of 1,000 high school students throughout their
undergraduate and graduate studies. Awards would cover tuition,
room and board and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly is a very significant grant if that's the
case,'' said Dorothy Ridings, president of the Council on
Foundations, a Washington, D.C.-based group that serves
foundations. ``It's an interesting approach because it's not for
bricks and mortar but for actual programmatic activity through
scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, called the Gates Millennium Scholarships, will be
open to all racial minorities, but will be aimed particularly at
black, Hispanic and American Indian students.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the scholarship program comes less than a year
after voters in Washington state passed Initiative 200, outlawing
the consideration of race in university admissions and some
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Washington, the immediate effects of I-200
have caused alarm as minority enrollments have plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the UW is expecting 40 percent fewer African American
freshmen, 30 percent fewer Latino and 20 percent fewer Native
American freshman than registered for classes last fall. If the
numbers hold, the three minority groups will make up only 5 percent
of the 1999 entering class.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Gates Jr. _ father of the Microsoft co-founder,
co-chairman of the Gates Foundation and a member of the UW Board of
Regents _ has been an outspoken opponent of I-200.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he donated $25,000 to the campaign to defeat the
initiative. And as a member of the UW's board, he has been
instrumental in crafting outreach and recruitment programs designed
to keep the university's doors open for minority students.
</P>
<P>
   That task has been made more difficult because the rollback of
affirmative action programs has meant public money can't be used to
attract and support minority students.
</P>
<P>
   Washington isn't the only state grappling with this issue.
California voted to outlaw affirmative action programs at it's
public universities in 1996. The same year, a federal appeals court
ruled that the University of Texas' use of race in admissions
decisions was unconstitutional. And efforts to roll back
affirmative action programs are under way now in Florida and
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   As more states outlaw affirmative action programs using public
money, the Millenium Scholarship Program would fill the void by
privately financing college educations for minority students.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter inviting presidents of area universities to Thursday
morning's news conference, Foundation co-chair Patty Stonesifer
wrote, ``I welcome you to learn about our new national program
dedicated to improving equity and access to higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the program will benefit promising students who are
already in college. Beginning in the fall of 2000, it will be
opened to high school seniors. The applicants must have a 3.3
grade-point average, be nominated by a teacher or their school's
principal and must also write an essay.
</P>
<P>
   For those selected, the Gates Foundation will bridge the gap
between the total cost of school and any other scholarship the
students are receiving.
</P>
<P>
   That difference is key to many students.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda and Bill Gates, his father, Gov. Gary Locke and the
presidents of several area universities are scheduled to be present
for Thursday morning's announcement at the Foundation's Seattle
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation is the umbrella
organization for the Gates' philanthropic work. It is presently the
largest philanthropic foundation in the United States and may soon
become the largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation focuses on global health and learning. A
statement on the organization's Web site talks about the founders'
goals: ``Too many people are denied access to the remarkable
advances of the 21st century in the areas of global health and
learning. Bill and Melinda are committed to bridging the gap in
access for all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent gifts in education include a $200 million commitment to
bring computers, Internet access and training to low-income
libraries in the United States and Canada. To date, approximately
$30 million in grants have been distributed under this initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The Gateses have awarded smaller gifts to higher education to
finance a variety of programs. Heritage College in Toppenish,
Wash., received $200,000 to automate the library for Internet
access. The United Negro College Fund received $100,000. The
University of Puget Sound received $1 million to renovate the
Collins Memorial Library.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion gift being announced Thursday is remarkable not
only for its scale, but for its scope, philanthropy experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer Reporters Kristin Dizon and Joel Connelly
contributed to this report. It also contains material from the New
York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
