<SLUG> BC-HOG-SIERRA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA CLUB DENOUNCES STATE AID TO CORPORATE HOG FARMS IN
MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An environmental group on Wednesday criticized the use of
economic development money to draw large corporate hog farms to
Missouri, creating pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments are spending millions of taxpayer dollars to bring
a pollution nightmare into America's neighborhoods,'' said Ken
Midkiff, director of the Sierra Club in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and hog farm operators disputed the findings,
saying that the economic development programs were creating jobs in
depressed rural areas and that pollution concerns were being
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   In their report, ``Corporate Hogs at the Public Trough,'' the
Sierra Club questioned the amount of government economic incentives
that went to companies operating huge hog and poultry farms.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri the Sierra Club report focused on Premium Standard
Farms, the Kansas City-based company that raises more than 2
million hogs a year across the state's northern tier of counties.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club said that more than $1.5 million from Missouri's
Department of Economic Development had gone to Premium Standard
Farms, as well as tax abatements that can extend for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Sierra Club report, officials in Sullivan
County granted the company a 100 percent tax abatement on its
packing plant for 18 years. And in north Missouri, an electric
company provides Premium Standard power at about one-third the
normal cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money is not creating economic development _ it's
creating environmental destruction,'' Midkiff said. ``Instead of
holding these polluters accountable for polluting our water and
air, governments are offering these factories tax breaks, direct
and indirect subsidies, and even outright cash outlays.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Arnot, a spokesman for Premium Standard, disagreed with
the club's criticism of state economic incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premium Standard Farms has never asked for or received
anything that wasn't available to any other industry creating
jobs,'' Arnot said Wednesday. ``We have never asked for special
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard employs 2,200 people in northern Missouri, has
a $56 million annual payroll, and pays about $2 million in taxes a
year, Arnot added.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, Arnot said, Premium Standard also had
worked to improve pollution controls. He said Premium Standard had
aggressively pursued pilot programs for waste treatment that would
help reduce the risk of spills.
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard also has been instrumental to the economic
turnaround in the areas where they locate, said Jim Gardner, a
spokesman for the state's Department of Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``After decades of population decline, now Sullivan County is
one of the fastest-growing communities in the state,'' Gardner
said. ``A lot of that is due to that solid economic base provided
by these companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sierra Club maintains that the economy has not improved
in north Missouri with the introduction of corporate hog farms. The
club found that Putnam County's unemployment rate has gone up,
while per capita income in Mercer County has dipped below its 1994
level, ranking next to last in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club said it found similar patterns in Kentucky,
Utah, Illinois, Iowa, Maryland, Arkansas, Oklahoma, North Carolina
and Mississippi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-ROSE-850&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-16 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROSE-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 FREDERICK ROSE, 75, BUILDER AND PHILANTHROPIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frederick Rose, a highly successful builder who poured his
energy into two dozen major apartment projects and an equal number
of institutions that adorn the New York skyline, from Lincoln
Center to Rockefeller University and the Children's Aid Society,
died Tuesday night. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   He died at his home in Rye, N.Y., after a brief illness, his
family said.
</P>
<P>
   A second-generation member of a New York real estate dynasty,
Rose could be found until earlier this year supervising
construction of a 50-story apartment house, the Belvedere, at 29th
Street between Fifth and Madison Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest project for Rose Associates, which owns or
manages 12,000 apartments in New York and 4 million square feet of
commercial space.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, and with equal enthusiasm, he was overseeing
construction of the $150 million Frederick Phineas and Sandra
Priest Rose Center for Earth and Space at the American Museum of
Natural History, the giant sphere that houses the new Hayden
Planetarium. Rose not only wrote a $20 million check for the
planetarium, but also was the project leader for the trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a builder in every sense of the word, not just of
buildings, but of institutions,'' said Ellen Futter, president of
the American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Rose also gave $5 million to the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, $15 million to the New York Public Library and $18
million to Lincoln Center, more than $95 million in all.
</P>
<P>
   A forceful man with a reputation for keeping his word, Rose
could breeze into a meeting, as he did earlier this year with his
longtime friend and partner, Charles Benenson, and within minutes
size up the situation and agree to a $24 million real estate deal
for land on 44th Street, near Third Avenue, for a 51-story
apartment house.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was still building tall buildings while his nephew, Joseph
Rose, the current chairman of the New York City Planning
Commission, labored to change the zoning laws to bar oversized
towers in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rose family's buildings were known more for
efficiency than architectural detail, Rose was most proud of
building two towers that won awards for design: the Bankers Trust
Building at 280 Park Ave., near 48th Street, and a 40-story
apartment house at 45 E. 89th St.
</P>
<P>
   His interests ranged widely.
</P>
<P>
   Rose always carried a stack of foreign currency and American
dollar bills, which he would fold into intricate origami figures of
birds, cows and walruses and present to his delighted friends. At
the end of a stuffy board meeting at Lincoln Center, Rose would
often stroll over to a piano and play a few songs for the amusement
of the other directors. He played golf up to four times a week and,
last year, hired a national chess champion to sharpen his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Benenson, who had been a partner in many of Rose's real estate
deals since the early 1960s, said he called his friend two months
ago, suggesting that they raise $100,000 from each of 10 people for
the refugees in Kosovo. The next day, Benenson recalled, the
developer called back and said, ``OK, we'll do it through the
American Jewish Committee, because we want to show the world that
Jewish people are helping Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three days later,'' Benenson concluded, ``we had $1.4
million. An engineer by training, Rose wrote in a 1994 journal
commemorating the 50th anniversary of his graduation from Yale
University that the central focus of his life had been his family.
He wrote that he had been on the boards of 35 organizations, from
Con Edison to Yale University. He took pride in being a builder.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he wrote: ``I don't read trash, watch TV or have an
interest in spectator sports. This leaves time for active
participation in things I enjoy: music, chess, tennis, golf,
travel, skiing and friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose's insistence on providing advice and hiring consultants for
projects to which he had contributed sometimes rankled other
developers, but institutions and their directors embraced him.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Rose was chairman of the real estate company
started by his father, Samuel Rose, and his uncle, David Rose, in
the Bronx around the time he was born, in 1923. The two brothers
built small apartment houses in the Bronx before moving into
Manhattan a decade later. Samuel had three sons, Daniel, Elihu and
Frederick, all of whom joined the company after World War II.
Frederick's son Adam, is now president of Rose Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Rose married his teen-age sweetheart, Sandra Priest of Rye, in
the early 1940s. She survives him, along with a daughter, Deborah
Rose; two sons, Jonathan Rose and Adam Rose, both of New York; two
brothers, Daniel and Elihu, and three grandchildren, Ariel, Rachael
and Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   Rose served in the construction battalions of the Navy Seabees
during World War II, rising to the rank of lieutenant before he
returned to New York and Rose Associates. He took charge of design
and construction, while Daniel did the planning and finances and
Elihu took over management of the family's apartment houses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rose built more than 2,000 units of middle-income housing under
the state's Mitchell-Lama program, as well as the family's first
office tower at 280 Park Ave.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike some developers who showed up in the gossip columns
during the 1980s and 1990s, Rose and his family avoided publicity.
He usually contributed money to charities anonymously, and word of
the donations rarely leaked out until years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He built good-quality housing and he was devoted to community
service,'' said Robert Shapiro, a real estate broker who knew Rose.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime opponent of rent control, Rose converted more than
3,000 apartments in Manhattan during the early 1990s into
condominiums and co-ops. Many people in the industry thought it was
a risky move, given the recession. But unlike many landlords at the
time who were struggling with enormous loans, the Rose family had
buildings that were largely free of debt, and the conversion went
off without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He secretly believed he was the finest construction
superintendent in the city,'' said his brother Daniel, who is now
chairman of Rose Associates. ``He liked to kick the bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose applied the same energy, enthusiasm and discipline to his
philanthropic work as his professional work, his brother said. When
Rose, along with his wife, gave $15 million to Lincoln Center, he
also helped engineer the construction of the Rose Building, a
31-story tower that houses rehearsal space and dormitories for the
Juilliard School of Music and offices for the School of American
Ballet and the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a mercurial mind and it was fun trying to keep up with
him,'' said Beverly Sills, the chairwoman of Lincoln Center. ``He
was a man of the world in every sense of the word. I'm really going
to miss him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
