<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Kahalani Drew loves her son, Keala, a brown-haired
5-year-old who likes to draw pictures and play in the park.
</P>
<P>
   She just hopes he won't kill her in her sleep.
</P>
<P>
   She and Keala's psychiatrist also hope the Valley's public
mental health system will relent and provide the sick child the
help they think he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are more concerned about their pocketbook,'' Drew
said.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, 29, is concerned about Keala, whose serious mental illness
has made him capable of sudden violence that would be shocking in a
youth three times his age.
</P>
<P>
   Violence sometimes urged on him by voices he calls ``the boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Keala has killed several pets, stabbed his mother, leaped from
moving cars, slashed the top of his thumb and been in and out of
six hospitals and clinics in eight months.
</P>
<P>
   He once ripped the leg off a rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, a jail detention officer, points to areas of her body _ a
puncture wound here from a pencil, a stab mark there from a fork, a
bite mark, a knife cut, the endless bruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know as a parent if I'm going to live or die,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Keala was hospitalized for his thumb. Dr. Manuel
Mota, the psychiatrist who diagnosed him with bipolar disorder,
asked that the boy be hospitalized for three weeks of psychiatric
care.
</P>
<P>
   The request was denied by Value Options, the firm that contracts
with the state to provide mental health services for the Valley's
poor and uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to comment on the case, citing
patient confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold Levine, medical director for Value Options'
subsidiary, ABS, said that in recent years psychiatrists have
diagnosed increasing numbers of children with bipolar psychosis.
Levine said they can be treated successfully with medication, and
it's unusual for them to be violent.
</P>
<P>
   Mota said Value Options officials decided that Keala's symptoms
weren't severe enough to warrant more than five days at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   And as for his history?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the scary part,'' Mota said. ``They are expecting him
to show more severe symptoms, and those are severe symptoms that
could cause serious harm to somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unpredictable. It's like walking into a minefield.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Keala's continuing search for help isn't an
unfamiliar one. Keala is one of 10,000 children receiving mental
health services, from medication to long-term hospitalization,
through Value Options.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, critics say, they are not getting the help they
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to pay for treating these children,'' Mota said.
``Between CPS (Child Protective Services), DDD (Developmentally
Disabled), Value Options and private payers, a lot of these
children just fall through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   But even when some help is available, as in Keala's case, many
patients' doctors and relatives say it is often not enough help or
not long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, a single mother, has insurance through her job. But her
mental health benefits were wiped out with Keala's first three
hospital stays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, three of the boy's medications are paid for by the
Arizona Health Care Cost Containment System, the state's Medicaid
system. The other two are covered by Drew's insurance, as are his
thrice-daily breathing treatments for asthma and his daily allergy
medication.
</P>
<P>
   For Drew, ``every day is a hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know if it's going to be a speed bump or if it's
going to be a total 10-foot wall that I have to climb over.''
</P>
<P>
   Mota calls Keala's self-mutilation of his thumb a ``red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful with this kid,'' he said. ``Maybe on
another day . . . he'll decide to stab his mother while she
sleeps.''
</P>
<P>
   Keala was different almost from the start of his young life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be sitting, playing, content and happy like any
little kid would be,'' Drew said. ``And then he would start
screaming, bloodcurdling screams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would check him, check his pants, do everything a mom does
and nothing would be wrong. Then I'd hold him, cuddle him and sing
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics from a favorite family song, I Do Believe the Lord
Above, would finally soothe the toddler.
</P>
<P>
   Problems persisted. He screamed when looking in the mirror and
tied things around his neck, pulling them tight.
</P>
<P>
   Mota says the boy suffers from a bipolar disorder with psychotic
features like hallucinating and hearing the voices of ``the boys,''
a group who Keala says tells him to do harmful things.
</P>
<P>
   Mota caught one such episode on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recorded him talking to the boys,'' he said. ``Five boys
were talking to him and telling him to be mean and hit his
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of this year, Drew said, her son chased her with a
large kitchen knife. She said she usually keeps the house carefully
secured, using duct tape to seal off cabinets and drawers and
keeping doors shut with latches. But the knife was in the
dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't harmed, and later took him for hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The voices also tell Keala to threaten others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll tell his therapist, `I'm going to kill you, bitch,' ''
she said. ``He says a lot of things, but he doesn't have the
physical strength to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has killed several animals, Drew said. He can be gentle
with them one moment and violent the next.
</P>
<P>
   He killed a rabbit by snapping its neck, crushed a small turtle
with his foot and strangled a cat with its leash.
</P>
<P>
   He also ripped the leg off another rabbit because it turned its
head away from him, Drew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just started laughing,'' she said. ``He said (to the
rabbit), `You don't do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Drew and her son live on her $21,000-a-year salary, supplemented
by a monthly $160 from Social Security. She said she receives no
child support from her ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   The two were evicted from their Phoenix apartment because, Drew
said, she was late with rent payments.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they live with friends in the Valley, and she pays a
monthly $300 rent. She's looking for a home of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Drew said she had to trade in her four-door car for a minivan
because Keala kept leaping out while she drove _ once in the
carpool lane of Interstate 10 _ or attacking her from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's strapped into a heavy-duty child-restraint seat in the
rear of the minivan, with no quick access to a door. Because the
van is a three-seater, there's a buffer between him and her.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, Keala has been admitted to a hospital or an
urgent-care center six times; his stays have varied from one night
to just over a month.
</P>
<P>
   Then, earlier this month, the voices told him to cut off the end
of his thumb and try to ``eat'' the blood, Drew said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy didn't seem to mind the pain and blood. That day, like
so many others, he just wore what Drew calls a distant and
disturbing stare.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed one night at an urgent-care center and then received
five days of psychiatric care at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Officials noted that Keala suffered from ``aggression, violent
outbursts, self-destruction and auditory hallucinations,''
according to records. He received counseling and therapy, was
deemed ``stable'' and discharged Sept. 8 because of the Value
Options denial.
</P>
<P>
   Both Drew and Mota believe Keala is stable, for now, but also
believe that Keala warrants further hospitalization or professional
care in his own home. But, as Drew notes, that stability changes
from on and off like a light switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `I want people to love me,' '' Drew said. `` `Why are
you scared? I'm a nice boy.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Susie Steckner can be reached at (602) 444-7129 or at
susie.steckner(at)pni.com. &QL; 
Jodie Snyder contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
