<HEADER>
A4006 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-HNS &LR;      09-16 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It pained him to say it. He smacked his lips and squirmed for just
an instant, but the words eventually came out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think he did a super job last year of keeping his team into
it mentally,'' Florida coach Steve Spurrier said. ``Sometimes you
go 9-0, 10-0, 11-0, you tend to get a little full of yourself. They
seemed to stay on an even keel throughout the run they had last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil and his coaches had a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it: If a national championship and a Knoxville
street named in his honor weren't enough to cap off a remarkable
1998 season, even Phillip Fulmer's favorite tormentor was tossing
compliments his way.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all folks in Tennessee want is for Fulmer and the
Volunteers to do it again _ with Saturday night's game at Florida
serving as the first big step on the way to the Sugar Bowl, site of
this year's Bowl Championship Series-designated national title
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You consistently raise the bar,'' Fulmer said. ``I like the
expectations. Kids work with those things in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us like it when you don't quite get it all done and
you get talked about and criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer heard plenty of that when talented Tennessee teams came
up short in all four seasons of Peyton Manning's record-setting
career. From 1993 to 1997, in fact, the Vols lost five straight to
the rival Gators, with the loquacious Spurrier usually ready to
apply the needle.
</P>
<P>
   Things are different now after a 13-0 season ended in a Fiesta
Bowl win over Florida State, wrapping up Tennessee's first national
championship since 1951. And while Fulmer isn't likely to be caught
resting on his laurels, those close to him have seen a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it gave him the recognition he deserved,'' quarterback
Tee Martin says. ``He's mentioned now among the elite coaches in
college football, the Bobby Bowdens and Tom Osbornes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He already had one of the biggest winning percentages in
college football. Winning the national championship got him over
the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over in 1992, Fulmer has compiled a record of
68-11, including this year's opening win over Wyoming. That .860
winning percentage is better than that of any other active coach.
</P>
<P>
   Until last season, though, he also carried the tag of a coach
who couldn't win the big one, even with some of the nation's top
talent. The losses to Florida were particularly damaging, but the
Vols finally broke through with a 20-17 overtime victory in
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Bowden and Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl,
Fulmer was voted Coach of the Year by his peers. As the 1999 season
got under way, critics were few and apologies were unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I feel validated rather than vindicated,'' Fulmer
says. ``You try to stay the course and look at your program and all
those things that give you a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go on forever and not win a national championship.
We've been awfully close and not been recognized as much as some of
our kids should have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to get over that hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   For his next trick, he will attempt to produce Tennessee's first
win in Gainesville since 1971. And oh, yes, a repeat of
Southeastern Conference and national titles would be nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a professional standpoint, last year was the pinnacle,''
Fulmer said. ``But it's not like you won the lottery and you
retire. You have to go about your business.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's visit to ``The Swamp'' is the next big item on
the agenda. If the Vols can clear that hurdle, the schedule becomes
an ally with only trips to Alabama (Oct. 23) and Arkansas (Nov. 13)
looming as potential stumbling blocks. (Georgia and Notre Dame
visit Knoxville.)
</P>
<P>
   With a return to Tennessee's house of horrors coming up fast,
Fulmer is well aware that the time for basking in January's glories
has passed. While even Spurrier is willing to give last year's
winner his due, things can change quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Driving by ``Phillip Fulmer Way'' on the Knoxville campus, he
says, is a regular reminder of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great honor,'' the honoree said. ``From the
standpoint of recognition, that's as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, they may take it down if I don't do well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
