<HEADLINE>
PEORIA RAISING COST OF GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAUN MCKINNON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The cost of building a house in north Peoria will
climb soon by $12,353, an addition to the bottom line that has
nothing to do with the price of drywall or red tiles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's the city's attempt to figure out how much growth
costs and then find a way to pay at least part of the bill,
choosing last week to increase impact fees on new construction by
as much as 300 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the benefits of growth, but we just believe it is
appropriate and responsible for those who benefit the most to pay
more for the cost of growth,'' Peoria Mayor John Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria, with its ever-spreading sea of subdivisions and
far-flung undeveloped edges, offers a nearly perfect study in the
struggle to cope with both sides of growth _ the side that produces
new revenue and the side that soaks it up again.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly every city, school district and service provider in
the Phoenix area faces the same hard reality about growth: Left
alone, it won't pay for itself. New homes may bring new taxpaying
residents, but until the residents bring their own streets, schools
and water systems, the cities will have to scramble for more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cities have to look to provide everything that everybody who
lives in those new houses wants and needs,'' Glendale Mayor Elaine
Scruggs said. ``You don't do that with rooftops. Houses cost cities
money. It costs about twice as much to provide services as we ever
get from the tax base. You have to have revenue coming in other
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban planners have long argued that single-family homes don't
generate enough money to pay for the services needed to keep their
residents happy, especially not in the first year or two. Sprawling
subdivisions also make a wobbly tax base for bonds to build
bigger-ticket items like schools or water systems. &QL; 
A `BALANCING ACT' &QL; 
On the flip side, home builders say commercial developers, who
could infuse a bigger shot of revenue to help support the homes,
are reluctant to stake an outpost in the suburbs until the people
are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a balancing act of what comes first and at what
rate,'' said Connie Wilhelm, president of the Home Builders
Association of Central Arizona. ``New growth can support new
growth. It is a timing issue of when the revenues are generated.
That's why you have to look at the whole area for a longer period
of time if you're going to evaluate homes.''
</P>
<P>
   She cites a 1987 study of two developing Phoenix neighborhoods
that looked at how much the city would spend on services for new
homes in the area and how much those homes would produce in
revenue, from taxes to money spent by homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Over a nearly 50-year span, the study predicted the city would
break even, spending and collecting about $1 billion, a testament,
Wilhelm argues, to working with the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   But with thousands of new people moving to the Phoenix area each
month, most budget-conscious cities and school districts must work
first with the snapshot in front of them. Trying to find enough
money to pay for new growth means trying to figure out how much
growth costs, and most planners agree that number is a rapidly
moving target. What's true in Peoria isn't necessarily true in
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy thing to do,'' said Tom Rex, research manager
for Arizona State University's Center for Business Research.
``There's no one right answer. The general consensus is, no, simply
building a house and collecting building permit fees and taxes
doesn't cover what it costs for services. But not every situation
is going to be the same.'' &QL; 
STUDIES OF COSTS &QL; 
Planning experts refer regularly to a handful of studies on how
much a new single-family home will cost local governments and
service providers, such as utilities. One study conducted by
Florida researchers more than a decade ago set the cost at about
$10,000 per house. A more recent and detailed study by Oregon
planning consultant Eben Fodor produced a price tag of about
$33,000.
</P>
<P>
   Broken down further, New Jersey researchers found that, in one
county, for every dollar a single-family home produced in taxes,
the local government spent $1.12 on public services. For every
dollar collected from commercial development, officials spent just
27 cents on services.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, planners say, the two sides should balance each other
out. The problem is, fast-growing neighborhoods are often swallowed
by subdivisions long before any commercial development arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Most cities are turning to impact fees to make up the difference
and keep up with needed infrastructure. Phoenix charges about
$9,000 per house in some neighborhoods, Peoria will collect more
than $12,000 in its still undeveloped northern edges, and even tiny
Queen Creek recently approved a $7,300-per-house impact fee.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria council members approved fee increases, repeating the
mantra that growth should pay for growth, a popular sentiment among
homeowners. &QL; 
`LINE IN THE SAND' &QL; 
But Wilhelm said communities used to accept the idea that a
neighborhood generated money needed to help support a new
neighborhood and that, down the road, that neighborhood would help
build up the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like somewhere, we drew a line in the sand and said new
homes have to pay for themselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That approach helps many cities build roads and water systems
they otherwise couldn't afford, but it drives up the cost of
housing and fails to address the needs for upkeep services in older
neighborhoods, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cities argue that as developers move farther and farther from
established neighborhoods, the cost of building roads and utility
infrastructure is just too high without substantial contributions
from the home builders.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix recently wrote into law a service boundary on the city's
northern end, outlying for developers where infrastructure will be
provided and where the builders will be on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club wants even more restrictions, growth boundaries
that would limit where a developer could build anything. That
proposal could end up on the ballot next year, and home builders
concede it would be popular among growth-weary Phoenix area
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say they're looking for other solutions. Some school
districts have begun working more closely with builders and city
planners, so no one is surprised when a new subdivision opens or a
school fills up. &QL; 
BETTER PLANNING NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   Glendale Mayor Scruggs said cities also need better long-range
planning, including stronger efforts to attract jobs and commercial
development to balance out the new homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to hold back those houses,'' she
said. ``There's always going to be home builders ready to build
houses. There's tons of them. But there are not so many
opportunities to land quality employers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Traw, a Phoenix developer and real estate broker, said
builders are simply building too much too fast, leaving cities and
school districts to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need open spaces, large lots, parks, schools,'' he said.
``Transportation should be Number 1 _ put the roads in first. You
need to look at the whole picture, not just yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Rex said the Phoenix area can't depend on growth to
support itself forever. Sooner or later, the boom will level off
and so will the steady increase in revenue. Because Arizona cities
rely so heavily on sales tax, he said, a slowdown in growth is like
a punch to the gut of local coffers. Fewer homes built means not
only fewer new people but fewer construction supplies bought. &QL; 
WHEN THE CYCLE ENDS &QL; 
For now, Rex said, when the latest wave of homes needs services,
the last wave is generating enough money to get by, but that cycle
will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why when we've had recessions, they've had such a
terrible impact,'' he said. ``Everyone's overextended themselves.
As long as things keep going the way they're going, we're fine; but
sooner or later, there's going to be another recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, most planners and housing analysts say, everyone in
a community winds up paying at least part of the cost of growth,
whether it's through taxes, housing costs or a decline in services
as the municipal budget is stretched to its limits.
</P>
<P>
   New-home buyers may be hit first. As impact fees climb higher,
Wilhelm said, home builders have no choice but to pass along the
costs to home buyers. With profit margins of 3 to 5 percent, she
said, ``there's no way they can absorb fees that high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no way they can do anything but pass it along,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although impact fees can help a city avoid raising taxes or fees
on the general population, housing experts say that if those fees
drive up the price of a new home, the price of existing homes in
the same area will probably also rise, affecting people who may
just want to move across town.
</P>
<P>
   And when growth doesn't pay its own way, Eugene, Ore., community
planning consultant Eben Fodor wrote last year, taxpayers have to
make up the difference, a subsidy he suggests actually stimulates
even more growth by lowering the private cost of developing land.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, ``the high costs of urban growth are unavoidable.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shaun McKinnon can be reached at (602) 444-7116 or at
shaun.mckinnon(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
