<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN FATALLY SHOOTS 7 AT CHURCH BEFORE KILLING HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CLARIFIES 2nd graf; ADDS background on other shootings; MINOR
edits thruout) 
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page)  (rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As a hymn ended and prayers began at a special service
for teen-agers Wednesday evening at a Baptist church in Fort Worth,
a man with a semiautomatic handgun walked in and began firing,
killing six people in the church before turning the gun on himself.
An eighth person died later at a hospital, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. David Ellis of the Fort Worth Police Department said three
teen-agers and three adults were shot to death inside the church in
the city's southwest corner. The age of the seventh person killed
was unknown.Ellis also said that a pipe bomb exploded on a balcony
inside the church sanctuary after the 7 p.m. shooting and that the
department's bomb squad was inspecting several suspicious packages
found at the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's cartridges, shrapnel and empty cart boxes and blood
splattered all over the wall,'' Ellis was quoted by The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Mendoza, Fort Worth's acting police chief, described the
gunman as a white male in his 20s or 30s but offered no other
information. He said the man had fired a semiautomatic handgun, and
officers had found at least three spent ammunition clips on the
floor of the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised the shooting had occurred inside a
church, the Fort Worth fire chief, Larry McMillen, responded, ``I'm
at the point where nothing surprises me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 8 p.m., police officers told reporters and
bystanders to move inside an elementary school across the street
from the church because of the explosives.
</P>
<P>
   A supervisor with the Fort Worth Police Department, S. Coe, said
officers evacuated the church, Wedgwood Baptist, and a bomb squad
swept the sanctuary for other explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Coe said the gunman arrived at the church shortly before 7 p.m.
and began firing. An estimated 150 teen-agers were attending the
weekly service for the annual ``See You at the Pole'' gathering,
where students affirm their faith and concern for the problems of
society by holding prayer time around their school's flagpole.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Martin, 17, told a local television station, KDFW, that
the man ``was very calm and looked normal and was smoking a
cigarette.'' She added that the gunman had walked into the
sanctuary, ``pulled a gun and began firing. I just saw him point
the gun and shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   A young man interviewed on CNN said the gunman paused at least
once to reload his gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw him keep shooting and reloading,'' said the man,
who was not identified. ``He'd empty it and then throw some more
bullets in there, and he kept shooting. I seen him sit down, he
kept walking back and forth in the very back aisle, and he kept
shooting straight. I was at the side between the door and the
window and he looked like he looked at me, so I got down and he
started shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting is the latest in a spate of mass killings. In July,
a disgruntled day trader, Mark Barton, walked into the Atlanta
stock firm where he had lost more than $105,000 and opened fire on
customers and employees before killing himself. Barton had killed
his wife and two children earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In May, six students were injured in Conyers, Ga., when a
student opened fire at Heritage High School. In April, 15 people
were killed in Littleton, Colo., when two students went on a
shooting rampage at their high school. Those shootings were another
chapter in a tale of violence involving young people and guns.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-98 school year students were killed or wounded in
Pearl, Miss.; West Paducah, Ky.; Edinboro, Pa.; Jonesboro, Ark.,
and Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A witness, Kristen Dickens, 14, told the Fort Worth newspaper,
``We had just finished singing and we were praying when he came
in,'' she said. ``We thought it was a joke. We were singing and he
told us to shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on MSNBC, a man who was in the church said that
``all of a sudden we heard some bang noises.'' He went on to say
that a man then ``kind of fell across the doorway and said he had
been shot.''
</P>
<P>
   A teen-ager interviewed on CNN said: ``We were on stage playing.
We heard pops. We thought they were toys or something. A guy
started screaming in the back of the auditorium. And we seen him
load his gun so we just dove and ran out the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Another youth who was in the church described the gunman as
looking like the Unabomer, add that at first he ``thought it was a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``See You at the Pole'' service is celebrated at churches
across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the day youth in America gather around the flag pole
at their school and pray for their school,'' said Mark Collins, a
Baptist minister in Houston. He said the practice started about
five years ago, he believes with a youth group in a small Texas
town.
</P>
</TEXT>
