<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES UNVEIL PLANS TO PUT `CUSTOMERS FIRST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - America West joined the nation's airlines Wednesday in
issuing customer service improvement plans that will be launched in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Under a June agreement that headed off congressional action to
force industry changes, each U.S. air carrier was required to
submit by Sept. 15 a plan for treating passengers better.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics remain skeptical that the new codes of conduct
submitted Wednesday to the U.S. Department of Transportation will
improve customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., labeled the plans ``nothing but
legalistic gobbledygook, which (does) nothing to protect
passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyden and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., had pushed for tough
legislation to force the industry to heed passenger complaints
about air travel horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   But an Air Passenger Bill of Rights proposed by the senators was
shelved in June when the Air Transport Association, an industry
lobbying group, proposed a 12-point voluntary customer service
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ATA President Carol Hallet said the airlines will do their part
to improve the air travel experience, and she called on the
government to do its part by improving the air-traffic control
system.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's ``Customers First'' plans for the airlines
require better communication with passengers on flight
cancellations and delays, as well as accurate information on the
lowest available fares. Customer service representatives must
respond to written complaints within 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers also must increase their liability for lost baggage
from $1,250 to a proposed $2,500, disclose cancellation and
frequent-flier policies and provide information on seat size and
legroom on specific aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   During long on-aircraft delays, the airlines must make
reasonable efforts to provide food, water, bathrooms and access to
medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   America West's plan adds some additional customer service
elements, but many of the policies already were in place, according
to spokeswoman Patty Nowack.
</P>
<P>
   Among the improvements is a commitment to notify passengers of
flight delays every 15 minutes at the airport gate and within five
minutes of the scheduled departure time when passengers are on the
aircraft at the gate or on the taxiway. An undisclosed number of
flight-tracking agents will be added to improve the flow of
information about flights, Nowack said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe-based airline, which is the dominant carrier in
Phoenix, also will provide brochures spelling out its customer
service policies, such as when a stranded passenger is entitled to
have the airline pay for a hotel room and meals.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, America West will compensate those travelers, unless
the flight is canceled because of inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, travelers will be entitled to receive meal money
of $5 for breakfast, $7.50 for lunch and $10 for dinner, plus $25
to purchase items if they don't have their baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, America West will provide ticket refunds within
seven days for credit card purchases and 20 days for cash
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   For competitive reasons, America West declined to say how much
it will cost to implement the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The other main carrier serving Phoenix, Southwest Airlines, said
it will be working to retrain many of its 28,000 employees to
implement its new customer service plan between now and Dec. 15,
according to spokeswoman Ginger Hardage.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Southwest's plan has few changes from its current
practices, but the new policy will be available in writing for
customers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the changes is holding airline reservations for 24 hours
before customers are required to pay for their tickets. This allows
travelers to shop for a better fare.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines says it will use 600 hand-held baggage scanning
devices in its busiest markets to help track luggage and improve
on-time performance. The Chicago-area-based airline also will
establish toll-free phone numbers for refunds and baggage inquiries
and a separate toll-free line for customer service complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In its hubs in Chicago, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Denver and
Washington (Dulles), United will deploy portable workstations,
called ``Mobile Chariots,'' that workers can use to check in
passengers, issue tickets and reaccommodate customers whose flights
are canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines will adopt an event recovery plan intended to
ensure that passengers will not be held on-board for more than an
hour if there is a delay when a plane lands at an airport.
</P>
<P>
   A New Year's weekend blizzard that stranded about 4,500
Northwest passengers on 32 planes for up to eight hours on the
runways at Detroit Metro Airport was one of the major issues that
prompted efforts to force air carriers to improve service.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest also will provide a customer-service booklet to assist
travelers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this article. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
