<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAST, RUSSIA'S 5TH, KILLS 4 AND HURTS 70 IN SOUTHERN CITY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RECASTS with Thursday's bombing; SUBS headline; UPDATES thruout)  (See RUSSIA-BOMBS-POLITICS) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A truck exploded next to a nine-story apartment
building in the Rostov region in southern Russia early Thursday,
leaving at least four people dead and 70 hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the blast, at 5:50 a.m. in the city of Volgodonsk,
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin ordered Russian special forces to
join firefighters and other rescuers at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth explosion in Russia since Aug. 31, when a blast
hit a Moscow shopping center, killing one and injuring 40. That was
followed by an explosion at a building in Dagestan that housed
Russian officers and their families, which killed 64.
</P>
<P>
   Two more explosions in Moscow killed more than 210.
</P>
<P>
   Russian police, disclosing their findings of the explosions of
the two recent Moscow blasts, said Wednesday that Chechen militants
had shipped tons of explosives into Moscow disguised as bags of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found out who carried out the explosions,'' Moscow's
deputy police chief, Aleksandr Veldyayev, said Thursday. ``The
terrorist attacks were carried out by Chechen fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Muscovites believe that the bombings, which have sent waves
of anxiety through the city, were the work of Islamic militants who
invaded Dagestan from bases in Chechnya, and people from the
Caucasus already have felt the backlash
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's bombing followed Russian press reports that said
``informants'' had indicated the rebels planned to attack not only
Moscow, but also Rostov and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the militants _ Shamil Basayev, the Chechen
warlord, and a Jordanian-born fighter known as Khattab _ have
insisted that they are not involved.
</P>
<P>
   The charges and denials have prompted an important question: If
the aim of the bombings is to pressure Russia to abandon Dagestan,
why would the Islamic rebels deny any involvement?
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mystery, a previously unknown group, the Dagestan
Liberation Army, called the semiofficial Itar-Tass news agency
Wednesday to claim it had organized the Moscow attacks. But some
experts said they doubted the group even existed.
</P>
<P>
   Assigning responsibility is important. Public sentiment here for
tough action against Chechnya _ and the Chechens who live in Moscow
_ is running high.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen government says that Russian conspirators carried
out the attacks, possibly to provide a pretext for the Yeltsin
government to declare a state of emergency and suspend the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one conclusion,'' said Chechnya's deputy prime
minister, Kazbek Makhashev. ``Russia needs a hot spot to solve its
own domestic political problems and its battle for power.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen authorities do not support the militants, who have
become a power to themselves near the Chechnya-Dagestan border.
</P>
<P>
   But they also do not want Russia to continue its bombing raids
against rebel positions inside Chechnya or step up its offensive
by, perhaps, launching a ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said that 27 suspects had been detained as
part of a campaign to find those responsible, but in their
briefings Thursday, Russian police and intelligence officials did
not name any.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted, however, that they had evidence that confirmed
the involvement of Chechen militants, aided by people of Slavic
appearance, an important asset since dark-skinned Chechens often
are viewed suspiciously in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
