<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN ALTERS CAMPAIGN RE FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain's elusive goal of limiting the
influence of big money in political campaigns finally may be within
reach, after a McCain decision to accommodate some Republican
objections to his bill.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the House passed a version of his bill Tuesday, McCain has
decided to drop its most controversial provision, a move he
believes will dramatically increase its chances of passage in the
Senate next month, The Arizona Republic has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is central to McCain's presidential campaign, in which
he presents himself as a reform candidate eager to ``take our
government back from the special interests and big-dollar
contributors.'' A Senate victory would lend his campaign momentum,
allowing him to claim ownership of one of the most significant
government reforms since the post-Watergate era.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill is unveiled Sept. 16, it will be missing a section
subjecting advocacy groups to federal spending limits and
disclosure requirements when they broadcast campaign advertisements
at election time.
</P>
<P>
   The provision long had been a staple of McCain's legislation,
which was supported by a majority of the Senate last year but was
never voted on because McCain and co-sponsor Russell Feingold,
D-Wis., could not manage the 60 votes necessary to overcome a
Republican-led filibuster. They fell eight votes short.
</P>
<P>
   The ad restrictions also were part of a similar reform bill in
the House that had McCain's blessing and was approved, 252-177,
late Tuesday night. All five House Republicans from Arizona voted
against the measure, at least partly because of the provision that
McCain is now planning to strip from the Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only item I had a problem with,'' Arizona Rep. Matt
Salmon said. ``If they can address that, I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's hope and belief is that there are senators who share
Salmon's view.
</P>
<P>
   If the House and Senate passed competing versions, it would be
left to a conference committee of both chambers to iron out the
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Like the House bill, McCain's version will still feature a ban
on ``soft money,'' the limitless, unregulated gifts collected by
national political parties from corporations, wealthy individuals
and unions. Soft money is supposed to build support for parties
rather than assist specific candidates, but both parties stretched
the rules during the 1996 presidential campaign and are poised to
do so again.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is also expected to contain language to enforce a
Supreme Court decision requiring approval from members before
unions use their dues for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain still supports his now-deleted ad provision because he
believes interest groups that act like campaigns should be
regulated like campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But after meeting privately with many senators, McCain became
convinced that if he were to resurrect the soft money ban, he
needed to change the voting ``dynamic'' that doomed the measure in
1997 and 1998, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the prior opposition to his bill was generated by
abortion foes, the National Rifle Association and other interest
groups that argued that the ad provision muzzled their political
speech.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the National Right to Life Committee said last year
that McCain's rules ``would cripple the pro-life movement'' by
restricting their advocacy efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said it was not subject to federal election laws
in 1996 when it waged a broadcast campaign to get Congress to back
a ``partial birth'' abortion ban. Under McCain's proposal, the
committee's radio ads, which mentioned members of Congress by name,
would have been subject to full financial disclosure requirements
if they had been broadcast at election time.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has not ruled out introducing the provision as an
amendment to the overall bill. That way, his aides reasoned, the
amendment could be defeated without taking down the entire bill
with it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time McCain has stripped down the bill to
gain support. Two years ago, he trimmed a section that would have
provided economic incentives to candidates who met specified
spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   In a key campaign speech, McCain told a New Hampshire audience
in July that Congress has been ``corrupted'' by soft money and that
he intends to prove wrong politicians who insist that voters don't
care about reforming the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is fond of quoting _ and disagreeing with _ a statement
by Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., a few years ago that voters weren't
much interested in overhauling the big-money system, and that ``not
a single race has been decided on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the Senate support for McCain's bill comes from
Democrats, whose national committee typically receives less soft
money than the GOP. McCain has managed over the years to attract
only a small minority of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   This year, supporters of the bill believe there is reason for
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel this time there is some momentum,'' said Jerome
Kohlberg, a New York businessman who founded the Washington-based
Campaign Reform Project. ``The monies are so enormous now, they've
doubled since four years ago, and people are getting sick and tired
of being dunned for enormous sums.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
