<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWENTIETH-CENTURY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURER TO COVER HOMES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Five years after the 1994 Northridge Earthquake
nearly ruined the company, 20th Century Insurance Co. announced
that it has resumed sales of home insurance policies in California.
</P>
<P>
   There is one big difference this time: The company will not be
selling earthquake policies. Customers who want that coverage will
be referred to GeoVera Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, insurance companies that sold homeowners policies
also were required to offer earthquake coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you don't have to sell the insurance. You have to provide
an outlet, which means we have a resource (for) the customer,''
said 20th Century spokesman Ric Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The company based in the Woodland Hills community of Los
Angeles' San Fernando Valley, pushed to the brink of bankruptcy by
more than $1 billion in losses from the earthquake, quit the
homeowners insurance market in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
   Officials announced in April that the company would be allowed
back into the homeowners market after agreeing to set up a fund for
customers whose earthquake-damaged homes still had not been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent the interim setting up the new program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first issue had to do with getting all the new forms and
rates approved by the regulators. We had to submit the entire
program again,'' said Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Rates will be about 7.5 percent lower on average than before the
company quit the homeowners insurance business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A 10 percent discount will be offered on homeowners insurance to
automobile insurance customers.
</P>
<P>
   While the traditional homeowners coverage will be less expensive
than before, quake coverage will not be a bargain, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will never truly be the same again,'' he said of quake
coverage. ``It is possible to obtain (policies) similar to what we
had before, but you're going to pay a significant amount for that
product now.''
</P>
<P>
   Reintroducing the homeowners line is part of 20th Century's
expansion plan for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Heller, a consumer advocate at the Foundation for Taxpayer
and Consumer Rights, said it is good to have another player back in
the homeowner market but that more quake providers are needed. The
organization's focus initially was on insurance issues.
</P>
<P>
   The only major policy writers today are GeoVera, Pacific Select
Insurance Co. and the California Earthquake Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that expanded coverage is available. Since
Northridge, more and more people have been dropping even the
limited (earthquake) coverage available, which could turn the next
disaster into an even greater disaster,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   Hills said 20th Century markets personal automobile insurance in
Arizona, California, Nevada, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
