<HEADER>
A4030 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-HOSPIT     09-16 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-HOSPITAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS and JENNIFER AUTREY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Family members and friends came to area
hospitals after the church shootings in Fort Worth, many of them
hugging and holding hands as they looked for loved ones _ and
hoped.
</P>
<P>
   One victim was a boy, celebrating his 16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Rebecca Collins, said the boy was ecstatic earlier in
the day because he finally was old enough to drive. ``He came to
lunch happy. He'd gotten his license. He was a very happy man,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was told that her friend, a 10th-grader at Brewer
High School, had been shot in the shoulder and in the spine.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said she and other friends had also planned to be at the
church. ``We were going to go, but we happened to miss the bus, so
we didn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she was relieved that she was not there, but that
she hurt for the victims. ``You're happy you're not there, but then
how can you be happy if they were?'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Of her friend, she added: ``He's great, very Christian, very
into Jesus. This isn't supposed to happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ambulance arrived at John Peter Smith Hospital at 7:30
p.m., carrying two females and a young man.
</P>
<P>
   One of the females, dressed in blue overalls, appeared to be
conscious but in shock. The other, shot in the upper chest, was
unconscious. The young man was sitting up on the stretcher as he
was wheeled into the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 minutes later, another ambulance carrying two wounded
males arrived. One of the victims was moving his arms and adjusting
his oxygen mask. The other lay motionless on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby, a woman whose clothes were spattered with blood
said her 17-year-old daughter, Heather MacDonald, was saved by a
young friend. As the gunman approached, ``she laid on top of my
daughter to protect her, and she got shot,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman said she was waiting for any word on the condition of
her daughter's friend.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brown said his wife, Jaynanne, was shot, but the bullet
grazed her head. She was taken to Harris Methodist Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   She was supposed to pick him up from work Wednesday night, Steve
Brown said, but instead decided to take their children to a prayer
meeting and concert at the church.
</P>
<P>
   He said Jaynanne Brown was sitting in the south foyer of the
church waiting for choir practice to start, talking with friends,
when they looked up and saw a man they didn't recognize walking
toward the side foyer.
</P>
<P>
   He had a cigarette in his mouth, and as he approached the people
in the foyer, his wife and friends said, ``Hope he takes it out
before he comes in.'' And then, Jaynanne Brown told her husband,
``All of a sudden he pulls out a pistol.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the bullets grazed his wife's head, and Brown said, ``God
was protecting my wife, because it went right across her head. We
could very easily have been burying her tomorrow (Thursday).''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brown said he learned about the shooting when his
sister-in-law saw reports of it on television. He borrowed her car
and drove to the church and then to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful she's ready to go home,'' said Brown, who is
head baseball coach at North Crowley High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank the Lord somebody protected her,'' Brown said. ``But
it's just a shame you can't go to church without something like
this happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Stuart, pastor at Matthew Road Baptist Church in Grand
Prairie, spoke to some of the family members waiting at Harris
Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't trust anybody anywhere,'' Stuart said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
