<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD STRUGGLING WITH BAT BUT NOT CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The bat never left Alex Rodriguez's hands
until he had swung it one more time.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners shortstop popped out to end an 8-4 loss to the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays Wednesday night, and he clutched his bat on
the jog to first and the trot back to the bench. A few steps before
the dugout, Rodriguez gave the lumber one soft, almost nostalgic
swing before dropping it to the turf and disappearing. It's been a
while since he's swung the way he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was hardly responsible for the loss, an unsightly
performance that featured three Mariner errors, two hit batsmen, a
wild pitch and a tie-breaking homer by Tampa Bay's Herbert Perry
off Frankie Rodriguez (2-4) in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   But he went hitless in five at-bats, four of the outs ending
innings, the last three with runners in scoring position. This
month, Rodriguez is batting .089, with just five hits in 56
at-bats. Since homering on Friday in Baltimore, he has been held to
one infield single in 24 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inexcusable, and quite honestly, it's embarrassing,''
Rodriguez said. `` ... It's been probably the biggest struggle I've
had in my young career. But what I'm enjoying about it is that it's
something I believe I can come out of. I have so much confidence in
my ability and my work ethic that everything's going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was reminded that the player who made the final out
Tuesday, Tampa Bay's Aaron Ledesma, had hurled his bat in disgust.
Rodriguez shrugged and considered the comparison. He is not prone
to outbursts _ though he did slam his bat to the dirt after popping
out in the fifth and worked out his frustration in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing the bat is not going to make it any better, it's not
going to relieve any stress or anything,'' Rodriguez said. ``Just
go out and work on my game, and that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes after the game, as most of his teammates were
leaving for the bus, Rodriguez was finishing a session in the
batting cage. Some players do that often; former Mariner David
Segui had trouble sleeping if he hadn't fixed his swing before
leaving the park. But Rodriguez takes postgame hitting only two or
three times a year, when he needs special attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's pressing,'' said hitting coach Jesse Barfield,
noting Rodriguez went through a similar stretch last September
before his 40th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``His swing is long _ Ray Charles can see that _ and he's flying
open the majority of the time. But he's a workaholic. As a matter
of fact, Wednesday he came out for extra work, and I had to tell
him to shut it down. I told him afterwards, `That's a compliment
for you, for a coach to have to tell a player to cut back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barfield and manager Lou Piniella believe Rodriguez is tired. He
has missed only one game since coming off the disabled list in
mid-May, and Piniella plans to rest him Thursday or Friday.
Mechanically, Barfield said, a player with tired legs relies on his
upper body, rushing instead of staying back in his stance.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-inning pop-up came on a high changeup from Wilson
Alvarez. Had Rodriguez been mechanically sound, the pitch would
have turned into his 38th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's on, you don't make a mistake like that,'' Barfield
said. ``If you gear toward right-center, anything middle-in like
that, especially a mistake, it's a dinger for him. It's a well-hit
ball, a line drive, and line drives for Alex are home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the season, starting Thursday in batting
practice, Barfield said he wants Rodriguez to concentrate on
hitting to the opposite field. He hasn't stopped hitting to right,
Barfield said, but by keeping that approach, Rodriguez's mechanics
are more likely to correct themselves. It takes a nearly perfect
swing to drive a ball out to right-center, Barfield told Rodriguez,
and the shortstop understood. He needs to get back in that habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I make my living,'' Rodriguez said. ``Any time I
get out of any type of funk, that's where I start hitting the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rodriguez will emerge from it, Barfield said, shaking his
head and smiling. There's no doubting that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he comes out of it,'' Barfield said, ``honestly, I feel
sorry for the pitchers he's going to face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
