<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-BOARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BOARD TO MEET ON ZACARIAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH   AND BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Stunned by an internal review of the Belmont
Learning Center, the Los Angeles Unified school board will
immediately evaluate Superintendent Ruben Zacarias' performance,
including accusations he failed to properly oversee the $200
million scandal, the Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Zacarias questioned the fairness of judging his
role in Belmont as outlined Tuesday by Don Mullinax, director of
the LAUSD Internal Audit and Special Investigations Unit. Several
Los Angeles Unified School District sources said the evaluation is
part of power struggle between Zacarias and the new reform board,
which feels the need to respond quickly to the scathing report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real infighting has begun, and it centers around who will
mete out the discipline to the employees mentioned by name in
Mullinax's report,'' said an administrator, who asked not to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a wounded superintendent who has been tarnished by
the report and a board with three new members above the fray.
Zacarias says essentially they are his employees and that he should
do any punishing. The board says he's tainted and shouldn't be
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax's findings _ that 16 current and former LAUSD officials
failed the district by allowing the nation's costliest high school
to be built downtown atop an oil field permeated with explosive
methane gas _ were disputed by three of those who face discipline,
including possible dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest defense came from Chief Counsel Richard K. Mason,
who blamed legal consultant David W. Cartwright and his firm,
O'Melveny and Myers, for the public works fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   O'Melveny, which investigators said should be sued by the
district for its role in Belmont, could not be reached immediately
for comment, but had previously denied misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   As the power struggle unfolded, several high-ranking sources in
the district, including two board members, told the Daily News that
the Board of Education will huddle this morning with outside legal
counsel to establish new parameters for Zacarias' job evaluation. A
review would begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Sales, a spokesman for the superintendent, said he was
unaware of the board's plans to discuss Zacarias' performance at
today's closed session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly within their purview to do it,'' Sales said.
``But given the fact that there is not an agreed-upon set of goals
and objectives for the superintendent, one wonders what form the
evaluation would take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly could not be based upon any objective measures
except for the (investigative) report. And that certainly is only
one small part of the superintendent's job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mullinax report charged that Zacarias ``failed to supervise
the Belmont project in a diligent, professional and effective
manner.'' Mullinax advised the school board to include his findings
in the superintendent's next evaluation, which had been expected to
take place in January.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax included Zacarias on a list of former and current
employees who failed to ``exercise proper management'' in the
Belmont project. The investigator told the board to discipline, if
not fire, the employees, including Chief Administrative Officer
David Koch and Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, a vocal critic of
Belmont, said Zacarias should be given a chance to take ``immediate
and decisive action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruben Zacarias has the information in his hands to hold senior
staff responsible for this fiasco. They all need to be fired,''
Wildman said. ``The stage is set for him to take action or suffer
the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   District policy calls for Zacarias, who became superintendent in
July 1997, to be evaluated on a yearly basis, with reviews to be
conducted each quarter. The ``expedited'' review would move up the
quarterly evaluation by a week.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda for today's meeting notes the board will discuss
``public employee discipline/dismissal/release.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member David Tokofsky said he had not been told his
colleagues were considering moving up the superintendent's job
evaluation or broadening the scope of the impending review to
include Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do evaluate him, I assume it will be a formative
evaluation, not a summative _ or do or die _ evaluation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tokofsky, who represents a constituency composed largely of
Latino residents, took heat in June when he refused to support a
move by lame-duck school board members to extend Zacarias'
contract.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Zacarias threatened he would resign if the new
reform-minded school board, which would take office one week later,
put its ``political agenda'' ahead of the district's educational
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias pledged to give the new board a chance to evaluate his
performance in January, saying he'd waive his fourth year ``if the
board members feel they cannot support me.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the Mullinax report Tuesday, Zacarias denied any
wrongdoing and argued he took steps to gain control of the project
when he took office.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent contended he quickly disbanded the Office of
Planning and Development, the branch overseeing the project.
However, the Office of Planning and Development was not disbanded
until February 1998, following the retirement of Dominic Shambra,
its director, eight months after Zacarias became superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales clarified Zacarias' statement Wednesday when asked about
the discrepancy. He said it took Zacarias time to shut the office
down.
</P>
<P>
   By several accounts, the Mullinax report took the school board
by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of well-thought-out decisions that need to be
made very soon,'' said board member Julie Korenstein. ``It's a lot
to digest and hard to respond to before we go through all the
materials.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
