<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINIELLA TAKES NOTE OF SINCLAIR'S HABIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ About halfway through his playing career,
Lou Piniella started taking notes. He kept a book detailing the
tendencies of the pitchers he faced and the way catchers called a
game, referring to it before he played and updating it regularly.
</P>
<P>
   As a manager, Piniella does the same thing, recording the
patterns of opposing managers, when they are likely to bunt, hit
and run, and so on. It is part of the preparation process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to encourage that to our players,'' the Mariners
manager said. ``The more prepared you are, the better, and you use
these team meetings here just to augment what you already have.''
</P>
<P>
   It encouraged Piniella, then, to learn of a purchase made by
rookie left-hander Steve Sinclair during the Mariners' weekend
series in Baltimore. Sinclair bought a notebook of his own, and
started filling it with details on the hitters he faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I just relied on the reports _ who was hot, who was
cold, and what our bullpen coach and pitching coach and advance
scout wrote out,'' Sinclair said. ``But that's what they saw
against a different pitcher, not against me. Now, I can have my own
personal notes on how (hitters) react to my pitching against them,
so I can use those.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair got the idea from casual conversations with Mariners
veteran Jamie Moyer, who has kept a book for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, with the Cubs and Rangers, Moyer, 36,
noticed the books hitters kept on pitchers. He didn't know exactly
how his teammates filled them out, but he thought it was worth a
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps, and it's a great reminder,'' Moyer said.
``But you still have to pitch. The book is just reminders, thoughts
and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitters can change, you can change as a pitcher. But it's a
lot of thoughts and ideas and experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair has had few experiences in the majors, and not enough
positive ones for his liking. In 13 games since being acquired from
Toronto in the David Segui trade July 28, Sinclair has walked nine
and allowed 12 hits in nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know over the next two weeks, I have to perform to my
capabilities and show the organization they got the man they
thought they were getting, show them I'm definitely going to help
this ballclub out,'' he said. ``Pitching-wise, I just have to
concentrate on each hitter, go right after them and let my stuff
get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will be watching his progress closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a nice arm,'' Piniella said. ``He's sneakier than I
thought he was. If he can master his control just a little bit more
and improve his breaking ball, there's no reason why he can't be a
usable left-hander out of the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners appear likely to pursue a left-hander in free
agency, but a spot could still be available for Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the left-handed hitters in this league, you need two
left-handers, one who's in a setup role where he can come in and be
a specialty pitcher, and one who can eat up 2-3-4 innings and keep
you in a ballgame,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES: Right-hander Brett Hinchliffe, who relieved starter
Ken Cloude in the fourth inning, threw 22/3 scoreless innings
before leaving with discomfort in his rib cage. ... The Mariners
were without relievers Jose Paniagua (groin) and Tom Davey (forearm
tendinitis) Wednesday night. Paniagua said he expects to return
Thursday night. ... Right-hander Denny Stark made his major league
debut, striking out Bobby Smith on a slider before allowing three
singles. ``I'm a little disappointed that after I did get that
first strikeout, I wasn't able to finish the inning,'' Stark said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
