<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4045 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-H     09-16 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
And on the 13th day, the streak ended.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies capitalized on a bullpen breakdown
Wednesday, scoring two runs in the 10th inning _ after pushing
across three in the eighth _ for an 8-6 victory at the Astrodome
that snapped the Astros' club-record 12-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' lead over second-place Cincinnati in the National
League Central Division was reduced to three games. The Reds beat
the Chicago Cubs 5-4 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After reeling off 12 straight victories _ the second-longest
streak in the majors this season _ the Astros suffered their first
loss since they fell to the New York Mets on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Glanville had a career-high five hits as the Phillies
snapped an 11-game losing skid and won for just the second time in
20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by two runs, the Astros tied the score at 6 in the
ninth inning of a game that featured three lead changes. Relievers
Jay Powell and Doug Henry combined to allow five runs and seven
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're counting on Henry and Powell to be setup men. We can't
get it done with three starters and (Billy) Wagner,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ``Obviously, I didn't push the right buttons
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen had not allowed a run in 19 innings prior to the
eighth inning. It was only the third time in 74 games the Astros
have lost when leading after the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the scored tied at 6, Glanville opened the 10th with a
single off Henry (2-3) and stole second. Following a one-out walk
to Bobby Abreu, Mike Lieberthal drove in the go-ahead run with a
double to left field. Rico Brogna added a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied the game in the ninth with two runs off Wayne
Gomes (5-5) _ with help from shortstop Desi Relaford.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett led off with a single and stole second. Ken
Caminiti, who drove in three runs, rapped an infield single to deep
short that Relaford threw away, allowing a run to score. Jeff
Bagwell reached on an infield single, and Tony Eusebio walked
before Paul Bako grounded into a double play as Caminiti scored.
</P>
<P>
   With Bagwell representing the winning run on third, however,
Ricky Gutierrez grounded out to third base to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After the Phillies regained the lead, Billy Brewer retired two
batters in the 10th for his first save of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Relaford started a one-out rally with a double
into the right-field corner and pinch hitter Alex Arias tied the
game at 4 with a triple. Glanville and Lieberthal added run-scoring
singles.
</P>
<P>
   Glanville homered, doubled and singled three times to finish
5-for-6.
</P>
<P>
   The loss overshadowed a gutsy effort by Scott Elarton, who
struck out a career-high 10 batters as he overcame a career-high
five walks, including four in the third inning that put him in an
early hole.
</P>
<P>
   Bothered by a sore shoulder most of the second half of the
season, Elarton allowed three runs and five hits before leaving
after six innings with a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the winning streak) had to end sometime,'' Elarton said.
``Unfortunately, we had a lot of chances to win. We'll just have to
start another streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti hit a two-run homer to straightway center field in the
first inning and a sacrifice fly in the fifth that tied the score
at 3. Later in the inning, Lance Berkman gave the Astros the lead
with an RBI single to center on a ball Glanville caught up to but
failed to hold.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman was cut down trying for second base.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies scored in the second when Lieberthal walked and
came around on singles by Rico Brogna and Kevin Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton's control problems put him on the ropes in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Glanville ripped a home run off the left-field scoreboard to
lead off and, following a strikeout of Ron Gant, Elarton walked
Abreu, Brogna and Jordan to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Anderson then walked to give the Phillies a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Elarton allowed only two hits while striking
out six of the next 10 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Bill Spiers gave the Astros a spark when he slid
into first to beat out a bunt single. Everett followed with a
double to put runners in scoring position, and Caminiti and Berkman
produced the runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
