<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNATIONAL-CRICKET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRICKET MAKING HISTORY IN L.A.'S SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Add another first for Los Angeles' San Fernando
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The first international cricket match broadcast live from North
America began Wednesday at Woodley Avenue Park in the Valley
community of Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   It drew only about 200 spectators. But organizers expect more
than half a billion people worldwide to tune in their TVs to watch
the five-day competition, with Woodley Park taking center stage as
perhaps the finest cricket field in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the field is one of the few not to use artificial
turf _ a no-no on the cricket circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes years to develop a field like this,'' said Atul Rai,
president of the Southern California Cricket Association. ``It is
beautifully maintained with tight, low-cut grass and no artificial
turf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is talk around the world that Los Angeles could be the
next cricket hot spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The match will be broadcast to scores of nations, including the
cricket-playing countries of England, Singapore, Australia and
Pakistan, Rai said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are billions of fans around the world,'' he said.
``They've been waiting for this for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cricket is similar to baseball, but is played on a circular
field. The game uses bats, balls and pitchers _ called bowlers.
Like baseball, a player is ``out'' when a fielder catches a ball or
when a runner is tagged between bases.
</P>
<P>
   The object is for the batsman to protect two wickets _ bits of
wood balanced on top of three vertical poles _ from the bowler who
is attempting to knock them down. The batsman protects them by
hitting the ball and running between the wickets, like running
bases, to score points.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional games used to be held over a five-day period, but
most games now have been shortened to a one-day version, Rai said.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the five-day tournament between Australia and
India, the top two international teams, hope the historic event
will make Americans ``mad keen'' for what once was an upper-class
British game.
</P>
<P>
   But many local fans don't need to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this is happening here. It's such a good
day,'' said cricket fan Sami Patel, 46. ``It's an exciting sport,
and to be able to come to an international event in the Valley is
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like the culmination of a dream, and it was a long
time coming,'' said Clifford Severn, 73, who has been playing
cricket in the Valley since he was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need this to go big in Los Angeles, and the United States,
because people around the world look here for the best-of-the-best.
That will make it even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian team captain Adam Gilchrist said he hopes the game
plants its American roots in Woodley Park _ and that the craze
catches on quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Americans fall in love with cricket, that will spring it
forward around the world,'' Gilchrist said. ``I think it can be
done here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's kickoff of the AXN American Challenge, presented by
the International Cricket Council, was one of the most anticipated
international sporting events of the year, Rai said. The tournament
is sponsored by AXN, part of the Sony Television Group, which is
funding the $15,000 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong event comes complete with an Australian television
crew and a popular Australian announcer, Ian Chappell, who will
provide play-by-play analysis.
</P>
<P>
   While cricket fever hasn't caught on in Los Angeles, it's not
entirely foreign in Southern California. Schoolchildren from the
Sheenway School and Culture Center in Watts and from Allesandro
Elementary School in Silver Lake have had cricket programs for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the kids came to the opening day and showed their stuff
on the field while the players took a lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing cricket for a year and it's really cool,''
said 9-year-old Jessica Santa Cruz from Allesandro Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play because I want to learn a new game, not the boring old
sports,'' said 16-year-old Yvette Villalobos from Sheenway School.
``It's fun and it's just as exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the game's excitement, cricket teaches lessons in
morality, discipline and acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great game for kids to learn. There is rigid
discipline, and everyone is treated the same,'' Rai said. ``In the
game, if a player is out he can't even look at the referee funny or
he will be fined.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Sheen, executive director of the Sheenway School, said
cricket helps teach her students equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to call it the common denominator. Everyone is equal in
cricket. There are no winners or losers,'' Sheen said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that cricket allows kids to keep the ``dignity'' that
other sports take away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football and basketball are so competitive and have racial and
skill divisions that aren't good to teach kids,'' Sheen said.
``There are no color barriers in cricket, and it emphasizes
involvement for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great game, and I hope it takes off here.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
