<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT AS GAME SLIPS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With everything that went wrong this season, the
Los Angeles Dodgers might have lost their mental health, but
physically, among the regulars, they remained healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Then right-hander Darren Dreifort left his start mid-batter in
the fifth inning Wednesday night with tightness in his pitching
shoulder. He will be evaluated today and his status for his next
start is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fine,'' said Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, who
was on the phone before Dreifort reached the top step of the
dugout. ``It's day to day, but we believe with an off-day
(today)... he'll be able to make his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how he feels. We're not going to risk the future of
one of our starters in the last two weeks of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   For the diehards, the Montreal Expos scored seven times in the
sixth and beat the Dodgers 10-7 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek left with a bruise on his right hand after
being hit with a pitch in the sixth inning. It's the same hand he
broke in June. He is listed as day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, making sure Dreifort wasn't seriously injured was the
Dodgers' top priority.
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy discussion with manager Davey Johnson and
trainer Charlie Strasser, Dreifort left after 63 pitches. There was
a runner on first and an 0-1 count to Trace Coquillette.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's in the midst of his best season as a professional. He
was in the midst of his best stretch since converting to a starter
last season, but Malone felt that was part of the problem.
Dreifort, 27, is also approaching a career-high in innings pitched
and has averaged better than 72/3 innings in his last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be just fatigue,'' Malone said. ``He's pitched a lot
lately. He's been going eight or nine innings in his starts. He's
not used to that. I'm sure it's just that his shoulder is a little
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse the Dodgers if they're quick to remove Dreifort when he
feels the slightest bit of discomfort, but they have good reason.
Anything pertaining to his pitching arm is going to be closely
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort missed the 1995 season after having reconstructive
surgery to repair a torn medial collateral ligament in his right
elbow, and the arm hasn't bounced back quickly after pitching
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort pitched a career-high 180 innings last season, which is
was more innings then he amassed in his previous three major-league
seasons. But Dreifort didn't pitch after a Sept. 4 start against
San Francisco because of soreness in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a breakout season for Dreifort. The right-hander
is 13-13, and with one more victory, will match his career-win
total entering the season. And though his 4.79 ERA doesn't reflect
it, Dreifort has pitched so well lately that Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said Dreifort will return to the rotation next year.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching four-plus innings against the Expos at Chavez
Ravine, Dreifort's inning total was 1782/3. He's already made a
career-high 29 starts.
</P>
<P>
   But the disappointing thing for the Dodgers is that Dreifort's
being removed from the game means they'll have to keep a closer eye
on his the rest of this season, if he returns. His final few starts
were also supposed to work toward his development as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort began his run of success with a complete-game shutout
against Florida on Aug. 18. It started a stretch in which he won
four of five starts and had a 2.08 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving with tightness in his shoulder against the Expos,
Dreifort had pitched at least seven innings in each of his last
five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos were shaping up to be the sixth in that line. Dreifort
allowed a one-out RBI single to Michael Barrett that tied the score
1-1 in the second inning, but the Dodgers took a 2-1 lead in the
bottom of the inning when Dreifort scored on right-fielder Vladimir
Guerrero's throwing error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
