<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     09-16 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX TRIPS ENDS EXTRA SPECIAL 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ After 13 days, a dozen games, nearly 7,000 air miles
and waking up one too many mornings in strange hotel rooms trying
to recall what city they were in, the road-weary Sons of Jimy
Williams ended their longest trip of the season with their longest
night.
</P>
<P>
   But their willingness to work overtime _ the Red Sox came from a
run behind in the ninth to tie the score on Trot Nixon's sacrifice
fly and stayed alive on a play in the 11th by forgotten Jeff Frye _
ended not only in exhaustion but exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs by Jason Varitek, the ironman catcher who barely had
enough energy left to circle the bases, and rookie Trot Nixon in
the 13th inning Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night lifted the Sox to a 6-4 win over
the Cleveland Indians, who will be their first-round playoff
opponents if matters remain status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing hard, that's about all we can do,'' said
Varitek, who singled in the ninth to put pinch runner Donnie Sadler
in position to score the tying run on Nixon's fly ball, then broke
a 4-4 tie when he just cleared the right-field wall with his 17th
home run, off loser Jim Brower (1-1). ``Play hard and try to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Indians) don't have to win right now. They're already
locked in (to a playoff spot). They're able to let things happen.
There's no pressure on them to win, so they're a little free and
easy about things. We have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On a night when ace Pedro Martinez struck out 14 batters in
seven innings but saw his bullpen unable to protect a one-run
advantage, the Sox emptied their bench to beat the Indians in the
rubber game of this three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   And on a trip they expected to give definition to their October
aspirations, the Sox compiled a 9-3 record for a 3 1/2-game lead
over idle Oakland in the wild-card race. With 16 games left,
including the next 10 at home, the Sox are 3 1/2 games behind the
Yankees in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know when they play the Red Sox, they're in for a
battle,'' said Frye. ``We may not be the best team on paper, but
that team doesn't always win.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye, who has been buried deep on the Sox bench since forcing
the team to recall him from injury rehabilitation at the start of
the month, entered as a pinch runner in the 10th, remained in the
game at second base, and made a diving stop with two on and two out
in the 11th on Omar Vizquel's bid for a winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't forgotten Frito, he's never forgotten,'' Martinez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does this game say? We never give up. We've shown it the
whole year. We're a little team, and we're overlooked a lot because
we don't have the big names, but we have players who never give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's home run was his fourth in the last five games,
including one in each of the three games here. The home runs by
Varitek and Nixon made a winner out of John Wasdin (8-3), the fifth
Sox pitcher, who finished with a Martinez-like flourish, striking
out three Indians in his two innings after spelling Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, who entered in the ninth, pitched three innings for only
the second time since Oct. 4, 1992, and first time since he went
three against the Dodgers Sept. 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felt pretty good,'' Beck said. ``Got the elbow working. Let's
see how fast this time I blow it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the conspiracy theory put forth by Williams after the
first game of this series, there was no electronic eye in center
field Wednesday night, tipping off the Indians what pitches
Martinez was throwing.
</P>
<P>
   These days, of course, it's an open question whether that would
be an advantage. Chances are Martinez could hold up flash cards on
the mound, or have it broadcast over the public address system what
was coming plateward, and most hitters still wouldn't have a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians were no different than anybody else
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, though they did something no team has been able
to do against Martinez in almost two months.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland pushed two runs across in one inning, the fourth,
ending a string of 51 innings, spanning eight starts, in which
Martinez had allowed no more than a run.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians then waited until Martinez departed to take a 4-3
lead, scoring twice in the eighth against relievers Rheal Cormier
and Rich Garces. Cormier gave up a two-out single to Jim Thome, his
old hunting buddy. After pinch runner David Roberts stole second,
Garces walked Richie Sexson on a full count, then gave up an
opposite-field double off the left-field wall to Tyler Houston, who
has had just 10 at-bats with the Indians since arriving from the
Cubs in a waiver deal Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was playing in place of regular third baseman Travis
Fryman, who was given a powder against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, however, rallied to tie in the ninth against Indians
closer Mike Jackson. Scott Hatteberg, serving as designated hitter
for the first time this season and becoming the ninth DH to start
for Williams in 1999, beat out an infield hit to deep short, his
second infield hit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Has Hatteberg, a catcher by trade, ever had two infield hits in
a game?
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that, a rhetorical question?'' he cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler ran for Hatteberg and sped to third on Varitek's single
through the right side. Pinch hitter Reggie Jefferson struck out,
but Nixon delivered Sadler with his fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get him early,'' Nixon said of Jackson. ``He's got
that slider and splitter, so that's why I jumped on the first
pitch. I knew all I needed was a fly ball with Donnie over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams used 15 position players, winding up with an infield of
Offerman at first, Frye at second, and Lou Merloni at third.
Offerman had given Martinez a 2-0 lead with a two-run homer off
Bartolo Colon in the third, then after the Indians tied it in the
fourth on a double, a bunt single, an infield hit, and a sacrifice
fly, Offerman's infield out after two walks and a wild pitch put
the Sox ahead in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been proud of them all year,'' Williams said of his team.
``This is our longest trip, I guess. But the main thing is we can't
let up. We can take a day off tomorrow, but then we have to get
prepared to play another team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS TREATED TO ALL THE SIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It took 14 strikeouts and 131 pitches from Pedro. It
took a ninth-inning, tying sacrifice fly from Trot Nixon. It took a
sliding 11th-inning catch by Damon Buford. It took a game-saving
dive, pop up, and throw by Jeff Frye (making his first appearance
of a two-week trip in the 10th inning of the 12th and final game).
It took four relief pitchers. It took solo home runs in the 13th
inning by Jason Varitek and Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   It took every bit of Jimy Williams's managerial acumen. It took
15 position players. It took 4 hours 40 minutes. It took the last
hours of Wednesday and the first quarter hour of Thursday. But it
was all worth it.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-inning, 6-4 victory over the Cleveland Indians to wrap up a
9-3 road trip? Who's kidding whom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I think we'd go 9 and 3?'' inquired Pedro Martinez, whose
seven innings of two-run ball resulted in his third no-decision of
the season. ``Yes, I would have said it was possible. It was a
matter of staying focused and staying healthy, and we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox left home two weeks ago Thursday two games ahead of
the Oakland A's in the wild-card race. They return up by 3 1/2.
They won three in Seattle, one in Oakland, three in New York, and
two in Cleveland. It will go down as one of the great road trips in
Red Sox history. Regardless of what happens from here on out _ and
with the perilous state of their starting pitching beyond Pedro,
anything could happen _ no one will ever be able to take away from
this gritty bunch the grandeur of a 9-3 September road trip,
culminating in what can only be described as a pennant race epic.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were four outs away from victory, leading by a 3-2
score with two away and no one on base in the eighth. But Jim Thome
bounced a single through the hole, chasing Rheal Cormier. Williams
summoned the usually reliable Rich Garces, but Richie Sexson worked
him for a base on balls and Tyler Houston brought both base runners
home with a double off the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The fun was just beginning. Scott Hatteberg, strangely inserted
as the designated hitter, led off the ninth with an infield single
to short. Varitek, rapidly gaining the reputation as the team's
``Mr. Clutch,'' rammed a single to right, sending pinch runner
Donnie Sadler to third. After pinch hitter Reggie Jefferson fanned,
Nixon hit the first pitch he saw from Cleveland closer Mike Jackson
for a professional sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck worked the next three innings, but not without a little
drama. The great moment of trepidation came when Enrique Wilson hit
a low liner to center with one away in the 11th. Buford, a fearless
chap, came racing in, sliding on his keister while blowing a bubble
as the ball settled into his glove. Had he missed the ball, Mr.
Wilson had a three-bagger, minimum, and maybe even an
inside-the-parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a reaction,'' explained Buford, who also claimed he had
no idea about the bubble-blowing bit until someone told him they
had seen it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The catch looked even bigger when Einar Diaz and Kenny Lofton
followed with singles. That brought up the dangerous Omar Vizquel,
who already had three hits, and who had tormented Pedro way back
when by working him for 18 pitches in his first two at-bats.
Vizquel smashed a ball to Frye's left, and this baby definitely had
RBI single inscribed all over it.
</P>
<P>
   But Frye ranged to his left, hit the deck, caught the ball, and
threw out the speedy Vizquel by a half-step at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to keep it in the infield,'' Frye shrugged.
``If I get him out, it's a bonus, right there.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving two on in the 12th, the Red Sox moved into the
13th against righthander Jim Brower. The leadoff man was Varitek,
who had just caught 12 innings and what appeared to be 11,432
pitches. He could have been forgiven had he taken three gentlemanly
swings and then returned to the dugout. Instead, he whacked an 0-1
offering into the right-field seats for his 17th home run of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't enough ways to describe what Jason has meant to
this team,'' gushed Martinez. ``I'd say he's right there with Nomar
for the most valuable player on the club. If I had to choose, it
would be a very tough decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason is unbelievable,'' agreed Buford. ``He's the Iron Horse
back there.''
</P>
<P>
   The win went to John Wasdin, the early-season good luck charm
whose entrance into a game usually causes Fenway regulars to reach
for the cyanide pellets. But this time Wasdin was The Man, working
two very nice innings.
</P>
<P>
   This victory was a true Jimy Williams special. ``We got
contributions from a lot of people,'' he pointed out. ``But that's
why they have the expanded rosters, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   So much happened after Pedro departed that you almost forgot he
had casually fanned 14 men in his seven innings. But it was Pedro
himself who summed up the real meaning of both the team's 84th
victory of the season and the spectacular 9-3 road trip. ``This
game shows how we never give up,'' he declared. ``We're a little
team, always underrated. We always play as a team. We keep on
proving it, and proving it, and proving it.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time it was well into Thursday morning, and there was
nothing anyone could say to challenge him. The game and the trip
had spoken for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 0240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
