<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4087 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     09-16 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPS PROTECT S.F. FROM SANDWICHES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You can still find drugs, cheap booze, cheaper
sex and assorted trouble and misery in the Tenderloin and around
the Civic Center. But for now, folks who live in and drift through
that part of town are safe from the menace of the Saturday
Free-Lunch Gang.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years, the cops finally launched an overdue
crackdown on a group of high school kids from the mean streets of
Marin who sneak across the bay every Saturday and hand out
sandwiches to the homeless in Civic Center and U.N. plazas.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, a student at the Branson School, a private
school in Ross, noticed that she and her friends usually had food.
She also noticed that homeless people in San Francisco often
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   So she and friends started ``Homeless Sandwiches.'' Every Friday
afternoon, they made hundreds of sandwiches, and every Saturday
morning, they took the ferry to the city, set up tables in one of
the plazas and fed 300 or so people. Free.
</P>
<P>
   Until last Saturday, when a police SWAT unit (Sandwich Worker
Assault Team) swooped in.
</P>
<P>
   One officer told the kids they had to move it, sorry, but orders
from above. Another, also friendly, told 'em the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   So the gang moved out of Civic Center Plaza, a couple blocks to
Hyde &AMP; McAllister, and set up shop.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, no fewer than seven police officers and a
lieutenant arrived at the crime scene and shut down the notorious
sandwich gang.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 students and four adults were told they didn't have the
proper permits and were committing several health code violations.
</P>
<P>
   One police officer got into the food line and said that by the
time he got to the front of the line, the operation better be shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   So they split. ``Homeless Sandwiches'' suddenly found itself
holding about 500 homeless sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is why the cops let this gang run wild in the
inner city for seven years, terrorizing inhabitants with free
lunches.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Police Lt. Paul Chignell, who recognized the
danger these kids posed to the community and spearheaded the
shutdown task force, referred me to his captain, saying, ``I don't
talk to The Chronicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess who just got crossed off my Christmas-card list?
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau said that he was looking into the
situation and that he told one student's parent, ``It's not a crime
to feed the homeless.'' He vowed to help the students get needed
permits and said he would urge his officers to act with
``compassion and common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown's spokesperson, Kandace Bender, said the
mayor is absolutely in favor of people, especially young people,
getting involved in civic-minded volunteer projects.
</P>
<P>
   But Bender said the students would be encouraged to go to an
established agency like, for example, Glide Memorial Church, and
volunteer their services, so people who come for meals can also be
exposed to a full range of services to assist the down-and-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor's office is happy to find a way to help them put
their energy and contributions to use,'' Bender said, ``because
those are admirable qualities. If they want to contact the mayor's
office, we're happy to work with them, find a place where they can
distribute food.''
</P>
<P>
   The student coordinator of ``Homeless Sandwiches,'' senior
Morgan Cosby, says she has worked at Glide and isn't interested in
going that route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're people helping people,'' she says. As opposed to people
helping other people help people.
</P>
<P>
   I could write a book about what I don't know about high school
students, but I know this: They don't like to be patted on the head
and told to report to the nearest adult.
</P>
<P>
   High school kids aren't kids. They are new adults who are
stumbling along, discovering incredible and creative ways to screw
up and to do good. On their own.
</P>
<P>
   Society keeps asking, ``What do high school students do when
they're not machine-gunning one another down in the hallways?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Homeless Sandwiches'' was one answer to that question.
</P>
<P>
   It's the students' thing, this little sandwich giveaway. They
invented it, they've kept it going, with minimal adult help.
</P>
<P>
   But after talking to Bender, the Health Dept. and the P.D., I'm
convinced that the city's master plan is to get these kids off the
streets and into a shelter.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen now is that either the cops and the city work
with the students and let them resume their sandwich biz under
their own leadership, or ... well, high schoolers can be a terrible
pain in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Cosby what will happen next Saturday, she said,
``We're going back and serving again.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope this gets worked out, that it doesn't come down to
sandwich-sniffing dogs and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   But if these young folks do get busted, instead of being sent up
the river, maybe they can be enrolled in a sandwich offender
diversion program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
