<SLUG> BC-BROWN-MAYOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 S.F. MAYOR REGALES D.C. WITH TALES OF THE CITY  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the nation's capital to raise money for his
re-election, Mayor Willie Brown painted an uproarious picture of
San Francisco politics Wednesday to a rapt audience of Washington
dignitaries who paid $500 each to see the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Brown mixed anecdotes and one-liners from his four-year journey
into municipal government before members of Congress, a Cabinet
secretary, the head of the AFL-CIO, the mayor of Washington, D.C.,
and other supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mineola, you only get bitten by one snake,'' he said,
referring to his hometown in Texas. ``In San Francisco, there are
780,000 of them that bite you.''
</P>
<P>
   To sustained laughter, Brown complained of his difficult
transition from state to local politics and described the 67
debates he participated in during his 1995 mayoral campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-seven debates _ with the same damn audience,'' he said.
``These people have no life. They just show up for anything
political. ... Now I don't have 67 stories. I don't have 67
responses. I just kept making s_ up.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown revealed his secret to answering questions to which he
doesn't know the answer: ``I use a little bit of ebonics ... and
then come to the punch line.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor poked fun at his rivals _ former Mayor Frank Jordan
and political consultant Clint Reilly _ and explained why he was
more combative in the second of two recent mayoral debates.
</P>
<P>
   In the first debate, which he described as ``mud wrestling,''
Brown said he calmly endured the ``vicious'' attacks of his
opponents because he wanted to remain above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the local media accused him of acting ``imperial,''
and during a walk through the Fillmore _ ``that's the 'hood,'' he
explained _ he noticed that African Americans were turning their
back on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter?'' Brown asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You let those white boys kick your ass,'' they responded.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he did not want to be seen as ``some sort of cream
puff,'' so he made sure he was ready to fight back in the second
debate and even packed the audience with his own vocal supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everyone who could get a work furlough,'' he said to
laughter, adding that the next day he was attacked by the media for
nearly inciting a riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work is cut out for me,'' he said, bemoaning his relations
with the local press.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 people attended the event at the posh Mayflower Hotel,
munching on muffins and cantaloupe as Brown delivered his 20-minute
monologue. The fund-raiser was put together by Eve Maldanado, San
Francisco's Washington lobbyist. A $500 contribution was requested,
though organizers said they did not know how much money was raised.
</P>
<P>
   Among the event's hosts were California Sens. Dianne Feinstein
and Barbara Boxer, and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
None was present.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein _ who, as San Francisco's mayor, appointed Frank
Jordan as police chief in 1986 and endorsed him for re-election in
the 1995 mayoral campaign against Brown _ endorsed Brown earlier
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   During his talk, Brown also gave a litany of anecdotes of his
encounters with San Francisco residents.
</P>
<P>
   He told of the woman who woke him up at 2:30 a.m. to complain
that her streetlight wasn't working. Brown said he took her number
and told her not to worry. After making certain the light was
working the next night, Brown set his alarm for 2:30 a.m. and
phoned the woman back, just to make sure her problem was solved.
</P>
<P>
   Brown told of a debate in the Mission neighborhood where a dog
owner told him that the community was deeply divided over whether a
neighborhood park should be used for ``off-leash'' dog runs or for
children playing soccer. He then demanded the mayor's position.
</P>
<P>
   After a moment of ``total and complete panic,'' Brown said he
responded: ``Be kind, I'm really trying to keep my job. And there's
no way I can keep my job if I answer this question.''
</P>
<P>
   And he told a story of a forum in Bernal Heights, where a woman
kept complaining that she had to wait too long to get her
prescription filled at her local drug store. The woman persisted
after Brown repeatedly told her he could do nothing about it.
Finally, Brown said he interrupted the event to tell her: ``Ma'am,
you've convinced me _ you absolutely need your medication.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Brown posed with members of the California
delegation who had served with him in the Assembly, including Reps.
Barbara Lee, D-Oakland; Maxine Waters, D-Los Angeles; Sam Farr,
D-Carmel; Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Los Angeles; and Grace
Napolitano, D-Norwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco; Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.;
Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas; and Chaka Fattah, D-Pa., also attended
the event. Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater was on hand to
pay his respects, saying Brown was a perfect ambassador for San
Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
