<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX     09-16 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Deteriorating language, deteriorating discourse
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question for today is: Is what passes for public discourse
in this country ruining the English language, or is what passes for
the English language in this country ruining public discourse?
</P>
<P>
   The answer _ and here, in a most unwriterly manner, I blow any
chance of creating suspense that just might sustain reader pursuit
of the outcome _ the answer is I don't know. On the other hand, I
do care.
</P>
<P>
   There are two increasingly annoying cases in point _
``experimenting with drugs'' and ``the gay lifestyle.'' Actually,
three. We'll get to the third in a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experimenting with drugs'' is verbal murk invented by
politicians who have been found out or who, confessing and of
course contrite, want to pre-empt before they are outed.
</P>
<P>
   Look, people who experiment with drugs work in laboratories and
wear white coats and do strange and perhaps untoward things to mice
who don't know what hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else has either used drugs _ some more, some less _ or
hasn't used drugs. No politician _ none, not one _ ever
experimented with drugs. They either smoked or snorted or shot up
dope, or rolled around naked in it for all I know, or they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   (There is, sort of, a third way. I am the only person on Earth
who believes the student Bill Clinton really didn't inhale. It
would be just like him. ``Gee, all the others are toking and I
don't want to look like a square but one day I'll run for high
office, so _ oops. Here comes the joint. I know what I'll do!'')
</P>
<P>
   For the record, and to be completely honest, I want to say
plainly here that I have never experimented with drugs. I don't
even own a white coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gay lifestyle'' is another of those
nails-on-the-blackboard screechers that shrivel the spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase is a dodge that seems somehow to be pretending to
politesse but is only an avoidance, a prissy way of not saying
someone is homosexual but is ``living the gay lifestyle.'' As if
living in Chicago, say, were not quite the same as being a
Chicagoan.
</P>
<P>
   There is no gay lifestyle. (There is a Chicago.) Some gays are
rich, some poor. Some are flamboyant, some mousey. Some have been
with their partners for decades; some play the field. Some sell
insurance; some work high steel.
</P>
<P>
   And, while we're at it, no one ``happens'' to be gay. You might
happen to be in Miami when it rains, but you don't happen to be
gay, or black or Jewish. These are not atmospheric randoms that
strike folks here and there, like falling tree limbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happens'' _ the third case in point _ is a patronizing and
pitying word deployed by majorities to half excuse minorities for
inconsiderately failing to be one of them: The poor dears can't
help it.
</P>
<P>
   For the record again, I do not happen to be white. My parents
planned it this way.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE _ In a recent column, I wrote that federal agents were
killed trying to serve arrest warrants on the Branch Davidian cult
in Waco. The agents had an arrest warrant prepared but were serving
a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
