u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-16 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Thursday, Sept. 16, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAIL-CLASSES (San Francisco) _ The classes were intended to
teach jail inmates their civil rights, but in the eyes of their
jailers, they went too far, turning into a crash course that taught
the students how to conceal their crimes and thwart police
investigations. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT NEWS (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-GAYS (Undated) _ Gay characters were found on a variety of TV
shows last season, barely raising an eyebrow and not generating
protests from notoriously trigger-happy fringe groups. But as any
gay person who watches television can attest, being accepted is one
thing, how you're portrayed is another. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-GEEKS ((Undated) _ Television was once dominated by a
strict demarcation: half-hour entertainment shows were usually
comedies, and one-hour programs were almost always dramas. Now,
there are no lines, as one-hour sitcoms (sans laugh tracks) abound,
and drama is crammed into half-hour shows like ``Sports Night.''
Then there is ``Freaks and Geeks,'' a one-hour comedy that scares
the bejesus out of anyone my age. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at ``Forces of Nature'' and
``The Prince of Egypt,'' which are being released on video. By
BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE (San Francisco) _ Beware the evil engines of
e-commerce. That's the message Douglas Rushkoff is bringing to
Silicon Valley _ the birthplace of e-commerce _ to promote his new
book, ``Coercion: Why We Listen to What `They' Say.'' One Valley
trade publication has already labeled the book the ``Blair Witch
Project'' of the e-commerce industry. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RICE (Undated) _ Spice it, sauce it, roll it, wrap it up.
Rice isn't just for steaming anymore. Winners of a recent contest
pulled out all the stops in creating new recipes for the world's
favorite starch. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   W/ FOOD-RICE-RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-INJURIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Thousands of children under the
age of 15 end up in the emergency room each year because of sports
injuries, from concussions to broken bones. As the school year gets
under way, health experts are reminding young athletes, their
coaches and parents to play it safe, especially during the start of
the fall sports season when many injuries, such as pulled muscles,
are more apt to happen. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   SCIFI-WRITERS (Delmar, N.Y.) _ On a quiet suburban side street,
in a nondescript white bungalow, veteran science fiction authors
George Zebrowski and Pamela Sargent have transformed their modest
home into a formidable writing factory. He plants himself in a
cramped, book-lined study in the front of the house and she is
rooted at a computer in a book-stuffed office in the back of the
house. Anchoring the isthmus between the partners' writerly spaces
is a spare bedroom overrun with thousands of scientific reference
books. BY PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   LION-KEEPER (San Francisco) _ For nearly a half-century, Jack
Castor has reigned supreme at the Lion House at the San Francisco
Zoo. On Friday, the era of Jack the Big Cat Keeper comes to a
bittersweet end. Visitors will have a last chance Friday to witness
Castor's legendary showmanship as he hand-feeds his beloved lions
and tigers. Then, he'll hang up his meat hook, lock the doors of
the Lion House and say goodbye to the zoo after exactly 48 years on
the job. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   RITA-MORENO (San Francisco) _ There are street clothes. And
there are gig clothes. And for entertainers such as Rita Moreno,
never the twain shall (or should) meet. We're talkin' flash here as
opposed to Polartech. We're discussing soigne fashion instead of
functional sweats. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-OAKLAND-A'S (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ Major League Baseball's
concerns about the long-term economic state of its game, in
addition to some behind-closed-doors politics, doomed former A's
executive Andy Dolich and Modesto supermarket magnate Bob
Piccinini's $122.4 million bid to buy the Oakland A's. Baseball
owners voted 28-2 on Wednesday to table any discussion of the
club's sale. By BRIAN MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Emerging from a squinty-eyed,
head-pounding, kill-me-now hangover from the worst game of his
professional career, Steve Young came as close as he gets to being
fighting mad. Mad at himself for playing so poorly, at his
teammates for not playing much better and at Hurricane Floyd for
not dropping in on Jacksonville sooner so the whole mess of an
opening game could be postponed until March or canceled outright.
By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Gun Exchange is
having a going-out-of-business sale, only partly because of
California's new gun laws. It's a personal decision by owners Beth
and Bob Posner, who inherited the 52-year-old store from their
father, the late Nate Posner. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ I can't get these creationists out
of my face. They've been at me, off and on, for weeks now with
letters and e-mails and phone calls. Some are bright and thoughtful
_ although wrong. Others are angry and utterly uninformed in their
wrongness. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
