<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Staying prepared for hurricanes
 &HT;    (For release Sept. 19, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ We are the lucky ones; Hurricane Floyd gave South
Florida the brushoff and headed for points north. But, as the good
people of the Carolinas are aware, you can't let your guard down _
two storms, Dennis and Floyd, in less than one month with half a
hurricane season still to go.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, whatever state of preparedness my home is in
today (for Floyd) will stay that way until such time as I sense a
seasonal all-clear. In anticipation of Hurricane Floyd, our
shutters went up, the patio furniture was moved into the living
room, potted plants and hoses relocated to the garage and pounds
upon pounds of useless patio junk stuffed into drawstring kitchen
bags in hope that my wife soon will allow me to move it out to the
curb for garbage pickup.
</P>
<P>
   With another hurricane, Gert, lurking near the Antilles,
anything is possible, despite weather forecasters predicting Gert
will turn north and on to oblivion. And so I maintain my
self-imposed ``red alert'' _ except for the plants, which I moved
outside.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear, though, that many in South Florida are standing
in place as well. In my neighborhood, which was ground zero during
Hurricane Andrew in 1992, most homes still have their shutters up,
and while I did not go around to sneak a peek at patios, I would
surmise that the redwood chaise lounge from the pool area is now
stationed in some hallway until the hurricane season wanes.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for a hurricane is a totally arduous task, followed by
the mental anguish as the storm gets closer. In readying my home
for Floyd, I spent the better part of two days putting up shutters,
lugging plants and taking down flower boxes, and just when I
thought I was through, there was something else.
</P>
<P>
   The freezer is filled with gallon-sized jugs of water, not for
drinking but for keeping the freezer cold if and when the power
goes out. I'm not going to remove them, either; not until all those
orange and red splotches disappear from the Weather Channel's radar
image.
</P>
<P>
   (As an aside on hurricane fashion, it has not escaped my notice
that television reporters standing at the gusty beach fronts or
before downed trees are wearing blue rain gear this year. Even
CBS's Dan Rather, who dashed down to the Carolinas for
I-was-there-too reporting, was in blue, as were most of the Weather
Channel's reporters. Last year, the dominant TV reporter
costume/slicker was yellow.)
</P>
<P>
   Although we in South Florida were spared Floyd, there remain
some questions in my mind about the storm, and about Gert behind
it. I don't know if it's because of improved technology, but I was
surprised that both Floyd and Gert were spinning winds of more than
150 mph. I cannot recall any time that two storms of that power _
just scant miles per hour short of catastrophic Category 5 _ were
one-two across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   This either can be traced to global warming, or to La Nina, or
to hyperbole from the weather bureau and media or to the likelihood
that hurricanes were that powerful in the past but because of lack
of scientific documentation, forecasters were unable to properly
gauge the windspeed so far out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   It is equally puzzling to me that the supposed 155 mph winds of
Floyd were not registered as striking the Bahamas at that level _
although any level of hurricane-force winds is too much wind.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot we don't know about hurricanes, but one thing we
do know and that is what hurricanes do. I got my equivalency degree
in Hurricane 401 the hard way with Andrew in 1992 and, despite my
rampant cynicism, am not about to belittle anything the weather
folks are telling me.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I'm not letting down my guard. I remain at battle stations
until the last hurricane of this season fizzles. Don't drop in
unannounced; the house is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
