<SLUG> BC-LION-KEEPER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `LION KING' PREPARES TO RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The lion king is giving up his throne.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a half-century, Jack Castor has reigned supreme at
the Lion House at the San Francisco Zoo. On Friday, the era of Jack
the Big Cat Keeper comes to a bittersweet end.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing his retirement 10 other times in the last few
years, Castor, 75, swears this time it's for real.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday at 2 p.m., visitors will have a last chance to witness
Castor's legendary showmanship as he hand-feeds his beloved lions
and tigers. Then, he'll hang up his meat hook, lock the doors of
the Lion House and say goodbye to the zoo after exactly 48 years, 5
months and 11 days of service _ longer than any other civil servant
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of visitors _ 25 million by his count _ have come
through the Lion House while Castor has been its animal keeper.
</P>
<P>
   They've crowded around the rails as Castor walked his
wheelbarrow dinner cart, lifted the cage doors and fed the hungry
cats. They've ``oohed'' as he stuck his face up to the cage to let
the cats kiss him hello, and held their breath as the wild animals
nibbled horsemeat morsels from his fingertips. They've clapped as
Castor had the lions and tigers do tricks. And they've heard his
tales.
</P>
<P>
   Such tales they were _ and he just happened to have the
snapshots in his shirt pocket to prove them.
</P>
<P>
   Like how he used to take cubs home with him so he could
bottle-feed and hand-raise them. Or how he once jumped into a cage
to save an injured lion. Or the time his favorite lion, Old George,
played tug-of-war with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a question of who owned the hand, that's all,''
said Castor.
</P>
<P>
   Castor repeated some of these stories Wednesday during a
retirement bash at the zoo. But he wasn't doing all the talking.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to celebrate Castor's years with speeches and gifts.
As Castor sat on a red throne wearing a red crown in honor of his
lion king status, David Anderson, the zoo director, presented him
with his trusty meat hook mounted on a plaque, and with a bronze
statue of a lion. An ode to Castor written by a former animal
keeper was read aloud. So were letters from U.S. Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Diane Feinstein, D-Calif., and Mayor Willie Brown. Board
Supervisor Michael Yaki presented a proclamation pronouncing it
Jack Castor Day in the City and County of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And scores of zoo employees, old friends and visitors gave hugs
and shared their memories.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ``Big Bison'' Dias, an animal keeper for 25 years,
remembered his own first day on the job in 1967. The zoo sent him
over to help Castor with the feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Castor took one look at him and casually mentioned that Dias
should be careful. The lions had a funny way of saying hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're grabbers,'' Castor told him. ``They always grab the
new ones first.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm . . . something about fresh meat . . .
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Castor can't believe it's over. Over the years, he
had taken care of 300 lions and tigers. He remembered them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a job I wouldn't have missed for the world,'' he
said. ``If I had to do it all over again, I'd probably start
earlier . . . ``I remember every single day. I'll always have those
memories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
