<HEADLINE>
AFFLECK EMERGES IN `FORCES OF NATURE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `FORCES OF NATURE'
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, DreamWorks, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99.
</P>
<P>
   While Ben Affleck shared an Oscar with Matt Damon for writing
``Good Will Hunting,'' he isn't taken too seriously as an actor
yet. Making ``Armageddon'' and ``Phantoms'' didn't helped.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Affleck has shown an impressive range in other pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The little-seen ``Chasing Amy'' showed off his dramatic skills,
as he played a lovestruck young man pursuing a bisexual woman,
while ``Forces of Nature'' offers his self-effacing comic side, as
did his cameo in ``200 Cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Forces,'' Affleck plays Ben Holmes, an unassuming writer of
book-jacket blurbs who's about to fly from New York to his wedding
in Georgia. Plane trouble and circumstances send him riding down
the road with a mercurial young woman.
</P>
<P>
   She's Sarah (Sandra Bullock), an infectiously fun free spirit
who loosens Ben up on the way to their sudden friendship, which
then veers recklessly toward romance.
</P>
<P>
   They're tossed together in comic misadventures that include
fires, a robbery, missed trains and wild weather _ not to mention
their own ``forces of nature.'' Meanwhile, sympathetic fiancee
Maura Tierney waits and wails amid a sea of guests.
</P>
<P>
   Like her, we wonder if Ben will ever say ``I do'' _ and if so,
to whom?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is fitting and satisfying, but it's the journey that
makes this movie worth watching. 3 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`THE PRINCE OF EGYPT' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998, PG, DreamWorks, CC, VHS $26.99, DVD $34.99
</P>
<P>
   Making animated movies on Disney's level used to be an elusive
goal. But this intelligent, handsome film attains such artistry in
bringing ancient Bible tales to vibrant new life.
</P>
<P>
   Its source is the book of Exodus, which tells the story of Moses
from childhood through his missions in God's service.
</P>
<P>
   The movie isn't preachy, although its musical numbers have
meaning and majesty, unlike Disney's formulaic Broadway-style
songs. ``Prince'' succeeds as thoughtful, adventurous, adult-level
entertainment that also embraces a child's sense of wonder.
</P>
<P>
   It's also gratifying to see a feature-length animated film with
no animals or other creatures as comic sidekicks. 3 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`SUBMARINE' EXTRAS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow Submarine'' is packed with extras on DVD (from MGM,
$29.98), including interviews with creative types and an audio
commentary track from animator John Coates and designer Heinz
Edelmann.
</P>
<P>
   Also on DVD is ``The Mod Odyssey,'' a cheeky seven-minute film
about the movie's creation; the original theatrical trailer
(running more than three minutes _ long by today's standards);
dozens of behind-the-scenes photos, including shots of the Beatles;
and three storyboard sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you can play the entire film with a music-only track _ no
dialogue or sound effects, just the Beatles' songs and George
Martin's orchestral work.
</P>
<P>
   On tape, ``Yellow Submarine'' costs $19.98. Both formats have
the previously unreleased animated song ``Hey Bulldog.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &LR;  &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
