<HEADLINE>
WHY SOME ROADS ARE CALLED BLUE STAR HIGHWAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I saw on a map that the North-South Freeway (Interstate 35-W)
is called the Blue Star Memorial Highway. Where did this name come
from, and why did it go away?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.T., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: There are Blue Star Memorial Highways all over the country
named by garden clubs to honor people who served in the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, the National Council of State Garden Clubs
began a program to designate Blue Star highways and place roadside
historical markers. One can be found on I-35 at a roadside park
north of Gainesville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name was taken from the small service flag that family
members placed in their windows during World War II,'' according to
the New York State Thruway Authority. ``A blue star signified a
family member serving overseas; a red star represented someone who
was injured, and a gold star meant a family member had died in
action.''
</P>
<P>
   To renew interest in the project, some clubs have begun efforts
to find and rededicate their state's Blue Star historical markers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I purchase Dr. Scholl's sandals?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.W., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: One Fort Worth-Dallas retailer recommended by the
manufacturer is Cooper's Shoe Store at 3857 S.W. Loop 820 in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's doesn't presently have the sandals in stock but can
special order them. Call (817) 292-0305 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   To buy them over the phone or find other places that sell Dr.
Scholl's footwear, call the Brown Shoe Co. at (800) 766-6465.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer has a World Wide Web site at
www.drschollsshoes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Bill Bradley and Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   _ P.H.H., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: To contact the announced Democratic candidates for the 2000
presidential nomination:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, 395 Pleasant Valley Way, West Orange, NJ 07052;
phone (888) 643-9799; World Wide Web www.billbradley.com.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, Box 18237, Washington, D.C. 20036-8237; phone (202)
263-6000; World Wide Web www.algore2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
