<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE A RICE DAY: INNOVATIVE DISHES SHOW SPLENDOR OF VERSATILE
GRAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ill.) 
(Eds.: See recipes) 
 
By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spice it, sauce it, roll it, wrap it up. Rice isn't just for
steaming anymore. Forget plain long-grain, short-grain, parboiled
and instant. Discover arborio, jasmine, basmati, brown,
black/purple Indonesian and Thai rice, red, sushi and sweet rice.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of a recent contest pulled out all the stops in creating
new recipes for the world's favorite starch.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Vanni of Libertyville, Ill., added orange marmalade,
toasted almonds and green onions to win the grand prize in Mr.
Food's Rice Recipe Contest. She won $5,000 and a subscription of
Mr. Food's EasyCooking magazine with her entry, Chicken and Rice
l'Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh fruit, especially tropicals such as mangoes, pineapple and
coconut, were often used in finalists' recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Other contest trends spotted by Kim Park of the USA Rice
Federation, headquartered in Houston:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rice moved to the center of the plate in one-dish meals such
as risotto, stir-frys, salads and paella.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contestants added flavors without adding a lot of ingredients
by using convenience products such as salsa, pesto, jarred sauces
(barbecue, Alfredo, spaghetti, etc.), soup mixes, rice mixes,
pudding mixes, seasoning packets, canned beans, frozen mixed
vegetables and mesquite-grilled chicken.
</P>
<P>
   _ International flavors abound. Ethnic flavors included
Mediterranean, Italian, Mexican, Spanish, Indian, Thai, Caribbean,
Japanese and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comfort foods are classic: There were numerous versions of
Broccoli Rice Casserole, Green Chilies and Cheese Rice Casserole,
Chicken and Rice Soup, and Rice Pudding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rice salads were the third most popular entries after main
dishes and side dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most popular main-dish partners with rice were boneless
chicken breasts, ground beef, turkey, sausage, shrimp, crab meat,
salmon and tuna.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vegetarian entrees also were represented _ especially with
beans, beans, beans!
</P>
<P>
   _ Wraps were big _ rice was wrapped in tortillas, puff pastry or
crescent rolls or spooned into pastry shells and pie crusts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several entries were variations of rice pancakes _ and not
just for breakfast. Savory rice pancakes also were served as
appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rice showed up in a variety of appetizers _ nachos, dips,
quesadillas, crab cakes and rice ``poppers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Fresh herbs were widely used _ especially cilantro and basil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other popular ingredients: coconut milk, dried cranberries,
artichokes, black beans, salsa, roasted red peppers and yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teas were used as flavorings _ especially mango, spearmint and
jasmine tea.
</P>
<P>
   For a free copy of Mr. Food's Winning Rice Recipes brochure,
send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to Winning Rice Recipes in
care of the USA Rice Federation, P.O. Box 740121, Houston, Texas
77274, or visit the Web site, Have a Rice Day Cafe, at
www.ricecafe.com.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers seem to know a lot more about rice than they used to,
and they're incorporating new types, flavors and mixes into daily
menus, Park said. Consumers like the cooking aroma of varieties
such as jasmine, Louisiana Popcorn Rice, Wild Pecan, Della and
Delta Rose.
</P>
<P>
   There are no hard and fast rules on the type of rice to use for
different cooking tasks, but some general suggestions include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Choose medium- or short-grain rice for creamy dishes, such as
risotto, and for desserts or dishes for which stickier rice is
preferred, such as sushi, molds or croquettes. Choose long-grain
rice when you prefer separate, distinct grains such as in pilaf.
</P>
<P>
   _ American rice does not need washing or rinsing before or after
cooking. In fact, washing removes valuable nutrients. Many recipes
using imported rice advise washing or soaking the rice before
cooking. If in doubt, follow package directions.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you cook a lot of rice, you may want to buy an electric
rice cooker. The microwave also produces excellent rice. It doesn't
take less time than conventional methods, but the rice has a good
texture.
</P>
<P>
   _ To produce perfect rice, measure rice and liquid, and time
cooking accurately. Keep the lid on while rice is cooking so steam
doesn't escape. Use the right size pot; most rice triples in volume
when it cooks.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the end of cooking time, carefully remove lid to avoid
steam. Test for doneness. If rice isn't quite tender or if liquid
remains, cook 2 to 4 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   _ If cooked rice is crunchy, add additional liquid, cover again
tightly and cook until tender.
</P>
<P>
   _ When done, remove lid and fluff with a fork to allow steam to
escape and to keep grains separate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
