<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d BC-FOOD-RICE-RECIPES-HNS     09-16 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RICE-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
W/ FOOD-RICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent marks needed over first e in sauteed and first e in
pureed) 
 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
 
FRIED RICE 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From ``The Rice Bible'' by Christian Teubner (Penguin Studio,
$34.95). &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 cups Thai long-grain rice (available at Asian markets) &QL; 
3 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
1/2 onion, sliced into thin rings &QL; 
1 (1-inch-long) cinnamon stick &QL; 
1 bay leaf &QL; 
3 whole cloves &QL; 
1/2 mace blade &QL; 
1 heaping tablespoon brown sugar &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thoroughly wash rice under cold running water. Transfer to a bowl,
cover with cold water and soak 20 minutes, then drain well. Heat
oil in a pot, then add onion rings and saute until golden brown.
Add cinnamon stick, bay leaf, cloves and mace; saute 3 more
minutes. Sprinkle sugar on top and caramelize, stirring constantly.
Add rice and stir 3 more minutes; season with salt. Add 2 1/4 cups
water, bring to a boil, reduce heat and cook until done, 10 to 15
minutes. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LEMON RICE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Rice Bible'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 cup basmati rice &QL; 
1/4 cup cashews &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon turmeric &QL; 
1 green chili &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon mustard seed &QL; 
8 fresh curry leaves (available in Asian markets) &QL; 
Juice of 1/2 lemon &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thoroughly wash rice under cold running water. Transfer to a bowl,
cover with cold water and soak 30 minutes, then drain. Soak cashews
in cold water. Bring 1 1/3 cups water to a boil in a pot with salt.
Add rice and turmeric; simmer 10 minutes. During this time, rice
should absorb all liquid (do not allow it to become too soft).
Transfer rice to a bowl; let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, remove stem from chili and cut flesh into rings,
removing seeds at the same time. Heat oil in a wok and briefly
stir-fry chili rings. Mix in mustard seed, well-drained cashews and
curry leaves; stir-fry 30 seconds. Stir in lemon juice. Add rice;
heat briefly and serve. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DILL RICE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Rice Bible'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 cup Thai long-grain rice &QL; 
1 green chili &QL; 
2 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
2 green cardamom pods &QL; 
4 tablespoons chopped fresh dill &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
Dill sprigs for garnish &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wash rice under cold running water until water runs clear.
Transfer to a bowl, cover with cold water and soak 15 minutes.
Drain well. Halve chili lengthwise, remove seeds and finely dice
flesh. Heat oil in a pot, fry cardamom pods 1 minute, then add
chili and fry briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in dill and salt. Saute over low heat for 2 to 3 more
minutes. Sprinkle in rice and saute 2 minutes. Add 1 1/2 cups
water, bring to a boil and simmer rice 10 to 12 minutes. Season to
taste. Serve in bowls garnished with dill sprigs. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GINGER RICE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Rice Bible'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 cups Thai long-grain rice &QL; 
1 (1 1/2-inch) piece fresh ginger root &QL; 
1 stalk lemon grass &QL; 
2 to 3 green onions, plus 4 for garnish &QL; 
1 red chili &QL; 
2 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
Pinch of brown sugar &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
Juice of 1/2 kaffir lime (available at Asian markets) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thoroughly wash rice under cold running water. Peel ginger and cut
into paper-thin slices. Slice lemon grass; cut green onions into
rings. Halve chili lengthwise, remove seeds and finely chop flesh.
Heat oil in a pot. Add ginger, lemon grass, 2 to 3 green onions and
chili; sweat 2 to 3 minutes (place in partially covered pan over
low heat and heat until moisture beads form and ingredients
soften).
</P>
<P>
   Add rice and continue to sweat ingredients. Season with sugar,
salt and lime juice. Pour in 2 3/4 cups water, bring to a boil,
reduce heat and simmer 15 minutes. Meanwhile, prepare green onions
for garnish: Trim most of the green part to leave green onions
about 2 1/2 inches long. Make repeated lengthwise cuts from the top
down to 3/4 inch short of the root; place briefly in ice water so
strips roll up decoratively. Serve rice in small bowls garnished
with green onions. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOUTH-OF-THE-BORDER LASAGNE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A finalist in the 1999 Mr. Food's Rice Recipe Contest for
Catherine J. Heimbach of Stockbridge, Wis. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 cups each: sour cream and bottled salsa &QL; 
Nonstick cooking spray &QL; 
6 cups cooked rice, divided &QL; 
3 cups shredded Cheddar cheese, divided &QL; 
1 (15- to 16-ounce) can black beans, drained and rinsed &QL; 
2 cups crushed tortilla chips &QL; 
 &QL; 
Combine sour cream and salsa in medium bowl; set aside. Coat a
13-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish with cooking spray. Layer bottom of
dish with 3 cups rice. Top with half the sour cream mixture, then
with 1 1/2 cups cheese. Add beans, remaining rice and remaining
sour cream mixture. Bake at 350 degrees 15 minutes; remove from
oven. Mix remaining cheese and chips and sprinkle on lasagne.
Return to oven and bake 5 minutes or until cheese melts. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MINI CRAB CAKES WITH ROASTED RED PEPPER SAUCE &QL; 
 &QL; 
A finalist in the 1999 Mr. Food's Rice Recipe Contest for Ellen
Burr of Truro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Red Pepper Mayonnaise (recipe follows) &QL; 
2 eggs, lightly beaten &QL; 
1 tablespoon seafood seasoning &QL; 
1 pound crab meat, shredded &QL; 
3 cups cooked medium-grain rice &QL; 
2 to 3 tablespoons vegetable oil, divided &QL; 
 &QL; 
Make Red Pepper Mayonnaise; refrigerate. Combine eggs and seafood
seasoning in medium bowl; whisk until blended. Stir in crab meat
and rice. Form 2 tablespoons mixture into a 2 1/2-inch patty.
Repeat with remaining mixture. Heat 1 tablespoon oil in large,
heavy skillet over medium-high heat. Add crab cakes in batches;
cook 2 1/2 to 3 minutes on each side or until browned. Add more oil
to skillet as necessary. Drain well on paper towels. Serve hot or
at room temperature with Red Pepper Mayonnaise. Makes 2 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RED PEPPER MAYONNAISE &QL; 
 &QL; 
3/4 cup roasted garlic mayonnaise (available in specialty markets) &QL; 
1/4 cup pureed roasted red peppers &QL; 
1 teaspoon seafood seasoning &QL; 
Combine mayonnaise, peppers and seafood seasoning; mix well. Makes
1 cup sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SANTA FE SMOKIN' RICE SALAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A finalist in the 1999 Mr. Food's Rice Recipe Contest for
Josephine D. Piro of Easton, Penn.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cooked rice, cooled to room temperature &QL; 
1 1/2 cups shredded smoked Gouda cheese &QL; 
1 cup smoked turkey breast cubes &QL; 
2 medium plum tomatoes, coarsely chopped &QL; 
1/4 red onion, cut into 1/2-inch slices &QL; 
1/2 cup creamy cilantro salad dressing (see note) &QL; 
Salt and black pepper to taste &QL; 
 &QL; 
Combine rice, cheese, turkey, tomatoes and onion in large bowl. Add
dressing and toss lightly. Season with salt and pepper. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Ranch-style dressing mixed with 1 tablespoon chopped
fresh cilantro may be substituted for creamy cilantro dressing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CINNAMON RICE PUDDING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A finalist in the 1999 Mr. Food's Rice Recipe Contest for Debbie
Jandro of Desert Hot Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups each: cooked rice and milk &QL; 
1/2 cup sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup butter &QL; 
2 cinnamon sticks &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla extract &QL; 
Ground cinnamon &QL; 
Whipped cream (optional) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Combine rice, milk, sugar, butter and cinnamon sticks in 2-quart
saucepan. Cook over medium heat until thick and creamy (20 to 25
minutes), stirring frequently. Remove from heat; remove cinnamon
sticks and stir in vanilla. Serve warm or chilled. Sprinkle with
ground cinnamon and top with whipped cream. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHICKEN AND RICE L'ORANGE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grand-prize winner in the 1999 Mr. Food's Rice Recipe
Contest went to Debbie Vanni of Libertyville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1 cup each: uncooked rice, orange juice and water &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
3 tablespoons butter, divided &QL; 
1/4 cup sliced almonds &QL; 
4 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves &QL; 
1/4 cup each: orange marmalade and sliced green onion &QL; 
 &QL; 
Combine rice, juice, water and salt in a 2- to 3-quart saucepan.
Heat to boiling; stir once or twice. Reduce heat, cover and simmer
15 minutes. While rice cooks, melt 1 tablespoon butter in large
skillet over medium-high heat. Add almonds and cook, stirring,
until golden, 2 to 3 minutes. Remove almonds; set aside. Melt
remaining butter in skillet. Add chicken; cook until brown on both
sides. Add marmalade to skillet and stir to coat chicken. To serve,
spoon rice onto plate; top with chicken. Sprinkle with almonds and
green onion. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
