<SLUG> BC-JAIL-CLASSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILERS DENOUNCE CIVIL RIGHTS CLASSES FOR INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The classes were intended to teach jail inmates
their civil rights, but in the eyes of their jailers, they went too
far, turning into a crash course that taught the students how to
conceal their crimes and thwart police investigations.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco sheriff's deputies, who run the city's jails, were
fuming over the four classes taught Monday and Tuesday at three San
Francisco jails, saying they not only instructed prisoners how to
avoid being caught but included role-playing skits that depicted
cops as racist, violent, incompetent doughnut munchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This teaches criminals how to use the criminal justice system
to their advantage and what the loopholes are,'' said David Hardy,
president of the San Francisco Deputy Sheriffs' Association. ``The
regular citizen on the street isn't going to know what to do when
they get a search warrant, but these guys have learned how to
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy also criticized the way the classes depicted cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with people knowing their rights, but
(police officers) were portrayed as racist and incompetent,'' he
said Wednesday. ``The mood of that course bred a lot of contempt
for police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to complaints from several deputies, department
officials acknowledged the classes were inappropriate and said the
instructor would not be invited back.
</P>
<P>
   The 2 1/2-hour classes were taught by criminal defense and civil
rights attorney Katya Komisaruk to about 120 male and female
prisoners awaiting trial for a variety of misdemeanor and felony
offenses. None of them posed maximum security concerns, jail
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a ``criminal defense guidelines'' sheet handed out
in the class, Komisaruk, who was invited into the jails by the
Sheriff's Department's Prisoner Legal Services division, taught
inmates how to avoid talking to police without an attorney or being
manipulated by a seemingly sympathetic police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The course also showed them how they could prevent police with
search warrants from entering their homes. In at least one class,
Komisaruk advised inmates to avoid stealing from larger department
stores because they have better security, according to deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy said that the courses also included good-cop-bad-cop skits
during which two actors portraying police officers used racial
epithets and were excessively violent when acting out scenarios
using inmate volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials asked Sheriff Michael Hennessey to halt the
classes Tuesday morning after fielding complaints from deputies
after the first two classes on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Department spokeswoman Eileen Hirst said officials
acknowledged the complaints and asked Komisaruk to quit using some
of the props in her skits and to avoid depicting law enforcement
officers in ways that would provoke ridicule. But Hirst said the
department's head of prisoner legal services had sat in on one of
the classes after that and found it still to be inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear this entire (group of classes) was found offensive
by many people, not just deputies,'' Hirst said, adding that
Komisaruk would not be asked back to teach the classes again.
</P>
<P>
   Hirst said state law required the Sheriff's Department to
provide legal materials and information to inmates. The ``know your
rights'' courses, such as Komisaruk's, have been used to address
the requirements for more than 25 years. The classes have been
taught by outside experts, including defense attorneys, public
defenders and legal scholars and were typically conducted in a
question-and-answer format, Hirst said.
</P>
<P>
   Komisaruk was brought in to teach the four classes after a
former inmate donated $250 specifically for civil rights
instruction. Hirst said a course curriculum that was submitted to
officials for review prior to the classes did not contain anything
offensive or objectionable, and the classes were approved.
</P>
<P>
   Komisaruk said she was surprised by the controversy, especially
since she had taught the very same class several years ago for the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the problem is,'' she said. ``It's a little
frustrating. It was going really well, and the prisoners seemed to
like it.'' Komisaruk, a former anti-nuclear activist, served two
years in federal prison after being convicted of destroying
government property, and while in prison applied to Harvard's law
school and was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Komisaruk acknowledged coaching class participants on what to
say to avoid self-incrimination when confronted by police but said
she firmly believed that her students should be fully apprised of
their legal and civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I usually say is there are lots of ways to handle a
situation,'' Komisaruk said. ``I try to be balanced. I'm always
trying to get in the how-to-do-good messages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
