<SLUG> BC-TREK-ROXANN-DAWSON-IN-VOYAGER-ART-ADV27-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV27 
 ROXANN DAWSON RIDES `THE BARGE OF THE DEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Roxann
Dawson in ``Star Trek: Voyager.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Six years.
 &HT;    Roxann Dawson has been playing ``Star Trek: Voyager's'' B'Elanna
Torres for six years. That fact struck the actress hard her first
day back on the set a few months ago.
 &HT;    ``It actually hits me every time I have to sit down and have the
makeup put on,'' Dawson says. ``The show always feels new. It
always feels real to me. Every story is unique. The cast feels like
a family.
 &HT;    ``And the makeup, which still takes two-and-a-half hours to get
on and nearly an hour to get off, is a big pain in the butt,'' she
adds. ``The makeup is really the only thing that makes me think
I've been doing `Voyager' for six years.''
 &HT;    If it weren't for the combination of makeup and prosthetic
appliances that so convincingly transforms her into everyone's
favorite half-human/half-Klingon, however, Dawson wouldn't get to
sink her teeth into such juicy episodes as ``Barge of the Dead.''
Airing on Oct. 6, ``Barge'' sends Torres on a treacherous trek
through Klingon hell after a near-death experience.
 &HT;    On the way to that hell aboard an ancient barge carrying
dishonored souls, Torres encounters her heretofore-unseen mother,
Miral (Karen Austin). That kicks off Torres' frenzied crusade to
save two souls, hers and her mother's.
 &HT;    ``The sets were phenomenal, the story is great and, as far as
being an actress is concerned, it's very exciting to get an episode
that is not only physically demanding but emotionally demanding,''
Dawson says by telephone from her trailer during a production
break. ```Barge of the Dead' is very true to form for B'Elanna, in
that I didn't have to stretch a lot to compensate for things that
didn't make sense.
 &HT;    ``I think it could be the best B'Elanna episode we've gotten to
do so far,'' she says. ``I haven't seen it put together in its
final form yet, but it felt very risky and daring while we were
shooting it, and I think it reveals a lot more than we've ever seen
of the character.
 &HT;    ``It's a very personal story and, at the end, without giving it
away, I think B'Elanna is a different person.''
 &HT;    At least as exciting for Dawson is ``Riddles,'' the ``Voyager''
episode airing on Nov. 3. The hour may focus on Neelix (Ethan
Phillips) and Tuvok (Tim Russ), but Dawson's presence can be felt
from beginning to end, as the actress makes her maiden voyage as a
television director with ``Riddles.''
 &HT;    ``I've been on a million sets with many directors for countless
years, not only on `Voyager' but on other shows as well,'' says
Dawson, who previously had directed for the stage. ``I soaked all
of that in. Also, I really did my homework and prepared for the
job.
 &HT;    ``There weren't a lot of things that were surprises,'' she adds,
``because I didn't expect the shoot to go smoothly. I expected
problems, so when they arose they did not throw me as much as they
would have otherwise. I keep saying this, but I really think my
preparation made me able to handle the various situations that
arose and still be able to enjoy the process.
 &HT;    ``It was such a great time for me,'' the actress says. ``In
terms of really enjoying it, it went way beyond my expectations.''
 &HT;    Right now the episode is in limbo, awaiting the attention of
executive producer Rick Berman, who will give it a final edit.
 &HT;    ``I handed in my version and I thought it looked really
wonderful,'' Dawson says. ``I was very, very proud of it.
 &HT;    ``The show was about nine minutes too long, so quite a bit needs
to be cut,'' she adds. ``I'm not quite sure what the final version
will look like, because it now goes to Rick Berman, but I am very
pleased with it at this point.''
 &HT;    Dawson hopes to direct again in the near future, but she'd
rather scarf down a plate of that slimy Klingon delicacy gagh than
request another episode too soon. She's still recovering from her
first outing, not to mention putting the finishing touches on two
sci-fi novels which she's co-written, due in May from Pocket Books.
 &HT;    ``I'm barely done with `Riddles,''' says ``Voyager's'' latest
hyphenate. ``It would sort of be like having the candy still in
your mouth and asking for more.
 &HT;    ``I think I need to give the producers time to determine whether
or not I succeeded with my first show.'' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' consult
the official Website at www.startrek.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
