<HEADER>
A4331 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-RITA-MORENO-HNS &LR;      09-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RITA-MORENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITA MORENO: A STAR WHO'S NOT SLOWING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There are street clothes. And there are gig
clothes. And for entertainers such as Rita Moreno, never the twain
shall (or should) meet. We're talkin' flash here as opposed to
Polartech.
</P>
<P>
   We're discussing soigne fashion instead of functional sweats.
</P>
<P>
   But it's functional sweats that Moreno is wearing when she
answers the door to her new Berkeley, Calif., home with a view. A
one-piece, soft-as-down gray, belted jumpsuit that makes her wiry,
size-six body look even smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure you're a size six?'' I ask her. But, there's the
matter of what she calls her rounded behind, that quite feminine
rump, pumped up from 45 years of dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno does no dancing (except for possibly her huge kohl-rimmed
eyes) during her current entertainment gig at the Plush Room. Plus,
the Plush Room is not Carnegie Hall. So certain corrections,
regarding couture, had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to change my entire wardrobe,'' she says, pulling her
performance clothes out of white garment bags. ``The stuff I have
for concerts is too big for the room. I use much more beads and
baubles. But the white skirt, the one I wore opening night, is all
transparent sequins. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Well, compared with the bugle beads she dons head-to-toe in
symphony halls, it is a symphony of simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno is a tiny, 5-feet-3 sprite with perfect and perfectly
tawny skin, slim arms, silken shoulders and graceful hands. Her
wardrobe begs display from the top of a piano lid, which is where
she's perched (or prone) through many of the 14 numbers in her act.
So the clothes have to work.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with a slinky pave sequined white skirt with a sexy slit
in the back is a leg-o-mutton-sleeved, zip-front jacket in black
taffeta with black velvet appliques outlined in black sequins. It
fits tightly at Moreno's exquisitely wasp waist, and when she
unzipped it opening night during ``Baby, Ain't I Good to You,'' to
reveal a sparkly black camisole, every man in the audience gasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sing a sexy song with a jacket on,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, Moreno wore a lavender bias-cut strapless sheath
with self-colored sequins and a matching shrug. When she reclined
on the piano, she stuck the microphone in her bustier.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like the right thing to do at the time. Although she
is a seasoned pro with some original and interesting work to her
credit _ the most recent is playing a nun drug counselor on HBO's
gritty series, ``Oz'' _ she's never done cabaret before and says of
opening night, ``I was scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you'd never know it.
</P>
<P>
   The look she was after for the Plush Room appearance, which is
her warm-up for the Algonquin Hotel gig in New York, was ``elegant,
sexy lady,'' she says. ``There aren't any outfits like that, so I
had to have them made.''
</P>
<P>
   The black fouffy-sleeved jacket was a copy for a Thierry Mugler
suit jacket. She's thinking about having it done in purple, too.
``I love separates,'' she says. ``It's something about looking
extremely glam, an in-your-face chic and casual. If I could do it,
I would roll up my sleeves.''
</P>
<P>
   She also adores collecting costume jewelry, the brighter the
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter always says to me, `Mom, why don't you have the
real stuff,' and I tell her: `I'm a Hispanic woman. I looooooove
costume jewelry.'''
</P>
<P>
   That most of her wardrobe, save the lilac number, is simple
black and white is pure Moreno. Even with her rented furniture
(``We moved in a few months ago and I still don't have my own stuff
up here yet,'' she moaned), Moreno's home, with the incredible
views of downtown Oakland and the East Bay, is all bare floors,
cream-colored couches and Moreno's collection of graphic Navajo
rugs done mostly in tones of black, white, gray and red.
</P>
<P>
   It is the house of an artist, with musical scores, tapes and
lyrics piled neatly on the dining-room table and folklore artifacts
arranged on tabletops.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is a cook's dream, with acres of granite counters,
panoramic windows that stretch the length of the back side of the
house and a handy conversation area around the center island, which
is equipped with a stainless-steel range and a shelf filled with
jar after jar of baby food for Moreno's grandbaby, her daughter
Fernanda's son, Justin.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno is one of those enduring and endearing performers who
injects her roles, as well as her performances, with kinetic
energy. Fans remember her electric Anita in ``West Side Story,''
for which she won an Oscar; younger fans can sing all her patter
songs from PBS's ``The Electric Company,'' which earned her an Emmy
and a Grammy; and her gay fans will never forget the Latin
spitfire, Googie Gomez, from Broadway's ``The Ritz,'' for which she
won a Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Her contemporaries include Chita Rivera and Shirley MacLaine,
hoofers with great legs (always the last to go, so they say) and
boundless energy. I ask her about the usual stuff. What she eats.
(Not much. It was 2 p.m. and she had to decide between a nap and
food. The nap won.) And her beauty regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to be horrified,'' she says. ``I use a Buff Puff
on my face every day of my life. And I've never had what most
people my age have. I don't get those tiny bits of loose skin under
my makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   (She's right, I am horrified . . . but, if it ain't broke, don't
fix it.)
</P>
<P>
   In clothing, as in furniture, Moreno says she loves ``simple
lines. Nothing too frou-frou.''
</P>
<P>
   It's her hair that has the runaway curls. At the age of 67 (she
turns 68 in December), she's finally stopped fighting her naturally
curly coif. ``When it's so damp here with all this fog, I have no
choice,'' she says with a laugh. ``My hair just goes `home.'''
</P>
<P>
   Home now is Berkeley, close to her daughter and away from the
Hollywood boogaloo, and, when she has to go back to film ``Oz,'' a
pied-a-terre in New York to accommodate Moreno and her physician
husband, Lenny Gordon, who has been her lighting director the past
15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
