<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-JAZZ-MAHOGANY-KANSAS-     09-16 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-MAHOGANY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO PLACE LIKE HOME FOR SINGER KEVIN MAHOGANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just six years ago, Kevin Mahogany supported
himself by working as a data processor while pursuing a dream: to
be a jazz singer. In nightclubs all over Kansas City he chased that
dream relentlessly, applying his rich baritone to the standard jazz
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he always sang jazz. Sometimes he lent his talents to
R&AMP;B or pop. But it all helped him to connect with audiences in
places like the Club at Plaza III and come to an understanding of
his gifts as a performer. And even when the dream seemed out of
reach, it was always on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mahogany, 41, is a star. A big man with charm to match, he
performs in such top-flight New York clubs as Birdland and Iridium,
is a favorite at jazz festivals nationally and internationally, and
has six well-received albums in the racks. In a critics' poll in
Down Beat magazine he was recently named Best Male Jazz Vocalist of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Mahogany rarely performs in Kansas City anymore _ even
though he was born here and still lives here. So his concert
tonight at the Uptown Theater should be a don't-miss event.
Patricia Barber, a fine Chicago jazz singer with a solid following
of her own, is also on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mahogany, who has dabbled in pop music in concert and on
recordings, insists he has no intention of abandoning jazz. And
that goes for Kansas City, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps me humble and it keeps me grounded,'' he said,
dressed in a T-shirt and jeans and relaxing in The Star's cafeteria
on a recent afternoon. The city reminds him of the days when he was
hungry for success, and that's a hunger he never wants to lose.
</P>
<P>
   In concert at the Uptown, it's a good bet that Mahogany will
focus on tunes included on his latest CD, ``My Romance'' (Warner
Bros.). Not only would that be a smart marketing move, but it would
also reflect his affinity for the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a project that I've wanted to do for a long time,'' he
said. ``An album of nothing but love songs and ballads. That's what
I get requests for, more than anything, when I'm out performing.
Everybody likes a love song.''
</P>
<P>
   And more than a few people like Mahogany, who, through a
combination of talent and luck, established himself on the national
scene just before vocal jazz shook off its cobwebs and reasserted
its popularity. Indeed, the competition has become fierce in the
last five years, with such nationally recognized stylists as
Cassandra Wilson and Diana Krall not only impressing critics but
also crossing over into the pop market.
</P>
<P>
   To Mahogany, the trend only makes sense once you understand that
both pop fans and jazz fans can appreciate a good tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny how they're parallel in that way,'' said
the vocalist, who has also written songs including ``Still
Swingin''' and ``Fix It in the Mix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both audiences know all the tunes. I try to mix a little fun
in with the seriousness of the music. Because it is entertainment _
which I think a lot of people, especially jazz artists, tend to
forget.'' At the Uptown, Mahogany's honey-smooth voice will be
accompanied by pianist James Weidman, guitarist Greg Skaff, bassist
Tyrone Clark and drummer Todd Strait. The latter two are local
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful thing about a Mahogany show is the interaction
between the singer and his combo: the exhilarating blend of fine
musicianship, unexpected turns and self-deprecating good humor. At
New York's Iridium in 1998, Mahogany used ``Fix It in the Mix,'' a
song about mishaps in a recording studio, as the basis for a skit
in which band members took hilariously incongruous solos.
</P>
<P>
   As he bantered with the musicians and joked with the crowd, you
could see what has made Mahogany such a success: His easy way with
people and his willingness to do whatever it takes to make a
performance not just entertaining, but memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who think of jazz singers as musty anachronisms have
been won over by Mahogany's charms. At the heart of his appeal is
the understanding that, when done right, jazz need make no
apologies for its timeless virtues. But he also understands that to
connect with audiences, the music must keep up with the times.
Indeed, he has come a long way since his days as a journeyman
Kansas City performer.
</P>
<P>
   His sound nods to tradition while incorporating contemporary
influences. In a given set, Mahogany may thoughtfully deconstruct a
jazz standard or thoroughly reinvent a pop tune. And he can scat _
that is, let loose a stream of nonsense syllables with rhythmically
infectious exuberance _ like nobody's business.
</P>
<P>
   A performance at the Monterey Jazz Festival in 1995 exemplified
his style. As laidback and informal as he is in his personal life,
onstage he comes across as an emissary from an earlier time: cool,
dapper, elegantly smooth. He harks back to singers like Billy
Eckstine and Joe Williams, who cradled listeners with their voices
and had more than a touch of class.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminated by the lights of the outdoor stadium and clad in a
cream-colored suit, Mahogany charmed the Monterey crowd with a
rendition of ``Since I Fell for You'' that virtually defined
romantic pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is such misery and pain,'' he sang, stretching each
syllable of mis-er-y as he strolled the stage on a Saturday night.
``I guess I'll never be the same, since I fell for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, in an indoor festival hall, Mahogany entranced
a more intimate crowd with a playful run through the Stevie Wonder
hit ``My Cherie Amour.'' Caught up in his own momentum, he sang
``pretty as the Milky Way'' instead of ``distant as the Milky
Way.'' But it didn't matter: He owned the room regardless.
</P>
<P>
   Then as now, Mahogany exudes an enthusiasm for jazz that makes
the music that much more accessible _ and has made his albums for
the Enja and Warner Bros. labels sought-after gems. But to hear
Mahogany at his charismatic best, you really need to hear him in a
live setting. Regardless of the setting, he communicates. In recent
years he has performed at both the Kansas City Blues &AMP; Jazz
Festival and the Kansas City International Jazz Festival.
</P>
<P>
   At the first International Jazz Festival in 1996, Mahogany
delivered a delightfully varied program that veered from the
infectious ``Little Black Samba'' to the swinging ``Our Love Is
Here to Stay.'' Even for listeners who had enjoyed him for years in
Kansas City clubs, his authority and range were revelatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He swings, and he has a foot in that old, great blues sound of
Kansas City,'' said Steve Irwin, co-producer of the annual event.
``And he's one of a very few singers anymore who can make you cry
with a ballad.''
</P>
<P>
   Vocalist Barber, who has been praised for her edgy, modern sound
and her ability to transform rock tunes like ``Light My Fire'' into
legitimate jazz expression, said she was impressed with Mahogany's
artistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to stay away from vocalists, because I don't want to be
influenced,'' said the singer, whose latest album is ``Modern
Cool'' (Premonition). ``But I've heard him on the radio, and I know
that he can sing. It's going to be quite a challenge to double-bill
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahogany, who is married to photographer Allene Mahogany, didn't
start out as a singer. When he was 12 he played saxophone in an
18-piece big band, Kansas City's New Breed Orchestra. Unlike many
people who pursue music at an early age but move on, he kept at it.
But not as a saxophonist.
</P>
<P>
   In his senior year at Lincoln High School, Mahogany began
singing. And he kept on singing: in a jazz choir he founded while
studying at Baker University in Baldwin City, Kan.; in Kansas City
rhythm and blues bands; and in his own jazz groups.
</P>
<P>
   Things weren't always easy: Just before his career took off with
the 1993 release of his first album, ``Double Rainbow'' (Enja), he
paid the bills by taking on temp work as a data processor. But
those days are far behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Mahogany's subsequent Enja releases, ``Songs and Moments''
(1994) and ``You Got What It Takes'' (1995), set the stage for his
move to Warner Bros., a major label with the clout to take his
career to the next level. But his first Warner album, ``Kevin
Mahogany'' (1996), had some critics worried that the jazz singer
was compromising his art. The album combined straight-ahead jazz
with more pop-oriented material, including tunes by Fats Domino and
Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back at it,'' Mahogany said, ``it was probably
ill-timed. I was doing the music that I grew up with, but still
with a jazz and blues sensibility about it. But I think what
happened was, because it was the first one at Warner Bros., people
thought I was trying to cross over.''
</P>
<P>
   On his subsequent albums, ``Another Time, Another Place'' (1997)
and last year's ``My Romance,'' Mahogany's approach has been more
traditional but no less adventurous. And he said he plans to
continue taking risks.
</P>
<P>
   After all, that's what jazz is all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
