<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4348 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     09-16 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDONALD'S PUSH INTO RUSSIA CHRONICLED IN FRANCHISER'S
AUTOBIOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1990, East met West _ over a hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year the first McDonald's opened in what was then
the Soviet Union _ in Pushkin Square no less.
</P>
<P>
   The event was global in news coverage because of its economic,
political and social significance: a true meeting of once highly
adversarial cultures, with fries and a milkshake on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The odds against that happening, despite changes at that time in
the business climate, were phenomenal, even for the multinational,
multibillion-dollar hamburger giant.
</P>
<P>
   But it happened largely through the 14-year effort of one man,
and it wasn't McDonald's founder Ray Kroc.
</P>
<P>
   Kroc may be synonymous with McDonald's in the United States, but
in Russia, George Cohon is the man behind the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   His amazing feat, along with the rest of Cohon's life, is
chronicled in his autobiography, ``To Russia With Fries: My Journey
From Chicago's South Side to Moscow's Red Square _ Having Fun Along
the Way'' (McClelland &AMP; Stewart, 335 pages, $21.95). Writer David
Macfarlane co-authored the book.
</P>
<P>
   The book's foreword is written by none other than Mikhail
Gorbachev, who sings the praises of this hamburger man.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the height of the period of stagnation, when the free
spirit of the market was totally nonexistent, George
enthusiastically pursued the idea of starting a business here, and
he succeeded, despite having to fight his way through the
bureaucratic jungle,'' Gorbachev writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not just a personal triumph for George. It was a
breakthrough which demonstrated that new economic relations between
our country and the rest of the world were possible. It was a
symbol of the good will of international business which would be
important in helping us build a democratic society.''
</P>
<P>
   This highly readable autobiography shows how Cohon put his small
life savings
into building what has become a $2 billion McDonald's franchise in
Canada and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In a personal twist, Cohon's experience in Russia was actually
like a return home. In 1906, his infant father and grandparents
escaped from their home in the Ukraine during the pogroms, barely
making it onto a crammed boat to America. The family name Kaganov
was changed to Cohon by an immigration officer at Ellis Island, he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohon immediately asks everyone who meets him to call him
George.
</P>
<P>
   Cohon's personal tone in the book must exemplify the type of
person he is. Time and time again, he tells readers how much he
learns from just talking to people _ anybody, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed these kinds of conversations and chance
encounters,'' he writes. ``I find myself talking with someone _ a
customer, a stranger at a store, a cab driver _ and I start
talking. This is how you learn things, this is how you find out
what other people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohon is also full of stories, hundreds of them, which makes for
an engaging autobiography. Not only are the stories interesting and
poignant, but they also jump around in time and space, keeping the
book from being linear, and consequently boring.
</P>
<P>
   His most fascinating tale has to be about his Russian
experience, however, and most of the book involves this trek. It
started with a chance meeting with a Soviet delegation observing
the Montreal Olympics, which got Cohon thinking that McDonald's
could be the food provider for the 1980 Games in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Cohon describes some of the many hurdles that were jumped to
fulfill such a contract, a contract he spent four years trying to
persuade the Soviets to give him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although their agricultural system seemed to be in almost
total disarray, we felt that its individual components were often
sound,'' he writes. ``There were potatoes, but they were rotting in
the fields. There were trucks, but they were stranded on the roads,
out of gas. It wasn't a question of inventing the wheel so much as
ensuring that gears were meshing and the wheel was turning
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohon ultimately did not get the Olympics contract, but his
efforts did pave the way for opening his first McDonald's there 10
years later.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Cohon describes, that significant step wasn't just a
fast-food restaurant opening. Because there was no independent meat
supplier, bakery or dairy up to the company's standards, all of
them had to be built _ in a massive 100,000-square-foot plant that
made products from meat to ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, our McComplex processes fifty-seven tons of food a
day,'' he writes. ``And it doesn't only supply what we need at
McDonald's; at any number of Moscow's finest restaurants and
hotels, as well as foreign embassies, chances are that the food _
the meat for the filet mignon, the cream in the creme caramel _
comes from our plant.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's turned out to be a tremendous example of Western
capitalism at work in the heart of the former communist stronghold.
Cohon's story is fun to read, but his life is significant enough to
wind up in the history books.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Public Speaking for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   By Malcolm Kushner
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books, $16.99
</P>
<P>
   By now, the ``For Dummies'' series is in the American lexicon,
and it deserves the honor by communicating information on tough
subjects painlessly to its readers with lively writing and snappy
graphics. Now the series tackles the much-feared task of public
speaking. This book is written by a popular Fortune 500 speaker,
who is also an author and attorney. His first section is titled ``A
Crash Course in Influencing People,'' which shows how in tune he is
with his subject. A great book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Joy of Work: Dilbert's Guide to Finding Happiness at the
Expense of Your Co-Workers''
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Adams
</P>
<P>
   HarperBusiness, $12.95
</P>
<P>
   This book is mean _ but it's also pretty funny. In addition to
Dilbert cartoonist Scott Adams' ideas on how to tweak your office
life into something fun, he pulls from the thousands of workers who
e-mail him with their own ideas. One such writer tells how he made
a copy of a co-worker's car key and changed the preset radio
stations every day for three months. Funny, but pretty cruel,
especially because the guy went to the car shop four times to try
and get it fixed. If you like this kind of gallows humor, this is
the book for you.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Patton on Leadership: Strategic Lessons for Corporate
Warfare''
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Alexrod
</P>
<P>
   Prentice Hall, $23
</P>
<P>
   I'm not making this up, although with some of these book titles
I wish I were. This book is coming out on Veterans Day, no less, to
tie in with the whole military theme. Instead of much narrative,
this book is largely made up of 183 one-page lessons that could
have been on a daily calendar instead of in a book. It's
interesting to see such a book when most of the management thought
today is based on getting away from hierarchical thinking.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
