<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR WORDS AGAINST VIOLENCE DO LITTLE WITHOUT GUN CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after the assassination of John F. Kennedy, a man who
was then one of America's most despised leaders had microphones
shoved in his face as he was asked to give his reaction to the
death of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm X would utter words that not only repulsed most of the
country at the time, but would cause his own Nation of Islam leader
to ban him to silence for months.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Americans, Malcolm seemed to show no sign of
remorse, and unlike many politicians of the day, he did not utter
the innocuous overused phrase, ``I'm shocked and saddened.''
</P>
<P>
   The defiant black Muslim activist distinctly proclaimed in 1963:
</P>
<P>
   ``The chickens have come home to roost.''
</P>
<P>
   He was acutely accurate and, in hindsight, profoundly poignant.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Wednesday's tragic shootings in a Fort Worth
church, those words reverberate in the city where Kennedy spent his
last night before heading to Dallas on that fateful November
morning.
</P>
<P>
   No one really understood Malcolm X then, because no one really
tried.
</P>
<P>
   His comments weren't meant to be flippant during one of
America's most painful moments, nor were they intended to be
disrespectful of the slain president.
</P>
<P>
   He was simply saying that in a country where violence is so
prevalent _ sometimes revered _ and in a nation that was so
tolerant of hatred toward those who were different, we should not
be surprised when violence rises up close to home and claims one of
our own who is greatly admired, truly cherished or deeply loved.
</P>
<P>
   As with other cities in recent months, my hometown is in
mourning this day, befuddled by a catastrophe that no one ever
believed could happen here.
</P>
<P>
   On a Wednesday night, when church people all over the state are
in prayer meetings, the unthinkable happens in a house of God, and
we all begin crying, ``Lord, have mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   But in light of so many destructive acts against so many
innocent people, our doubts intrude on our good thoughts, and we
begin to ask, ``Lord, don't you have any mercy left?''
</P>
<P>
   This was not God's doing. It was man's. It was ours.
</P>
<P>
   We should have paid attention to the chickens, for they've been
headed home to the roost for some time.
</P>
<P>
   For years, in our blind and selfish arrogance, we have sent the
wrong messages to adults and teen-agers about violence, and then
feigned shock when our communities were rocked by random,
senseless, man-made calamities.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a state where politicians believe that during
campaigns they have to be seen with guns as big as their smiles,
shooting down some innocent critter.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected. How can you get elected in Texas these days
without proclaiming your love for guns?
</P>
<P>
   Just this year, the Texas Legislature passed a law prohibiting
government agencies, counties and municipalities from suing gun or
ammunition manufacturers. Gov. George W. Bush ceremoniously signed
the bill in May.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years earlier, the state proudly instituted the
right-to-carry law, allowing citizens to carry concealed weapons.
(I'm sure I'll hear after this massacre that if someone in the Fort
Worth church had been ``packing,'' this tragedy could have been
prevented or lessened.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Fort Worth leaders have expressed concern about the
regularly scheduled gun shows held in public buildings, they have
not voted to prevent these blatant displays and the sale of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   After a dreadful event such as the one in this city Wednesday
night, we'll hear plenty of words denouncing violence.
Unfortunately, our actions continue to speak loudly to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Above all the rhetoric, there will be a loud flapping noise ...
of the chickens coming home to roost.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is associate editor, vice president and
columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
