u e BC-TV-GAYS-HNS &LR;      09-16 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYS FIND ACCEPTANCE ON TV IS FOLLOWED BY STEREOTYPING JOKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gay characters were found on a variety of TV shows last season,
barely raising an eyebrow and not generating protests from
notoriously trigger-happy fringe groups.
</P>
<P>
   But as any gay person who watches television can attest, being
accepted is one thing, how you're portrayed is another.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that gays would gripe most about never seeing an
accurate loving relationship _ with kissing and at least the hint
of a regular sex life.
</P>
<P>
   But the new issue may be that gay characters are the buffoon or
mocked openly. After viewing the available fall programs, I can
tell you that your skin better be thick. Countless shows have gay
jokes in them, a concept that was unthinkable just two seasons ago.
Gays now can sit back with the Irish and the Italians and feel what
it's like to be out from under the politically correct shield.
</P>
<P>
   It's open season in Hollywood, a copycat town that apparently
has got the message _ across the dial _ that it's OK to make fun of
gays. Here's a status report, based on viewing most of the pilots _
expect a continued barrage as the season goes on.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Grown Ups,'' the UPN series starring Jaleel ``Urkel''
White, there were nearly a dozen gay jokes. ``The man knows all the
lyrics to `Funny Girl,''' says one character, about a gay roommate.
Another: ``The best six words I've heard all week: My wife has a
lesbian friend.'' The friend is not gay, and says: ``Just because
I'm single and played freshman softball doesn't mean I'm a
lesbian.'' To which White says, ``No, but it's a red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   In Fox's ``Get Real,'' a girl doing a voice-over mentions she's
got bad news for her parents. The camera shows a poster of the
Indigo Girls, and she says, ``And, no, I'm not gay. Get real.''
Later her grandmother mentions the ``lesbian'' poster and asks the
question.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBC action series ``Third Watch'' it's not clear if an
older fireman is playing gay or not. He grabs another's butt, then
later says, ``When's the last time you've been with a man?'' By the
way, he's the station-house cook. And he gets gunned down brutally
in the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   In NBC's romantic comedy series ``Cold Feet,'' a woman worries
that the man she's interested in is gay. ``I'm sure he's gay. He's
got orange pants.'' Her female friend says: ``Orange pants?
Definitely not gay.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's new David E. Kelley vehicle ``Snoops'' got some pre-pilot
buzz when it was suggested there was sexual tension between star
Gina Gershon (who played a lesbian in the film ``Bound'' and
appeared on the coming-out episode of ``Ellen'') and Paula
Marshall. Kelley said Gershon's role was written for a man. But
there were no direct gay jokes in the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   In CBS's sitcom, ``Work With Me'' a character says: ``We'll be
like Bert and Ernie _ but without the gay overtones.'' Another says
to a male co-worker: ``One day you'll meet a woman _ a woman,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Grow Up,'' an ABC sitcom, features a character who realized
he was gay after he'd been married to a woman. ``Being gay and
having a wife are incompatible,'' he says. ``Unless you're a
politician or a movie star.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ABC comedy, ``Then Came You,'' has yet another gay man
who was married before. ``We fought over the silliest things. I
hated her cooking. She hated my homosexual affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies Man,'' a CBS sitcom, has a male character talking about
how great it would be to be gay, saying he wished he had ``the
strength to stroke a man like a pussycat.'' There are several jokes
spun from that routine.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, these are just the pilots. If they've gone to the gay
jokes this early, they certainly will return. And you probably can
count on other shows making stereotypical gay jokes as well.
</P>
<P>
   The new series ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' the very funny NBC sitcom, has
two gay characters and such jokes are essential to each episode.
Many continuing series also have showed no signs of restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, ethnic jokes in the modern PC world of television are
almost always forbidden _ except if they're aimed at the Irish or
Italians or, to some extent, the Polish.
</P>
<P>
   What the ``acceptance'' of gays has created is a field day for
writers who want to tip over what once was a sacred cow. Granted,
even a few of the best shows use gay jokes. Some of the jokes are
even funny.
</P>
<P>
   But with all manner of ethnic groups protesting their lack of
representation on the airwaves these days, you have to wonder if
gays soon will follow, complaining about being so common that they
are no longer sacrosanct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
