<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ACTION-REVIEW-LADN     09-16 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTION-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ACTION' TELLS THE BLEEPING TRUTH ABOUT TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Tonight refers to Thursday, Sept. 16)  
BY DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Action'' is a ------- funny comedy, easily the
best sitcom of this ------- fall season. Sure, it may anoint pop
culture with the most deleted expletives since Nixon's Watergate
tapes. But what gets lost in complaints about how the show may
contribute to the coarsening of our culture is the fact that it
takes a knowing, acute and scabrously uproarious look at the very
people who are paid boggling gobs of money specifically for
coarsening our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Creator/executive producer Chris Thompson pours more than 20
years of personal experience into this satire of Hollywood hubris,
and the show entertains in the gleeful way in which it depicts
behavior that ranges from merely rude to outrageously appalling.
Our guide through this minefield of malice is Peter Dragon (Jay
Mohr), producer of schlockbusters who, as the series opens, is
coping with the failure of his latest action flick, the Christmas
release ``Slow Torture'' (alas, this means they'll never make
``Slow Torture 2: Now It's Unbearable'').
</P>
<P>
   Peter is related spiritually, if not directly, to Artie, Larry
Sanders' crass, irascible producer. It's not like the guy has
absolutely no principles _ for one thing, he refuses (thus far, at
least) to cast O.J. Simpson in one of his films, even though, as
Simpson's agent points out, children in Calcutta know his face.
Peter replies, ``Yeah, they know to run away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's fiercely devoted to his head of security and uncle,
Lonnie (Buddy Hackett, Mohr's hero and mentor). (Go figure: Mohr
and Hackett last appeared together in a sweetly charming children's
movie, ``Paulie.'' Their ``Paulie'' co-star, Tony Shalhoub, will
soon air directly opposite them on NBC's upcoming, and
significantly inferior, ``Stark Raving Mad.'')
</P>
<P>
   But for a guy ostensibly on top of the world, Peter's life seems
in shambles. His wife left him to serve as the beard for the gay
but far more powerful and vicious studio mogul Bobby G, the only
man before whom Peter, for numerous reasons, wilts and who pulls
the plug on his next film. His production company just mistakenly
paid a quarter of a million dollars for a script he hates. A minion
observes, ``We've bought crappy scripts before,'' to which Dragon
responds, ``Yeah, but that was on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter changes his mind when he encounters Wendy (Illeana
Douglas), a former child star turned hooker, on the way to ``Slow
Torture's'' premiere (in most sitcoms, couples meet cute; in
``Action'' they meet violent). He quickly assesses her as
invaluable simply because unlike the rest of his staff, she's no
sycophant. She tells the truth, and she happens to like that script
Dragon hates, ``Beverly Hills Gun Club.'' Peter decides to keep her
around; as the season progresses, we'll be party to the production
of Dragon's latest movie and see whether Wendy's script sense is
savvy enough to keep her off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Mohr is very funny as Dragon, who is pathological in his ways:
Even when confronted with unimpeachable evidence of the truth, he
evenly and assuredly insists on his lies. Douglas serves as a fine
foil.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its toxic laughs, ``Action'' represents a gamble for its
creators and Fox, the network airing it. Mainstream audiences may
have trouble warming to the vitriolic characters, the bleeped
swearing and the show-biz minutiae; it also must compete against
NBC's long-sturdy (but cracking) Thursday night lineup. And even
the show's champions will no doubt find distracting the manner in
which the series adheres to network guidelines and avoids showing
Mohr's potty mouth while he makes verbal poo _ swirling cameras and
close-ups on Mohr's eyes will get old quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But adventurous viewers more in tune with cable rather than
network fare will want to accompany Peter and Wendy on their
excursion through the Neverland called Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight will feature two episodes _ the pilot, featuring a cameo
by Keanu Reeves, and an episode not made available for advance
screening because footage with Salma Hayek was added a couple of
weeks ago (or, in the TV vernacular, at the last minute). At least,
that's the network's excuse for not supplying the episode for
review, but ``Action'' will tell you, those in the entertainment
industry lie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The  &LR; show &UR; : &LR;  ``Action.'' &QL; 
What &UR; : &LR;  Sitcom about amoral Hollywood action filmmakers. &QL; 
The stars &UR; : &LR;  Jay Mohr, Illeana Douglas, Buddy Hackett. &QL; 
Where &UR; : &LR;  Fox (Channel 11). &QL; 
When &UR; : &LR;  9 and 9:30 tonight (regular time slot: 9:30 p.m.
Thursdays). &QL; 
Our rating &UR; : &LR;  3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
