<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE WANTS IN ON THE `A' DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ran a big pension fund in a city where venture
capitalists and buyout firms were making money hand over fist, it
would be only natural to want to get in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what Massachusetts Treasurer Shannon O'Brien is
aiming to do. As head of the state's $27 billion public pension
fund, O'Brien wants to put more dollars into so-called
``alternative'' investments and boost returns as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sitting in one of the venture capital centers of the
country,'' says O'Brien. ``That is something we should be able to
take advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyout firms purchase stakes in private companies. Venture
capitalists provide seed money to brand-new businesses. Both types
of deals are considered alternative investments because they are
less liquid, less traditional, and higher risk than the stocks and
bonds pension funds typically purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The state's pension fund _ officially the Pension Reserves
Investment Management Board, or PRIM _ has been making buyout and
venture investments since 1986. At the moment about 4 percent of
the fund, or $1.2 billion, is tied up in alternative investments.
</P>
<P>
   Those investments haven't done badly. Over the past 13 years,
they have returned an average of 15 percent per year. Over the past
three years and five years, the returns have topped 20 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers haven't met the fund's own goals _ topping the
Standard &AMP; Poors 500 Index by 5 percentage points a year and
achieving results that beat 75 percent of comparable pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made money but we are poised to do better,'' says Scott
Henderson, PRIM's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The past decade has been a golden age for buyout and venture
investing. Buyout specialists like Boston's Thomas Lee and Bain
Capital have doubled and tripled their money on deal after deal.
Venture capitalists have sometimes done even better, especially
when they have put money into fledgling technology companies. When
Siemens, the German technology giant, purchased two small
Massachusetts companies in March, the venture investors turned an
$18 million investment into $160 million in 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Pension funds put up a chunk of the money the dealmakers use,
but in this world, just being willing to write a check is not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can get into `B' and `C' deals,'' says O'Brien. The
trick is to get into ``A'' deals, those offered by top names in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Getting entry to that exclusive club requires cultivating the
right people and demonstrating a long-term commitment to this style
of investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``PRIM has had a fair amount of turnover over the years and that
is not healthy for maintaining the critical relationships you
need,'' says Steven Galante, editor of Private Equity Analyst, a
Wellesley newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   PRIM executives concede as much. The pension fund was not active
in venture investing in the early 1990s, so when venture firms went
looking for money later in the decade, they did not have
Massachusetts on their lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not in the game and you have not been a reliable
investor, it is tough to break in,'' says Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Venture firms can be particularly choosy about whose money they
use because they do not need to raise as much money as buyout
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Massachusetts is not giving up. PRIM officials have
targeted a series of top-tier venture and buyout firms they want to
get to know better. O'Brien hopes the relationship-building process
will get an assist from some of the heavy hitters who sit on PRIM's
investment committee.
</P>
<P>
   They include Jack Meyer, president of Harvard Management; Allan
Bufferd, MIT's treasurer; and a new addition to the group, David
Swensen, chief investment officer at Yale. The elite universities
have been leaders in the alternative investment field.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced the time is right for putting lots of
new money into venture and buyout funds. They worry the eye-popping
returns generated in the field will attract too many eager
investors _ including PRIM.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a ton of money out there chasing a small number of
good deals,'' says Richard Charlton, president of New England
Pension Consultants, a Cambridge firm.
</P>
<P>
   But the state pension fund is committed to doing more. PRIM's
goal is to have 8 percent of the fund in alternative investments,
up from the current 4 percent. Given the nature of things, it will
be years before we know if that is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
