<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      09-16 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSULATION DOES A LOT TO SAVE HEAT, BUT NOT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (First of two articles.)
</P>
<P>
   There is no better time than right now to insulate your house,
or add to insulation already there. Why now? You'll see graphic
savings in your heating bills, and can compare your bill at the end
of the season with past ones to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   If you insulate everywhere possible in your house, the savings
in heat will be amazing. You can save up to 50 percent, depending
on what you do. Actaully, insulation alone does not do it all.
Insulation must work with vapor barriers and other ways of
buttoning up to be fully effective.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the weather is cool and dry, or should be, at this time of
year, so if you do some of the work yourself, you will be more
comfortable. There is nothing quite so miserable as laying
fiberglass batts or blowing cellulose in an attic floor in hot,
muggy weather.
</P>
<P>
   So, how to begin?
</P>
<P>
   Begin by wearing protective clothing: especially a respirator
and goggles. Clothing to potect the skin is also good, but not as
important as a respirator and goggles unless you are allergic to
fiberglass. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The five w's &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, begin with an old newspaper instruction for reporters. When
writing a story, the reporter must be aware of the five w's
essential to that story: who, what, when, where, and why.
</P>
<P>
   We can apply that to insulation, too.
</P>
<P>
   1. Who? You, of course, can do some of the insulating yourself,
if you have the time and inclination. Other types of insulation,
such as blowing insualtion in walls cavitgies, are best done by
pros.
</P>
<P>
   2. What? Insulation, and the type of insulation is predominantly
fiberglass. Another insulation for certain applications, such as
blowing in walls, is cellulose. A third type, rigid board
insulation, includes Styrofoam and polyisocyanurate (isn't that a
great word; it make one feel so smart), also called High R
Sheathing and Thermax, among other brand names. Rigid insulation is
good in certain applications such as places where fiberglass or
cellulose is not practical to install.
</P>
<P>
   Insulation is the least expensive of the building products, and
probably does the most good. Fiberglass and cellulose cost about 25
to 50 cents a square foot; the rigid insulations are a lot more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   3. When? We already mentioned when it is good to insulate, in
cool, dry weather. But insulation can be installed any time.
</P>
<P>
   4. Where? Any wall, ceiling, or floor that separates the heated
living space of a house from the outdoors or unheated space. These
walls, ceilings, and floors can not only be insulated, but in some
areas you can also add insulation.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, insulation was installed when the standards were
lower; less insulation was used. Today's standards are considerably
higher, so adding insulation is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   5. Why? To save heat. And, insulation will save on cooling bills
as well.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's go to work. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The attic floor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First priority is the attic floor, because it easy for the
homeowner to do and saves the most heat.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose there is no insulation there at all. If there are
floorboards, take them up and put them aside. And be careful
walking on those exposed floor joists; it is a good idea to put
down a sheet of plywood to stand and kneel on when working over
open joists.
</P>
<P>
   Insert 6-inch-thick batts, or rolls, of fiberglass insulation
between the joists, with the paper backing, which is a vapor
barrier, down, touching the ceiling below.
</P>
<P>
   One cardinal rule in insulating a house is this: Always put the
vapor barrier (paper or polyethylene) toward the heated part of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Six inches of insulation used to be standard; standard now is at
least 12 inches of fiberglass. So, after installing 6 inches, add
another 6 inches of unbacked fiberglass, and if the original 6-inch
inch piece comes up to the tops of the joists, or nearly so, put
the second 6-inch layer at right angles to the joists.
</P>
<P>
   A good insulaton for this purpose is Poly-Wrap, 8-inch-thick
fiberglass wrapped in perforated polyethylene, so it is not a vapor
barrier. The polyethylene of the Poly-Wrap (there are similar
products under different names) makes handling the material more
comfortable, and easy to position over insulation already there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Keep the soffits clear &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another cardinal rule in laying insulation on an attic floor is
to avoid putting insulation in the soffits, which are where the
roof overhangs the wall. If this area is filled, serious
condensation problems can occur, and if the soffits are ventilated,
it obviously blocks the vents.
</P>
<P>
   Remember those floorboards that you put aside? You can't put
them back with 12 inches of insulation in place. If you want the
floorboards in place for storage, you cannot insulate above the
joists. A compromise is to put the floorboards in a small area of
the attic, adequate for storage, and put 12 inches in the rest of
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   If there is already insulation in place, you can add to it; the
attic floor is one of the few places where you can add insulation;
other areas just don't have the room.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to take up the floorboards, you can have
cellulose or fiberglass blown in by a professional. Watch him like
a hawk to prevent blowing insulation into the soffits. When
insulation is blown in place, baffles are put at the end of each
joist space to prevent insulation from slopping into the soffit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ah, those cathedral ceilings &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you have a cathedral ceiling, and the ceiling finish
(plasterboard or other covering) has not been applied, you can
insulate that space by stapling 6-inch fibrglass between the
rafters, with the paper backing facing the room.
</P>
<P>
   But be sure to leave a 1-inch air space between insulation ion
and roof boards. To accomplish this air spce, staple Styrofoam
chutes to the roof between rafters before installing the
insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Serious moisture problems can occur if this is not done. To get
air flowing in tht space, install a ridge vent on the very top part
of the roof, and also soffit vents. Remember, the soffit is the
space created by the roof overhanging the wall. Vents go on the
underside of this overhang.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said it is easy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The basement ceiling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next place to insulate is the basement ceiling. This, too, you
can do yourself. But why bother, you might ask; doesn't hot air
rise, so the air in the house will not go down through the floor
and into the basement? And why not keep the basement warmer anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Hot air does rise, but heat will definitely pass through
an uninsulated barrier (the floor) into a colder area such as the
basement. And anything that warms an unlived-in basement is wasted
heat.
</P>
<P>
   So, insulate the basement ceiling. Apply 6-inch Fiberglass
insulation with the paper backing up, touching the floorboards
above.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the insulation in place with insulation hangers, also
called lightning rods (they have nothing to do with lightning),
which are pointed wires stuffed between joists and spaced every 24
inches. They come in different lengths to accommodate joists 16 and
24 inches on center.
</P>
<P>
   The basement ceiling is a good place to use the poly-wrapped
insulation instead of the 6-inch variety. It is 8 inches thick and
can be stapled. But it is not a vapor barrier. It is a good idea,
if you use the poly-wrapped material, to staple polyethylene
plastic on the floorboards between joists, as a vapor barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes someone will put in the insulation with the paper
backing down. This is wrong, but if you do it this way, or find
your basement ceiling insulated this way, it may be OK. Just check
behind that paper; if it is damp, or wet, then you know why it is
wrong; that moisture has been trapped in the insulation, and now is
the time to reverse it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Third priority: the walls &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third priority is the walls. Insulating the walls of a two-story
house is more important than insulating the walls of a one-story
house because you will lose less heat through the walls of a
one-story house than those of a two-story house.
</P>
<P>
   However, any insulation in the walls is good, and blowing in
insulation _ fiberglass or cellulose _ is best left to
professionals, people who do this for a living. Blowing tools and
techniques have improved over the years, so there is no fear of
sagging or settling of the insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Blowing insulation into an existing house is quite an operation,
because insulation must be blown into all cavities between studs,
and under and over windows, and over doorways. Workers first remove
shingles or clapboards at the right places and drill holes through
the sheathing. In oirder to blow in insulation properly, a hole
must be drilled at the top and bottom of each wall cavity between
studs.
</P>
<P>
   Workers then insert a hose into each hole for blowing, then
cover the hole, and replace shingles or clapboards.
</P>
<P>
   On brick houses, insulators can make holes in the interior
walls. They can also make holes in the brick, filling them later
with brick-colored concrete. This latter trick is not a good idea.
Those patched bricks will stick out like sore thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Drilling holes on the inside walls is not too bad, but remember,
the crewmen are insulators, not plasterers, and their filling of
the holes in the interior walls will not be so hot. But you can
smooth them out yourself, at your leisure.
</P>
<P>
   And as you enjoy fixing those hole patches, you can enjoy the
heat _ and money _ you are saving this winter, thanks to the
insulation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEXT: Plugging up any and all holes: vapor barriers, caulking,
windows, and doors. And sometimes, adding insulation. And don't
forget ventilation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
