<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4392 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-16 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALVAREZ UP FOR NEW CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The two most surprising teams in the 1994 World Cup
were probably Colombia and the United States. The Colombians failed
to meet expectations and their tournament ended in tragedy, and the
US exceeded expectations to form the basis for a professional
league.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Leonel de Jesus Alvarez Zuleta could not have imagined he
would someday leave Colombia to become a teammate of some of those
US players in their league. But Alvarez joined Major League Soccer
two years later and has become a fixture in the league, one of its
most credible and ardent advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez has adjusted quickly to New England _ he arrived in a
trade from Dallas Aug. 16 _ but the move has not been easy.
Alvarez's wife lost a baby after the first trimester, while she was
in Dallas and he was in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be better, but in life you face challenges,'' Alvarez
said Wednesday. ``And this is a time for a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, 34, has brought cohesiveness and experience to the
Revolution midfield, and he has also revived the team's fighting
instincts. Most of the time Alvarez is a subtle enforcer. However,
Alvarez can assert himself, as he did in confronting Edwin Gorter
in the second half Saturday after Gorter had been cautioned for
kicking the Revolution's Mario Gori in a game that ended in a Miami
shootout victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution hope Alvarez's influence can help galvanize the
team for Saturday's game against Columbus, as they trail Miami by a
point for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference with
four games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team you saw against Miami was not lacking in heart,''
Alvarez said. ``It was not like when we lost to Tampa, 5-1 (Sept.
4). If we are a little more ambitious and convinced of our own
abilities, we can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become more united since the Tampa game. Hope is still
there, and with support of the fans we can qualify for the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez has an enforcer's reputation, and indeed he has endured
some difficult and malicious threats. During the 1994 World Cup,
Colombia faced pressures that are to difficult to describe within
the context of the US sporting paradigm. Player Andres Escobar was
killed in Medellin after Colombia had been eliminated. But such
threats had been carried out before and have been since. Alvarez,
like anyone who played in Colombia's Liga Dimayor, knew players,
referees, and politicians could be equally expendable in a country
in the midst of socioeconomic upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   In the US, Alvarez has encountered just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '94, we thought we were going to win against the US because
we had won every time we played a friendly,'' Alvarez said. ``But
they won the important one, and it wasn't luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being in the US because there are a lot of good, young
players and they like it if you help them. Everything I do, I do
from the heart and it has been rewarding to work with these
players.''
</P>
<P>
   The first impression of Alvarez is that he is uncompromising,
even unapproachable. But fans and teammates are finding him to be
accessible and supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might not look it, but I am content,'' Alvarez said. ``I
would be happier if we were in a better position. But there are
other teams who are in the playoffs and we have much, much better
players and more quality than they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to be positive and keep our morale high. We can
win and we can win intelligently. But it is not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Jeff Causey, who was ejected from the shootout
Saturday night, will be eligible to play against Columbus . . .
Salvadoran striker Elias Montes will train with the Revolution for
two weeks before going to France for a tryout . . . John Harkes
(hamstring) is probable for Saturday . . . Dan Calichman suffered a
concussion in a collision with teammate Giovanni Savarese in
practice Wednesday at Babson College in Wellesley.
</P>
</TEXT>
