<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-FURYK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURYK IS OUT TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It must be a question he's constantly asked,
because Mike Furyk is ready with the explanation. Get out those
notebooks and pens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got it square going back, and he's got it square going
through.''
</P>
<P>
   That's it?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,'' he said. ``He won't hit it very far doing that,
but that's not his game. It's a simple swing. But that's his game.
That's his life. His swing is simple. His life is simple.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's not nuclear physics?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his swing. He makes it work.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of work, Jim Furyk was in the middle of some at the
practice range following the third round of the recent NEC
Invitational in Akron, Ohio. But he wanted his swing coach, so he
nodded to his father to hurry things along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get over there,'' said Mike Furyk, so the
interview was over. ``But it's a good swing. It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   There are millions of reasons to support Mike Furyk's
assessment, as in the nearly $6.5 million in prize money Jim Furyk
has earned since joining the PGA Tour in 1994. He's the most
consistent thing this side of a Hawaiian sunset, so steady, in
fact, that caddies have been known to call him ``T-4'' because he
is usually near the top of the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have another nickname,'' said Rick LaRose. ``I call him
ATM.''
</P>
<P>
   LaRose is the men's golf coach at the University of Arizona,
where future touring pros are as much a fixture of the landscape as
days without rain. ``But Furyk,'' said LaRose, ``had so much heart,
more than any player I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   These were talented Arizona teams in the early 1990s, so that is
a bold statement. Robert Gamez was the star attraction when Furyk
arrived, then along came studs named Manny Zerman, David Berganio,
and Harry Rudolph. And though Furyk played on an NCAA championship
team, that was overshadowed by the exploits of the archrival at
Arizona State _ Phil Mickelson. The gifted lefthander won an NCAA
individual title, then the US Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the lack of attention bothered Furyk, think again.
``He's the most down-to-earth, normal person,'' said LaRose. ``I
mean, I've never seen a guy with so much notoriety stay the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the notoriety is for the right reasons, said Furyk.
To the contrary, there is the matter of his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came out, it was the only issue anyone wanted to
talk about,'' said Furyk. ``If I shot 66 and came in to meet the
media, they would talk 25 minutes about my swing and five minutes
about the 66.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS analyst David Feherty jokes the swing looks like ``an
octopus falling out of a tree,'' and casual observers who wouldn't
know a 4-iron from a curling iron will tell you it doesn't look
right.
</P>
<P>
   Team Furyk is amused by it all. OK, it's not conventional. The
swing goes up, then out, then loops inside, but give them a little
credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that big a deal,'' said Jim, the son and student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's square at impact. And the key is, he does the same swing
every time,'' said Mike, the father and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk is the reason Mike Furyk quit the golf business. He's
also the reason he got back into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a club pro (in Pennsylvania), but after Jim was born in
1970, I quit,'' said Mike. ``I wanted to have summer vacations and
coach Little League, so I got out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the life of a salesman, though he never sold his son on
the game that now dominates his life. Jim Furyk bought that on his
own. ``He played golf because he wanted to play golf,'' said Mike.
``He asked me to help him, and I did, but he asked me.''
</P>
<P>
   There were countless summer days when Mike and Linda Furyk would
drive their only child to the golf course and drop him off. The key
phrase being ``drop him off.'' Jim was on his own to figure things
out and that mentality is still a hallmark of his success; the game
comes easier to many of his peers, but Furyk has never minded the
hard way to success.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no big deal if friends and teammates found immediate
fame while Furyk's first pro stop was something called the Hooters
Tour. He won and moved on to the Nike Tour. He won there, too;
twice. That got him to the big show and his first year saw him
finish 78th on the money list. Then 33d, then 26th, then fourth,
then third.
</P>
<P>
   He was so busy establishing himself on the PGA Tour, however,
that he didn't notice being noticed. That sort of snuck up on him,
which explains the strange feeling he had one day while driving
what was clearly marked a courtesy car. Suddenly he had this
thought: What if someone drives up to this car and peers in and
notices . . . Jim Furyk? Who is Jim Furyk?
</P>
<P>
   That's the side he gets from his mother, said LaRose.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of her in him. He always had a lot of common
sense and I'm sure it comes from her. He's been smart enough to
keep on being Jim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim is Jim. Give him credit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one is more committed to tournament golf than Furyk. When he
enters a tournament, rarely does he leave early. He missed 14 cuts
his rookie season, but since has missed just 21 in 134 events. That
includes a solid stretch in majors _ in 18 starts he has missed
just one cut while registering six top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, considering the depth of talent against which he
competes, but Furyk knows the critics are out there. They say he's
only won three times, low considering he's had 41 top-10 finishes
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I want to win,'' said Furyk. ``I'd trade in some of
those top 10s to get in the winner's circle. But I don't finish in
the top 10 because I want to finish in the top 10. I finish there
because I'm trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd like a little credit for beating Nick Faldo in singles, 3
and 2, at the 1997 Ryder Cup, and as he prepares to play again for
the United States in next week's matches at The Country Club, it
deserves mention that Furyk sets up as a premier match-play player.
</P>
<P>
   That's because he's so patient, so unwavering in his commitment
to his abilities, said Mike Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Jim does is play his own game,'' he said. ``He won't
overpower golf courses, but he plays hard courses well, where
there's a premium on par. He just doesn't force things.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a team concept, remember, said the elder Furyk, ``If
(Jim) is your friend, he's your friend and you don't have to worry
about him running hot and cold.''
</P>
<P>
   These friends range from the stars (David Duval) to the
unheralded journeymen (Bob Burns, Guy Boros, Berganio), to his high
school buddies, and they will tell you that Furyk is a Ford Bronco
and Pizza Hut guy, though Mike Furyk sounds almost apologetic when
he concedes his son recently splurged by buying a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, a crack in the image? Furyk joins another in a long line of
pro golfers with expensive toys?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an 18-foot boat,'' said Mike Furyk. ``It's not a ship. I
mean, there's no crew or anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
