<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-STORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF WIND BLOWS, THE COUNTRY CLUB FEELS SECURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ John Cornish had a feeling he might be
twisting in the wind before this Ryder Cup was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a surprise,'' said Cornish, chairman of The Country
Club's Ryder Cup Committee. ``When the Farmer's Almanac came out
for 1999, it predicted that we could have a bad hurricane season,
and that stayed in the back of my mind. Now it is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornish, and course superintendent Bill Spence, are not only
concerned about Hurricane Floyd, they're also keeping an eye on
Gert, the next in line. Although forecasters are now saying it
won't affect the Boston area, Gert could provide the big hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do everything possible to make sure this event
goes as scheduled,'' said Cornish, ``so over the next few days we
are going to be into crisis management.''
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: The Country Club at Brookline, host for the Ryder
Cup, beginning with practice rounds scheduled to begin Tuesday,
with match play starting Friday and concluding the following
Sunday, and the world watching. The event has been in the planning
stages for five years. The tickets have been distributed. Some
33,000 patrons are expected each day. More than 200 corporate tents
have been assembled. However, even the best of those are designed
to handle winds just up to 60 to 70 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   If Floyd or Gert come calling, the winds could be much higher
than that, and there is no telling where the tents could wind up.
Maybe in Worcester, the sight of the original Ryder Cupin 1925.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved machines and people into place to prepare for
what might come,'' said Bill Spence, who is in charge of making the
course playable. ``Losing trees could be a problem, but I have
confidence it won't be. We lost about 40 or 50 to a hurricane back
in 1985, and since that we have continued a very intensive tree
program. This past year, for safety reasons more than anticipating
any hurricanes, we have had continuous pruning by arborists from
Hunt and Hulteen. We have taken down all of the trees, and branches
on trees, that we thought might be hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, we had that April Fools' Day surprise snowstorm,
and when I drove up the driveway that day coming into the club, I
was really happy. We had done such a good job with the trees, we
didn't have any damage. Meanwhile, the Arnold Arboretum, which is
just a mile or so away, had severe damage.''
</P>
<P>
   If and when the high winds come to Brookline, the arborists will
swing into action. ``We have emergency lighting available and can
use it to work all night,'' said Spence. ``I am very confident that
no matter what we get, our golf course will be very playable for
this event. If we have to, we will start the cleanup process as
soon as the winds subside.''
</P>
<P>
   Water is already being drained from the seven ponds on the
property, in preparation for the heavy rain that might come. That
will allow the course to drain easier into the collection areas,
which will have been emptied.
</P>
<P>
   Cornish and his emergency planning committee of Spence, Ken
Burns, Mike Gilligan of the PGA, and Rich Kelleher from the town of
Brookline, have another list of potential problems to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get too much rain, and it is very wet, we will not have
parking at our three immediate local areas, Putterham (Meadows),
Larz Andersen (Park), and Allandale Farm. We do not want to do
damage to these areas. This is when our emergency parking plan will
kick in. We have a fleet of shuttle buses standing by, and they
won't be used unless it is for a parking emergency. If this
happens, people will be bused in from the parking lots at
Foxborough and the Dedham Mall instead.''
</P>
<P>
   The most unfortunate scenario would be for Gert to blow into
Brookline late next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a rain date agreement with the PGA,'' said Cornish.
``That would have the final day on Monday. Everything would be
pushed back to Monday. We wouldn't have more than one rain day.
Many of the golfers have commitments and have to leave town. The
matches could be reduced to two days instead of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, in Valderrama (Spain), there were very heavy
rains on Friday and Saturday. Matches were delayed late into the
day, and some could not be finished until the next day. If this is
what we would have to do, due to the weather, then this is what we
will do, but all of us will be doing a lot of praying until this
thing is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
