<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
Sept. 17. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   HUD _ Suddenly housing chief Andrew Cuomo is biting Sen. Kit
Bond in the leg, contending that despite his reputation in places
like Kansas City, the Missouri Republican is no friend of public
housing. 30. David Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD: Lead poisoning of children always has been a problem in
Kansas City, but it's only been in the past couple of years that
health authorities have taken an aggressive approach to prevention.
Armed with federal grant money, new equipment and tougher laws,
hundreds more children now are being tested, and dozens of homes
are being cleaned of lead. In some Kansas City zip codes, as many
as 26 percent of kids tested have high blood lead levels, which can
reduce IQ and cause learning disabilities, high blood pressure and
kidney damage. Photos. Alan Bavley. 44.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: The Missouri Senate begins debate on the partial-birth
abortion bill today. Twenty-three votes are needed to override the
governor's veto of the bill. Also checking on reports that Planned
Parenthood would immediately stop providing abortions if the
override passes. Will Sentell and Kit Wagar. 30. Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   HAIR. Scofflaws at the Renaissance Festival have been brought to
justice; the Kansas Board of Cosmetology shut down the festival's
hair weavers last weekend because they didn't have the proper
licenses. But wait: a federal judge in San Diego recently ruled
that requiring hair braiders to undergo hundreds of hours of
cosmetology training ``is irrational and certainly unreasonable.''
Could the ruling have an impact here? John L. Petterson. 15.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   MILES. Folo on the Miles Prentice - Kansas City Royals ownership
situation. Steven Rock. 15.
</P>
<P>
   GYM. Live coverage of World Team Trials gymnastics, women's
prelims. Howard Richman. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   CHIEFS. Dan Williams hasn't played an NFL down in nearly two
years. Williams, who held out the entire 1998 season in a contract
squabble, may see that streak end Sunday against the Broncos. If
Williams doesn't play because of a recent injury, we'll see how the
Chiefs continue to play without him. Randy Covitz. 20-22.
</P>
<P>
   GRIESE. The Broncos' Brian Griese threw three touchdown passes
in his debut as an NFL quarterback, and he was disappointed. Is
that a sign of great things to come? Jonathan Rand. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Anaheim at Kansas City, 1:05 p.m. David Boyce. 16-18.
Photos
</P>
<P>
   HANAK. Getting Jeremy Hanak from Louisville, Colo., was
considered a recruiting coup for Kansas in 1995. He's even the
subject for the Jayhawks' 1999 promotional poster. But he's bounced
from one injury to another throughout his career. Now, he gets to
return to nearby Boulder for a final time in his career. Bob
Dutton. 25-28. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   MUFT. Missouri's offense made the UAB game too close for
comfort. Blocking for the punt team handed UAB 14 points. Penalties
and ill-advised forces in the passing game, got MU 14 more points.
Looking for improvement? It has to come here against a point-happy
Western Michigan team. 15-18. Mike DeArmond.
</P>
<P>
   KSFT. Darren Howard is 2.5 sacks away from being Kansas State's
all-time leader in sacks. He got one against Temple. He could pass
Nyle Wiren this week. Kent Pulliam. 14-16.
</P>
<P>
   BKCOL. Column on Nebraska quarterback Eric Crouch. 18. Blair
Kerkhoff.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE BUDGET OFFER:
</P>
<P>
   Jazz-Mahogany: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just six years ago, Kevin
Mahogany supported himself by working as a data processor while
pursuing a dream: to be a jazz singer. In nightclubs all over
Kansas City he chased that dream relentlessly, applying his rich
baritone to the standard jazz repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he always sang jazz. Sometimes he lent his talents to
R&AMP;B or pop. But it all helped him to connect with audiences in
places like the Club at Plaza III and come to an understanding of
his gifts as a performer. And even when the dream seemed out of
reach, it was always on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mahogany, 41, is a star. A big man with charm to match, he
performs in such top-flight New York clubs as Birdland and Iridium,
is a favorite at jazz festivals nationally and internationally, and
has six well-received albums in the racks. In a critics' poll in
Down Beat magazine he was recently named Best Male Jazz Vocalist of
the year. Calvin Wilson. 1600 words.
</P>
