<HEADLINE>
ACID `ACTION' A SMART ANTIDOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ACTION 
Starring: Jay Mohr, Illeana Douglas, Buddy Hackett 
On: Fox 
Time: Thursdays at 9:30. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Action'' may be one of the most satirical shows ever to
puncture the happy daze of network TV comedy. It's a razor sharp
take on Hollywood, USA, where all the sharks have perfectly capped
teeth and Xanax dust around the gills. In the same nasty way that
HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show'' roasted late-night talkers,
``Action'' lampoons the amoral moneybags behind the violent
blockbusters that break box office records each week. It's a
cynical, adult half-hour that is so extremely uncute, we might be
wrong-headed to think of it as a sitcom in the way ``Friends'' is a
sitcom. Let's call it a venomcom.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of ``Action,'' which premieres Thursday, Sept. 16 with
episodes at 9 and 9:30, is that it's co-produced by Joel Silver,
the brash maker of bloated action flicks like the ``Die Hard,''
``Lethal Weapon,'' and ``Predator'' series. Silver apparently has a
sense of humor (or self-loathing) about himself and the absurdities
of his big-budget world, because the gags in ``Action'' revolve
around Silver-esque projects with wonderfully silly names like
``Slow Torture'' and ``The Beverly Hills Gun Club.'' And of course
there's the show's central character, a slimeball action producer
who has no conscience and who has acid running through his veins.
His perfect name: Peter Dragon. The perfect actor who plays him:
Jay Mohr, best known as the two-faced agent from ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   The premiere of ``Action'' is directed by Ted Demme, the
director of ``The Ref'' and ``Beautiful Girls'' who cut his chops
at MTV in the late 1980s. Demme brings all his in-your-face
music-video panache to the show right from the start, as Dragon
steals a studio parking space reserved for the Employee of the
Month, a commisary worker named Manny. Manny confronts Dragon, and
the camera swirls dizzyingly around them as Dragon flames Manny
with an obscenity-ridden (and bleeped out) rant: ``I've made 10
motion pictures that have earned this studio a billion dollars.
Unfortunately for you, I am the employee of the bleeping century.''
A few fast edits later, Dragon is breathing fire into his cell
phone, yelling, ``She can come to the premiere, she can come to the
post-premiere party, but she cannot come to the post-premiere
party-party.'' The show moves at Dragon's teeth-grinding,
amphetamine pace.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem facing ``Action,'' aside from its placement
opposite NBC's Must-See TV, is whether viewers will welcome such a
convincingly unlikable character into their homes each week. My
guess is that Mohr's Dragon will grow more sympathetic as we see
him increasingly subjected to the humiliations of the studio food
chain. The more you watch Mohr, the more you see his Dragon as an
oversized child whose sarcasm is born of insecurity and justified
paranoia. He knows all too well that producers are only as hot as
their last domestic gross. On the way to the premiere of his ``Slow
Torture,'' he's so nervous he vomits out the door of his limousine.
Later, he'll have to answer for his box-office shortcomings to a
gay mogul who happens to be married to Dragon's ex-wife. The bald
mogul, said to be modeled after Fox's Barry Diller, is famous for
his insanely large penis, which Dragon glimpses in one of the
racier scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The show also makes Dragon less abrasive by giving him two
quirkily likable consorts. He falls in with an unimpressed hooker
named Wendy Ward (yes, Peter and Wendy), who becomes his muse and
script reader. Played by the wonderfully wry-eyed Illeana Douglas,
Wendy is a fallen child star and recovering coke addict who is
actually resigned to not making it on the big screen. And Dragon's
benevolent limo driver and uncle is played with a hint of
sentimentality by none other than Buddy Hackett. The ``Action''
producers also promise plenty of funny, self-mocking cameos, like
those in the movie ``The Player'' and shows like ``Larry Sanders''
and ``Lateline.'' Keanu Reeves, who recently starred in Silver's
``The Matrix,'' shows up to goof on the low IQ of action fans while
Wendy performs a sexual favor on him.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Action'' was previewed for critics over the summer, it
has been hyped as either the savior of the fall season or the cause
of the decline of Western civilization. Originally created for HBO
by Silver and ``Larry Sanders'' alum Chris Thompson before Fox
scooped it up, it is an alarm clock of bleeped-out obscenities with
nonstop sexual situations and jokes about gays and Jews. (The
premiere has an ongoing confusion between screenwriters Adam Rafkin
and Alan Rifkin, with Dragon exclaiming, ``You're telling me we
spent a quarter of a million dollars for the wrong Jew?'') This is
a comedy whose main conceit of Hollwood is prostitution. What this
means is that parents should keep children away from the show,
despite the fact that it airs on a network, and not pay TV.
</P>
<P>
   But for adults, ``Action,'' which does not have a laugh track,
is a smart and healthy antidote to so much of the Hollywood puffery
that envelops us, from glitzy magazines and incessant ad campaigns
to the weekly box office contest. It is a frank depiction of the
vulgar battle that Hollywood is waging on our souls. And, as
``Action'' shows us, there are more than a few atheists in those
studio foxholes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
