<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-PAPERLESS-RESEARCH-AR     09-16 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERLESS-RESEARCH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIMINATING PAPER SPEEDS MEDICAL ADVANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As part of its ordeal to get permission to market its
drug to treat rheumatoid arthritis, Celebrex, G.D. Searle at one
point sent an 18-wheel truck to the US Food and Drug
Administration, loaded with pallets of paper records on 14,000
people who had participated in 61 clinical trials over a five-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   While computers seem to be everywhere in medicine these days,
with consumers able to go on line to buy Viagra and Prozac or seek
out medical advice from Dr. C. Everett Koop, the former US surgeon
general, they have been slow to make their way into the grueling
research and government approval process _ regarded by many as the
biggest roadblock in delivering medical advances.
</P>
<P>
   From drug makers and hospitals to physicians and insurers, the
health care industry is looking to get off the slow-moving paper
trail and somehow drive on to the Internet superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most conspicuous barrier is within the FDA itself,
which only began using computers eight years ago and still relies
on, literally, truckloads of handwritten paper documents from
patients, physicians, and other medical professionals collected by
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   And much of that data still had to be entered into a computer
system, with an army of people needed to make sure nothing was
missing and no mistakes were made in transcription.
</P>
<P>
   Watching this mountain of paper grow, several emerging
companies, including two in the Boston area, have begun working
with the FDA on procedures for electronic capture of patient
information in ways that would cut clinical trial costs, speed up
decision-making, and ultimately lower the price of new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   One is PHT Corp. of Boston, which is working with four of the
nation's 10 largest pharmaceutical companies on ways to capture
detailed patient information during a clinical trial using
PalmPilots, the hand-held scheduler and electronic mail device
developed by 3Com Corp.
</P>
<P>
   PHT, formerly Personal Health Technology, buys the PalmPilots
and strips out the business software, replacing it with custom
programs that record and transmit
</P>
<P>
   patient data via the Internet, first to PHT's own computers and
then to the pharmaceutical company sponsoring the drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Called the PlexxNet Patient LogPad, it is meant to replace the
unreliable paper diaries used in 20 percent of clinical trials
worldwide. The pitfalls in diaries are numerous, including patients
often forgetting to write down when they took their medication or
how they felt afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average compliance with paper diaries is about 50
percent,'' said James Becker, PHT's chief operating officer. ``That
means pharmaceutical companies have to throw out a lot of data from
participants. Some clinical researchers say that some participants
will fill out their diaries in the parking lot just before seeing
their physician.''
</P>
<P>
   With LogPads, he said, patients are required to report their
data daily via telephone modem. They respond to questions with
yes-or-no boxes; describe pain intensity by touching a point on a
simple graph; and indicate where they felt the pain by tapping on
an outline diagram of a human body. The unit can also be programmed
to deliver timely reminders for taking medication. Each patient
also can write a short message before signing off with his initials
and sending in their report.
</P>
<P>
   Becker and PHT cofounder Stephen Raymond say LogPad patients are
more conscientious, with compliance in one clinical trial that used
the units at more than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PHT charges pharmaceutical firms $300,000 to $400,000 for a
trial involving 200 to 300 patients, a fee that includes custom
programming and related computer and Internet services. Becker said
more than 1,000 LogPads will be in use by the end of this month,
most of them for early-stage trials involving pain, angina, and
smoking cessation.
</P>
<P>
   LogPad still requires training users, sometimes a problem with
elderly patients. But Raymond says the typical participant is
trained in less than 30 minutes. And if data is not sent in on
time, a manager knows this immediately and can follow up. Missed
days in paper diaries sometimes aren't detected for a week or more.
</P>
<P>
   Another start-up is Phase Forward Inc. of Waltham, which picks
up where PHT's LogPad leaves off. Phase Forward provides clinical
data management services for drug companies and the firms they hire
to conduct clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors or other health care personnel who work with patients
involved in these drug experiments type their records and
observations directly into desktop computers and send this data
instantly to Phase Forward, which then forwards these files to the
research administrators.
</P>
<P>
   This system replaces a hodge-podge of faxes, phone-call memos,
and paper records _ typically 50 to 100 pages for each of the
hundreds and sometimes thousands of patients who take part in
clinical trials _ with a single digital database.
</P>
<P>
   Once in place, that database that can be repeatedly used to
analyze, review, and verify information the trial is under way, and
then submitted electronically to the FDA for its review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting information on line where clinical trial researchers
could enter and access information directly could reduce the delays
and overall time needed for FDA approval by at least 25 percent,''
said Dr. Lee S. Simon, associate professor of medicine at Harvard
Medical School and director of clinical research in rheumatology at
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Bleicher, Phase Forward's cofounder and chairman,
estimates the current processing delay of 12 to 15 weeks that
follows each clinical trial could be reduced to two days using
electronic data captured over the Web. ``Right now about 10 to 15
percent of the clinical trials are done electronically, which we
think will climb to more than 85 percent in the next five years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Phase Forward's cofounder is Richard Dale, who previously worked
at Vermeer, a Cambridge developer of Web-based desktop publishing
software that was acquired by Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Bleicher, who once ran clinical trials for Alpha-Beta Technology
Inc. of Worcester, which is now out of business, spent 2 1/2 months
working with Dale to develop the company's business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Phase Forward charges $100,000 to $300,000 for its services
depending on the magnitude of the clinical trial. The company has
105 employees, and was launched two years ago with $400,000 in
private investment, followed by $4 million in venture funding from
Atlas Venture in Boston and North Bridge Venture Partners in
Waltham. It recently received another $8 million from those two
sources plus Sprout Group of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond clinical trials, other start-ups are trying to provide
more Internet tools to physicians, insurers, and hospitals with the
goal of creating a global network of computers for all players in
the health care system. For example, 10,000 PalmPilots are being
distributed to doctors nationwide by ePhysician, of Mountain View,
Calif., to use for direct submission of prescriptions to pharmacies
and access to results of lab tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
