<HEADLINE>
HERE SHE IS, SINGLE AND CHILDLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dee Dee, our all-purpose advice columnist, was thrilled to hear
that the Miss America pageant board of directors voted to extend
the eligibilty requirements to women who have been divorced or
pregnant, as long as they have no children.
</P>
<P>
   Now she hears the directors are reconsidering, because of
pressure from state pageant officials who are furious about the
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee doesn't agree with those fogeys who say the proposed new
criteria would lower the high moral tone of the pageant. Nothing
can sully the event. It's almost a religious experience. In fact,
it actually may be a religious experience, given the frequency with
which contestants mention the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Dee Dee thinks the pageant should bend even further
and extend eligibilty to women of a certain age. After all, they
keep saying it's not a beauty contest. But enough about Dee Dee's
thwarted ambitions. She's here to clarify as only she can the mass
confusion that has broken out about the proposed new elegibility
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I read that under the new guidelines, the Miss America pageant
would be open to women who've had abortions. Here's my question:
How did pageant officials know if contestants in previous years
hadn't?
</P>
<P>
   DUBIOUS, SNEEZEWEED, VT.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, participants were required to swear a solemn
oath and sign a contract stating that they had never been married
or pregnant. As I'm sure you know, a Miss America contestant would
never lie. The new rules, if adopted, do away with that
requirement, which, as Dee Dee sees it, has always been superfluous
due to the exemplary morals of all the contestants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the new eligibility rules for Miss America, is there a
limit to the number of times you can have been married? I ask
because I have recently been divorced for the third time. I have
written a moving song about my marital history, which I perform
while simultaneously tap-dancing and playing the marimba. I figure
I'd be a cinch to win the talent segment.
</P>
<P>
   SINGLE AGAIN, SHEEPNOSE, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   As Dee Dee inteprets the new rules, there's no reason a
three-time loser like yourself can't enter the pageant, as long as
she exhibits the the requisite high moral character. Go for it.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   I am enthusiastically male and have no current plans to undergo
a sex change. However, being Miss America has always been my secret
dream. Under the new rules will I be allowed to compete?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GLEN OR GLENDA, WINESAP
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may have been able to compete under the old rules, because
while aspirants were required to swear they'd never been married or
pregnant, they were not asked to swear they were female.
Personally, Dee Dee thinks it is very narrow-minded and sexist of
pageant officials not to allow men to participate. This is a
democracy. Every little girl, and every little boy too, should be
able to aspire to be Miss America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My husband is being very difficult about my plans to divorce him
so I can pursue my goal of becoming Miss America. I told him the
divorce is only temporary, but he stubbornly refuses to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   THWARTED, FEVERFEW, MAINE
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee thinks you must ask yourself if you see any kind of
future with a man who is so selfish that he puts his marriage vows
ahead of your dream of becoming Miss Anerica, the noblest calling a
woman can aspire to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
