<HEADLINE>
WITH LATINO BOXERS, FANS THROW CULTURAL IDENTITY INTO THE RING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes cultural differences box)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this corner hovers Melissa Soto, a Chicana born in East LA
who now lives in Boston. Across the ring, er, room, is Soto's
boyfriend, Juan Figueroa, a proud Puerto Rican.
</P>
<P>
   The two began dating six months ago. Then Oscar De La Hoya and
Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad came between them.
</P>
<P>
   See, De La Hoya and Trinidad are welterweight boxers. And De La
Hoya is Mexican-American; Trinidad is Puerto Rican. On Saturday,
the 25-year-old hunks will climb into a Las Vegas boxing ring, both
undefeated and with 55 knockouts between them. Their highly
anticipated battle has caused rifts in the community of Latino
fight fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going at it for five months about who's going to
kick whose ass,'' says Figueroa, 29. ``As a matter of fact, we
can't watch the fight together. If we do, that might be the end of
the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, a skillful but little-known Puerto Rican boxer has
been enthusiastically embraced by his American countrymen. In past
interviews he's cockily promised that once the pair enter the ring,
De La Hoya ``will visit the canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who fought his way into America's heart by winning
the gold medal in the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, is the darling of
the Chicano population. De La Hoya has heard the constant taunts
from Trinidad and he's all riled up: ``I haven't felt this way
since I fought (Julio Cesar) Chavez the first time,'' he told the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   As two very distinct cultures duke it out in the ring, this
fight is Boricua vs. Chicano, East Coast vs. West Coast, salsa vs.
mariachi, rum vs. tequila. In preparation for the big day, Soto and
Figueroa come out arguing. Ding. Ding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxers shouldn't be pretty boys,'' says Figueroa of the
handsome De La Hoya, causing Soto to screech in dispair. ``Trinidad
has wanted to fight De La Hoya for the longest time. De La Hoya's a
corporation. He's been fighting people to make money. Now that he's
made all the money he can't run away from Trinidad anymore. His
time has come.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, it's Soto's time. And she starts with an
apology, ``I'm sorry you had to talk to him first.''
</P>
<P>
   For Soto, De La Hoya is the local hero. She grew up in the same
East LA neighborhood as he did. She spouts the words ``role model''
and ``representative'' when she talks about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar was like the Latino fighter,'' says Soto, 23. ``Now this
fight is more than that because it's not just (one) Latino. Puerto
Ricans in New York and Boston can relate more to Trinidad. So, of
course, that's why they're more into him now.''
</P>
<P>
   For many fans, the upcoming fight is the most exciting boxing
battle in years. Think Muhammad Ali vs. George Foreman, Sugar Ray
Leonard vs. Marvin Hagler, and you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of decades ago in boxing, the top fighters in any
division would wind up meeting each other within one or two years.
Now it takes forever,'' says Angelo Figueroa, editor of People En
Espanol in New York and a former amateur boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's a tremendous amount of excitement,'' Figueroa
continues. ``And of course even though we consider ourselves (all)
Latino, it allows us to engage in national (heritage) pride for a
day as well. So, believe you me, it does create a bit of a rivalry
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilliam Rivera, entertainment editor for Latina Magazine in New
York has heard the ruckus. ``Puerto Ricans are like, `Yeah,
(Trinidad's) going to kick (De La Hoya's) butt and then Mexicans
are saying `Yeah, we're going to kick some butt.' It's really
scary,'' she laughs. ``The whole thing is funny because you think,
`We should all just get along.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The listeners of WNFT-AM (1150), the 24-hour Spanish-language
Mega Communications radio station in Boston, got along well enough
on a recent Thursday morning as they enthusiastically dissected the
fighters. Couched between advertisements, traffic information,
news, and a few merengue tunes, more than 30 people from aired
their views in the space of an hour.
</P>
<P>
   One Dominican said he thought De La Hoya would win, although the
caller had respect for Trinidad's skills. Another believed De La
Hoya would win with the help of his strong hook.
</P>
<P>
   A few callers said they thought De La Hoya was afraid to fight
Tito, as Trinidad is affectionately called. They believed De La
Hoya won a previous fight with Pernell Whitaker in a questionable
decision. Of course, the hecklers were Trinidad fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying De La Hoya lost,'' scoffs Maria Elena Verdugo,
station manager at Mega Communications in Charlestown, a
Mexican-American who had posters of De La Hoya decorating her
office when she worked in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all of those fights and he didn't lose any,'' Verdugo
continues. ``Whitaker gave him a very close fight, but it wasn't
given to De La Hoya.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every Latino toes the expected line, however. On Thursday
morning, Alejandro Miguel, a Puerto Rican on-air personality, tells
the listeners he's supporting Trinidad because of his fighting
abilities _ not his nationality. And several Puerto Ricans call in
and place their hopes on De La Hoya. Many are women, which gets the
on-air staff a bit riled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are choosing De La Hoya because he's pretty,'' says Mega
morning man Tony Ramia derisively, after one Puerto Rican woman
pledged her faith in De La Hoya's skills.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel scolds, ``It's the quality of the fighters, it's not
because he's Puerto Rican or pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a beauty contest,'' exclaims the third Mega morning
voice, Mega-Tonin Pimentel. But it is worth noting that these guys
_ all Puerto Ricans _ were chanting ``Tito! Tito! Tito!'' before
taking calls about the fight.
</P>
<P>
   That type of enthusiasm must be making people in Trinidad's camp
smile. For years Latinos have eagerly followed De La Hoya's
matches. He's got such a huge fan base that EMI Latin recently gave
the fighter a recording contract. Even Rivera, a passionate
Trinidad supporter, reluctantly reveals that she's seen most of De
La Hoya's fights. ``I have to represent,'' she says sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   This battle gives Trinidad a taste of De La Hoya-size fame in
the United States, notes Verdugo, who even admits to being a
Trinidad fan _ when he's fighting anyone other than De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   But when two favorites enter the ring, nationality can be a
deciding factor, as one caller noted in Spanish during her recent
on-air moment (a staff member translated her comment): ``If I
wasn't Puerto Rican it would be a draw for me because they're both
so good. But I'm a Puerto Rican woman and I have to go with the
home team and stick with Tito.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course there's even a disagreement about which group is more
loyal to its heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans are a lot more passionate about their people than
Puerto Ricans,'' says George Mier, the Puerto Rican program
director at Mega Communications. ``Since we're part of the US we
tend to, you know, be more Americanized than anything. So we go
with whomever. It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But get Verdugo started on the subject, and she exclaims, ``I
think with the fans of Trinidad it's more a nationality thing than
looking at the quality of the fighters. Because Trinidad is good
but if you look at the type of fights Oscar did, his track record _
there's a reason why they call him the golden boy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOW MEXICO AND PUERTO RICO DUKE IT OUT IN THE CULTURAL ARENA
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--PUERTO RICO &QL; 
 &QL; 
They call themselves: &QL; 
Boricua, the Taino Indian word for Puerto Rican &QL; 
 &QL; 
Food for thought: &QL; 
Asopao, a traditional gumbo of chicken or shellfish &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pop singers: &QL; 
Ricky Martin made Latin music hip with ``Livin' La Vida Loca'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hollywood Playaz: &QL; 
Jennifer Lopez sizzled with George Clooney in ``Out of Sight'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
We will rock you: &QL; 
Rock band PUYA wrote a fight tribute song for Trindad &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bestselling authors: &QL; 
Esmeralda ``When I Was Puerto Rican'' Santiago &QL; 
 &QL; 
Favorite Red Sox pitcher: &QL; 
Pedro Martinez (Hey, he's Dominican) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--MEXICO &QL; 
 &QL; 
They call themselves: &QL; 
Chicano, the once derogatory term coopted by US-born Mexicans &QL; 
 &QL; 
Food for thought: &QL; 
National dish mole is a sauce of chili powder, nuts, and chocolate &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pop singers: &QL; 
Photo of Luis Miguel with Mariah Carey shows he lives la vida loca &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hollywood Playaz: &QL; 
Salma Hayek wooed Will Smith and Kevin Kline in ``Wild Wild West'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
We will rock you: &QL; 
De La Hoya prefers mariachi to the Mexican rock group Mana &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bestselling authors: &QL; 
Sandra ``The House on Mango Street'' Cisneros &QL; 
 &QL; 
Favorite Red Sox pitcher: &QL; 
Pedro Martinez (Hey, he's Dominican) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
