<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGEON-FLAP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIGEON RACERS FEEL DUMPED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEYMOUTH, Mass. _ To Jim Gallagher, a pigeon flier from
Weymouth, his birds are thoroughbred racers and sleek, muscular
messengers of the skies.
</P>
<P>
   He gives them names like Ace and Baron and Pursuit. He keeps 100
of them in plywood ``condominiums'' in his mother's backyard. On
weekends, he and other pigeon enthusiasts at the Weymouth
Sportsmen's Club race against a dozen other pigeon clubs in the
Boston area. He remembers the time one of his birds flew 600 miles
from Ohio in barely 14 hours, through high winds and brutal heat,
to get back home to him.
</P>
<P>
   But to Weymouth's public health agent, the pigeons are dirty,
hazardous creatures who should never be brought near a club where
members meet and eat hamburgers and hot dogs and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a health edict, the executive board of the
sportsmen's club decided last month to oust the birds and their
owners, some of whom have been members for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a flap that has bitterly divided the 75-year-old sports club,
its board on Aug. 26 evicted pigeons and pigeoneers, citing unpaid
bills, stolen property, and health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Marino, Weymouth's director of public health, said he
concluded without inspecting the sportsmen's club that ``having
pigeons in a place where people meet and eat is categorically a
very bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Even clean pigeons can transmit salmonella and psittacosis, or
parrot fever, as well as bird lice, to humans. So he recommended
that the birds be kept outside the building, which is in a patch of
piney woods near the Braintree line.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, we're talking about a clubhouse, not a coop,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Animosities created by this health edict led the club's
executive board to terminate the membership of three pigeon
enthusiasts and suspend 27 more, said Daniel Affsa, a Weymouth
lawyer representing the board.
</P>
<P>
   The approximately 30 members of the club's pigeon committee are
outraged. They say the health charges have been trumped up to mask
an unethical power play by a few board members seeking to impose
their own, gun-oriented agenda on the membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bag job,'' said Peter Hultman, 52, Northeast regional
director of the American Racing Pigeon Union and one of the pigeon
enthusiasts whose membership has been terminated.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that pigeons are kept in the sportsmen's building
for only about 30 hours a year, when they are banded and inspected
before races, and when only other pigeoneers are present. Members
are fanatical about cleanliness and ``give them better care than a
lot of people ever get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the winged pests that gather in city parks and
line the eves of buildings, annoyingly dropping excrement on cars
and passersby. They are silkier, smarter, bigger, and more muscular
than their urbanized counterparts, and bred to fly at speeds of
more than 70 miles per hour for up to 15 hours a day. ``They're the
thoroughbreds of the pigeon world,'' said Jim Swindler, 77, of
Braintree, who has raised homing pigeons since he was 11 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In the weekend pigeon races, each bird owner sends up to 15
pigeons, which are inspected and banded and transported to an
agreed racing site, 100 to 600 miles away. Then the birds are
released. Bands attached to their legs record when they reach home
on a time clock, and results are tabulated and compared.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeon handlers over the years have included King Solomon, Queen
Elizabeth II, Roy Rogers, and Walt Disney. Since the days of the
Roman Empire, pigeons have been used to carry messages through
enemy territory, and they had a distinquished record in World Wars
I and II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Allied bomber carried a pigeon, and if the plane went
down, they'd strap a message on the pigeon's wing with the map
coordinates, so rescuers could find them,'' said Swindler, who
served in the Army's 282d Signal Pigeon Corps in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as he does on racing days, Swindler was sitting in a
rickety plastic lawn chair in his backyard, scanning the skies,
waiting for his pigeons to come home.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that morning, a friend had trucked about 30 of his
beloved birds to Palmer, about 55 miles away, and released them _
secure in the knowledge that, no matter what happened, they would
try to fly home.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the pigeons swooped down and landed on his rooftop.
And Swindler was all smiles as they cooed and chortled to their
mates and hopped back into his backyard coops.
</P>
<P>
   The homing pigeon's loyalty and proud history make the current
conflict all the more painful to the pigeoneers. They think the
birds are being blamed in a battle that is really about something
else.
</P>
<P>
   What precipitated the current controversy, they say, was the
defeat of a motion to change the requirement for sports club voting
privileges from five to two year's prior membership. Most of the
pigeoneers are longtime members, while gun owners are relative
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher added that the eviction feels especially egregious to
pigeoneers because about 25 years ago, when the sportsmen's club
was in dire financial straits, the pigeon people held raffles and
potluck dinners, donated property, and provided plumbing and other
services to fix up the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very personal stake in that building,'' he said. As
he spoke, some of his pigeons circled overhead, taking their
afternoon exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Hultman also said many of the pigeon handlers are deeply
offended by charges that they stole club property _ when they were
merely removing their own tables and chairs after they were ordered
out of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's trying to throw out the pigeon people,'' said Affsa,
the lawyer, who said the charges of stolen property and unpaid
bills ``may have been inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he said the executive board's decision must be
approved by a two-thirds vote at a membership meeting Sept. 29. At
that time, most of the pigeoneers ``probably will be welcomed back
into the club,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A welcoming spirit was not in evidence at an executive board
meeting Tuesday night, however, when officers locked their doors
and refused to discuss differences with Hultman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a parent corrects a child, sometimes the child cries,''
executive board member Donald Hunt, a former Weymouth selectman,
told a reporter earlier that day. ``Don't you know how children
are?'' he asked. ``They whine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They never talk to us as men,'' Hultman countered. ``We
respect their pistol-shooting hobby. But they don't respect our
sport at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
