<HEADLINE>
CHEAPER PCS CLICK WITH BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Jeffrey Miller, 34, marched into the grand
showroom at Microcenter recently with a shopping list: He wanted a
personal computer, a monitor, and some software. And when he was
approached by a salesman, Miller got right to the point about
price: ``I have $500 in my pocket. Point me in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   If you had demanded that price from a salesman a year ago, it
probably would have provoked eye-rolling laughter. But these days,
with PC makers slashing prices, Internet providers offering $400
rebates on computers, and some stores promoting ``free'' PCs, savvy
shoppers are feeling entitled to bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, 1999 purchases are up and low-priced computers make
up a far greater share of them. Many PC makers apparently came to
the conclusion early this year that they had to woo the low-end
buyer. Corporations and businesses did not seem to be investing
heavily in new upgrades, perhaps worrying more about getting past
the Y2K issue, and many people who already had PCs felt their
models were good enough for now.
</P>
<P>
   So vendors turned their attention to price-sensitive consumers
who could not manage the $1,000-plus hurdle in buying computer
equipment. First-time buyers are the overwhelming majority of
people taking advantage of PCs at cut-rate prices. These
bargain-hunting buyers include families with young children,
workers with yearly incomes below $30,000, and college students.
Others are seeking a cheap second computer for their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer markets are growing much more than the corporate
market,'' said Stephen Baker, senior analyst for PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   Sales numbers show it. Of all desktop personal computers sold in
July, 36 percent cost less than $600, compared to 3 percent in that
price range in July of last year, according to PC Data, a market
research firm in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   And 76 percent of the personal computers purchased in July sold
for under $1,000, compared to 50 percent the previous July.
</P>
<P>
   These bargain PCs have helped fuel a record-high volume in
computer sales this year. Unit sales are up 28 percent compared to
1998 sales.
</P>
<P>
   This banner year for price-conscious customers is occurring as
several major new and established companies compete aggressively in
this market. The deals are found at retail stores, as well as
through mail-order programs. One of the most popular promotions,
which became more widespread during the back-to-school rush and is
expected to continue through the holidays, is the $400 rebate on
computers from some Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Computer industry analysts say the cut-rate computers may help
push down prices throughout the industry, including prices of
higher-performance computer models. Analysts say the cut-rate trend
is certain to help bring closer the day when PCs become standard
appliances in nearly all American homes, which some predict could
happen in a couple of years. Currently, about half of households in
the country own a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tapping into a market of people who wouldn't have bought
before,'' said John Brown, research manager for the Framingham,
Mass.-based International Data Corp. ``They may have thought they
didn't need one. But now, if it's cheap enough, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Aliya and Ahsen Khan, a newly married couple in Somerville, have
established a $700 budget to purchase their first computer,
monitor, and printer. As recent college graduates on a limited
buget, they need every price break they can get and the low
computer prices allow them to consider some extras, such as a fax
machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that the market is coming down,'' said Ahsen Khan,
23, while price-shopping at Best Buy in Cambridge last week.
</P>
<P>
   The one catch with the hefty rebate offers is that customers
have to sign up for a three-year binding contract with the Internet
provider, which costs about $20 a month. But the $400 rebate goes a
long way, especially if a buyer chooses a low-end $400 computer
model. That, arguably, makes the computer ``free.''
</P>
<P>
   Another road to a ``free'' computer is provided by Free-PC.com
of Pasadena, Calif. This year it offered 10,000 free computers to
customers willing to watch constant on-screen advertising, but
buyers have to meet certain requirements, including being rich
enough to buy what the company promotes.
</P>
<P>
   The $400 rebate programs, offered primarily by Prodigy,
CompuServe, and Microsoft Network, have some risks. Consumers must
abide by the three-year agreement, although during that time,
Internet fees may plummet or other options, such as Internet cable
access, may become more popular. Early-termination fees are hefty,
sometimes up to the full cost of the remainder of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, some buyers like the rebate program because they
figure that, for now, they would be paying monthly Internet fees
anyway. And the $400 rebate generally can be applied to any model
in the store, whether low or high end.
</P>
<P>
   The low-end models, which are from new companies such as
eMachines as well as established players like Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard, are generally good for most of what people need.
The PCs offer word-processing functions, access to the Internet,
and the ability to play basic games.
</P>
<P>
   But consumers should beware of the warranty protections. Many
low-end makers require customers to send in the machine to an
out-of-state site for repairs. On the other hand, a model that
costs just a few hundred dollars more might be covered for repairs
at the local store where it is bought. A slightly more expensive
model may also provide faster speed, crisper graphics, and the
ability to play more sophisticated games.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Burkett, retail sales manager at Microcenter in Cambridge,
said he has found that most buyers interested in the bargain or
``free'' computers are young families and working-class people who
could never afford a $1,000-plus investment for a computer, plus
monthly Internet access. Most first-time buyers cite the Internet
as a primary reason for buying a computer.
</P>
<P>
   With rebates, these consumers can pay next to nothing for their
startup equipment. And many of these customers are used to living
from paycheck to paycheck, he said, so the monthly Internet-access
fees fit into the way they think about budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think in terms of monthly bills, just as they might auto
insurance,'' he said. ``And now, they just have to figure out
whether they can put $20 more a month in their budget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
