<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-WOMEN-LEADERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE WOMEN AT SUMMIT IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Never before has a state government been led
entirely by women _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   The Granite State, long a bastion of Yankee tradition and
political conservatism, now has a woman governor, House speaker and
Senate president. It's something of an historic moment _ not that
any of the three women is particularly excited about it.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, Republican Donna Sytek, shrugs and calls it ``a
historical footnote.'' The Senate president, Democrat Beverly A.
Hollingworth, similarly attaches no great significance to the
milestone, pointing out New Hampshire has long had many women in
its Legislature. ``It's something to be expected,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Shaheen, the two-term Democratic governor, is only
slightly more enthusiastic. ``For years, nobody thought anything of
having three men in these positions,'' she said. ``Now, it sends a
subtle message that that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But scholars who study state government sense that something
important could grow out of what has happened here. The New
Hampshire example could encourage more women to run for public
office, bringing more gender balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be a woman president until enough women are
considered viable candidates and put themselves up for candidacy,''
said Cindy Simon Rosenthal, a political science professor at the
University of Oklahoma and the author of ``When Women Lead,'' a
book about the leadership style of women politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal argues that women politicians tend to be less
aggressive and more collaborative in their leadership styles. They
like to listen and talk things out, rather than force a vote. They
aim for solutions that create more winners than losers. And they
tend to concentrate more on issues that affect women and children,
such as education. But she acknowledged, also, that not all issues
can be solved by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some problems don't lend themselves to discussion and
collaboration and sometimes you just have to bite the bullet,''
Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire leaders know all about that.
</P>
<P>
   The question that hangs over their heads is whether they can
break the gridlock that brought the House, Senate and executive
branch to a standstill for much of this year. A statewide property
tax to relieve the education funding crisis resulted in a $100
million budget shortfall, and lawmakers have bitterly disagreed
over how to close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Sytek wants to cut the state budget to eliminate the $100
million deficit. Shaheen would like to institute a capital gains
tax and to legalize video poker at the state's racetracks.
Hollingworth, meanwhile, vigorously opposes gambling and would
prefer an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Sytek is pessimistic that a consensus is more likely, just
because Hollingsworth has succeeded the late Clesson ``Junie''
Blaisdell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't changed since Junie died. People haven't
changed their positions,'' Sytek said. ``So we're facing the same
intractable problems we faced when we went into recess with a
different president of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that Hollingworth was elected by the same
coalition of Democrats and Republicans who elected Blaisdell.
``It's not a dramatic change,'' Sytek said. ``The Senate president
will wear more colorful clothes now.''
</P>
<P>
   That three women would rise to leadership in New Hampshire was
not entirely unexpected. New Hampshire has always fielded a
volunteer legislature, the largest in the nation. State
representatives and senators earn $100 a year, to help defray their
expenses. That means that the two chambers have been made up of
retirees with time on their hands, people who are independently
wealthy, and many women whose husbands are the family breadwinners.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for the American Woman and Politics at
Rutgers University, the Granite State has the nation's sixth
highest percentage of women lawmakers at 31.6 percent. Washington
state is first with 40.8 percent, and Alabama is last with 7.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pound, the executive director of the National Conference of
State Legislatures, said women are gaining seats in the
legislatures at a rate of about 1 percent a year. Currently, the
average percentage of women elected to state government is 22
percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Shaheen, Sytek and Hollingworth, the rise to power came
after years in the Legislature. Shaheen, 52, was first elected to
the state Senate in 1990 from Madbury. Sytek, 54, was elected to
the House from Salem in 1977, during a special election. And
Hollingworth represented Hampton in the House and now the Senate
for the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hollingworth ran a seasonal business, a beach motel that allowed
her to participate in the legislature the rest of the year.
Shaheen's husband worked as a lawyer and a judge, giving her the
financial flexibility to get involved in politics. And until
Sytek's daughter was ready to go off to college, her family was
able to make do on just her husband's salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this has a great deal of honor to be here, this is a
low-paying job,'' said Hollingworth, who got a raise from $100 to
$125 a year for winning the Senate presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Why do they stick with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all interested in seeing the state run as efficiently
and as well as possible,'' said Shaheen. ``Obviously, that doesn't
mean our philosophical differences will go away just because all of
a sudden there are three women in these positions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
