<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMMONIA AND WATER COULD CLEAN BLEACH STAIN ON GLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I cleaned old siding with bleach and TSP, but spilled some on
new glass doors. How can I remove it?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BUTKE, Shrewsbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have not tried anything, a strong solution of ammonia
and water may do it. If not, it means the TSP and/or the bleach,
but more likely the TSP, may have etched the glass; cleaning
products like Fantastic, for instance, can etch glass.
</P>
<P>
   First, try washing the glass with vinegar. If no go, try Du
Pont's rubbing compound, or Never Dull Magic Wadding, sold in some
hardware stores. Finally, try washing with Zud or Lime-Away, sold
in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Try these suggestions one at a time, and do not combine any of
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I installed 6 inches of fiberglass insulation in a crawl
space ceiling where the crawl space was 4 feet from ground to
joists. That was easy. In an area where the joists are just 6
inches above the ground, I took up the floor and put down 6-inch
fiberlgass with the paper vapor barrier stapled to the tops of the
joists. That was easy, too, but after I put the floorboards back
down, I realized that I did not put poly on the ground under those
joists, to keep water vapor from migrating up through the earth and
into that space, where it could cause decay. Is it really necessary
to put the poly on the ground? I am not happy at the prospect of
ripping everything out and putting it back after I put down the
poly.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD BODURTHA, Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well . . . let's put it this way: You were concerned enough
about it to call the handyman, and you will continue to be
concerned no matter what the handyman says. Therefore, you will not
be happy until you install the poly, as odious as the work is.
</P>
<P>
   So that is what I suggest. If you leave it as is, you run the
risk of water vapor getting in that space and rotting out the
joists, a distinct possibility. Ventilating that space is difficult
and iffy because it is so shallow. If the space opens into the
basement or a crawl space, and the basement or crawl space is
ventilated, it should take care of air flow in that restricted
area.
</P>
<P>
   So, bite the bullet, throw down the gauntlet, grit your teeth,
and do it. You will be glad you did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for an adhesive to bond vinyl to concrete. I
have some vinyl treads I'd like to glue onto concrete steps. I
tried a kind of contact cement that did not work.
</P>
<P>
   EDWARD McKENNA, Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Contact cement was not the thing to use, as you found out. It
is unlikely to stick to either material. But you can try an
adhesive caulk. One type is called Pheno-Seal, and it should work
with the vinyl tread because it is a phenolic-vinyl caulk. It also
should work on concrete. The caulk comes in a caulking cartridge,
so it is an easy matter to apply the material from a caulking gun.
Apply several beads of the caulk on the concrete where the tread
will go, then press the tread in place, so that the tread flattens
those beads. I don't think there is any need to put a weight on the
treads, but it won't hurt. Let the adhesive caulk set overnight. Be
sure to apply a bead of caulk at the perimeter of the tread to keep
out water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I had my chimneys swept, the chimney sweep could not get
his brush through one of the flues. Then he discovered a stovepipe
going crossways through the chimney and blocking most of it. The
pipe was for an old kitchen stove, now long gone, and the opening
in the chimney was covered. The blockage does not seem to be
affecting the gas-fired hot water heater. Should that pipe come
out? I'd hate to have to break into the wall again. The sweeps
found no deterioration in the masonry but recommended I install
flue liners.
</P>
<P>
   M.D., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a shame you have to break into the wall, but that is the
only way you will get the pipe out, and I think it should be
removed because it is blocking two-thirds of the flue. Once it is
removed, you have to brick up the opening in the chimney with brick
and mortar. Then you can fix the hole in the wall that you made to
get the pipe out.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you can do this yourself, and save a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   As for installing new flue liners, it is not only a good idea
but may be required, because both flues are serving gas burners.
Burning gas creates a lot of water vapor, which, if it condenses in
the chimney, combines with soot and other fire byproducts to form
an acid that will degrade the bricks or clay flue liners of the
chimney. A stainless steel or aluminum flue liner will prevent
this.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The treads of my outside brick stairway have lost mortar, and
I am reluctant to take them apart to repoint. Do I need a bonding
agent for this work?
</P>
<P>
   JIM SEE, Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Good news. You don't need a bonding agent when you repoint,
and you don't have to take apart the steps, either. You only have
to chip out the old mortar to 3/4-inch deep and as wide as the
joint, and press in new mortar. You don't have to chip out mortar
where the mortar is sound. Buy Sakrete Mortar Mix at a building
store, add water to make a crumbly, not soupy, mix, and press it in
the joint. Press heavily; weakly applied mortar will fail quickly.
A bonding agent is necessary when a thin layer of concrete is
applied over an old layer, such as a floor, patio, driveway, walk,
or even a vertical wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
