<SLUG> BC-ROBIN-WILLIAMS-IN-JAKOB-THE-LIAR-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JAKOB'S' LEADER: ROBIN WILLIAMS FINDS LAUGHTER IN HELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Robin Williams
in ``Jakob the Liar.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Last year, ``Life Is Beautiful'' proved that there's no place so
grim that laughter can't be found there _ not even a Nazi
concentration camp.
 &HT;    Now, a year after Italian writer/director/star Roberto Benigni
became Hollywood's latest darling by masterfully mixing tears and
laughs in a Holocaust setting, Robin Williams _ considered by many
to be America's funniest man _ is out to prove that there's more
where that came from.
 &HT;    Don't assume that Williams is trying to cash in on Benigni's
success, or that his new film, ``Jakob the Liar,'' isn't the
biggest risk of his career. Williams had already begun shooting
``Jakob'' in Hungary and Poland by the time ``Life Is Beautiful''
exploded at the box office, and he'd committed to the film at a
time when the blending of humor and the Holocaust was anything but
money in the bank.
 &HT;    The actor admits that at first he was edgy about tackling the
tragicomic novel by Polish-born Jurek Becker, who spent much of his
youth in the Lodz ghetto and wrote his book while living in East
Germany. It has been filmed before, incidentally _ a
German-language adaptation won a Silver Bear award at the 1974
Berlin Film Festival.
 &HT;    The current film, which will open on Sept. 24, co-stars Alan
Arkin, Bob Balaban, Michael Jeter, Armin Mueller-Stahl and Nina
Siemaszko. Set in 1944 in a Nazi ghetto somewhere in Poland, it
casts Williams as Jakob Heym, who almost despite himself ends up
passing on encouraging radio reports to his friends in the ghetto _
news of German losses and the approaching end of the war which is,
unfortunately, entirely fictitious.
 &HT;    ``He keeps making up stuff to keep it going because people
become really dependent on it,'' Williams says. ``He has a vivid
imagination, fabricating news of German defeats, American
intervention mixed with tall tales of Benny Goodman and the Andrews
Sisters showing up to entertain the advancing allies.
 &HT;    ``Of course he doesn't have a radio,'' Williams adds, ``and he
risks arrest and certain death by spinning these tales. His stories
are lies, but they keep hope and humor alive, and the suicides in
the ghetto stop so long as he keeps inventing good news.''
 &HT;    The actor's wife, Marsha Garces Williams, is one of the film's
producers. She was the one who first read the novel and thought of
Jakob as a perfect role for Williams. She showed him the book, and
both were moved by the story, and particularly by the way the
ghetto dwellers managed to carry on despite the atrocities playing
out around them.
 &HT;    ``Humor was an important part of them going on,'' Williams says.
``It's weird to think of people still having a sense of humor in
the face of that, but they did.
 &HT;    ``Even the Holocaust survivors who read the script said, `Don't
be afraid of it, because that existed,''' he says. ``Despite
suicides and shootings, they would still have concerts and
productions. As a species, there's a kind of gallows humor that we
know exists.
 &HT;    ``Do I get afraid of it? A little bit,'' he admits. ``Will I
fail sometimes with it? Will it be in bad taste? Occasionally. But
I know people in the most extraordinarily horrific situations will
still have moments of comedy. It's that somehow-surviving vestige
of humanity that keeps you going in the face of atrocity.''
 &HT;    The question of balance was pivotal to the script, he says.
Becker's novel goes back and forth between humor and tragedy, with
brutal scenes of Nazi violence placed cheek-by-jowl with ordinary
scenes of everyday life in the ghetto.
 &HT;    ``There is a sense of sadness to Jakob,'' Williams says. ``He's
lost his wife. He's gone through a lot of different things, and yet
he still carries on _ he's still a survivor.''
 &HT;    At the beginning of the story, Williams says, Jakob doesn't even
see himself as Jewish.
 &HT;    ``He says, `I'm not, I don't light the candles on Shabbat,'''
the actor explains. ``But to the Gestapo, he's the biggest Jew
there ever was. He thought of himself always as Polish, and then
he's forced to be here. In a weird way, he finds out how Jewish he
really is.''
 &HT;    It's a particularly challenging role, one unlike any Williams
has done before. But that in itself isn't too unusual for an actor
who began as a standup comedian and has since refused to be
pigeonholed, establishing himself in everything from the zany
comedy of ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' (1987) and the moving drama of
``Awakenings'' (1990) to Disney's animated ``Aladdin'' (1992) and
even a 1988 Broadway stint in Samuel Beckett's bleak comedy,
``Waiting for Godot.''
 &HT;    In keeping withhis reputation for the unexpected, the
47-year-old Williams announced at the Toronto Film Festival in
mid-September that he may return to performing live on stage.
 &HT;    Which doesn't mean an end to his film career, of course. After
finishing ``Jakob'' he filmed Disney's ``Bicentennial Man,''
reteaming with Chris Columbus, who directed Williams' hit ``Mrs.
Doubtfire'' (1993). Due to open in December, the film casts him as
a robot who gradually becomes more human.
 &HT;    Next year he'll go serious again to star in ``Damien of
Molokai,'' the story of a Belgian priest who cared for lepers in
Hawaii in the late l800s.
 &HT;    Making ``Jakob the Liar'' was something of a labor of love,
Williams says, because it allowed him to run the whole gamut of
humor.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes it's a black comedy, sometimes it's physical,
sometimes it's medicine _ different types, different forms,'' he
says. ``Sometimes it can be outrageous, and sometimes it's so
subtle.''
 &HT;    And he hopes audiences will come away from the picture with a
lot more than a few giggles.
 &HT;    ``The humanity of it,'' he says. ``A memory of people, a memory
of lives. It's a very intimate portrayal of life in the face of
death.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Jakob the Liar,'' consult the
official Website at www.sony.com/jakobtheliar. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
