<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-PROFILE-WOLF-BOS &LR;      09-16 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PROFILE-WOLF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE LEFT NO DOUBT WHO CALLS THE SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Only one federal judge in Massachusetts has summoned
to his courtroom two different US attorneys as well as the regional
boss of the FBI for on-the-spot tongue-lashings.
</P>
<P>
   And only one federal judge has trooped a parade of lawyers in a
major Mafia case into the courthouse pressroom to personally
deliver a ruling he thought reporters should cover.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Mark L. Wolf, the jurist who crafted the
661-page decision that keeps intact criminal charges against the
region's top mobsters, likes to be in charge, reigning at his own
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf clearly relished directing the spectacle that played out in
his courtroom for most of last year, overseeing a cast of FBI
agents, and the occasional mobster, summoned to the witness stand
to talk about the shadowy world where lawmen and outlaws meet.
</P>
<P>
   And while Wolf is known for devoting vast time and effort to
every task, from devising court policies on indigent defendants to
selecting high school interns, he has plunged into no subject more
deeply than the New England Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 52-year-old Reagan appointee has in his 14 years on
the bench become the de facto Mafia judge. Uncannily, Wolf has
drawn one racketeering case after another in the court's
computer-monitored lottery, and he has handled each with a singular
devotion _ some say bordering on obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's paid to decide cases, not to crusade against the
government,'' said one former federal prosecutor not involved in
this case. ``This Whitey Bulger thing is important, but so are a
lot of other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision was a year in the making and nearly five
years after the hierarchy of the region's Irish and Italian mobs
was charged with extortion and racketeering. That period was five
times the median length of time it takes for a criminal case to be
resolved in the nation's federal courts, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   And the case isn't over. As Wolf writes in his 74-page summary:
``This case has been pending for almost five years. The defendants'
motions to dismiss and to suppress have been the subject of
intensive litigation for more than two years. Nevertheless, the
merits of (Stephen ``The Rifleman'') Flemmi's motion to dismiss
cannot yet be decided. Thus the present posture of this case may be
disappointing to the parties and to the public, as it is, frankly,
to the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: more hearings.
</P>
<P>
   That intense level of involvement in so many Mafia cases may
have imparted a sense of personal outrage in Wolf when he
discovered that he, too, had been in the dark in the past when
deciding on wiretaps and prison terms without knowing that Flemmi,
James ``Whitey'' Bulger, and Angelo ``Sonny'' Mercurio were FBI
informants.
</P>
<P>
   But Wolf supporters say his motivation for hauling in
prosecutors and agents to face tough and embarrassing questions was
focused solely on the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most public-spirited person I have ever met,'' said
Michael Kendall, a former Wolf protege in the US Attorney's office
who has shared an interest with him in aiding Southeast Asian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Even Richard S. Swensen, former special agent in charge of the
Boston office of the FBI, found merit in the public flogging. ``The
judicial airing of allegations in this matter, albeit at a slow
pace, might have been healthier than letting them be whispered
about and festering below the surface,'' said Swensen, who heads
the Boston office of Investigative Group International.
</P>
<P>
   To some, Wolf's glacial pace is grounded in profound concerns
about being overturned on appeal. The result: exhaustive compiling
of testimony leading to down-the-middle rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You brief about briefing, that's the Wolfian problem,'' said
one lawyer not involved in the present case. ``You have a hearing
to decide on what to brief, and you brief on what the hearing will
be about. It's endless.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice, say Wolf's fans and critics, was born of painful
experience. It was Wolf, as an assistant in William Weld's US
Attorney's office, who aggressively investigated the Kevin White
administration, prosecuting Theodore Anzalone, White's one-time
chief fund-raiser. Anzalone was convicted of money laundering, but
the US Court of Appeals for the First Circuit overturned the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   As a judge, Wolf took great pains in the sentencing of Mafia
boss Raymond J. ``Junior'' Patriarca, only to be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Some defendants, particularly Patriarca, have applauded Wolf for
treating them respectfully. But some people who have worked closely
with Wolf tell a different story. Law clerks say they have had to
ask permission before going to lunch or running an errand.
Witnesses have missed vacations or been forced to stay overnight
because of easily avoidable scheduling problems.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, who lives in Weston, graduated from Yale University and
Harvard Law School. He is married and has two sons.
</P>
<P>
   While criminal defense lawyers have applauded Wolf for probing
the dark corners of FBI conduct, some were disappointed that he
stopped short of punishing the government by dropping charges or
seriously weakening the case against the last generation of
big-name gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Wolf is an extraordinarily bright judge, but I don't
think he or any other judge would have the courage to do what needs
to be done in that case,'' said Patriarca's lawyer, John F.
Cicilline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
