<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVEN IS NEARER THAN WE THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Lynn had foreign house guests this summer, a young man
and woman who consider themselves full-time peace walkers. Marcus
and Atsuko spent last winter with a group walking from Auschwitz to
Hiroshima to commemorate the 50th anniversary of World War II and
to stir the conscience of the world. Then the two of them came to
Marblehead to continue their peace work and to earn a little money.
They arrived with nothing but the clothes on their backs and a
small backpack each, the sum total of their worldly goods. In the
weeks that followed, Atsuko tutored Japanese students at Salem
State College in English. Marcus, an Australian by birth, assisted
a stone mason.
</P>
<P>
   When fall arrived, they decided they had earned enough to drive
across the United States. There was only one problem. They had no
car. As such things go, however, fate intervened on their behalf.
Atsuko ran into a student whose car was so pathetic he was thinking
of ditching it. It was easy for her to persuade the desperate young
man to give the car to her and, confident of Marcus's skills with
an engine, the two of them set off at the end of August with their
two small backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn got a card a week later.
</P>
<P>
   It said: ``This car is near heaven!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe that?'' Lynn said to me in disbelief. ``The
car's already broken down twice, you know, and they're thrilled
that they've managed to cover 500 miles. Isn't that amazing?''
</P>
<P>
   We sat in Lynn's yard, contemplating Atsuko's words. It was
suddenly clear, in a way I'd never seen before, that the quality of
what you have makes much less difference to your enjoyment than
your attitude. If someone had offered them a chauffeur-driven limo,
Atsuko and Marcus couldn't have been more pleased. Their excitement
came, not from the car itself, but from their own overflowing
gratitude at finally having ``wheels.'' I shouldn't have been
surprised. All summer long, I'd noticed that they displayed an
acute appreciation of material benefits _ like bagels and lox for
breakfast _ that most of us, buried under an avalanche of things,
seem to have lost.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, an aunt warned me that the love of camping my husband
and I shared was doomed to end. ``As you get older, you'll want the
comforts of home,'' she prophesied, dismayed by our unheated,
unplumbed, unelectrified shelter in Vermont. As time goes by,
however, my husband Jack and I love it even more for the very
reason that Atsuko and Marcus love their car so much. When things
don't come easy, when you have so little that any small improvement
is earth-shaking, when you have to struggle to obtain a favorable
outcome, you find yourself filled with a dizzying delight that a
simple purchase cannot rival.
</P>
<P>
   Take staying clean in Vermont. There's a little pool in our
stream that forms a perfect bathtub. Every spring, however, heavy
runoff chokes the pool with sand and pokes holes in the dam we've
built. We devote an afternoon or two to pulling up rocks and
shoveling out the sand, rebuilding the dam and stopping the major
leaks. I never wash up without recalling the effort it took to
create such an delicious bathing spot. Covered with dirt, hot and
grimy from the day, I never sink into the icy water without
thinking, ``Oh, this is near heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   On cool days, we take hot showers, using our solar shower. We
found a branch from which we hang the plastic bag, with its
swinging nozzle. I nailed a piece of wood onto the tree for a soap
dish; Jack hung a tarp as a shower curtain for guests. The sun
doesn't work on cloudy days, so before we shower, we have to haul
water up from the stream, gather wood to start the fire, w
minutes, then carefully pour the hot water into the bag through a
funnel we've made from a plastic half-gallon jug.
</P>
<P>
   In order to leave some water for Jack, I get wet, turn off the
water, soap myself, and then give myself three lovely minutes of
hot water drizzling down my back and legs. By the time I grab a
towel off a nearby branch, I feel so clean and fresh I could laugh
out loud. It's thrilling to feel the cool air on my damp skin. I'm
eager for the comfort of a warm shirt as it slips over my head. I
never get into clean clothes without thinking, ``This is definitely
near heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, of course, I wash without paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Civilization always pales. Familiarity breeds indifference. How
perverse human nature is! Why is it that the key to thoroughly
enjoying what you have turns out to be having just enough and no
more?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
