<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR 2000, DESIGNERS SUGGEST WE LIGHTEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a mood swing in the air and on the runways
here this week, as more than 70 American designers showcase their
first collections of the new millennium. Clothes have a happy,
whimsical feeling. Ruffles are back. Color is everywhere. Spring
2000 promises to look fresh and upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   With designers seeming optimistic about Y2K, women's apparel may
experience a rebirth of sorts. The '90s will be remembered as a
decade of sartorial austerity, when minimalist silhouettes and
black and gray fabrics defined the chic look, and pockets were
derided as ``clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming decade, the fashion industry is apparently
intent on not taking itself too seriously. Rather than tidy
pantsuits or sweater sets, the modern silhouette will require a bit
of whimsy _ mixing and matching unexpected colors, fabrics, and
textures.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Herrera's spring collection, for example, pairs patent
leather tops with cotton pants, suede tops with linen pants, and an
organza shirt with sequined pants.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Calderin, an instructor of fashion design at Lasell College
in Newton, said the mixing of textures is a key part of future
fashion. ``One of the main things of importance to a designer is to
create a center of interest,'' he said. Because many modern clothes
have a smooth finish (body-hugging stretch fabric, for example),
they need to be grounded by something warmer, softer, and textured
so they won't look too futuristic, he said. ``Designers are tying
in clever things like a crocheted scarf. . . something to make it
look more real.''
</P>
<P>
   After the monochromatic '90s, designer Han Feng's collection is
a shock. She unabashedly combines pink blouses with red skirts and
yellow blouses with green skirts. Linda Allard at Ellen Tracy mixes
blue shirts with yellow skirts and green shoes.
</P>
<P>
   William Calvert's spring collection includes a fire-engine red
sweater worn over pink pants. ``People will look cool in color.
Orange, fire-engine red, shocking pink. Sometimes, they'll wear it
mixed up, sometimes, tonal. . . Each piece has its own color and
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Andre, president of the wardrobe management company
Organization by Design, cautions consumers not to take the trend
too literally. ``It might look fabulous at a cocktail party, but
the big word is appropriateness. Don't let designers lead you down
that road. . . Color is hard to pull off. If you have a fuchsia
dress with a boa, you'd better have the right shoes with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these post-feminist times, designers boldly placed
girlish ruffles on runways all week long. Design house Badgley
Mischka, the darling of the sophisticated Hollywod set, put a
ruffled hem on a turquoise sequined evening gown. Whether that
dress makes it to the Oscars remains to be seen. Designer Rebecca
Taylor put ruffles down the front of one dress and around the
collar of a top. Oscar de la Renta placed ruffles down the back,
around the neck, and completely around various gowns.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, synthetic fabrics like Tencel and
polyester have been promoted as a comfortable and nonwrinkling
option, especially for people who travel frequently. But this
spring, cotton and other natural fabrics appear to be making a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Donna Morgan, who calls cotton a ``sleeper'' fabric,
said at least half of her spring line will be made from cotton.
Herrera and design house BCBG Max Azria also embraced the fabric.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
