<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACKS SEEING A MIRROR IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Do you think when Peyton Manning looks in
the mirror he sees Drew Bledsoe? And do you think when Drew Bledsoe
looks at video of himself from six years ago he sees Peyton
Manning?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the AFC's best gunslingers will go head-to-head Sunday at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They are both mild-mannered, polite, and come from strong
families where their fathers, in particular, were heavily involved
in their football development. Mac Bledsoe was Drew's high school
coach, while Archie Manning was an outstanding NFL quarterback who
seemed to teach his son the right path to success at the University
of Tennessee and now at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Both Manning and Bledsoe had outstanding rookie seasons, poised
beyond their years. They are both pocket quarterbacks who ``like to
get the ball out to the real athletes,'' as Bledsoe put it
Wednesday. Both were instrumental in bringing their respective
organizations from doormat to contender. Well, the jury is still
out on the Colts, who were 3-13 a year ago. But following a 31-14
win over the Buffalo Bills last Sunday, Manning could be on his way
to doing what Bledsoe did in his second pro season _ leading his
team into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton looks very good,'' said Bledsoe. ``He's progressed very
quickly. He looks completely different now than the quarterback we
saw the first time we played them last season. He's had one of the
more successful rookie seasons ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bledsoe and Manning were involved in flip-the-coin
decisions on draft day _ the Patriots decided on Bledsoe over Rick
Mirer in '93 and the Colts took Manning over Ryan Leaf last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bledsoe who talked to Manning after his junior season,
when Manning was toying with the idea of turning pro. Bledsoe told
Manning about his first year and the difficulties associated with
leaving school.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, taking the advice of Bledsoe and others, including his
father, elected to stay at Tennessee. He then won the Heisman
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And the extra year helped Manning quickly lose the
deer-in-the-headlights look he had in that first game against New
England Sept. 14, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Manning said the talk with Bledsoe helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He faced a similar situation,'' Manning said. ``He was a
quarterback who had the chance to come out early. He came out and
he gave me his reasons, including that he didn't have a very good
team coming back and that he worried about getting hurt because of
it and hurting his chances in the draft. He just said, `Do what you
want to do because you can't look back.' He said, `You're going to
struggle.' It was something I had to accept. So I did what I had to
do and I had a chance to get through my senior year and prepare
better for the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he spoke to Manning to give him ``perspective''
rather than advice, the same thing Manning is now doing for
Cleveland rookie Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just gave him the understanding of what was going to happen
to him,'' said Bledsoe. ``He knew it was going to be hard. But he
got through those times and maintained his confidence. You're
starting to see the fruits of that already. He was more successful
his rookie season than I was. He had the best rookie season of any
rookie quarterback ever. Now they're going to have to develop a
team around him, just as they did around me. If they continue to do
that, he can take them to where they want to be. They looked
awfully good last week. They beat Buffalo and it was a real
beating. It wasn't fluke plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning threw 28 interceptions last season _ three against the
Patriots in Week 2 _ but he also threw for 26 touchdowns and 3,739
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said the Colts' brass allowed Manning to make mistakes,
just as Bill Parcells and the Patriots had done with Bledsoe back
in 1993, when the Patriots went 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a rookie quarterback out there, you have to let
him make mistakes and stick with him,'' said Bledsoe. ``It's a
tribute to his coaching staff that they did that with Peyton
because he's going to be so far ahead because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning said he thanked Colts coach Jim Mora and general manager
Bill Polian after last season for ``showing patience with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I could have been over my head. The New
England game was a good example. It wasn't much fun, throwing three
interceptions and fumbling. What Coach Mora told me is it's easy to
come out of the game when you throw an interception, but it's hard
to stay in and avoid the fourth and fifth interception. I felt I
learned some things and I realized it's a long-term thing and you
have to be in it for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning learned about perseverance and that there was always
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be mentally strong and when you have a bad game,
you have to respond the next week,'' Manning said. ``Talent has a
lot to do with it. You have to work hard to stay effective.''
</P>
<P>
   As he waited for Manning's game to mature, Polian decided to
trade Marshall Faulk, an older running back, and replace him with
rookie first-round pick Edgerrin James. The Colts' offensive line
is young, as are receivers Marvin Harrison and E.G. Green. Like the
Patriots back in '94, the Colts should be together for a while.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, mature quarterbacks come back to a city
where they were embarrassed and try to exact revenge. That 29-6
loss to the Patriots still haunts Manning. Two of his throws went
to Ty Law, one for a 59-yard touchdown. The third went to Lawyer
Milloy. But even in that game, Manning completed 21 of 33 attempts
for 188 yards and a touchdown. Last year, Manning's offensive line
protected him well, surrendering only 22 sacks, in part because
Manning got rid of the ball quickly. He is trained to dump the ball
if he feels pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing on the road in front of a hostile crowd,
like last year when we had fumbles and interceptions, you don't
have a chance,'' Manning said. ``The main thing is to protect the
ball. If you're going to beat New England, you have to score points
because their offense is so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our division, I think, is the best in football. Buffalo,
Miami, the Jets, and New England are excellent teams and whoever
wins it has to be a favorite to win the Super Bowl. We're a better
team, but everyone is better, too. Beating Buffalo gives us a lot
of confidence, but New England had a huge win over the Jets. It's
funny but you don't hear New England mentioned as much but we have
the upmost respect for them.''
</P>
<P>
   What became obvious to Manning, as it had for Bledsoe, is that
the offseason between the first and second years is critical. It's
the first year a player can take part in the conditioning program
and work with other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have fun last season, so we worked hard in the
offseason,'' said Manning. ``All the receivers stayed here in the
offseason and we worked on our timing. This year, we had that, and
I feel we're on the same page because of it. I can take that and
add to it that last year I took every snap and I saw a lot of
different defenses. I faced a lot of situations, two-minute drills
and protecting leads. I'm a not a 10-year vet, but I feel I saw a
lot. I appreciate the patience they showed and now I'm trying not
to make as many mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are hoping Manning has another learning experience
Sunday, though they fully understand they will be paid back for
that first game, sooner or later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
