<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-CHURCHSHOOTING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS LINE UP TO DONATE BLOOD TO SHOOTING VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Feeling helpless and wanting to help in any
way they could, dozens of people were lined up even before the
doors opened Thursday at the Carter BloodCare Center in the city's
Hospital District.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Wednesday evening's shooting at a Baptist church,
blood supplies were low because of routine local demand, and many
supplies from across the nation already were en route to the East
Coast in anticipation of Hurricane Floyd, said Viqui Litman, the
blood center spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after the center on Rosedale Street had opened, they
had received more donors than they normally receive in a week, but
still more is needed, Litman said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that, with multiple gunshot wounds, one patient could
easily go through more than 50 units of blood.
</P>
<P>
   The blood center's Dr. Leland Baskin said the shootings were
straining the bank's already short supplies. Baskin said the demand
is up 10 percent this year, while supplies are down 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were short on all types. We were in the `red zone,' meaning
we were down to double digits on O-negative and O-positive,''
Litman said.
</P>
<P>
   Litman said Carter BloodCare, its satellite offices and blood
mobiles were extending hours. A temporary blood donation unit also
was set up at John Peter Smith Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be here for as long as it takes,'' Litman said.
</P>
<P>
   The wait was 2 or 3 hours, but that didn't faze many donors.
</P>
<P>
   Brandie Bach of Arlington, said her husband, a Fort Worth police
officer, was working at the crime scene and she wanted to do her
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's a terrible tragedy. They said the
neighborhood needs to come together and give blood. I think it's
the least we can do. It's just terrible that something like this
had to happen to get everybody to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Gray said he was a friend of the family of Justin Ray, who
was listed among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known the family for seven years and I watched him grow
up,'' Gray said. ``It's strange because just the other day I saw
him and he was showing off the truck he had just bought with his
own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good kid. The only gang he belonged to was the Boy
Scouts,'' Gray said. ``It all makes me wonder what's wrong with
society. People should be safe at home, at school ... and
particularly if you can't be safe at church what is wrong with
society?
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not just guns. If they took away all the guns, there
still would be people chunking rocks at each other,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm speechless,'' said Lisa Taylor of south Fort Worth. She
said she grew up two blocks from Wedgwood Baptist, where the
shooting took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the Prince of Darkness stealing from America.
Giving blood is my way of reaching out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Davis of east Fort Worth said he's a regular blood donor.
The shooting prompted him to donate sooner than he had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just terrible. I lived in Littleton, Colorado, for a
time. It's all too strange. Now it's happening in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Littleton has a stigma because of the shootings there.
Now Fort Worth has joined the ranks of the infamous cities. It's
all kind of sad,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just too close to home,'' said Gabrielle Schmidt of
Crowley. ``You feel so helpless. I think that's why you see so many
people here today. Everyone wants to reach out and help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines were there, too. A group from the 14th Marine
Regiment at Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base Fort Worth were at
the blood center early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us have kids, too,'' said Marine Chris Dickinson.
``This is hard for their families. You try to put yourself in their
shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
