<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-DELAHOYA     09-16 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA-TRINIDAD FIGHT IS ON A RECORD PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Athletes, promoters, agents, and team owners all
love to say the same thing. ``It's not about the money,'' they tell
you while they stuff their pockets with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this week it is about the money and nobody is trying to
hide it.
</P>
<P>
   Money is pouring into Las Vegas and into the coffers at TVKO,
the pay-per-view arm of HBO that will distribute the broadcast of
Saturday night's welterweight unification fight between Oscar De La
Hoya and Felix Trinidad. With three days to go, there is talk that
this will become the first non-heavyweight fight to do at least one
million pay-per-view sales, and promoter Bob Arum is promising it
will shatter the previous non-heavyweight record of more than
800,000 buys and $34 million in pay-per-view revenue, which De La
Hoya set with Pernell Whitaker two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an issue,'' Arum boasted Wednesday. ``It's going to
leave every non-heavyweight fight in the dust. The only question is
how close does it come to the heavyweight pay per views.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a question no one can answer, but Mark Taffet, senior
vice president of TVKO and the point man of the fight's
distribution, was cautiously optimistic Wednesday while trying to
downplay Arum's bombast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a heavyweight unification fight with Lennox Lewis and
Evander Holyfield and it did 1.2 million, so that's the ceiling,''
Taffet said. ``Can this fight top that? You don't top a heavyweight
unification fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it do very well? Yes. Will it set a new record? We can
only hope.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is hoping more than Arum's longtime rival, promoter Don
King. While De La Hoya is guaranteed roughly $21 million and
Trinidad $8.5 million, after King lops his $2 million promotional
fee off the top of Trinidad's $10.5 million purse, King stands to
cash in big time if the fight tops the 850,000 mark because he will
rake in $8 for every person who pays $49.95 to watch the bout over
that figure.
</P>
<P>
   If the fight does 1 million buys that would equate to $50
million in pay-per-view revenue alone and it would mean King takes
in an additional $1.2 million. It is assumed Trinidad would get a
piece of that additional revenue, but such assumptions are
dangerous when King is involved because no one swings a faster or
more lethal calculator than he does.
</P>
<P>
   King has accused Arum of not doing enough to promote the bout to
purposely cut down on those sales, claiming ``Arum would rather
lose money than see me make any money,'' but nothing could be
further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Radio, television, and national newspapers will be saturated
this week with ads, including a lengthy list of cross-promotional
advertising with cosponsors of the fight such as Puma and Met-Rx.
Both have deals with De La Hoya and are running ads that mention
their products in conjunction with their spokesman's Saturday night
showdown with Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   The real measure of how money is driving this match came at the
final press conference at Paris Las Vegas Casino Resort (which
comes complete with its own mini Eiffel Tower and Arc de Triomphe)
when De La Hoya came to the podium to speak of his greatest
challenge. It was nearly five minutes before he got to Trinidad
after first mentioning TVKO, HBO, Time-Warner, Puma, Met-Rx,
Budweiser, Kodak, McDonald's, Mennan, and Excite.com, the official
website of the Trinidad-De La Hoya fight.
</P>
<P>
   And that list doesn't include the many business connections
around the country, international television revenue, ticket sales
to the soldout event at the 12,000-seat Mandalay Bay Events Center,
and other spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The bout will be televised in 60 countries and in Hispanic areas
sales have already skyrocketed. In Puerto Rico, Trinidad's
birthplace and home, Arum claimed more than 30 percent of the
island's pay-per-view capacity had already been bought and was
estimating there would be an 80 percent buy rate by the opening
bell.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, there are 43 million addressable homes in the US and,
as Arum points out, ``if we do 3 percent, it's 1.3 million. I think
we can do 4 or 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems a bit of a reach, even by Arum's standards, but HBO
senior vice president for programming Lou DiBella conceded,
``Hispanics are the most loyal fans boxing has. They buy fights at
a far higher percentage than other demographic groups and this has
everything they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a Mexican-American hero in Oscar and a Puerto Rican
one in Trinidad. They have a fight whose outcome is being debated
and is in doubt. They have two great champions. It's too early to
tell how it will do, but the early (pay-per-view) numbers are
sensational. Compared to other big fights, it's tracking well.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other big fights, it's scalping well, too. Prime
tickets are going for $7,000 each and average seats are being sold
for $3,000-$4,000. The fight was the first in Las Vegas history not
to have a single ticket available for public sale, all of them
having been snapped up by the casinos and the two promoters. The
live gate has been estimated to be worth $13.5 million, which would
be nearly twice the previous non-heavyweight high set by De La Hoya
and Julio Cesar Chavez at Caesars Palace in 1996, when they did
$7,579,100 on sales of 14,738 seats.
</P>
<P>
   By way of comparison, the largest live gate in Vegas history was
the $14,277,200 Evander Holyfield and Mike Tyson did for their
first fight at the MGM Grand Garden in 1996, in a building that
seated more than 16,000. Had the fight been staged at the Thomas
and Mack Center on the UNLV campus (as Lewis-Holyfield II will be
Nov. 13), it is estimated De La Hoya-Trinidad would still have been
a sellout and might have shattered the Holyfield-Tyson record.
</P>
<P>
   With all this as background, Leonard Armato, agent of Shaquille
O'Neal among other sporting luminaries, will hold a summit meeting
Friday at Mandalay Bay for all of De La Hoya's major sponsors.
Armato, who runs the marketing end of De La Hoya's career, will
call together representatives of Met-Rx, Puma, McDonald's, MCI,
Logo Athletic, EMI (the recording company that has signed De La
Hoya to do a CD of Latino love songs), Budweiser, and Electronic
Arts video games, who together have paid his client an estimated $9
million this year in promotional fees.
</P>
<P>
   They will not be here to talk about the fight. They'll be here
to talk about the money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
