<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-GEEKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FREAKS AND GEEKS' IS A TEEN SHOW NOT NECESSARILY AIMED AT KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television was once dominated by a strict demarcation: Half-hour
entertainment shows were usually comedies, and one-hour programs
were almost always dramas. Now, there are no lines, as one-hour
sitcoms (sans laugh tracks) abound, and drama is crammed into
half-hour shows like ``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``Freaks and Geeks,'' a one-hour comedy that
scares the bejesus out of anyone my age.
</P>
<P>
   The new NBC offering takes a ``nostalgic'' look at high school,
circa 1980. Here is what is scary: (1.) My time in high school is
now far enough removed to qualify as ``nostalgia.'' When did my
teen years fall into the same category as ``Happy Days''? (2.)
Creator Paul Feig and executive producer Judd Apatow have
reproduced the era to perfection, from the clothes to the music
(dude, Zeppelin cranks) to the laissez-faire social attitudes that
existed before the Just-Say-No epoch.
</P>
<P>
   This last part will be a tricky proposition for the show based
on Feig's high school days in Michigan, a time when drug use,
especially pot, was extremely commonplace, drunken-driving was
something kids laughed about and schools had cigarette-smoking
areas marked off _ for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deal with it head on,'' Feig said. ``We don't moralize
anything. If you moralize it ... kids are going to turn it off like
that. A lot of people did it, we aren't going to say they didn't.
(But) we never are going to say it's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   But here is something different: this is a teen show that,
heavens to WB, is not necessarily aimed at kids. You would think a
high school show slated for Saturday nights (premiering this week)
would be deader than Leif Garrett's career.
</P>
<P>
   But besides geeks, there will be a segment of viewers who may be
interested in this show who will be home: those of us in high
school in 1980 who aren't going to spring for a baby-sitter every
Saturday night. There could be enough people hanging out, trying to
remember days when they were cool, or at least thought they were,
for the show to stick.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that this is really, really funny, with some
realistic angst thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   The story is universal _ high school life in fact hasn't changed
all that much. There are still ``freaks'' (stoners, burnouts, pick
your nomenclature) and ``geeks'' (nerdy outsiders). There are still
bullies and the bullied, although the 9mm in the backpack is a
tragic new wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Freaks and Geeks'' is better digested if one knows who
John Bonham was (Led Zeppelin drummer who lived life harder than he
pounded his kit), or can hum old Styx songs (lame pop camouflaged
by power chords). And for people of that age there are going to be
uncomfortable moments watching this show, faded memories
retriggered by a song or a T-shirt or catch phrase, of the less fun
side of high school that we have pushed back in our minds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the kids to watch in this series is Samm Levine, who
plays geek Neal. The kid has the personality (and passing physical
resemblance) of a young Albert Brooks, and is blessed with the
ability to do a pretty good Capt. Kirk impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other kids on the show, as well as young actors on
another period comedy, ``That '70s Show'' (Fox), Levine said he is
playing a teen from another time just as he would play one from
today. After all, there were jerks then, there are jerks now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the freedom to play the part pretty much the same
way,'' he said. ``Kids are always faced with the same problems,
whether it is 1980 or 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine even did some research, not so much for the show as for
his own survival. ``When I was a freshman, after having such a
terrible time in high school, being shoved into lockers, I found
friends of mine who were in their 20s and 30s,'' Levine said. ``I
said, `What was it like when you were in high school? Was it any
different?' They said, `No. I got pushed around by bullies, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   You can call that reassuring, I guess. The song remains the
same. If you didn't get the reference in that last line, ask an
elder. They are probably home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
