<HEADER>
A4458 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-JAZZMAN-RENEWED-LADN     09-16 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZMAN-RENEWED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ INNOVATOR HORACE SILVER ON A MISSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Five years ago, jazz legend Horace Silver checked
into the hospital and nearly checked out of this earthly life. The
pianist had blood clots in his legs and lungs; one night, he
stopped breathing and his family was told to prepare for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Silver made it through that night and the subsequent three-week
hospital stay as well as a recent 10-day hospitalization that saw
him confronting the same malady. Now, stronger and healthier,
having just celebrated his 71st birthday with family and friends,
Silver thinks back to those times of discomfort and feels almost
glad for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me thinking, that's for sure,'' Silver says from the
living room of his home in Malibu. `` &UR;  &LR; `Well, God may have spared
me this time, but I don't know how much longer I've got on this
earth. So I'd better try to make hay while the sun is shining and
try to get as many songs out as I can.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, you know, I've got all these tunes sitting on the
shelf that God has given me and he didn't give them to me to just
sit in the closet. He gave them to me to share with the world. And
that's what I've got to do while I'm still able.''
</P>
<P>
   If Silver speaks with an evangelical zeal about his musical
mission, it's because he has spent more than half a century
creating a body of work that few jazz musicians can touch. He and
drummer Art Blakey defined the hard bop movement in the 1950s,
developing a sound that blended blues and gospel into a passionate
mix that came to be described as ``soul jazz.'' The two artists
also virtually invented the quintet model that had a simple front
line _ tenor sax, trumpet _ backed by a rhythm section of bass,
drums and piano.
</P>
<P>
   The consistently outstanding quintet recordings Silver made in
those early days for Blue Note and continued to deliver to the
classic jazz label for some 28 years are celebrated in a new,
four-disc set, ``Horace Silver Retrospective,'' released Tuesday.
The box's 45 prime selections begin with Silver's first trio
compositions, takes in a generous selection of his classic
jazz-funk recordings like ``Senor Blues,'' ``Filthy McNasty,''
``Sister Sadie'' and ``Doodlin''' and ends with several the
pianist's underappreciated 1970s gems.
</P>
<P>
   The collection coincides with the release of ``Jazz Has a Sense
of Humor'' (Verve), an album of nine new Silver compositions that
swings with the same infectious joy that characterizes his best
work on Blue Note. The album's title reflects Silver's strong
belief that music has the power to lighten spirits and make people
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the good Lord has blessed musicians with talent in
order to make people happy,'' Silver says. ``All the arts can make
people happy, but, in my personal opinion, I think music comes
first in uplifting people and then comedy second. So why not
combine the two?''
</P>
<P>
   Since Silver took an interest in metaphysics some 30 years ago,
his music has often taken on a rather fervent mystical tone. One
Blue Note set from 1970 aimed to ``bring a little more health,
happiness, love and peace into life.'' A 1997 album, ``A
Prescription for the Blues,'' pictured the pianist wearing a
doctor's lab coat on the cover, his hands holding a pestle and
mortar.
</P>
<P>
   In person, Silver comes across as animated as one of his famed
quintet recordings. It's easy to see why Miles Davis hired Silver
to play with him on several mid-'50s recording dates for both the
Blue Note and Prestige labels. The man's enthusiasm is positively
contagious, not to mention contagiously positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put a fire in my playing,'' Davis wrote of Silver in his
autobiography. ``I wanted to take the music back to the fire and
improvisations of be-bop ... But I also wanted to take the music
forward into a more funky kind of blues, the kind of thing that
Horace would take us to.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver's most famous recording remains the title cut from his
1965 album, ``Song for My Father.'' Even if you haven't heard the
song, you probably have. Steely Dan songwriters Donald Fagen and
Walter Becker more or less appropriated ``Father's'' bass line for
their hit, ``Rikki Don't Lose That Number.'' (``I was flattered,''
Silver says. ``And it's given me a good bit of promotion, too.'')
</P>
<P>
   Silver wrote ``Song for My Father'' after visiting Brazil with
Sergio Mendes and returning home with a bossa nova beat stuck in
his head. The melody he came up with, though, was Cape Verdean, a
sound Silver's Portugese father enjoyed while growing up in Maio of
the Cape Verde Islands, located off the coast of Senegal in Africa.
The elder Silver had tried for many years to persuade his son to
jazz up a Cape Verdean folk song and ``Song for My Father'' was a
way to honor the request.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, it was a way of honoring the man who pointed him
toward his life-long career. Silver was 10 and living in Norwalk,
Conn., when his father and uncle brought home an old upright piano
obtained from neighbors who were moving to Florida. Silver's father
played guitar and violin (his mother died when he was 9) and often
performed with various relatives and friends at parties.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing his neighbors play, the young Silver decided he
wanted to learn piano, too. But he found the lessons tougher _ and
duller _ than he imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd learn to play a tune in two weeks, but they had
me playing all these boring scales,'' Silver recalls laughing. ``I
wanted to quit, but my dad said, `No. You wanted this piano, so you
stick with it. You're going to thank me for this one of these
days.' And I certainly do thank him for it!''
</P>
<P>
   Silver quickly developed his own irresistible style, emphasizing
rhythm and subtle, buoyant melodies, incorporating the techniques
of a variety of influences _ Thelonious Monk, Bud Powell, Teddy
Wilson and Art Tatum, among others. For Silver, having an
individual voice is everything. He remembers one day, early in his
career, playing piano at a friend's house when the doorbell rang
and the great Monk walked into the room.
</P>
<P>
   Monk watched Silver play, standing over the young pianist while
he worked out his song, and, at one point, Monk, never one to keep
his opinions to himself, reached over Silver's shoulders and said,
``Hey, man, why don't you play this part here like this?' and then
showed Silver how he thought the song should be played.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's response?
</P>
<P>
   ```I said, Well, Monk, yeah, that's beautiful, but I kind of
like it the way I do it,''' Silver remembers. ``And he thought I
was just saying that because I didn't want to sound like him, and
you know what? He was right. As much as I respected Monk, I didn't
want to be no Thelonious Monk clone. I want to be Horace Silver,
somebody with his own voice and style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's what I tell all these young musicians today,''
Silver continues. ``It's the stylists that have the lasting
recognition. There's a lot of fine musicians out there now. You
hear these guys playing their butts off, but who are they, you
know? They're schooled in technique, they can improvise, but when
the record is over, I still need the announcer to tell me who they
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older guys, you didn't have to wait. You knew the sound
right off. `Oh, that's Art Farmer playing trumpet.' Or `That's
Clifford Brown.' Or Hank Mobley. Or Joe Henderson.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of trumpeter Brown, all the musicians Silver
named were part of his legendary Blue Note quintets during his long
stint with the label. Silver has always had a knack for discovering
fine, young musicians. His new album, ``Jazz Has a Sense of
Humor,'' features several such players, and he's already thinking
about using them again on his next album, the beginnings of which
are evident on the writing table next to his piano. It's full of
eraser shavings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contract calls for one record a year, and that's kind of
tough with the backlog of material I have,'' Silver says. ``And I
keep writing. I can't stop. I don't want to stop. I've got so much
more I want to say. I need another 50 years.'' &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
