<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIECHICKS-EARL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHICKS ARE MAKING A KILLING OFF `GOODBYE EARL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks' ``Fly'' has been the hottest country CD since
its recent release _ and perhaps the hottest song on it is a little
number about friendship, a marriage gone very bad and a deadly
serving of black-eyed peas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye Earl'' _ ``that Earl song'' for short _ tells the
story of two high-school friends, Mary Anne and Wanda, who conspire
to kill Wanda's abusive husband after he ``walked right through
that restraining order and put her in intensive care.''
</P>
<P>
   Country and folk music are no strangers to death: Classics such
as ``Knoxville Girl'' and ``Pretty Polly'' recount horrible ends,
and Garth Brooks' controversial ``The Thunder Rolls'' also dealt
with domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Earl'' _ well, ``Earl'' is different. Spirited and brisk,
it's a ``happy'' tune, with none of the tense drama of ``Thunder''
and a can't-help-but-sing-along chorus. Just try not tapping your
toes as lead singer Natalie Maines recounts the two serving up a
lethal dinner, wrapping Earl in a tarp and disposing of him in a
nearby lake, or hollering ``Earl had to die! Goodbye Earl!'' along
with her.
</P>
<P>
   In just over a week, ``Goodbye Earl'' has become country music's
conversation piece, ``like an Elvis bust on a coffee table,'' as
one local music director puts it: Dozens and dozens of listeners
around the country are requesting it, and it's receiving as much
airplay as the CD's flagship single, ``Ready to Run,'' in some
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge, huge _ and the response is overwhelmingly
positive,'' says Smokey Rivers, assistant program director for
KPLX/99.5 FM in Fort Worth-Dallas, adding that the station is
playing ``Earl'' ``four or five times a day,'' as much as ``Run.''
``It's our strongest request right now. We played four or five
tracks when the CD came out, but this one took off. I think people
are treating it as a tongue-in-cheek deal, not a real story.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks' first CD, ``Wide Open Spaces,'' has sold more than 6
million copies, earned the trio the Grammy for best country album,
and remains at No. 2 and No. 23 on the Billboard country and pop
charts, respectively, more than 18 months after its release.
</P>
<P>
   So the early response to ``Fly,'' which was released Aug. 24,
has been huge. And the word-of-mouth generated by ``Earl'' is a
major reason why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it _ it's an in-your-face song and it has a great
hook,'' says Jamie Matteson, country music editor at Gavin.
``Usually when you think of a song like this, it'll be a sad
ballad, a cry-on-your-sleeve record. This is like taking control of
the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   And while ``Earl'' is mostly seen as a fantasy, to some it's
extremely real. Both Rivers and Jay Roberts, music director of
WQYK/99.5 FM in Tampa, Fla., say that numerous listeners have
called in with their own stories of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   In Tampa, that meant devoting more than an hour of a recent
morning show to women who wanted to talk about their experiences;
the station also gave out numbers of area women's shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional,'' Roberts says. ``One lady said she's
gone through years of abuse, and her 13-year-old daughter finally
convinced her to leave and get help.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Rivers says his station has received no complaints,
others have. Roberts says ``Earl'' is ``polarizing'' and that some
callers think the lyrics are too strong.
</P>
<P>
   And over at KSCS/96.3 FM in Fort Worth-Dallas, music director
Linda O'Brian reports about an 80-20 split of positive and negative
feedback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people love it, say it's ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' set to
music, and a very vocal group of people hate it,'' she says. ``They
think it promotes violence and teaches (that) vigilantism is OK.
And the arguments these people make _ do their kids not play video
games or go to violent movies?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just campy and goofy and fun and tongue-in-cheek. There's
too many other things in life to angst over other than a new Dixie
Chicks record _ it's not worth getting a wrinkle over.''
</P>
<P>
   But for at least the next several weeks (and maybe longer) it's
certainly going to be worth talking about _ and controversy about a
song is always a very good way to get people to buy the CD it's on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said when the CD came out that it's another `Rumours,'''
says Rivers, referring to the 1977 Fleetwood Mac LP that generated
hit after hit and became one of the most popular records in
history. ``There's songs on `Fly' that are going to be huge. It's a
country masterpiece, for sure. We're going to be playing it for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
