<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-A'S-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL OWNERS REJECT SALE OF OAKLAND A'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Major League Baseball's concerns about the
long-term economic state of its game, in addition to some
behind-closed-doors politics, doomed former A's executive Andy
Dolich and Modesto supermarket magnate Bob Piccinini's $122.4
million bid to buy the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball owners voted 28-2 on Wednesday to table any discussion
of the club's sale. They also blocked a sale of the Kansas City
Royals, another small-market team, and approved the sale of the
majority stake of the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The A's vote, executed in a stately resort on the banks of Lake
Otsego in baseball's birthplace, effectively kills any hope for the
Dolich-Piccinini group to buy the club, because a Monday deadline
for sale set by Oakland city officials will pass without any
further discussion of the bid. Owners shortened a two-day meeting
into one in order to leave town early and avoid any travel delays
associated with Hurricane Floyd, and voted early Wednesday evening
on the A's sale.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership of the club will stay in the hands of current owners
Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann, who bought the team in 1995 and now
have the option to put it up for sale to any new bids or keep the
team indefinitely. Schott and Hofmann, as part of an escape clause
in their contract with the city of Oakland and Alameda County, can
also now take the A's out of the Coliseum after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolich-Piccinini group would have been bound by the existing
lease to keep the team at the Coliseum through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann declined comment as he left the meeting, and Schott put
out a press release stating he and Hofmann were ``committed to
produce a competitive team and keep the franchise stable.'' There
was no mention of moving the team; nor was there mention of keeping
the team in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual,'' said A's team President Mike
Crowley. ``I'm already budgeting for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   East Bay politicians, some of whom made the trip to Cooperstown
to show support for what they believed was the best opportunity for
a long-term future in Oakland for the A's, were outraged at the
owners' vote. Some intimated the owners had rejected a solid
proposal in order to accomplish covert goals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the goals:
</P>
<P>
   _ To protect the San Francisco Giants' long-term viability as
they move into a new stadium and face debt-servicing issues.
</P>
<P>
   _ To reopen the bidding so the group headed by Arizona real
estate man Lyle Campbell, an ally of baseball Commissioner Bud
Selig, can re-enter the process. The Campbell group dropped out
when the city of Oakland and Alameda County officially recommended
the Dolich-Piccinini group to Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an elaborate scam,'' Alameda County Supervisor Mary King
said. ``We came here to be the conscience of a community, but
apparently Major League Baseball is not interested in conscience.
Maybe we wouldn't have wasted our time and energy and capital if we
knew Major League Baseball would sacrifice the city of Oakland's
interests for the San Francisco market. . . . Maybe the public is
out of its league when dealing with this power and influence that
goes beyond public scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piccinini: ``I think Major League Baseball just kicked
Oakland right in the stomach. . . . They had a perfect opportunity
to make Oakland successful, and they short-circuited it. They're
scared about the long-term viability of the San Francisco market.
They can't allow it to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   At a hastily called news conference at Oakland City Hall
Wednesday, Mayor Jerry Brown said he had asked Hofmann whether he
would be interested in extending the lease agreement on the
Coliseum to keep the franchise in Oakland longer, but the developer
didn't give an answer.
</P>
<P>
   However, the mayor is hopeful Hofmann would be interested in
keeping the team in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is from the area,'' Brown said. ``He's got a lot of money.
He likes the team. I don't see any reason why he would want to move
the team somewhere else. It's a dollars and cents business.
Political sentiments do not carry the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the sale acknowledged that the owners might
have been turned off by East Bay politicians' telling them who
would own one of their franchises. They also speculated that owners
might have rejected the bid in an attempt to get more money out of
a future bid, thus driving up the value of all the owners'
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory held that Schott and Hofmann had an interest in
killing the sale, since the team is winning and making money, and
the owners would then have the option of leaving the Coliseum after
2001. The A's are the third-lowest drawing team in the American
League, despite having the fifth best record.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said too many concerns existed about a small-market club
such as Oakland _ the A's $22 million payroll is among the lowest
in baseball _ being sold at a time when he had commissioned a
so-called ``blue-ribbon panel'' to produce a report on the game's
economic future. The panel includes Yale President Richard Levin,
political columnist George Will, former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell
and former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich and Piccinini interpreted Selig's talk of the blue-ribbon
panel as the owners questioning the viability of Oakland as a
baseball market. The panel is said to be discussing long-term
solutions to the competitive problems affecting baseball, in which
small-market teams such as Montreal and Kansas City have trouble
beating big-market teams such as Atlanta and New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
