<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-LIDDY-DOLE-COX     09-16 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIDDY-DOLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole puts her can-do record on the line
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jacksonville
</P>
<P>
   Out the windows of the swank River Club, the first distant signs
of Hurricane Floyd were taking shape on the horizon Monday as
Elizabeth Dole and Rep. Tillie Fowler worked the tables at a
$500-a-plate luncheon fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting backdrop for a candidate who touts her
leadership of one of the world's premier disaster relief
organizations, the American Red Cross, as part of a long list of
credentials. Fowler, the former Georgian who represents
Jacksonville in Congress, is one of many friends andassociates who
are playing major roles in Dole's campaign. She has known Dole for
25 years and named her youngest daughter, Elizabeth, after her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a strong conservative, without the hard edges,'' the
congresswoman, who sits on Dole's national finance committee, told
the group, which included one notable Democrat, former Florida Gov.
Farris Bryant, as well as regular Republican contributors and
members of the Jacksonville business community.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time for Dole to step in front of the podium with a
clip-on microphone, a bit of choreography she has become known for
since she spoke for her husband at the 1996 Republican Convention
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the stump speech without hard edges. The lines don't
change much from one campaign stop to another, and the delivery is
an unvarying combination of warmth, eye contact and upbeat, can-do
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   She speaks of her desire to ``energize'' younger Americans who
have turned away from the ``noble endeavor'' of public service
``because, frankly, of the ugliness of politics in some cases.''
</P>
<P>
   She delivers the line with a knowing look that makes it easy for
Republicans irate over President Clinton to understand what she's
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not running for president because I'm a woman, and I don't
want people to vote for me because I'm a woman. I want people to
vote for me because I'm the most qualified,'' Dole told an audience
at a luncheon last week in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is difficult to talk about her style without
reference to her gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that she's a woman is a plus, but just her sense of
propriety and her appealing to the better side of us, I find very
attractive,'' said Georgia state Sen. Tom Price.
</P>
<P>
   In part, perhaps, because she is a woman attempting to do
something none has done before, her speech includes a litany of her
accomplishments, as president of the Red Cross and in an impressive
list of government posts.
</P>
<P>
   She reminds audiences that as transportation secretary, she was
the first woman to head a branch of the military, the Coast Guard,
which carried on an active program of drug interdiction on her
watch, and she managed the privatization of Conrail. She talks
about her role in resolving the bitter Pittston coal strike when
she was labor secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a seat-warmer,'' she told a group of Georgia
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Almost always, the speech begins with what she patly describes
as ``the bed joke,'' in ``Unlimited Partners,'' the joint
autobiography she wrote with her husband before his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a male supporter who wrote presidential candidate Bob
Dole to complain that a People magazine picture of the Doles making
up their bed together had led his wife to insist that he also help
out with housework. ``Buster, you don't know the half of it,'' the
former senator replied. ``The only reason she was helping make the
bed was because they were taking pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters have criticized the scripted nature of her campaign.
``Doonesbury'' has lampooned it. But there's some truth in her
supporters' claim that Dole's front-of-the-podium delivery has an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   She seems to have the greatest impact on younger women, from the
businesswomen who lined up to be photographed with her in Atlanta
to the flag corps members in an Iowa high school band who reacted
excitedly when they spotted her waiting to begin marching in a
parade last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to bring a new generation of voters into her
campaign was a factor in Dole's strong third-place finish in the
Iowa GOP straw poll, and it's the selling point most often cited by
her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To raise the money to compete with well-financed rivals, Dole is
spending much of her time these days raising money from Republicans
of the more traditional variety. It's a delicate process: Many of
her staunchest supporters, such as Fowler and Georgia co-chair
Oscar Persons, also have close ties to the Bush crowd.
</P>
<P>
   This effort has not been helped by the impression that her
campaign is in flux. In recent days her communications director,
Ari Fleischer, and press secretary, Michael Paranzino, have
resigned, saying they still support her but want to pursue other
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has been criticized, perhaps unjustly, for not fleshing out
her stock speech with more substance on the issues. It's true that
she seldom varies her remarks and cuts off her press availabilities
at most appearances after a few questions.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she has clearly defined positions on
antiballistic weapons and drugs. Her position on gun control _ she
says that if there are child safety locks on pill bottles there
ought to be on guns, and questions whether ``anyone needs an AK-47
or an Uzi to protect their families'' _ is a bold departure from
her Republican rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign hopes to lend some substance to her education plank
today with a policy speech in Melrose, Mass., where she was an
11th-grade student teacher while she was studying for a master's
degree in education at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't understand why the media doesn't quite get
it, that you don't leave the Red Cross and have a full-fledged
organization up and running the next day,'' Dole said, with a trace
of irritation, last week.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of impatience with the pace of her campaign has followed
her long after her departure from the nonpartisan organization,
however. After her boost in Iowa, she took a 10-day vacation _ in
New Hampshire, of all places _ which added to the perception that
she was squandering an opportunity to make headway.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters say the deliberate pace comes in part from an
urge to achieve consensus before moving ahead. In ``Unlimited
Partners,'' Dole admits to a ``tendency to overprepare,'' which
also shows in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But as a political wife, she has had more experience with the
rhythm of a presidential campaign than any of her rivals, possibly
excepting Pat Buchanan. And with her frequent references to the
young girls who tell her they wanted to be the first woman
president, Dole signals an awareness that she is making history
with her race, and feels an obligation to run it all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
