<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. 49ERS ASSESS THEIR DISASTROUS OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Emerging from a squinty-eyed,
head-pounding, kill-me-now hangover from the worst game of his
professional career, Steve Young came as close as he gets to being
fighting mad.
</P>
<P>
   Mad at himself for playing so poorly, at his teammates for not
playing much better and at Hurricane Floyd for not dropping in on
Jacksonville sooner so the whole mess of an opening game could be
postponed until March or canceled outright.
</P>
<P>
   They played 15 games in 1987, after all, and still crowned a
champion at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 49ers absorbed a 41-3 thrashing by the Jacksonville
Jaguars that was still very much with them on Wednesday as they
began preparations for Sunday's home opener against the New Orleans
Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Young has the worst passer rating in the league by
far. It's a figure that looks more like a clocking in the high
hurdles than a way to rate quarterbacks _ 14.3. Even
jerk-for-the-ages Ryan Leaf managed a 39.0 in his disaster of a
rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Young's quarterback rating, which is only 83.3
points below his career average, the NFL's weekly sheaf of
statistics shows the 49ers to be 28th in the league in total
offense, down 27 spots from their No. 1 ranking of last year, and
tied for last in the crucial category of turnover differential at
minus-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be a passion for football,'' Young said. ``I'm
not sure this team (has) the passion to play football, 49er style.
We need to be able to do so every week, starting on Sunday. We
didn't play with the passion we needed to play with (at
Jacksonville).''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariucci, perhaps the most affable coach in the NFL, took
exception to Young's lack-of-passion statement. In fact, he swatted
the entire subject back to his quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask him. I don't know what he's talking about,'' Mariucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've heard that ever from Steve. I
didn't see it that way. I thought we came out to play, indicative
of the first half. We weren't playing well on offense but we were
playing hard. The defense came to play . . . I don't understand the
(lack of) passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Young blamed himself for being rusty at Jacksonville, saying,
``I did not take care of my end. It's got to be gone now. It's been
a long couple days. There are rough days out there in the NFL.
You've got to clench your jaw and go at it for 15 weeks. You need
to see that mind- set from everybody on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   After one very bad week, it's fair to question whether the
chemistry on this team is tonic or toxic or something else
entirely. Twenty-one players who were on the roster for the
season-ending playoff defeat to Atlanta last Jan. 9 are no longer
with the 49ers, including good guys and leaders such as Merton
Hanks, Kirk Scrafford, Irv Smith, Randy Kirk, Terry Kirby, Chris
Doleman and Ty Detmer.
</P>
<P>
   In their place are newly minted 49ers like Charlie Garner, Mark
McMillian, Marvin Washington, Jeff Garcia and Lawrence Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many new guys,'' Mariucci said. ``I think the
chemistry is going to be developed as we go. Every day there are
new guys. Guys are not tight and don't know each other. That
requires some time. Chemistry doesn't happen overnight. You got to
go through the ups and downs of a season, then you develop
chemistry as you go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, the 49ers need to know if Lance Schulters
is there to stay as the starting free safety; if R.W. McQuarters,
the team's No. 1 draft pick from 1998, can be a starting
cornerback; if Gabe Wilkins can be a force at defensive end; if
oldster Charles Haley and youngster Chike Okeafor can rush the
quarterback like dogs chasing a man in sirloin slacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, change can be good, to get some fresh talent,
younger talent, who can be young 49ers and contribute,'' the coach
said. ``All these young guys, we see bright futures for. They've
been thrown to the wolves. They've got to do it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tell these kids in camp is we're going to play with
rookies but we can't play like rookies. You're going to have
growing pains. You're going to have a learning curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now the learning curve is steep. According to the starting
quarterback, the work should be undertaken with passion _ even if
the head coach doesn't know what he's talking about.
</P>
</TEXT>
