<P>
   &UR; HURRICANE FLOYD &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times plans two pages of stories and photos on
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-RDP (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Hurricane Floyd comes ashore
near Cape Fear, N.C., with 110 mph winds, flooding the Carolina
coasts with more than a foot of rain as tens of thousands of people
huddled in shelters. At least seven deaths are blamed on the storm.
More than 480,000 people customers in the Carolinas and Virginia
have lost power. Flooding and power failures combined to shut down
Portsmouth, Va.'s water supply system, which serves 110,000
customers. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (New York) _ The New York region braces. Schools in
New York City and New Jersey are closed; barrier beaches expected
to be hardest hit. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY-SCENE (New York) _ How the New York metropolitan
region handled a day in which much of business, etc. shut down. By
N.R. Kleinfield.
</P>
<P>
   Other N.Y. sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BAHAMAS (Abaco) _ Report on damage from the storm to
the outer islands. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-PRIVILEGE (Washington) _ Citing executive privilege,
the White House refuses a congressional request for documents
supporting the Puerto Rican clemency decision. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Congress sent legislation to
President Clinton on Thursday that would boost salaries for the
next president, federal workers and the lawmakers themselves. By
Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEXAS SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SHOOTING (Fort Worth) _ Police on Thursday sought a motive
for the nation's latest killing rampage, a shooting spree that
began Wednesday night when a man spewing anti-Baptist rhetoric
burst into a church service for teen-agers and opened fire. Seven
people were fatally shot before the gunman _ identified by police
as Larry Gene Ashbrook _ killed himself at the Wedgwood Baptist
Church. Seven others were wounded, three of them seriously. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SHOOTING-ASHBROOK (Fort Worth) _ What we know about the
shooter, 47-year-old Larry Gene Ashbrook of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SHOOTING-SCENE (Fort Worth) _ The scene, the church, the
neighborhood, etc. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SHOOTING-BUSH (Grand Rapids, Mich.) _ Saying there was a
``wave of evil'' sweeping America, Republican presidential
candidate Texas Gov. George W. Bush cut short a campaign trip today
to rush home to Texas where a gunman killed eight people, including
himself, at a church. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ Developments in the wake of the latest
Russian bombing, this time a truck bomb in southern Russia, which
has killed at least 17 people. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said Thursday that the United States would not support further
multilateral assistance to Russia unless it cracked down on
corruption. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-AUSTRALIA (Darwin, Australia) _ Foreign troops, ships, and
planes converged on this northern Australian city Thursday, as an
international peacekeeping mission prepared to depart within days
for strife-torn East Timor. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK (Brussels) _ Gen. Clark scheduled to give
assessment of Kosovo bombing. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCHROEDER (Berlin) _ Beleaguered Chancellor Schroeder
gives a major speech to Parliament on deep spending cuts. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-FOLKMAN (Undated) _ Dr. Judah Folkman, the leader of
research into attempts to fight cancer by starving the tumors of
blood, reports finding another potent natural inhibitor of blood
vessels. It is the third to be discovered in his laboratory. This
advance, however, comes amid setbacks and questions involving his
work in the field, angiogenesis. By Nicholas Wade. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JUPITER-MOON (Tucson, Ariz.) _ Analysis of striking
scalloped lines on the surface of Jupiter's moon Europa yields the
strongest evidence yet that there is a global liquid ocean below
the icy surface. The new analysis, scientists argue in the journal
Science, makes Europa a prime target in the search for life beyond
Earth. By John Noble Wilford. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WYO-NUKE-WASTE (Jackson Hole, Wyo.) _ Jackson Hole residents,
led by the lawyer Gerry Spence, are fighting plans for a nuclear
waste incinerator in Idaho, which they say will blow smoke into the
Grand Tetons. This is the latest fight over nuclear waste
incinerators. Four have been proposed and none built so far. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRCANE-INSURE (Atlanta) _ Looking at how insurance companies
prepare for a big hurricane like Floyd. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The column: Looking at the U.S.
trade deficit and the dollar. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TALKS (Detroit) _ The United Automobile Workers union and
DaimlerChrysler reach a tentative agreement on a new three-year
contract for 75,000 workers. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   BT-AT&AMP;T (Undated) _ British Telecommunications and AT&AMP;T form an
alliance to provide mobile telephone services around the world. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CRESVALE (Tokyo) _ A Japanese investigator's question
about a signature turned out to be the single thread that unraveled
a multimillion-dollar scandal involving Cresvale International. The
role Japanese regulators played in the eventual arrest in the
United States of Martin Armstrong, who is accused of defrauding
Japanese investors, has helped burnish their reputation. Japan's
financial regulators began operations a little more than a year ago
and have struggled to operate under severe constraints. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CABLEVISION-SONY (Undated) _ Cablevision and Sony announce a
deal to offer digital services in New York, using about $1 billion
worth of Sony set-top boxes. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   FEDEX-WARNING (Undated) _ FDX Corp., the parent of Federal
Express, says higher fuel costs drove its fiscal first-quarter
profits below Wall Street expectations and that second-quarter
profits may also miss forecasts. Share fall more than 10 percent in
early trading.
</P>
<P>
   NBC-PAXON (New York) _ NBC confirms plans to invest $415 million
for a 32 percent stake in Paxson Communications. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., stocks are lower. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 61 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 3 points,
the Nasdaq composite down 25 points. The 30-year bond was priced to
yield 6.08 percent. European markets were also lower, with London
down 0.81 percent and Frankfurt down 1.54 percent. Tokyo's Nikkei
closed down 2.73 percent. The Hong Kong market was closed because
of Typhoon York. In New York, Hurricane Floyd shortened the
sessions for commodities the Treasury. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Gail Collins' ``Public
Interests.''
</P>
