<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-REVIEW-HAMMETT-TEX     09-16 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-HAMMETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM SPADE'S BACK, AND SO'S THE CONTINENTAL OP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nightmare Town''
</P>
<P>
   By Dashiell Hammett
</P>
<P>
   Short fiction
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $25
</P>
<P>
   There is, I'm told, an excellent pop music band calling itself
Dead Can Dance. What I know for certain is that Summer '99's
nickname ought to be Dead Can Write.
</P>
<P>
   So far, we've had posthumous novels by Ralph Ellison
(''Juneteenth,'' excellent) and Ernest Hemingway ``True at First
Light,'' execrable). Now we have the return of 38-years-dead
Dashiell Hammett, in the form of ``Nightmare Town,'' a collection
of whodunit yarns turned out for various crime magazines during the
'20s and '30s. The Ellison and Hemingway books have demonstrated
the kind of uneven results we can expect when the literary closets
of deceased hall-of-fame writers are dredged for any remaining
words that could be put into print and earn substantial bucks for
surviving relatives. There can be great treasures (''Juneteenth''
was a diamond-in-the-rough classic brilliantly trimmed and polished
by a gifted editor) or noxious effluvia (Hemingway while living
didn't want ``True at First Light'' published, for darned good
reason).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightmare Town'' falls, truthfully, in between, although it's
much closer to ``Juneteenth'' than ``True at First Light.''
Hammett's writing career was meteorlike: He burned brilliantly for
a short time, then fizzled out. His considerable modern reputation
results from reader familiarity with just a few of his novels:
``The Maltese Falcon,'' of course, plus ``The Thin Man'' and
perhaps ``Red Harvest'' and ``The Glass Key.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hammett earned his original renown with a series of
brilliantly crafted short stories for so-called mystery slicks, or
magazines. ``The Maltese Falcon,'' for instance, was reworked into
a novel after initially seeing print as a five-part magazine
serial.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after 1934 _ and Hammett lived to age 66, dying in 1961 _ no
further Hammett fiction was published in his lifetime. William
Nolan's superb introduction to ``Nightmare Town'' provides the
details. Essentially, drink and paranoia, some of the latter truly
earned (he was briefly imprisoned for refusing to provide names to
investigators during the ``Red Scare''), combined to dry Hammett
up. But before this personal disaster, he created absolute gems of
mystery yarns, many of which have been forgotten because they
simply weren't available for subsequent generations to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightmare Town'' goes a long way toward correcting this
literary misstep. Samuel (never ``Sam'' to his creator) Spade fans
will rejoice in three tales featuring their hero. The title story
is the longest, and it evokes the nonstop shoot-'em-up gore-fest of
``Red Harvest.'' Best of all, though, we get lots of visits from
the Continental Op, Hammett's alter ego based on the author's
experiences as a Pinkerton detective. The Op, never otherwise
identified, is a nondescript agent for hire who is interested only
in the satisfactory conclusions of his assigned cases. He is the
model on which all subsequent hard-boiled fictional sleuths have
been based. Hammett thought up the first one, and the best one.
</P>
<P>
   There are some clinkers in the collection, although their
presence is pretty much predictable. ``Ruffian's Wife,'' told from
the distaff perspective, isn't as clever as Nolan's
otherwise-distinguished notes would have readers believe.
``Nightmare Town'' lists into slapstick at some points, although
its unusual drive-into-the-distance conclusion saves the overall
story.
</P>
<P>
   But Hammett, who wanted his stories to combine complexity and
gritty realism, wrote so much on the literary edge that he was
bound to fall off once in a while. ``Nightmare Town's'' failings
can at least be attributed to ambition, not indifference. And when
Hammett is on, when he has his characters and dialogue rolling, he
frankly mesmerizes.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Nightmare Town'' should be classifed as a must-read,
whether you enjoy reading the modern-day mysteries of Cornwell and
Kellerman, Evanovich and Parker, or else simply want to appreciate
the stylings of a master. Hammett is acknowledged as the finest
mystery writer ever, but that is because he chose to write
mysteries. Later on, in the dregs of his career, he tried
``straight'' fiction and failed miserably, never producing a novel
worth publishing. But had he turned his attention to that genre at
the height of his powers, we might now be ranking him with Ellison
and Hemingway as simply a great writer. Read ``Nightmare Town,''
and you'll understand why.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
