<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
IT'S TIME TO GIVE SOFT MONEY A HARD TIME (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Personally, I prefer hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   I almost said that the first time someone threw the term ``soft
money'' at me. Not knowing at the time that the person was
referring to a way of contributing to political campaigns, I
supposed he was talking about paper tender of the realm that had
through repeated exchange lost its crispness, or such
representations of wealth as stocks, bonds or Treasury Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is my belief that millions of Americans are still
clueless about what politicians, pundits and other advocates for or
against it are talking about when they discuss soft do-re-mi. And
for that reason, those citizens may not grasp the importance of
this week's vote in the U.S. House of Representatives on the
Shays-Meehan campaign finance reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   That bill _ sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Marty Meehan, D-Mass. _ among other things would prohibit the soft
stuff _ i.e., large, unregulated contributions from corporations,
wealthy individuals, labor unions and other groups to the political
parties, ostensibly for ``party-building'' purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Huge amounts of that ``soft money,'' through various
subterfuges, wind up being used in the campaigns of individual
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot like laundering illegally obtained money. In fact,
that's a good way for those who are just beginning to pay attention
to the recurring debate over campaign finance reform to get a
handle on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   More than $260 million was laundered into the campaigns of the
presidential and congressional candidates three years ago. And
leading up to the 2000 elections, contributions to the parties are
reported to be almost double what they were at this point in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking to stop the political money laundering assert that
it corrupts the political process, subverts public policy in
crucial areas, dilutes the credibility of Congress and the
executive branch, and contributes to public disillusionment and
voter apathy.
</P>
<P>
   They have hit the nail square on the noggin. There is a strong
correlation between declining voter participation and the growing
perception that elected representatives are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most politicians aren't, or at least don't want to be,
for sale. But they know, realistically, that they must be
continuously on the make for campaign funds to pay for the TV time
they must buy to get elected and then re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, therein lies the crux of the problem. Most voters do
get their strongest impressions of the candidates from the
television ads that interrupt the programs they are trying to
watch. Although the unwanted intrusions into voters' viewing
provide little useful information, they can have a cumulative
effect upon the viewer that works to the benefit of the candidates
who run the most ads.
</P>
<P>
   Something clearly needs to be done to break the bondage of
candidates to television. But that's wishful thinking. For now,
doing something to curtail political money-laundering would help
immensely.
</P>
<P>
   Banning soft money and that other form of laundering called
``issue advertising,'' which is also prescribed by Shays-Meehan,
would not, of course, eliminate the stench of money from political
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In his bid for the presidency, Texas Gov. George W. Bush appears
to be touting his ability to raise campaign money as the primary
reason why he should be elected _ either that, or he is trying to
scare off other challengers by letting them know that he can buy
more time to insult TV viewers' intelligence than they can.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Bush is raising the money himself. And since that
``hard money'' goes directly to him, some significant restrictions
attach to his taking it, and he must make known where any
contribution over $200 comes from.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about political money laundering is no respecter of
parties. Fifty-four Republicans defied their party leadership and
voted for Shays-Meehan, which passed by a vote of 252-177.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are those who say that the Senate version of
it _ sponsored by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell D.
Feingold, D-Wis. _ will again be talked to death in the upper
house. Although there were enough votes in the Senate to pass it
last year, backers could not muster the necessary 60 votes to end
the filibuster ordered by the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   That unfortunate bit of recent history, however, need not
necessarily repeat itself. Minds can be changed if enough voters
will phone, fax, write and let their senators know that they are
disgusted with political money-laundering.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
