<HEADLINE>
BOOK RAILS AGAINST E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Beware the evil engines of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message Internet expert Douglas Rushkoff is bringing
to Silicon Valley _ the birthplace of e-commerce _ to promote his
new book, ``Coercion: Why We Listen to What `They' Say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coercion'' is a studied rant against public relations,
marketing, promotions, professional sports and other forms of hype.
But the pages that are getting the most buzz are the ones railing
against e-commerce, the burgeoning online industry that promises to
be the digital version of the industrial revolution.
</P>
<P>
   One valley trade publication has already labeled the book the
``Blair Witch Project'' of the e-commerce industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rushkoff, who has made a living writing Internet books
(``Cyberia: Life in the Trenches of Hyperspace'' and ``Media Rant!:
Hidden Agendas in Popular Culture''), just smiles when he hears
about that reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' said the hyperkinetic, 38-year-old New York
University professor. ``E-commerce is, at its heart, a legal Ponzi
scheme and a remorseless selling machine which threatens to destroy
more than it could ever create.''
</P>
<P>
   Rushkoff's arguments: E-commerce is really the automated
manifestation of tried-and-true marketing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in ``pacing and leading,'' retailers have
traditionally sold products by learning customers' preferences
through focus groups and surveys (the ``pacing'') and then using
that information to steer buyers toward similar products
(``leading'').
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, e-commerce sites collect streams of data on
customers and constantly suggest similar but different buys.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, for instance, regularly offers recommendations of
books that a user may be interested in, based on past selections.
</P>
<P>
   These techniques, Rushkoff points out, are constant and
automatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how many books you buy on Amazon, there's always
more titles being suggested,'' said Rushkoff. ``There's no human
hand on the throttle. E-commerce customers become rats on a wheel.
The machines never get tired of trying to sell us something.''
</P>
<P>
   Rushkoff saves his more scathing criticism for the e-commerce
industry itself.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, he argues, e-commerce is similar to the scheme
dreamed up by Charles Ponzi: Early e-commerce investors, such as
venture capitalists, make their profits by luring later investors _
such as Internet stock buyers _ into the e-commerce industry.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, because no real profits are being made, these later
investors are left holding the bag. Or, in this case, worthless
stocks of profitless online retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-commerce is an economic hack,'' said Rushkoff. ``E-commerce
sites aren't there to make money. They're there to be
advertisements for investment dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce, Rushkoff declares, threatens to leave us with a
heavily commercialized Internet that is best at creating anxiety,
alienation and, in the end, financial ruin for late-coming
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an Internet drained of fun,'' he said. ``A medium devoid
of a basic humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rushkoff is an e-commerce critic, he is also a
beneficiary. His book, published by Riverhead Books, zoomed to No.
5 on Amazon's daily bestseller list after its debut (it's currently
No. 937).
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I shouldn't use Amazon as an example so much,''
Rushkoff said, sheepishly. ``They've been very good to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
