<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLICATION EMOTIONS ABOUT THE CLOSING OF A GUN STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yet another family business is closing in San
Francisco, but it isn't just another business. There won't ever be
a store like this in San Francisco again, just as stagecoaches
never again will carry banks' money.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Gun Exchange on Second Street is having a
going-out-of-business sale, only partly because of California's new
gun laws. It's a personal decision by owners Beth and Bob Posner,
who inherited the 52-year-old store from their father, the late
Nate Posner.
</P>
<P>
   A sign in their window says, ``Over the years many of you have
become like family. Some of you represent the third generation of
our customers. We will miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   California's new ``junk gun'' law isn't well-defined, and the
Posners don't know which guns in their inventory will be
categorized as junk, so they're playing it safe by selling them
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big stores will suffer more from these laws than the
little dealers because they have a bigger inventory,'' said Bob
Posner. Incidentally, because of its old-fashioned design, the
Model 1911 Colt that served in four wars will be considered a junk
gun.
</P>
<P>
   After Littleton, there's not a lot of room in America for
sentimentality about guns.
</P>
<P>
   Another new law will limit gun purchases to one a month, but
puts the responsibility for enforcement on buyers and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good time to get out of the gun business, even though the
passage of those laws has sent gun sales through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Now that every gun at the store has been marked down, they will
be selling as fast as the store's computers can interface with
state computers in the state capital in Sacramento _ which isn't
very fast.
</P>
<P>
   If anything has driven the Posners out of business, it's the
sheer amount of paperwork involved in selling guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be nice to have a social life again,'' said Bob Posner.
</P>
<P>
   I got to know the Posners five years ago when the Board of
Supervisors passed a special tax on guns sold in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it was political posturing at the expense of the only
large gun store in the city. Ironically, the Gun Exchange served
local cops and didn't deal in cheap guns. It also equipped
generations of San Franciscans with expensive shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   The store is finally going away. Now residents will have to
drive a few miles to South San Francisco to get a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the thing I discovered as a bleeding-heart member of the
media who befriended the owners of a gun store. Bob and Beth Posner
are great people, former '60s types who once had unruly hair, and
are tolerant in their attitudes toward everyone except those who
would ban guns.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Posner prides herself on being pro-choice, pro-free speech
and pro-gun. She sees no inconsistency. ``The Second Amendment is
what backs up the First Amendment,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   I entered the store as a typical liberal. Five years later I'm
still a typical liberal, but have a greater understanding of both
San Francisco and a gun culture that are disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if all the guns in America disappeared, but I
don't think that'll happen soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Gun Exchange has been like a lunch-hour club for cops,
assistant DA's, and a lot of people who remind me of my outdoorsman
Maine grandfather. In modern-day San Francisco, he'd be considered
a mass murderer of Bambi's family.
</P>
<P>
   I could drop in at the Gun Exchange and pick up some dirt on
someone, and get a whiff of gun oil and the lost culture of Field &AMP;
Stream I knew as a lad.
</P>
<P>
   As an L.L. Bean type of guy, I love the trappings of that
culture, so I bought belts made by the craftsmen at Mulholland
Brothers of Potrero Hill, and a Randall knife made by the famous
knife makers in Orlando, Fla., who were the subject of my first
feature story when I was a reporter at the Orlando Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gun Exchange I also would see the diversity of people in
San Francisco who own guns, but don't talk about it. Nowadays being
a target shooter is worse than being a heroin addict, or even a
politician.
</P>
<P>
   There always was an abundance of good cop gossip, and stories
from the guys in the diminishing working class of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Posner always had great items, like the one about all the
government bureaucracies that use excess funds at the end of the
fiscal year to buy holsters and cleaning rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary how many people are legally carrying guns on the
streets of San Francisco,'' Posner once told me. ``Even the General
Services Administration, which takes care of desks, has personnel
who carry guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Posner is similarly nervous that the fear of Y2K has caused the
Smith &AMP; Hawken set to buy the products of Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   There are far too many guns in America, and you can applaud the
closing of a gun store if you want. But a lot of people, especially
San Francisco cops, will miss the Posners' store.
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco, and the end of gun stores is as
inevitable as the end of smoking in bars.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Bob Posner ate a hamburger while sitting on a
case of marked-down ammunition. ``Maybe I'll start a politically
incorrect department store,'' he said wryly. ``I can sell furs,
cigars and red meat.''
</P>
<P>
   All those things are more acceptable than guns. The problem is,
the wrong gun dealers are quitting the business. The Posners are
leaving what has basically been their home for their entire lives.
If you think that will save other people's lives, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   But the guys who sell their goods from trunks of cars will still
be around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
