<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANCE GOES `INCOGNITO' IN THIS THRILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The made-for-TV movie ``Incognito'' is billed as a heavy-duty
romantic suspense thriller but is as lightweight as air. It centers
on a female insurance executive being stalked by a nut case who
raped her after she saw him gun down a woman at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Released from jail on the dreaded ``technicality,'' the
psychopath, named Scanlon and played by a grunting Phil Morris,
orbits Erin Cortland (Allison Dean), showing up at her office, her
house, in the elevator of her office building, pretty much
unaccosted by the police.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Erin's wealthy father, played by Ron Glass, (Barney
Miller) hires a bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Hunter (Richard T. Jones) is soft-spoken and charming and
carries a rather large gun. It's a given that Jake and Erin first
squabble over his protective services (she wants space; space can
get her killed, he warns), come to a truce, and then fall for each
other. But even that is clumsily handled by scriptwriter Shirley
Pierce and director Julie Dash, who stage so few scenes leading up
to an intimate interlude that it seems forced.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the chemistry between the two leads is so lacking that
by the credits, I wondered whether Erin and Jake would just go
their separate ways, never to speak again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incognito,'' which will air Friday, is the first of 10
original films adapted from the popular Arabesque line of
African-American romance novels, and this first choice certainly
has the heroic melodrama and woman-in-jeopardy silliness that, for
whatever reason, are requirements of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it different from a Judith Krantz or Danielle Steel _
besides its paltry $850,000 budget _ is that the leads and the
majority of workers populating the plush insurance company owned by
Erin's family are black.
</P>
<P>
   Race and money aside, ``Incognito'' runs into the same problems
as Steel offerings. In trying to give a love affair depth and
context, the film is weighed down by too many other elements. Here
it's a subplot that involves Erin's fiance, an opportunist who may
or may not be stealing from the insurance company. That, along with
the terrifying Scanlon, was a bit much to keep track of. Dash wants
to hand us a twist on an old theme, but it inadvertently keeps the
romance and thriller sides from ever meshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incognito'' also squandered any opportunities to explore
wealth, class and privilege among a racial group usually shown as
monolithic. Jake's idea of a safe house was the modest home he
shares with his sister (Vanessa Williams) in the low-rent district
of Los Angeles. Other than her question of ``Why are we in South
Central?'' Erin seemed rather at home there.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, who attended Southern Methodist University in Dallas, does
a serviceable job as the terrified heroine. Jones, a terrific actor
who was a regular on the short-lived drama series ``Brooklyn
South,'' does what he can, despite having to mutter silly machoisms
(''He's a technofreak with a bad chip on his shoulder,'' he barked
about Scanlon), playing Jake as a sensitive soul who cooks fish.
</P>
<P>
   Morris must have jumped at the chance to play the bad seed. Here
he embodies someone who is not middle-class and refined, (even his
zany ``Seinfeld'' character was a lawyer), a man teetering on the
brink of violent madness.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, in a setting in which the terror literally kills the
romance, he must have seen his role as something of an actor's
playground.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
