<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATIONISTS ARE BUGGING HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I can't get these creationists out of my face.
</P>
<P>
   They've been at me, off and on, for weeks now with letters and
e-mails and phone calls. Some are bright and thoughtful _ although
wrong. Others are angry and utterly uninformed in their wrongness.
</P>
<P>
   They're all disturbed over a column I wrote a few weeks back,
after the Kansas State Board of Education essentially removed the
teaching of evolution from the state's school curriculum. I said in
that column that evolution is the foundation of modern biology. I
said that people who interpret literally the spontaneous creation
described in the Book of Genesis shouldn't try to write their
religious beliefs into law _ not in a country where the First
Amendment empowers citizens to reject such beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   I also noted that most people have no problem reconciling the
process of evolution with faith in a supreme creator who set the
mechanism in motion. That view is referred to by the more
thoughtful creationists as ``theistic evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   They dislike it almost as much as athiests dislike it. And I've
heard from a mob of them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that column went out to hundreds of newspapers across
North America. So, not only am I hearing from angry local
creationists, I've been swamped with outraged communications from
far-away places. One guy from the Akron, Ohio, area got me live on
the phone. He was beside himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we can't teach creationism in the public
schools,'' he fumed. ``They teach religion now. But the religion
they teach is humanism.''
</P>
<P>
   I rplied: ```That's not a religion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is. Humanism confers godlike status on human beings.
That's a religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Humanism is a philosophy that says that we ought to treat
another decently because it's the right thing to do. I don't know
the extent to which the concept of treating each other with
kindness is promulgated in the public schools, but a religion it
isn't. I've spent 30 years working on English language newspapers.
Words _ like religion, for instance _ have specific meanings.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him if he had a dictionary handy. Fortunately, he did.
Look up religion, I suggested. Then I asked him: What does it say?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he told me, ``it says that religion is concern over
what exists beyond the visible world. It says that it's different
from philosophy in that religion operates through faith or
intuition rather than reason and that it generally includes the
belief in a supreme being or a group of spiritual beings that
either created the world or have the power to influence the world's
events.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' I said. ``What else does it say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It says that religion is the belief that prayer or ritual or
living by certain principles of everyday life can bring you reward
in an afterlife, and that ignoring those things can bring you
punishment in the afterlife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, does humanism meet that definition?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't want the schools teaching evolution,'' he
replied. ``It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Evolution is a theory, I told him. ``That's defined by my
dictionary as a coherent explanation for observed data. You're
entitled to reject the theory. What you're not entitled to do is to
tell me that my kids can't be exposed to widely accepted scientific
theories that you reject on religious grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want the truth taught,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   So, I grabbed my dictionary and read him the definition of
truth. It's defined as ``a verified or indisputable fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, he agreed that neither evolution nor creationism
meets that definition. Which means that this guy's next move might
be to try to have another subject removed from the public school
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I suppose, we can kiss English goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Times Union, Box 15000,
Albany, N.Y. 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
