<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-INJURIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH EXPERTS REMIND YOUNGSTERS TO PLAY SAFE, AVOID INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The last thing Nicholas Russell, 14, thinks about
when he plays football or hockey is getting injured. ``We always
stretch a lot before practice, and we always make sure we have the
right equipment,'' said Russell of Ballston Spa, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Yet each year, thousands of children under the age of 15 end up
in the emergency room because of sports injuries, from concussions
to broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   As the school year gets under way, health experts are reminding
young athletes, their coaches and parents to play it safe,
especially during the start of the fall sports season when many
injuries, such as pulled muscles, are more apt to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical that student athletes and everyone else
participating in sports have a proper warm-up period with a few
minutes of stretching before engaging in any sports activity,''
said Dr. Lynne T. Nicholson, department chief of physical medicine
and rehabilitation at Sunnyview Hospital in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   That advice is especially important for athletes under 15
because their growing bodies are more susceptible to certain
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are marked differences in coordination, strength and
stamina between children and adults,'' Nicholson said. ``In young
athletes, bone-tendon-muscle units, which are growth areas within
the bones and ligaments, experience uneven growth patterns, leaving
them susceptible to injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hutchins, athletic trainer at Albany Academy here, said the
most common problems include pulled hamstrings and shinsplints, a
painful condition caused by irritation of the fibrous membrane
surrounding the shinbone, or the front part of the leg above the
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Runners and anyone else who puts in a lot of miles on hard
pavements or tracks without shock-absorbing footwear, are
vulnerable. To minimize symptoms, trainers often use tape or ice.
In severe cases, the best solution is rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids will come in after the summer and they're
potentially out of shape for the amount of work they do in
practice,'' Hutchins said.
</P>
<P>
   He and many other school coaches and trainers try to keep
students active over the summer with suggested training schedules.
For those students who don't follow through, the challenge for
Hutchins is trying to encourage them to pace themselves and to
allow plenty of time for stretching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes it,'' Hutchins said about stretching. ``It's a
constant battle for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only can stretching minimize the risk of shinsplints and
pulled muscles, but improved flexibility can boost speed,
coordination and strength.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, a ninth-grader at Saratoga Springs Junior High School,
has learned that lesson firsthand over the years.``I don't mind
it,'' he said. ``If it helps, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides taking the time to warm up and cool down, Nicholson
offers these tips to help prevent common injuries:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the proper equipment: Make sure your shoes are designed
for the activity you plan to use them for. Be prepared to replace
shoes as they wear out. Running in a pair of poorly made shoes may
also cause discomfort and injury. Always wear appropriate gear,
including helmets, padding and mouth guards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't force the body: If an activity doesn't feel comfortable,
it may be because of improper technique. An incorrect foot plant or
stride can lead to ankle or other injuries. Learn proper form or
technique for optimum safety and performance, and don't overdo it.
Get treatment for a persistent sharp or sudden pain that occurs
during athletic activity, Nicholson said. ``If ignored, a mild
injury can become serious. For instance, untreated tendinitis can
lead to a torn tendon, a much more complicated injury that will
sideline an athlete for weeks or months.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Get rest and relaxation: Even professional athletes take a day
off. At least once a week, give the body a rest. Besides stretching
and warming up, Russell spends time off the athletic field keeping
his body healthy during the sports season.``I try to eat well, I
take vitamins every day, and stay away from junk food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Wood can be reached at swoodtimesunion.com or at
454-5445.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
