<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4650 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-SCIFI-WRITERS-HNS &LR;      09-16 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIFI-WRITERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCI-FI WRITERS TALK ABOUT THEIR CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELMAR, N.Y. _ On a quiet suburban side street in a nondescript
white bungalow, veteran science fiction authors George Zebrowski
and Pamela Sargent have transformed their modest home into a
formidable writing factory.
</P>
<P>
   He plants himself in a cramped, book-lined study in the front of
the house, and she is rooted at a computer in a book-stuffed office
in the back of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Anchoring the isthmus between the partners' writerly spaces is a
spare bedroom overrun with thousands of scientific reference books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes about 100 of those reference books to make one
science fiction novel,'' said Zebrowski, 53, author of dozens of
novels and short stories in the genre. ``You've got to research
cutting-edge science to write a cutting-edge science fiction
novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who have never married, met in 1964 as philosophy
students at the State University at Binghamton, N.Y. They started
living together in 1970 and both have supported themselves as
full-time writers ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we put our income together, it's a solid middle-class
living,'' said Zebrowski, whose speech still carries the Bronx
accent of his youth.
</P>
<P>
   They left Binghamton after three decades and moved to Delmar in
1996, in part to be close to Sargent's family. Even after three
years in their Delmar home, they're still unpacking some of the
hundreds of boxes of books that filled three moving trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like moving an institution,'' said Zebrowski, a man
with a sweep of gray hair and a pronounced limp from a childhood
hip defect that could not be repaired despite two series of
surgeries that hospitalized him for many months as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private tragedies,'' Zebrowski said with a dismissive wave of
a cane. ``Everyone has them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two writers share their book-saturated house with a minimum
of furnishings and a 16-year-old black-and-white cat named Spencer
(after Spencer Tracy). On days when the writing is going well and
Sargent is able to summon all of her creative energies to construct
alternative histories and imagine societies of the future, she is
not conscious of Zebrowski's typing a mere 40 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get lost in my work and forget he's there,'' she said. ``I
sit down at my computer in the morning and the next thing I know,
it's evening.''
</P>
<P>
   During those writing blitzkriegs, Sargent has completed the
draft of a novel in as little as 10 weeks. Although Zebrowski
sticks almost exclusively to the SF genre, Sargent has branched out
into historical fiction, including an epic novel about Genghis Khan
titled ``Ruler of The Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   That 1993 novel barely registered on the U.S. publishing radar,
but it made Sargent something of a short-lived literary celebrity
in Spain and earned her an advance from a German publisher three
times as large as any of her novels in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent said she moves easily between the past and the future in
her work. ``In a way, science fiction and historical novels require
a similar craft,'' she said. ``They're both period pieces about a
time and culture that are not mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Zebrowski knows firsthand the fickle publishing world, too. His
acclaimed 1979 SF novel, ``Macrolife,'' sold fewer than 5,000
copies in hardcover in the U.S. But sales in its European editions
were much stronger. In all, the 35 books Zebrowski has written or
edited have been published in more than six languages.
</P>
<P>
   The partners occasionally collaborate on writing projects,
including write-for-hire books in the Star Trek series. They don't
read each other's works-in-progress, but when a manuscript has gone
through several rewrites, they pass it across the house and become
initial editors. They are tough on each other's prose. Then it's
back to the computer keyboard in their respective offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``All writing is rewriting,'' Zebrowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zebrowski and Sargent have won critical acclaim, major
literary prizes and a devoted readership within the insular world
of science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real small club and everyone knows each other,'' said
Zebrowski, noting there are about 1,200 members of the Science
Fiction Writers of America. Zebrowski and Sargent have been
co-editors of that group's newsletter, The SFWA Bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the Albany, N.Y. region's literary circles, the pair
remain largely unknown. ``It's that notion of prophets being
strangers in their own land,'' Zebrowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The fiftyish Sargent, who declines to give her precise age,
thinks her anonymity locally has to do in part with the fact that
she is a self-described ``painfully shy'' person who avoids public
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not comfortable doing an author tour and the
marketing part of writing,'' said Sargent, in a baggy black
T-shirt, a mane of dark hair and thick eyeglasses, who makes
occasional eye contact with a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Zebrowski will appear at several local book signings in the fall
to promote his latest novel, ``Cave of Stars'' (HarperPrism, $24).
The story is set in 2331, on the fourth planet of Tau Ceti. Humans
abandoned the dying planet Earth hundreds of years earlier in
starship arks. They traveled to distant stars and planets like Tau
Ceti IV and live in macrolife mobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Zebrowski received the 1999 John W. Campbell Memorial Award for
science fiction from the Center for the Study of Science Fiction at
the University of Kansas. He was honored for his novel ``Brute
Orbits.'' Previous winners of the prestigious award include Arthur
C. Clarke, Ursula K. LeGuin, Kingsley Amis, Philip K. Dick and Kurt
Vonnegut Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
