u e BC-FILM-GAME-SPI &LR;      09-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GAME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN COSTNER PULLS OFF HIS THIRD BASEBALL MOVIE, `FOR LOVE OF THE
GAME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movie star career of Kevin Costner, as everyone knows, has
been on a downward spiral since his 1990 Oscar triumph, ``Dances
With Wolves.'' He's spent most of the decade since making a series
of legendary, ego-driven flops, and one sappy romance.
</P>
<P>
   So a certain air of desperation hangs over ``For Love of the
Game,'' his last film of the waning decade he once threatened to
own _ especially since it's a baseball movie, a genre he would seem
to have milked dry with his two '80s hits, ``Bull Durham'' and
``Field of Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   But, amazingly, he pulls off this third trip to the well.
Despite a creaky moment or two, it's an entertaining star vehicle
that works as both an engrossing competition movie and a poignant
love story. With a little luck, it could be just the big hit
Costner needs to jumpstart his career.
</P>
<P>
   He plays Billy Chapel, the 40-year-old star pitcher of the
Detroit Tigers, who is having the worst day of his life: his
girlfriend (Kelly Preston) is leaving him, the team he's served for
18 years is being sold, he's being traded to the Giants, and his
arm is killing him.
</P>
<P>
   When he goes out to face the mercilessly jeering fans at a
season-ending game in Yankee Stadium, he can't help but tune out
his surroundings and look back on his career, and on the course of
his failed relationship _ which we see dramatized in periodic
flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   As the game proceeds, Billy is so lost in his memories that he
doesn't notice that none of the hated Yankees are getting on base,
and that he's gradually building himself a perfect game _ so that,
suddenly, he has the opportunity to rejuvenate his career, or
retire in glory.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans will note the movie is hardly an accurate picture
of the state of our troubled national pastime. At one point, the
Tigers owner (Brian Cox) tells Billy that this game they have given
so much now ``stinks'' but the script never begins to tell us why.
</P>
<P>
   It also conveniently omits the things in Billy's life that might
distance us from his plight _ no mention of multi-million-dollar
salaries or palatial Florida estates. As depicted here, he lives
out of a suitcase and is as pure and unsullied by big money as Roy
Hobbs, Joe DiMaggio or Casey at the Bat.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can forgive this artistic sleight of hand, the movie
goes down like a cool glass of lemonade on a hot day. Director Sam
Raimi not only captures all the thrill of the game at its best, he
manages to keep the movie's romantic and athletic elements almost
perfectly balanced.
</P>
<P>
   As a romance, he gets a lot of help from Kelly Preston, who has
finally risen from the starlet class, and comes perilously close to
walking away with the movie. She creates a character of real depth
and substance: not just long-suffering and beautiful, but curiously
flawed and uncannily resourceful.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's Costner's vehicle, and he carries it with a
gimmick-free performance that emphasizes all his best qualities as
a star: an endearing masculine charm, a skillful underplaying of
almost every scene and a willingness to be, at times, infuriatingly
human.
</P>
<P>
   For Love of the Game. Directed by Sam Raimi. Screenplay by Dana
Stevens, from the novel by Michael Shaara. Cast: Kevin Costner,
Kelly Preston, John C. Reilly, Jena Malone, Brian Cox, Vin Scully.
Universal. 137 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0174 </DOCNO>
