<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESSES FACE TOUGH Y2K DECISIONS ABROAD
 &HT;    780&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last Tuesday, when the State Department assessed
how well other countries are preparing for Y2K computer problems,
it refused to rank nations according to risk, saying its
evaluations were intended to ``help Americans make their own
decisions'' about year-end travel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Jan. 1 just 15 weeks away, business owners soon will
have to make those determinations. For example, should they have
workers in frigid Russia at the darkest time of the year when the
State Department says Y2K disruptions there ``are likely to occur
in key sectors of electrical power, heat, telecommunications,
transportation, and financial and emergency services?''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no major companies have announced plans to cut business
ties with Russia or other northern-latitude countries with
vulnerabilities to the software flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill, a Minnesota-based commodity giant, stirred up a
controversy in South Africa recently when it said it would avoid
doing businesses there from Dec. 15 to Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, more U.S. companies may make announcements
about curtailing global operations because of Y2K worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have plans to discontinue service (to Moscow).
However, we are realistic,'' said Kip Smith, spokesman for Delta
Air Lines. ``We know this is a complex situation, so we are, of
course, making contingency plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Those plans ultimately may include canceling Delta flights. ``We
are still collecting a lot of information from different places ...
so we can make wise decisions about our service and our people,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug can cause older programs to misunderstand dates
starting with Jan. 1, 2000. It has the potential to trigger
malfunctions in the equipment used to generate power, control air
traffic, deliver water, track billing and much more.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, so many tens of billions of dollars have
been spent by companies and government agencies to correct the
problem that mainstream experts no longer expect catastrophic
failures of basic services.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department's assessments of 196 nations suggest
the outlook is less optimistic for many countries. For example, the
State Department says that in Venezuela, ``it appears that there is
a moderate risk of disruption in the electric power sector, which
could have implications for all other local sectors.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's a fairly good chance the lights will go
out for some indefinite period, which could mean the banks won't
open, hospitals will be chaotic and so on. Meanwhile, Ford Motor
Co. has a huge plant in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to continue operating such a plant with the help of
backup generators would be a judgment call ``based on safety and
security,'' said Ford spokeswoman Kathleen Vokes. If employees
would be safer at home than trying to get to work on darkened
streets, they will be allowed to be absent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Venezuelans who face Y2K disruptions would be able
to ride out the difficulties with the help of family and friends.
But what about American workers who might be far from loved ones
during massive service disruptions? Those are the very employees
