<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4663 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BARRY19-COX     09-16 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BARRY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Big Trouble' yields big laughs in Dave Barry's debut novel
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two dumb-as-a-stump lowlifes named Snake and Eddie have
unwittingly managed to get their hands on a nuclear bomb in a
suitcase, smuggled out of the former Soviet Union, and are about to
take it through the metal detector at Miami International Airport.
Clean-cut high school students are running around Coconut Grove
playing a game called ``Killer,'' in which they stalk one another
at night with squirt guns. The Miami police and the FBI are
stumbling over each other, and the hero, such as he is, is a former
newspaper reporter barely surviving with his own ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds more like one of Carl Hiaasen's comic Florida noir
thrillers than the work of Pulitzer Prize-winning funny-guy
columnist Dave Barry, and it is more like Hiaasen. ``Big Trouble,''
Barry's first novel, is obviously deeply indebted to Hiaasen's
pioneering warped work in what Barry, in his introduction, calls
``The Bunch of South Florida Wackos genre.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen, a columnist at The Miami Herald along with Barry,
obviously bears his friend no ill will for having copied his
loose-but-clever plot structures so closely. He's given Barry a
big-time blurb on the book jacket, as have old Barry chums Stephen
King and Elmore Leonard. This is known in publishing as
``log-rolling,'' in which simpatico fellow authors all join hands
and sing ``That's What Friends Are For.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the cover blurbs are correct: ``Big
Trouble'' is a very funny novel, with more laughs per chapter than
most of Barry's 20 or so nonfiction books, some of which seem to
have been written on auto-pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Trouble'' involves a large cast of characters who start at
vastly different points and end up influencing, arresting, killing
or lusting after one another. There's Eliot, who was fired from his
newspaper after trashing his editor's office (a fantasy staple of
the journalist-turned-novelist); his teenage son Matt, who's
involved in the game of Killer; Arthur Herk, a mean, corrupt,
alcoholic developer (the only kind in Miami-based thrillers); John
and Leo, formerly Ivan and Leonid, the Russian arms smugglers;
Walter the too-macho cop; and Roger the dog, ``the random result of
generations of hasty, unplanned dog sex,'' who has ``the
intelligence of celery'' but a crucial role at several plot turns.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone gets pretty much their just desserts. The Justice
Department may not always live up to its name, but an omnipotent
novelist can hand out rewards and punishments in a fitting way, and
Barry does.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, ``Big Trouble'' is Barry's poison-tipped valentine
to his adopted city of Miami, to its poly-ethnic stew, its heavily
armed population and its Borgia-like politics. Publishing would be
better off if Barry wrote less ``Dave Barry Turns 40, Does Japan,
etc.'' and wrote more novels like ``Big Trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Big Trouble. By Dave Barry. Putnam. $23.95. 272 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Barry's first novel moons Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer covers television for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
