<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-HELL19-COX     09-16 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HELL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frustrated clerk takes wheel on a road trip through `Hell'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept.19.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Ridley's ``Everybody Smokes in Hell'' is the best B-movie
you'll read this season. It's a headlong dive through a world
inhabited by the kind of jazzy, jivey lowlifes that Elmore Leonard
and Quentin Tarantino might team up to put on film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell'' is an amusing hybrid: Sometimes it reads, sometimes it
unreels. It all centers on Paris Scott, a workaday night-shift
clerk at an L.A. convenience store. Paris is a black, frustrated
daydreamer who's been dumped by the most beautiful woman he's ever
known. Leaving his lousy job one night, what appears to be a
scraggly white street person, half passed out against Paris' '74
Gremlin, asks Paris to take him home.
</P>
<P>
   In another book or movie, Paris would kick the guy aside and
drive off. End of book. End of movie. In the manner of this sort of
high pulp fiction, however, Paris worries about the karmic
consequences of such an act and drives the guy home, ``a way, like
a gambler's ritual, of keeping more trouble out of his already
troubled existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that tossed-off act changes the course of Paris'
life. It veers from a flat-lined Nowheresville to a careening,
episodic ... movie that suddenly runs through the worlds of rock
stars and music execs and gangstas, along with the preening,
cut-rate flotsam those worlds attract. Drugs, sex and violence are
merely a geography through which everyone navigates.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Score becomes the only motivation, and not getting dead
the only strategy to getting there. Ridley, who's written both for
film and TV (``Martin'') and published two previous novels (``Love
Is a Racket,'' ``Stray Dogs''), is in joyful command of this
out-of-control world.
</P>
<P>
   Each page is fueled by the standard bag of caper-novel tricks,
executed with a fresh voice and a sure hand. There's run-on
observation (``The girl behind the counter was nineteen and white
trash distilled to its purest form: uncontaminated, unaffected,
undetrashified by the many and various ethnicities in the city
she'd migrated to.''). Nodding dialogue of the profoundly
air-headed (``You writing a script? You going to photograph models?
What's the angle now? What are you almost going to do with your
life?'') Dumb-luck/bad-luck plot twists. And an unending collection
of characters that includes the most sadistic female bad guy you
ever wished you'd never met.
</P>
<P>
   It's Ridley's gift to love everyone he creates, good or evil,
and allow them to turn disgusting or venal or sweet of their own
free will. It's what elevates his pulp fiction to ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times when the book's pretense of biding time until it
becomes a movie grows tiresome; it turns lazy in ways that are
surprising from an author whose imagination is otherwise so
righteously hyperactive (one chapter begins: INT. VIDEO STORE _
MORNING; toward the end, some chapters are reduced to a few
sentences).
</P>
<P>
   And as is true of even the best caper fiction _ even Leonard's _
things wrap up a little too handily here, as if the writer is being
paid for a certain number of pages, and once that quota is reached,
everything must end.
</P>
<P>
   But those are not the kind of quibbles you should apply to a
book whose strength is the thrill one gets from its imperfect,
don't-look-back energy. ``Hell'' is a vivid, outrageously unpretty
joy ride that feels like it can be read in a minute, or watched in
an hour and a half. Read it soon at a theater near you.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Everybody Smokes in Hell. By John Ridley. Knopf. $23. 236 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A careening, episodic trip through the world of
rock stars and music execs.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes about television for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
