<HEADER>
A4665 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DANCE-MOBY17-COX     09-16 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-MOBY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music you can really dance to
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Moby is a vegan who admits a fascination with
pornography. He's a Christian, a descendant of Herman Melville
(hence the nickname) and has disavowed monogamy (``I'm incapable of
sustained romantic involvement. It's a brain dysfunction of mine,''
he said in a 1997 online chat). He has remixed artists as diverse
as Michael Jackson and Metallica. He's either a mass of
contradictions or the perfect postmodern Renaissance man. He's also
an unpredictable and prodigiously talented musician and sonic
architect.
</P>
<P>
   Moby, born Richard Melville Hall, was raised in Connecticut and
makes his home in New York, where he crafts dance music of shining
beauty and pumping authority. He's also an in-demand remixer and
producer, having worked with remixed Metallica and Ozzy Osbourne,
and having turned down production offers from Guns N' Roses and
Hole.
</P>
<P>
   Filling dance floors in 1991 with the percolating ``Go,'' Moby
was the techno/dance world's artist most likely to cross over into
the mainstream. Following several more singles, he released
``Everything Is Wrong'' in 1995, a remarkable distillation of his
work to that point. It was Spin magazine's album of the year and
showed up on Top 10 lists in Entertainment Weekly, The Village
Voice, Rolling Stone and many more publications. Then, perversely,
at a time when America's music press was trumpeting electronic
dance music as the next big thing, Moby released ``Animal Rights,''
a guitar-heavy grab bag that alienated a good chunk of his fan
base.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the 34-year-old artist released what may well be his
finest album to date. ``Play'' finds him pushing the edge of
electronic dance music once again. Many of the tracks use a
cappella field recordings by archivist Alan Lomax of Deep South
African-American blues and gospel singers.
</P>
<P>
   In his review in Spin, Charles Aaron wrote, ``To hear an
electronic dance album looking backward as intently as it dreams
forward is a real-time joy, and Moby rides the groove with a buzz
reminiscent of his early swirling techno anthems `Go' and `Ah
Ah.''' The magazine further lauded Moby's efforts when ``Play''
gained the No. 20 spot on its list of the 90 best albums of the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   This fall finds Moby branching out into another realm: playing
fashion model in a Calvin Klein ad campaign. ``The only reason I
did it was because a bunch of my friends who were musicians were
doing it,'' he said. ``I thought that if they were OK with it, then
I'd do it. My one condition is that they don't try to make me look
sexy. If I tried to look sexy, I'd just end up looking like an
idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   When not doing fashion shoots, Moby is keeping up with a massive
tour schedule. He and his band have been on the road for two months
and will be gigging until after New Year's Day. He says he enjoys
the touring, though. ``Especially right now. It's summertime and
the shows are going well _ almost every show has been sold out.
It's great when the record's doing well and I'm on a label (V2)
that's very supportive. When the record isn't doing well and ticket
sales are slow, then it can be a drag.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, he's playing on a bill with bands with which he has
little in common; in fact, he sticks out like a frat boy at a Cher
concert. He's used to it, though, having played quite a few similar
shows on this tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did one in Buffalo,'' he recalls, ``and there are
about 10 bands on the bill, and I can't tell them apart. When you
have four white guys onstage with guitars, they start to sound the
same after a while. I also had the distinction of being the only
one who didn't yell, `Show us your (breasts)' from the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   His much-discussed Christianity isn't much like the version
you'll find at your local Baptist church. In an essay he wrote for
the ``Everything Is Wrong'' album, Moby said that ``conservative
Christian values are these _ humility, mercy, compassion, love,
honesty, etc. Nowhere in the Bible does Christ encourage his
followers to be intolerant, greedy bigots.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of five thoughtful and expressive short essays in the
``Play'' CD booklet, Moby writes that ``fundamentalism (of any
kind) troubles me. The world is too big and too intricate to
conform to our ideas of what it should be like.''
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way as our world, Moby's music is
unpredictable, constantly evolving and changing, defying
expectations in the most delightful ways.
</P>
<P>
   Moby will also perform a free show at midnight tonight at
Cobalt, 265 E. Paces Ferry Road N.E. 404-760-9250.
</P>
<P>
   Moby
</P>
<P>
   7:45 p.m. Saturday. Part of the 99X Big Day Out event. Music
starts at 1:15 p.m. $30 lawn seats; reserved seats sold out.
Lakewood Amphitheatre, 2002 Lakewood Way S.W. 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
