<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KRONOS-QUARTER17-COX     09-16 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRONOS-QUARTER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kronos program a tale of tape, tango, global works
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Kronos Quartet fears nothing but fear itself.
</P>
<P>
   The eclectic program it will play Saturday at Emory University
(Ga.) is standard with this cutting-edge group. The composers
include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Americans Steve Reich and Terry Riley. Reich's ``Triple
Quartet,'' written for Kronos, features the live quartet playing
against two tape recordings of itself. Riley's ``Requiem for Adam''
was written for the son of founding violinist David Harrington. The
boy died at age 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rezso Seress of Hungary, whose ``Gloomy Sunday,'' written in
1933 after the suicide of his lover, spawned a wave of copycat
suicides. (At one point, the British Broadcasting Corp. banned its
broadcast.) The arrangement for Kronos is by Argentine composer
Osvaldo Golijov and is based on the sound of a Hungarian Gypsy
band.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anibal Carmelo Troilo of Argentina, the great bandoneonista
who inspired the late Astor Piazzolla in his virtuoso tango
compositions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Franghiz Ali-Zadeh of Azerbaijan, who uses traditional Central
Asian material in her compositions. ``Oasis'' is from her ``Silk
Road'' cycle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rahul Dev Burman of India, best known for his film scores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aleksandra Vrebalov of Yugoslavia. Already a prize-winning
composer at 29, Vrebalov wrote ``Panonia Boundless'' as an ode to
freedom. Panonia is the ancient Roman name for the plains of
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   The major work on the program is the Quartet No. 2 of Alfred
Schnittke, the finest composer of the latter Soviet era, who died
last year at 65.
</P>
<P>
   Kronos watchers will note a new face in the foursome. Longtime
cellist Joan Jeanrenaud took a leave of absence last year and was
replaced by Jennifer Culp. Now Jeanrenaud has made her departure
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wear and tear of 20 years is certainly part of that,''
said Harrington, the only charter member left in the group. Violist
Hank Dutt joined the quartet in 1977, second violin John Sherba in
1978. Culp has the honor of being not only the youngest but also
the only San Franciscan in the San Francisco-based ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   While Kronos is at Emory, another eminent American quartet is at
Spivey Hall. The Emerson String Quartet will be playing more
standard fare: two Haydn quartets (``Quinten'' and ``Lark''),
Shostakovich's Quartet No. 14 and Samuel Barber's popular ``Adagio
for Strings.''
</P>
<P>
   Audience participation
</P>
<P>
   It's not often that the audience's voice is heard in a concert
(except when composers include ambient sound in their work). But
the audience gets quite a voice in the last event of NextFest, a
new-music weekend at Emory.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Craig Hultgren, 44, cellist with the contemporary
music ensemble Thamyris, sent out a search party for new works for
solo cello. The harvest of his work takes place Sunday. From more
than 110 submissions from composers in 12 countries, a panel of
judges chose eight works:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``With Love'' for cello, prepared tape and decorated cello
cases (1986) by Vivian Adelberg Rudow, 63, of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Incantation I'' for amplified cello and computer-generated
tape (1994) by C. Matthew Burtner, 29, a fellow at Stanford
University's Center for Computer Research in Music and Acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fast Music'' (1994) by Don Freund, 52, a professor at
Indiana University, who wrote the piece for the Japanese virtuoso
cellist Tsuyoshi Tsutsumi.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Artist and His Model'' by Charles Norman Mason, 44, who
teaches at Birmingham Southern College and wrote the piece for
Hultgren.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Parallax 2 `Apparitions,''' fine lines for cello and tape
(1992) by Paul Rudy, 37, University of Missouri/Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pizzicato'' (1996) by Arthur Jarvinen, 43, California
Institute of the Arts. The piece, written for his wife, Lynn
Angebranndt, imitates the use of the left hand by players of the
guitar and electric bass. The cellist dispenses with the bow
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Garland'' for cello and video (1991) by Robert Carl, 45,
Hartt School of Music, University of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pipeline Burst Cache'' for cello and tape (1998) by Craig
Walsh, 28, University of North Carolina at Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Another eight compositions were selected for special mention.
Two of these are by Southern composers: ``Three Gestures'' by
Nickitas J. Demos of Georgia State University and
``drowningXnumbers'' by Dorothy Hindman of Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   The printed program for the concert includes a ballot. At the
end of the performance, ballots will be collected and tallied, and
a winner announced.
</P>
<P>
   When the program was played in Birmingham in July, Mason won and
received a $1,000 prize. The winner at Emory also will receive
$1,000. The program will be performed a third time in Mobile, Ala.,
where the winner will receive $500.
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m. Sunday. $10. Performing Arts Studio, Emory University,
1804 N. Decatur Road. 404-727-5050.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson String Quartet
</P>
<P>
   8:15 p.m. Saturday. $30. Spivey Hall, Clayton College &AMP; State
University, 5900 N. Lee Ave., Morrow. 770-961-3683.
</P>
<P>
   Kronos
</P>
<P>
   Quartet
</P>
<P>
   8:15 p.m. Saturday. $25. Performing Arts Studio, Emory
University, 1804 N. Decatur Road N.E. 404-
</P>
<P>
   727-5050.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
