<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-AUTUMN17-COX     09-16 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AUTUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Tale' has the Rohmer magicBy Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Autumn Tale'' offers something more astonishing than all the
special effects and spectacular gross-out stuff we've seen this
summer at the movies. Namely, two nice-looking women in their
mid-40s sharing a glass of wine and some good talk.
</P>
<P>
   The last of esteemed French director Eric Rohmer's ``Four
Seasons'' series (some played here, some didn't), ``Autumn Tale''
is a comedy with, as the title suggests, a bittersweet autumnal
tone. And therein lies its richness.
</P>
<P>
   The long-widowed Magali (Beatrice Romand) runs a vineyard in the
Rhone Valley. Now that her children are grown, she grudgingly
admits to her married best friend, Isabelle (Marie Riviere), ``I
need to meet a man, but I refuse to do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem. Behind her back, Isabelle places a personals ad,
and then ``test drives'' the best prospect, Gerald (Alain Libolt),
by pretending to be Magali. Meanwhile, more matchmaking is afoot.
Young Rosine (Alexia Portal), who dates Magali's son, Leo, thinks
that Etienne (Didier Sander), her college professor and former
lover, would be perfect for her. Both prospects are invited to a
wedding so Magali can look them over (and vice versa) without
knowing she's being fixed up.
</P>
<P>
   Romand and Riviere, who've acted in Rohmer films of decades ago,
create indelible portraits of longtime friends who, as the somewhat
labored vineyard analogy insists, have become better with age. With
her mass of wiry jet-black hair and aging hippie wardrobe, Romand
is both earthy and vulnerable. Riviere, playing a chic bookstore
owner, exudes an endearing poise mixed with sensitivity and a
genuine caring for her friend. Even the brash, hardheaded (and
occasionally hardhearted) Portal means well.
</P>
<P>
   What's especially amusing here is how much more we learn about
the matchmakers than the matchmakee. Isabelle finds herself feeling
flirtatious with Gerald, while Rosine, though she insists she's
doing all this for Magali, seems to relish the hold she still has
over Etienne. And while theirs are decidedly secondary roles, the
men have something to play as well. Gerald is a divorced salesman
at loose ends _ ``I've lost contact with life,'' he confesses to
Isabelle. Meanwhile, Etienne, though he clearly hasn't lost his
taste for girls far too young for him, comes off as more than just
a cliched cad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn Tale'' is a film full of generosity, humor and insight.
By being both sympathetic to and ironic about the simple fact that
the prospect of seeking out romance reduces all of us to cringing
adolescents, the nearly 80-year-old Rohmer imparts wisdom that's
aged to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn Tale''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Marie Riviere and Beatrice Romand. Directed by Eric
Rohmer. Not rated, but the theme may be too mature for children.
Subtitles. 1 hour, 52 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Ripe comic-romance wisdom presented by a master
named Eric Rohmer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
