A4668 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-ACID-SPI &LR;      09-16 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ACID-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORIES IN `THE ACID HOUSE' PROVIDE A BIT OF A GIGGLE BUT LITTLE
ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will fans of ``Trainspotting'' flock to this film trilogy based
on a book of short stories by ``the poet laureate of the chemical
generation,'' Irvine Welsh?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, if they learn the rough-and-tumble Scot also wrote the
screenplay. It's tough to gauge because three years have passed
since ``Trainspotting,'' Danny Boyle's hallucinogenic parable of
drugged out contemporary urban youth, splashed onto screens and
we've since had lots of film rip-offs that have attempted to grasp
the same darkly funny, urgent look at ``choosing life'' _ complete
with hip, commercially inclined soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   Director Paul McGuigan assembles a sharp cast of British and
Scottish actors. And he certainly has an inventive eye (he began as
a photographer and graduated into TV documentary) and it's not the
direction that feels flaccid in this film. Surprisingly, it's the
stories themselves, which provide a bit of a giggle but little
else. They rely on quirkiness and schoolboy puerility to garner
their laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The first segment, ``The Granton Star Cause,'' and the last,
``The Acid House,'' are smug and self-serving stories about losers
who wind up glorified by circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Granton Star Cause,'' soccer player Boab Coyle (Stephen
McCole) is having a bad day. His teammates have sacked him, his
girl has dumped him and his parents have kicked him out so they can
have S&AMP;M sex. Even his boss has let him go. What's a guy to do?
Head to the pub, of course. But for Boab, an afternoon of drink
leads to a meeting with God (Maurice Roeves), who is fed up with
the human race and has decided to set an example with old Boab
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The second story, ``A Soft Touch'' is more effective and could
be likened to the improvisational, craggy films by Ken Loach or
Mike Leigh. It's also the most complex and truthful. A young man,
Johnny (Kevin McKidd) marries his pregnant girlfriend, Catriona
(Michelle Gomez). After their daughter is born, Johnny takes on the
role of breadwinner and parent because his wife wants nothing to do
with him.
</P>
<P>
   He's ``a soft touch,'' a caretaker of a guy who always does the
right thing despite the pain it causes. When Johnny is humiliated
by his wife's leaving him for their sleazy user of a neighbor, his
degradation is complete. He sees that he must change if he is to
avoid a dismal fate _ but can he?
</P>
<P>
   The final segment is the most prototypically Welsh. In ``The
Acid House,'' Coco Bryce (Ewen Bremner) drops a tab of acid and
runs out into a storm where he is hit by lightning simultaneously
with an ambulance carrying a posh English couple, Rory (Martin
Clunes) and Jenny (Jemma Redgrave), who have just had a child. Coco
and the infant exchange personalities _ to caustically humorous and
provocative result.
</P>
<P>
   The Acid House. Directed by Paul McGuigan. Written by Irvine
Welsh. Cast: Ewen Bremner, Kevin McKidd, Maurice Roeves, Martin
Clunes, Jemma Redgrave. Zeitgeist Films. 112 minutes. Unrated
(adults only).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-COLE17-COX     09-16 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offbeat `Adventures' agelessly amusing
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Sebastian Cole'' is as shaggy and unformed
as its hero's haircut. That's part of its charm. It's a
coming-of-age tale that recognizes that coming of age is an ongoing
experience that lasts long beyond adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1983, this amiably meandering comedy-drama unfolds in
upstate New York. It's there that Sebastian (Adrian Grenier)
listens with his startled sister and mother to his stepfather's
news: Hank (Clark Gregg) intends to become a woman, and he hopes
that's OK with the family.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't. The news sends mom (Margaret Colin) fleeing back to
her native England, dragging Sebastian with her, while sis heads
prematurely for college out west. But a few months later, sick of
the damp Old Country, Sebastian returns to the States. There he
moves back in with Hank, whose permed hair, earth-mother necklaces
and flowing frocks are helping him become ``Henrietta.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these changes, this is the same person who tough-loves
Sebastian into getting up every day for school and doing his best.
He's still a loving stepdad; he's just trying to find himself. So
is Sebastian, a wily student who supplements his innate smarts with
the occasional scam or reckless stunt (such as riding his bicycle
through the high school hallways, disguised behind a ski mask). He
wants to be a writer. He's looking for experience, whether that
means drinking himself into a stupor in the parking lot of the
liquor store or going to New York and looking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Tod Williams obviously enjoys his characters'
foibles and usually doesn't force them toward easy solutions or
revelations. Hank/Henrietta is only one of the many characters,
including Sebastian's sardonic school friends and his
on-again-off-again girlfriend (Aleksa Palladino). The film is
casually paced and takes its time, which might make some viewers
impatient. But if you're looking for a movie as interested in
texture as plot, you might give these ``Adventures'' a look.
</P>
<P>
   ``The
</P>
<P>
   Adventures of
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Cole''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Adrian Grenier and Clark Gregg. Rated R for language,
crude sexual references and substance abuse. At Tara.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 52 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A shaggy, elliptical coming-of-age tale.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
