r e BC-MOVIES-HARDBODY17-COX     09-16 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HARDBODY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Hands': Special touch of humanity
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A car dealership's publicity stunt gradually reveals itself to
be a bloodless blood sport in ``Hands on a Hard Body.'' S.R.
Bindler's riveting 1997 documentary unfolds primarily in a tent set
in the parking lot of a Nissan showroom in small-town, Texas, 125
miles east of Dallas. It's here that 23 lucky contestants, drawn at
random, meet at 7 a.m. on a Tuesday morning, jockeying to win a new
$15,000 truck.
</P>
<P>
   All they have to do is be the last one standing beside it, with
one hand touching the vehicle. No leaning. No sitting. No
squatting. No sleeping. Take your hand off the truck and you. Are.
Out.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight hours later, we've learned a lot about not only
the weary-eyed winner of the pickup, but the 22 who have buckled,
whether due to numb ankles and backs, exhaustion or the sort of
disorientation from sleep deprivation that sends one contestant
stumbling home in her socks in the wee hours of the morning (her
friends manage to catch up with her after three blocks).
</P>
<P>
   Among the memorable players are Benny Perkins, who presides over
the grueling marathon like a tailgate sage. Winner of the same
contest two years before, chosen to compete again, he knows the
competition is equally a matter of physical and emotional
endurance: ``It's who can maintain their sanity the longest.''
</P>
<P>
   The contestants include gawky young men, gray-haired guys and
about an equal number of women. They debate the merits of youth and
maturity in this sort of endurance test, and observers bet on who's
likely to last longest, based on their footwear, attitude and
eating habits (carbs: good; candy bars: bad). By the end of the
film, expectations have been tested, proved and just as often
upturned.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed before and during the marathon, the contestants have
different reasons for being there: the heck of it, the need for
another vehicle or a chance to sell the truck to pay off debts and
move on with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   For a woman named Norma, supported by a ``prayer chain'' at her
church, her motives are partly religious. Sustaining herself on
gospel tapes and bouts of divinely inspired laughter, she says,
``We believe in the power of prayer and the strength of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's extremely spiritual,'' Benny observes. ``It's a little
bit scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Norma and her friends think the Almighty would take such a
personal interest in the disposition of a Nissan pickup is never
addressed. But that's ultimately a strength of ``Hands.'' The movie
could take the easy way out by underscoring the eccentricity and
delusions of some contestants. Instead, the more time we spend
under that tent, the more nobility and depth director-editor
Bindler finds in these people.
</P>
<P>
   As the hours lengthen, he captures the ambiguity each time a
person pulls out of the contest: After a point, these strangers
become friends, making loss and victory a communal experience. Once
the contestants dwindle to a bleary four, the movie becomes
remarkably suspenseful; you find yourself rooting for all of them.
The beauty of ``Hands'' is the ways it finds something uplifting in
this bone-wearying stunt. Director Brindler gives us a good,
salty-sweet taste of what humanity is all about.
</P>
<P>
   When one fellow drops out of the race, he returns the next day
to cheer his former competitors on. In his words, ``There's not
that many tryers in the world today.'' Whether they succeed or not,
the subjects of the movie all gain heroic stature, just for
wishing, for wanting and for trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands on
</P>
<P>
   a Hard Body''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by S.R. Bindler. Rated PG for some brief
profanity. 1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A gripping documentary about a modern-day endurance test.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murrray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
