<HEADER>
A4672 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-IDAHO17-COX     09-16 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IDAHO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Twins Falls' an exercise in brotherly togetherness
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you've heard of identical twins being close? Brothers Michael
and Mark Polish took that idea to painful extremes when they made
``Twin Falls Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like an 18th-century corset,'' co-writer, co-star and
director Michael says of the device they wore to play conjoined
(aka ``Siamese'') twins Francis and Blake Falls. Made of fabric and
steel ribbing to simulate the movement of flesh and bone, the
girdle bound the two together from chest to legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as uncomfortable as you can imagine, but it helped with
the sweating and the anguish,'' says Michael, who plays the weaker
of the movie's brothers, Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Now playing, ``Twin Falls Idaho'' is a melancholy tale of love.
Basically a three-person drama, it shows us what happens when a
sympathetic young prostitute (Michele Hicks) meets the brothers and
finds her initial repulsion changing to compassion, then love for
one of the Falls boys.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Northern California, Michael and Mark, 28, became
fascinated with conjoined twins after seeing a photo of the famous
19th-century circus attractions Chang and Eng Bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were intrigued by the notion of two people being stuck
together all the time,'' Michael says.
</P>
<P>
   With the Polish brothers (it's pronounced POE-lish), sticking
together is a choice. They wrote the script in tandem, though they
chose separate tasks when making the movie. ``I took the director's
credit because it was easier to let Mark focus on the acting,''
Michael says. ``He had to carry the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really difficult to be an actor-director. I never wanted
to do that; I never thought that's where my talents would lie. We
always wrote screenplays that would allow me to direct and Mark to
act.'' Before their feature debut with ``Falls,'' Michael was
best-known for directing the award-winning short ``Bajo del Perro
(Under the Dog),'' starring his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Working on a $500,000 budget and an airtight, 17-day shooting
schedule, the brothers realized they couldn't even take the time to
allow rehearsals for the other actors. It was largely shoot-and-go.
The two did take time to polish their work as one physical unit,
playing the guitar (Mark's right hand strumming, Michael's left on
the frets) and walking in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really are one creature,'' Michael points out. ``We
thought it would be better if they had a kind of fluidity. I think
we magnified that a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about his inspiration for the dank, clammy look of the
movie's interiors, and he pauses a moment, knowing where this is
going. ``Regardless of who I say my inspirations are, people always
refer to David Lynch,'' he says. ``I think he's a master filmmaker,
but our first inspiration was painting.'' In particular, he and
Mark responded most to the precisely lit canvases of Edward Hopper
and Vermeer.
</P>
<P>
   As for filmmaking influences, he cites the late Krzysztof
Kieslowski, best-known perhaps for his 1990s trilogy of linked
movies, ``Blue,'' ``White'' and ``Red.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Michael Polish says ``Twin Falls Idaho'' is the first
of three scripts he and Mark have written, with name-places for
titles. The next one they plan to shoot: ``North Fork.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about building a dam,'' he says. His words come out with
a dry sort of noncommittal tone that suggests it's about a whole
lot more. You might just as easily describe ``Twin Falls Idaho'' as
``the story of two brothers who have a close relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it turns out to be, the next film will continue the
Polish brothers' exploration of what Michael calls ``Americana.''
He says, ``I feel our work is just as American as another film,
although it's dark. I like to think that America has a lot more
diversity than just Julia Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin Falls Idaho''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mark and Michael Polish. Directed by Michael Polish.
Rated R for kinkiness and adult themes. At Tara.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   An eerie and intriguing film about troubling doubles. (Eleanor
Ringel Gillespie)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
