<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CLASSICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GRAND ILLUSION,' `NORTH BY NORTHWEST' DELUXE REVIVALS IN EVERY
SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little over a decade ago, an eminent critic stated that, while
it was still too early to predict most of the long-term effects of
the video revolution on the movies, one thing was for sure: It
would destroy the theatrical revival business.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, did he get a wrong number. The audience for deluxe revivals
of great movies has grown steadily through the '90s. This year,
we've had a new-print, audio-enhanced, restored version of a
``Third Man,'' ``Blade Runner'' or ``Yellow Submarine'' almost
every week.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in fact, we have two re-tooled, golden oldies back on
the big screen where they belong: Jean Renior's 1937
French-language ``Grand Illusion,'' and Alfred Hitchcock's 1959
thriller, ``North By Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Illusion'' is a film that regularly makes the polls of
the cinema's great masterpieces. Among its many distinctions is the
fact it was the first foreign-language film to ever be nominated
for a best picture Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   It's a drama set mostly in a French and British POW camp in
Germany during World War I, and deals with the relationships
between the prisoners and their captors, and between the prisoners
themselves _ who soon team up along various class and social lines.
</P>
<P>
   The film is often called one of the great pacifist films, and,
while that may be true, it's anti-war message is extremely subtle,
and critics have debated for 50 years over what exactly the ``grand
illusion'' of the title refers to: Is it war in general, WWI in
particular or something else?
</P>
<P>
   But its story is so perfectly (and economically) told, its
characters are so rich and human and civilized, and its dialogue is
so intelligent and revealing that the film just wraps a spell
around you that's hard to describe, but impossible to forget.
</P>
<P>
   The gorgeous new print of this latest re-release of ``Grand
Illusion'' was made from the original camera negative, which was
long thought to have been destroyed in World War II, but turned up
recently in Toulouse. It's also been re-subtitled, and seems much
sharper than my memories of the older versions.
</P>
<P>
   The week's other major revival, ``North By Northwest,'' is being
shown via a new print with a restored, re-mastered soundtrack, and
was struck both to celebrate the film's 40th anniversary this year,
and last month's 100th anniversary of the birth of its director,
Alfred Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   It's an irresistible comedy-thriller staring Cary Grant as a New
York advertising man, mistaken for the target of a group of
unusually confident foreign spies, who spends most of the movie
being chased by them all over America.
</P>
<P>
   At least three sequences in this film are icons of the cinema _
Grant and co-star Eva Marie Saint hanging from Mount Rushmore,
Grant chased through a corn field by a malevolent crop-duster,
Grant and Saint making out in a train berth as the train goes into
a Freudian tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertigo'' may be Hitchcock's most artistic film, and
``Psycho'' may be his scariest, but ``North By Northwest'' is, for
my money, his most entertaining. Ernest Lehman's script is a marvel
of wit, sophistication and unrelenting menace, and just everything
about the movie ``works.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant gives a performance that seems the summation of his
persona, Bernard Herrmann's score is his most edgy and compelling,
Robert Burks' VistaVision visuals are staged with an epic and
surreal flair, and Hitchcock found just the right tone to
crystallize these elements into a stunning genre perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Illusion (1937). Directed by Jean Renoir. Written by
Renoir and Charles Spaak. Cast: Jean Gabin, Pierre Fresnay, Erich
von Stroheim, Marcel Dalio, Dita Parlo. Rialto Pictures. 117
minutes. In French with English subtitles. Unrated. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   North By Northwest (1959). Directed by Alfred Hitchcock.
Screenplay by Ernest Lehman. Cast: Cary Grant, Eva Marie Saint,
James Mason, Martin Landau, Jessie Royce Landis. MGM/Warner Bros.
136 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS17-     09-16 3063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Jill
Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures
</P>
<P>
   of Sebastian Cole'' R (profanity, crude sexual references,
</P>
<P>
   substance abuse)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Adrian Grenier and Clark Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   As shaggy and unformed as its hero's haircut. That's part of the
charm. Set in 1983, this amiably meandering comedy-drama unfolds in
upstate New York, where Sebastian (Adrian Grenier) listens with his
sister and mom to his stepfather's news: Hank (Clark Gregg) intends
to become a woman. Writer-director Tod Williams enjoys his
characters' foibles and doesn't force them toward easy solutions or
revelations. (SM) 1 hour, 52 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa's
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Kingdom'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary
</P>
<P>
   It has some eye-poppingly large pachyderms, but it isn't as
visually astounding as ``Everest.'' Still, this Imax film has its
share of lovely images, including time-lapse shots of the sun
setting on the dusty horizon and a massive storm whirling across
the plain. (SM) 40 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska:
</P>
<P>
   Spirit of the Wild'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by Charlton Heston.
</P>
<P>
   It's big, it's bold, it's big ... The sheer size of the latest
Imax offering sometimes makes it an eye-opening experience.
Otherwise, this visit to the far, brrr-cold reaches of our biggest
state is just another Discovery Channel-style nature flick. The
film spans millenniums _ and throws in bits and pieces about the
ice age, the Klondike Gold Rush, caribou hunting and bears. (Bob
Longino) 40 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' R (sexuality, sexual dialogue,
</P>
<P>
   profanity, drinking)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jason Biggs, Alyson Hannigan and Chris Klein.
</P>
<P>
   It's a raunchy, throwaway, pre-adult, R-rated high school
sexcapade with dirty dialogue and more than one risque encounter
between students that's broadcast over the Internet. There's also
the grossest joke involving a beer you're likely ever to see on
film. Little in ``American Pie'' deserves honest laughs. (Bob
Longino) 1 hour, 35 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn Tale'' Not rated, but the theme may be
</P>
<P>
   too mature for children.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Marie Riviere
</P>
<P>
   and Beatrice Romand.
</P>
<P>
   Magali (Beatrice Romand), a widowed Frenchwoman in her mid-40s,
becomes the object of matchmaking by her best friend and by the
young woman who's dating Magali's son. By being both sympathetic to
and ironic about the simple fact that seeking out romance reduces
us all to cringing adolescents, director Eric Rohmer, now almost
80, imparts wisdom that's aged to perfection. Subtitles. (ERG)1
hour, 52 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Better Than Chocolate'' Unrated, but contains nudity
</P>
<P>
   and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Wendy Crewson
</P>
<P>
   and Karyn Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   A sunny but badly scattered gay romantic comedy. The Canadian
comedy follows the love lives of a group of lesbians connected to a
bookstore called Ten Percent. Full of subplots, it's hard to
actively dislike. But like a puppy, it's sloppy and hyper and badly
in need of discipline. (SM)1 hour, 43 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Heather Donahue,
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Leonard and Michael Williams.
</P>
<P>
   It's a journey into the kind of terror that comes from trying to
glimpse something in the shadows just beyond the campfire. Three
students head into the woods to document an 18th-century witch
tale, then disappear. The movie wrings chills out of the slightest
effects _ odd twiglike contraptions hanging from trees, a pile of
stones, strange noises in the night _ but its power comes from
psychological intensity. (SM)1 hour, 27 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Streak'' PG-13 (profanity, violence
</P>
<P>
   and crude humor)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Martin Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   A decent, disposable Martin Lawrence vehicle. He's a crook
posing as a cop to recover a $17 million diamond he stashed years
ago. Basically a series of quick skits, there's enough action
scenes to mollify audiences who can't get enough of gunfire and
breaking glass. While it doesn't exactly streak along, at 93
minutes ``Blue Streak'' gets the job done. (SM)1 hour, 33 minutes.
C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Bowfinger'' PG-13 (sex-related material
</P>
<P>
   and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Steve Martin,
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy and Heather Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin has come up with a beautiful premise for a movie.
Martin plays a hapless Hollywood producer with a stinky script and
a gem of a way to get it filmed with impossible-to-get megastar Kit
Ramsey (Eddie Murphy). ``Bowfinger's'' got a few good laughs but
not much more. Sadly, it never takes on Hollywood with the zing of
``Wag the Dog'' or ``The Player.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 37 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Chill Factor'' R (profanity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cuba Gooding Jr.
</P>
<P>
   and Skeet Ulrich.
</P>
<P>
   Summer's last-gasp action movie. There's a newfound deadly
chemical substance that'll blow and snuff out millions if not kept
cold. And two bickering heroes (Skeet Ulrich and Cuba Gooding Jr.)
who must keep military hooligans away from that chemical by
stuffing it inside an ice cream truck and putting pedal to the
metal. Unfortunately, ``Chill Factor'' doesn't have enough gas to
outgun its own concept. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 40 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Blue Sea'' R (excessive gore, dismemberment)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   There is precious little that is original about this movie. It
really doesn't matter, though. When the plot kicks in and the
killer shark starts prowling and munching, the film delivers all
the thrills, explosive action and sheer gore that audiences have
come to expect from the shark genre. (Hap Erstein, Cox News
Service) 1 hour, 45 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dinner Game'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   With subtitles
</P>
<P>
   Starring Thierry Lhermitte
</P>
<P>
   and Jacques Villeret.
</P>
<P>
   A feast of foolishness. A bunch of snotty Paris yuppies holds a
weekly dinner to see who can bring the biggest idiot as his guest.
Publisher Thierry Lhermitte thinks he's got a sure thing when he
meets Jacques Villeret, who builds scale-model monuments out of
matchsticks. But fate intervenes when Lhermitte throws out his back
and is forced to spend the evening with Villeret. (ERG)1 hour, 22
minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Dudley Do-Right'' PG (mild comic action violence,
</P>
<P>
   profanity, innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Fraser
</P>
<P>
   and Sarah Jessica Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dudley Do-Right'' is just plain wrongheaded. Based on one of
the weaker elements of Jay Ward's TV 'toon series ``The Bullwinkle
Show,'' this live-action takeoff has so much less to offer. Brendan
Fraser (``George of the Jungle'') plays Dudley and it's clear he'd
rather not be here. There's not one joke or one slapstick moment
that's funny. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 27 minutes (including a new
``Fractured Fairy Tales'' cartoon short). F+
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story Imax
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' (SM)44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``For Love of the Game'' PG-13 (sexual situations, profanity
</P>
<P>
   and drinking)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Costner
</P>
<P>
   and Kelly Preston.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard it tries to hit, Kevin Costner's new baseball
flick whiffs a lot. Costner plays Billy Chapel, a Detroit Tigers
pitching god in his waning years who first learns his team is being
sold and he'll be traded and then that his girlfriend is dumping
him. As he pitches what could be a perfect game, he flashes back
over his life. (Bob Longino)2 hours, 18 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands on a Hard Body'' PG (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   S.R. Bindler's riveting 1997 documentary unfolds primarily in a
tent set in the parking lot of a Nissan showroom in small-town
Texas, where 23 lucky contestants jockey to win a new $15,000
truck. All they have to do is be the last one standing beside it,
with one hand touching the vehicle. The more time we spend under
that tent, the more nobility and depth director-editor Bindler
finds in these people. (SM) 1 hour, 37 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' PG-13 (brief nudity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Rupert Everett, Cate Blanchett, Jeremy Northam and
Julianne Moore.
</P>
<P>
   A less-than-ideal adaptation of Oscar Wilde's play. In 1895
London, a respected politician's public and private lives are
threatened by a devious blackmailer who knows a secret from his
past. The fine cast is stymied by director Oliver Parker's
literal-minded approach. What remains is a well-acted, very
well-appointed period piece that becomes more stifling and less
engaging as it goes along. (ERG) 1 hour, 37 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``In Too Deep'' R (profanity, sensuality, some violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Omar Epps and LL Cool J.
</P>
<P>
   A decent undercover-cop thriller highlighted by some smart
performances. Omar Epps is quite good as the detective, but LL Cool
J is a revelation as the ruthless drug kingpin, a monster made all
the scarier by his seeming benevolent charm. (SM)1 hour, 50
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspector Gadget'' PG (wacky violence, profanity
</P>
<P>
   and innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Broderick
</P>
<P>
   and Rupert Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The best gag is the first one in Disney's big-screen version of
TV's popular animated part-human, part-machine, mucho-gizmo lawman.
Matthew Broderick is perfectly cast as Gadget. Rupert Everett goes
over the top as bad man Sanford Solex. Kids will enjoy watching
them both. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 20 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' PG (fantasy action and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Aniston and Harry Connick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Nice story for kids, nifty look for adults. In 1957, a giant
metal-eating robot crash-lands on Earth and is befriended by
9-year-old Hogarth. But the robot's trail of munched-on trucks and
grain silos attracts a super-paranoid government agent. The
interesting mix of voice talent in this animated film includes
Jennifer Aniston as Hogarth's mom and Harry Connick Jr. as a
beatnik with seductive Elvis eyes. (ERG) 1 hour, 24 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Stinks'' R (profanity and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring French Stewart
</P>
<P>
   and Bridgette Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   And so does this movie. Playing like a revenge fantasy from
someone stung by a real-life palimony suit, writer-director Jeff
Franklin's misogynist diatribe miscasts irritating character actor
French Stewart as a TV writer about to marry his longtime
girlfriend Chelsea (Bridgette Wilson). She's a sexy parasite; he's
equally rancid. The movie has nothing to do with love. It's about
lust, lucre and well-paid losers. (SM)1 hour, 33 minutes. D-
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' PG-13 (profanity, some violence
</P>
<P>
   and sensuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hugh Grant, James Caan
</P>
<P>
   and Jeanne Tripplehorn.
</P>
<P>
   An effete British auctioneer (Hugh Grant) experiences culture
clash when he finds himself married to the mob, literally. Call it
a sleeping-with-the-fish-out-of-water comedy. Grant's one-trick
performance as an elegant bumbler is treadworn. He's terrific at
it, yes. But it's time to show more range. (SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes.
C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Muse'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Albert Brooks, Sharon Stone
</P>
<P>
   and Andie MacDowell.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Brooks wrote, directed and stars in this Hollywood fable
about a screenwriter who's ``lost his edge'' and is sent to an
honest-to-the-gods Muse (Sharon Stone) for inspiration. Stone is
delicious. She plays her Muse as a mix of material girl, expert
networker and distracted spoiled child. In other words, she's
modeled her after half of Hollywood. (ERG) 1 hour, 37 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery Men'' PG-13 (comic action violence
</P>
<P>
   and crude humor)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Stiller, Geoffrey Rush,
</P>
<P>
   Hank Azaria and Janeane Garofalo.
</P>
<P>
   It's a spoof! It's an adventure! No, it's an amiable mess. Ben
Stiller and Janeane Garofalo headline a ragamuffin team of
superhero wannabes. But the movie is mostly like its hapless heroes
_ kind of clumsy and good intentioned but with none of the knack it
takes to save the day, or itself. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 1 minute. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Providence'' R (teen drug use, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   sexual references)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Shawn Hatosy
</P>
<P>
   and Alec Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Just ignore the Miramax marketing campaign. This movie may be
written by the ``There's Something About Mary'' gang, but it's
bittersweet funny, not raucous comedy. It's a coming-of-age tale of
a '70s Rhode Island teen (Shawn Hatosy) that captures the shaggy,
druggy ``what-next'' feeling that followed in the uncertain years
after the Summer of Love had come and gone. (SM) 1 hour, 42
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Runaway Bride'' PG (profanity and sexual innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Roberts
</P>
<P>
   and Richard Gere.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning, alas, doesn't strike twice in this reunion of
``Pretty Woman'' stars Julia Roberts and Richard Gere. However, the
film isn't a fiasco and it does well by its intended audience,
i.e., anyone who wants to see Roberts galloping on horseback in
full wedding regalia. She's a bride who's already choked at the
altar three times and is about to try again. He's a cynical
journalist who's betting she'll run. (ERG)1 hour, 56 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' PG-13 (intense thematic material
</P>
<P>
   and violent images)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Willis, Haley Joel Osment and Toni Collette.
</P>
<P>
   A surprising, spine-tingling gem. Eight-year-old Cole (Haley
Joel Osment) can see ghosts, not the Casper variety but restless
phantoms with their skulls blown open. It's a fascinating, odd film
that speculates on what the relationship between the restless dead
and a liaison to the living world might be. Plus, this film has the
best, and loveliest, last-act twist of the year. (SM)1 hour, 47
minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Stigmata'' R (profanity, sexuality, intense violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Patricia Arquette
</P>
<P>
   and Gabriel Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Let it bleed without you. This mishmash of ``The Exorcist,''
``The Omen,'' etc. stars Gabriel Byrne as a Vatican investigator
sent to examine a young woman (Patricia Arquette) who's showing
signs of the stigmata, the wounds suffered by Christ on the cross.
Unfortunately, the movie prefers sensationalism to making sense.
It's enough to make you long for the good ol' days of pea soup and
spinning heads. (ERG)1 hour, 42 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Stir of Echoes'' R (profanity, sexual content
</P>
<P>
   and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Bacon
</P>
<P>
   and Kathryn Erbe.
</P>
<P>
   A ghost story with too many echoes of other flicks. It might
have seemed intriguing had it landed in theaters before ``The Blair
Witch Project'' and ``The Sixth Sense'' gave us new twists on the
spooky movie genre. A little boy sees ghosts and his hypnotized dad
(Kevin Bacon) goes wiggy while hunting what happened to a teen girl
haunting their home. (SM) 1 hour, 50 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' PG-13 (violence, sexuality, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   teen drinking)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Helen Mirren, Katie Holmes, Barry Watson and Marisa
Coughlan.
</P>
<P>
   It barely makes a passing grade. Three high school kids take
their evil history teacher hostage in her home and then try to
figure out how to get out of the mess they've created. It ends up
being a wishy-washy remake of 1980's silly ``Nine to Five.'' As the
tied-up teach, Helen Mirren is pretty good. Her young co-stars,
however, fail to match her talent. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 35
minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``The 13th Warrior'' R (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Antonio Banderas.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, cheesy movies can be great fun. That's true of this
rip-roaring yarn about a medieval Arab poet (Antonio Banderas)
who's drafted by a roving gang of rowdy Vikings to help rescue a
Norse village from a mysterious enemy that comes from the mist,
kills everything in sight and leaves a trail of headless corpses.
This flick hits the ground running and never stops. (ERG) 1 hour,
43 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pierce Brosnan and Rene Russo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Windmills of Your Mind'' is still on the soundtrack, but
lots of other gimmicks from the 1968 original have been excised.
That's good. This remake is a guilt-free summer diversion. Pierce
Brosnan is an appealing billionaire gentleman rogue, stealing
priceless paintings. But it's really Rene Russo's film. As the solo
investigator hot on his trail, she prowls the screen savoring a
smart, sexed-up character. (SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``trick'' R (sexuality, profanity
</P>
<P>
   and mature themes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Christian Campbell
</P>
<P>
   and John Paul Pitoc.
</P>
<P>
   In this sturdy and well-acted gay romantic comedy, two guys
spend a night looking to make love in all the wrong places. Gabriel
(Christian Campbell) and Mark (John Paul Pitoc) pick each other up,
both clearly intending a mutually gratifying one-night stand. But
as the evening wears on, they're still on the street. The obstacles
become more contrived as the movie goes on. But, overall, ``trick''
is a minor treat. (ERG) 1 hour, 30 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin Falls Idaho'' R (kinkiness and adult themes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mark
</P>
<P>
   and Michael Polish.
</P>
<P>
   Eerie. Intriguing. Identical twins, Mark and Michael Polish,
play conjoined (the popular term is Siamese) twins. Moving at its
own slow, surreal pace, the picture shows what happens when a young
hooker (Michele Hicks) falls for one of the twins, thus creating a
strange pas de trois. Exploring themes of love and loneliness, the
movie suggests that sometimes, wholeness can only be found by
letting go. (ERG) 1 hour, 45 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some Imax films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
(Jill Vejnoska) 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Jill
Vejnoska write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
