<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-STREAK17-COX     09-16 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STREAK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Genial `Blue Streak' a capable heist caperBy Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good cop solves a crime by thinking like the perpetrator.
Given that logic, it makes sense that a real-life criminal would
make a terrific policeman. He can look at a crime scene and see
exactly what went down, while the officers around him are still
scratching their heads. That's the playful idea behind ``Blue
Streak,'' a decent, disposable Martin Lawrence vehicle. It never
gets maximum mileage from its crook-as-flatfoot premise, but it
stirs up decent laughs and action.
</P>
<P>
   Martin plays Miles Logan, a thief newly sprung from two years in
lockup. When he goes to the then-construction site where he stashed
a $17 million diamond, he discovers the finished building is the
new Los Angeles Police Department. Which means that he has to
infiltrate the station masquerading as a cop in order to track down
the missing rock, located somewhere in the AC vents.
</P>
<P>
   Miles not only succeeds in his charade, he keeps accidentally
doing the right thing, catching crooks and becoming a hero to his
erstwhile enemies, the cops surrounding him. (It's a comic reversal
of the current ``In Too Deep,'' starring Omar Epps as an undercover
cop dangerously drawn to the drug figures he's trying to bust.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Streak'' doesn't ask big questions about identity. It's
basically a series of quick skits, letting Lawrence bluster and
give free rein to his spastic dances of victory or frustration.
Director Les Mayfield throws in enough action scenes to mollify
audiences who can't get enough gunfire and breaking glass. While it
doesn't exactly streak along, at 93 minutes ``Blue Streak'' gets
the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Streak''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Martin Lawrence. Rated PG-13 for action violence,
continual profanity and some crude humor.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A decent, disposable Lawrence vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4677 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS19-COX     09-16 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern politics no longer as lively in prosperous era
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time to catch him was on a summer's night, down some dirt
road the lawyers and the bankers and the important people had no
need to travel. He called such an occasion ``a speakin','' but it
was more like a religious revival. He'd get to flailing those arms
like a man swatting mosquitoes, his brow beading with sweat, a
shank of frizzy rust-brown hair falling almost to his bulging
pop-eyes, and he'd hear the shouts of people whose voices no one
else heard. ``Pour it on 'em, Huey! Pour it on 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he got going good the seersucker suit would hang on him
damp and limp, and two sizes too big. About this time the head
would be pivoting furiously, the vitriol spewing forth in all
directions but mostly in the direction of Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   As archetype, the Southern politician is both caricature and
social symbol, the embodiment of the region's politics and the
unflattering reflection of its people. Huey Long, dead of an
assassin's bullet before he was 43, was by all odds the most
ambitious and the most demagogic of a lot that has included his
brother Earl, Tom Watson, Pitchfork Ben Tillman, Theodore K. Bilbo,
Big Jim Folsom, Gene Talmadge and Jesse Helms. All have been, in
one way or another, embarrassments outside the flock of the
faithful and some were scoundrels to boot. But none have been
bland, none have been dull. ``From afar,'' V.O. Key wrote half a
century ago, ``outlanders regard Southern politics as a comic opera
staged on a grand scale for the amusement of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican inroads
</P>
<P>
   Key's magisterial work ``Southern Politics'' is the starting
point for anyone presuming to write about Southern politics, a book
whose analytic incisiveness is exceeded only by Key's gift for the
right phrase and the elegant synthesis of ideas. But the South of
which he wrote is not the South of today, even if some of its
problems _ race in particular _ endure in ameliorated form. Even
before Key's time, various ``New Souths'' were being prematurely
heralded, the first by Henry Grady, the editor a century ago of The
Atlanta Constitution. None was really new. All were backwaters of
poverty, pellagra and the poll tax, economic dependencies that
moved Franklin D. Roosevelt to declare the South ``the nation's No.
1 problem.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying that as the century closes. The South, if it is
not new, is manifestly different, nowhere more so than in its
politics. A few Cenozoic mastodons cling to office, but the
flamboyant demagogues of years past are being replaced by moderates
and conciliators. A more far-reaching change has also taken place:
The South now elects Republicans as well as Democrats, and in
numbers that have brought virtual parity between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   As Alexander Lamis, editor of ``Southern Politics in the 1990s''
(Louisiana State University Press, $39.95), acknowledges, the Solid
South of one-party rule had begun to corrode in the postwar years.
It corroded further in the '60s and '70s, and by 1990 it was gone
for good.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Lamis, a political scientist at Case
Western Reserve University, teams of journalists and political
scientists examined election results in the 11 states that Key had
studied, and the Republican rise is documented in cold, hard
numbers. No less than other Southern states, Georgia ``has emerged
into mainstream competition between two evenly matched political
parties that can take no office for granted.'' (The Georgia chapter
is co-written by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's Tom Baxter,
along with political scientists Michael Binford of Georgia State
University and David Sturrock of Southwest (Minnesota) State
University.)
</P>
<P>
   In bed with religious right
</P>
<P>
   With the Sun Belt South's prosperity has come suburbanization,
an erosion of the old black-white coalition that had sustained the
Democratic Party and a growing willingness of white Southerners to
identify themselves as Republican. But the GOP's ascent has been
neither smooth nor uniform. It must still scrounge for good horses
to run a race, especially on the local level. And once it made
itself a bedfellow of the religious right, it found itself a party
divided _ economic conservatives and social moderates on one side,
single-issue religious conservatives on the other. Lamis quotes
U.S. Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.) on the frustration of having to
placate the religious right: ``They're not always wrong, but if you
don't always agree with them, you're always wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Such pith, alas, is an exception in ``Southern Politics in the
1990s.'' One of the pleasures of Key's book was a prose that put
matters just so, even in chapter subheadings. In Georgia, for
example, one found ``Rule of the Rustics.'' In Mississippi, ``Rout
of the Aristocracy: The Percys and the Bilbos.'' In Louisiana,
``Why a Huey Long?''
</P>
<P>
   Why things happen is always more interesting than what did
happen, and Key was both politically and sociologically acute. If
the 400-some pages of ``Southern Politics in the 1990s'' offer more
confirmation than elucidation, perhaps the grayness of presentation
is itself among the changes the South has witnessed for both better
and worse.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
