<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BARGEREPORT1STAKE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A casual, cultural excursion
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER _ Ask anybody who's been on a few
cruises and they'll tell you that each has its own set of quirks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a different personality for every type of cruise,''
says Carol Heinrich, a Roswell travel agent who estimates she's
traveled the world's oceans and rivers more than 20 times in the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``On ocean vessels, you might have a wide variety of on-board
entertainment, but the scenery may be limited,'' Heinrich
continues. ``On a river cruise, your entertainment is primarily
going to come from other passengers, but you'll get to see more of
a particular region.''
</P>
<P>
   Put RiverBarge Excursions in the latter category. Launched just
a year ago by New Orleans entrepreneur Eddie Conrad, the cruise
line aims to be a casual, culturally focused alternative to the
Dixieland flashiness of the Delta Queen and other riverboats and to
the party-hardiness of many Caribbean cruises. Its River Explorer
hotel barge travels the Mississippi, Missouri and Ohio rivers, as
well as the Intracoastal Waterway along south Louisiana and Texas
on seven theme trips, including ``The Delta South,'' which visits
Louisiana's historic River Road plantation region, and ``Cajuns and
Creoles,'' which tours the Atchafalaya Basin.
</P>
<P>
   I recently signed on for the four-day ``Delta South'' excursion
and found a lot to love _ cheerful service, bountiful buffets,
spacious staterooms _ along with a few problems.
</P>
<P>
   The following is a report card of sorts for the trip. The grades
given for each category reflect my experiences as well as some of
my fellow passengers' on one particular excursion. Scores may rise
or drop depending on the itinerary and/or an individual's
temperament.
</P>
<P>
   ROOMS WITH A VIEW
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations: A-
</P>
<P>
   Many other cruise lines take a caste-system approach to putting
up guests, with accommodations ranging from closet-size cabins with
bunk beds to sprawling suites. RiverBarge is nicely egalitarian.
</P>
<P>
   The River Explorer's 99 staterooms, which forgo fussiness for
utilitarian comfort, are all the same size _ 200 square feet. They
are all air-conditioned and come with either one queen-size bed or
two twin beds. Each has a full-size bathroom with a shower and tub,
a rare luxury for a cruise vessel. (Most ship cabins have only
showers.) And no telescopic porthole views here. The rooms on the
lower Royal Deck feature large picture windows, while the upper
Platinum Deck rooms have sliding-glass doors leading to small
balconies, perfect for river-gazing. Binoculars are provided so you
can better read the T-shirt of that guy standing on a passing
freighter.
</P>
<P>
   When you get tired of the Mississippi's sights, you can plop
down on the bed and watch satellite TV or pop a video in the VCR _
movies are available for free in the game room. Each stateroom also
comes equipped with a mini-refrigerator, a telephone and a coffee
maker.
</P>
<P>
   ALL YOU CAN EAT ... AND THEN SOME
</P>
<P>
   Food: B
</P>
<P>
   Those who have savored the duck rillettes with truffle on a
Holland America cruise or supped on salmon and scallop
``carpaccio'' aboard the Radisson Diamond may find RiverBarge's
cuisine a tad ... common. The River Explorer's galley serves up
no-frills fare _ breakfast and lunch are buffet-style, dinner is a
la carte with ``blue plate specials'' to match the theme of each
excursion. Our dinner menu featured competently rendered Cajun
favorites such as jambalaya, crawfish etouffee and shrimp creole.
</P>
<P>
   The food may not be fancy, but, oh my, is there a lot of it. The
almost obscenely well-stocked buffets would bring out the glutton
in Calista Flockhart. For breakfast my first morning on the river,
I piled my plate with sausage, bacon, corned beef hash, scrambled
eggs, poached eggs, a waffle, canteloupe, pineapple, peaches and a
blueberry mini-muffin. Modest portions of each, to be sure, but
still _ oink! Lunch the next day was equally light, an unabashed
calorie-fest of pork tenderloins, shrimp po-boys and red beans and
rice with sausage.
</P>
<P>
   The galley's casual-dress, open-seating policy is also a plus.
Meals are served within a two- to 2 1/2-hour period, during which
guests can come and go at their leisure. If you miss a scheduled
meal, don't worry. The galley keeps a refrigerator stocked with
leftovers, which you are encouraged to raid whenever you feel
hungry.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S THE PARTY?
</P>
<P>
   On-board entertainment: C
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an externally focused cruise line,'' boasts RiverBarge
President Jeff Krida, meaning the company emphasizes culturally
significant shore tours over the on-board dances, Broadway reviews
and theme nights offered by other cruises.
</P>
<P>
   It shows. On longer excursions, RiverBarge may occasionally
invite guest performers aboard _ the ``Cajuns and Creoles'' tour
features brief appearances by a Cajun music group and a humorist.
But on our four-day trip, the only scheduled activities were two
hourlong lectures _ one on the Civil War and one on the history of
barges _ presented by crew members who frequently read from notes.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, guests were left to make their own fun. Some
played Scrabble or rummy in the galley, some took a dip in the hot
tub on the top deck, some sipped beer at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Soper, a 37-year-old court reporter from Minneapolis,
summed up the feelings of many. ``This is a little mellow for me,''
she said. ``I wouldn't have minded seeing a show or two.''
</P>
<P>
   True to Heinrich's words, my fellow bargers provided much of the
on-board entertainment. Soper quizzed me at length on my
illustrious life as a travel writer; we were both dismayed to find
out she had been more places than I had. And I learned all about
Atlanta, Texas, from Jay and Shirley Clements, who have lived there
most of their lives. A timber town almost halfway between
Texarkana, Texas, and Shreveport, La., Atlanta was settled by
Georgia expatriates. Surrounding communities include Marietta,
Smyrna and Douglasville. Seems only fair that they should have a
share of our smog.
</P>
<P>
   FROM RIVER ROAD TO BOURBON STREET
</P>
<P>
   Shore tours: B+
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, shore excursions are RiverBarge's forte. On our trip,
we explored rural and urban history alike, making two stops at
antebellum estates in Louisiana's plantation country before barging
back for an enlightening bus tour of the Big Easy.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop was Oak Alley Plantation, about 60 miles north of
New Orleans. This Greek Revival stunner is the perfect postcard
image of an antebellum mansion: A canopy formed by two rows of
giant live oaks, planted almost 300 years ago by a French settler,
shades the quarter-mile path from the river to the main house.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1837-39 by a sugar planter named Jacques Telesphore
Roman III, the mansion is ringed by 28 Doric columns and features
such fancy-weird indoor adornments as ceiling medallions made of
horse hair and plaster and cypress fireplace mantels painted to
look like marble.
</P>
<P>
   Next we visited Nottaway Plantation, another Greek Revival manse
about 38 river miles north. Our arrival came later than expected.
We were scheduled for an early evening tour, but delays at the boat
landing and tricky logistics with the shuttle buses put us in
Nottaway's grand entrance hall at about 9 p.m. It was worth the
wait. The 65-room mansion, considered the largest in Louisiana,
twinkled in the warm night, and our hoop-skirted guides greeted us
with glasses of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Back in New Orleans at journey's end, we embarked on a
three-hour bus tour that took us from the French Quarter to the
Garden District to Lake Ponchartrain. Our guide, a New Orleans
native, was an encyclopedia of local trivia. He filled us in on the
origins of Louis Armstrong's nickname, Satchmo (it's short for
``satchel mouth''; when the trumpeter performed on the streets of
New Orleans as a youngster, he kept his coins in his cheeks to foil
thieves), and the procedure for burying multiple bodies in the
city's above-ground tombs (don't ask).
</P>
<P>
   A quibble: Two plantations and a bus tour over four days was a
little skimpy. One more stop would make this itinerary a must for
history buffs.
</P>
<P>
   SHINY HAPPY PEOPLE
</P>
<P>
   Service: A
</P>
<P>
   If we heard it once on our trip, we heard it a hundred times:
``If you need anything at all, please don't hesitate to ask.'' It
was the crew members' mantra, and darned if they didn't seem to
mean it.
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, the 42-person staff of the River Explorer does
``helpful'' right. Servers in the galley call you by name and scold
you good-naturedly when you get up to get your own soda refill.
Housekeepers leave sweets _ peppermints, chocolates, Rice Krispie
Treats _ in your room each day. Guest relations manager Skippy
Trahan entertains passengers waiting to disembark for shore tours
with saucy Cajun jokes featuring a pair of backwoods dimwits,
Boudreaux and Thibodaux.
</P>
<P>
   No crew member is off limits. In the pilot house, the captain
eagerly welcomes visitors _ you can stay all day and listen to him
patiently describe the functions of the various knobs, dials and
screens. If you're lucky enough to be sailing with relief captain
Joe Aucoin, ask him to tell you about riding out Hurricane Juan
while piloting a diesel barge on the Mississippi in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And for once, there are no ulterior motives for the niceness.
The cruise line maintains a strict no-tipping policy _ that means
no envelopes left on your pillow on the last morning, no extended
hands at the bar and no expectant bellhops hesitating in the
doorway of your room.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
