<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER: the doorway of your room.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY METAL, MUDDY WATERS
</P>
<P>
   Scenery: B-
</P>
<P>
   Maxine Loffler of Snellville gushes about the gorgeous views on
her December cruise with RiverBarge. The 58-year-old retired banker
sailed the ``Route of Jean Lafitte'' along the Intra-
</P>
<P>
   coastal Waterway from New Orleans to Port Isabel, Texas, making
a scenic stop at the edge of Louisiana's Barataria swamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were deer all along the shore, the crew shined a
spotlight on them,'' Loffler remembers. ``Then we looked up in the
trees and saw that they were filled with great white birds (likely
egrets).''
</P>
<P>
   Nature lovers would be wise to opt for Lafitte's course or the
``Cajuns and Creoles'' swamp trek over the ``Delta South'' trip.
The stretch of the Mississippi we traveled offered few natural
wonders. Birdwatching bargers were hard-pressed to find a feathered
friend through their binoculars, and aside from the rare live oak,
the banks were dominated by stubby willows _ plain-Jane sisters to
the more dramatic weeping variety. And the 40-foot levee that
brackets the Mississippi made it impossible to view the vast sugar
cane fields or stately plantations inland.
</P>
<P>
   No, here nature took a back seat to man-made wonders. Freighters
the size of small countries passed within several dozen feet of our
barge every few minutes. Dizzyingly high suspension bridges cast
ribbonlike shadows over the top deck. And, oh, those petrochemical
refineries!
</P>
<P>
   Despite the abundance of industry, there was a notable lack of
pollution. No oil slicks stained the sides of the barge, no
cast-off chemical drums littered the banks. Here, man and nature
seem to have developed a mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   FLOATS OUR BOAT
</P>
<P>
   Final grade: B
</P>
<P>
   So is a RiverBarge cruise worth the money? Excursions can cost
from $740 to $2,995 (based on double occupancy), depending on the
length of the trip and the time of year. All in all, I'd say it's a
fine value, provided you're prepared to deal with the occasional
snafu and a lot of relaxation time. As for the above complaints,
well, fellow passenger Jay Clements said it best when we were late
getting to Nottaway Plantation: ``I've always heard that if people
aren't griping just a little bit, they're not having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   RiverBarge: Seven themes for all seasons
</P>
<P>
   RiverBarge offers seven theme excursions that cover an area from
Huntington, W.Va., to Matamoros, Mexico, just below the
southernmost tip of Texas. Below is an itinerary for each. Note
that each excursion is offered at various lengths _ the ``Delta
South'' voyage, for instance, comes in four-, six- and eight-day
packages. You may make more or fewer stops than the ones listed.
</P>
<P>
   Excursions are sold out until Thanksgiving. Some tours are
seasonal _ check with RiverBarge for specific dates. Prices vary
according to length of trip. Dates are subject to change.
Information:
</P>
<P>
   1-888-282-1945 or visit www.riverbarge.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  America's Junction. See where the Mississippi and Ohio rivers
meet, then tour various ports along the Ohio River Valley,
including Louisville, Ky., where you might opt to spend the day at
Churchill Downs racetrack. (Offered June, July and October 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Arch &AMP; the Pyramid. The name refers to signature landmarks
in St. Louis and Memphis, respectively. Begin the tour in either
port, witness the confluence of the Mississippi and Ohio rivers and
explore small-town life in Columbus, Ky., and Cape Giradeau, Mo.
(Offered June and August 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cajuns and Creoles. Learn about the cultures, languages and
cuisine indigenous to Louisiana's Atchafalaya Basin. Includes
guided tours of swamps, bayous and lakes between New Orleans and
New Iberia, and stops at Creole plantations along the Mississippi
south of Baton Rouge. (Offered December 1999; April and May 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Delta South. Explore the plantation country between New
Orleans and Baton Rouge, making stops at antebellum mansions along
River Road, the collective name for the country lanes that run
along both sides of the Mississippi in the area. Longer versions of
this trip continue to Memphis, with visits to Natchez and
Vicksburg, Miss. (Offered December 1999; January, February, March,
May and November 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expanding Frontiers. Travel from Memphis or St. Louis along
the Mississippi to the Ohio River and on through the Cumberland
River Valley, with a final stop in Nashville. (Offered July and
September 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Route of Jean Lafitte. Trace the ``treasure route'' of
pirate Jean Lafitte from New Orleans to Matamoros, Mexico. This
excursion is divided into two eight- to 10-day trips: ``Bayous and
Buccaneers'' visits New Orleans, the Atchafalaya Basin and
Galveston, Texas; ``South to the Border'' departs from Galveston
Bay and continues to Port Isabel, Texas, where passengers board a
bus for a day trip to Matamoros. (Offered December 1999 through
early March 2000, then November 2000 through March 2001.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Show Me'' the Big Muddy. Follow Lewis and Clark's expedition
route down the Missouri River from St. Louis to Kansas City, Kan.
Tour Harry Truman's hometown of Independence, Mo., and visit Daniel
Boone's log cabin in Boonville, Mo. (Offered August and September
2000.)
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
