<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-RIVERBARGE19-C     09-16 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RIVERBARGE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A barge cruise along the mighty Mississippi offers time and
space to watch the world roll by
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER _ It may be the slowest game of chicken
in history.
</P>
<P>
   As the River Explorer barge inches upriver _ destination:
Nottaway Plantation, 18 miles south of Baton Rouge _ it meets a
massive oil tanker headed back to New Orleans. Up in the pilot
house, relief captain Joe Aucoin studies the approaching vessel,
which looks like it might close the half-mile gap between us in,
oh, about a day.
</P>
<P>
   Aucoin knows who's boss here. ``You got to give the big boats
some room, especially if they're coming downriver,'' says the New
Orleans native in a thick Cajun-country drawl. At length, he
reaches over and taps a short steel steering lever and the barge,
no scrawny
</P>
<P>
   dinghy at 860 tons, adjusts course.
</P>
<P>
   The two giants pass _ eventually _ without incident. There's no
desperate hand-over-hand wrenching of a giant wooden wheel, a la
``Shipwrecked.'' No frenzied radio calls, no drama. A tap is all it
takes to navigate these placid waters. The Mississippi may be
mighty, but it's a quiet strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it gets choppy, but only a little,'' says Aucoin,
who's been piloting barges, tankers and cargo ships up and down the
Big Muddy for 25 years. ``The only thing you have to worry about is
the traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, our ``Delta South'' voyage, a four-day exploration of
Louisiana's historic plantation region offered by RiverBarge
Excursions of New Orleans, covers a stretch of the Mississippi
teeming with industry. Convoys of cover-top barges haul corn and
grain. Chemical tankers get their fill at loading platforms along
the banks. Imposing Coast Guard icebreakers loom over sprawling
shipyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, so many of these companies have changed names,
changed hands,'' Aucoin says. ``The river never changes.''
</P>
<P>
   And to experience it from the decks of the River Explorer is to
go with the unhurried flow. The 730-foot, 198-passenger barge
hotel, launched a year ago this week, crawls along at a tad over 15
mph. At times, the workers walking on those land-anchored loading
platforms seem to be traveling faster.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers loll on lattice-steel chaise lounges on the top deck,
basking in the hot sun and contemplating the endless rows of
willows lining the Mississippi. A tugboat chugs by. A fat cloud
drifts lazily in the sky. And the river rolls on. Mile after
tranquil mile.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a tense, Type A personality, or a jaded traveler used
to glitz and spectacle, this may sound like a slow boat to boredom.
But a lot of folks seem to love the pokey pace.
</P>
<P>
   RiverBarge's four- to 10-day excursions, which include
itineraries on the Mississippi, Missouri and Ohio rivers and along
the Intracoastal Waterway from New Orleans to southernmost Texas,
are sold out until Thanksgiving. More than half of next year's
trips are booked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a less intense experience than other cruises,'' says
RiverBarge president Jeff Krida, who's along for the ride to
schmooze travel agents the cruise line is courting. That's
experience talking _ Krida was president of the rival Delta Queen
Steamboat Co. for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Delta Queen's immensely popular paddle wheelers,
RiverBarge doesn't offer a lot of snazzy trappings. The decor is
more Holiday Inn than high Victorian, mealtime is come-as-you-are
(with no assigned seating) and the entertainment tends toward guest
lecturers and indigenous music performances rather than ice cream
socials or sock hops.
</P>
<P>
   But Krida says his target audience, Americans 40 and older, is
drawn to the casual atmosphere, the comparatively huge staterooms,
the no-tipping policy and, above all, the price tag. A RiverBarge
sailing is cheaper than the average Delta Queen excursion and
includes meals and shore tours _ everything but alcohol and phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Count Jay and Shirley Clements of Atlanta, Texas, among the
satisfied customers. ``I'd love to come back and take the
Intracoastal Waterway trip,'' says Jay, 64, as he strolls the
grounds of Oak Alley Plantation, the first shore tour on our
excursion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see so much on a cruise like this,'' he continues,
surveying the breathtaking allee of live oaks that flank the
walkway to the main house. ``We took a cruise to the Bahamas once,
and being out on the ocean in such a big boat, we might as well
have been in our den at home.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis travel agent Betty Heimburger, making her first
RiverBarge trip, likes the cruise because ``it's relaxed, more
intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly in a rush to go nowhere herself, she takes in the view
and enjoys a rare south Louisiana breeze by the barge's outdoor
snack bar. ``This would be perfect for an older couple, maybe on a
second honeymoon, who don't want to deal with the party crowds on
the other cruises,'' she adds. ``They would have plenty of time and
space to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Time? Space? Now those are unique concepts. The Mississippi
means to teach us all about them.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the River Explorer after the plantation tour, Jay
Clements appears ready for the lesson. ``It's a long way from one
end of this barge to the other, and Shirley and I know because
we've walked it,'' he marvels. ``And still, we're just a dot out
here on the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
