<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-VINTAGE-CLOTHES19-COX     09-16 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINTAGE-CLOTHES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Age cannot wither nor custom stale the infinite variety of
vintage clothes, retailers find
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the world's top fashion designers unveiled their
spring/summer 2000 collections in New York last week, some
retailers weren't interested. To purveyors of vintage clothing and
accessories, the hottest styles aren't still to come; they've
already been worn. Decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the beige silk Shantung pants with the slim
leg and tab belt at Stefan's Vintage Clothing in Little Five
Points. Shop owner Rebecca Birdwhistell thinks the pants are such a
rare find that she could get at least $1,000 for them. But she's
not selling.
</P>
<P>
   The slacks were worn by none other than the late Fred Astaire in
the 1953 movie ``The Band Wagon.'' Birdwhistell found them in a box
of old clothes she purchased for $100 at an open-air market in New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the high point of the last six months, in terms of
being excited about finding something totally cool,'' she says. ``I
saw sewn into the label `Metro Goldwyn Mayer.' Underneath that was
handwritten `Fred Astaire.' To me it's a piece of American film
history, and I'll probably never find another pair.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage clothiers such as Birdwhistell travel nationwide in
search of garments. Anything worn between the 1940s and the 1970s
qualifies as vintage, but the older, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a swing skirt, a Jacqueline Kennedy-esque fitted
suit or a mini-dress with go-go boots, the best finds, retailers
say, are at garage sales, flea markets and estate sales away from
the big cities.
</P>
<P>
   Angela McLean, owner of Psycho Sisters, which sells vintage and
resale clothing at four metro Atlanta locations, likes to shop in
Florida, Alabama and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as trendy as Atlanta, so if older people retire and
donate their clothes to thrift stores or have a garage sale, I'm
still able to buy them for a price point and pass on the value to
my customers,'' McLean says.
</P>
<P>
   Birdwhistell, who spends at least 60 percent of her time on the
road, likes shopping in Texas and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Although vintage clothing is becoming a hot commodity _ a tartan
1948 Schiaparelli bustle skirt sold for more than $25,000 at a
recent Sotheby's auction _ retailers say they aren't in the
business for the money. They do it because they love collecting old
clothes and can earn a living at it.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Clayton, owner of Twice Is Nice in Hapeville, (Ga.) has
sold vintage clothing for more than a decade. Some of her old hats
and dresses have even appeared in movies, including ``Boxing
Helena'' and ``To Dance With the White Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wanting swing dresses now because young folks are back
into swing dancing,'' Clayton says. ``I also sell a lot of things
for '70s parties and '50s parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
