<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-SHOOTING (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Seven young people were
slain at a Baptist church gathering Wednesday night by a gunman who
may have been upset over efforts to convert Jews to Christianity.
Witnesses said he was muttering obscenities and began shooting
after someone stood up and told him he needed to find Jesus. By JIM
HENDERSON and KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-GUNMAN (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Larry Gene Ashbrook, the
47-year-old gunman, grew up in the conservative Church of Christ
and may be a member of the Christian Identity movement. Police
removed journals and notes from the house he apparently shared with
his 85-year-old father. His father, a retiree from the Katy
Railroad, died in July. By EVAN MOORE
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-BUSH (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Saying there was a ``wave of
evil'' sweeping America, Gov. George W. Bush cut short a campaign
trip up north to rush to Fort Worth where a gunman killed seven
people and himself at a church. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CAROLINA (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Hurricane Floyd hits
land in North Carolina and continues up the coast dumping heavy
rain across several states. Three deaths reported in North
Carolina, where flooding is worst in memory. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FLOODS (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Millions of residents
begin to return home, many feeling lucky, but some, particularly in
North Carolina, finding high water and more high water. By TONY
FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Bryan, Texas) _ Prosecutors show the jury the
chain used to drag a 49-year-old black man to his death and could
rest their case Thursday. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-CLINTON (Washington) _ Invoking executive privilege,
President Clinton bars administration officials from talking about
or making public documents on his offer of clemency to 16 Puerto
Rican militants. The move incenses Republican lawmakers who have
demanded that the president explain his reasons for the offer. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-CLINTON (Washington) _ Federal officials expressed dismay
over the fatal church shooting in Texas and urged the nation to
take steps to protect children from gun violence. ``We know there
is nothing we can do to ensure this will never happen. But there is
a lot more we can do to ensure it will happen more rarely,''
President Clinton said. ``We have to act as if it were our own
children being targeted.'' By ANDREW BROMAN
</P>
<P>
   NASA-GORE (Washington) _ The satellite proposed by Vice
President Al Gore to provide continuous, live images of Earth from
space via the Internet is expected to cost up to $220 million, or
four times the cost forecast by NASA, according to the space
agency's inspector general. By STEVE LASH
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore addresses
Hispanic chamber of commerce, other Hispanic events during
``Ganamos con Gore'' week. By CRAGG HINES.
