<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-0917-COX     09-16 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-0917-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ANOTHER APARTMENT BOMB ROCKS RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    550&AMP;add
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW Fearful Russians, uneasy about sleeping in their own
beds, reeled Thursday after yet another bomb ripped apart an
apartment building _ this time an early morning blast in southern
Russia that killed at least 17 and wounded more than 150.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth devastating bombing of an apartment block in
two weeks, apparent terrorist attacks that have left nearly 300
dead.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, some politicians and observers wondered whether the
government of President Boris Yeltsin would be the next victim if
the state security agencies cannot end the wave of terror.
Speculation has grown with each bombing that Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin, or Yeltsin himself, could be forced to resign amid
the reign of panic that began on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion Thursday in the southern city of Volgodonsk ripped
the face off a nine-story, 144-unit apartment building. Authorities
believe the explosives may have been hidden in a truck or in
underground pipes.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll was expected to rise as 20 of the 72 injured
admitted to area hospitals were reported to be in grave condition.
</P>
<P>
   As in the previous blasts, no group claimed responsibility for
the explosion in Volgodonsk, a city of 250,000 about 500 miles
south of Moscow and near Russia's turbulent southern republics.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities suspect the bombings are the work of
terrorists aligned with Muslim insurgents from the breakaway
republic of Chechnya. Federal troops have been engaged in fierce
battles against the guerrillas for the past five weeks, seeking to
drive them from the southern Russian republic of Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen leaders have denied any link to the explosions in
Russia, though the car bombing of a Russian military residence
compound in Dagestan on Sept. 4, killing 64, was widely believed to
be directly linked to the ongoing fighting in the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Panic has swept Russia in the wake of the explosions,
particularly in Moscow where two apartment buildings were
destroyed. A bomb blast at an eight-story apartment building in
Moscow on Monday killed at least 119 people.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first explosion in Moscow last Thursday _ at an
apartment block on the southeastern outskirts of the city, claiming
93 lives _ police have been inundated with calls from nervous
residents. Between Monday and Thursday morning, Moscow police had
received 900 calls from people reporting suspicious activity they
believed to be the setting of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bombing set off a round of high-level government
meetings as Yeltsin and his government struggle to respond to the
unprecedented campaign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the strength and resources to wipe out terrorism,''
Yeltsin said, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a traditional Yeltsin ally, Yegor Stroyev, the
chairman of Russia's upper house of parliament, has urged Yeltsin
to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the series of bombings and an unfolding scandal linking the
Kremlin to allegations of money laundering and corruption, rumors
have swirled throughout Moscow that Yeltsin may leave office before
the scheduled end of his term next summer. By leaving early and
calling early presidential elections for December, Yeltsin would
attempt to improve the chances for Putin, his chosen successor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stroyev is scheduled today to chair an extraordinary session of
the Federation Council to discuss the security crisis in Russia. He
told reporters on Thursday that some of his comments in the article
may have been misunderstood, but he stopped short of a direct
denial.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary rumors say Yeltsin could use the security crisis to
declare a state of emergency and indefinitely prolong his term in
office.
</P>
<P>
   And in a measure of the deep distrust Russians have for their
government, the country's newspapers have been full of stories
suggesting that Russian political intrigue could be behind the
bombings as a means of tipping the political balance ahead of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   So prevalent were rumors of possible Kremlin links to the
explosions, that a spokesman for the FSB, the federal security
service, gave a radio interview Thursday to deny them.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Zdanovich, the FSB spokesman, said it was ``absurd''
that some politicians and media reports have suggested that the
country's security forces and the Kremlin ``were involved in these
acts of terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, a likely presidential candidate, said
the federal government had been late in reacting to the security
threat. He blamed the Chechens for the attacks and called for
retaliation against ``a bandit community engaged in terrorism,
slave trade and robbery.''
</P>
<P>
   The government is considering isolating Chechnya by placing a
military corridor around it. However, it is far from certain
whether Russia's poorly financed army could accomplish such a
mission.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Russia is placing its security forces on its own
streets to guard against further bombings.
</P>
<P>
   About 80,000 regular police and Interior Ministry troops have
been mobilized in Moscow alone to search apartments and vehicles
and to patrol streets. Since Monday, all 30,000 residential
buildings in the city of 10 million had been inspected at least
once, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for the FSB, authorities since Monday
have prevented explosions at six different apartment buildings in
Moscow where they have discovered caches of explosives and timing
devices. In one building alone, police confiscated 3.5 tons of
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
