<SLUG> BC-PET-DAYCARE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME-ALONE PETS GET A LIFE AT DOGGY DAY-CARE CENTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candee Brodsky was a guilt-ridden parent. She and her spouse
worked full time in suburban Chicago, leaving their children home
alone every day, locked in the kitchen and sleeping in laundry
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, the Brodsky kids were lonely and unsociable _
until Mom signed them up for day care. Now, twice a week, Snickers
and Sassi Brodsky, two Jack Russell terriers, spend the day at
Playful Paws, one of a burgeoning number of dog day-care facilities
opening nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs are happier, and Brodsky is thrilled. ``It's worth
every penny,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike kennels that keep dogs in cages, doggy day care allows
constant interaction among canine clients. The businesses cater to
dog owners who, like Brodsky, are gone during the day and want a
better life for their secluded pups. Clients report marked
improvement in their dogs' social skills and a marked decline in
pet-owner guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``After about a month of going there, he was a totally different
dog,'' says Sara Moeller, whose black Labrador retriever, Jake,
attends day care once a week in Dallas. Jake, she reports, went
from hyper and distrustful to mellow and gentlemanly in four
visits.
</P>
<P>
   At Playful Paws in Prospect Heights, Ill., humans drop their
charges off in the mornings and pick them up in the evenings. The
5,000-square-foot ``activity center'' includes a living room with
love seat, television, rugs, dog beds and toys. Pups chase balls in
the outdoor playpen and are treated to massages and agility
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hottest trend in animal care across the country,''
says owner Tracy Arnold, a former CPA who quit her job a year ago
to open Playful Paws in August.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold and other dog day-care entrepreneurs chalk up demand for
their services to several things. An increase in dual-income
families means no one at home during the weekday, and a healthy
economy is leaving people with more discretionary income.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are waiting longer to have kids, and they
still want to have that place where they can pour out their
affection,'' adds Kimberly Garsed, owner of Urban Dog Playcare in
Los Angeles. ``These people think their dogs are their children.''
</P>
<P>
   A hot trend on the coasts for a couple of years, doggy day care
is becoming ubiquitous. This year, the American Boarding Kennel
Association will offer two seminars on starting a doggy day-care
business at its annual meeting in October. And dozens of facilities
in states such as Colorado, Ohio, Florida, Nevada, California and
Massachusetts advertise their services on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Dee's Doggie Den claims to be the first and only doggy day care
shop in the Dallas city limits. Dee Fort opened her
3,000-square-foot facility in November 1998 at the corner of
Mockingbird and Skillman and takes about eight to 12 day-care dogs
a day. She warns off-the-cuff entrepreneurs against diving into the
business unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hardest work you have ever done in your life,'' she
says. The dogs ``move at a rate of four paws to our two feet. But
the other side of it is that it is so rewarding to see dogs playing
and having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Day-care clients say the interaction makes their dogs more
confident and trusting around unfamiliar people and other pups. It
reduces separation anxiety and the sometimes destructive behavior
of dogs left alone all day. Plus, active dogs burn calories _ and
energy.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jake started going to day care, Moeller would return from
work to a pet ready to ``go, go, go,'' she says. Now, ``I'm
exhausted from work, he's exhausted from playing all day, and we
come home and have a very nice evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Most doggy day-care businesses require pets to have up-to-date
immunizations (beware of those that don't, say owners), and most
ask pet and owner to submit to an interview. Aggressive dogs are
usually turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Costs range from $8 (for a small dog at Dee's in Dallas) to $30
a day at Urban Dog in Los Angeles. Arnold charges $26 for a day at
Playful Paws, outside Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky can afford two days a week for Snickers and Sassi but
would like to make it three. She's an enthusiastic proponent of day
care for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dog lovers understand it,'' Brodsky says. ``And the people who
are not dog lovers look at me like I have three heads.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
