<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPLENDOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPLENDOR': A MENAGE A TROIS FOR THE GOOD LOOKS AND THE LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregg Araki's film ``Splendor'' is almost a textbook example of
what can go wrong when an artistic bad boy decides to be good. Or
rather half-good, since the romantic triangle ``Splendor'' explores
_ a pretty woman living happily with two pretty men and sharing her
bed with them _ is in its way transgressive.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Splendor'' Araki, best known for his shiny Pop Art
exercises in post-teen-age nihilism, has created a kind of '30s
screwball comedy for the millennium. The movie is certainly lovely
to look at, with its dreamy close-ups of attractive people
meticulously posed for a camera that worships their youth and
beauty with a naked adoration.
</P>
<P>
   But in examining the menage a trois of Veronica (Kathleen
Robertson) and her two lovers, Abel (Johnathon Schaech) and Zed
(Matt Keeslar), ``Splendor,'' which opens Friday in New York , is
largely devoid of genuine human feeling. Take jealousy. Yes,
there's a smidgen or two but nothing that can't be comfortably
taken in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Competitiveness? In dutifully uniting to serve their common
mistress, an aspiring film actress, Abel and Zed appear to have
quelled any anxieties about which one she might prefer or who might
be better in the sack.
</P>
<P>
   Passion? None is apparent. When the three are shown in bed
together, Abel and Zed resemble playful puppies gently nuzzling
Veronica from either side, while she effuses all the erotic heat of
a matron reading magazines while under a hair dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica, who narrates the story in a blase singsong, meets her
two honeys at the same nightclub on the same evening. She instantly
recognizes Abel, a sometime rock critic who is dressed as Prince
Valiant for the occasion, as her witty, intellectual soul mate,
although we are never treated to any of his witty, intellectual or
soulful observations. Zed, the drummer for an aspiring rock band,
she tells us, is a magnetic sexual animal with perfect abdominals
who seduces Veronica on the floor backstage that very night.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few months, Veronica juggles the two suitors who
grudgingly tolerate each other's existence until the night they
accidentally meet at an outdoor rock event and nearly come to
blows. Veronica calls an emergency meeting at which she cajoles her
rivals into kissing each other.
</P>
<P>
   While Abel shyly pecks Zed on the cheek, Zed plants a light,
lingering, kiss on Abel's lips that Abel seems to enjoy. But once
the three begin sharing the same house and the same king-size bed,
the movie steers away from pursuing any homosexual hanky-panky.
</P>
<P>
   Even after trouble arrives in the form of Ernest (Eric Mabius),
a wealthy and charming young television director who falls in love
with Veronica at first meeting and whisks her off to Hawaii for a
quickie vacation, Abel and Zed wouldn't dream of turning to each
other for sexual solace. They'd rather sit around at night getting
drunk and moaning over the absence of their shared sweetie.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a formulaic path that brings a predicable major
complication and a last-minute race against time borrowed from
``The Graduate,'' ``Splendor'' reaches a simpering, feel-good
ending. Think of it as ``Jules and Jim'' reimagined as an Archie
comic book with the sexual roles reversed, and photographed by
Bruce Weber for a photo spread in Seventeen magazine.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Splendor' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It has sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   `SPLENDOR'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by Gregg Araki; director of
photography, Jim Fealy; music by Daniel Licht; production designer,
Patti Podesta; produced by Damian Jones, Graham Broadbent and
Araki; released by the Samuel Goldwyn Co. Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kathleen Robertson (Veronica), Johnathon Schaech (Abel),
Matt Keeslar (Zed), Kelly Macdonald (Mike), Eric Mabius (Ernest),
Dan Gatto (Mutt) and Linda Kim (Alison). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STRINGS-FILM-REVIEW-N     09-16 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRINGS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPEAKING IN STRINGS': FIERY VIOLINIST LIVING AN OPERATIC LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long after the phenomenal Italian-born violinist Nadja
Salerno-Sonnenberg moved to the United States at the age of 8, she
attended a class whose students were asked to play show and tell by
talking about their favorite thing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But when this brilliant young musician presented a recording of
the Brahms violin concerto to the class, she was met with derisive
laughter. She was so upset, she recalls in Paola di Florio's
sympathetic documentary portrait, ``Speaking in Strings,'' that she
angrily cursed her classmates and ran from the room in tears.
</P>
<P>
   This humiliating childhood experience speaks volumes about the
problems of being a classical musician in a pop universe. But Ms.
Salerno-Sonnenberg's aggressive response to her peers' scorn was
also an indication of the bluntly feisty personality behind her
extravagantly romantic style.
</P>
<P>
   When performing a piece like the Tchaikovsky Violin Concerto,
Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg becomes carried away and lays herself bare.
And her fiery emotionality, much of which derives from her
childhood passion for opera, has not been greeted with unanimous
critical approval.
</P>
<P>
   While the film remembers Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg's teen-age
celebrity _ she once joked with Johnny Carson and had her own
segment on ``60 Minutes'' _ it devotes the bulk of its energy to
her problems as an adult. The personal price of being a classical
superstar, the film suggests, is high, especially for a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it Janis Joplin who once described the agony of ending up
alone in a motel room at the end of the night after having
ecstatically bonded with an audience? Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg seems
to have suffered similar frustrations after pouring out her heart
and soul on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene she is shown being reassured by a psychic that yes,
she will one day have a child. Earlier in the film she begins to
talk about a recently broken relationship but stops herself when
she begins to weep.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the movie draws a curtain over her intimate personal
life. We meet no lovers, past or present, only admiring, loyally
protective friends, associates and family members.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg's serious troubles began five years ago
when she cut off the tip of her left little finger while slicing
onions. The accident would have ended the career of a less
determined performer. Until she regained the use of that finger,
she risked permanently injuring her hand by refingering her
repertory and continuing her concert schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted and depressed, she suffered what she calls an
``existential crisis'' and attempted suicide. But luck was on her
side. When she pulled the trigger, the gun she held to her head
clicked without firing. After that, she recalls, she had to learn
to embrace life ``a minute at a time.'' She has since discovered
that happiness is something that ``takes guts.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the personal turmoil it presents, the woman who emerges
from ``Speaking in Strings,'' which opens Friday in New York, is a
likable down-to-earth person who seems to know herself very well.
If it takes courage to be happy, the movie suggests, it may take
even more courage to live out a larger-than-life destiny whose
precipitous ups and downs are a measure of the talent being served.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SPEAKING IN STRINGS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Paola di Florio; director of photography, Peter
Rader; edited by Ellen Goldwater; original score by Karen Childs;
produced by Ms. di Florio and Lilibet Foster; released by Seventh
Art Releasing. Running time: 73 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROMANCE-FILM-REVIEW-N     09-16 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROMANCE': HER LIBIDO AS THE NAVIGATOR, ONE WOMAN'S ADVENTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her solemn, sexually graphic ``Romance,'' Catherine Breillat
explores the nature of a woman's need for male attention and erotic
love. Though many of her film's insights might be obtained from
back copies of Cosmopolitan plus a smattering of the Marquis de
Sade, watching it is a memorable experience for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Not least of these is its blunt hard-core frankness. It's
doubtful that the film's intellectual aspects would command the
same attention if the camera did not make the actors' genitals as
familiar as their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The carnal and cerebral erotica in ``Romance'' have already
achieved the considerable feat of shocking France. No doubt the
film also intrigued French audiences with its mix of stony
posturing and bedroom candor, though its air of detachment
literally leaves a lot to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Breillat is capable of emphasizing the archetypal aspects of
her heroine's affair with, say, a character played by an Italian
porn star (Rocco Siffredi), even as she films the kind of encounter
that ordinarily keeps the archetypes at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Her film hovers between passion and philosophical argument
without fully achieving its ambition to fuse the two.
</P>
<P>
   Marie (Caroline Ducey), a schoolteacher, is engaged in a
dead-end relationship with a male model named Paul (Sagamore
Stevenin). Paul is so bored with Marie that he's bored when she
fellates him. Wearing white clothes against the white sheets of
their white bedroom, they discuss this situation in ways that send
Marie reeling into sexual adventures with new men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance'' is schematic enough to change its palette to red as
its heroine heats up.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Ducey's performance can be raw enough to reveal
glimpses of Marie's desperation, ``Romance'' does invite strong
empathy with her situation. Rebounding from Paul into a bar, she
flashes the kind of newly reckless smile that anyone would
understand.
</P>
<P>
   On the dance floor, she picks up Paolo ( Siffredi) for a talky
fling. Being with Paolo leads her to conclude (``it's
metaphysical'') that there is a relationship between the size of
her lover's penis and her state of mind. A male director would take
a barrage of flak for coming to comparable conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Later, and more meaningfully for Marie, she becomes involved
with Robert (Francois Berleand), a school principal with an
encyclopedic interest in sexual bondage. Through watching these
two, the viewer can discover, among other things, that it is slow,
demanding work to tie up someone in esthetically satisfying ways.
</P>
<P>
   As they establish the limits of their sadomasochistic bond,
Robert does most of the talking (``It's strange, obscenity doesn't
bother women'') while Marie experiences unexpectedly profound
emotions. Subsequent encounters with a brutish stranger and a group
of gynecologists heighten the film's efforts to strip its boyishly
built heroine of all her illusions and most of her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The seriousness of Ms. Breillat (``36 Fillette'') is never in
question, at least as far as the taint of exploitation is
concerned. The clinical nudity around which her film revolves is
indeed essential to its central idea, that of a woman who frees
herself from masculine power and cruelty by venturing into the
unknown and going as far as her libido will take her.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that much of this journey covers fundamentally
familiar ground, except at those rare moments when the film comes
up with startling visual metaphors for the mind-body dilemma. When
Marie imagines herself divided at the waist, with a kind male
companion for her upper body and her lower engaged in anonymous raw
sex with strangers, ``Romance'' is as eloquent as it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Romance' is being released unrated. But an NC-17 rating would
have been otherwise inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   `ROMANCE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Catherine Breillat; in French, with
English subtitles; director of photography, Yorgos Arvanitis;
edited by Agnes Guillemot; music by D.J. Valentin; production
designer, Frederique Belvaux; produced by Jean-Francois LePetit;
released by Trimark Pictures. Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Caroline Ducey (Marie), Sagamore Stevenin (Paul), Francois
Berleand (Robert) and Rocco Siffredi (Paolo).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
