<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TAX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TAXMAN': BEYOND THE CALL OF DUTY, AN ODD COUPLE OF CIVIL
SERVANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unlikely pair of sleuths, aided and abetted by the
atmospheric Russian community of Brighton Beach, Brooklyn,
transform the familiar materials of ``Taxman'' into a offbeat
little charmer of a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-born Avi Nesher wrote the film's screenplay with
Roger Berger, whose background is in tax investigation. As directed
by Nesher, ``Taxman'' makes heroes of its outcast investigators,
speaks up for all low-level workers who retain a sense of justice
and honor in a greedy, immoral and indifferent world, and looks
where it can in the midst of gunplay and threats to find pockets of
decency, kindness, good humor and familial warmth.
</P>
<P>
   The sleuths are Al Benjamin (Joe Pantoliano), an impulsive,
obsessive New York State tax investigator, and Joseph Romero (Wade
Dominguez), a bright young Russian-speaking police officer. What
brings them together is a Russian Mafia mass murder that leaves six
people dead in the Brighton Beach office of a small gasoline
company.
</P>
<P>
   Although Benjamin and Romero are dedicated to their jobs, they
are huge annoyances to their superiors. Benjamin's boss considers
his doggedness a pain in the nether regions, and Romero's only
value to his superiors seems to be his language skill and his
ability to fetch coffee. Although intelligent and eager, he is by
his own admission a bad shot and can't drive well.
</P>
<P>
   But Benjamin, who has spent months before the murders pursuing
the idea that someone in the Brighton Beach Russian community has
been defrauding the authorities of millions of dollars in gasoline
taxes, reluctantly agrees to accept Romero's help after they meet
at the death scene.
</P>
<P>
   In their relentless, often discouraging pursuit, they find their
way up the ladder of corporate concealment and past armies of
Russian Mafia thugs and hit men to the so-called cabbage: the
Russian Big who is in league with a major American oil company.
</P>
<P>
   On the way Benjamin and Romero meet everyone from Andre Rubakov
(Michal Chiklis), a kindly Russian-born gas-station owner, and his
beautiful daughter, Nadia (Elizabeth Berkley), to an assistant
United States attorney, Peyton Cody (Robert Townsend), who very
reluctantly agrees to take on the case.
</P>
<P>
   When not staking out the streets of Brighton Beach by day and
gas stations by night, despairing over the progress of their
investigation, grieving over the carnage inflicted by suicidal
Chechnyan hit men or chasing them through the desolate off-season
landscape of Coney Island, Benjamin and Romero dance at a
Russian-Jewish wedding, share delicacies from Zabar's and reveal
themselves to each other and to the audience as endearing if
slightly wacky company.
</P>
<P>
   For civil servants like these, it's a delight to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Taxman' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has strong language and violence.
</P>
<P>
   `THE TAXMAN'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Avi Nesher; written by Nesher and Roger Berger;
director of photography, Jim Denault; edited by Alex Hall; music by
Roger Neill; production designer, Michael Krantz; produced by
Nesher and Kathy Jordan; released by Phaedra Cinema. Running time:
104 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Joe Pantoliano (Al Benjamin), Wade Dominguez (Joseph
Romero), Elizabeth Berkley (Nadia Rubakov), Michael Chiklis (Andre
Rubakov) and Robert Townsend (Peyton Cody).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
