<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LUCIE-FILM-FILM-NYT &LR;      09-16 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCIE-FILM-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCIE AUBRAC': IN WAR A BOND BECOMES AN EROTIC EPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who can forget that moment in ``Casablanca'' when Ingrid
Bergman, carried away by passion, her eyes shining, surrenders her
judgment to Humphrey Bogart and tells him that from now on he has
to do the thinking for both of them?
</P>
<P>
   Echoes of that moment resonate through Claude Berri's stirringly
romantic film ``Lucie Aubrac,'' except that the roles are reversed.
This time it is the woman (the film's title character, played with
a riveting authority by Carole Bouquet) who does the crucial
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunningly audacious scheme, she comes up with a plan to
rescue her husband, Raymond (Daniel Auteuil), a leader of the
French Resistance, who has been found guilty of war crimes by the
Nazis and faces execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucie Aubrac,'' like ``Casablanca,'' is set during the height
of World War II. The story it tells, based on the title character's
novel ``Ils Partiront Dans l'Ivresse'' is essentially true. What
raises the movie above the level of a well-made World War II
thriller is its convincing, uncorny portrait of a marriage whose
heightened passions reflect the sort of nobility that is a staple
of World War II films from ``Casablanca'' through ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The early scenes of Lucie and Raymond together show a union in
which the couple's mutual respect, courage and moral fiber feeds
their intense erotic bond. When they make love, you have the sense
that Lucie and Raymond are more than lovers. Each one is a hero in
the other's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   For them lovemaking is a sacred rite of mutual worship. And true
to the spirit of World War II films, they emerge as unblemished
paragons of virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The twist is that this relationship is not your standard
``strong man sweeps melting beauty into his arms'' movie coupling.
Lucie, the aggressor, stalks through the film like a lithe, elegant
tiger, effusing a kind of moral hauteur along with a lethal
intensity of purpose. We sense the same qualities when she is
making love to her somewhat older husband, and he regards her with
the awed tenderness of a child.
</P>
<P>
   He is the one whose eyes shine, who blissfully surrenders. Ms.
Bouquet's and Auteuil's embodiment of this relationship feels so
natural that when Lucie conceives her extremely perilous plan to
save his life, you have no doubt that if anyone can pull off the
impossible, she can.
</P>
<P>
   Around this vision of an extraordinary marriage, Berri has
constructed a gripping period thriller that clicks along without
resorting to hyped-up shock effects or gimmicky suspense. It begins
with a smoothly executed scene of Raymond and his fellow Resistance
members scurrying on the railroad tracks near Lyons to plant a
device that will blow up a German supply train.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently we meet Raymond and the other underground freedom
fighters and learn something of the movement's elaborate
self-protective rituals and protocol. Eventually, however, Raymond
and his friends are betrayed, arrested and interrogated in scenes
that show Nazi brutality without rubbing our faces in torture.
</P>
<P>
   When all appears to be lost, Lucie concocts a daring rescue plan
that requires her to adopt a false identity and pose as a desperate
young woman pregnant with Raymond's child. Through a chain of
connections that involves bribery, she meets with a Nazi official
and begs that the condemned Raymond be allowed to marry her before
his execution so that her child can have a name.
</P>
<P>
   That is just the beginning of a scheme to ambush a military
truck carrying Raymond and take him to safety. Although it is the
sort of operation that has been detailed in innumerable caper
films, it is directed here with a taut efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   One reason ``Lucie Aubrac'' succeeds is that it doesn't oversell
its characters' bravery. These are people who feel that they have
no choice but to do what they must, and you root for them every
step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Lucie Aubrac' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It contains sexual situations and torture
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   `LUCIE AUBRAC'
</P>
<P>
   Produced, written and directed by Claude Berri; in French, with
English subtitles, based on the novel ``Ils Partiront Dans
l'Ivresse'' by Lucie Aubrac and on Konrad Bieber's English
translation, ``Outwitting the Gestapo''; director of photography,
Vincenzo Marano; edited by Herve de Luze; music by Philippe Sarde;
production designer, Olivier Radot; released by October Films.
Running time: 116 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Carole Bouquet (Lucie), Daniel Auteuil (Raymond), Patrice
Chereau (Max), Jean-Roger Milo (Maurice) and Eric Boucher (Serge).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BREAKFAST-FILM-REVIEW     09-16 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAKFAST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS': THE AFFLUENT SOCIETY? WELCOME TO THE FUN
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What could be a more fitting theme for Alan Rudolph's
phantasmagoric screen adaptation of Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s novel
``Breakfast of Champions'' than that flowery 1950s ballad,
``Stranger in Paradise''? The song, which runs through the movie
like an ironic leitmotiv, distills an Eisenhower-era mood of
sanctimonious freeze-dried optimism tinged with paranoia that the
movie conjures with a demonic fervor.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days, the movie reminds us, when it was almost a
heresy to disparage the booming affluence of a society that
television, then in its infancy, promoted as an unfolding paradise
on earth.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent decades, of course, the pendulum swung so far in
the other direction that when Vonnegut's satire was published in
1973, it was almost a heresy (italics)not(end italics) to disparage
a corrupt, ``plastic'' culture poisoned with a thousand toxins,
from Watergate to Muzak.
</P>
<P>
   Today the wild exuberance with which that novel ridiculed the
grossness and absurdity of American greed and Babbitry seems
somehow naive. It is with a bitter self-awareness that we accept
the price of our present comfort as a willed, guilty blindness to
the problems of the rest of the world and to serious inequities
within our own society.
</P>
<P>
   In such a cynical climate, the vigor of Vonnegut's satire can
seem overheated and obvious. That's why Rudolph's film, made in a
spirit of gleeful early-'70s irreverence, also seems naive.
</P>
<P>
   Visually evoking a composite modernity that embraces half a
century of tackiness, the movie looks and feels like a frantic,
live-action psychedelic cartoon. Although its many targets,
including small-town conformity and greed, sexual prudery and
mass-cultural boorishness seem easy and familiar, the movie flails
at them with a wild, free-for-all energy. In its tone, the movie
might be described as a John Waters film divested of camp.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if you accept ``Breakfast of Champions'' as a work
unambiguously committed to spray-painting the screen with the
author's satiric vision of modern America as an absurdist madhouse,
it still churns up quite a head of froth.
</P>
<P>
   Watching it is a little like taking a ride through a giant fun
house. As you lurch furiously around the corners, you are
continually assaulted by visual and literary jokes that pop out you
like faces wearing maniacal grins, then disappear into the
blackness a moment later.
</P>
<P>
   A man delivers a sales pitch through a face on a thousand-dollar
bill. As one character walks through a parking lot, the ground
seems to give way like rubber under his feet. Another character
eases himself through a mirror to become a reflection of himself
staring back from an alternate universe.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing wrong with such clever tricks is that their
accumulation tends to smother the narrative and diminish the larger
metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakfast of Champions'' is set in mythical Midland City, a
suburb of nightmarish sterility through which runs an unnaturally
blue river choked with chemical wastes. It is a place whose
gleaming factories belch smoke and where the soil in a recently
constructed housing project has been deemed contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Midland City's leading citizen and local hero is Dwayne Hoover
(Bruce Willis) a buttoned-down, toupeed car salesman who in a
series of garish television commercials, embodies American success
as a grotesque exercise in robotic self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the film, Dwayne who has alienated his
neurotic wife, Celia (Barbara Hershey) and his son, Bunny (Lukas
Haas), an aspiring lounge singer with a taste for glittery costumes
who slowly goes insane (or sane, depending on how you look at it).
Leading him toward his doom (or his salvation) is Kilgore Trout
(Albert Finney), an obscure, crusty old science-fiction writer who
travels to Midland City to be the guest of honor at the town's
first arts festival.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the movie takes place at Dwayne's surreal car
dealership, which is crammed with hideous tchotchkes and whose
piped-in soundtrack of Martin Denny exotica is attuned to its
win-a-free-trip-to-Hawaii contests. In this chirping, soulless
garden of kitsch, Dwayne's toadying employees do things like put on
Dwayne Hoover masks to collectively greet their boss.
</P>
<P>
   We meet his troubled right-hand man, Harry Le Sabre (Nick
Nolte), a closet transvestite who is on the verge of exploding from
withholding his secret. Other satirical characters include Dwayne's
smile-button of a secretary (and sometime girlfriend), Francine
(Glenne Headly), and Wayne Hoobler (Omar Epps), a desperately eager
car salesman who regards Dwayne as a capitalist god.
</P>
<P>
   The sterling cast, led by Willis, who deftly breaks his typical
mode to play Dwayne, pumps a lot of adrenaline (sometimes too much,
as in Nolte's case) into their caricatures, with Finney especially
fine. In the end, you have to admire Rudolph for making a film this
defiantly uncommercial.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, ``Breakfast of Champions'' is an incoherent mess.
But it never compromises its zany vision of the country as a
demented junkyard wonderland in which we are all strangers groping
for a hand to guide us through the looking glass into an unsullied
tropical paradise of eternal bliss.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Breakfast of Champions' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has some strong language
and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   `BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alan Rudolph; written by Rudolph, based on the novel
by Kurt Vonnegut Jr.; director of photography, Elliot Davis; edited
by Suzy Elmiger; music by Mark Isham, with songs performed by
Martin Denny; production designer, Nina Ruscio; produced by David
Blocker and David Willis; released by Hollywood Pictures. Running
time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Bruce Willis (Dwayne Hoover), Albert Finney (Kilgore
Trout), Nick Nolte (Harry Le Sabre), Barbara Hershey (Celia
Hoover), Glenne Headly (Francine Pefko), Lukas Haas (Bunny Hoover),
Omar Epps (Wayne Hoobler), Buck Henry (Fred T. Barry) and Vicki
Lewis (Grace Le Sabre).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
