<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      09-16 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUDGING AMY': ANOTHER MOM, ANOTHER DAUGHTER, ANOTHER CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hartford, Conn., is within shouting distance of Providence,
R.I., in more ways than it seems. The Connecticut city is the
setting for CBS's new ``Judging Amy,'' which, like last year's NBC
hit ``Providence,'' sends a successful professional woman into
serious emotional regression as she moves back to her leafy New
England hometown to live with her family and start her life over.
The welcome difference is that the premiere of ``Judging Amy'' is
like ``Providence'' without the treacle.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Brenneman plays Amy Gray, a newly divorced mother and lawyer
who moves in with her widowed mom and becomes a family court judge.
So far she sounds suspiciously like Melina Kanakaredes' Syd, a
plastic surgeon who moves in with her widowed dad and works in a
Providence clinic. But where Syd is Mother Teresa in disguise (not
a concept that allows for many surprises from week to week), Ms.
Brenneman gives Amy an engaging and intelligent mix of strong will,
confusion and nerves. Even more winning, in ``Judging Amy'' the
family dynamics are realistically fraught.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win the judgeship in a raffle,'' Amy tells her
argumentative, interfering mother, Maxine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, not far from it,'' says Mom, superbly played by Tyne
Daly with mother-knows-best impatience. Because she had been a
social worker for decades, Maxine thinks she knows and has seen it
all. She is also well-connected enough to get a police car to
follow her daughter when she is late and speeding to court.
</P>
<P>
   Amy also has an appealing relationship with one of her brothers,
Vincent (Dan Futterman, in a likably natural performance), a
would-be writer working as a dog-groomer. Together they can have
honest, if unproductive, talks about how to handle Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brenneman, who is also an executive producer of the show,
found the idea in the life of her own mother, a juvenile court
judge. ``Judging Amy'' may be the television equivalent of a chick
flick, but the opening episode is never as cloying as its special
time slot suggests: Sunday at 8, usually the home of ``Touched by
an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   When Amy gives her young daughter, Lauren, a speech about how
the best job she'll ever have is being a mom, she ends by asking:
``How was that? Not too sappy?''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's OK,'' the little girl says. ``You're nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   That scene shrewdly undercuts the sentimentality. But it also
drops a huge hint that Lauren is too observant to be a convincing
child. And, in fact, the series' second episode (which moves to its
regular time slot, Tuesday nights at 10) is disappointing. With Amy
harried by a long day in court yet determined to make a difference
to the families she is assigned to help, the episode has a
familiar, perfunctory tone. In that episode, ``Judging Amy'' seems
be turning into ``Providence'' before our eyes, which would be the
most serious regression of all.
</P>
<P>
   If you watch enough crime movies, can you get away with murder?
In ``A Slight Case of Murder'' (8 p.m. ET Sunday on TNT), a
pleasing, tongue-in-cheek suspense story, William H. Macy plays
Terry Thorpe, a film critic on cable television, the kind of man
who is seen peering down his nose over half-glasses in ads on the
sides of buses. Terry gets his chance to do more than critique
murder plots when he accidentally causes his girlfriend's death.
</P>
<P>
   As he explains in one of many wry asides to the camera, she
slipped on a ice cube during an argument and hit her head on the
coffee table. Sure. But seconds later we see that it happened just
that way. So why shouldn't life be like a movie?
</P>
<P>
   Terry tries to hide all evidence of his involvement in the death
because he has been two-timing his primary girlfriend. In a role
that echoes his delicious ``Fargo'' character, Macy is great fun to
watch as a guilty man trying to look innocent. (He was also the
film's co-writer, along with the its director, Steven Schacter;
they based the script on Donald E. Westlake's novel ``A
Travesty.'')
</P>
<P>
   The terrific cast also includes Felicity Huffman as the
girlfriend who lives, James Cromwell as a blackmailing private
investigator and Adam Arkin as a dense police detective. He invites
Terry home for dinner, cooked by a wife who seems to have walked
out of a 1950s Disney film. Nothing, of course, is what it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the many movie references, including a glimpse of
``Gaslight'' and Terry's prominently displayed poster for ``In Cold
Blood,'' ``A Slight Case of Murder'' does not come with a
self-reflexive post-modern spin. The movies are merely a congenial
backdrop for this modest, amusing film.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JUDGING AMY'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Hall, Joseph Stern, Connie Tavel and Amy Brenneman,
executive producers; produced by Barbara Hall Productions Inc., in
association with CBS Productions and 20th Century Fox Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Amy Brenneman (Amy Gray), Tyne Daly (Maxine Gray), Dan
Futterman (Vincent Gray).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
