<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4727 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-VIRGIN-0917-CO     09-16 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VIRGIN-0917-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN POLITICS: DON'T TOUCH THE VIRGIN OF GUADALUPE
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (r) religion categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY The mother of Mexico is becoming the mother of all
election squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's ruling party filed an official elections commission
complaint this week charging that Vicente Fox, a top presidential
rival, unlawfully exploited the image of Mexico's beloved Virgin of
Guadalupe for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do that stuff with the Virgin,'' said political
analyst Raymundo Riva Palacio, commenting on the spat over the
Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against Fox _ whom polls show is highly popular _
threatens to gnaw at him just as he is kicking off his official
campaign to oust Mexico's ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party,
or PRI, from the presidency after 70 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the PRI requested that Mexico's Federal Elections
Institute investigate whether Fox should be sanctioned or fined for
waving a banner of the Virgin of Guadalupe at a Sept. 10 political
rally.
</P>
<P>
   The battle began when Fox was holding a campaign rally that day
in Leon, in the state of Guanajuato, which he governed until
recently stepping down to pursue the presidency. Delegates
representing Mexico's conservative National Action Party, or PAN,
recently named Fox their nominee for Mexico's presidential election
on July 2, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally of some 5,000 people in Leon, Fox's children gave
him a banner as a gift. When he unfurled it publicly, it proved to
be an image of Mexico's Virgin of Guadalupe, topped with a
crucifix. Some reports say that Fox waved the banner and implied he
would carry on a battle for democracy begun in 1810 by the Mexican
priest Miguel Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   In Fox's home state of Guanajuato, Hidalgo exhorted the masses
to rise up and fight for independence against the Spanish, shouting
``Long live the Virgin of Guadalupe.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's action was a lightning rod for instant criticism in a
country that's at once deeply Catholic and deeply committed to
keeping religion out of most politics.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mexico's most beloved presidents, Benito Juarez, fought
in the 19th century to curb the power of the Catholic church, which
was seen as an ally of the Mexican elite. After the Mexican
revolution, Mexicans fought another civil war over the suppression
of priests and Catholic practices.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Mexican government has tried to strike a
balance, allowing religious freedom but forbidding religious
organizations from getting involved in politics and prohibiting
politicians from using religious symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The Virgin of Guadalupe is a potent symbol that goes beyond
religious faith. Legend has it she appeared to a Mexican Indian in
1531, instructing him to build a shrine in her honor. The Virgin
was dark-skinned and spoke to the Indian in his language _ details
that have fueled the Virgin's reputation as ``the mother of all
Mexicans'' and a symbol that cannot be claimed by any one political
group.
</P>
<P>
   Following Fox's use of the Virgin banner at a rally, Mexico's
interior secretary said Fox had shown ``an insolent lack of
respect,'' but he said he considered ``the case closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church weighed in next, not condemning Fox but
gently chastising him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know to what end he's using the Virgin of Guadalupe,''
said Mexican Cardinal Norberto Rivera Carrera. ``I think we all
carry the Virgin of Guadalupe with us. He can do that too, but the
Virgin of Guadalupe belongs to all Mexicans and should not be used
for partisan purposes. She is the only thing that unites all
Mexicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the PAN have a reputation for being closer to
Catholic doctrine than other parties in Mexico. But Fox _ who is
running an anti-corruption, anti-PRI campaign _ has never been
viewed as promoting the church or Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was forced to issue an apology, explaining that the
banner was gift from his children, who simply wanted to ``invoke
the protection of the Virgin . . . during my campaign for the
presidency of the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not my intention to use this image as an instrument in
my campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
