<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OFTEN-THEATER-REVIEW-     09-16 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFTEN-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DO YOU COME HERE OFTEN?': BATHROOM HUMOR THAT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don't be alarmed by that toilet at the center of the
stage. True, the fact that it is dramatically spotlighted in blue
in the opening seconds of ``Do You Come Here Often?,'' the
ecstatically inane two-man show at Performance Space 122, would
seem to portend an evening of the most adolescent sort of blue
humor. And anyone who has sat through this summer's comic movie
blockbusters has certainly had enough toilet jokes for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Yet aside from a mild reference to the effects of eating soap on
the digestive system, there is nothing here at all reminiscent of
the gross-out fare of ``South Park'' and ``American Pie.'' The
toilet in ``Do You Come Here Often?,'' performed by two inspired
British comedians, Sean Foley and Hamish McColl, is used for more
exotic purposes. They involve, among other things, an all-important
door key, some bright yellow toy ducks and a miraculous garden of
artificial flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jozef Houben, ``Often'' provides winning
confirmation that when it comes to doing pure silliness, nobody
beats the British. Bringing to mind antecedents ranging from early
music hall teams to the giddy surrealism of Monty Python, this tale
of two men trapped together in a bathroom (with pastel fixtures, no
less) piles absurdities so high that you can't imagine the whole
thing won't topple into a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   But Foley and McColl, who work under the name the Right Size and
won a Laurence Olivier Award for this production, know perfectly
well that comic chaos requires the utmost precision. There's an air
of free-associating delirium in ``Often,'' a sense of jokes and
gags forever breeding mutant progeny, but you never feel that the
slightly seedy-looking clowns on stage aren't in total control. And
while they definitely have an original comic voice, their style is
also as classic as commedia dell'arte.
</P>
<P>
   The show's central premise is both simple and outlandish, and it
evokes memories of more somber theatrical fare, especially such
existential heavyweights as ``No Exit,'' ``Waiting for Godot'' and
Harold Pinter's ``Dumbwaiter.'' David Seymore (McColl) and Kevin
Kevin (Sean Foley) _ and these are not, the characters would like
you to know, their real names _ waken to find themselves bound and
gagged, locked in a pink-and-blue eyesore of a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The men don't know each other, and they don't remember how they
got there. Presumably they are the victims, as David says with grim
relish, of ``dark forces that are yet to reveal themselves.'' The
key to the door is found quickly and, of course, just as quickly
lost. And thus begins a strained cohabitation that will last for
the next quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
   Hewing to the rules of comedy team basics, a la Laurel and Hardy
or Abbott and Costello, the show presents characters of distinctly
different ilks and hence destined to annoy each other. David, who
wears a morning suit (he has come from a wedding reception), is a
party boy with an overdeveloped sense of whimsy, a bit like Dudley
Moore in ``Arthur.'' His life, he recalls bleakly, involved ``an
awful lot of yachting...pretty much endless yachting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kevin (his ``secret middle name'' is Kevin) is a more
salt-of-the-earth sort, wearing street clothes over his pajamas,
who after much hesitation sums up his earlier existence by saying,
``I tend to watch a lot of television.'' These details, by the way,
emerge only after the men have been together for a number of years.
And that's well before they think about pooling their resources, a
carton of milk and a single egg. The egg later shows up atop a
strange piece of headgear worn by McColl, which Foley matches by
wearing a similar contraption topped by a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Does any of this sound funny to you? Probably not. And it is
probably to the credit of the Right Size that its hilarity doesn't
translate into synopsis. Yet having seen ``Often,'' I find myself
laughing as I write these things down, marveling that jokes that
were repeated again and again seemed to acquire new punch with each
delivery. (My favorite, and please don't ask me to explain, was
Foley's exquisitely timed rendering of the words ``Hello, Mrs.
Spicer.'')
</P>
<P>
   And while the evening's prevailing spirit may sound anarchic, it
represents a canny balance of disparate comic elements. These range
from the hoariest of puns and sight gags (``I can't believe you're
still doing this sort of material,'' Foley grumbles more than once)
to stories within stories of Borgesian complexity and periodic
leaps into the past. In the process the evening becomes a wily
commentary on the ways people mark and kill time. The games the men
play, for the record, range from the tedious ``find the dot''
(Kevin's choice) to the impersonation of bees and flowers (David's
favorite).
</P>
<P>
   The feeling of dizziness mounts as the show keeps calling
attention to its artificial nature. The door that stands between
the men and the outside world can be picked up and carried around,
and the passage of years is indicated by a set of increasingly long
cloth beards with elastic bands. Such devices are used without
winking self-consciousness; unreality is an accepted part of
reality. As the show nears the end of its 70 minutes, the
adversarial prisoners achieve a state of harmony that is pure
show-business rhapsody. It takes the form of a music-hall-style
duet (by Chris Larner), accessorized with pastel canes, that
centers on the gleefully iterated phrase, ``We're both dead.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an enchanted moment, a reminder of how classic comedy finds
redeeming form in life's frustrations, the logic in its illogic.
The song, of course, is one of the silliest you've ever heard. But
by that point, having followed Foley and McColl through 25 years of
slapstick and non sequiturs, you somehow feel that everything
suddenly makes absolute sense.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DO YOU COME HERE OFTEN?'
</P>
<P>
   Written and conceived by Sean Foley, Hamish McColl and Jozef
Houben; directed by Houben; designer, Alice Power; music and songs
by Chris Larner; choreography by Ryan Francois; lighting designer
and production manager, Tom Albu. Presented by Incidental Colman
Tod Productions and Dodger Theatricals. At Performance Space 122,
150 First Ave., at Ninth Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sean Foley (Kevin Kevin) and Hamish McColl David Seymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
