<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PEKING-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-16 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEKING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PEKING LETTER,' A SILLY BUT LIVELY EXTRAVAGANZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MAUREEN CORRIGAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what surely must be a bow to Graham Greene, Seymour Topping
dubs ``The Peking Letter,'' his novel about the Chinese Communist
revolution, ``an entertainment.'' Early in his writing career,
Greene used that term to refer to his thrillers; later he came to
rue that label because for many years the academic literary
establishment followed his lead and dismissed those
``entertainments,'' classic suspense novels like ``The Ministry of
Fear'' and ``The Third Man,'' as piffle. In the case of ``The
Peking Letter,'' however, the designation ``entertainment'' may be
less of an albatross than a shrewd antidote to critical venom.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, as this reader snorted at the panting dialogue,
melodramatic chapter endings and whopping coincidences that compose
Topping's novel, the cheery label ``entertainment'' admonished her
to lighten up and enjoy this silly but undeniably lively
extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Peking Letter'' is about love among the ruins of war, in
this case the Chinese civil war of the late 1940's when the armies
of Chiang Kai-shek and Mao Zedong battled for control of the
country. The story opens in October 1948 in Peking. Mao's troops
are massing outside the city; inside, Chiang's forces have been
ordered to fight to the death. Without diplomatic (or authorial)
intervention, a bloody siege will ensue that will surely destroy
not only countless lives, but also the artistic treasures and
imperial buildings that grace the old capital.
</P>
<P>
   As history tells us, Peking was spared when the general
commanding the Nationalist troops surrendered to the Communists.
Topping knows of this turn of events from firsthand witness. He
covered the Chinese civil war as a correspondent for The Associated
Press before moving in 1959 to The New York Times, where he served
as a foreign correspondent in Moscow and Hong Kong and rose to
managing editor. In his preface, Topping admits that although his
account of events in the novel is drawn from his reportorial
experience, most of his characters and their adventures are
figments of his imagination. The biggest figment of them all is a
tall, red-haired American named Eric Jensen who, in this fantasy
revision of history, singlehandedly saves Peking _ as Beijing was
then known to Westerners _ from destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen is an unlikely young man to play the role of Great White
Hope. A scholar in residence at the Peking Language School, where
he is researching Taoist philosophy, Jensen cultivates a taste for
hot Chinese antiquities, yellow wine and the joy of girls at the
House of Three Pleasures. Nor is the latter pursuit Jensen's only
undercover work. He has been blackmailed into the role of spy for
the CIA: his mission dictates that he gain the confidence of
left-leaning students and intellectuals in order to provide
information that will ease a rapprochement between the U.S.
government and the Chinese Communists after the Communists come
into power.
</P>
<P>
   So how does Jensen save Peking? His heroic adventures begin when
he falls in love with a beautiful pro-Communist medical student who
goes by the English name Lilian. She and her compatriots ask Jensen
to carry a letter to the American ambassador in Nanking requesting
him to persuade Chiang Kai-shek's more open-minded vice president,
Gen. Li Tsung-jen, to authorize the surrender of Peking. Besotted
with Lilian, Jensen agrees to the mission in characteristically
overheated verbal style: ``Yes. ... I'll do it. Of course, I'll do
it. ... for her, for Peking.'' Soon Jensen is dashing hither and
yon about the country, being pursued by his outraged CIA controls
as well as by secret police from the Kuomingtang, Chiang's
Nationalist Party, led by an evil mixed-race fellow known as ``The
Blue-Eyed One.''
</P>
<P>
   For a gangly redhead at large in China, Jensen somehow manages
to blend into the crowd well enough to thwart capture again and
again. The plot of ``The Peking Letter'' strains as badly as a pair
of chopsticks maneuvering to pick up a mandarin orange. The novel's
characters are uniformly underdeveloped, a problem common to the
plot-driven thriller that its close cousin, the detective story,
sometimes overcomes through the serial unfolding of its main
characters. As one would expect from an old China hand like
Topping, however, the novel does offer a sweeping view of China on
the verge of a cataclysmic change. Readers glimpse the effects of
war and revolution on the lives of characters ranging from Ying the
pedicab man to the many Western expatriates living the good life in
China. Topping is evenhanded to a fault in his political cynicism.
Neither the Nationalists nor the Communists win any points for
compassion; ditto the plutocrats versus the peasants.
</P>
<P>
   We learn that Lilian's father plans to scoot off to the United
States with his ill-gotten bank profits; a few chapters on, we
witness peasants stealing rice from the bedsides of wounded
soldiers. Equating the stealing of the nation's resources by the
banker class that supported the Nationalists with the petty crimes
of hungry peasants implicitly denies how greatly the revolution,
whatever its excesses, bettered the lives of millions of Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   In a world this grim, love offers the only solace. To his
credit, Topping keeps readers guessing until his novel's final
pages as to whether the fate of his wartime sweethearts will more
closely resemble that of their besieged romantic counterparts in
Ernest Hemingway's sodden ``Farewell to Arms'' or Herman Wouk's
more upbeat ``Winds of War.'' As for the Chinese Communist
revolution, whose 50th anniversary is being observed this fall, its
outcome _ indeed like its appellation _ is still evolving.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Beijing in June, my Chinese guide corrected me
when I referred to ``the revolution.'' ``Not revolution,'' the
guide said. ``True Founding of the Nation.'' Revolution, she
explained, was a somewhat distasteful term of uncertain political
pedigree, more befitting the student uprising in Tiananmen Square
than the righteous rise of Mao and his followers to power. We
nodded at each other and kept the peace.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE PEKING LETTER'
</P>
<P>
   A Novel of the Chinese Civil War
</P>
<P>
   By Seymour Topping
</P>
<P>
   300 pages. Public Affairs. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
