<HEADER>
A4737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      09-16 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMOPHOBIA STAYS HOME, SEX AND DRUGS GO TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Hatosy, Alec Baldwin, Jon Abrahams, Jack Ferver, Amy
Smart, Tim Crowe, George Wendt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Corrente &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In the grittier precincts of Pawtucket, R.I., the year is 1974,
the paint is peeling off the porch, and young Tim Dunphy ( Hatosy)
is getting drunk and stoned a little too regularly to suit his
father, the blustery and bigoted Old Man Dunphy ( Baldwin). A year
away at prep school might straighten Tim out. ``Prep. Prepare you
to not get your neck broken by me,'' says the old man.
</P>
<P>
   A Dunphy friend donates the tuition, and Tim, his meager
personal effects slung over his shoulder in a trash bag, is on the
bus to Cornwall Academy in leafiest Connecticut. Awaiting him is a
stereotypical assortment of hidebound, vindictive school
authorities and repressed prep schoolers, who help Tim into the
required shirt and tie (a clip-on) and escort him to class.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring Hamlet his favorite author, Tim hasn't the slightest
idea what is going on. Luckily he's an engaging, resilient boy who
sticks to Pawtucket values and takes Cornwall as it comes. That
attracts Jane (Ms. Smart), a top student and good person at
Cornwall's girls division, who supplies friendship, romance and,
though Tim professes to study efficiently only when high, steady
help with his schoolwork.
</P>
<P>
   At home Old Man Dunphy, ever the skeptic about such upscale
endeavors despite having encouraged them, sits around with his pals
playing cards while they all stoke their homophobia. Beneath the
guarded crustiness, he loves his boy, though he won't discuss the
death of Tim's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile back on campus an accumulation of rules infractions
having to do with drugs and girls in boy's rooms undoes Jane's
acceptance to Brown and threatens to send Tim back to Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Some schoolboy scuffling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX At school there is much talk about sex, and a boy
masturbates, heard but not seen in the dark. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Obscenities fly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE The film's primary sin is the heavy use of drugs and
alcohol at home and at school. And homosexuals are not spoken
kindly of in the Dunphy kitchen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND 13 This is a very appealing film for viewers this
age, with two strong, positive central characters as bona fide role
models, their pot smoking notwithstanding. But parents may well
have objections on other grounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP An R-rated film for all the usual reasons, but it
transcends the form for a change and becomes a worthwhile
experience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Albert Brooks, Sharon Stone, Andie MacDowell, Mark Feurstein,
Jeff Bridges &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Albert Brooks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 97 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a great career,'' a crass young studio executive (
Feurstein) tells the screenwriter Steven Phillips ( Brooks). Maybe
it's time to try television. Anyway, Steven's movie-writing deal is
terminated, and he has minutes to get off the lot. Brian De Palma
needs his office.
</P>
<P>
   With a wife (Ms. MacDowell), children and a major screenwriterly
house to maintain in Hollywood fashion, Phillips is desperate.
Spielberg grants him a meeting: Stan Spielberg, that is, who
himself hasn't seen the other Spielberg in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   When all looks darkest, Phillips' friend Jack Warrick (
Bridges), another screenwriter, who lives in a chateau and is
obviously cooking on all cylinders, has a suggestion. There's a
woman he consults from time to time, a muse (Ms. Stone), who if she
is treated right can inspire a man to do his best work. Better
even.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is she from? Greece?'' Jack asks. Actually her name is
Sarah, and she'll go to work filling Jack's head with great
concepts. In return he is to put her up in a suite at the Four
Seasons Hotel at $1,700 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah, who is good company despite abruptly shifting whims and
demands, starts Phillips working on a comedy about an aquarium.
Just as fruitfully, she soon has his wife, Laura, making
sensational cookies that sell by the ton at places like Spago.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Sarah moves into the Phillips house and bosses Steven all
over the place while she and Laura have a great time hustling
cookies to all the right people. A desperate Martin Scorsese, in
one of several cameos by film people, shows up desperately needing
advice from Sarah on a new project. A couple of psychologists from
Ohio also appear, and they have quite a different take on the
muse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Almost eerily, none, though Sarah hops into bed nude, and
alone, and Phillips has a notion that Laura is attracted to her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A few mild vulgarities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 There is really nothing here to interest them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 Some children will be attracted to the movie talk,
Hollywood ambiance, sitcom situations and attractive characters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP The film is pretty far from normal teen-age fare,
obviously, but many will like it and it does make pleasant and
harmless entertainment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICKEY BLUE EYES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Grant, Jeanne Tripplehorn, James Caan, Burt Young, James
Fox, Joe Viterelli &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kelly Makin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 102 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Double murder. Vito Graziosi. ``Ring any bells?'' asks Gina
Vitale (Ms. Tripplehorn), who is explaining the facts of life to
the cultivated, mild-mannered Englishman, Michael Felgate ( Grant).
Michael, who smoothly wields the gavel at an art auction house, has
asked Gina to marry him. Gina at first demurs because she's the
daughter of a mobster ( Caan) who, along with ``relatives'' like
Graziosi, will try to control their lives forever.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Michael wants to proceed, and so he becomes
kissing buddies with the Graziosis and the Vitales. In some
respects it's a good move. Usually surly and late with their
deliveries to the auction house, truck drivers suddenly arrive
ahead of time and are actually civil. Sotheby's, Michael's chief
competition, has a fire.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a down side. Michael's future in-laws start using
the auction process to do a little money laundering. The FBI wants
to use the wedding ceremony to nail Graziosi. As for Michael and
the nuptials, Gina wants out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE A gangland figure is shot and left in a pool of blood.
Otherwise there is the threat of violence and some phony gore, but
all is in the spirit of a Mafia comedy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Occasional dirty talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 No for all kinds of reasons but primarily because
the film would be a total bore for most children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP Teen-agers will yawn, but if they have seen
everything else and still feel a need to go to the movies, this one
will do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
