<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4742 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-RADIO-     09-16 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-RADIO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK RADIO RINGS WITH DENUNCIATIONS OF CHURCH SHOOTINGS _ BUT NOT
OF GUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ On talk radio Thursday, discussions centered
on God's grace, senseless violence and the prospect of Larry Gene
Ashbrook burning in hell.
</P>
<P>
   Talk show hosts Mark Davis and Billy Hayes joined their callers
in venting about gun control, the news media and the decay of
society.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at life as a Monopoly game, the people Ashbrook killed
and wounded in a Fort Worth church don't ``have to pass Go, don't
have to collect $200; you go straight to heaven,'' said Hayes, who
calls himself ``Humble Billy Hayes'' on his talk show on KLIF AM.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook ``goes straight to hell,'' Hayes said. ``May you burn
in perdition, Larry Gene Ashbrook.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting live from outside Wedgwood Baptist Church, WBAP
AM's Davis described the crime scene with its yellow police tape,
the remote TV and radio vans and the endless stream of gawkers.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothesizing about what may have happened at the church
Wednesday night and what may have been in Ashbrook's mind, Davis
said: ``Let's frame it this way: Some people are just evil. We ask
the question, `Why?' ... Sometimes, there is no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Jones on KRLD AM interviewed reporters, hospital
officials and members of the Fort Worth bomb squad. One of his
first callers attacked TV stations as being too intrusive in the
tragic first moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are clowns,'' said a caller who identified
himself as Jim.
</P>
<P>
   Another caller, Art, told Jones that the news media shouldn't
``glorify'' people like Ashbrook by using their names on television
and radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to check out like that, they don't deserve
to be remembered for jack,'' Art said.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempt to use the shootings as justification to impose
stricter gun control laws was vehemently rejected by callers to
Davis' and Hayes' shows. Both hosts said the tragedy might been
averted if the churchgoers ``had been packing.''
</P>
<P>
   Callers especially took exception to comments that Vice
President Al Gore made during an interview on ``Good Morning
America,'' in which he said something obviously must be done about
the proliferation of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Dave, who said he is a 20-year-old law enforcement officer, told
Davis: ``Another liberal blames the gun and not the criminal ...
I've never seen a gun jump up and shoot anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   On Hayes' show, however, Eugene disagreed, asking, ``why do we
need automatic weapons that can destroy seven lives'' so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
