<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HERE SHE COMES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For some time now, the Miss America pageant that
comes to your television screen Saturday has had pretensions of
being more cerebral than it really is _ which is simply a
long-running beauty contest, a throwback to a more quaint, innocent
era.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers have tried to stress that the winner must have a
talent for something (almost anything will do), special community
interests that demonstrate compassion and the brains to talk
lucidly to an interviewer. They actually call their body-baring
swimsuit segment a display of ``physical fitness in swimwear.''
There will always be a public relations person.
</P>
<P>
   These surface cosmetics don't kid anyone, however. We all know
the basic appeal is the opportunity to ogle gorgeous, shapely young
women prancing around in sexy outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Pageant officials have suddenly provoked a public uproar by
deciding to expand the pool of eligible beauties. They eliminated
the rigid ban against a prior divorce or abortion, recognizing that
many modern, unmarried young women have active sex lives. The idea
was to encourage more entrants, whose numbers have been dwindling
lately.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that parading naked down the runway wearing nothing
but the ubiquitous stiletto heels had suddenly become the preferred
standard. Outraged protesters screamed that the pageant was ruined
and the winner's image as the American ideal of virginal purity was
compromised. Sex, the previously unspoken lure, had unmistakably
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   The most dogmatic critics trashed young women who have fled
unhappy, sometimes abusive marriages or ended a pregnancy they
feared would ruin their lives physically, emotionally or mentally
if carried to term. ``We've gotten away from morals,'' Mary
Richardson, executive director of the rival Mrs. America
International Pageant, sniffed. ``Wrong is wrong and right is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't about morals, or even perpetuating a mythical
feminine ``ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all marriages and pregnancies are idyllic. Some are terrible
experiences that cannot be tolerated. No outsider can fairly judge
another individual's morality when it comes to decisions about
personal sanity and survival.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this is really about the politics of the religious
right. Any suggestion that abortion _ a legal procedure, after all
_ is not totally immoral and impermissible under any circumstances
drives the hard-right activists to the microphones, the lecterns,
the courtrooms and the ballot boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Some state pageant directors have sued the central organization
to revoke the change. The pageant's chief executive, Robert Beck,
capitulated to the pressure by postponing the revisions until he
can assess the scope of the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying notion that the Miss America contest is among
innocent, wholesome young women free of self-centered ambition or
artifice who would be corrupted by competing against a divorcee is
silly on its face. This is a business, for which there are
financial and psychological rewards. To get to the finals, these
women have to be pros at the game.
</P>
<P>
   They come well-packaged, taping their breasts together for
deeper cleavage, plying on shiny stuff to make their eyes and lips
glisten, subjecting their bodies to expensive personal trainers,
studying boring current events and paying for the most expensive,
form-fitting gowns they can find.
</P>
<P>
   Why should they be forever held up as sweet little milkmaids,
when they so obviously are not? And why is their private life
anybody's business, so long as they have no criminal record?
</P>
<P>
   The Miss America pageant should simply follow the pattern set by
the military to deal with the issue of gays in its ranks. ``Don't
ask, don't tell'' is the right solution for everyone. We are a
tolerant, secular society.
</P>
<P>
   Under the armed forces policy, privacy is important so long as
personal habits are not advertised to the world at large or
interfere with job performance. The policy isn't working perfectly,
but it seems to be a sensible, if uncomfortable, compromise.
</P>
<P>
   What do the beauty pageant protesters want? Gynecological exams
of every contestant to prove her sexual status?
</P>
<P>
   Who cares, really? This is not an election for leader of the
free world or even local councilperson. It is a rivalry of physical
beauty, the concept of which itself has changed over the decades to
include minorities and disabilities that once would have been
considered imperfections.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a shame if the self-appointed moralists scare
pageant officials into retreating into a decorative but ultimately
fake world that no longer exists, or even interests us very much.
What if they gave a certifiably virginal pageant and nobody came?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstnews.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
