<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON INVOKES EXECUTIVE PRIVILEGE IN CLEMENCY CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton invoked executive privilege
Thursday to bar administration officials from publicly discussing
his offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican militants or releasing
government documents related to his decision.
</P>
<P>
   The move incensed congressional Republicans who have repeatedly
called on the president to explain his reasons for granting
clemency to members of the FALN, initials for the Spanish name of
the Armed Forces of National Liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy White House counsel Cheryl Mills said in a letter to the
House Government Reform Committee that Congress had no authority to
overturn the president's clemency decision and, therefore, has no
right to investigate how that decision was made.
</P>
<P>
   Executive privilege is a claim by the president or a high
administration official that he or she should not be forced to
testify because it could hamper effective decision-making by the
president. Mills said Clinton needed to invoke the privilege in
this case to ``assure that the president receives candid advice
from his advisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the committee, which has
held hearings into the clemency issue, said the president has a
``moral obligation'' to explain his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``By claiming executive privilege, he is, in essence, telling
the American people that it's none of their business,'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans and members of the law enforcement community
have accused Clinton of offering clemency to the Puerto Rican
nationalists to help his wife's all-but-announced Senate candidacy
from New York where some 1.3 million Puerto Ricans are eligible to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Several administration officials had been scheduled to testify
Monday before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee's terrorism
subcommittee about their recommendations to the president on
whether the Puerto Ricans should be granted clemency.
</P>
<P>
   However, late Sunday night, the Justice Department ordered the
officials not to appear before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Burton's committee subpoenaed officials from the
FBI, the Justice Department and the White House to testify at a
Thursday hearing on the clemency issue. The Senate Judiciary
Committee also said it would issue subpoenas for documents and
testimony regarding the clemency case, according to the committee's
chairman, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas left the White House with the choice of either
allowing the officials to testify or invoking executive privilege
to block their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the legal advice of the attorney general, the president
is invoking executive privilege over certain documents and
testimony relating to the grant of clemency,'' said Jim Kennedy,
spokesman for the White House counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the White House would release some 10,000 pages of
documents related to the clemency decision, including thousands of
letters exhorting the president to show leniency toward the
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   But documents ``directly related to the exercise of the
president's constitutional authority are not being provided,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   This marks the fourth time that Clinton has asserted executive
privilege to withhold testimony or documents from Congress,
according to Justice Department records. He asserted executive
privilege three times in 1996: when Congress demanded documents
related to the White House travel office firings, a joint FBI-Drug
Enforcement Agency memo to Clinton on drug enforcement, and
foreign-policy documents on the administration's Haiti policy.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also has asserted executive privilege in
litigation and independent counsel investigations, most notably
when Clinton sought to shield his deliberations with aides and
lawyers from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation into
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, the FALN has been linked to 130 bombings that killed
six people _ including four police officers _ and maimed dozens of
others. In addition, the group was involved in a number of armed
assaults against government buildings and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of the 16 Puerto Ricans offered clemency by
Clinton was directly linked to bombings that caused injuries or
fatalities, a point the president has cited in explaining his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 FALN members offered clemency, which required them to
renounce violence, 14 accepted and two declined.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Senate voted 95 to 2 for a resolution calling
the clemency decision ``deplorable.'' The House passed a similar
measure last week by a 311-41 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The votes have no actual impact on the clemency granted to the
Puerto Rican militants since Congress has no constitutional
authority to overturn the offers.
</P>
<P>
   The president has insisted that politics played no role in the
clemency and that he was swayed in large part by the lengthy prison
terms _ nearly 20 years in several cases _ already served by the
FALN members.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton extended the offer after a lengthy review by former
White House chief counsel, Charles F.C. Ruff, according to the
White House. Prominent human rights advocates, including South
African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and former President Jimmy
Carter, backed the move.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement organizations and former FBI agents who have
investigated the FALN strongly criticized the clemency offers.
</P>
<P>
   Gibert G. Gallegos, president of the Grand Lodge, Fraternal
Order of Police, the nation's largest law enforcement organization
with more than 283,000 members, told a Senate committee on
Wednesday that the president had ``used his constitutional power to
release unrepentant terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Former FBI Special Agent Richard Hahn, who investigated FALN
attacks from 1975 to 1987, told the committee that the president's
decision sends a ``frightening message'' to terrorists that the
United States is not serious about protecting its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   At the same hearing, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who has
urged Mrs. Clinton to seek the Senate seat, lashed out at the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret greatly the actions of President Clinton,''
Torricelli said. ``I hope the committee will learn more about his
motivations and the process so that it's never repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a poll released Thursday showed that half of New York
state voters disapprove of Clinton's clemency decision, while only
12 percent approved.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac College poll of 911 New York State registered
voters, which was conducted September 7-13, found that another 35
percent said they don't know enough about the subject to offer an
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
