<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4783 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-MEXICAN-ART-EXHIBIT-T     09-16 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-ART-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNFLINCHING LOOK AT POSTREVOLUTIONARY MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DICK REAVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, the day on which Mexico celebrates its independence
from Spain, the Dallas Museum of Art opened ``Indigenismo to
Modernism: Art in Postrevolutionary Mexico, 1920-50,'' a 58-piece
exhibition that will run through Feb. 13. In the spirit of its 30
artists and their subject matter, entry to the show is free.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, drawn mostly from the holdings of Texas collectors
and institutions, highlights artwork on paper: lithographs,
photographs, wood and linoleum cuts, with a half-dozen canvases
thrown in for good measure. Muralists Diego Rivera, David Alfaro
Siqueiros and Jos Clemente Orozco headline the exhibit, which
includes works by Frida Kahlo and Rufino Tamayo. But the best works
are by unheralded figures. Even the work of a handful of
foreigners, mostly photographers, makes the show: Prints by Edward
Weston and Laura Gilpin, both Americans, and Frenchman Henri
Cartier-Bresson, are among the works on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indigenismo'' is a word whose literal meaning is
``indigenism,'' a term nonexistent but comprehensible in English.
It roughly means ``Indianism,'' and it came into use during
Mexico's frustrated attempts to define a national character.
Between about 1920 and 1950, Mexican intellectuals and artists felt
that, thanks to the Revolution of 1910, their country had become
truly independent for the first time since the Spanish conquest.
They wanted to give independence a cultural stamp. Their school of
thought, predominant then and not entirely defeated today, held
that Mexico was a non-Western nation, rooted in indigenous or
Indian culture _ a culture oppressed by, and corrupted by, its
mixture with European influences.
</P>
<P>
   To introduce viewers to the context of the era, curator Cheryl
Hartup recruited three lithographs on a common theme, the persona
of the revolutionary martyr Emiliano Zapata, and hung them side by
side. These lithos, by Mexico's most famous muralists, make a good
starting point for viewing the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   As if to stress his grandeur, in the depiction by Siqueiros,
Zapata sits atop an undersize horse, with mountains the size of
molehills in the background. Orozco's Zapata litho consists of
hundreds of men in broad-brimmed sombreros, seemingly shuffling
along together, most with heads bowed, in ignorance or weariness or
humility _ or all three. Those whose faces are visible have
bug-eyed visages, like caricatures of their leader. Rivera's
Zapata, by contrast, stands dismounted in the stiff pose of a
European saint, a Spanish conqueror underfoot _ and even his horse
looks noble. Two of these renditions come from veterans of the
Revolution _ Siqueiros and Orozco. Rivera, who is widely criticized
as romanticizing Mexico's past, spent the revolutionary period in
France and Spain, much of it in the warrens of European cubists.
</P>
<P>
   Historical iconography is not of concern to many Americans, but
there is something in the DMA exhibit for everyone. Even those who
don't know Zapata from ``zapato'' will be taken by a portrait of a
young woman from the Tehauntepec region, in a crimson festival
dress. The picture, in ink and gouache, is by Miguel Covarrubias, a
man whose name is a mouthful in any language but whose contribution
to ``Indigenismo'' displays the high sheen and nearly
photorealistic detail that Americans appreciated in illustrations
he produced for Vanity Fair and The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   A work in tempera by Alfredo Ramos Martinez, ``Workers,'' when
viewed from a distance of 10 feet appears to be a colorful but
otherwise ordinary expressionist rendering of women working in a
field. But on closer examination, it delivers a surprise. The work
is painted upon a sheet of newsprint, from the classified-ad
section of the Dec. 10, 1944, edition of the Los Angeles Times. The
fine lines of the newspaper, far from distracting, lend a delicate
texture to the work, a sort of tantalizing hint in its background.
Look more closely; there's a joke here! Curator Hartup says that
Ramos, who moved to Los Angeles to provide medical care for an
ailing daughter, originally painted on newsprint for lack of
materials. But he liked the enhancement that it gave his works, and
he didn't give up the trick even when better times came along.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable work in ``Indigenismo's'' displays may well
be ``Mxico se transforma en una gran ciudad'' (Mexico City
Transforms Into a Big City), from Alfredo Zalce, a teacher and
muralist born in 1908. The 1947 etching, owned by the University of
Texas at Austin, is one of those that cannot be reproduced in DMA
brochures or in the public press, not only because of copyright
problems but mainly because its sentiment is outrageous: Readers
would howl and consuls would call were it waved like a banner.
</P>
<P>
   The etching shows men in an urban landscape, clad in rags,
rummaging through tow sacks. The men may be burglars, or they may
be bums; it's hard to tell. A malnourished dog prowls in a garbage
can near the center of the image; reclining legs in wrinkled pants,
from which bare feet protrude, lie in the foreground: somebody is
sleeping on the street. The human characters in the image have
simian faces and simian hands. Poverty degrades the poor, the
message seems to say. But ``gran ciudad'' is more than a protest of
homelessness. The multilevel buildings in the picture come only to
shoulder-height on its monkeylike men, and in that detail, the work
says something else, something sardonic: Although modern society
impoverishes us, we dwarf its towering accomplishments. The wit and
style of ``gran ciudad'' are as Mexican as can be _ this is an
indigenismo drawing. But its message is ironically, if lamentably,
quite universal. This nationalist work speaks as clearly to viewers
in contemporary Texas as it did to Zalce's countrymen a
half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
