<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAMME-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VERS LA FLAMME': CHEKHOV'S PAIRS IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Chekhov or Dr. Laura? In ``Vers la Flamme,'' the
choreographer Martha Clarke has focused her familiar brand of
imagistic dance theater on sexual encounters and marital
unhappiness.
</P>
<P>
   There is more than that to the five stories by Anton Chekhov
that Ms. Clarke uses as a springboard for her often ingenious,
always beautiful and largely uneven new work at the New Victory
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   What is missing is the subtlety of Chekhov's narrators, their
change of tone within a story. With a couple in various states of
undress in each episode, ``Vers la Flamme'' suggests everyday
fodder for a radio psychologist, not an exploration of human
behavior with a moral and social dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Should one then forget Chekhov and concentrate on Ms. Clarke?
She has been doing this kind of thing since she joined Pilobolus
Dance Theater shortly after it was founded in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Forgetting Chekhov may be the best course. ``Vers la Flamme''
has little depth, with one episode as an exception. But it is never
boring, and its tour de force is Ms. Clarke's use of Scriabin's
piano music, played onstage brilliantly by Christopher O'Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center, which is presenting ``Vers la Flamme'' through
Sunday as part of its New Visions series, has billed the piece as
an experimental music collaboration. Yet it was the American Dance
Festival that commissioned the work with Lincoln Center. ``Vers la
Flamme'' had its official premiere at the festival in Durham, N.C.,
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of her generation, Ms. Clarke has extended the
definition of dance. Although she has not had the worldwide impact
of Pina Bausch, she uses movement in an unconventional way that
only professional dancers can execute with the right rhythmic
phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   When the American Dance Festival founded and managed her
independent company Crows Nest 20 years ago, her leading dancer was
Felix Blaska, a French dancer who now returns to give a simply
outstanding and powerful performance.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true in the second tale, ``Enemies,'' in
which the intensity that Blaska showed originally in Roland Petit's
ballet company translate easily into Ms. Clarke's expressive but
reductive movement vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   She has done better before. In ``The Garden of Villandry,'' a
woman was torn between two men. Who was the husband? Who was the
lover? The hints came in the Pilobolus style of weight shifting in
the partnering.
</P>
<P>
   Here again the women are often held on the men's sides, and what
looks like natural gesture or a walk is incorporated into a finite
phrase of movement. Often, and in nearly every episode, a couple
spins or revolves in a metaphor for passion.
</P>
<P>
   When a woman falls at her lover's feet, one recalls Martha
Graham's retort to a viewer who objected to her unseemly collapse
in a ball gown. Graham replied that the fall was equated with her
character's reaction to a lover across the room.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Ms. Clarke's lovers are usually in a literal clinch rather
than yards apart and her style has lost some richness without
attaining a perfect distillation of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Enemies'' is the exception. Blaska is the country doctor
grieving with his wife, Paola Styron, over the coffin of their dead
child. George de la Pena is Abogin, the boorish landowner who drags
the doctor from his mourning to attend to a supposedly sick wife.
His spouse (Kate Coyne) in fact runs off with her lover (Alexandre
Proia).
</P>
<P>
   Michael Yeargan's stationary set is a blue room with peeling
paint whose atmosphere changes wonderfully with Stephen
Strawbridge's lighting and the emotionally coded music, mostly
Scriabin preludes and a Rachmaninoff prelude as an epilogue. Not
for nothing was Scriabin interested in color theory and how colors
affected the psyche. O'Riley plays Scriabin's ``Flammes Sombres,''
in this episode, and ``Vers la Flamme'' is the piece played at the
end of the fifth tale.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Enemies'' Ms. Styron spins as hammering is heard offstage.
The small coffin is being prepared. She and Blaska sit hunched in
silhouetted despair. The music rumbles as Abogin charges in,
oblivious to the compressed desperation that Blaska telegraphs in
his tightened body.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coyne, a British dancer, and Proia, formerly with New York
City Ballet, rush by to signify their affair; she is in knickers.
Compared to the doctor's grief, the affair looks trivial, a gap
that Blaska explains through his fists swinging in hysterical rage
as he gazes toward the ever-present coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lady With the Lap Dog,'' the first episode, elicited no
applause at the New Victory (209 W. 42nd St., Manhattan). Jane
Greenwood's period costumes, as elsewhere in the work, are fine,
and Ms. Styron as the lady looks vulnerable enough. De la Pena, as
her lover, has a good moment when his smugness gives way to real
passion, but Ms. Clarke rarely goes beyond illustration.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Darling'' Ms. Clarke adds a risky cartoonish flavor to
a story about a woman who cannot live without a man. Ms. Coyne has
an engaging comic flair and flips nicely over an armchair. Blaska
and Proia succumb as her husbands, and de la Pena, a lover, mounts
her in a no-nonsense way. When Sean Dalal, as a child placed in her
care, goes to bed, we do not hear the cry of alarm he utters at the
end of the Chekhov story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grasshopper'' fares better with the Canadian dancer and
choreographer Margie Gillis. She is her stunning self and does what
she usually does in her own work: She bares a breast, lets down her
long hair and simulates a breakdown, here as the wife who prefers
her lover to her worthy husband.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Nervous Breakdown,'' a student who is disgusted with more
than what Ms. Clarke tells us, suffers a crisis in a bordello. The
whores are pictured as stereotypes. But there is something
extraordinary in the way Ms. Clarke has Proia, the student,
transform his lean tall frame into a cringing boyish body that
scales the walls for escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
