<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Gulliver' Travels to DVD Format
</P>
<P>
   This week DVD got its second megatitle, ``The Matrix,'' to go
with its first, ``Titanic,'' released in August. Distributors say
about one million copies of each are headed for the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, with two million DVD players in use, that divides
into one ``Titanic'' and one ``Matrix'' for every two machines, a
sales rate no DVD booster could logically complain about.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year the number of DVD machines is expected to
be four million. That cuts the disk-to-player ratio, but by that
time there will be several animated titles from Disney that should
sell at least a million copies each and probably more.
</P>
<P>
   What does this say about DVD? ``Good steady movement,'' said
Dick Kelly, president of Cambridge Associates, a consulting company
that monitors the format. DVD, he said, has gone beyond early
adopters and is approaching, in the lingo of the marketers, ``early
mass.'' That's not to say a rush, however. At the moment DVD seems
to be settling in as a kind of sidekick to the VCR, whose sales are
as high as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The disk also continues to move beyond action films like ``The
Matrix.'' DVD is a special pleasure with restorations like
``Gulliver's Travels,'' Max Fleischer's 1939 animated film, which
is to be released on disk and videocassette on Tuesday by Winstar.
Colors are the way they were in the '30s, and multiple tracks offer
a choice of the original soundtrack, stereo, surround sound and
(the ultimate) Dolby Digital surround sound.
</P>
<P>
   Released originally by Paramount, ``Gulliver's Travels,'' is no
classic, but it has an interesting history. Fleischer's adaptation
of Jonathan Swift's tale of the gentle giant washed onto the shores
of the tiny Lilliputians followed Disney's ``Snow White'' by two
years.
</P>
<P>
   At several junctures in the film a few of the small folk bear
more than a passing resemblance to the seven dwarfs, and while
making new clothing for Lemuel Gulliver, the little craftsmen all
but whistle while they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paramount wanted competition with what Disney had done, so
Fleischer was under direct orders to make it similar,'' said Tom
Reich, an animation expert who produced and directed the
restoration for Audio Galaxy, a production company based in the
Universal Studios Complex in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Fleischer _ better known as the creator of Betty Boop
and the man who first brought Popeye to the screen _ got
bushwhacked. ``At the time Fleischer was the larger of the two
studios,'' Reich said. Since 1936 he had made 20-minute films that
were billed as opening features in theaters. ``Then Disney
surprised everybody with a full-length feature,'' he said.
Originally planned for 20 minutes, ``Gulliver's Travels'' ballooned
to 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot of work. More than 700 artists produced almost
640,000 frames. The film did very well in theaters. Fleischer later
moved on to industrial films and television. Everyone knows what
happened to Disney.
</P>
<P>
   God Said ``Ha!''
</P>
<P>
   In her monologue the actress Julia Sweeney recalls that during
her hysterectomy the doctors lost track of one of her ovaries.
``Don't worry, it's going to turn up eventually,'' she was told. By
that point in her life Ms. Sweeney had honed a fine humor about
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   A ``divorce made in heaven'' is followed by news that her
incurably ill brother and her parents are coming over to her place
_ permanently. ``What happens when your brother gets cancer and
your entire family moves in with you?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney remembers asking in the self-help section of a
bookstore. ``Where is that book?'' As her crises deepen, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, her film stays ``quick-witted
and funny without betraying the sadness of the events described.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 85 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   My Favorite Martian
</P>
<P>
   A three-eyed, three-stomached Martian hops in the trunk of an
unwitting television newsman named Tim O'Hara (Jeff Daniels).
</P>
<P>
   Back at Tim's place the extraterrestrial becomes Uncle Martin
(Christopher Lloyd), an urbane if excitable fellow in constant fear
of being discovered. And he has reason, it turns out, as the
government closes in on the visitor, who tends to literally fall
apart physically when he gets depressed.
</P>
<P>
   In an adaptation of the '60s sitcom, Daniels and Lloyd play off
each other nicely to make ``an amiable family entertainment''
(Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Disney. $22.99. 100 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release
date: Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Children of Heaven
</P>
<P>
   Two Iranian children, Ali (Mir Farrokh Hashemian) and his
sister, Zahra (Bahareh Seddiqui), share the same pair of sneakers
because she has lost hers and they don't want their parents to find
out. From then on every detail of impoverished life in Tehran is
detailed down to the careful unraveling of a woolen garment so it
can be knitted into some thing else.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, though, life is sweet and the feeling manipulative in
Majid Majidi's film, in which ``no reality beyond the economic
intrudes upon a fairy-tale atmosphere'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 88 minutes. Farsi with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN PLAYHOUSE. The acclaimed PBS series adapted from the
works of American writers (and some foreigners) comes to home video
for the first time with six productions: Mary Austin's ``Land of
Little Rain,'' with Helen Hunt, 65 minutes; Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s
``Who Am I This Time?,'' with Susan Sarandon and Christopher
Walken, directed by Jonathan Demme, 60 minutes; Willa Cather's ``O
Pioneers!,'' with Mary McDonnell, 118 minutes; Arthur Miller's
adaptation of Henrik Ibsen's ``Enemy of the People,'' with George
Grizzard and John Glover, 118 minutes; Terrance McNally's ``Andre's
Mother,'' with Sada Thompson and Richard Thomas, 60 minutes, and F.
Scott Fitzgerald's ``Under the Biltmore Clock,'' with Sean Young,
80 minutes. 1999. Monterey. $19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   LORD PETER WIMSEY. Dorothy Sayers' blue-blooded sleuth reappears
from his '70s Masterpiece Theater days in ``Clouds of Witness,''
about a murder during a family retreat at Riddlesdale Lodge. 1999.
Acorn. $59.95, five cassettes. 225 minutes. Release date: Sept. 21.
Information: 800-999-0212.
</P>
<P>
   LULU ON THE BRIDGE. Attention Harvey Keitel fans. The jazz
saxophonist Izzy Maurer ( Keitel) takes a stray bullet and winds up
with a dead man's briefcase in which he finds a strange stone. That
leads him to Celia (Mira Sorvino) and together they take a dark
look into Izzy's soul. Shown abroad, Paul Auster's film wasn't
released in the United States. 1999. Trimark. $69.99. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Sept. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
