<TEXT>
<P>
   A Change Of Scenery &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman.'' And say
hello to ``The Price.''
</P>
<P>
   Word this week that ``Death of a Salesman'' would close on Nov.
7 was quickly followed by news that a revival of ``The Price,''
Miller's 1967 play, would open on Broadway two days later, at the
Royale Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur believes it's never had a great production in New
York,'' said David Richenthal, lead producer of ``Salesman'' and
``The Price.'' ``I hope this production helps discover the play.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of two brothers locked in a battle over their loyalty
to family, ``The Price'' comes to New York after appearing at the
Williamstown Theater Festival in August. The four-person ensemble _
Jeffrey DeMunn, Bob Dishy, Harris Yulin and Lizbeth Mackay _ is
being directed by James Naughton.
</P>
<P>
   From a financial standpoint Richenthal seems to be betting that
lightning strikes twice. ``Salesman,'' after all, began a
nine-month run at the Eugene O'Neill Theater with stellar reviews,
lunched on a bushel of Tonys and will end with its producers
pocketing a healthy profit. (Who says it's a sad story?)
</P>
<P>
   Richenthal said the inability to find a replacement for Brian
Dennehy, the production's Willy Loman, was the main reason for the
close.
</P>
<P>
   Among the actors who had declined to follow in Dennehy's sizable
footsteps were Albert Finney, Stacy Keach and Charles Durning.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy, hoarse from performing, denied that his health had
played a role in the decision to close, but admitted that playing
Willy was not easy: ``I'm 61 years old, and this is a tough deal.
November was always a target. And there's something inside of me
that says it's time to move on.'' He added that he would have
missed a week's worth of performances in mid-November to shoot a
movie.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the hunger for theaters, the O'Neill was snatched
up as soon as it was available; the next tenant will be ``Wrong
Mountain,'' David Hirson's absurdist comedy, opening on Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   At the John Golden Theater, meanwhile, ``Side Man'' is heading
south, to Washington. The show closes its yearlong Broadway run on
Halloween before embarking on a monthlong run at the Kennedy Center
for the Performing Arts on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The move makes way for the comedian Jackie Mason, who will begin
performances of his latest, ``Much Ado About Everything,'' at the
Golden on Nov. 16.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an impressive run for ``Side Man,'' which began
performances at a 99-seat theater in the East Village before
leapfrogging to Broadway. Along the way two of its leads, Edie
Falco and Frank Wood, became stars. Ms. Falco won an Emmy Award
this week for her work in ``The Sopranos,'' and Wood won a Tony for
``Side Man.'' The play's author, Warren Leight, won the Tony for
best play in the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the accolades, the production will probably earn back
only half of its initial $750,000 investment on Broadway. But Jay
Harris, one of its producers, explained that regional productions
are in the offing for Cincinnati, Chicago, Seattle and
Philadelphia, and that the play's commercial producers will share
almost half of any movie deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect the subsidiary rights will help us recoup and make
a profit,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Salesman'' needn't wait. Richenthal declined
to go into specifics, but box office figures show that ``Salesman''
probably earned almost $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Salesman'' should be satisfying for Richenthal,
who lost big money on the critically acclaimed, financially
disappointing productions of Horton Foote's ``Young Man From
Atlanta'' in 1997 and Robert Schenkken's ``Kentucky Cycle'' in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enormous satisfaction to have a production work on all
wheels: critical, financial and artistic,'' he said. ``It's been
win, win, win, win.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Hunting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like other artistic directors, Douglas Aibel of the Vineyard
Theater has his favorite playwrights, and Craig Lucas is one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   When Lucas offered his latest play, ``Stranger,'' to the
Vineyard, Aibel said yes immediately, even though the company lacks
a place to show it because the season at Vineyard's East 15th
Street Theater is full.
</P>
<P>
   So Aibel is hunting for a stage for ``Stranger,'' which is about
a random meeting between two people, one of whom has done something
terribly, terribly wrong. ``We're leaving no stone unturned,''
Aibel said, adding that he hoped to find a theater within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to rehearse in December for a January opening in a
house that seats 99 to 199 people. The director Mark Brokaw has
committed to the project, as has Mary-Louise Parker, whose history
with Lucas goes back to ``Prelude to a Kiss'' in 1990. She also
appeared in Brokaw's last outing at the Vineyard, ``How I Learned
to Drive,'' the 1998 Pulitzer winner by Paula Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am keenly aware of the fact that the combination of these
parties would be so valuable to the play and that we had a window
of opportunity to put them together,'' Aibel said. ``We all just
connected with the play immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they just need a theater. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ After talk of a Broadway run, ``The Unexpected Man'' by
Yasmina Reza, who wrote ``Art,'' is going Off Broadway under the
auspices of the Roundabout Theater Company. Eileen Atkins will
star, as she did in London. Nick Nolte, who was rumored for a New
York run, will not appear; the search is on for a male lead.
Performances are scheduled to begin at the Gramercy Theater on Jan.
14.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two Off Broadway shows appear to be hits before their first
performance. Producers of ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' the musical
adaptation of the Joyce short story, has already sold out its
initial six-week run at Playwrights Horizon. Performances begin on
Oct. 1. At the Greenwich Street Theater the producers of Douglas
Carter Beane's new play, ``Country Club,'' have announced a
four-week extension. Previews began on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
