<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-KIDS-TOOBUSY-TEX     09-16 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-TOOBUSY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEDS NEED ACTIVITY, BUT HOW MUCH IS TOO MUCH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday, Kathryn and Michelle have dance class. Tuesday, only
one of them has volleyball practice, so that's an easy day.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, says their mother, Traci Destena, Michelle has
dance and her other sister, Heather, has tumbling and dance
classes. Or is that dance and track?
</P>
<P>
   Destens laughs and wonders out loud how she does it all, whether
this is extracurricular overkill.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is constantly telling me we're doing too much,''
the Fort Worth mother says. ``But my philosophy is to keep them
busy so I don't have to worry about them getting into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping her child out of trouble is also one of the reasons
Valerie Robertson of Fort Worth says she lives a hectic life,
chauffeuring her daughter from activity to activity. Moriah
Robertson, 13, has volleyball practice at 7 a.m. most days. On
Wednesday nights, when she does not have volleyball or basketball
games, she goes to GAP, a Christian fellowship meeting at St. Paul
Lutheran Church. She also has swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gets nuts,'' says Valerie, who as a single mother
occasionally relies on her boss, parents and friends to help get
her daughter from here to there.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Kids today are busier than ever, participating
in organized sports in record numbers and taking on activities that
leave them less time for unstructured play and good old outdoor fun
than today's baby boomer parents enjoyed during their childhoods.
In the past two decades, the change has been significant: According
to a 1998 University of Michigan study that provided the first
detailed look since 1981 at how American children spend their time,
free time _ defined as time left over after eating, sleeping,
personal care, attending school, preschool or day care _ has
decreased from 40 percent to 25 percent of a child's day.
</P>
<P>
   Kids have less time for the simple business of being kids.
Something to worry about?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some children thrive on that stuff, and it really seems to be
good for them,'' says David Cross, associate professor of
psychology at Texas Christian University in Fort Worth. ``But
parents have to exercise common sense. They have to realize that
more isn't necessarily good.''
</P>
<P>
   Child psychologists agree that too much activity can do more
harm than good. Overloading children with everything from soccer to
piano to gymnastics can create a sort of obsessive-compulsive need
for activity, they say. But figuring out how much is too much is
not a simple matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are so individual,'' says Alice Wiedenhoff, staff
psychologist at the Child Study Center in Fort Worth. ``There are
some kids who thrive on having almost every moment of their day
filled and some who need downtime. It's everything in moderation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiedenhoff said that kids need to be well-rounded, and a variety
of extracurricular activities allows for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the bottom line is that parents need to be
responsive to the individual child's interests and desires,'' she
says. ``One of the hard things is there's a really fine line
between meeting the needs of parents and those of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no hard-and-fast rules about the amount of
time kids should spend in extracurricular activities, drawing the
line between kid-initiated and parent-pushed activities is the key,
say experts. Many agree that the best approach is to allow the
child to choose the activities.
</P>
<P>
   Problems may come when parents _ for reasons varying from
wanting to keep kids out of trouble to trying to live out their own
dreams through their kids to wanting to boost their child's resume
for college admission _ cram together a tight schedule that leaves
kids almost no room for relaxing. Cross says that the pendulum has
swung from a time when kids had little except their imaginations to
occupy them after school and on weekends to now, when it often
seems as if every minute of their lives is planned by their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because most activities children partake in are of a
competitive nature, there isn't enough time left in the day for
kids to be kids,'' Cross says. ``They have to achieve. They have to
grow up. They don't have downtime to decompress, even though we all
need that.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Mountrose, a California-based educator and author of
``Tips and Tools for Getting Thru to Kids,'' warns that there is a
``kind of escalating unconscious competition going on in the
country,'' and urges parents to remember that ``the back yard is
still there. It doesn't have to be abandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Mountrose also says that parents who believe that keeping
children busy is a deterrent to temptations such as drugs and
alcohol and hanging out with the wrong crowd are fooling
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``What counts in the long run is the relationship between parent
and child,'' he says. ``Provide activities for your kids, but make
sure it's not a substitute for creating family bonds, dialogue,
trust and the real security parents are looking for to make their
kids responsible grownups.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret to finding a proper balance, Mountrose says, depends
on the child. The other part depends on whether the parents are
leading a healthy life or only sacrificing for their child.
</P>
<P>
   When the push for more and more activity seems to come from kids
themselves, rather than their parents, though, the results are
usually happy.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Luper, 17, of the Fort Worth suburb of Hurst, is Exhibit
A.
</P>
<P>
   He is vice president of the senior class council and Fellowship
of Christian Athletes, plays on the L.D. Bell High School football
team and belongs to various other committees and sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always stuff,'' says his mother, Karen Luper, who
added that Kevin's day sometimes starts as early as 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Luper said that she is happy that her son is involved with so
many positive things. Although she sometimes worries whether he's
putting himself under too much stress, ``he seems to thrive on
it,'' she says. ``These are Kevin's choices.''
</P>
<P>
   For some families, though, letting go of the mind-boggling
assortment of activities is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of trying to juggle soccer, basketball,
horseback riding and softball, Jennifer Baspeds and her husband and
their daughters are tuckered out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing soccer this semester at all,'' says the
Kennedale mother.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only activity on the schedule for Basped's two
daughters is English horseback riding _ once a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't scheduled that yet, but it will be on the same day,
at the same time, and that will do it for us until after
Christmas,'' Basped says. ``I'm elated.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Mountrose's ``Tips and Tools for Getting Thru to Kids''
may be purchased for $12.95 by calling (800) 929-7889 or from the
Web at www.gettingthru.org.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
