<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: ALL AT ONCE, OUTPOURINGS OF ASIAN ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It's almost too much,'' said Jim Lally, a Manhattan
dealer who specializes in Chinese works of art, discussing the many
events scheduled for Asia Week, the name given by New York auction
houses and dealers to this week's sales of Asian art, which end
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lally, who said he would do his show in March, said it was
exhausting to view the previews, then to attend five days of Asian
sales at Doyle's, Christie's and Sotheby's in addition to seeing
special exhibitions at private galleries like Alvin Lo on East 57th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 70 exhibitors from the United States, Europe, Asia
and Australia are selling antiques at the Arts of Pacific Asia
Show, which runs through Saturday at the 69th Regiment Armory at
26th Street and Lexington Avenue. And on Sunday aficionados of
Asian art head to Washington for the opening of a National Gallery
of Art show, ``The Golden Age of Chinese Archeology: Celebrated
Discoveries From the People's Republic of China,'' which runs
through Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In New York there has been a wealth of Asian furniture and works
of art for sale this week, the same week that the World Monuments
Fund, a nonprofit group that raises money to save cultural sites,
released its new list of the 100 most endangered sites around the
world, 21 of which are in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the auctions show is the magnitude of cultural resources
of China,'' said Bonnie Burnham, president of the fund. ``What
we're pointing out is what neglect China's cultural sites find
themselves in.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``There is extraordinary material on the market
at the moment. Our list shows incredible material in advanced
states of decay. There is a tradition of neglect in China, but the
Chinese are now working to preserve what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the interesting works in the fine-furniture department
this week were several showstoppers and several sleepers that
Christie's was offering.
</P>
<P>
   The most amusing is the ultimate in portable furniture, a rare
folding, reclining armchair from the 17th century, usually called a
``drunken lord's chair.'' It is a version of a West Indian
planter's chair.
</P>
<P>
   Antique Chinese furniture is made without nails, and this chair
comes apart to the extent that it folds flat enough to carry under
your arm. It is made of huanghuali, the most revered Chinese
hardwood, which is difficult to carve, and is highly polished,
perhaps too highly. The serpentine wooden armrests, anchored by
tenons, easily flip up, allowing the seat and the back to go flat.
The headrest folds down beneath nicely carved dragon-head finials
on the top rail. And the footrest folds flat.
</P>
<P>
   While the handsome brass decorations on the top rail are not
original, said Theow-Huang Tow, the international director of
Chinese works of art for Christie's, the brass decorations on the
side and the iron cross bar are original. There are few traces of
wear on the armrests and the footrest, but there are traces of red
lacquer on the bottom, which means that it might once have been
lacquered.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the chair is as comfortable as it is beautiful,
unlike a Chinese scholar's chair, which is all form and no
function.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Chinese screens were once considered an
obligatory element in a fine traditional decor, especially one by
Sister Parish, Mario Buatta or Mark Hampton. There were two
remarkable screens at Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   The first has 12 panels and is nearly 11 feet tall. Made of
huanghuali, the screen has upper and lower panels with openwork.
The top panels have incised decorations, mostly pictures of
precious scholar's objects. Tow said the space between the top and
bottom panels, now covered in plain, cream-colored cloth, probably
would have once displayed calligraphy or landscape paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The second piece, a Coromandel lacquer screen, also has 12
panels. It dates from the Qing Dynasty and was made during the
reign of Emperor Kangxi, who spurred his imperial workshops to make
the best possible examples of glass, porcelain, textiles and
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Although made in China, Coromandel screens were named for
English East India Co.'s port on the Coromandel coast of India, a
post on the way to the West, through which the screens were
shipped. The screens often portray scenes of courtly life at a
gentleman's villa, Tow said.
</P>
<P>
   This one is unusual because it is done in brown, not black,
lacquer. It also has a long dedication in Chinese on the back,
which says it was presented to Magistrate Tian in Fujian in 1687 on
his birthday and commissioned by 30 emissaries, magistrates and
administrators. The screen is signed and stamped with the seal of
an official of the Imperial Academy who composed the text.
</P>
<P>
   The carvings on the piece tell a story almost the way a comic
book does. Inside its deep border are scenes of celebration at a
wealthy man's house. The gentleman is on a dais in the center of a
large open pavilion, in front of a ceremonial screen.
</P>
<P>
   A large man, elaborately dressed, he sits in a yoke-back chair,
a symbol of power, with two attendants holding giant banners behind
him. From his perch, he can view his gardens and see his guests as
they approach on covered walkways.
</P>
<P>
   Other carvings depict the ladies of the house, off in a separate
reception hall. Each carries her own symbol of wealth or power,
like a scepter. As the guests arrive, and grooms attend to the
horses, some women dance. Two children watch a cockfight without
disturbing a pet deer.
</P>
<P>
   Above this picture, in the border on top, the artist has laid
out a series of the items of value that a gentleman owned: hand
scrolls, brush pots, an incense burner, a vase of peacock feathers
and a piece of coral. Below that is a menagerie of real and
mythological animals, including tigers, buffalo and dragons, which
are auspicious symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, much of the furniture and objets d'art shown on
the screen was displayed next door this week at Christie's
showroom: lacquered straw boxes, large wooden brush holders and
several pieces of furniture. All were for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The least pretentious, but totally elegant, piece of furniture
at Christie's was a small huanghuali side table, only 32 inches
high and 28 inches across. Nick Grindley, a London dealer,
pronounced its proportions perfect.
</P>
<P>
   It had a slight ridge at the edge of the top, called a
water-stopping molding, and most unusual, a shallow hidden drawer.
Its long, tapering coltish legs ended in small hoof feet.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Flacks, a Manhattan dealer in Chinese furniture,
preferred something else _ a simple huanghuali Ming bench with a
soft mat seat and high hoof feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely right in every way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lally, who rarely buys furniture, said, ``It's the star of the
show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
