<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Sept. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After dumping flooding rains of 3 to 10 inches over a large area
from eastern Virginia to New England on Thursday, the remnants of
Hurricane Floyd will move steadily away from the Northeastern
states Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will end Friday morning in the New England states from
southwest to northeast. Showers will linger in the northern
mountains through much of the afternoon. Strong winds from the
northwest averaging 20 to 30 miles an hour with higher gusts will
accompany the return to drier air in the wake of the storm. Most of
the interior Northeast will have ample sunshine, although some
puffy cumulus clouds will form near the Appalachians. Afternoon
temperatures will be within a few degrees of the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   After a cool dawn, abundant sunshine will boost temperatures to
comfortably warm levels this afternoon in most of the South.
Humidity will be low except over southern Florida, where the return
of tropical moisture will promote widely scattered thundershowers.
Very warm air will surge into the northern Plains as winds from the
southwest combine with plentiful sunshine. Farther south, clouds
and a few showers will linger from the eastern slopes of the
southern Rockies to western parts of Oklahoma and Texas as moist
winds ascend the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Generally dry and warm weather with abundant sunshine will cover
most areas west of the Rockies. A few afternoon thunderstorms will
form over the mountains of northern Arizona, eastern Nevada and
southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Foreshadowing Floyd &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the wettest day on record at Wilmington, N.C., yet
much of the rain fell when Hurricane Floyd was more than 200 miles
from the city. The daily total was 13.38 inches, smashing the
previous record for 24-hour rainfall of 9.52 inches set in
September 1938. The rain began late Tuesday as tropical air ahead
of the hurricane surged into the Carolinas. A nearby stalled front
became the focus for showers to develop along. This was related to
the hurricane's movement, but was an indirect effect. Thursday, the
Northeast Coast was soaked in a similar way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-LINDBERGH17-COX     09-16 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LINDBERGH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Under A Wing' daughter's loving memoir of growing up a
Lindbergh
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Two years ago, Reeve Lindbergh _ youngest child
and second daughter of the famed aviator _ got up close and
personal with the Spirit of St. Louis for the first time. During
off hours, a cherry picker hoisted Lindbergh and son Ben within
touching distance of the plane, which hangs suspended from the
ceiling of the Smithsonian's National Air and Space Museum. ``I
touched the plane, put my hand on the handle,'' Lindbergh recalled,
and for one transcendent moment, she was transported to 1927 and to
one of the century's great adventures _ an adventure that
determined her own fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Ben,'' she raved, ``this is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' the boy enthusiastically replied. ``I've never
been in a cherry picker before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh laughed, realizing that her children _ from Ben's
spirit of living in the moment to the dimple in the chin of
daughter Susannah, born months after Charles Lindbergh's death in
1974 _ bring her closer to her father than any airplane ever could.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so much like him,'' she recalled. ``My father lived
very much in the now.'' So much so that she could never prevail
upon him to talk about his trans-Atlantic flight: ``If you asked
him about it, he would laugh and say, 'Read my book; it took me 17
years to write it.'''
</P>
<P>
   You won't find the cherry-picker anecdote in Lindbergh's 1998
memoir, ``Under A Wing'' (Delta, $12.95), but the story is typical
of the book's insightfulness and frequent tone of amused affection.
</P>
<P>
   This is a decidedly untrendy memoir in this post-``Mommy
Dearest'' period. Wouldn't the payoff have been greater had she
written a whiny volume about an overbearing, often absent father?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' Lindbergh, 53, protested, ``I was well cared for, and
warmly and kindly raised by my parents. I loved the way they
created a family in spite of everything they endured. As we look
back on the older generation, our children are looking back on us,
so it behooves us to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh nonetheless speaks unflinchingly about her parents,
from her father's controversial pre-WWII isolationism to her
mother's recently revealed affair with her physician in the '50s.
But her lyrically written memoir brims over with admiration and
love and gratitude, crediting her parents' remarkable partnership
with creating ``a family structure that became the strongest
element in their lives ... and the strongest element in mine.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child and young woman, Lindbergh couldn't be bothered with
reading her mother's books. As an adult, she cherishes them as a
way of bringing her closer to her mother, now 93, after a series of
small strokes has made communication more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   And she has followed her mother's example not only as a writer
but as a memoirist. Although she has written novels and continues
to write children's books, she has a stronger sense than ever of
her adult voice. ``Working with family material is what I'm most
interested in and what I do best,'' she said. ``I do my writing in
a sense to pay tribute and also to understand, to figure it out for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh was born in 1945, decades removed from both her
father's flight and the tragic 1932 kidnapping of the brother she
never knew, Charles Jr. (She first learned about the kidnapping by
reading a Life magazine retrospective.) Lindbergh, who was born
gregarious, concedes she was often frustrated by her parents'
compulsive reclusiveness: ``I could not understand why he could not
sign autographs and meet people. My father would leave restaurants
when people would recognize him, and I thought, 'What a pain.' I
thought it was all about him. Now I realize it was all about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh lives on a farm in St. Johnsbury, Vt., with her writer
husband, Nathaniel Tripp. Her mother, who lives nearby, inspired
her to write as a child and continues to be an inspiration today.
``My mother was always writing, and she believed if you had
anything interesting to say, you had a moral and aesthetic
obligation to write it down. And my father always told me, when you
write it, use permanent ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh admires A. Scott Berg's landmark biography
``Lindbergh,'' which recently won the Pulitzer Prize, in spite of
such intensely personal revelations as Anne Morrow Lindbergh's
affair in the '50s with her physician and friend, Dr. Dana Atchley.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Lindbergh discounted sister Anne's belief that their
mother had an affair, protesting, ``They're too old.'' Today, she
has accepted the probability: ``Both of these men are dead. My
father, lovely as he was, was difficult and just gone much of the
time. Immoral person that I am, I personally think it was a
wonderful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh said her mother, who gave Berg unlimited access to her
husband's thousands of boxes of papers, isn't aware the biography
reveals the affair. When her son Land asked her opinion of Berg's
562-page tome, Anne Morrow Lindbergh delivered one of the pithiest
pieces of recent literary criticism: ``It's very heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   When he asked what she thought of all this new attention to her
late husband, she replied, ``I'm for Lindbergh.''
</P>
<P>
   Land raised his glass and said, ``I'm for Lindbergh, too,'' and
mother and son shared a toast.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Reeve Lindbergh said, is more lucid today than
several years ago, when she was disoriented by a stroke: ``She
tends to be monosyllabic, but she does tend to be on the mark.''
</P>
<P>
   And her response to her daughter's book? ``She said it was about
a fearless heroine,'' Lindbergh said.
</P>
<P>
   The remark is true, she added, if her mother applied it to
herself. Her mother sustained her not only through the loss of her
sister Anne to cancer in 1994, but through the loss of a son nearly
10 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most moving chapters is ``The Lost Baby,'' a saga of
intergenerational loss and courage. One morning, while staying at
her mother's house in Connecticut, Reeve Lindbergh went to wake up
her 2-year-old son, Jonathan, and found him dead. (He suffered a
seizure related to infant encephalitis.) Her first impulse was ``to
scream and run from the room _ anywhere, everywhere,'' but her
mother begged her not to do it, Lindbergh wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw my child's body, after he died,'' she said to me,
sitting beside me in my chair and beside Jonathan's still body in
his crib. ``I never sat with my son this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lindbergh wrote, she might ``run, flee, shriek, explode,
tear the world apart.'' But at that moment, instead, ``we were
sitting together, my mother and I, sitting quietly next to that
crib in that house, not with one dead baby, but with two.''
</P>
<P>
   For her mother, the experience was ``just a terrible, terrible
echo,'' Lindbergh said. ``She was extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinary. It's a word often used to evoke Charles
Lindbergh's life in all its remarkable phases, from aviation to
conservation.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeve Lindbergh likes to think less of the ways her father
was unusual than the ways he was ``very representative of this
country and this century,'' she said. ``He came out of the agrarian
past, and jumped into the technological age, and he brought with
him the strengths and weaknesses of the technological age,'' she
said. ``He grew tremendously; he became very open and
philosophical, and I give him great credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
