<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COWARD-CENTENNIAL-2TA     09-16 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWARD-CENTENNIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOEL COWARD CENTENNIAL APPROACHES: A BLITHE SPIRIT AS LIFE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never had a nervous breakdown looked so glamorous. It
was one thing to fall to pieces onstage; characters in plays had
been doing that since ``Oedipus Rex.'' But it was something else to
come unglued in exquisite evening clothes while stormily playing
the piano, with a chic little gold box filled with something
illegal in your pocket. Nicky Lancaster might be a petulant,
mother-fixated egotist, prone to hysterics and addicted to drugs,
but it was impossible not to be mad about the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was Noel Coward propelled into the fame that he would wear
with such satisfied crispness for the rest of his life. He was 24
then, almost exactly as old as the 20th century, and starring in
his own drama ``The Vortex,'' which had only barely squeaked past
the government censors. Tout le beau monde of London trekked to the
Hampstead theater in which ``The Vortex'' opened: le beau monde was
shocked; le beau monde was thrilled. The venerable matinee idol
Gerald du Maurier lamented, ``The younger generation are knocking
at the door of the dustbin.'' The novelist Stella Gibbons would
later recall of Coward's appearance in the play, ``He seems to me
incarnate the myth of the '20s (gaiety, courage, pain concealed,
amusing malice).''
</P>
<P>
   Soon to follow was the inevitable West End transfer, bolstered
by panting newspaper and magazine articles on this thoroughly
modern star who, though scarcely the self-destructive lotus eater
of his play, knew it couldn't hurt for people to think he was.
Photographs appeared of Coward in bed, wearing (in his own words)
``a Chinese dressing gown and an expression of advanced
degeneracy.'' Suddenly men of all classes were dressing and talking
like Coward, all ``sleek and satiny'' as Cecil Beaton described it,
and a new kind of celebrity _ sharp, shiny and supremely
self-conscious _ had slid into the public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   A character in ``The Vortex'' says of the ``divinely selfish''
Nicky, with prophetic reference to the young man who conceived and
portrayed him, ``I'm quite sure Nicky will be happy as long as he
goes around attracting people; he loves being attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel Coward, the playwright, actor, composer, fiction writer and
cabaret star who would have turned 100 on Dec. 16, did indeed love
being attractive. It was an essential part of his art, and in his
later years he could never understand the young actors who made a
point of looking unkempt. Star quality, as the critic Kenneth Tynan
wrote, was Coward's Holy Grail, a trait of which he said happily,
``I don't know what it is, but I know I've got it.'' And to allow
stellar light to dim or tarnish was to him a grave act of
irresponsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrations surrounding the Coward centennial this fall,
which range from film and television festivals to New York
productions of two of his late works (``Waiting in the Wings,''
``Noel Coward in Two Keys''), bear witness to the staying power of
this impeccably maintained persona. They also speak of the stamina
of a man who entered show business as an 11-year-old child actor
and never really left it until his death in 1973, refusing to let
his public image sag even as his critical and popular reputations
yo-yoed exasperatingly.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the key features of that image had been engraved in
Coward's epochal appearance in ``The Vortex,'' a production he
chose to have mounted over another property he had ready, the
delicious (and far superior) ``Hay Fever,'' because he knew it
would make a bigger noise. Later writing of that time in the memoir
``Future Indefinite,'' Coward said: ``All that was important for
monotonous future reference was the created image _ the talented,
neurotic, sophisticated playboy. ... It still exists today, with
the slight modification that I am now an aging playboy.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also essential distinctions to be made between Nicky
and Noel. Nicky Lancaster was the victim of what Coward described
in song as ``those 20th-century blues,'' the malaise that settled
on the youth of Britain after the First World War. Coward was the
victorious manipulator of that same sensibility, the chronicler of
a flaming hedonism that he never allowed to consume his own talent.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs, by the way, were anathema to him; as his longtime
assistant Cole Lesley wrote, he had ``an absolute horror of losing
control of his senses.'' This meant that love, whose predations
Coward documented so wryly in plays like ``Private Lives,'' was
always regarded as dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   For all its attention-grabbing sensationalism, ``The Vortex''
was less subversive and more puritanical than the great,
``lighter'' comedies for which Coward became best known. ``The
Vortex'' morally condemned its two most charismatic characters:
Nicky and his vain, professionally beautiful mother, Florence.
</P>
<P>
   In works like ``Hay Fever,'' ``Private Lives,'' ``Design for
Living'' and ``Present Laughter,'' glamour would be equated not
with decadence but with vitality. Glamour becomes a life force,
bringing light and animation to a drab, gray world of outmoded
values. Life in Coward's urbane comedies of manners (as opposed to
his more sentimental and patriotic plays in which the middle and
lower classes figure) can be divided into those who have it and
those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, the characters in ``Hay Fever,'' revived
this summer in London under Declan Donnellan's direction. The
members of the Bliss family, at whose country home the play is set,
are both insufferable and irresistible. Headed by the actress
Judith Bliss and her woolgathering novelist of a husband, the clan
is self-obsessed, self-indulgent and self-dramatizing. But everyone
else in the play at least temporarily falls in love with them, and
they are undoubtedly of that breed who whenever they enter a room,
to paraphrase Coward, raise its temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Elyot and Amanda, the divorced couple in Coward's
masterwork, ``Private Lives'' (recently produced at the Royal
National Theater in London), who have the misfortune to reunite
during their honeymoons with two other people. Despite the
ferocious incompatibility that regularly leads them to blows and
tantrums, Elyot and Amanda, in parts fitted on Coward and his
lifelong friend Gertrude Lawrence, are made for each other.
</P>
<P>
   They speak the same glittering language, in which the frivolous
becomes dead serious and vice versa, and their poor, utterly
conventional new spouses can't begin to understand them. That
Amanda's marriage to the handsome, prosaic Victor is doomed is
evident once he says to her, ``I'm glad I'm normal,'' and Amanda
answers: ``What an odd thing to be glad about. Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like elitism? Of course it does. But it's
important to note that the particular snobbery of these plays isn't
based on traditional notions of class. Coward and Lawrence, child
actors both, were scarcely products of upper-class backgrounds. The
emblems of brittle, whimsical sophistication they became were
willed, artificial constructs that could accommodate even Coward's
homosexuality in a society where it was still a jailable offense.
The title ``Design for Living'' says it all.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The sexually ambiguous trio of that comedy (written for and
first enacted by Coward, Alfred Lunt and Lynn Fontanne) love, fight
and recouple into various combinations. But they aren't allowed to
settle into a happy menage a trois until they have all become
wildly successful in their different artistic fields (play writing,
painting, decorating).
</P>
<P>
   By the play's end they represent an aristocracy of freshly
minted stars, set in relief by the stodgy socialites that surround
them. Their rules are their own, and they ply them with blithe
arrogance. One thinks of the playwright John Osborne, an angry
young man of a later age, when he described Coward's self-invention
as his great contribution to the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Coward was a sucker for real royalty. (He became great chums
with both the Queen Mother and Princess Margaret.) Yet it was his
self-invented characters who established the new conversational
tone for fashionable society _ sprinkled with ``darlings,''
``divines'' and a host of ironic superlatives _ that endures today.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mistake to dismiss Coward-speak as merely shallow.
There's a very modern bravado in the frivolity, a sense of people
gallantly waving sparklers in a newly darkened world. As Elyot
famously says to Amanda during a discussion of death: ``Let's be
superficial and pity the poor philosophers. Let's blow trumpets and
squeakers, and enjoy the party as much as we can, like very small,
idiotic schoolchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the works of Oscar Wilde (whom Coward described as ``a
tiresome, affected sod''), in which filigree elegance becomes an
end in itself, Coward's plays implicitly place bright archness over
a limbo ungoverned by any knowable god. He specialized in profound
superficiality. This may be why his comedies never translated very
well into Hollywood films in a country that prefers superficial
profundity, evidenced by the sort of spiritual and self-help books
found on best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Tynan went so far as to argue that Coward's dialogue anticipated
that of Harold Pinter, citing the resonant line from Coward's
``Shadow Play'': ``Small talk, a lot of small talk, with other
thoughts going on behind.'' (It makes sense that in the 1950s, when
Coward was railing against the kitchen-sink dramatists, he had
praise for Pinter, ``at least a genuine original.'') Tynan also
provided a wonderful summary of Coward's contribution to the
language of the theater: ``Coward took the fat off English comic
dialogue: he was the Turkish bath in which it slimmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement hints at the discipline that informed every aspect
of Coward's life. It extended from his writing habits to his rigid
insistence, when directing, that his actors know their lines on the
first day of rehearsal; from his clipped, staccato delivery of his
own songs and dialogue to the careful presentation of his public
self. ``I take ruthless stock of myself in the mirror before going
out,'' he told Beaton.
</P>
<P>
   Elements that might erode this discipline were to be avoided if
possible. Sexual attraction was perceived as an anarchic force,
probably doubly so given Coward's status as a gay man in England in
the early part of this century. ``I am no good at love,'' went one
of his song lyrics. And in his 50s he wrote in his diary of a
current infatuation, ``All the gallant lyrics of all the songs I
have ever written rise up and mock me.'' This clash of order and
romantic chaos is an abiding theme in his plays, from ``Private
Lives'' and ``Blithe Spirit'' to the wistful ``Song at Twilight,''
in which he made his last appearance as a stage actor.
</P>
<P>
   His public rarely saw him in any sort of disarray. The Coward it
knew was the jaunty, waspish and eternally sleek star of the
cabaret acts he began in the 1950s. ``One's inside self is a
private place and should always stay like that,'' he once said.
Tantrums, depressions, doubts: the display of these was reserved
for the intimate surrogate family of assistants, friends and his
companion of decades, the actor Graham Payn.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Design for Living,'' the playwright Leo describes life as
``a question of masks, really; brittle, painted masks.'' He
continues, ``We all wear them as a form of protection; modern life
forces us to.'' Knowing that you're wearing a mask inevitably leads
to a certain self-detachment, which may be the most modern element
of all in the Coward mystique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always acting, watching myself go by,'' says Garry
Essendine, Coward's alter ego, in ``Present Laughter.'' As this
century ends, with a renewed emphasis on the conscious manipulation
of style and image, Coward seems especially pertinent. Certainly he
anticipated the current crop of chic, irony-wrapped, androgynous
young movie stars and pop idols.
</P>
<P>
   These descendants might also do well to follow the master's lead
in self-deprecation. As the novelist Rebecca West wrote of Coward,
after lamenting his colossal narcissism and addiction to applause:
``His sensitivity knew this and was shocked, and he regularly
rough-housed his own vanity by considering himself in a ridiculous
light. This he did for the good of his soul.''
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL EVENTS:
</P>
<P>
   A host of events marking the 100th anniversary of the birth of
Noel Coward is planned in New York City this year. ``Mad About the
Boy: Noel Coward on Film,'' a 10-part screening series, begins
Friday and runs through Oct. 21 in the Rose Cinemas at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music. During the same weeks ``Mad About the Boy: Noel
Coward on Television,'' a five-part screening series, will be at
the Museum of Television and Radio. From Sept. 23 to Oct. 5 the
Museum of Modern Art will present the Billy Rose Tribute to Noel
Coward, a film retrospective. Beginning on Nov. 3 his musical
``Sail Away'' will be presented at Weill Recital Hall. In December
``Noel Coward in Two Keys,'' a pair of one-acts, will be performed
(theater and dates to be announced). On Dec. 1 a special
performance sponsored by the Mabel Mercer Foundation is planned at
Carnegie Hall. Previews begin on Dec. 3 at the Walter Kerr Theater
of his comedy ``Waiting in the Wings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
