<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4829 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-KIDSHEAVEN17-COX     09-16 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KIDSHEAVEN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gray's latest offers parenting tips
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In John Gray's universe, men are from Mars, women are
from Venus, children are from heaven, and parents are ... well,
parents are just overwhelmed and confused.
</P>
<P>
   Some moms and dads try to be buddies with their children, then
wonder why the kids won't behave. Some act like prison wardens to
maintain order, then worry that their kids aren't creative enough.
Finding middle ground between hard and soft parenting seems
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where Gray fits in. Or at least his new, common-sense,
``positive-parenting'' guide, ``Children Are From Heaven'' (Harper
Collins, $25.95, 357 pages).
</P>
<P>
   The way the author of the best-selling ``Men Are From Mars,
Women Are From Venus'' sees it, parents need take only five easy
steps to give children the freedom to ``discover and express their
true selves.'' Children are always going to resist guidance, says
Gray, a family therapist, but there are ways to manage that
avalanche of rebellion without turning the home into Devil's
Island. He says:
</P>
<P>
   _ Let children be different. This will allow them to develop
their ``unique inner potential and purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Let them make mistakes. Children who correct themselves will
better learn from their missteps.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tell children it's OK to express negative emotions. According
to Gray, this will teach them to manage their emotions and develop
a ``feeling awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tell children it's OK to want more. They will develop a
healthy sense of what they deserve and learn to delay
gratification.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give them permission to resist parents' guidance. Doing so
will help children develop a better sense of themselves, and by
learning to manage a child's resistance, parents stay in control
while also giving their child freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Now, wasn't that easy? Gray seems to think it is. And here's
another easy fix: Trim the hours kids spend watching TV. Parents
rely too much on the boob tube at a time when they need desperately
to interact with their children, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of parents try to parent and get all this resistance, so
they just park their kids in front of a video or a TV set and
there's, like, this nice six hours of calm in the house, so they
assume everything is fine,'' he said. ``A lot of parents have no
idea what goes on inside their children's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Parenting styles today are a convoluted mess inspired by
previous generations, Gray says. Parents who are too soft are most
likely avoiding the hard-as-nails approach of their own parents.
Others get tough because their own parents were soft and didn't
pass along skills for managing their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a kind of environment that embraces all of these
different freedoms,'' Gray said. ``Let's just come forward and
acknowledge that we want to give these to our children. And yet, to
balance that so our children will be healthy and whole, we need
strict control.''
</P>
<P>
   So, strictness is OK in moderation, as long as it's not too
strict. Gray uses the example of a parent with a 7-year-old who
doesn't want to wear a jacket to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some parents say, OK, let the child experience the
consequences of not wearing a jacket instead of going through what
it takes to make the child wear the jacket,'' he said. ``What this
child experiences is that not only are they not prepared to meet
the challenges of the world, but they feel they can't trust their
parents to protect them as well. Children need to feel a dependence
on their parents and that they can depend on their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   So, at whom is this book aimed _ good parents who want to do
better or mediocre moms and dads who don't have a clue and have
never bought a parenting guide?
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope with this book is that parents who wouldn't normally
realize that they need help would hear from other parents or
teachers that this is a helpful manual,'' Gray said. ``Parents are
recognizing that what they're doing isn't working and they're
looking for answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
