r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN17-COX     09-16 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LCRA water fight fodder for the Legislature
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In brief remarks to the crowd gathered for Sen.
Gonzalo Barrientos' re-election announcement last week, Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry said this: ``I've learned that of the 31 members who
serve in the Texas Senate, this man has the toughest
constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Barrientos said one of the reasons _ but not the
only one _ he is running again is ``because the Austin City Council
needs me.''
</P>
<P>
   There was more laughter.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a state secret that legislative reaction to Austin
and its hyper-political citizenry runs the gamut from bemusement to
contempt. Austin bashing is popular sport, supported for fun and
profit by lobbyists with an array of clients with a variety of
interests. The curious nature of municipal politics keeps Austin's
enemies stocked with eye-rolling anecdotes they gleefully relay to
an audience that can't get enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   What's keeping them in yucks lately is the microscopic analysis
of the water deal offered by the Lower Colorado River Authority.
While Austinites insist on worshiping at the altar of process,
legislators and others around the state are once again shaking
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Tell anyone outside of Austin that the council is balking at
securing a 50-year supply of water at a 30 percent discount and
they'll look at you as if you were from the planet Zotz.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal is said to have majority council support, the
doubts raised about it and the delay in signing the deal makes
people who would jump at the deal wonder what's wrong with us.
</P>
<P>
   Should the support erode, they won't wonder any more.
</P>
<P>
   I asked an influential member of the Legislature how members
would react if Austin booted the water deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody would say anything right away,'' he
drawled, ``but six or so years from now, when you come to the
Legislature asking to bail you out, we'd tell you what we told
Corpus Christi and San Antonio: 'You had your chance, so (action
verb) you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked the same question, another influential member couldn't
stop laughing at first, then declined, saying between guffaws that
he didn't want to be perceived as meddling in local affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of office bring legislators to town between sessions
more often, so they are getting more than the biennial dose of the
local charm these days.
</P>
<P>
   Process is ingrained in the local political culture. Nothing
moves in a hurry, and people are quick to express their effrontery
if they have even the slightest notion that they've been excluded
from something whether they have anything constructive to add or
not. It's a wonder they have time, though, given their regular and
lengthy attendance at the Temple of Righteous Indignation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rate of participation in local elections is low,
local politicians are hesitant to offend any constituent group that
claims a membership of more than five. So, we do process. Political
junkies love those meetings. True story: I once heard a member of
an advisory board say that she didn't allow her children to play
war games. Instead, she taught them how to play meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, it's the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could just learn to tell the Legislature, 'Yeah,
we're different. In the way that East Texas is different and in the
same way that the Valley is different,''' sighed a political
consultant. ``But, instead we use that corruption language'' in
communicating with legislators who don't see things in the ``Austin
way.'' We just love to tell them off.
</P>
<P>
   And legislators just love it when we do. It gives them something
to write about every couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   A modest prediction: This ongoing hand wringing over the LCRA
deal is going to result in a miracle. It has the potential of
turning water into ink.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
