r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN17-COX     09-16 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The race for Perry's job _ if we need a race
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The race to be the next lieutenant governor is
on _ despite an effort by one of the Senate's most respected
members to keep it from happening.
</P>
<P>
   Factors that may affect who wins include whether senators want
to make the office less powerful; whether the senator chosen would
seek the position at the next election or just be a caretaker; and
whether Gov. George W. Bush, if elected president, might resign as
governor early to help the Republicans hold the lieutenant
governor's position.
</P>
<P>
   The senator openly campaigning is David Sibley of Waco, who is
telling his colleagues he's willing to discuss giving the
lieutenant governor's powers to appoint committees and their chairs
and set the order of legislation to the Senate. He also said he
might serve as lieutenant governor only until the next election and
then seek re-election to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   By actively campaigning, he's ignoring the wishes of good friend
and fellow Republican Bill Ratliff of Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff wrote in a June 3 letter to senators that he feared an
active race could bring the warfare and lingering resentments
typical of races for House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Texas senators have known almost two
years ahead that a vacancy might exist in the lieutenant governor's
office. If Bush wins the presidency in 2000, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry
will become governor.
</P>
<P>
   Should that happen, the Texas Constitution requires the 31
senators meet within 30 days of a vacancy and choose one of their
own to be the acting lieutenant governor, while holding on to the
Senate seat. The senator chosen could decide later whether to run
for election as lieutenant governor or re-election to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff's letter said he would ``consider it the highest
compliment'' if the senators chose him to succeed Perry. But he
strongly counseled against a ``speaker's race'' campaign where
pledges of support are collected.
</P>
<P>
   To do otherwise, Ratliff said Tuesday, could endanger the
collegial environment usually present in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, Republican Teel Bivins of Amarillo followed with a
letter saying he would be ``deeply honored'' if senators chose him
but would not campaign for it.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley, however, sent Ratliff and Bivins letters on Aug. 6,
pledging that while they would remain friends no matter what, he
was concerned that if senators wait until after the November 2000
general election, a ``vacuum'' might develop that would hinder ``a
timely and productive start'' to the the next session of the
Legislature in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Republican J.E. ``Buster'' Brown also would like the job, but
telephoned his colleagues asking them to ``keep their powder dry''
until a vacancy actually occurs. (Brown's chances, other senators
say, weren't helped by a young woman in his district office
recently filing a sexual harassment complaint.)
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jeff Wentworth of San Antonio, caught Tuesday as he
was between planes headed for 12 days in China, said he's talked in
person to about 10 colleagues. While he'd like the job, he said
he's mostly asking senators to avoid diluting the presiding
officer's powers.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth said he wants ``a direct relationship with one
president of the Senate,'' rather than a committee of senators.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican jockeying could be moot if Democrats win a Senate
majority in the next general election. There are 15 of them, to 16
Republicans, and the Democrats could be in the majority if they can
take back the East Texas seat held by Republican Drew Nixon of
Carthage and hold Democrat David Cain's Dallas-to-Tyler seat.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic majority might produce a Democratic lieutenant
governor _ most likely moderate-conservative Ken Armbrister of
Victoria, unless a schism produces a deal crossing party lines that
could go in many different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats interested include Royce West of Dallas and Mike
Moncrief of Fort Worth. But Senate Democratic Caucus Chairman
Gonzalo Barrientos of Austin has also urged his colleagues to
refrain from campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats win a majority, would Bush quit early, so the
current Senate rather than the new one would pick Perry's
successor?
</P>
<P>
   Bush won't say. ``The governor will deal this issue when the
time comes,'' spokeswoman Linda Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
