<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     09-16 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ASTRONAUT'S WIFE,' starring Johnny Depp and Charlize
Theron. Directed by Rand Ravich (R, 100 minutes). Stylish direction
and the heat generated by these two stars can't outweigh the
familiarity of the story line. It concerns an astronaut who returns
to Earth behaving a little strangely. And not for nothing does Ms.
Theron, as the title character, wear the hairdo seen on Mia Farrow
in ``Rosemary's Baby.'' Even creatures in other galaxies can guess
what's coming. Still, the visual style suggests that this
first-time director might fare better with fresher material. And
Depp holds interest by playing the astronaut as one part NASA, two
parts Elvis (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT,' starring Heather Donahue, Michael
Williams and Joshua Leonard. Directed by Daniel Myrick and Eduardo
Sanchez (R, 87 minutes). A horror film shot outdoors by its actors,
who play three scared filmmakers at work on a spooky documentary,
this is a fine example of how to make something out of nothing _
nothing but terrific imagination and a game plan so enterprising it
should elevate its creators to pinup status at film schools
everywhere. With tentacles including a hit Web site, an elaborate
fake witch mythology, a book tie-in, a special on the Sci-Fi
Channel and more, this clever indie is at the center of a new form
of synergy and an inspired multimedia blitz (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BOWFINGER,' starring Steve Martin, Eddie Murphy and Heather
Graham. Written by Martin. Directed by Frank Oz (PG-13, 97
minutes). This hilarious, good-hearted spiritual descendant of
``The Producers'' is a comic coup for Martin. And it's directed by
Oz every bit as winningly as his ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels'' and
``In and Out.'' Murphy is razor sharp in a dual role as both a
grinning fall guy and the kind of hotshot action star whose very
presence is enough to get a movie made. Martin, sublimely funny,
runs circles around him as an unscrupulous filmmaker trying to
trick the star into appearing in his movie. ``Did you know that Tom
Cruise had no idea he was in that vampire movie until two years
later?'' this filmmaker inquires. Made fondly and knowingly, with
nonstop good humor (Maslin). `CHILL FACTOR,' starring Cuba Gooding
Jr. Directed by Hugh Johnson (R, 110 minutes). A deadly chemical
defoliant (military code name Elvis) must be transported to a safe
place across the Montana high country in a rattling ice cream
delivery truck before it falls into the hands of a maniacal traitor
who wants to peddle it on the international market. Gooding,
clowning it up, is the hapless driver. Stale macho jokes and
formulaic cliffhangers drive this chase-by-numbers thriller on the
bumpy road to nowhere (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `EARTH,' starring Aamir Khan, Nandita Das, Rahul Khanna and Maia
Sethna. Directed by Deepa Mehta (Not rated, 99 minutes). It is
1947, and India is about to explode into ethnic violence as British
colonial rule ends and the country is partitioned into two nations,
mostly Hindu India and mostly Muslim Pakistan. These momentous
changes are observed by Lenny (Ms. Sethna), the 8-year-old daughter
of a well-to-do Parsi family in Lahore. As Hindus, Muslims and
Sikhs slaughter one another in the streets, old friends become
deadly enemies. Caught in the middle is Shanta (Ms. Das), Lenny's
beautiful Hindu nanny who has two Muslim suitors. The movie's
child's-eye view somewhat mutes its dramatic sweep (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `DUDLEY DO-RIGHT,' starring Brendan Fraser, Alfred Molina, Sarah
Jessica Parker and Eric Idle. Directed by Hugh Wilson (PG, 90
minutes). Based on the vintage Jay Ward animated series, this
live-action romp tries to be both zany entertainment for children
and nostalgia for those who grew up on Ward's snarky creations
(Rocky, Bullwinkle et al.). And it works pretty well, too. Beyond
the sure-fire goofy presence of Fraser and the comic possibilities
of a Canadian Mountie who rides his horse backward, this jokey romp
has an appealing, try-anything spirit. The characters now use cell
phones. And Ms. Parker's Nell, who formerly spent her time tied to
the railroad tracks, has become a former U.S. ambassador to Guam.
But the formula hasn't lost its fun (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `EYES WIDE SHUT,' starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman.
Directed by Stanley Kubrick (R, 145 minutes). This last cryptic,
spellbinding addition to the Kubrick canon provides a stunning
epiphany for the summer of the dirty joke. It's a dead-serious film
about eros and mortality, one that flirts with the ridiculous but
sustains its fundamental eeriness and gravity throughout. Cruise,
as a doctor caught up in a nighttime sexual odyssey of strange,
dreamlike clarity, and Ms. Kidman, as the wife who sparks his
jealousy by speaking frankly of her own libido, give themselves
over body and soul to the filmmaker's meticulous and delicately
balanced scheme. Given the dark themes and explicit nudity found
here, the R rating, achieved by digital alterations to 65 seconds'
worth of film, is a joke (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE,' starring Shawn Hatosy, Alec Baldwin and
Amy Smart. Written by Peter Farrelly, Bobby Farrelly and Michael
Corrente. Directed by Corrente (R, 95 minutes). Three of Rhode
Island's finest, the director of ``Federal Hill'' and the brothers
behind ``There's Something About Mary,'' collaborate on a rowdily
funny yet also unexpectedly tender coming-of-age tale. This rueful
and very likable comedy tells of a Pawtucket teen-ager who is
abruptly separated from his druggy old cronies and packed off to a
Connecticut prep school, where he is a sharp-eyed observer of the
characters around him. Loosely knit, sometimes uproarious, the film
benefits enormously from Baldwin's deft performance as the boy's
small-minded, memorably impossible father (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED VIOLIN,' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Jason Flemying,
Greta Scacchi and Don McKellar. Directed by Francois Girard (not
rated, 130 minutes). ``The Red Violin'' follows the colorful
300-plus-year journey of a priceless violin from its construction
in an Italian workshop in 1681 to a contemporary auction in
Montreal. As it makes its way from Vienna to England to China, the
instrument becomes the inspiration for some richly photographed
historical tableaux. If the movie's narrative energy is undermined
by a plodding screenplay and wooden acting, the music, composed by
John Corigliano and played by Joshua Bell and the London
Philharmonia Orchestra, is sublime (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `RUNAWAY BRIDE,' starring Julia Roberts and Richard Gere.
Directed by Garry Marshall (PG, 110 minutes). When the stars and
director first collaborated, on ``Pretty Woman,'' Ms. Roberts was
cast as an adorable Los Angeles streetwalker. Nine years later
she's as far as she can get from Rodeo Drive, geographically and
otherwise. Playing the stern proprietor of a small-town Maryland
hardware store, she takes an awfully long while to slip from
scowling into flirtatious romantic-comedy mode. And when the sparks
start flying between her character and Gere's likably stubborn
newspaper columnist, they fly on cue. Funny minor characters and
one-liners offset the not-so-pretty story of a woman who habitually
jilts her men (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
