u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-16 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPIRAL JETTY' GIVEN TO DIA; A LONG-LOST INGRES; '99 CARNEGIE
INTERNATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Spiral Jetty' Given to Dia
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Spiral Jetty,'' Robert Smithson's monumental
Earthwork, has been given to the Dia Center for the Arts by the
artist's estate.
</P>
<P>
   That Dia should become the caretaker of one of Smithson's
greatest works is fitting. ``It's part of Dia's forever mission to
take care of epic projects that don't fall within the normal scope
of a traditional museum,'' said Michael Govan, its director.
</P>
<P>
   The gift helps establish Dia as the center for giant works in
the landscape. It owns Walter De Maria's ``Lightning Field,'' near
Quemado, N.M., which it maintains and makes available to the
public. Dia also provided the initial support for James Turrell's
``Roden Crater'' near Flagstaff, Ariz., and supports Michael
Heizer's work in the Nevada desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiral Jetty,'' created in 1970 on the Great Salt Lake in
Utah, is made of black basalt rocks and earth from the site,
forming a coil 1,500 feet long and 15 feet wide that stretches out
counterclockwise into the lake's translucent red water. ``Spiral
Jetty' is submerged in the lake because it was built when the
lake's water was unnaturally low. Before Smithson died in a plane
crash in 1973, when he was 35, he had considered adding further
material to insure that ``Spiral Jetty'' would be more visible.
</P>
<P>
   Govan said that Dia was studying ways to make ``Spiral Jetty''
more accessible. He also intends to collect and centralize the
historical documents that relate to the project. ``We plan to
acquire other works by Smithson,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dia has scheduled a viewing of a film that the artist made of
the ``Spiral Jetty'' and its making; it will take place on the roof
of Dia's building at 542 W. 22nd St. in Chelsea on Sept. 29 at 7
p.m. The film will also be included in the Whitney Museum of
American Art's exhibition ``The American Century: Part II,
1950-2000,'' which opens Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   A Long-Lost Ingres
</P>
<P>
   When ``Portraits by Ingres: Image of an Epoch'' opens at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art on Oct. 5, it will give viewers a peek
at who was who in France from the last years of the Revolution to
the Second Empire.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the portraits are well known to art historians, a
full-length image of Queen Caroline Murat, Napoleon's youngest
sister, painted in Rome in 1814, is being shown in a museum
exhibition for the first time. Its whereabouts had been unknown for
125 years until a dealer recognized it in a restorer's studio in
Belgium in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The painting shows the queen wearing a hat trimmed with ostrich
feathers, standing in front of the window of her private chamber in
the Palazzo Reale in Naples. It was recorded by the historian and
writer Mario Praz in his 1964 book ``An Illustrated History of
Interior Decoration.''
</P>
<P>
   Praz showed a black and white image of the portrait, along with
other pictures of the queen, to illustrate the decorative
metamorphosis of this part of the palace from Empire decor to
Biedermeier furnishing. But Praz did not know who painted the
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait records an important moment in Ingres' history. For
starters, Ingres was never paid for the portrait, even though it
was completed and delivered to his patron, the queen's husband,
Joachim Murat, because Caroline lost her throne after the Battle of
Waterloo when the French administration was expelled from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Ingres called the painting an ``unhappy success,'' because the
queen was dissatisfied with the way he painted her head and her
hat, which he painted over three times but never successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of Ingres' most enigmatic portraits,'' said Gary
Tinterow, the Englehard curator of European paintings at the Met.
``It is also one of the smallest, most jewel-like of Ingres'
finished portraits, and its aura is heightened because it was even
lost to the artist, who hoped to obtain it for several
exhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Carlier, the Belgian dealer who discovered it, was able
to sell the Ingres portrait to a New York collector, who is now
lending the painting to the exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnegie
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half years and hundreds of visits to artists' studios
have gone into the making of the 1999 Carnegie International, the
survey show of contemporary art that takes place every few years at
the Carnegie Museum of Art in Pittsburgh. The last one, in 1995,
was organized by Richard Armstrong, then a curator of contemporary
art at the Carnegie and now its director. This year's show is
overseen by Madeleine Grynsztejn, who filled Armstrong's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995 the show reflected upon the heritage of Minimalism,''
Ms. Grynsztejn said. ``My concern is with artists at the end of the
millennium and with what constitutes reality in this day and age.''
</P>
<P>
   The show opens Nov. 6 and runs through March 26, featuring the
work of 41 artists from 22 countries. Some are young, emerging
artists; others are well known. The youngest is the American
painter Laura Owens, 29, and the oldest is Alex Katz, 72. ``I felt
a cross-generational conversation was important,'' Ms. Grynsztejn
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the show would also be carefully balanced to include
painting, sculpture, mixed media, film, video and site-specific
installations. ``Each Carnegie International is different because
each reflects its moment in time,'' she added. ``We live in a world
where information circulates at an incredible pace, and this has
had a tremendous effect on the art that is produced.''
</P>
<P>
   An Inaugural Award
</P>
<P>
   To recognize collectors who embody Duncan Phillips' commitment
to encouraging public appreciation of art, the Phillips Collection
in Washington has created an annual award. On Saturday, the first
Duncan Phillips Medal will be given to Leonard Lauder, the
cosmetics magnate and art collector, who is also chairman of the
Whitney Museum of American Art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
