<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Sept. 17. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Josephine Schmidt; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ The scourge of terrorism spread to
Russia's heartland on Thursday, as a massive explosion tore apart
an apartment complex in the southern city of Volgodonsk. At least
18 people were killed and more than 200 wounded when a bomb went
off near a nine-story building. It was the fifth bombing in less
than three weeks and underscored how vulnerable Russia remains to
terrorist attacks despite heightened security. By Michael R.
Gordon. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-PRIVILEGE (Washington) _ Citing executive privilege,
the White House refuses a congressional request for documents
supporting the Puerto Rican clemency decision. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-RDP (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Hurricane Floyd comes ashore
near Cape Fear, N.C., with 110 mph winds, flooding the Carolina
coasts with more than a foot of rain as tens of thousands of people
huddled in shelters. At least seven deaths are blamed on the storm.
More than 480,000 people customers in the Carolinas and Virginia
have lost power. Flooding and power failures combined to shut down
Portsmouth, Va.'s water supply system, which serves 110,000
customers. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (New York) _ Hurricane Floyd brought its fierce
winds and torrents of rain last night to a New York region that was
waiting and well prepared, flooding roads and knocking out some
power but failing to inflict any devastating damage. By David W.
Chen.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY-SCENE (New York) _ To a large extent, the city hid.
It wasn't always clear from what. Sure, Hurricane Floyd was
supposed to roar into town Thursday and topple buildings and
catapult buses over the World Trade Center _ but where was it? The
day the hurricane was due was very much a day of pointed contrasts
in the metropolitan area, with portions of the area being pounded,
while the city itself was tricked by a non-event. By N.R.
Kleinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SHOOTING (Fort Worth) _ Police on Thursday sought a motive
for the nation's latest killing rampage, a shooting spree that
began Wednesday night when a man spewing anti-Baptist rhetoric
burst into a church service for teen-agers and opened fire. Seven
people were fatally shot before the gunman _ identified by police
as Larry Gene Ashbrook _ killed himself at the Wedgwood Baptist
Church. Seven others were wounded, three of them seriously. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
