<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LANDLORD WHO REMEMBERS RENTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Sept. 23)  
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some property owners may forget how it is to be a renter, to
walk into empty rooms with white walls and beige carpeting and
space for a garden out front and to declare it perfect.
</P>
<P>
   And then, because there are more than a hundred others before
you, to have to go back to the classifieds, the phone, the map and
start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   A woman whose name we'll change to Mary remembers her own days
of renting, so when she put an ad in the newspaper for a
two-bedroom, one-bath townhouse at the low Sonoma County, Calif.,
price of $725, she started feeling guilty almost from the
beginning, knowing she was bound to disappoint many people.
</P>
<P>
   She deliberately kept it low, because she says, ``I know how
hard it is to find a decent place, and I'm not in it for the
profit. People told me I could get $800, $825 or more, but I
deplore the horrible high rates.'' The phone kept ringing. Her
message machine filled. She heard from about 160 people in two
days. ``This is crazy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Mary go through her stack of applications, telling
stories about the people she was going to have to call and say
``sorry'' to, it is clear that the landlord business is not for the
soft-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people told me what a wonderful deal this was, that
they'd been looking for so long, that even some $900 apartments are
dumps. Or they're not in safe neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of greed out there. One retired woman
said she lives in fear that her landlord will raise the rent just
because he knows he can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma County is a desirable spot, in large part because of its
diversity, Mary says, but how diverse or desirable is any place
that prices itself above people with marginal incomes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's our sense of reality? Most people are working class.''
</P>
<P>
   She looks at her list and asks, ``Do we want to lose people like
this?'' They include retail clerks, a warehouse manager, a
beginning acupuncturist, a social worker, a nonprofit agency office
worker, a customer service representative.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a full-time college student married to an agricultural
worker with a baby and a brother who would help share the rent.
Here's a pensioner who supplements by doing in-home care for an
elderly patient. A single mother who moved her two kids into an
$850 apartment and right back out because the owner refused to
clean it as promised. A working pair with a sick child whose
grandmother promised $500 a month toward the rent.
</P>
<P>
   Mary remembers a time when the rule was that housing should be
no more than a quarter of a family's income. But who, she wonders,
can do that today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any idea how many young people have already been
through bankruptcy? People are living on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary, a physical therapist, rented until she was 40, mostly in
San Francisco. She's familiar with the routine, ``staying with
friends while you look for someplace that you can afford and isn't
a dump.''
</P>
<P>
   She bought her place 15 years ago, qualifying as a low-income
buyer. She lived there for a while and then married. Now she lives
in a much larger house with her husband, and money is not the issue
it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, ``Doesn't $800 seem like a lot?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we want to become just a haven for the rich.
Working people are what ground a community. If we lose them, we
lose a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. We lose artists and poets, people who work for
public radio, beginning teachers who can't afford to live in the
same town as their students.
</P>
<P>
   We create child-care hassles, long commutes, stressed-out
families needing two jobs, two cars.
</P>
<P>
   Mary has a good friend who works as a massage therapist,
massages AIDS patients for free and struggles to pay her $700 rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of an old Marxist,'' Mary says. ``I ask myself, why
we need so much and so many?''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of a week Mary had chosen. Her new tenant is a single
woman who works for a foundation that helps families in crisis. She
goes to the same church as Mary's brother-in-law and heard about
the house from him. Mary feels a little guilty for taking what she
considers ``the easy way out,'' but hopes the woman lives there for
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like being in the rental business,'' Mary says. ``I
get too involved.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
