<SLUG> BC-BOX-DE-LA-HOYA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATURDAY'S FIGHT WILL DEFINE OSCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LOWELL COHN   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Don King opened his big mouth on Wednesday. Don King
opens his big mouth every day, but Wednesday was special even for
him.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final, ultra-deluxe press conference for Saturday's
so-called ``Fight of the Millennium'' between Oscar De La Hoya and
Felix Trinidad. King, who is the promoter for Trinidad, had
something to say to Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet you a million dollars,'' King shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Arum considered the proposal with a face so sour he looked as if
he'd just sucked on a lemon. Then Arum launched into a long sermon
about the evils of gambling, explaining that he would fire anyone
from his company who bet on fights.
</P>
<P>
   He said this to hundreds of reporters dying to dash out to the
craps tables.
</P>
<P>
   He said this in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, no one was persuaded. But one thing was clear.
King had called Arum's bluff, or to use the language of the
streets, he'd told Arum, ``Put your money where your mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   King's dare was generally seen as a victory for his fighter over
De La Hoya. Or to put it another way: Arum's refusal to ante up the
cash was perceived as a vote of no confidence for De La Hoya. That
may be unfair, but the little world of boxing never has been about
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya should know that. He is called the Golden Boy, and
some experts consider him the best boxer in the world. But an
undercurrent of doubt persists. De La Hoya knows about the
undercurrent.
</P>
<P>
   It is said he is not Mexican enough. This criticism is cruel,
but it is out there, anyway. The knock against him is that he's a
hero to white America, not to Mexicans. He stands accused of
selling out.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of De La Hoya not being Mexican enough is also a
criticism of his boxing style. Fair or not, Mexicans are
stereotyped as face-first brawlers who enjoy taking a punch if they
then can administer one of their own. Bobby Chacon, now punch
drunk, used to delight boxing fans in San Francisco and Sacramento
with that rough style.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya will have none of that. He is tall and
slender-waisted, definitely not made for the hit-and-be-hit style
of boxing. He would rather avoid a blow than take one. And who can
blame him? Fact is, around certain neighborhoods in Los Angeles he
is perceived as lacking in machismo.
</P>
<P>
   He is also handsome. With his straight nose and square jaw he
looks like a smaller version of Clark Kent. This, some people hold
against him, as well. You see, De La Hoya doesn't want to get his
face messed up, not when it's up there on billboards selling all
kinds of products. At the press conference, he thanked his sponsors
(I counted six) for being ``on board with me.'' He's more like a
conglomerate than a pug.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing people wonder why he has had so many trainers. A guy
named Robert Alcazar is De La Hoya's official trainer, but for most
of his fights De La Hoya also has another trainer who's better
known than Alcazar. He has had Emanuel Steward, who developed
Thomas Hearns, and he has had former lightweight champ Carlos
Ortiz, and he has had a bunch of others. Right now, he has Gil
Clancy, who, years ago, brought along former welter and
middleweight champ Emile Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   The result of all these trainers, some insiders think, is that
De La Hoya has been taught too many styles, and sometimes these
styles conflict. If you believe this argument, you reach the
inevitable conclusion that he has no clearly defined style. He's
like a child prodigy piano player who has been taught by six
different music teachers with six different theories.
</P>
<P>
   Although De La Hoya has a gleaming smile, which seems to
indicate he has the world by the tail, it is said that he is a
lonely guy who trusts no one. His father, Joel, owns part of him,
but Joel never compliments his son. De La Hoya admitted this to the
media the other day. This lack of praise makes De La Hoya so gloomy
he doesn't want his father in training camp with him.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say the words ``dysfunctional family''?
</P>
<P>
   Although De La Hoya is known as a knockout puncher, some experts
believe, as he moves up through the divisions (he began as a
lightweight), he has not brought his punch along with him. And then
there's the issue of his chin. Some absolute mediocrities have put
him on the canvas, which makes you wonder about the tensile
strength of his jaw bone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact remains he is the most exciting, most marketable
fighter around, and he is probably the most talented. This is an
age in which casual fight fans care only about heavyweights. He has
made them interested in welters, guys who weigh 147 pounds. That's
an accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad is the best fighter De La Hoya has faced. If he beats
Trinidad, De La Hoya will eliminate the doubts, perhaps define
himself as a great fighter. Finally, that's what the Fight of the
Millennium is all about _ giving himself a definition. Anything
would be better than the question that constantly dogs him right
now: Who is Oscar De La Hoya?
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
