<SLUG> BC-PREGAME-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INNOVATIVE ADS PROMOTE PRE-GAME SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a decade, the testosterone-driven network studio
programs that precede National Football League games on Sundays
have been battlegrounds for analysis, player features and scoops on
signings, suspensions and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox and CBS programs from noon to 1 p.m. are attempts to
lure fans to watch the games that come after the shows. And the
ESPN show, which now runs from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m., is a huge
pre-game appetizer, a reminder to watch its game at 8:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Since its introduction in 1994, ``Fox NFL Sunday'' has preached
the entertainment value of its foursome: three former football
players _ Terry Bradshaw, Howie Long and Cris Collinsworth _ plus
former basketball player and longtime host James Brown. Their
interaction is packed with raucous banter, mainly between Bradshaw
and Long, a style that reached a new level last season with the
addition of the long-necked Collinsworth, who quickly became the
butt of their insults.
</P>
<P>
   To promote the program this season, Fox has transformed the
foursome into animated Claymation characters through the work of
Will Vinton Studios in Portland, Ore. Animating Bradshaw, Long,
Brown and Collinsworth makes sense: the Fox television network is
replete with cartoon series like ``The Simpsons,'' ``King of the
Hill,'' ``Futurama'' and ``The P.J.'s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to appeal to younger viewers who have abandoned
the pre-game shows to watch other things and to break through the
clutter in a unique way,'' said Neal Tiles, the senior vice
president for marketing at Fox Sports. ``This was an easy way to
take the guys into a fantastical realm.''
</P>
<P>
   One spot is set in the Fox Television Network studio commissary.
Bradshaw uses a ketchup bottle and table utensils to diagram a play
when a stream of ketchup goes awry and lands on Ally McBeal, a
prime-time Fox star. She initiates a food fight by hurling a
drumstick at Bradshaw that is swallowed by John Madden (``Tastes
like chicken!'' he says), Fox's top game analyst.
</P>
<P>
   In a second spot, Collinsworth asks Long to switch seats on the
studio set with him. Bradshaw suggests they arm-wrestle. ``Cris,
are you sure?'' Brown asks. Within seconds, Long tears off
Collinsworth's arm, then uses it to gesture at viewers to watch the
day's games. ``Don't miss it,'' says Long, a former defensive end
for the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't view CBS and ESPN and ABC as our competition,'' Tiles
said. ``We compete in a larger world of advertising with Nike and
Anheuser-Busch.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots were created by Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding San Francisco,
part of the FCB Worldwide unit of True North Communications. They
will run through December and include other Fox prime-time stars.
Fox is also buying time for the spots on wrestling programs on the
TNT and USA networks, ``South Park'' and ``The Man Show'' on Comedy
Central and the ``Howard Stern'' show on E! To reinforce the
marketing, Fox has licensed the four characters to Equity Marketing
to produce figurines for sale at mass merchandisers like Wal-Mart
Stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a novelty, we think our guys, in Claymation form, will
sell,'' Tiles said, adding that Fox is considering turning the
announcing quartet into Saturday morning cartoon crime fighters in
the mold of ``Scooby Doo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great extension to talk to the next
generation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday NFL Countdown,'' the football preview show on ESPN, a
unit of Walt Disney, is promoting itself by casting its announcers,
including Chris Berman, Tom Jackson, Sterling Sharpe and Stuart
Scott, as professors of football at Bristol University in
recognition of the cable network's headquarters in Bristol, Conn.
The spots, now in their third year, were originally created by
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland but are now produced by Lowe &AMP;
Partners/SMS in San Francisco, part of the Lowe Group unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want viewers to feel that if you go anywhere before the
game for insight, you should go to Bristol U.,'' said Lee Ann Daly,
ESPN's senior vice president for marketing and advertising. ``We
believe it reinforces our positioning that our pre-game show serves
the fan better than anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, Berman and Jackson entice students to register for
classes like ``No-Huddle Offense 101'' and ``History of the Central
Division.''
</P>
<P>
   In a second, Jackson, a former Denver Broncos linebacker,
randomly tackles male and female students on campus in an attempt
to integrate real-life experiences into his teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that sports is entertainment and we have to
entertain and inform audiences,'' Ms. Daly said. `It's incumbent
upon us to serve things up in a way that differentiates us. The
programming differentiates us, but the spots differentiate us even
more.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is using a second set of promotional ads, created by Wieden
&AMP; Kennedy, to drive viewers to its games. The network has brought
back a group of dogs, that, through the use of animation and
prosthetic limbs, speak and play poker. Rather than chatting only
to one another, as they did last season, the dogs converse with
people, including John (Big Dawg) Thompson, a rotund Cleveland
Browns fan who wears a hound dog mask, and players like Wayne
Chrebet of the Jets and Jason Sehorn of the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Performing the voice-overs are the actors Art Carney and Jeffrey
Tambor, the comedian Gilbert Gottfried and the retired basketball
star George Gervin. Carney's son came for an audition and said his
father wanted to try out. ``He said his father wanted him to tell
us, `I'm not dead yet!''' Ms. Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Sports was confronted with a different challenge, more
modest than reinforcing a successful program with familiar
personalities. Last season, when CBS returned to broadcasting pro
football after a four-year hiatus, its ``NFL Today'' studio program
was a creative failure. The sports division overhauled the show by
jettisoning three rookie analysts in favor of the more experienced
Randy Cross, Craig James and Jerry Glanville, but kept the host,
Jim Nantz.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Towey, the creative director of CBS Sports, said the goal
of a light-hearted series of promos, created in-house, was to
illustrate the group's interaction. ``I want the faces and
personalities to be upfront,'' Towey said. ``People have to know
our guys and that their interaction is different than it was last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   For one spot, set in a Brooklyn diner, a nosy waiter intrudes
into the announcers' fast-paced conversation about the forthcoming
season. Who is this guy? they ask. ```A big fan,'' Nantz says,
reintroducing a character played by actor Tony Hoty in spots for
the program from 1992 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Towey described the more lavish campaigns by Fox and ESPN as
``very extreme stuff with terrific execution,'' but added, ``We're
more focused on football. Our guys have fun but it's all about the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC Sports no longer has a ``Monday Night Football'' pre-game
show _ a one-season experiment last year was an awkward muddle _
but is marketing the highly rated games by comparing the brawny
excitement of pro football with snatches of Monday night
entertainment in foreign countries, such as Irish clog dancing and
a Japanese variety show. ``Ain't America Great?'' the ads ask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
