<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-TORONTO-SHOES-FACTS17     09-16 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-SHOES-FACTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shoe facts, gifts the right fit
 &HT;    EMBARGOED for Sunday, Sept. 19
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Bata Shoe Museum has a great gift shop filled
with all kinds of shoe-related products. There are books _
including many versions of the Cinderella story _ as well as
stationery, jewelry, umbrellas and scarves.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can't get to Canada, some of those same products can
be found at The Museum Co. at the Mall at Fairfield Commons.
</P>
<P>
   A cute nightshirt sprinkled with images of shoes proclaims: ``If
the shoe fits, buy it in every color!'' It's $25 and one size fits
all. The store also carries ruby red slipper pins for $25 and $60
and guest soaps shaped like shoes for $8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started with the shoe book we carry,'' says Brad
Wiseman, store manager. ``People loved seeing the different shoes
throughout the ages.''
</P>
<P>
   The book he's referring to is ``Shoes: A Celebration of Pumps,
Sandals, Slippers &AMP; More'' by Linda O'Keeffe (Workman, $11.95),
with more than 1,000 photos.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum Co. also sells a line of miniature shoes called Just
the Right Size. Made by Willitts Designs, they range from a 1880
opera boot to a 1950 golden stiletto. There's also a ballet
slipper, a golf shoe and a cowboy boot. The little shoes (31 now in
the collection) are $15 to $25 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women of all ages are buying them,'' says Wiseman, ``and we've
had lots of mothers and daughters come in that collect them.''
Customers can register and receive notification as shoes are added
to the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Check bookstores for other shoe books, including these two
lavish art books:
</P>
<P>
   _ Valerie Steele's ``Shoes: A Lexicon of Style'' ( Rizzoli,
$40): Steele, chief curator of the museum at the Fashion Institute
of Technology in New York, insists, ``there is a bit of Imelda
Marcos in many women.'' Chapters are arranged by type of shoe:
court shoes and pumps, slippers and mules, stilettos, sandles, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shoes: Objects of Art and Seduction'' by Paola Buratto
Caovilla (Skira, $60)
</P>
<P>
   is creatively put together and covers topics ranging from the
history of shoes to shoemaking. Writes the author, wife of designer
Rene Fernando Caovilla, ``Not all shoes are made for walking, but
all can seduce.''
</P>
<P>
   FASCINATING FOOTNOTES
</P>
<P>
   _ Napoleon Bonaparte had servants walk around in his new boots
to break them in before he wore them.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average person walks the equivalent of 3 1/2 times around
the Earth in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who are left-handed are also left-footed, having the
tendency to put their left foot forward first.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average person takes 9,000 steps a day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women are four times more likely to develop foot trouble than
men.
</P>
<P>
   _ North Americans spend almost $18 billion a year on footwear.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average North American buys five pairs of shoes a year, as
do the English and Germans. The French tend to buy slightly more.
Italians, Spanish, Russian and Swedes manage with about 3 1/2 new
pairs each year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eight pairs of ruby slippers were made for Judy Garland to
wear in The Wizard of Oz; the last pair to be auctioned sold for
$165,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The boots worn by Neil Armstrong for his walk on the moon in
1969 were jettisoned before returning to Earth to prevent
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   _ The original French version of the Cinderella story features a
fur slipper instead of a glass one. The confusion arose in the
similarity of a French word for white fur (vair), which resembled
the word for glass (verre).
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: The Bata Shoe Museum
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
