<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-TORONTO-SHOES17-COX     09-16 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-SHOES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Museum steps into world of shoes
 &HT;    EMBARGOED for Sunday, Sept. 19
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ I must admit I was expecting someone _ and something _
totally different.
</P>
<P>
   When I read that Sonja Bata's personal shoe collection was the
cornerstone for a new Toronto museum, I envisioned a fashionable
socialite with a shoe addiction and a couple of rooms in an old
house filled with shelves of her designer shoes.
</P>
<P>
   I figured I'd be there for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my surprise when I arrived at the busy corner of St.
George and Bloor streets and gazed at the contemporary five-story
limestone building designed to suggest a giant shoe box and lid.
Clever and enticing window displays ranged from giant feet with
appropriate quotes (''shoestring budget,'' ``fancy footwork''
``head over heels'') to a list of celebrity shoe sizes: Marilyn
Monroe (7AA), Fred Astaire (10 1/2), Robert Redford (9D) and
Shaquille O'Neal (22EEE).
</P>
<P>
   Inside North America's first shoe museum is the world's largest,
most comprehensive collection of shoes and shoe-related objects and
_ if you're lucky _ the woman who started it all.
</P>
<P>
   My one-hour visit turned into four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Bata believes that we obtain a glimpse of history by
looking at what people wear on their feet and that our footwear
tells a lot about each of us. She knows that shoes have been
adapted to suit the needs of different peoples _ and that through
them we are given clues to their environment, activities, social
position and traditions. And she is fascinated by all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone steps out of their shoe, it doesn't become
lifeless, there's an imprint left of that person,'' insists Mrs.
Bata, ushering us to the office where she continues to work every
day as chairman of the Bata Shoe Museum Foundation. ``Shoes tell
you more than any other artifact.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the museum's 10,000 artifacts spanning 4,500 years are
Chinese silk shoes for binding women's feet, pre-Columbian
sacrificial boots, bear fur shoes for Japanese Samurai and human
hair slippers for Australian Aboriginal executioners.
</P>
<P>
   There are shoe-shaped ornamental artifacts (Majolica hand
warmers and inlaid fruitwood snuffboxes) and graphic materials
illustrating the history of footwear. There's also a display on the
age-old craft of shoemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity footwear ranges from Queen Victoria's ballroom
slippers and Robert Redford's cowboy boots to Elton John's
monogrammed silver platform boots and Elvis Presley's blue patent
loafers. In a mini-theater, viewers watch news and film clips of
celebrities, at the end of each segment the spotlight shines on the
real shoe once worn by that celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors learn fascinating tidbits: evidence of shoemaking
exists as early as 10,000 B.C., one-quarter of all the bones in the
human body are found in the feet, the wedding custom of throwing
rice actually began with throwing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that Queen Elizabeth I popularized high heels and wore
them to make her diminutive stature more imposing and that
Salvatore Ferragamo and Vivienne Westwood weren't the first
designers to think of platforms: The museum has a velvet-covered
platform mule from 16th century Venice.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked if I could peek behind the scenes, I was taken on a
fascinating tour of storage rooms by conservator Ada Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the 1800s there was no differentiation between the
left and right shoes,'' she told me, picking up a pair of shoes
from the 1620s to illustrate.
</P>
<P>
   An artifact sheet on every shoe in the collection includes
information ranging from a description of the shoe to its material,
measurements, date, owner, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also tell when someone had problems with their feet,''
she says. ``These Nikes were John McEnroe's. He had a bunion and
would slice the side of the shoes to relieve the pressure. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is a horseshoe from Rising Star, who won the
Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the permanent exhibits, the museum hosts special
exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   A current retrospective features beautiful designer footwear
produced by Herbert Levine Inc. between 1948 and 1975. The Levines
_ Beth, the designer and Herbert, the marketing expert _ were known
for breaking the rules in their use of materials, fabric and
technology. For her wedding, Liza Minnelli requested red silk
wedding shoes reminiscent of those worn by her mother in The Wizard
of Oz. The Levines' kabuki shoe, a variation of the platforms worn
by Japanese stage actors, was an inspiration for the late Gianni
Versace. The company also has created paper shoes, pumps shaped
like racing cars and sandals with Astroturf insoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese Footgear: Walking the Path of Innovation'' will be on
exhibit until January, showcasing traditional and occupational
footwear of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Bata's passion for shoes began many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in Switzerland, studied architecture and in 1946
got married to a shoe man,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That ``shoe man'' wasn't exactly a cobbler; he was Thomas J.
Bata, son of a well-known Czech shoe manufacturer who had emigrated
to Canada at the beginning of World War II. Today, Bata is the
biggest shoe company in the world.
</P>
<P>
   When the company began introducing shoes to developing countries
around the world, Sonja Bata became involved, fascinated by the
various cultures and the shoes that reflected them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated how different shoe shapes developed when feet
are all the same,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Bata believes that shoes not only trace a path through
technological development but also mark even the subtlest shifts in
a society's attitudes and values. They illustrate social status,
climate, religion, sex, profession.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, when the collection had outgrown available private
storage space, the Bata family established its foundation to manage
the collection more professionally and to create a center of
knowledge about the role of footwear in social and cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also publishes books and funds field trips to
collect and research footwear in areas where traditions are
changing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Bata is an advocate of specialized museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that museums were big state museums like the
Metropolitan in New York that have everything from armor to Fabrege
eggs,'' she says. ``Today we are more sophisticated, we want more
specialized information. And we want education and entertainment as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   She's convinced her museum will become a destination point for
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to leave our museum saying it was fun, that
they never realized shoes were so exciting and that this is the
whole world expressed in shoes!''
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GO:
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: The Bata Shoe Museum.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: 327 Bloor St. West, Toronto, Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   HOURS: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday and
Saturday; 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. Thursday; noon to 5 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ADMISSION: $6 for adults, $4 for students and seniors, $2 for
children, $12 for families. On the first Tuesday of every month,
admission is free (prices in Canadian dollars).
</P>
<P>
   PHONE: (416) 979-7799.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
