A4858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NASCAR-RUDD-YATES-NYT     09-16 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-RUDD-YATES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YATES GOES WITH A PROVEN WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Robert Yates made a driver change in one of his
cars, he went with a guy he figured he could teach how to win.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he's going with a guy who already knows.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, the combination of Yates and Ricky Rudd, a steady
veteran who has won at least one race for 16 straight seasons, will
be one of the most interesting combinations to watch in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd has agreed to a three-year deal with Yates, replacing Kenny
Irwin in Yates' primary car.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who grew up in open-wheel competition, couldn't make the
transition from NASCAR's truck series to Winston Cup as quickly as
he needed to do with the high profile Yates car. With no real
background in stock cars, and no knowledge of what he needed to do
or what the car needed to do to win, Irwin, who is 30, struggled
with Yates for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as having a driver who knows his way around each and
every race track, it's so important, and it's something you don't
do overnight,'' Yates said. ``We knew that two years ago when we
hired Kenny. I think we've given a lot back to the sport for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've brought a guy to this arena that's going to be here for
a long time and do a good job,'' Yates said of Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   At 43, Rudd is at the opposite end of the pole. Rudd grew up in
stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   He has been running Winston Cup since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He has experience in pressure situations, having driven for Rick
Hendrick and others in cars that were expected to do well.
</P>
<P>
   He has been on his own, running a team since 1994, and he has
experience in multi-car operations, having driven for Hendrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to win, and he knows how to win at every single
race track,'' Yates said. ``That's hard to come by these days, and
we're happy to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd has high expectations for his first year with Yates. ``I
feel like a top five in the points is realistic for year one,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kenny Irwin did a great job,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can almost see myself ... in 1981 I drove for DiGard,
Gatorade. I wasn't ready for that ride,'' Rudd said. ``I was a
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed the size of the cars, they changed the wheel
base. I knew I wasn't ready for that ride, but I knew if I didn't
take it, that might be my last good opportunity,'' Rudd said. ``I
came out of there, and it helped me a lot. It prepared me for years
down the road, and I started winning shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Irwin is a great race car driver, and I think he'll be
great for some time,'' Rudd said. ``I think he's got a good future.
I think he'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd and Yates will combine their operations, with the Yates car
operating out of the shop Rudd owns.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet certain how the two teams will merge, in terms of
personnel, and what will happen to the two crew chiefs, Doug
Richert with Yates and Michael McSwain with Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the toughest thing when you merge something, you've
got 100 people. I don't know how that's going to shake out,'' Yates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yates could have a potent combination with Rudd in No. 28 teamed
with another veteran driver _ Dale Jarrett _ in Yates' second car,
No. 88.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there needs to be a bounce off of knowledge between
the two teams, and I would say the 88 has probably been feeding the
28 a lot of information. I think it's probably been a one-way flow,
maybe,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd noted that both he and Jarrett like the same kind of
chassis.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
