<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; kan-z
k b BC-WEDGWOOD-GUNS-EDITORI     09-16 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDGWOOD-GUNS-EDITORIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GUNS, NO SAFE HAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 Editorial  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something is terribly wrong with America when teen-agers being
fired upon at a Texas church thought that their pastor was ``trying
to play a joke on us'' in a scene ``out of a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Images of violence in the media are so pervasive that young
Americans have come to accept gun play as our cultural norm, even
in houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Wednesday at Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth
was no joke, as victims and survivors now know. It was real. It was
horrible. And worse, it was familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Once again an armed gunman appeared calm as he mowed down
screaming children. There are frightening echoes of last April's
Columbine High School massacre in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in August, gunman Buford O. Furrow's motive in a
killing at a Los Angeles area Jewish community center was hatred
against Jews and non-whites.
</P>
<P>
   The motive of the Fort Worth gunman, identified as Larry Gene
Ashbrook, was not known immediately. Seven people initially were
dead and others were wounded. Ashbrook fatally shot himself after a
spree in which he used a pipe bomb and 9mm semiautomatic and
.380-caliber handguns.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, as in other cities known for their mass shootings
at schools, motive takes a back seat to means.
</P>
<P>
   The means in these cases were deadly firearms that were used
against unarmed people, including children.
</P>
<P>
   Too many guns are in too many hands.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be people who believe that they have a reason,
however irrational, to kill. But it is the access to firearms that
takes people beyond motive to criminality that can result in
multiple victims.
</P>
<P>
   The issue in Fort Worth, as elsewhere, is the proliferation of
firearms. This proliferation is what makes no place safe, not
child-care centers, not movie theaters, not schools, not workplaces
and not even places of worship.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is sacred so long as there are too many guns in too many
hands and too many lawmakers in Congress and the state legislatures
who want to keep things that way.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional lawmakers should look to Fort Worth as they keep
chipping at gun-reform measures _ such as those pertaining to
trigger locks and gun shows _ as part of the juvenile crime
package.
</P>
<P>
   So far all Congress has to show for gun control this session is
passage of a measure allowing schools to post the Ten Commandments.
This idea looks even more ludicrous in considering the shootings at
a church. The gunman was not stopped by Christian symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Too many guns in too many hands is the issue that the Texas
Legislature, which this year passed a bill protecting gun
manufacturers from lawsuits filed by local governments, needs to
consider. It was in Texas, by the way, that legislators this year
also did away with the prohibition of guns in churches.
</P>
<P>
   Only in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
