<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-INTERNET-POLITICS17-C     09-16 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THORNY INTERNET POLITICS ISSUES DEBATED IN REAL TIME
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``This is the future,'' Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah,
proclaimed Thursday as an Internet site devoted to political issues
fed a blurry image the size of a postage stamp to computer
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' Bennett said, his nearly bald head bobbing slowly in
the video frame, ``we had door-to-door campaigning. Then we had
newspapers, followed by television and by cable. And now we have
the Internet. This is where political campaigns are going.''
</P>
<P>
   The unique four-hour webcast, titled ``the Frontier of Internet
Politics,'' brought together political leaders and cyberspace gurus
to ponder such issues as ``the 2000 Campaign and the Future of
E-Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But the technical limits posed by the streaming video were
hardly as daunting as public policy challenges posed by the
increasingly popular online medium.
</P>
<P>
   The political panelists who followed Bennett's upbeat
introductory remarks gave equally glowing reports on the coming
promise of grass-roots democracy, reduced dependence on traditional
media, lower campaign costs and even widespread Internet voting.
</P>
<P>
   However, the moderator of the ``2000 campaign'' forum, Albert
Gidari, warned that the Internet ``poses a clear threat to
traditional political party structures.'' Gidari heads Savvy.com, a
high-tech consulting firm to online firms.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the forum left the most vital issue of all _ how to
regulate, if at all, political activity on the Internet _
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the issue briefly took center stage in
Congress when Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the third-ranking Republican
in the House and an ardent foe of tighter campaign finance laws,
proposed that the Internet be preserved as a political free-fire
zone. DeLay's proposal was promptly branded as a ``poison pill''
aimed at splintering support for reform.
</P>
<P>
   At least for the moment, DeLay's gambit put him in the same camp
as James Dempsey of the Center for Democracy and Technology, a
liberal-leaning Washington-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is uniquely decentralized, global, abundant,
inexpensive, interactive and user-controlled. The campaign finance
laws were developed for the centralized, scarce, and expensive
media of radio, television and print,'' Dempsey said in the
webcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initial efforts to apply the Federal Election Campaign Act to
these new and varied Internet communications have yielded troubling
results, threatening to burden _ even silence _ the voice of
average citizens in American political life.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Dempsey spoke, his center was issuing a fresh report on
the issue which concluded: ``It would be worse than ironic if rules
designed to de-emphasize the unfair advantage of money, to broaden
the diversity of groups that can have an impact on the election
process and to 'return our electoral process to the people' were
applied to deter individuals from using the 'electronic soapbox' of
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, warned David Mason, a Republican who was nominated
to the Federal Election Commission by President Clinton last year.
While agreeing with much of the thrust of Dempsey's argument, Mason
noted that ``as an enforcement agency, we have a problem. We have
the law (to uphold) out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mason: ``If your proposals are adopted, we're going to
handicap political parties on the very media that you're saying we
ought to be promoting as a grass-roots force in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That raises some real questions about equity and about equal
protection under the laws. So my view is that you're either going
to be stuck with a completely deregulatory approach or you're going
to be stuck with a regulatory agency making some very difficult
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more skeptical comments came from Fred Wertheimer,
president of Democracy 21 and former head of Common Cause, a
government watchdog group aligned with liberal causes.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer raised the possibility that Internet exemptions could
allow a president to blithely take bribes so long as all of the
transactions were confined to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would caution very strongly that the simple way out is to
say, why don't we just exempt the Internet from campaign finance
laws,'' he said. ``But the purpose of existing laws is to protect
the public from corruption. I don't think we can simply accept the
idea that since regulation sounds like a bad idea on the Internet
we will give up on the notion of protecting citizens against
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The live political webcast was sponsored by D.C. Orbit Network
(www.dcorbit.com). The Washington-based group serves as a
clearinghouse for 16 non-partisan political and public affairs web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The report released Thursday by the Center for Democracy and
Technology, titled ``Square Pegs and Round Holes,'' may be found on
the group's web site, www.cdt.org.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
