<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-DRIVERS-NY     09-16 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DRIVERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR MUSICAL CHAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NASCAR-RUDD-YATES) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest domino has been knocked down, and the rest of the
line will fall, too.
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Yates signed Ricky Rudd to a three-year contract as
the replacement for Kenny Irwin, the best available ride for next
year on the Winston Cup circuit was gone.
</P>
<P>
   And that means other drivers searching for jobs _ but perhaps
hesitant to commit elsewhere while the Yates car was still open _
will now take what they can get.
</P>
<P>
   The best seat open now is the Chevy unexpectedly vacated by Ken
Schrader, who left to replace Ernie Irvan in Read Morton's Pontiac.
Morton's car is popularly regarded as Hendrick Motorsports' test
Pontiac. It gets its engines from Hendrick and has other ties to
that team as well.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader's former car, owned by Andy Petree, has potential.
Petree, Richard Childress and Dale Earnhardt are all tied together
through a research and development group jointly funded by all
three teams. Petree's car would seem to be the new prize, but there
might be problems here.
</P>
<P>
   Some wonder if the loss of Schrader will also mean the loss of
Petree's new sponsor, Oakwood Homes. Schrader is the one who
brought Oakwood Homes to Petree and some think with Schrader now
gone, Oakwood Hhomes might be, too.
</P>
<P>
   Petree denies this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're firmly committed,'' Petree said, ``but we've got to
put a good driver in the car. Their expectations are of having
Schrader or someone equal to him. They're doing their part and
we've got to do ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Petree was furious when Schrader told him he was leaving,
because the two had just agreed on an extension of Schrader's
contract, although Schrader hadn't signed it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Petree needs to get a driver acceptable to Oakwood Homes.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nemechek could figure here. Nemechek was Yates' alternate
choice to replace Irwin if Rudd was unavailable. He has qualities
Petree is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   First, he represents a sponsor well. And second, he has a strong
knowledge of cars and what has to be done to make them go fast.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other candidates out there are Irwin and Wally
Dallenbach, but word is that Irwin has already signed with Sabco to
replace Nemechek, although that won't be announced until the final
race in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach, meanwhile, may be headed to Cal Wells' new team,
which took Rudd's sponsor, Tide, to start the ball rolling.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
