<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans a lead story and two pages
of inside coverage on Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-RDP (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Hurricane Floyd comes ashore
near Cape Fear, N.C., with 110 mph winds, flooding the Carolina
coasts with more than a foot of rain as tens of thousands of people
huddled in shelters. At least seven deaths are blamed on the storm.
More than 480,000 people in the Carolinas and Virginia have lost
power. In Portsmouth, Va., flooding and power failures combined to
shut down the water supply system, which serves 110,000 customers.
By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (New York) _ Hurricane Floyd brought its fierce
winds and torrents of rain to a New York region that was waiting
and well prepared, flooding roads and knocking out some power but
failing to inflict any devastating damage. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY-SCENE (New York) _ To a large extent, the city hid.
It wasn't always clear from what. Sure, Hurricane Floyd was
supposed to roar into town Thursday and topple buildings and
catapult buses over the World Trade Center _ but where was it? The
day the hurricane was due was very much a day of pointed contrasts
in the metropolitan area, with portions of the area being pounded,
while the city itself was tricked by a non-event. By N.R.
Kleinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-OBSESS (Undated) _ From North Dakota to London, and
certainly from New Jersey through the five boroughs and around to
New England, Floyd fixated millions of people Thursday, staring at
some from television screens with its Cyclopian eye etched in
synthetic orange swirls and blasting others right in the face with
potent rainy gusts. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BAHAMAS (Abaco) _ Report on damage from the storm to
the outer islands. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
