<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SURGEON-GENERAL-FIREA     09-16 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURGEON-GENERAL-FIREARMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEON GENERAL ASSAILS `EASY ASSESS TO FIREARMS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As one would expect of America's family doctor, U.S.
Surgeon General David Satcher encouraged everyone to exercise 30
minutes a day and eat more fruits and veggies.
</P>
<P>
   But Satcher took on tougher topics as well during his Thursday
morning address to more than 1,000 health care professionals in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He assailed the country's ``easy access to firearms'' and
``glamorization of violence'' which ``certainly played a part'' in
Wednesday's Fort Worth shooting spree and suicide that left eight
people dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, in Japan, there were 15 children who died from
firearms. In England, there were 30. In Canada, there were 105. In
the United States, there were 5,000,'' he said. ``There's something
wrong with that picture.''
</P>
<P>
   He criticized complacency regarding AIDS. ``We have made some
progress, (but) it's not real progress in my opinion,'' he said,
because the rate of new infections in the United States has not
decreased.
</P>
<P>
   He called for universal access to health care and the
elimination of disparities in overall health across ethnic lines,
citing dramatic differences in American life expectancies. Average
life expectancy in the U.S. is now 76.5 years, he said. For white
women, it's 80. For black women, it's about 74. For white men, 73.
For black men, 67.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the uninsured, the underserved, the underrepresented _
but let me tell you, that's not the whole story. We also have the
uninspired,'' he said. ``Three thousand teen-agers become smokers
every day. Explain that to me. Why do people use drugs and inject
dirty needles and get the AIDS virus? What is it going to take to
turn that around? We've got to find a way to reach the uninspired
and uninformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher's appearance at the Edwin Hornberger Conference Center
in the Texas Medical Center kicked off a planned series of
educational seminars put on by the City of Houston Health and Human
Services Department for employees and other medical and public
health professionals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Afterward, he toured the new Houston Community College System
Health Science Center, the city's La Nueva Casa health clinic and a
mobile HIV testing unit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Satcher, a highly respected doctor and educator, who until
recently headed the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, was appointed surgeon general and assistant secretary
of health last year. The position was vacant for three years after
the controversial Dr. Joycelyn Elders was fired in 1994 for making
what many considered inappropriate public remarks about
masturbation
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Satcher's causes have included suicide
prevention, placing health warnings on cigars and reducing the
waistlines of America's overweight population.
</P>
<P>
   The physician's remarks were preceded by a presentation from
Stephen Klineberg, a Rice University sociologist who has conducted
an annual survey of Houston's attitudes and concerns for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Klineberg provided the backdrop to the health care discussion by
outlining Houston's shifting economy and racial makeup. Houston now
has a majority-minority population with a composition that is
roughly one-third white, one-third Hispanic and one-third blacks
and Asians combined.
</P>
<P>
   He said Houstonians are embracing the city's diversity to a
greater degree than ever before. But within that diversity are
gaping differences in education levels among immigrants: 57 percent
of Asian immigrants have college degrees; 54 percent of Mexican
immigrants do not have high school diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Without a college degree ``you are condemned to poverty. You
will make minimum wage the rest of your life,'' Klineberg said.
``This is not a vigorous blue-collar economy. Education is the
critical determinant.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher called for a closing of gaps between the races in terms
of good health and emphasized that quality of life is as important
as longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not just concerned about when they're going to die.
They're concerned about how they're going to live,'' he said.
``They are concerned about how they feel when they get up in the
morning, how they feel when they go to bed at night. Whether or not
they're enjoying sex. Quality of life is a major goal... Not just,
can we get people to live longer (but) can we get them to live
better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
