<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BLAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS BEGIN TO DOUBT GOVERNMENT AS BLASTS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the death toll rose in Thursday's apartment bombing
in southern Russia, President Boris N. Yeltsin sought to dispel
fears that his government is powerless to halt the deadly
explosions sweeping the country,
</P>
<P>
   But with each passing day, Russians have less faith that the
state can protect them. The blast that ripped through a large
apartment building in the southern city of Volgodonsk early
Thursday killed at least 17 residents and wounded 180, 20 of them
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion, which investigators called a terrorist act, was
the fourth deadly apartment blast this month, a wave of violence
that has claimed close to 300 lives and further eroded what little
credibility Russian authorities still enjoy among their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authorities have enough will and enough resources for the
struggle against terrorism,'' Yeltsin said in a telegram to the
governor of Rostov region, where Volgodonsk is located.
</P>
<P>
   But as the country once again tuned into to the grosteque
footage of rescue workers searching the ruins for survivors, few
here shared in their president's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians lashed out at law enforcement agencies' lack of
preparedness. Analysts predicted more violence. Yeltsin, his
presidency already reeling from an international money laundering
scandal, charges of Kremlin corruption and a bloody insurgency in
the Caucasus, seemed weaker and more isolated than he has ever been
during his 8-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important for the residents of tens of thousands of
apartment buildings across Russia is that they have seen the
weakness of a state that only a decade ago ran one of the most
tightly monitored and oppressive societies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that we are alone, that no one can protect us,''
said Tamara Chernyshova, a television producer who lives in a
Moscow high-rise with her husband and two small children.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's blast was the fifth deadly explosion in Russia since
Aug. 31, when a bomb detonated in a central Moscow mall, killing
one person and injuring 40. Early this month, an apartment building
in the southern Russian region of Dagestan that housed military
officers and their families was rocked by a blast that killed 64.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a blast ripped through an apartment building in the
southeast Moscow residential neighborhood of Pechatniki, killing
93, and on Monday a bomb levelled a similar apartment complex on
Kashirskoye Highway in southern Moscow, killing 118.
</P>
<P>
   Police have responded with a massive citywide operation called
``Whirlwind,'' which they say has uncovered several tons of
explosives and possibly prevented as many as six more blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Russian investigators say they also have figured out how the
perpetrators had managed to sneak tons of explosives into Moscow
without being detected by disguising it as bags of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow police spokesman Kirill Mazurin also said he could
not rule out a new attack in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the death toll in Thursday's explosion in Volgodonsk
might have been much worse if not for their efforts to clear out
basements and attics. The explosives this time were hidden in a
truck or in an underground pipe outside the nine-story building.
The powerful blast, the equivalent of 600 to 1,000 pounds of
dynamite, demolished the front of the complex and damaged 20
surrounding buildings and formed a crater 12 feet deep and 40 feet
wide. As with all the apartment blasts, the explosion went off at a
time when people were asleep at home, meaning that the as yet
unknown attackers were trying to cause maximum casualities.
</P>
<P>
   No one immediately claimed responsbility, but officials
immediately fingered the people they blame for the other blasts,
insurgents from the breakaway Caucasus region of Chechnya who have
been fighting the Russian army in the neighboring southern Russian
region of Dagestan. The Chechens deny responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, speaking on Russian TV after a
meeting in which he ordered his cabinet to improve security across
the nation, appealed to citizens to look after themselves. ``I want
to turn to military veterans, police veterans. Take the initiative
on yourselves,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people across Moscow are way ahead of him. Frightened
residents have been organizing patrols and other actions to protect
themselves and their homes since Monday's blast.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians, meanwhile, derided the Kremlin's
security drive as too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said that Thursday's
blast demonstrated ``the paralysis of the entire law enforcement
system in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts place the blame on the lack of funding for the
post-Soviet security agencies, resulting in huge cuts in
intelligence and counter-terrorism forces. That is part of the
problem, but it is also true that the successors of the Soviet KGB,
which concentrated on protecting Communist rule and fighting the
Cold War with the West, never truly developed a force effective at
battling terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Russian counter-terrorism techniques place a priority on shows
of force, such as paratroopers on bridges and tanks on roads
leading into the city, rather than the development of intelligence
that can help head off attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians charge that Yeltsin has stood pat even after
rebel commandos staged successful surprise raids on Russian cities
during the 1994-1996 civil war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these terrorist acts, the state has not take any
action,'' said , Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov leader of an
anti-Kremlin coalition and a likely candidate in presidential
elections scheduled for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The elections, plus a parliamentary vote set for December, have
been the subject of numerous rumors. One popular Moscow newspaper
with close ties to Luzhkov, Moskovsky Komsomolets, has been
alleging for days that the Kremlin, or someone behind those in
power, has been setting off the bombs themselves to create an
excuse for declaring a state of emergency and cancelling elections.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Kremlin and Russia's Federal Security Service, the main
successor to the former KGB, Thursday angrily denied the
allegations. Other rumors swirling in the capital have predicted
that Yeltsin would soon replace Putin, or that the embattled
president himself was preparing to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Such a rumor, which would have gripped the country just a few
years ago, is now a side-issue for Russians worried about whether
or not they will wake up the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can Russia, shaken by a vicious attack, find normal,
forward-looking leaders and strategists for itself? For the time
being, this is not certain,'' asked the Noviye Ivestiya newspaper
this week. ``But what is clear is that the existence of each one of
us depends on this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
