<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-NBC-PAXSON-BOS &LR;      09-16 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-PAXSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC TO BUY ONE-THIRD OF PAXSON COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC, left on the sidelines while CBS merged with Viacom last
week, has moved to extend its own reach and enlarge its audience by
announcing plans to buy a one-third stake in Paxson Communications
Corp., owner of Pax TV.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Federal Communications Commission, the
agreement will broaden NBC's national distribution system to
include more than 120 stations either owned by Paxson
Communications or affiliated with Pax TV.
</P>
<P>
   The deal rekindled concerns about media consolidation in fewer
and fewer hands _ a trend US Representative Edward Markey (D-Mass.)
has called ``communications cannibalism.'' Mark Crispin Miller, a
media professor at New York University, said the NBC/Pax agreement
is another step toward making ``independent voices on TV a thing of
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As with Viacom, so here,'' he said. ``It reinforces the
control of a few over a range of outlets that should belong to the
many.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Telecommunications Act prohibits a major broadcast
network from owning another. However, analysts said the NBC/Pax
deal may pass muster with the FCC because the commission may
consider Pax a station group rather than a network under its
guidelines. An FCC spokesman did not return calls. Under the terms
of the $415 million deal, NBC can take full operating control of
Paxson Communications in three years, also subject to FCC approval.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger-is-better mania has overtaken the television industry
as networks scramble to develop multiple revenue streams to compete
with cable. That scramble has intensified since the FCC last month
lifted the prohibition against companies' owning more than one
station in the same TV market.
</P>
<P>
   A key question left unanswered by the NBC/Pax deal was its
impact on NBC's 220 local affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference, NBC president Bob Wright made clear
that he sees only an upside for the network itself as he proclaimed
that the deal will give NBC a ``long-sought second outlet for our
entertainment programming.'' In Boston, that could mean viewers
will eventually be able to watch NBC programs not just on Channel 7
but also on local Pax station Channel 68.
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely unlikely that NBC would ever air first-run
programs on Channel 68 rather than Channel 7. A more plausible
scenario is that the network would use the smaller station to
broadcast reruns of miniseries, made-for-TV movies, entertainment
specials, sports events, and perhaps sitcoms and dramas _ all of
which could cut into Channel 7's audience.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, the network that coined the slogan ``Must-See TV,'' might
reduce the sense of urgency viewers feel about exactly when they
``must see'' an NBC program if there is a second channel on which
to watch the same program a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't hurt NBC, but it potentially hurts the
affiliates,'' said Michael Goodman, senior analyst at the Yankee
Group. Paul R. Krumins, a TV industry consultant who heads Copley
Entertainment, disagreed that it will cut into affiliates' audience
share but said it does increase NBC's leverage in dealing with its
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that NBC will use Pax stations as another outlet
for news programs produced by MSNBC or CNBC, the cable channels
already eating into the audience of NBC affiliates. That could also
spell trouble for affiliates, for whom every viewer counts because
revenues are directly tied to audience levels.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Carson, general manager of Channel 7, said the
Boston station doesn't ``feel threatened'' by the NBC/Pax deal,
though he acknowledged that the audience for affiliates is
``diluted'' when viewers ``can see the same things more than once''
on other channels.
</P>
<P>
   NBC affiliates are currently in talks with the network over
``exclusivity'' arrangements that address that issue. During a
conference call among affiliate executives Thursday afternoon,
Wright joined in to discuss the Pax deal.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between NBC and its affiliates have grown testy over
issues of compensation, but Carson dismissed any speculation that
the network would ever turn to the Pax stations as its primary
delivery system. ``The reality is that the Pax stations are a bunch
of second- and third-tier UHF stations,'' he said. ``As an outlet
for programming, it would be a disaster for NBC to switch their
whole signal to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBC/Pax deal represents a triumph for Lowell W. ``Bud''
Paxson, chairman of Paxson Communications, who founded Pax TV just
one year ago as a ``family entertainment network.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe, Paxson
</P>
<P>
   conceded that NBC ``can do whatever they like when they own
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
