<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4916 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS &LR;      09-16 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTERED DRUG SHOWN TO PRODUCE CANCER-FIGHTING PROTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A potent new cancer-fighting protein discovered in the
Boston lab of Dr. Judah Folkman can be made by slightly altering a
drug that's already on the market, and therefore could enter human
trials as early as next year, say officials of a Framingham biotech
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The new protein seems to be at least as powerful as endostatin,
the widely publicized tumor-starving drug also discovered in
Folkman's lab. Endostatin is about to enter its first, long-awaited
human tests in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Called antiangiogenic antithrombin, or aaAT, the new protein is
being described publicly for the first time Friday, in the current
issue of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Molecular Oncology in Framingham, which has licensed the
rights to develop aaAT, announced the protein's discovery last
February but neither it nor Folkman would identify it or divulge
any details until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Another Genzyme unit, Genyme Transgenics Corp. in Framingham, is
already producing the mother protein, called antithrombin III, that
can be chemically converted into the new tumor-shrinking drug.
Genzyme Transgenics produces antithrombin III in the milk of
genetically modified goats at its farm in Charlton. This shortcut
should make aaAT easier to make than endostatin and perhaps
cheaper, but no pricing information on either drug has been
released.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, a newly discovered substance must go through years of
development and animal testing before it can move to human clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, ``there should be no hindrance to human
therapeutic trials'' of aaATT, which, because it is really the same
molecule as antithrombin III, ``has been used unwittingly in
transfusion medicine for more than 10 years,'' wrote Robin W.
Carrell, a researcher at the University of Cambridge in England.
Carrell wrote a commentary on the discovery in Friday's Science. He
meant that the new protein is so similar to antithrombin III that
people who received the latter drug were getting aaAT as well, with
no additional risks.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, the director of the surgical laboratories at Children's
and a pioneer in the study of how the body grows new blood vessels,
said the finding of the new anti-tumor protein suggests there may
still be more to be found in the body's clotting system
</P>
<P>
   ``What surprised us is that the body has such a storehouse of
proteins hidden inside other proteins that turn off blood vessel
growth and do only that,'' Folkman said.
</P>
<P>
   The substances are called angiogenesis inhibitors, because they
block the growth of new blood vessels _ a process called
angiogenesis _ that is used both in normal body functions, such as
wound healing, and is exploited by tumors so that they can grow and
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Like endostatin, angiostatin and a number of other proteins
currently offering hope of a new weapon against cancer, the new
protein attacks the linings of blood vessels that grow into tumors
to nourish them. The vessels then die off and the tumor is left
without a life support system.
</P>
<P>
   In Folkman's view, there are perhaps 8 or 10 anti-angiogenic
substances naturally in the body, and most of the time they appear
to keep any cancers that form from spreading. Therefore, giving
large doses of anti-angiogenic drugs when someone has cancer is
like enhancing the body's natural defenses. The anti-angiogenic
drugs will probably work best used in combinations with each other
and with other cancer therapies, says Folkman.
</P>
<P>
   In mouse experiments, aaAT dramatically shrank lung tumors that
had been implanted on the backs of mice, and caused no apparent ill
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite potent,'' said Dr. Michael O'Reilly, a researcher
in the Folkman lab at Children's Hospital who discovered aaAT in
1997, shortly after also discovering endostatin. ``It's hard to say
how potent it is'' in comparison with endostatin, said O'Reilly,
because equivalent forms of aaAT and endostatin haven't yet been
tested.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful protein was discovered hiding inside antithrombin
III, which helps regulate the body's blood clotting system.
O'Reilly found that the new substance, aaAT, is made when certain
enzymes produced by tumors act on antithrombin III and change its
structure slightly. As a result of this change of shape, it no
longer affects blood clotting but instead attacks newly formed
blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly discovered aaAT when he implanted human lung tumor
cells under the skins of laboratory mice. The idea was to mimic
what sometimes happens in humans when someone has an established
tumor that has spread, creating little colonies, or metastases, at
distant sites. If surgeons remove the primary tumor, in some cases
the metastases grow more aggressively. Folkman has shown that
primary tumors can secrete antiangiogenic substances that keep
secondary cancer growths from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   In his mouse experiments, O'Reilly found that if a second tumor
was implanted on the other side of the mouse, it often was kept
small and harmless by the primary tumor's production of some
antiangiogenic substance. When he purified the material, it turned
out to be aaAT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
