<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-INITIATIVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TREASURY CHIEF TO HEAD INITIATIVES SUPPORT CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin, the private-sector
financier who is widely credited with helping balance the federal
budget and managing the Asian and Mexican financial crises, has
accepted the chairmanship of the Local Initiatives Support Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Rubin, who resigned as Treasury
secretary in May, said Thursday he was making the LISC job the
first undertaking of his post-governmental life because the
problems of inner cities and distressed rural areas ``are a
critical economic issue for all of us, no matter what our economic
circumstances or where we may live.''
</P>
<P>
   LISC, a New York-based organization started in 1979 by the Ford
Foundation, manages and channels investment of billions of dollars
in private-sector funds in distressed urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, 61, who amassed a fortune as a top executive of the
investment house of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. before he entered
government, said: ``I will most likely re-engage in the financial
world in some serious fashion, but I have not made any judgment yet
as to how or with whom.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rubin is best known for adroit, occassionally daring
management of global economic issues, the native New Yorker was
associated with the traditional Democratic Party policies of former
New York Governor Mario Cuomo before the Clinton presidency, and he
signaled Thursday that he now will focus again on those domestic
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems are not intractable,'' he said. ``An awful lot
has been accomplished. As Treasury secretary I was struck by how
effective community leadership has been around the country at
making real progress.'' He said he was particularly interested in
helping secure access to capital for urban entrepreneurs who are
capable of large-scale undertakings, and in attracting a broader
spectrum of private-sector interests to community development
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Paul S. Grogan, who became a vice president of Harvard
University last year after 12 years as LISC's executive director,
said an initial, important function of LISC was ``raising the
comfort level for private-sector participation in affordable
housing'' development, and that Rubin would be able to lead the
organization's efforts to perform a similar function in commercial,
retail development in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin ``is a capitalist, a believer in the system, who believes
what's wrong is that not everyone is participating in the system,''
said Grogan. ``He believes you can't fix that with solely
government money, that you have to recruit private interests and
private capital. What attracted him to LISC is... it is an
organization that has done that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
