A4922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-AUSTRALIA-BOS &LR;      09-16 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-AUSTRALIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS WARNED OF PEACE-KEEPING DANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARWIN, Australia _ Australia's leaders Thursday steeled their
nation for the grim possibility that some soldiers deployed in the
coming days to restore peace to the violence-torn territory of East
Timor may come home in bodybags.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also pointed to the risks in deploying the
peacekeeping force, which will include 200 American support troops,
but said the mission was needed and worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us be under no misconceptions: It's going to be a
difficult and demanding task. ... I can't say there is no chance of
casualties,'' Admiral Chris Barrie, chief of the Australian Defense
Forces, told reporters here, where 4,500 Australian troops are
expected to deploy by early next week in response to a wave of
killing and destruction following a landslide vote for independence
in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a multinational force to restore security and relieve
suffering there is Australia's ``most significant military
undertaking. . . . since the Second World War,'' Barrie said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations estimates 7,000 East Timorese have been slain
since election results on Sept. 4, and at least 200,000 of the
territory's 870,000 people have fled their homes or been forcibly
relocated _ and many are in danger of starvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a dangerous operation and I've never pretended
otherwise,'' Prime Minister John Howard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two newspaper polls this week show that more than 70 percent of
Australians favor sending troops to East Timor, a former Portuguese
colony just 430 miles north of here.
</P>
<P>
   But as protesters and politicians in Indonesia bluntly warned of
violence against peacekeepers, it remains to be seen how long the
Australian public will stay committed to the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Thursday authorized about 200 US troops for logistics,
intelligence and transport, as well as elements of the US Pacific
Fleet for support. ``Of course, on any mission like this there are
dangers and risks of casualties,'' Clinton said. ``But this force
is well-equipped for the job and it is a job that is in the
interest of peace and stability.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen other nations, including Thailand, Canada,
Britain, New Zealand and South Korea, have offered soldiers to the
mission. Unlike the UN peacekeeping operation in Bosnia, where
blue-helmet forces were hamstrung by limited rules of engagement,
the force planned for East Timor has the mandate to use deadly
force to stop violence.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has had as many as 26,000 troops in East Timor in the
last week, and a condition of Jakarta's decision last Sunday to
invite foreign peacekeepers was that they would serve alongside
Indonesian troops. Western officials have voiced concerns that
Indonesian soldiers _ who stood by or even aided rampaging militias
_ might sabotage the peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read about special forces doing things in a clandestine
and a covert way,'' Barrie said. ``My biggest apprehension is that
things don't go the way I've outlined them and we don't get the
cooperation we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia invaded East Timor in 1975, sparking a war of
resistance. By 1980, 200,000 people had died from battle, famine
and disease. Indonesia's military is blamed for gross human rights
abuses in East Timor over the years, and for aiding pro-Jakarta
militias. Australia was the only major nation to recognize
Indonesian rule in East Timor, but it also became Jakarta's loudest
critic during the latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia Thursday scrapped a 4-year-old security treaty with
Australia to protest perceived meddling and support for Timorese
independence. It was largely symbolic, but it exposes growing
tensions in what is arguably the most important strategic
relationship in the south Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Australia spends nearly $5 billion a year training Indonesian
military officers at Australian colleges and in joint exercises
here and in Indonesia. Australia even trained Indonesia's special
forces branch _ which is blamed for orchestrating militia violence
in East Timor _ until last October, when strong evidence of human
rights abuses elsewhere by the unit emerged.
</P>
<P>
   At a protest in Jakarta Thursday, one demonstrator held a banner
reading: ``Australian soldiers welcome to East Timor. Graves have
been prepared for you. Rest in hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australian embassy in Jakarta, the consulate in Bali and
several Australian businesses received threatening telephone calls
Thursday, and two Australian mining companies pulled staff out to
Singapore as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   An advance team of 25 Australian and 25 Thai military officers
will visit East Timor Saturday and the first wave of 2,000 foreign
troops is expected to deploy by Monday, Indonesian military
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise announcement, Indonesia's commander in East Timor,
Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri, said his troops would pull out once UN
forces arrive. ``Once they get in, I will pull out. I hope the
process will take not more than one week,'' he told Reuters news
service. It was unclear, however, whether he was referring to the
multinational force or to a UN-organized force expected to replace
this mission later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
