<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sept. 17 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-FRAMEUP (Los Angeles) _ A 22-year-old man was freed from
prison after prosecutors concluded he had been framed by an LAPD
officer who has led police to a massive corruption probe involving
11 other officers. Javier Ovando was release from prison on Salinas
and was expected to be taken into custody by immigration officials
for a deportation hearing. By Rick Orlov, Lisa Van Proyen and
Philip Browne. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT-REPORT (Los Angeles) _ After a four-hour meeting with
the Los Angeles school board, Superintendent Ruben Zacarias said he
will step aside from discussions of discipline and terminations
stemming from the Mullinax Report. The report found widespread
wrongdoing and incompetence among top LAUSD administrators,
including Zacarias. By Greg Gittrich, Beth Barrett and David Baker.
(Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CHIMP-NAME (Los Angeles) _ The chimp with the mystery father at
the Los Angeles Zoo at least has a name now: Jake. After sorting
through the suggestions of more than 1,000 children, Los Angeles
Zoo officials selected the name submitted by 10-year-old Miguel
Guzman of Compton. The identity of the chimp's father has still not
been determined. By Troy Anderson. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-CINEMAS (Los Angeles) _ Massachusetts-based General
Cinemas, which has been focusing on its Northeast and Midwest
operations, is moving toward selling the half-dozen multiplex
theaters it operates in the Los Angeles area in a reflection of the
declining popularity of older theaters. By Dave McNary. (Will move
in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOMAIN-TEEN (Los Angeles) _ Sterling Clark is hoping her ticket
to a music career leads through the White House. The 15-year-old
Studio City intern wants to finance her college education with the
proceeds of the sale of an especially presidential Internet domain
name. Just $150,000 buys the following:
``President-of-the-USA.com.'' For another $30,000, buyers also can
have ``President-USA.net.'' But Jeff Tinsley, chief executive of a
domain name broker GreatDomains, which recently auctioned Drugs.Com
for more than $800,000, said Sterling is shooting a bit high for
the domain name she owns. His advice: Ask for $30,000. By Jason
Cohen. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
