<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-LETTER     09-16 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-LETTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SHOOTER SENT STRANGE LETTERS TO PAPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Larry Gene Ashbrook sent at least two
letters to the Fort Worth Star-Telegram over the summer describing
bizarre tales of encounters with the Central Intelligence Agency,
psychological warfare, assaults by co-workers and druggings by
police.
</P>
<P>
   In the letters, dated July 31 and Aug. 10, Ashbrook said some
people mistakenly believed that he was a serial killer or child
abductor or linked to several high-profile crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were outlandish things in these letters,'' City Editor
Stephen Kaye.MDNM/ said. The first letter ``rambled. It was hard to
follow. It didn't seem very plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate reaction was that there was not much we could do
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Ashbrook paid a visit to Kaye at the Star-Telegram's
downtown office.
</P>
<P>
   But the man Kaye recalls meeting was unlike the man the nation
has come to know as the man who shot seven people to death and
wounded seven others Wednesday night. Ashbrook also killed himself
after the slaughter at Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, he was just the opposite of someone you'd be
concerned about,'' said Kaye, describing Ashbrook as a tall, thin
man with somewhat long hair. ``He was very cordial. He was very
apologetic for bothering me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying, `You're not a bother, I just can't do anything
for you. These are hard things to prove that are in your letter.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, who made one unsuccessful attempt to contact Ashbrook by
phone after receiving the letters, invited him to send a letter to
the editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm sorry to take your time up,' '' Kaye said. ``He
couldn't have been any nicer.''
</P>
<P>
   Managing Editor Kathy Vetter.MDNM/ also received copies of the
letters from Ashbrook, and wrote him a short reply saying that the
paper could offer no remedy for his problems and suggesting that he
seek an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the letters appeared threatening, Vetter and Kaye
said. Had they been, police would have been contacted, Vetter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see letters like that two and three times a week,'' Vetter
said. They are often from people who feel they're being persecuted,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, you just can't look at these things and see
danger. I wish I could do that, because if I had that ability,
those things would go to the cops every time. But 99.99 percent of
them are just people who want to vent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before in my career have they turned out to be anything,
and it's hard to believe that they ever will again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The letters were given to Fort Worth police Thursday, after Kaye
heard a radio program about Ashbrook and realized his connection to
the letters.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said Thursday that they had not had time to read the
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Having met Ashbrook left an impression on Kaye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can go through a situation like this, where
you've had a contact with someone and then this has happened, and
not feel something,'' said Kaye, who is part of the team of editors
coordinating news coverage of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a little eerie that he was here and that he was
reaching out to the newspaper,'' Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators interviewed a man Thursday who had been
circulating letters in the community warning about germ warfare
after residents became concerned that the letters might have come
from Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   That man said he stopped distribution a couple of days ago after
a police officer told him that residents were complaining and
warned him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Bob Garrity Jr..MDNM/ said there appears to be no
connection between Ashbrook and the germ-warfare letters.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
