<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-ART-425&AMP;A     09-16 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-ART-425&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 18 DIE, HUNDREDS HURT AS BOMB EXPLODES IN SOUTHERN
RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The threat of terrorism spread to Russia's heartland
Thursday as a huge explosion tore apart an apartment complex in the
southern city of Volgodonsk, killing at least 18 people and leaving
more than 200 injured.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing, at 5:57 a.m., was the fifth in Russia in less than
three weeks and underscored how vulnerable Russia remains to
terrorist attacks, even with heightened security. Almost 280 people
have died in the mysterious series of explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's blast bore the hallmarks of the earlier detonations
that have frightened and bewildered the public. The target was an
apartment house for ordinary citizens. The bomb went off as they
were sleeping. And no one claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The blast went off just nine miles from a nuclear power plant.
Russian authorities said the plant was unfinished and had not been
supplied with nuclear fuel. But the episode has generated concern
that terrorists may turn to their attention to Russia's vast
nuclear infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin signed a decree calling on law
enforcement and other government agencies to develop plans within
three days to protect industry, transportation, communications,
food processing centers and nuclear complexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to grit our teeth,'' Putin told a meeting of Russia's
cabinet. ``I'm calling on you to be more disciplined and vigilant,
in deeds not words.''
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin said security forces would try to seal
off the breakaway republic of Chechnya. There should be ``no
transport links'' to Chechnya, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tough talk, the images on the television news
Thursday night seemed to underscore the nation's defenselessness.
The bomb in Volgodonsk was hidden inside a truck or in a manhole.
It left a 50-foot-wide crater. The facade of the apartment house
was peeled away and the ground littered with mutilated bodies.
</P>
<P>
   One woman featured in Thursday night's news broadcast regained
consciousness in the hospital only to find out that her husband was
dead and her children missing. The death toll is likely to rise as
rescuers pick through the debris. About 25 of those hospitalized
are in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's bombing is the first outside Moscow since the string
of explosions began Aug. 31 at the upscale Manezh shopping center
near the Kremlin. The blast Thursday suggested that terrorists were
responding to the stepped-up security in the capital by taking
their campaign to less protected towns and cities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Volgodonsk, about 700 miles south of Moscow, was established in
1956 when workers came to the area to build a dam and hydroelectric
plant. A factory, formerly named after Soviet leader Leonid
Brezhnev, was built there to produce equipment for nuclear power
stations.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion also gave some credence to ominous reports that a
band of Islamic militants was planning a nationwide campaign of
violence. Vyacheslav Izmailov, who is a specialist on the Caucasus
for the newspaper Novaya Gazeta and is also a retired military
officer, said he had been tipped off by an informant that 10
attacks were planned in Moscow and that other bombings would take
place in St. Petersburg and in the Rostov area, where Volgodonsk is
located.
</P>
<P>
   Izmailov said the informant indicated the explosions were
organized by two leaders of the Islamic insurgency in Dagestan,
Shamil Basayev and Khattab. But he said the attacks are being
carried out by Slavic mercenaries, as well as Chechens, making it
difficult for the authorities to identify the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Basayev and Khattab have denied any involvement. But Izmailov's
account has been widely accepted by many Russians, adding to the
climate of fear.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The bombing has unnerved residents of Rostov-on-Don, a large
city about 120 miles to the west, where a festival has been planned
for Saturday to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Moscow explosions, we canceled the evening festival
events,'' a Rostov resident named Tatyana, who declined to give her
last name, said in a telephone interview. ``After Volgodonsk, we
canceled the entire festival. People are really scared.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tatyana, Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and other
dignitaries from the capital were expected at the celebration, but
now only Patriarch Aleksy II of the Russian Orthodox Church is
planning to attend a religious service.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As rescuers combed through the rubble at Volgodonsk, police in
Moscow continued their efforts to safeguard the capital. A police
spokesman said that a new cache of explosives _ more than three
tons disguised as 76 sacks of sugar _ was found in a garage.
</P>
<P>
   The garage was rented by the same man who leased space in the
two apartment houses demolished in bombing attacks here. He used
the stolen passport of a dead man named Mukhit Laipanov.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Moscow police said they had uncovered another large
cache of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovsky, a tycoon and former executive secretary of the
Commonwealth of Independent States, an organization of former
Soviet republics, said he believed the blasts had been organized by
Chechen militants.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that Russia's leading politicians were to blame
because they failed to come up with a political plan for restoring
Chechnya or develop a military plan to contain the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrorist acts won't be halted,'' he said. ``It will go on for
a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
