<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-MASSIEU-0917-C     09-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSIEU-0917-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH SUICIDE NOTE, FORMER DRUG PROSECUTOR TRIES TO IMPLICATE
MEXICAN PRESIDENT IN KILLINGS
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With a fatal overdose of anti-depressants, Mario
Ruiz Massieu beat the rap the U.S. government was about to mount
against him alleging drug trafficking at some of the highest levels
in the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday _ the day after his reported suicide _ it became
clear that the former Mexican anti-drug prosecutor was still trying
to strike back from the grave.
</P>
<P>
   In a suicide note revealed by his lawyer Thursday in New Jersey,
Ruiz Massieu accused Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo of being
involved in the 1994 assassination of presidential candidate Luis
Donaldo Colosio, who represented Mexico's ruling Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   He also implicated Zedillo in the 1994 killing of Ruiz Massieu's
brother, Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu, who was also a high-ranking
PRI official.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations in Mario Ruiz Massieu's note were immediately
dismissed by members of the Zedillo administration, who were busy
with activities on Thursday celebrating Mexico's Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mario Ruiz Massieu lived lying and died lying,'' said Mexican
Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, interviewed by reporters at
an Independence Day parade. ``Mr. Mario Ruiz Massieu on various
occasions tried to deflect blame by tossing smoke bombs to confuse
public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The assassinations of Colosio and Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu
are woven into a tangled web of scandal and political and
drug-related violence that has disgusted Mexicans, tainted the PRI
and obliterated the reputation of Mexico's last president, Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, who served between 1988 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Mario Ruiz Massieu's suicide ``is another death along a
dark road in Mexico that leads nowhere and everywhere at the same
time,'' said Milenio magazine editor Ignacio Rodriguez Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Ruiz Massieu reportedly took his own life at his
home in New Jersey just two days before he was to be arraigned in
Houston on charges that he laundered $9.9 million in alleged drug
bribes. Last month Ruiz Massieu was indicted for illegally moving
the illicit millions into Texas banks from Mexico. He was under
house arrest in New Jersey, where he fled from Mexico four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The trial in Houston, Rodriguez Reyna said, could have revealed
potentially explosive allegations about drug traffickers' influence
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are politicians in Mexico who are breathing
easier today,'' Rodriguez Reyna said after hearing about the
suicide Wednesday. ``Massieu must have known who else in government
had ties to narcotics trafficking. There was always quiet talk in
government that prosecutors here were too afraid to look too deeply
into his drug connections.''
</P>
<P>
   During Salinas' administration, Ruiz Massieu was a deputy
federal prosecutor in charge of hunting down and jailing the same
narcotics traffickers he was accused of assisting.
</P>
<P>
   In March of 1995, Ruiz Massieu was traveling en route to Spain
when he was arrested at the Newark International Airport in New
Jersey for failing to declare all of $46,000 in cash he was
carrying.
</P>
<P>
   After Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu was murdered in 1994, Mario
Ruiz Massieu was the prosecutor put in charge of investigating the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, before his death, Mexican officials wanted to bring
Mario back to Mexico and have him stand trial on corruption charges
and for allegedly covering up the real story behind his brother's
death.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Mexican authorities tried to have Ruiz Massieu
extradited to Mexico to face charges related to his brother's
murder and abuse of his authority. Authorities here say Ruiz
Massieu conducted a sham investigation designed to protect his
brother's real killer _ Raul Salinas, Carlos Salinas' brother, who
has been convicted in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas is also believed to have accepted millions of
dollars in bribes from drug traffickers. Swiss authorities believe
he stashed the drug money in Swiss and British bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu's lawyers say he was suffering from extreme
depression and apparently could not face the possibility of a
conviction and life in prison in connection with the charges in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Ruiz Massieu claimed he was innocent and the
victim of a conspiracy built on fabricated evidence and paid
witnesses. He apparently did not try to link Zedillo to drug
trafficking in his final message to the public, but he didn't mince
words about the assassinations of Colosio and his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``To find my brother's murderers an investigation should be
initiated beginning with Zedillo,'' Ruiz Massieu wrote in the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to Colosio and his brother, Ruiz Massieu also
wrote, ``(Zedillo) and I know that he was not detached from both
political crimes of 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Zedillo administration predicted that Ruiz
Massieu's accusations would not take root in Mexico and would fade
after several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not dealing with a martyr here,'' the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, added. He said Ruiz Massieu's
reputation was so poor that few would take him seriously for long.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico is a country where conspiracy theories thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Some here met the news of Ruiz Massieu's reported death by
suicide with skepticism. A few people interviewed on streets in
Mexico City by television stations said they thought it was
possible Ruiz Massieu was killed to keep him from spilling too many
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in New Jersey said Ruiz Massieu appeared to have died
by taking an overdose of Zoloft, a drug used to treat depression.
An autopsy is being performed.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman John Russell at the U.S. Justice Department in
Washington, said that the case against Ruiz Massieu will probably
be dismissed after an official cause of death is confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire services contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
