u a BC-COLLEGE-Y2K17-COX     09-16 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-Y2K17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K concerns cause Ohio schools to delay winter term
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Y2K bug _ or at least the fear of it _ is
stinging some of the region's colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Dayton will postpone the start of its winter
term two days and Cedarville College one day as a precautionary
measure against potential year-2000 computer glitches. Other
schools will closely watch events to determine whether they'll need
to cancel classes for a ``calamity day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton and Cedarville join Ohio State University, which had
already announced it would delay the start of classes from Jan. 3
to Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   School officials insist their own computer systems are _ or soon
will be _ Y2K compliant, and they foresee no major problems on
their technology-dependent campuses. But some out-of-state students
and their families had let school folks know they didn't
particularly want to fly cross-country the day after the witching
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're being extra-cautious, which is fine'' for this
unique circumstance, said Tom Westendorf, UD's registrar. UD will
start winter classes Jan. 5 instead of Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   UD's computer and telecommunications specialists told university
officials they were concerned about Y2K-related problems in the
newly expanded student network and recommended the delay to ensure
the system was healthy and ready for students when they return,
Westendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Cedarville College spokesman Roger Overturf said the college's
decision to push back winter term one day was made ``to allay the
fears of those who have Y2K concerns,'' especially those who must
travel to return to school. Cedarville will now start classes Jan.
4.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State University officials don't expect any serious Y2K
problems on campus, but OSU Interim Chief Information Officer James
Davis said it's ``impossible to anticipate all Y2K-related problems
or to predict all Y2K-related behaviors with 100 percent certainty.
While the probability of major problems is now very low, there will
continue to be a risk of glitches that will need to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Miami Valley schools _ including Edison Community College,
Central State University and Antioch College _ already are
scheduled to start later in January and do not face a decision on
whether to postpone the startup of winter term. Wright State
University, Sinclair Community College and the University of
Cincinnati are among schools deciding to make no change in their
Jan. 3 resumption of classes.
</P>
<P>
   A special Wright State task force examined the potential impact
of Y2K, gathering information from hundreds of suppliers and
vendors that provide the university's power, transportation,
financial and other services, and came away assured that there
would be no significant problems, said Paul Hernandez, WSU's
director of computing and telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   If major problems do occur, WSU will follow the same delay and
cancellation procedures it would for a weather emergency, Hernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair will approach the challenge the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Jan. 2, if we find the world is caving in around us, we
may announce we won't have classes the next day,'' Sinclair
spokesman Gary Honnert said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
