<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINA-ARCHAEOLOGY-EXH     09-16 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ARCHAEOLOGY-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A VERY BIG DIG _ CHINA'S TROPHIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: D.C. area, Houston, San Francisco)   (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology: Celebrated Discoveries
from the People's Republic of China,'' which opens Sunday at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington, makes every possible effort
to knock your socks off. And through a sheer bigger-than-life,
Turandot-in-Beijing style spectacle it succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a compilation of more than 200 objects, many of
which have been brought to light in China during the past 25 years
or so. The National Gallery did a similar show in 1974 in
cooperation with the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City;
the current one, put together by the same museums, is being billed
as a kind of update.
</P>
<P>
   The time frame covered is broad, to put it mildly. It begins in
the late prehistoric period, circa 5000 to 2000 B.C., and ends
semi-late, in the 10th century A.D. The media represented are many:
bronze, lacquerware, jade and silk head an eclectic list. The
objects selected run from exemplary to awesome, and they are served
up in a theatrical, charisma-enhancing installation.
</P>
<P>
   You don't just look at this show. You are encouraged to gasp at
the sight of colossal bronze cauldrons, sigh over long-buried
silks, get the shivers in a simulated crypt and enjoy an interlude
of comic relief at the sight of snooty court ladies with figures as
round as pots.
</P>
<P>
   The total spectacle is riveting and rewards any time spent with
it. But, that said, there are some caveats. The material isn't all
that fresh. Several of the big-gun attractions _ the jade shroud
from the tomb of Liu Sheng, terra-cotta warriors from Shaanxi _
have been textbook staples for years. And certain pieces, or types
of pieces, are repeats from the Guggenheim Museum's popular
``China: 5000 Years,'' which played New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the National Gallery exhibition, like the
Guggenheim's, is conceived on a badly outmoded, trophy-show model,
one that both creates and reinforces an appetite for more of the
same. There are differences though in the approaches the two
institutions have taken.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim presented its Chinese art Bloomingdales-style, by
medium. Walking up the Frank Lloyd Wright ramp, you had your bronze
department; you had your jade department. Everything looked
expensive and beautiful, which, of course, it was. But any sense of
historical or social complexity, or of diverse cultures _ elite and
nonelite, urban and regional _ bubbling up in China, has been
glamorized out of existence, and just at the time when with-it art
historical research is pointing in exactly the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington show, organized by Xiaoneng Yang, curator of
Chinese art at the Nelson-Atkins, at least complicates that
picture. The title declares right up front that, yes, this is a
buffet event, heavier on snacks than food (there is a distinction),
though some of the snacks will be pretty sensational. And the show
makes an effort to suggest the myriad, often interactive cultures
at work in a huge chunk of geography over a long history.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition starts with Neolithic vessels and jades unearthed
at various sites, mostly in the 1970s and '80s. Taken together they
might be seen as a kind of esthetic starter kit; the seeds of
Chinese writing, figurative art and the near-mystical reverence for
jade are all here.
</P>
<P>
   So is a wealth of eye-catching beauty. From the Majiyayao
culture comes a clay pot covered with whorls of calligraphic black
lines. And from the Taosi Longshan culture is a basin painted with
suavely moderne patterns of tilting pink and white rectangles on a
black ground. This vessel turned up in 1982; its design is, so far,
unique, and it is making its publication debut in the show's
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronze Age, circa 2000 to 771 B.C., brings onto the stage
metal objects, the ritual beakers and cups and wine jars that have
for centuries been regarded as spiritual embodiments of ancient
China. Whether petite or ponderous (one cooking pot in the show
creaks in at 500 pounds), they are utensils rather than sculptures,
with specific uses in life and beyond the grave.
</P>
<P>
   No art made anywhere else really resembles them. With their
dark, amphibious-looking, gravity-soaked forms, they suggest living
things, silently absorbing and radiating energy. Yet for all their
heft they can be lyrical, even buoyant, with rhythmic lines coiling
across their surfaces, and arpeggios of tacklike knobs standing out
in relief.
</P>
<P>
   The show offers stellar examples of the early dynastic vessel
types familiar in many Western museums. But it also includes a
group of startlingly expressive figurative sculptures that were
produced in southern China during the same period and occupy a
different universe from the northern classical norm.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are three hollow bronze heads, two still partly
covered with gold leaf. Most impressive, though, is a life-size
figure, the only one yet recovered from Bronze Age China, perched
on a high base. Possibly a deity or a priest, his body tapers
gently upward (think of the shape of a wooden clothespin) from the
hem of his flared robe to his cylindrical head. He holds his
enormous hands, the fingers curled into circles, out in front of
him.
</P>
<P>
   This enigmatic being is among the more remarkable discoveries of
the 1980s. And though he is no longer hot archaeological news, his
presence here is important as a dramatic example of parallel
traditions flowing through Chinese art.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if the Washington show has anything substantially novel
to offer, it is its concentration of work from southern and
southwestern China. This is particularly true of a trove of
material from the state of Chu. Installed for maximum impact at the
top of the stairs in the second-floor galleries, it constitutes a
mini-show in itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Chu state flourished between the eighth and third centuries
B.C., far from the imperial capitals, and was once regarded by
historians as a semibarbaric backwater. But this view has been
revised. The sprawling state had an ambitious, sophisticated
aristocracy, a religion with shamanistic overtones and an
innovative art that is only beginning to be understood.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chu sculpture can be persuasively naturalistic, as in the case
of a painted lacquer deer with a teardrop-patterned coat and real
antlers. But it can also be outlandish beyond belief. An attenuated
bronze figure, with a plump bird's body, a serpentine neck and
horns bristling from its head is as surreal an image as China has
ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   This creature was discovered in the tomb of a nobleman, Marquis
Yi of Zeng, excavated in 1978, and is one of the revelatory finds
of the past quarter century. Snugly built, nearly airtight, the
tomb was essentially a below-ground version of a four-room palace.
</P>
<P>
   There was an armory and a bedroom, where the marquis was
interred with his eight concubines. The ``kitchen'' held the
coffins of 13 young women, presumably servants or musicians. And
the living room or reception hall was equipped with a full court
orchestra of chimes, woodwinds, drums and 65 bronze bells. These
bells are not in the show, but a set of 26 from another site is.
</P>
<P>
   The site yielded the single largest cache, pound for pound, of
bronze objects ever discovered in one place, and examples of this
hoard are on view. One is a bronze drum stand in the form of a
seething tangle of snakelike dragons that could come straight from
Rodin's ``Gates of Hell.'' Another is a wine vessel set in a low,
wide bowl, both covered with a filigree encrustation that looks
exquisite and pathological, as if it were eating away the solid
form beneath.
</P>
<P>
   Chu art has been described as flamboyant, but it goes way, way
beyond that into some wild, demonic rococo realm. Yet it also has
its stately side, evident in the stolid set of bells in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Such instruments were not casual accessories, the Chu equivalent
of a piano in the parlor; they were emblems of social and political
power as well as a source of pleasure. The central, symbolic role
of music in ancient Chinese culture is a rich field for
cross-disciplinary research, and it is the subject of at least two
other exhibitions this season: one opens Friday at China Institute
in New York; the other is scheduled to open April 30 at the Arthur
M. Sackler Gallery in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When the National Gallery show arrives at imperial China, it is
on well-trod ground. Here, as at the Guggenheim, one finds a suite
of life-size terra-cotta warriors and horses from the tomb of the
first emperor at Shaanxi. Also on hand is the body-fitting jade
shroud from the tomb of Liu Sheng. From the top of its helmet to
the soles of its booties, it is made of hundreds of small cut
plaques sewn together with gold thread. In the same room is a less
finely made shroud, which has recently been rebound with red silk.
</P>
<P>
   The show ends with the Tang dynasty, 618 to 906 A.D., an
effervescent, expansive era. Its cosmopolitan spirit is evident in
examples of Buddhist art, a foreign import, and in painted clay
statuettes of mounted riders, male and female. Each is a
near-caricatural sketch of the non-native people who filled the
Tang cities, adding to the multicultural dynamo that China has
always been.
</P>
<P>
   Taken from start to finish, ``The Golden Age of Chinese
Archaeology'' is an eventful trip. But with so many aspects of
Chinese art crying out for elucidation (it's amazing how much we
don't know about the function and meaning of ancient material), how
helpful is such a show?
</P>
<P>
   International exhibitions on this scale are geared to be many
things: crowd-pleasers and good-will advertisements for nations,
corporate sponsors and institutions. But they should also be major
opportunities for advancing knowledge, bringing scholarly minds,
far-flung materials and challenging ideas together in ways that can
radically alter how a culture is seen.
</P>
<P>
   The pocket-survey of Chu material embedded within the National
Gallery show, and last season's ``Edo: Art in Japan, 1615-1868'' at
the same museum, prove that focused exhibitions of unfamiliar
material can be visually smashing, intellectually stimulating and
enormous fun. Our major museums are the only ones in a position to
bankroll such enterprises. The Washington showcase of Chinese work,
which must have cost a bundle, is highly diverting, and often more
than that. But now it's time for some grown-up exhibitions of this
very grown-up art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology: Celebrated Discoveries
from the People's Republic of China'' opens on Sunday and remains
at the National Gallery of Art, Fourth Street at Constitution
Avenue, NW, Washington, (202) 737-4215, through Jan. 2. The
exhibition, sponsored by Eastman Kodak Co., travels to the Museum
of Fine Arts in Houston (Feb. 13-May 7) and the Asian Art Museum in
San Francisco (June 17-Sept. 11).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
