<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK STILL MAKING THE CASE FOR EFFECTIVENESS OF NATO BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Gen. Wesley K. Clark, NATO's supreme allied
commander, ended the bombing of Yugoslavia more than three months
ago. But this week he was still waging a high-intensity battle to
convince allied public opinion that the bombing had been as
effective in Kosovo as he said it was in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by almost a squadron of allied military pilots and about
20 linear feet of secret bound folders of bomb-damage assessment
reports, he took his campaign to the stage of a NATO news-briefing
auditorium here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation, Clark produced evidence to counter
suggestions from several sources that the allied command had
exaggerated or deliberately distorted claims of damage to Serbian
military and police forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We destroyed enough'' he summed up. ``The conflict ended on
NATO's terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. John Corley of the U.S. Air Force, chief of an allied
assessment team that went to Kosovo after the Serbian forces had
pulled out, said exhaustive investigations had led to the
conclusion that actual damage was almost what pilot reports had
thought it had been in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Corley said that allied planes from the United States, France,
Britain, Germany, the Netherlands and other countries had hit 93
Serbian tanks and that 26 of those strikes were considered
``catastrophic kills,'' with wreckage found on the ground by his
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs had asserted, and some western news organizations had
reported, that just 13 tanks had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Corley said the assessment team had concluded that 153 armored
combat vehicles, 339 other military trucks and transports and 389
artillery pieces and mortars had been hit and badly damaged, if not
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were not that far off those given by Clark when the
bombs stopped falling in June. He estimated then that 110 tanks,
210 armored fighting vehicles and 449 artillery pieces had been
struck. Thursday, his assessment was that the bombing had put out
of action more than a quarter of the 350 tanks, a third of the 430
armored combat vehicles and more than half the 600 to 750 heavy and
light cannon, anti-aircraft guns and other heavy weapons that the
allies believed Serbian forces had in Kosovo during the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   As he and the pilots did earlier this week here for NATO
ambassadors and senior military officials, Clark and his briefers
produced pictures and videos to show that the withdrawing Serbian
forces had dragged off many damaged tanks and other heavy equipment
for possible salvage.
</P>
<P>
   And despite earlier reports that the Serbs had flummoxed allied
pilots who were flying at 15,000 feet with scores of clever
cardboard and plastic tank and artillery decoys on the ground, the
generals said NATO fliers were well aware of Serbian deception
tactics and had hit nine tank decoys and 16 other mock-ups of other
heavy weapons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But for a military commander who presided over a 78-day mission
that produced not a single allied casualty in combat and achieved
the aim of allowing hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanian
refugees to return home after the Serbian forces had been driven
out of the province, Clark seemed surprisingly on the defensive,
perhaps because political leaders in allied capitals have been
asking how effective the bombing really was since it ended.
</P>
<P>
   Early this summer, he got an unpleasant surprise when the
Pentagon and the White House announced that he would be moved aside
two months early, next April, to make room for his successor, Gen.
Joseph W. Ralston of the Air Force, vice chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs,
confirmed that the British general in charge of NATO forces in
Kosovo had rejected an order from Clark to send in tanks and
armored personnel carriers to seize the Pristina airfield from
Russian troops who occupied it in June. The Russians were staking
out a claim there to participate in operations .
</P>
<P>
   Clark would not comment Thursday on that incident. Instead, he
confined most of his answers to questions about the effectiveness
of the bombing of Serbian forces in Kosovo, even while dismissing
``bean counting'' of targets destroyed as a flawed indicator of
success in the bombing campaign. The ultimate measure of that, he
said, was the Serbian pullout.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bombing have often pointed out, however, that
before that occurred, allied air power had been unable to prevent
Serbian paramilitary forces and the police from systematically
laying waste to scores of villages in Kosovo, killing thousands of
civilians and driving out hundreds of thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
   A planner of the bombing campaign, Col. Edward Boyle, said
Thursday: ``Only 50 percent of the flying days were good weather.
It was not a perfect world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And allied concern about inadvertently causing civilian
casualties by high-altitude bombing led commanders to call off many
attacks after Albanian refugees died in an air attack on Serbian
forces who had mixed in with them in a road convoy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Phil Haun, an Air Force A-10 pilot based in Germany who
flew 25 missions in Kosovo, said, ``The Serbs reacted to everything
we did. There were peaks and valleys. Our actual tactics evolved
over the period, but the Serbs were very smart on the ground and on
how we engaged them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark declined to say whether he thought that targeting Serbian
forces in Kosovo was as important or more important than the
strategic bombing of power plants, radio stations, military
headquarters and other key installations inside Serbia itself in
getting President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to capitulate to
NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single mission is documented,'' Clark said. ``All the
lessons learned in this campaign have to be approached from the
point of view that NATO achieved what it set out to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
