<HEADER>
A4942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUGAR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-16 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGAR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUGAR TOWN': A LOS ANGELES SNAPSHOT OF ASHRAMS AND AMBITION 
</HEADLINE>
 ( Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af) 
By JANET MASLIN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night, not long after having had her chakra unblocked by a
good-looking therapist, a hilariously Type A film production
designer named Liz (Ally Sheedy) meets the guy fixing the wheat
grass machine at the health food store. When they go out on a date,
she tries to figure out whether his career prospects are any better
than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this like a resting place for you?'' Liz asks sweetly.
``That's not a judgmental question.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when it's time for the good night clinch, he says ``I'm
not sure it's appropriate for the first date, but ...'' Liz closes
her eyes and puckers her lips. But instead of a kiss she gets an
envelope full of head shots of her companion, who turns out to be
an aspiring actor. ``Seeing as you meet so many directors and
all,'' he explains, and that is hardly the end of it. Not much
later in ``Sugar Town,'' the same user wants Liz to provide a
reference for him when he rents a condo.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to pick a favorite character in this knowing,
warmly funny Los Angeles ensemble film, although Ms. Sheedy's
performance as the high-strung embodiment of every known self-help
fad is hard to beat. But all the actors in this nimble comedy
directed by Allison Anders (``Gas Food Lodging'') and Kurt Voss
share the same amusingly jaundiced view of show business, and of
its own special brands of back-stabbing and striving.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a lovingly etched set of characters who are variously
on the ways up or down, and who can never stop obsessing about the
difference, Ms. Anders and Voss shot their film in only three weeks
and successfully caught lightning in a bottle. The use of friends'
houses and clothes contributes to the gratifying indie spirit here,
but best of all is the spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The actors in this Altmanish weaving of stories play their
roles with obvious zeal. And many of them happen to be very
familiar with this comic terrain.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of ``Sugar Town'' centers on a group of aging rock stars
who look like the real thing. (And they should: the group is played
most amusingly by John Taylor of Duran Duran, Martin Kemp of
Spandau Ballet and Michael Des Barres, whose ex-wife Pamela wrote
the book on California groupiedom.) Clive (Taylor) still has
die-hard groupies at the doorstep he shares with Eva (Rosanna
Arquette), a once-hot tamale of an actress who has just auditioned
for the role of Christina Ricci's mother.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Perfectly in keeping with the spirit of the film is the scene
in which a woman from an ashram arrives with a son she claims is
Clive's. Even though she and Clive have matching tattoos, he claims
not to remember her. Then she abandons the boy, who wears ghoul
makeup, thinks he's a lot cooler than his father and hates being
called Nirvana. He prefers Nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Los Angeles would this happy family coexist with a
Topanga Canyon guitarist and pig farmer (John Doe), who has a
pregnant wife and a brother known as ``Uncle Rick the Junkie,'' or
with Gwen (Jade Gordon), the new housekeeper who's busy doing an
``All About Eve'' job on Liz.
</P>
<P>
   As played by the attention-getting Ms. Gordon with wonderful
guile, Gwen starts her climb by persuading Liz to wear a smock on a
date with a record producer (Larry Klein, a real producer), then
snagging the man herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just too funny,'' she coos at him. ``Just a guy who
hates pretense,'' he replies. That's the kind of sweet talk that
gives this wise little comedy its name.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `SUGAR TOWN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Allison Anders and Kurt Voss; director
of photography, Kristian Bernier; edited by Chris Figler; music by
Larry Klein; production designer, Alyssa Coppelman; produced by
Daniel Hassid; released by USA Films/October Films. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Rosanna Arquette (Eva), Beverly D'Angelo (Jane), Michael
Des Barres (Nick), John Doe (Carl), Martin Kemp (Jonesy), Ally
Sheedy (Liz), Larry Klein (Burt), Jade Gordon (Gwen) and John
Taylor (Clive). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   `Sugar Town' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes occasional profanity and sexual
situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
