<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-TECH17-COX     09-16 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-TECH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    During the storm season, it helps to think low-tech
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes it takes a hurricane to remind us of who we
can trust when the lights go out.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine for a moment that your telephone and electrical service
are out.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know what the Weather Channel is saying about the
hurricane? Unless you have a laptop computer and a wireless modem,
you're out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   You can type www.weather.com until the moon is blue and nothing
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   And that cable modem of yours? It's a rather ugly little box
sitting by that equally worthless big screen TV. The power of
technology _ for most of us _ is literally gone with the wind at
times like that.
</P>
<P>
   Even battery-powered cell phones and pagers depend on being in
range of a transmitting cell (and if you own either, you've almost
certainly found a ``dead zone'' or two, storm or no storm). And if
the wind gets strong enough and knocks down a few cell sites, then
things will be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, that transistor radio _ the one you bought
for $11.95 down at Target _ cranks right up. Spin the dial and
you'll find some of the best weather information available.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fancy radar maps and streaming video images of guys
with good haircuts standing in the rain, you'll hear calm, deep
voices from local radio stations telling you where to go if the
roof just blew off your house, what roads are closed, how to
contact your insurance agent and when to pack up the family and
start running for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, once you have the weather information you need, there's
something soothing about listening to a little music while the wind
blows.
</P>
<P>
   If you set great stock in those MP3 music clips you've been
downloading from the Internet, then you're in for a real surprise.
You just tune in to an oldies station and listen.
</P>
<P>
   I know this seems pretty obvious to you now. But how ready are
you for the next time the lights go out at your house?
</P>
<P>
   At times like that, most of us find that our logical skills and
memory are on par with that of a river otter. So now _ while you
are thinking clearly and the sky is a friendly blue _ take a moment
to assemble a home survival kit.
</P>
<P>
   First on our list are flashlights. Get several good ones and
make sure that you keep them supplied with fresh batteries. Now
stash them in several easy-to-find locations around the house.
After all, the rest of the kit that we assemble will be worthless
if you can't find it in the dark. (Keeping batteries tightly sealed
in a Ziploc bag placed in the refrigerator slightly extends their
life, by the way).
</P>
<P>
   Make one of the flashlights you buy a rechargeable one and keep
it plugged in to the AC power.
</P>
<P>
   Now add a transistor radio. If you can afford it, get one that
receives audio from television stations as well as the regular AM
and FM broadcast bands. You won't have any trouble finding a good
one for $40 or $50.
</P>
<P>
   While you are at the store, buy some candles. That way, even if
a storm never takes away your electrical power, you can turn down
the lights on purpose and have a romantic dinner with someone you
care about. If your companion is smart, they'll be impressed to be
around someone who knows enough about technology to use candles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
