<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SUICIDE NOTE, FORMER OFFICIAL BLAMES PRESIDENT FOR DEATH OF HIS
BROTHER
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This was added to A1 as a boxed reefer.) 
(sw) 
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a last, bitter attack on the political system he
once served, a former Mexican justice official who apparently
killed himself on Wednesday rather than face money laundering
charges in the United States blamed President Ernesto Zedillo for
both his own death and the assassination of his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Ruiz Massieu asserted in a suicide note that was made
public on Thursday by his widow that Zedillo never forgave his
criticism of governing party officials after his brother,
JoseFrancisco, a party leader, was shot to death in Mexico City in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took revenge for that,'' Ruiz Massieu, a former deputy
attorney general, wrote of the Mexican president. ``To find the
killers of my brother, an investigation must be undertaken that
starts with Zedillo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu offered no evidence to support his assertions. One
of his American lawyers, Cathy Fleming, suggested that some
information that Ruiz Massieu had never disclosed would be made
public ``at an appropriate time.'' But the Mexican attorney general
quickly dismissed the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the voice of a psychopath who is about to take
his own life,'' the attorney general, Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, said
in Mexico City. ``Mario Ruiz Massieu lived telling lies and he died
telling lies.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in her Manhattan offices less than 24 hours
after Ruiz Massieu was found unconscious in the New Jersey
apartment where he had been under house arrest, Ms. Fleming denied
earlier reports that he had feared being jailed in Houston, where
he was to have appeared in federal district court on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just got tired,'' she said. ``He didn't have the
fight anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long, legal struggle that began when he fled Mexico in
March 1994, Ruiz Massieu had overcome four different attempts by
the United States to extradite him to Mexico to face charges there
that included graft, money laundering and the abuse of his
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said he had acted to undermine the
investigation he led into the murder of his brother, so as to hide
the role of Raul Salinas de Gortari, a brother of Mexico's former
president, in ordering the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu had also survived a civil money laundering trial in
1997, after which the authorities seized nearly all of a $9 million
fortune he had secreted in Texas banks. Federal prosecutors
asserted that Ruiz Massieu, who led Mexico's anti-drug efforts at
the end of the administration of former President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, had taken bribes from some of the country's biggest drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ruiz Massieu had long been treated for depression and
was facing the most serious case yet made against him, his widow,
Maria Eugenia, said she had had no inkling that he had grown
desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew anything,'' she said, standing stoically before a
line of television cameras in Ms. Fleming's Manhattan offices.
``Our life was always normal and happy. He never showed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Ruiz Massieu never much resembled the man that
court files finally described.
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious, tightly wound lawyer, he had served in a long
series of government posts, including two stints as a deputy
attorney general and one as Mexico's ambassador to Denmark. He also
wrote a series of books, including one entitled, ``The Legal
Framework for the Combat of Drug Trafficking.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said an autopsy would be performed on Ruiz Massieu on
Friday, but that a toxicological report on the medication on which
he apparently overdosed could take days to complete. Ruiz Massieu,
however, left little doubt that he had decided to end his own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is I and only I who decides when to end my life in order to
recover freedom,'' he wrote. ``The killers are they who have taken
it away from me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
