<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-NYC17-COX     09-16 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-NYC17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From runways to runaways: Fashion Week rained out
 &HT;    By Scott Walton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manhattan was at its calmest and craziest Thursday as
it cowered under the eye of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani issued the order for schools and
businesses to close and people to go home no later than 3 p.m., it
was heeded. But New Yorkers did not go easily into the night.
</P>
<P>
   There were intervals when the din of police and fire sirens
pierced the soggy air. And then there were stretches of time when
the usual honking of horns in stalled traffic ceased, leaving
nothing but the hiss of drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   One minute, you saw cabbies and motorists jockeying for position
and exchanging profane gestures in Times Square. The next, you saw
people with resigned looks of hopelessness trying to hail taxis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typical New York,'' said a stranded Bill Lasche, vice
president of product and trend direction of the Birmingham,
Ala.-based Saks Inc. ``I don't mean that in a negative way. But
wouldn't you know this would happen during Fashion Week, when all
these designers had put so much effort into producing their
shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Saks Inc. fashion director Arlene Goldstein had checked out of
her Manhattan hotel as well only to find her flight back to
Birmingham had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those poor designers will never get back the momentum they had
going this week,'' Goldstein sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Fashion Week's governing body, 7th on Sixth, was forced
to announce the cancellation of the bulk of its runway show
schedule Thursday due to the mayor's weather emergency
pronouncement. The hope was to reschedule those pre-empted shows on
Saturday, when most of the editors from out of town had planned to
depart.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation swirled around Fashion Week's headquarters, The Tent
at Bryant Park, as to whether the maverick British designer
Alexander McQueen would go ahead and stage his spring/summer 2000
show on the Hudson River's Chelsea Pier late Thursday night,
regardless of the weather. (At 3 p.m., an hour before the brunt of
the storm was expected to hit Manhattan, a publicist for McQueen
answered the phone and said he would.)
</P>
<P>
   Though New York's news outlets had taken great pains all week to
track Hurricane Floyd's path up the Eastern seaboard, the storm
still caught the clothing industry by surprise. Those attending
Bill Blass' farewell collection preview had to contend with The
Tent's leaking roof and two inches of standing water. And, horror
of all horrors, Vogue editor Anna Wintour showed up IN THE SAME
PLAID PLASTIC PONCHO four or five others had also received as
welcome-to-town gifts from Burberry's.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, the news station New York One cautioned viewers
against driving and forecast flood warnings and wind gusts of up to
50 mph. A polo-shirted Giuliani, who said 911 calls had doubled in
volume, was shown cautioning city residents. ``We're dealing with a
very serious storm,'' he said. ``You can hopefully avoid any fatal
danger. But you cannot avoid any inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Millennium Hotel on Times Square, doorman Adrian
Green kept order among those waiting for cabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it all today,'' Green said in a deep Carribean
accent. ``You've just got to roll with the punches. I'm standing
here with my feet all wet, but I don't want to let the guests know
it bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   And were guests tipping any better than usual given the
circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we do not discuss,'' Green said cordially.
``For all I know, you're with the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   When Amoc Dixit's turn at the cabstand finally came, the
Minnesotan ran for it like it was the last lifeboat off the
Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wanna know what this is like?'' Dixit asked over his
shoulder. ``It's so bad I have to take a train down to Philadelphia
just to catch a plane back home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
