<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-GUNS-T     09-16 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-GUNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SHOOTINGS REKINDLE GUN-LAW DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
and JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shootings at Wedgwood Baptist Church reignited a national
debate over gun control Thursday, but the usual passions were
cooled by the numbing realization that the unthinkable had happened
again.
</P>
<P>
   After a season of carnage that began with the April 20 shootings
at Columbine High School, the latest explosion of violence left
partisans on both sides searching for words to match their
emotions. A high school in Colorado. An office building in Atlanta.
A day-care center in Los Angles. Now a church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, again, we have seen a sanctuary violated by gun violence,
taking children brimming with faith and promise and hope before
their time,'' a somber President Clinton said. ``Our nation's
support and prayers are with the families of the victims, those
still suffering in the hospital, and the entire Fort Worth
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's stunned disbelief echoed across the country as
Americans grappled with yet another bloody tragedy involving a
troubled person with a gun. Seven people were fatally shot and
seven were wounded Wednesday when Larry Ashbrook, an emotionally
disturbed loner, opened fire during a youth prayer rally.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook, 47, ended the shooting spree by killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go again _ more images of kids who have been
completely traumatized because their friends have been killed in
front of them,'' said Joe Sudbay of Handgun Control Inc. ``These
are not isolated instances anymore. They are becoming almost
commonplace, and that's very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   For North Texas lawmakers, the shootings underscored the
oft-stated truism that violence can occur anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really struck home when I heard the news. I grew up a
couple of miles from there,'' said Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas.
``You know it could happen anywhere, and yet you always hope that
it won't happen in your own community.''
</P>
<P>
   Others focused on the fact that the shootings occurred in a
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence struck in that one place where we should feel most
secure,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving, Texas.
``So long as there are people who have no regard for the sanctity
of life, we will never be safe. Not even in God's house.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a ritual that has played out all too often this year,
both sides in the gun debate drew sharply different lessons from
the latest tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened because there are far too many guns and there is
far too much access to them in America,'' said Sudbay, a gun
control activist. ``The American people want stricter gun control.
They see the connection.''
</P>
<P>
   But GOP Rep. Joe Barton of Ennis, Texas, a gun rights advocate,
said more laws would not have changed anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who want to do bad things will be able to get
weapons,'' he said. ``If people are going to call for gun control,
why not call for the incarceration of 47-year-old men that are
depressed or call for closing down churches that want to have
public meetings on prayer?''
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth shootings also focused attention on Texas gun
laws. At a time when other states have responded to gun violence by
restricting sales and ownership, the Texas Legislature has
generally gone in the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   After approving a right-to-carry law in 1995, state lawmakers
passed legislation this year protecting gun manufacturers from some
lawsuits seeking damages for gun violence. In 1997, they removed
churches from the list of locations where concealed weapons are
automatically banned.
</P>
<P>
   Texas state Rep. Ray Allen, R-Grand Prairie, co-author of the
right-to-carry law, said the legislation might have helped prevent
Wednesday's tragedy if someone in the church had been armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A licensed holder might have been able to stop that attack or
at least divert attention until the police officer arrived,'' Allen
said. ``One deranged person with a gun can kill and reload again as
long as he faces no effective opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Suzanna Hupp, R-Lampasas, who survived the 1991
massacre that killed her parents at a Luby's cafeteria in Killeen,
said she sees no connection between the recent gun violence and gun
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns are not allowed in public schools, but there have been
shootings at schools. Look at where they are not occurring. There
have been no mass shootings at gun shows or at NRA conventions, yet
these are where the so-called gun nuts congregate,'' she said,
referring to the National Rifle Association. ``Let's get a clue,
folks, and use some brains and common sense on this issue. Let's
get past the emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno said the Fort Worth
shootings should lead to a re-examination of the national approach
to gun laws, mental health and hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999 alone, we have watched as innocent people were gunned
down while attending school, while walking home from a church or
synagogue, while playing at a summer camp, while working in their
offices, while delivering mail, and now while worshipping in their
church,'' she said. ``All of these events cry out for America to
come together and to address them in an effective, permanent
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   While cautioning against a rush to judgment about the cause of
the Fort Worth violence, Vice President Al Gore urged Congress to
approve gun control legislation. A House-Senate conference
committee is considering a package of proposals that would require
background checks for all gun show sales, ban high-capacity
ammunition clips and require safety devices for all new guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families across the country are having a discussion about guns
this morning, and almost every morning, because there are too many
of these tragedies. They didn't occur to this extent before there
was a flood of guns easily available to people,'' Gore said on
ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   But even some of the most ardent gun control advocates
questioned whether the latest violence will change any minds in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress wasn't moved by Columbine. Congress wasn't moved by
what happened in Atlanta. Congress wasn't moved by the shootings in
Los Angeles,'' Sudbay said. ``Is anything going to move Congress to
do something to protect America's kids from firearms?''
</P>
<P>
   NRA lobbyist Gib Lewis, a former Texas House speaker from Fort
Worth, said he will be ready if the shootings prompt efforts to
tighten state gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure if somebody tries to pass some restrictions on
guns,'' Lewis said, ``we will spring into action.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Michael D. Towle contributed to this report in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
