<HEADLINE>
SHOOTINGS DEVASTATE A PICTURE-PERFECT NEIGHBORHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN AUSTIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Nancy Dragoo was quietly paying bills in her
home office Wednesday evening when she heard hammering on the front
door and opened it to find a frantic woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``She pounded on my door and said, `Call 911, somebody's
shooting up the church,' '' said Dragoo, who lives across the
street from Wedgwood Baptist Church on Wales Avenue. ``I don't know
what I thought, 'cause I couldn't even believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Disbelief was the prevailing sentiment Thursday among residents
on the quiet, shaded street that borders the church where gunfire
left eight dead.
</P>
<P>
   Wales Avenue is the kind of place where people know their
neighbors, mothers hug little kids who live down the street, and
folks invite strangers into their neat, brick, ranch-style houses
for ice water on a hot day.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's a street that seems better suited to an episode
of ``Leave it to Beaver'' than one where TV satellite trucks cover
a mass killing and CNN crews offer to rent a resident's laundry
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't have happened here,'' said Cristina Robertson,
17, who has lived on Wales Avenue, a few hundred feet from the
church, most of her life. ``Nothing ever happens here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very close-knit neighborhood,'' she said. ``It's like
something out of a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of her neighbors, Robertson was outside Thursday
morning, surrounded by parents, younger children and teen-age
friends who stayed home from work and school to console one another
and come to grips with their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's voice shook as she looked toward the church that
looms so large in the neighborhood, and now in the national news.
Robertson was a longtime friend of Justin Ray , who died in the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson was visiting Damon Barnard, another neighbor, on
Thursday. Barnard was standing next to Ray when he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the one who carried him out,'' Robertson said of
Barnard. ``They were ... best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnard declined to discuss the killings. He stayed in the house
and plugged in the electric bass guitar that he frequently picked
with his Christian-rock band down the street at Wedgwood Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw it all,'' said his mother, Anita Barnard. As she spoke,
she put her hand to her mouth and clenched her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She and her children have lived in the neighborhood for 14
years. She was watching her youngest child in the front yard when
three police cars raced by the house with their lights on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   She jumped into her car and drove half a block, parked, jumped
out and began trying to find out what had happened to Damon, who
was in the church.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't remember how long it took her to learn whether her
own son had survived the shooting, but she has a pretty fair idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 500 years,'' she said. ``Too long to wonder if you child
is dead or alive.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
