<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No mystery: Friedman takes non-P.C. stance
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politically correct is not a term in Kinky Friedman's
vocabulary. The man who formed a band called the Texas Jewboys and
gained notoriety with such songs as ``Get Your Biscuits in the Oven
and Your Buns in the Bed'' has brought his same irreverent tone to
his series of mystery novels.
</P>
<P>
   His latest, ``Spanking Watson'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23), is not
likely to win any converts among critics who think the Texan
frequently weaves back and forth across the line of good taste.
</P>
<P>
   Set in New York, the novel revolves around detective Friedman's
(yes, his protagonist is named Kinky Friedman) search for a Dr.
Watson to his Sherlock Holmes. Throw in a lesbian dance class, mock
death threats and real murders, and you have another wacko
whodunit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect everybody to like it,'' Friedman said in a
telephone interview from Houston. ``Americans are the most hung-up
people on the planet _ racially, sexually and politically. We don't
grasp satire and irony very easily. Europeans are much more attuned
to satire. Why is it that Americans don't get it? Maybe we get what
we deserve, and we deserve Dr. Laura and Rush Limbaugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman's books sell well in the United States, but they do
even better in other countries. His novels have been translated
into 16 languages, and young German readers tell him they read his
books in both German and English to teach themselves English.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this shows is there is universal appeal and that the
books are clearly divinely inspired,'' Friedman quipped. ``The Lord
must be writing these books using me as a vessel.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman will sign books at 7 p.m. Sept. 24 at Chapter 11
Discount Books, 1544 Piedmont Ave. 404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Southern accent: The University of Alabama is launching a new
paperback reprint series, Deep South Books, that will spotlight
some of the best writers of the region. Among the first works to be
published are Vicki Covington's ``Gathering Home'' and ``The Last
Hotel for Women'' and Nanci Kincaid's ``Crossing Blood.''
Covington's books are set in the turbulent Civil Rights era in
Alabama, and Kincaid's novel deals with racial and political issues
in 1980s Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ghost writers: The output of dead authors continues to grow.
Following the release of ``McNally's Dilemma,'' written by Vincent
Lardo but with Lawrence Sanders' name prominently displayed on the
cover, Dutton is publishing ``Chain of Command,'' a new cop
thriller by William Caunitz (``One Police Plaza''). The only
problem: Caunitz died in 1996, and nowhere in Dutton's fall catalog
does it mention ``co-author'' Chris Newman.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literature abroad: Apparently reading tastes in other
countries mirror those of the United States. According to the
newsletter Publishing Trends, Danielle Steel's ``Granny Dan'' is
No. 1 in the United Kingdom, while Mary Higgins Clark's ``We'll
Meet Again'' occupies the top spot in France. Tom Wolfe's ``A Man
in Full'' is No. 4 in India.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
