 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta _ A free Fodor's Travel Seminar with Fodor's editorial
director Karen Cure is 7:30 tonight at Barnes &AMP; Noble in
Alpharetta. Cure will discuss planning the perfect weekend getaway,
using the newly designed Fodor's Gold Guides that give pointers on
quick trips to Cancun, Cozumel, New York, Orlando and other popular
destinations. 7660 North Point Parkway, Alpharetta. 770-993-8340.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta, Ga. _ The 19th Annual Arts in the Heart of Augusta on
the Riverwalk Friday through Sunday showcases visual and performing
artists representing 35 countries whose people live in Augusta.
Ireland's is the featured group, but there will be seven stages of
entertainment, juried fine arts and a crafts fair, hands-on art
activities for children and a global village with ethnic foods and
exhibits. 706-826-4702. Also, Historic Augusta's 7th Annual Antique
Show and Sale is at Enterprise Mill, a restored cotton mill built
in the late 1800s. Dealers will offer period furniture, fine art,
porcelain, jewelry and decorative accessories. 706-724-0436.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta, Ga. _ The Morris Museum of Art presents ``The
Charleston Renaissance,'' a comprehensive study of art created in
Charleston, S.C., between 1915 and the 1940s, through Nov. 7.
706-724-7501.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Social Circle, Ga, _ The Historic Homes of Social Circle Tour
on Saturday comprises seven historic homes, including the residence
of chef Nathalie Dupree, where her PBS television show ``Nathalie
Dupree Entertains'' is taped. Tickets $15. 770-464-0463.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Helen, Ga. _ Oktoberfest in northeast Georgia's Alpine village
begins Thursday and continues through Nov. 6, with German music,
authentic food and beer in the Festhalle. Thursdays-Saturdays in
September, daily except Sundays in October. 706-878-2181.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Macon, Ga. _ Sweet Georgia Jam celebrates Macon's musical
heritage through Sunday, with performances, street parties and
church concerts throughout the city. Featuring Otis Redding III,
Clarence Carter, Billy Joe Royal, Divine, T. Graham Brown and the
Macon Symphony. 912-743-7136 or www
</P>
<P>
   .maconartsalliance.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ellijay, Ga. _ The Fourth Annual Apple Pickin' Jubilee at
Hillcrest Orchards takes place Saturday and Sunday and Sept. 25-26.
The down-on-the-farm festival includes family-oriented activities
such as apple picking, milking a cow, honeybee demonstrations, pig
races, clogging, country bands, Southern barbecue, a petting farm,
wagon rides, children's games and a John Deere Derby. 706-273-3838.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gatlinburg, Pigeon Forge and Sevierville, Tenn. _ Smoky
Mountain Harvest Festival Sunday through October includes
decorating contests, special events and local craft shows.
1-800-267-7088.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frankfort, Ky. _ The Kentucky Folklife Festival, Thursday
through Saturday, includes barbecue, concerts, riverboat rides, art
and storytelling. 502-564-1792.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Raleigh _ The North Carolina Museum of Art presents ``Monet to
Moore: The Millennium Gift of Sara Lee Corporation'' today through
Nov. 7. The collection includes masterworks of impressionist and
modern European art. 919-839-6262.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lafayette, La. _ Festivals Acadiens, Friday through Sunday,
celebrates the rhythm of Cajun life in the heart of French
Louisiana with Cajun and Creole cooking, Zydeco bands, exhibits and
arts and crafts. 318-232-3737 or www.lafayettetravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Decatur, Ala. _ The Racking Horse World Celebration, Friday
through Sunday, features best-of-breed competition in 141 classes.
256-353-7225.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Palm Beach, Fla. _ The Flagler Museum presents ``A Young Man's
Legacy: Rare Photographs of the Titanic,'' opening Thursday and
continuing through Nov. 14. The exhibit includes rare and
unpublished photographs documenting the elaborate construction and
opulent interiors of the ill-fated ship. 561-655-2833.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lauderdale-by-the-Sea, Fla. _ Ocean Fest 99, Friday through
Sunday, features scuba divers from around the world gathering for
the Ocean Fest Dive Show and Festival, with 200 dive-related
exhibits. 1-800-699-6764.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ The Alabama Shakespeare Festival presents ``Lost
Highway: The Music and Legend of Hank Williams'' through Sunday.
The play, by Mark Harelik and Randal Myler, tells the story of one
of country music's most tragic stars through his music, including
``Your Cheatin' Heart'' and ``Mind Your Own Business.''
1-800-841-4273 or www.asf.net.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
