<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's been a Blass: The dean of U.S. designers says goodbye
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Blass said bye-bye to the clothing business
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old designer, who rose from humble beginnings in
Evansville, Ind., to become the darling of women with serious dough
presented his final collection to a crowd so appreciative of his
accomplishments that even hurricane warnings couldn't keep them
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of my swan song, this is more like `Swan Lake',''
Blass said as rain-soaked admirers lined up to offer post-show
congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most influential American designer (he was the
first to market his name in a big way and forever changed the
status of designers), Blass bid his adieu with a bang, not a
whimper. The runway preview of his decidedly dignified
spring/summer 2000 designs was spiced with Lenny Kravitz's raucous
rendition of ``American Woman,'' Stevie Ray Vaughn's ``Pride and
Joy'' and Elvis Presley's ``Jailhouse Rock.'' (The latter
accompanied models strutting in horizontally striped sequined
pants.)
</P>
<P>
   Proving he hasn't lost touch with what's trendy, Blass showed:
pants that rolled seductively around the hips, caressed the thighs
and flared gracefully from the ankle down; an abundance of floral
embroidery up the sides of skirts and dresses and all over his
evening gowns; jackets hemmed at the hip; and outfits awash in
tropical colors (coral, lime green, lemon yellow and sea blue).
</P>
<P>
   He even offered up a few innovations not seen this week: floral
overskirts worn with matching pants, and slit skirts in doubled
layers of contrasting colors.
</P>
<P>
   It was a collection full of the kind of clothes mature women
covet and younger women admire. The suits (embroidered or trimmed
with raffia) were sleek, the frocks (knee- to floor-length)
feminine and the tube tops added a racy twist.
</P>
<P>
   The fastidious designer's farewell was a fond one, however
one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one Bill Blass,'' said philanthropist Judy
Peabody, one of the many gathered backstage to say their last
good-byes. ``I feel sad about this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the official farewell,'' Blass declared. ``And it's a
great sigh of relief. I'm delighted to be out of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly won't be traveling in my retirment, because I hate
to travel,'' he added. ``But I will be writing a book. I just need
some time off... I've been doing this for 50 or 60 years and I'm
not going to miss it one bit. I was actually relieved when there
was talk of canceling (the show) due to the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton is Fashion Editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
