<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-NY     09-16 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEASURE PASSES THAT WOULD GIVE RAISE TO CONGRESS, PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Miss.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress Thursday passed and sent to President
Clinton a spending bill that will increase its members' salaries,
as well as those of federal workers and the next president.
</P>
<P>
   The measure contains a $4,600 raise for members of Congress,
increasing their annual incomes to $141,300 a year, a 3.4 percent
raise. The sum is about twice the average lawyer's income and
roughly five times what the average American wage earner makes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to sign the measure, which would increase
congressional salaries in January. It would be the third increase
Congress has given itself in seven years. Lawmakers voted
themselves a raise in January 1998 and in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Though conservative lawmakers have opposed raises, federal law
grants members of Congress an annual salary increase unless the
members vote to block it, which they chose to do from 1994 until
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Government workers would receive pay increases next year
averaging 4.8 percent, which would be their biggest increase in pay
in 18 years. The bill would also double the salary paid the
president to $400,000 in January 2001, when Clinton's successor
will be sworn in. That would be the first pay increase for a
president in 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   If the $200,000 salary paid back then to President Richard Nixon
had been adjusted for inflation, it would now be nearly $900,000.
That salary would be about average for a chief executive of one of
the nation's 200 largest corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The salaries of federal judges are usually linked to those paid
to lawmakers. But a House-Senate conference will have to add an
increase if judges are to keep pace with Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Senate voted 95-0 for a $49.5 billion
transportation bill that increases spending for roads, mass transit
and airports. The House has passed a $50.7 billion measure, and the
two versions must now be reconciled in a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill Congress completed and sent to Clinton
Thursday, a measure financing the Treasury Department and several
smaller agencies, is only the third of 13 annual spending bills
Congress has completed this year. A fourth, financing the District
of Columbia, was finished late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hope is evaporating that Congress will finish its only required
task _ spending the government's money _ on time. Eight working
days remain for Congress until the 2000 fiscal year begins on Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of obstacles ahead,'' said Rep. C.W. Bill
Young, R-Fla, who heads the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Those obstacles include the Republican leadership in Congress,
which has been unable to agree on a strategy to pass this year's
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Spending caps imposed by Congress have left the bills about $30
billion shy of what many members think will be needed to finance
favorite programs, win passage and send the bills to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are considering measures like charging
billions of dollars in emergency agriculture aid that would be
spent in the fiscal year 2000 against the previous year's books,
and delaying billions of dollars in Medicaid payments due to the
states in September 2000, thus charging them against the 2001
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, no money would be saved, but the spending would
not be counted in the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   If the new fiscal year begins on Oct. 1 without spending bills
signed into law, the government must operate on stop-gap bills
called continuing resolutions. That is a fragile architecture, and
if it breaks down in political disarray, a repeat of the government
shutdown of 1995 is possible.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest and most complicated spending bills are in limbo.
The measure financing labor, health and human services has been
drained of billions of dollars to finance other spending bills, and
it has not even been written, much less debated. Congressional
aides said it was increasingly likely that the measure would never
be completed, but instead rolled into an omnibus spending bill that
could be passed in October or November.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Congress passed an omnibus spending bill that
became a 4,000-page behemoth containing $21 billion in additional
spending that violated the caps, or spending limits, that Congress
solemnly imposed on itself in 1997. Unless some magical solution
conceived through creative accounting appears, the same could
happen this year, senior congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in Congress have vowed to keep their hands
off the billions of dollars in surplus Social Security money. But
in an emergency, like an immediate need for disaster relief in the
wake of Hurricane Floyd, they might have to tap that money, said a
senior aide to Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
