<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-NOISE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quiet, please: Theaters get tough on noisy patrons
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with increasing complaints about noise during movies, AMC
Theatres is starting to crack down on the offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The chain has begun asking adults not to bring children younger
than 6 into R-rated movies after 6 p.m., and warning that if they
do so, and the child becomes disruptive, they'll be asked to leave.
To sweeten the blow, though, they'll give parents a pass to come
back another time.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of weeks, AMC will begin attacking another big
irritant by asking patrons to turn off cell phones and beepers
before entering auditoriums. AMC, with nine theaters, is one of the
largest theater operators in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   To spread the word, the Kansas City, Mo.-based company is
posting signs and getting ushers to speak to audiences about the
noise policies before a movie begins. Ushers will also speak
one-on-one with parents bringing in young children.
</P>
<P>
   AMC is testing the increased emphasis on etiquette in its
Atlanta and Dallas theaters, and may extend it to other theaters in
its Southeast region. Its Eastern region already has such a
program.
</P>
<P>
   The R-rated movie policy, which the company considered extending
to PG-13 movies, is based on noise-reduction rather than judgments
about the appropriateness of those movies for young children, said
AMC regional operations manager Gary Suter. In the evening, most
watching R-rated movies are couples on dates who expect an
atmosphere free of noise distractions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to make it so everybody can have a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has gotten some questions from parents about the
policy, but most seem to understand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Could all this mean a return to common courtesy? Don't count on
it, especially if you're hoping the new policies will stop the
couple behind you from talking back to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to deal with it,'' Suter said. ``But that's a
totally different issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
