<SLUG> BC-TV-MURDER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's `Murder' trying to cover up accident
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody does weaselly better than William H. Macy, who reached
his acting apex as the flop-sweating car salesman and would-be
criminal mastermind Jerry Lundegaard in ``Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy goes to the weasel-well again in ``A Slight Case of
Murder,'' a clever little spin on film noir he co-wrote, from a
novella by Donald Westlake. It's so different from the earnest,
paint-by-numbers style of most TV movies that it's easy to forgive
its minor flaws, and just enjoy watching Macy stammer and stumble
his way through another delicious role.
</P>
<P>
   This time out, Macy is Terry Thorpe, a movie critic on a
cable-TV show who accidentally kills his girlfriend during an
argument. He tries to cover up the crime, with disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   The first disaster is a visit from a bottom-feeding private
detective (James Cromwell of ``Babe'' in a toupee so hideous it has
to be deliberate), who uncovers what happened and blackmails Terry.
He's only just getting that situation under control when he becomes
a suspect for the cops, led by Adam Arkin as a detective who may or
may not be pretending to be a dumb bungler (a la Columbo).
Meanwhile, he's dealing _ barely _ with both of those, when his
other girlfriend (Felicity Huffman of ``Sports Night,'' Macy's
real-life wife) begins to question his erratic behavior and
increasingly dubious yarns about what's going on. The last thing he
needs is for the detective's over-sexed wife (a hilarious Julia
Campbell) to fall in lust with him, which is of course what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder'' toys with viewers, just as the fates toy with Terry
Thorpe. He teaches a college course in film noir and lectures about
characters he can now identify with: ``a good man trapped by fate
... (in) claustrophobic desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe isn't really a good man, although he thinks he is, which
is key. He's certainly more likable, though, than Jerry was in
``Fargo,'' and since ``Murder'' is told completely from his point
of view (including irritating talking to the camera breaks), we end
up rooting for him. He's one weasel we hope will somehow pop out of
this trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Slight Case of Murder''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
