<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOLLAR-NORRIS-COLUMN-     09-16 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: AMERICA, HEAL THYSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are few things more enjoyable than spending more than you
earn. Especially if you are convinced you can keep doing so
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is now in that position. As a nation, it is
outspending its income by more than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   That fact does not prove that the party is about to end. Many of
the trends that have enabled Americans to spend so much remain in
place. But the recent weakness of the dollar against the Japanese
yen may be the first sign that this party's liquor supply may be
running low.
</P>
<P>
   The measure of such overspending is known as the current account
deficit _ the broadest measure of what we pay to foreigners for
goods, services and other miscellaneous things, less what we
collect from them. It's been big for some time, but now it is
ballooning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Commerce Department reported that the deficit
reached $80.7 billion in the last quarter, or nearly a billion
dollars a day. That was up 18 percent from the previous quarter _
which itself had been a record.
</P>
<P>
   The proper way to look at such figures is relative to the size
of the economy. There, too, it's a record, equaling 3.63 percent of
gross domestic product, more than twice what it was a couple of
years ago. The previous peak, set in the final three months of
1986, was 3.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The growing deficit has not been a problem so far because the
rest of the world has been happy to take all those dollars we pay
for things and invest them in dollar-denominated assets. They give
us cars and barrels of oil, and we give them pieces of paper called
securities. The United States was attractive because it has been
growing while Japan was in a prolonged recession, Europe was
plagued by low growth and high unemployment, and much of the
developing world was in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, things are starting to change for the better
overseas. Japan is growing, albeit in a stuttering manner, and
attracting investment. The yen has risen sharply against the
dollar, as the Japanese central bank has intervened only
half-heartedly. The recovery in most of developing Asia is well
under way. Europe is also looking healthier, although the German
government's weakness and indecision has hurt the euro.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, alternatives to investing in the United States
are starting to look more attractive. As less money comes into this
country, the pressure on the dollar will increase.
</P>
<P>
   That pressure probably is not going to be too intense for a
while. The Japanese probably will do a better job of holding the
yen down, and speculators who have lately been betting against the
dollar will move on to other markets. But at some point the huge
current account deficit will begin to seem important to investors
and currency traders. Then the dollar will really begin to slide.
``The trade deficit can get bigger and bigger, and no one will care
_ until they do,'' said Robert Barbera, the chief economist of
Hoenig &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Then the U.S. government will face difficult choices.
Protectionist pressures will grow in Washington, and the Federal
Reserve will be forced to raise interest rates _ already higher
than in Europe or Japan _ to attract investment. But those higher
rates could depress inflated stock prices and cause foreigners to
flee America rather than invest more. The higher interest rates
rose, the more pressure the dollar would face.
</P>
<P>
   You may remember that that is exactly what happened to Mexico in
1994, when the world suddenly stopped sending the capital needed to
finance a growing current account deficit. In the aftermath of
that, the United States has lectured that countries must live
within their means. Physician, heal thyself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CABLEVISION-SONY-NYT &LR;      09-16 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLEVISION-SONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY, FOR FIRST TIME, TO SELL SET-TOP BOXES TO CABLEVISION
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 9th graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(rk) 
 By   SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sony Corp. of Japan Thursday made its first big move
into the U.S. cable television market, with the announcement that
the Cablevision Systems Corp. would buy more than $1 billion worth
of Sony equipment to deliver advanced digital television services
in the New York City area.
</P>
<P>
   Sony makes cameras, studio monitors and other video equipment
used by television production operations around the world, and many
U.S. consumers who subscribe to direct-broadcast satellite services
use Sony decoders to view programs on their televisions. But until
Thursday Sony had not broken into the market for the set-top boxes
that are in almost every one of the roughly 67 million U.S. homes
that use cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision, one of the nation's largest cable television
carriers, serves about 2.7 million customers in the New York area.
With systems in New Jersey, Long Island, Westchester County and
many areas of New York City, Cablevision is the largest cable
provider in the metropolitan area. (Manhattan is served by Time
Warner Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Cablevision said that the new Sony gear would allow
consumers to view movies on demand, play interactive games on their
televisions and enjoy crisper video.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like moving from buggies and carriages to supersonic
transports,'' said James L. Dolan, Cablevision's chief executive.
``The easiest way to characterize it is that this technology puts
the consumer in control of the services on their television set.''
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision says it intends to begin deploying the new services
in the New York area next year, but Cablevision executives would
not say just how many customers in which communities would be
offered the new services by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision executives said the company intended to spend more
than $1 billion on Sony set-top boxes and an unspecified additional
amount on advanced Sony gear that would work in the core of
Cablevision's network.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Howard Stringer, chairman of Sony's
U.S. operation, described the deal as ``another critical step in
our strategy to marry the power of our electronics and technology
assets with our vast entertainment holdings to create a compelling
21st century lifestyle experience.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional aspect of that experience will be the ability to
receive and send electronic mail on the television. But it will not
include high-speed Internet access. Cablevision said it would
maintain its involvement in the high-speed cable modem service
Excite(AT)home, which would remain separate from the advanced
television services covered by the Sony deal.
</P>
<P>
   If there were losers in Thursday's announcements, they appeared
to be General Instrument Corp. and Scientific-Atlanta Inc., which
currently dominate the market for cable television equipment.
Cablevision uses both companies' systems but seemed to show no
hesitation in moving to Sony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a replication of anything we're doing with GI,''
said Wilt Hildenbrand, Cablevision's senior vice president for
engineering and technology. ``This is a new way of bringing
services to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony uniquely has that capability,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, General Instrument said it had agreed to be
acquired by Motorola Inc. Sender Cohen, an analyst at Lehman
Brothers, said that the Sony deal highlighted the rationale behind
the General Instrument acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The set-top box market has been a duopoly between GI and SA,
so this is obviously a negative for them,'' he said. ``But this
clearly makes the Motorola deal that much smarter, because General
Instrument can use Motorola's brand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ENCRYPTION-EXPORT-NYT     09-16 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCRYPTION-EXPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE ENDS CONTROLS ON EXPORT OF DATA-SCRAMBLING TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bucking pressure from the Justice Department, the FBI and
intelligence agencies, the White House on Thursday essentially
eliminated its complex controls on the export of data-scrambling
hardware and software, handing a surprise victory to congressional,
high-technology and privacy groups that have spent years fighting
for the change.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders, who had been planning to vote later this month on
a bill to overturn the Clinton administration's policy, said they
were elated by the change and would pull their bill back until the
administration could draft final regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge,'' said Rep. Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., who, along
with Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., whose district includes Silicon
Valley, has been championing legislation to eliminate the
encryption export controls.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is used to scramble data and computer
communications in general, and especially to keep them private on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Goodlatte called the administration's
new position ``very close'' to the intentions of his bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous victory for everybody who has been
proposing that the administration change its export policy on
encryption so that we can make it more widely available and U.S.
companies can compete overseas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The change would significantly simplify the Commerce
Department's complex and inconsistent licensing requirements for
the export of strong data-scrambling technology, and essentially
allow U.S. companies to sell their products abroad after a one-time
review. The exceptions would be for products being sold to foreign
governments or military establishments. And a prohibition would
remain on the export of computer security technology to nations the
Unites States labels as terrorist: Iran, Iraq, Libya, Syria, Sudan,
North Korea and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Despite increasing pressure over the last few years from
industry, Congress and privacy groups to lift the controls, the
administration, at the urging of the FBI and intelligence
officials, has resisted calls for change. Law enforcement officials
have insisted that the widespread availability of strong encryption
products would make it harder for them to fight terrorists and drug
cartels in the Digital Age.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Freeh, the FBI director, had been pushing to tie any
easing of the export controls to requirements that software and
equipment manufacturers develop technology that would give police
agencies a backdoor key to unscramble encrypted communications when
they suspect a crime has been committed.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials finally lost that argument to the
industry and privacy groups, which noted that strong encryption
products made in other countries were already widely available.
High-technology companies said export controls were simply giving
their competitors overseas an unfair advantage in the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates also said that the export rules deprived
Internet users of the most advanced technologies for keeping their
data and communications safe.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession to police agencies, the administration said it
would push for additional money to help law enforcement and
national security experts develop new ways to detect and fight
crimes in electronic settings.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also said it would propose legislation to set
the standards under which investigators would be able to seek
``spare keys'' held by third parties.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Davidson, a lawyer for the Center of Democracy and
Technology, an online civil liberties group based in Washington,
said that proposal would ``open a whole new, complex debate _ under
what circumstances the government should have access to our most
private data.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes were proposed as the House was preparing to vote
this month on the so-called Safety and Freedom Through Encryption
Act proposed by Goodlatte and Lofgren. They followed a report from
a presidential advisory panel in June recommending that the
administration eliminate most of the export controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised that they moved this much this quickly,''
Goodlatte said. ``But we are very pleased that they have done so
and that they have come this close. There is no doubt that this
announcement is a direct result of the fact that we had 258
co-sponsors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
