<HEADLINE>
FRANTIC 911 CALLS BEGIN A NIGHT OF HORROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The first of almost two dozen 911 calls
arrived at 6:55 p.m. Wednesday night, as a man called to say he
thought shots were being fired in the Wedgwood Baptist Church
sanctuary. The tape begins with the caller's tense news that
someone is shooting amid a youth rally in the church.
</P>
<P>
   The 911 operator picks up the call with a routine greeting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort Worth 911, operator K 684.''
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``Shots fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``How many shots were fired?''
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``Whitman Baptist Church, Whitman and Walton. Southwest
Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``OK, is there anybody hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``I don't know. There's a big rally going on here; I
don't know what else is going on. It may be a, well, if it's a skit
or something I don't know about it, but I'd rather have you on your
way than ...''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: OK, what's your name?
</P>
<P>
   Caller: name deleted.
</P>
<P>
   The caller tells the operator that the assailant pointed a gun
at him and fired several shots.
</P>
<P>
   The operator asks for a description of the shooter. The caller
says he recalls little in his attempt to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had on glasses. He was clear down the hallway. All I saw
was the flash of the muzzle and man, I headed out the other
direction,'' the caller says.
</P>
<P>
   The second call revealed the horror taking place in the church.
The woman caller, who says she is the church nursery coordinator,
says that she was not in the sanctuary but that people are wounded
at the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the A building. There's a lady who looks like she is
bleeding from the head,'' the woman says.
</P>
<P>
   She describes what she saw: ``A bunch of teen-agers came running
out (of the church) crying,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``Tell me what you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``OK. There's a lady bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``Has she been shot?
</P>
<P>
   Caller (talking to wounded person): ``Have you been shot? She
said, `Yes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The caller says people are ``Jumping in their cars and taking
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman then sees a victim who is dead or severely injured.
.MDNM/ Other calls came from outside the church. One caller says
she was about to drop off her child when she was warned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving my son up there and people came running out and
saying, `Get out, get out, get out.' '' the woman says. ``I know
that man that was yelling at me. It's not fake. He said someone was
in there killing everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Another caller from inside the church tried frantically to get
across to emergency workers just how serious the situation was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have shots being fired, shots being fired at Wedgwood
Baptist Church, 5522 Whitman Ave. Many people are hurt, OK?,'' the
woman says. ``We've got a Columbine incident going on in the place.
I have no idea what is going on.'' The woman is transferred to a
MedStar dispatcher who asks for more information about how many
people are injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea. I was upstairs. I heard guns being fired.
Shots are still being fired. I'm upstairs trying to call 911,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher asks whether people are still in the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``I don't know. I don't hear gunfire anymore. I need to
go check.''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``No. You need to stay where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``OK, there's teen-agers here. I just heard gunfire
again. I don't know what's going on in there, but please hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
