<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTINGS-MENTAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD PSYCHIATRIC HELP HAVE AVOIDED THE CHURCH SHOOTINGS?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Resending to fix e-mail address) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MEDE NIX 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should anyone have been concerned about mass killer Larry Gene
Ashbrook, whom neighbors described as a social outcast and who
wrote letters filled with unusual claims and references to serial
killings?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, mental health professionals say, is yes, no and
maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at what happened, everybody's light goes on and
says, `We missed that; we really didn't even think of it,' '' said
Dr. Saundra Gilfillan, assistant professor of psychiatry at the
University of Texas-Southwestern Medical School in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think of it more with kids now because of all the school
shootings,'' said Gilfillan, medical director of the Parkland
Health System's psychiatric services. ``But neighbors or
acquaintances don't usually think of it with adults. In hindsight,
it probably wouldn't have been unreasonable to think someone should
have helped him find a psychiatric evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   But how?
</P>
<P>
   Lauralee Harris, executive director of the Mental Health
Association of Tarrant County, which serves Fort Worth, said it is
often hard to tell when people need help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most mentally ill people are not problematic,'' said Harris.
``They say things that don't make a great deal of sense or do
things we wouldn't do. However, sometimes people are so obviously
over that line that they clearly need help from neighbors and
friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said that, if someone is extremely depressed, talking
about suicide or hurting others, police should be called and the
person's statements should not be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe a person is suicidal or dangerous, absolutely
call the police,'' Harris said. ``A 911 call is very appropriate.
We suggest if it's someone you don't know well, don't try to
challenge their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Tarrant County, Mental Health-Mental Retardation can do a
crisis response, but a person's got to be very, very ill,'' she
said. ``From what I'm hearing, I don't know if a crisis team would
have responded (to Ashbrook's behavior.) It seemed like he was
functioning and getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Churches sometimes attract those with mental illness, who may be
reaching out for help, the professionals said. Ministers said that
is a concern for churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We greet everyone who comes to our church with a warm
welcome,'' First Baptist Church pastor Charles Wade said. ``If our
ushers and greeters detect some anxiety or frustration on the part
of the visitor who comes, we seek to minister to them gently and
firmly as needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A church cannot allow itself to take on a siege mentality,''
he said. ``We will not fence people out and thereby fence ourselves
in. God's people must always be vulnerable, but they must also be
careful. We try to do both.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hearon, associate director of programs of the Mental Health
Association of Greater Dallas, said that as a licensed professional
therapist she is required to call police if she believes someone is
suicidal or homicidal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for John Q. Public, that's a hard call in today's world,''
she said. ``We can't predict behavior, especially if mental illness
is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/ As development director of Mental Health Association of
Colorado, Michelle Hoffer dealt with the aftermath of the shootings
at Columbine High School. She said that her agency has tried to
focus on prevention and intervention for those with mental illness
and at risk of suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to do because there was so much emotion,'' Hoffer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several education programs were developed, many geared towards
suicide and depression, including a speakers bureau and brown-bag
talks for corporations on conflict management, suicide and grief. A
separate program was developed for middle- and high-school
students, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge response,'' Hoffer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every time we hear about these shootings, we cringe
because we wonder whether it will reduce or add to the stigma of
mental illness,'' she said. ``We hope it's an opportunity for us to
get the word out that mental illness is treatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilfillan said that the Wedgwood shootings should serve to
heighten awareness about mental illness, and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best we can hope for is to teach people about suicide, and
suicide potential, and maybe we should be looking and listening in
a different way,'' she said. ``This will make us keenly aware of it
for right now. It will go away, but it will rear its head again.
It's a societal dilemma that probably has not run its course
yet.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What can be done? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How can we better respond to mental illness? Send us your ideas
by fax to Solutions, at (817) 390-7313, or by email at solutions
(at) star-telegram.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
