<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: REFORM PARTY 101 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Text shown in bold should be set in italics.)  
 (bl)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura has come up with the exciting idea
of recruiting Donald Trump to run as the Reform Party presidential
candidate. This is the sort of creative coupling that could come
only from a chief executive who moonlights as a professional
wrestler. Who better for the balanced-budget party than a man whose
fundamental business philosophy has always been that if you borrow
enough, the banks can't afford to foreclose on you.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's search for a presidential candidate has left
many people puzzled, wondering how any organization's leadership
could apparently regard Trump, Pat Buchanan, Lowell Weicker and
Ross Perot as equally suitable standard-bearers. I have been
looking into this matter, and I am prepared to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Who is eligible to become the Reform Party candidate for
president of the United States? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   According to party leaders, any U.S. citizen who agrees with the
Reform platform and is prepared to spend the money necessary to get
on the ballot. All it takes is several million dollars and a dream.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What's in the Reform Party platform? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A whole lot of stuff, actually, down to abolishing the
Appalachian Regional Commission. But the three biggest points seem
to be government reform, trade protectionism and balanced budgets.
The platform specifically says the party opposes tax cuts until the
national debt is paid down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Does Pat Buchanan oppose tax cuts until the national debt is
paid down? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   According to his spokesman, Buchanan's only problem with the
Republicans' proposed $792 billion tax cut is that it is not large
enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What does the Reform leadership say about that? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Russell Verney, says he ``can envision Pat
Buchanan with a straight face saying he supports the party
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Does Gov. Jesse Ventura, the only Reform Party member ever to
actually get elected to anything, support Pat Buchanan? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who calls Pat Buchanan a ``retread,'' has been floating
the names of Donald Trump and former Connecticut Gov. Lowell
Weicker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is Lowell Weicker a protectionist? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weicker says, ``Hell, no.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Does Donald Trump support the Reform Party platform? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Trump could probably work it into his current political
ideology, which seems firm only in regard to the virtues of tax
incentives for real estate development and the evils of alimony.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What is the current makeup of the Reform Party membership? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party members seem united mainly on the goal of
opening up the political process until it is finally yawning so
wide that they can step into elective office themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What ever happened to Ross Perot? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When last seen, Perot was still promising to assemble a panel of
first-class experts to come up with a new plan to look under the
national hood and retool the governmental engine, as soon as he
gets the crazy aunt out of the attic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What are the chances that Perot will change his mind and run
for president again himself? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Very slim, since Perot dislikes the limelight and never swerves
unexpectedly from one course to another on the basis of an
inexplicable, lunatic whim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Will the Reform Party survive into the next millennium? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-century prophet Nostradamus had a great deal to say
about this topic in a passage translated from Latin only minutes
ago:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The money-mantled minion leaps into the abyss,
</P>
<P>
   Then rises up.
</P>
<P>
   His second, shouting, leans upon the rope. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The seer is unusually forthright here. The rope-leaner is
obviously Ventura in his wrestling persona, whose promotion of
Trump will bear fruit in the year 2000. The first stanza depicts
the luxury-apartment and casino developer accepting the
presidential nomination, in a ceremony followed by a final
cataclysm and the Rapture. A slightly different interpretation
argues that the text foresees President Clinton's recent trip to
New Zealand, during which economic adviser Gene Sperling was
photographed bungee-jumping off a 150-foot bridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
