A4982 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-MURDER-REVIEW-355&AMP;     09-16 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MURDER-REVIEW-355&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TNT'S `MURDER' MAKES US PARTY TO A KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Fargo,'' William H. Macy was Jerry Lundegaard, a car dealer
and world-class schlemiel who tried wiggling free of the law's
vise.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few pints of Lundegaard in Terry Thorpe, the
character Macy co-wrote (with Steven Schachter) and plays in
Sunday's frothy movie ``A Slight Case of Murder'' on TNT cable.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe is a New York film critic with the sophistication and
some of the confidence that Lundegaard lacked. But like Lundegaard,
he unravels and makes bad decisions as the police close in on him.
</P>
<P>
   His crime is murder. But not the cold-blooded variety. Or even
deliberate _ which means that, technically, it's more like
manslaughter than murder. Try telling that to the cops.
</P>
<P>
   He shoves a girlfriend during a quarrel in her apartment, her
head hits a table, she dies and slam, bam, Thorpe's in a jam.
</P>
<P>
   We first meet him at the scene of the crime. He's arguing with
himself. Call the cops and say it was an accident, thus exposing
his little affair to his other girlfriend (Felicity Huffman)? Or
wipe out his fingerprints, hoof it and hope for the best?
</P>
<P>
   Soon Thorpe stops talking to himself and starts talking to us.
Right at the camera. He's making us his accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard,'' he confides to us, in the midst of lying to
police investigators. ``I have a newfound respect for actors.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead police investigator is an aspiring screenwriter played
by Adam Arkin. And the movie's other complication is a tough
blackmailer played by James Cromwell (``Babe,'' ``L.A.
Confidential'').
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun is that ``A Slight Case of Murder,'' which is
based on a Donald Westlake novella, finds and sustains a seriocomic
tone that keeps anyone from taking it too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   And part of the enjoyment is in the technique. It's a bit like
watching a ``Columbo'' episode from the viewpoint of the killer _
experiencing his cycles of tension and relief as the hunt goes hot
and cold.
</P>
<P>
   Then too, the killer is a film expert, and his banter with
viewers reflects it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' he says to viewers at one point. ``I know this
looks like a scene out of `Notorious.' I'm not Claude Rains. I'm
more like John Cassavetes in `Rosemary's Baby.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the networks' fall season continues to grind along. I
know it looks like ``The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari.'' But it's more
like Dustin Hoffman in ``Ishtar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy'' gets a sneak preview _ well, OK, a preview _
Sunday on CBS. It stars Amy Brenneman (``NYPD Blue'') as a single
mom who comes home to Connecticut and becomes a juvenile court
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Tyne Daly plays her mother, a retired social worker, and Dan
Futterman is cast as Brenneman's brother. The series is loosely
based on the life of Brenneman's own mother.
</P>
<P>
   Tune in and you can see Brenneman trying to cut through
courtroom bureaucratese by saying, ``I'd like to talk to the DCF
about the OTC. And I'd like to talk to the DAD. The dad.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as good as it gets. The show is predictable, inexcusably
pokey and, when Daly and Brenneman bump against each other in the
heavier mother-daughter slogs, dangerously close to smarmy.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, ``Judging Amy'' moves to 10 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   _ VCR ALERT: ``There's Something About Mary,'' the movie that
taught us to be very careful about what we put in our hair, makes
its pay-cable debut at 9 p.m. Saturday on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
