<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-NC17-COX     09-16 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-NC17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. beachfront residents reassess risk
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. _ When Sandy McCaughey moved here two
months ago, her mother warned her she was headed for ``hurricane
alley.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey, 35, laughed off the warning then, but not now. Her
shifting sentiment reflects how some hurricane-battered residents _
joining the ranks of coastal planners and environmentalists _ are
having second thoughts about life at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go back today and the house is gone,'' the Philadelphia
transplant said Thursday, ``I'm out of here. I can't handle the
stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with 2.6 million coastal dwellers from Florida to North
Carolina, in the nation's biggest peacetime evacuation, McCaughey
fled this week in advance of Hurricane Floyd. Two weeks ago, tens
of thousands of North Carolinians evacuated because of Hurricane
Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, five of the Atlantic's most powerful hurricanes
have wrecked coastal North Carolina. In 1996, Bertha and Fran made
landfall at Cape Fear, as Floyd did early Thursday, leaving behind
extensive flooding and beach erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the context of five hurricanes in three years, it makes
beachfront development seem like madness,'' said Orrin Pilkey, a
coastal geologist and professor at Duke University. ``We're
thumbing our nose at nature, and nature always bats last on the
coast.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, hundreds of thousands of motorists were trapped on
gridlocked interstate highways in Georgia and the Carolinas. The
experience illustrates how rapid development is increasingly
inconvenient, even risky, during disasters.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Interstate 40 flooding blocked the main highway
from Wilmington to Raleigh. It slowed the return of Floyd evacuees
who had spent the past day or two on the road, some searching
futilely for hotel rooms hundreds of miles from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things that I didn't think any of us
totally anticipated,'' said John Copenhaver, Southeast regional
director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency. ``Some of the
traffic problems were worse than we expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an emergency management standpoint, including state and
local, that's something we need to take a look at _ how do you
evacuate such a huge number of people from the coast without
putting them into such terrible traffic?''
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina's Pender County _ including part of Topsail
Island passed over by Floyd's eye _ the tidal surge piled 4 feet of
sand atop N.C. 50. It's the only road to the west end of the
island, a narrow spit battered by recent hurricanes, especially
Fran.
</P>
<P>
   The county's emergency management spokeswoman, Mary Anne George,
said she doubts Floyd's wrath would cause people to abandon the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get sand in your toes, you just have to hang
around,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Bush, a coastal geologist at the State University of West
Georgia, said rebuilding beaches is expensive for property owners,
as well as state and local taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, North Carolina generally has been viewed as a
leader in coastal management, Bush said. But as development
increases, state regulators have been pressured to bend the rules.
</P>
<P>
   At the northern tip of Wrightsville Beach, owners of the Shell
Island resort fought to build a seawall to guard the high-rise
building from an encroaching inlet. State law prohibits seawalls.
</P>
<P>
   Seawall disputes have erupted on North Carolina's Outer Banks as
well, including the fight over whether the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse
should be moved inland or bolstered at its perilous Atlantic perch;
the lighthouse was relocated in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there are sandbags, the beach can't rebuild itself,''
said Bush, who on Thursday was surveying erosion on Oak Island,
N.C., near Cape River.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're holding the beach back in a place where it doesn't want
to be,'' he said. ``The beach wants to be where the road is. But
there are houses between the road and the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Few places offer a better glimpse at how residents and officials
battle hurricanes to enjoy life on the shore than Wrightsville
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   New Hanover County is North Carolina's second-smallest county in
square miles, but one of the most densely populated, with roughly
150,00 people. It trails only booming Charlotte and Raleigh in
projected growth through 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Just east of Wilmington, Wrightsville Beach has a year-round
population of 3,200. During summer, it swells to 40,000, including
25,000 day trippers to the beach, long known for Johnnie Mercers
Pier.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Bonnie knocked off the end of the pier. Since then
it's been demolished and is now being rebuilt. The pier symbolizes
the storm-weary sentiment along this narrow barrier island.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of property for sale on Wrightsville Beach,
more so than a year ago,'' said town alderman Barry Mowbray. ``The
most significant thing is the stress of leaving your home five
times in 38 months.''
</P>
<P>
   The increasing turnover of property isn't foreboding, said Mayor
Avery Roberts, a 10-year island resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The property values keep going up, even though we have those
hurricanes,'' the 73-year-old mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 reappraisal valued his 3,500-square-foot home on Lollipop
Sound at $1.1 million. Its 1991 appraisal was $459,000.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's emergency meeting of aldermen to discuss storm
damage, Roberts was eager for the island to be reopened to property
owners. He got his wish by midafternoon, when the decision was made
to allow them to return at 6 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It was possible only after a restoration of sewer services, one
of numerous problems spawned by Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that can go wrong today is going wrong,'' town
manager Tony Caudle told aldermen during an emergency meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The county's landfill was closed, so Wrightsville Beach dump
trucks couldn't empty their loads. That bogged down the removal of
storm debris.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding clogged sewer drains with 10 million gallons of water.
It couldn't be pumped out until electricity was restored to the
island's main pumping station during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The high storm surge washed away soil under a portion of the
four-lane drawbridge road leading from the mainland to Wrightsville
Beach. State highway workers hurriedly put in fill dirt at the
urging of town officials who wanted all lanes to reopen for
islanders' return.
</P>
<P>
   The surge also buckled wooden docks in Banks Channel and turned
a large sailboat on its side.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolling the debris-littered island, police officer Trey
Jordan pointed out problems not easily detected. While damage to
homes and businesses was light, the storm surge caused widespread
flooding of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you see had 3 feet of water in it,'' Jordan said,
driving along the back side of the island near the Intracoastal
Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downstairs anywhere on this island is a major risk,'' said
26-year-old Dawn Allison, who has moved several times on
Wrightsville Beach. She's not interested in moving to higher ground
off the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are lucky enough to live on the beach,'' she said,
sipping a beer as she waited to return home, ``you are lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
