<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-RADIO-1000(     09-16 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-RADIO-1000(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SUNDAY, AND VENEZUELANS HAVE THE PRESIDENT'S EAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ On line 2, Yamile was calling from Puerto
Ordaz to ask how she could help her father collect the pension due
him. On line 1, Zuly from Guarenas was waiting for her turn on the
air, hoping to get in a word about AIDS prevention campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Live from the studios of Radio Nacional de Venezuela here, it's
``Hello, President,'' the country's most unusual radio show. It
features President Hugo Chavez taking calls every Sunday morning
for two hours from any Venezuelan with a problem, a complaint or a
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   So when Pedro Marrero, 72, a resident of the same neighborhood
where Radio Nacional is based, called recently to complain about
his minuscule $150-a-month pension, Chavez expressed sympathy, just
as many talk show hosts would do. It is not fair, he said, that top
executives of the state oil company can retire with as much as
$25,000 a month in benefits while a bus driver like Marrero has to
struggle to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do away with this,'' he said earnestly before
suddenly changing the subject and asking Marrero if his wife made
good coffee. When Marrero said she did, Chavez, who took office in
February promising to lead a peaceful social revolution, urged him
to ``send a cup over here for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the calls, which average about 14 a program, come from
ordinary Venezuelans who have run into problems with the state
bureaucracy and want the president to help them resolve problems
involving housing, education, health, schooling or sewage.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Eduardo Plaza, for instance, called in from Trujillo to
complain that a corrupt Health Ministry functionary was holding
back a permit that would allow him to move his pharmacy to a new
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to check it out,'' promised Chavez, who in 1992
led an unsuccessful coup attempt. A presidential aide, Capt.
Orlando Pina, said that a follow-up dossier was prepared both for
each case discussed on the air and the 700 or so additional letters
sent to the station each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president himself reads a lot of them,'' he said, ``and
attends personally to the ones that are most affecting.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Between calls on one recent program, Chavez found time to
ruminate about topics ranging from the health of Atlanta Braves
slugger Andres Galarraga, who is Venezuelan, to the geography of
the Amazon. At one point he even broke into an Andean folk song,
stopping after the first verse and apologizing for his imperfect
rendition by saying, ``I'm a little hoarse today, brother.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also makes a point of discussing his official agenda for
the coming week, mentioning people and groups he is to meet and
why. He often announces major policy initiatives on the show,
sometimes even to the surprise of Cabinet ministers, regularly
blasts his critics and set off a diplomatic dispute with
neighboring Colombia by declaring on the air that he was recalling
his ambassador to Bogota in response to a perceived insult in a
speech by an official there.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also has both a regular television show, ``Face to Face
With the President,'' and a weekly newspaper, The President's Post,
and rarely passes up a chance to express an opinion on any subject
that interests him. On a trip to New York in June, he threw out the
first ball at a Mets game and eventually wandered up to the
broadcast booth, where he delivered the Spanish-language color
commentary during what turned out to be an extra-inning game.
</P>
<P>
   But he has shown a particular affinity for radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was in prison following the events of 1992, he studied
the news media very closely,'' said Teresa Maniglia, director of
Radio Nacional. ``He came to understand that even when television
is unavailable, radio gets you everywhere and anywhere, and not
long after he became president, he hatched the idea for this
program and even came up with the name for it.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Hello, President'' first went on the air in May, only a
handful of state-run stations carried it. Now the program's
popularity is such that more than 60 stations broadcast it,
including many that are privately owned and one each in Mexico and
Spain, and it has become the highest-rated program in its time
slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever met Hugo Chavez, you sense right away that he
is a simple person who has a tendency to break protocol,'' Ms.
Maniglia said when asked to explain the show's rapidly growing
following. ``That is innate in him, and people like it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so many people were going to the Radio Nacional studios
in hopes of speaking with the president after the program,
generating traffic congestion and neighbors' complaints, that
Chavez has had to expand the idea. He now goes directly from the
studio to the presidential palace every Sunday to meet with
constituents who wait for him there with petitions and requests for
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't attend to all of them, and that was bothering me,''
Chavez said on the air in explaining the decision. ``So now they
can wait comfortably in the shade, sitting on chairs, drink some
juice and have access to toilets. Last week I spent an hour with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a broader sense, the program also exemplifies Chavez's
notions of what constitutes democracy. He has repeatedly attacked
Venezuela's National Congress and its state legislatures as
unrepresentative bodies that are out of touch with the citizenry,
and has sought their dissolution on the ground that they respond
not to the people's wishes but only to what he calls ``a corrupt
and discredited party elite.''
</P>
<P>
   To complement traditional republican institutions, Chavez has
made it clear that he favors as much direct personal contact as
possible between national leaders and the masses, without
intermediaries, whether they be elected officials or the press,
getting in the way. Those views are likely to be reflected in the
new constitution that a National Constituent Assembly loyal to
Chavez is now drawing up.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the show also provides political benefits, allowing Chavez
to demonstrate his common touch and solidify his popularity, which
is at a record 75 percent favorable level. Sept. 5, for example,
was the day before the 21st birthday of his eldest daughter, and he
closed the program by reminiscing about her birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even have the money to pay the clinic,'' he recalled,
explaining that he was an army lieutenant in a provincial town at
the time and had to make a trip to Caracas to ``ask for a loan so
that I could pay the bill.'' At that point, his voice choked and he
fell uncharacteristically silent, overcome by emotion as an
associate gently patted him on the back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
