<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-CHARGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON TO CLOSE SOME FACILITIES, FIRE WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. will take an unexpected charge against earnings of
up to $450 million to close some facilities and lay off workers.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks will help make up for a shortfall in revenues in
Raytheon's core defense business _ a shortfall that will cause the
nation's third-largest defense contractor to miss earnings
estimates of 95 cents per share for the third quarter and $4 per
share for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon executives didn't reveal Thursday whether there would
be any cuts in Massachusetts. Raytheon chairman and chief executive
Dan Burnham did say the restructuring would focus on the company's
electronics and construction business units, with many of the cuts
to involve administrative and support workers. Chief financial
officer Frank Caine specifically cited Raytheon's Lexington
headquarters as a likely target. Plans for the cuts will be
finalized over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions that we're talking about are necessary to ensure
that we can continue to meet our long-term revenue growth and
profitability goals,'' said Burnham.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmation of the cutbacks came Thursday in order to stanch
Wall Street whisperings that have pummeled Raytheon stock this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were rumors that the company was going to miss their
earnings,'' said Joseph San Pietro, a senior aerospace analyst
</P>
<P>
   for Wasserstein Perella Securities in New York. Matters weren't
helped when Burnham suffered a broken wrist and some broken ribs in
a fall from a horse last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about the health of Burnham and his company knocked
Raytheon's Class A shares from 65 5/16 on Monday to 60 3/4
Wednesday, while Raytheon Class B shares went from 66 to 60 15/16
in the same period. So Burnham and his chief financial officer
Frank Caine decided to end the speculation by revealing the bad
news _ or as much of it as they were certain of.
</P>
<P>
   Investors rewarded Raytheon's candor by sending its stock to a
52-week low _ 53 1/2 for Class A and 53 5/8 on Class B shares, both
traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham said while defense-contract revenue was growing, the
rate of growth was lower than had been expected because of delays
in government decisions to issue contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with underlying defense spending up,'' he said, ``the big
programs tend to get awarded months later than what I think were
reasonable presumptions beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the ongoing restructuring of Raytheon, which
began when Burnham took the helm last October, has revealed still
more ways to trim costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As all of the operations have come together, we're finding
that we have more opportunity on support costs,'' Caine said. That
means a close look at administrative jobs in all of Raytheon's
business units, as well as its headquarters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst San Pietro believes the moves by Raytheon reflect a
decision to continue strengthening its position in the tough market
for defense and aerospace companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, San Pietro noted the revenue slowdown is largely
due to delays in receiving income for defense contracts that are
already signed. That means the missing revenue is merely delayed
and will flow into the company in future quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-AUSTRALIA-NYT &LR;      09-16 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-AUSTRALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL FORCE SET TO DEPART FOR EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-U.S.) 
(mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARWIN, Australia _ Foreign troops, ships and planes converged
here as an international peacekeeping mission prepared to depart
within days for strife-torn East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from Britain, Thailand and nine other countries,
including a small contingent of Americans, will join 4,500
Australian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is expected to provide transportation
services, including the airlifting of trucks and other heavy
equipment, according to Adm. Chris Barrie, chief of the Australian
defense forces.
</P>
<P>
   The United States may also help with logistics and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie expressed confidence that the force, expected to number
7,000 troops, would be successful. But he acknowledged that there
could be casualties, and suggested that a hostile response from
Indonesia's army posed the greatest threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear is that things don't go as I've outlined, and
we don't get the cooperation we need,'' Barrie said.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has promised to allow the international force to
restore order in East Timor, which has been convulsed by violence
since its people voted for independence in a U.N.-organized
referendum last month.
</P>
<P>
   But with reports that Indonesian troops have supported and even
joined with anti-independence militias in acts of terror, there is
no guarantee that the militias will simply step aside.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie said the rules of engagement under which the troops would
operate had not been determined. But he added, ``We will not put
the force in there with its hands tied behind its back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will get a very good outcome, and we can do this
quickly with their support,'' he said. ``But don't let me shy away
from the tough question. We will deliver on this mission. Let that
not be in doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The first foreign troops, 250 Gurkha soldiers dispatched by
Britain, landed here Thursday. The Gurkhas, who are Nepalese, were
selected because of their ability to operate in the tropical
climate of East Timor, according to their commander, Brig. David
Richards.
</P>
<P>
   As the military mobilization here picked up pace, so too did
efforts to provide food and other relief to the thousands of East
Timorese who have been forced to flee their homes. U.N. officials
said Thursday that food drops organized by the World Food Program
would begin imminently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS &LR;      09-16 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON RETURN SET, BUT FOR WHOM IS HE FIGHTING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson sat at a podium in the Hollywood Theatre
of the MGM Grand Casino Thursday looking like a well-used up 1970s
lounge act.
</P>
<P>
   His hair was back to the thicker cut he wore in his earliest
days as a boxer and didn't quite look right after years of seeing
him with a closely shaved cut and a trademark gash along one side.
</P>
<P>
   His shirt bore a strong resemblance to the disco style of 20
years ago with a wide collar and wild swirling designs all around,
a shirt from back when he was a kid who believed boxing could save
him from a life of poverty, crime, and self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two decades later, here sat Tyson, broke again and forced
to train relentlessly for fights that will earn big money for the
IRS, Showtime, the MGM, his lawyers, his accountants, his doctors,
his seldom-seen wife, his new promoter Dan Goossen, his new manager
Shelly Finkel, his new trainers Tommy Brooks and Jay Bright, and
even his long-fired trainer Kevin Rooney, who holds a judgment
against Tyson that pays him $250,000 a fight until Rooney gets $4
million out of him.
</P>
<P>
   But what is in it for Mike Tyson?
</P>
<P>
   That question seemed to hang in the air unanswered Thursday as a
33-year-old man trapped in a personal twilight zone spoke of
preparing for an Oct. 23 return to the ring against Orlin Norris,
Tyson's first fight since serving a six-month jail sentence in
Maryland on an assault charge that stemmed from a fender-bender
highway accident. Fittingly, it is a fight unlike any since the
disco days of his career, a match that is sure to be fought before
a less-than-sellout crowd and will be shown on cable television
rather than pay-per-view, the outlet for nearly all of Tyson's
fights over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Tyson seemed aware of his fate and resigned to it, a
man more acted upon than acting. At one point it was suggested that
Tyson failed to show the fire he used to have when he barely
escaped a January match with Frans Botha. It was a fight in which a
tentative Tyson lost every round until he dropped a one-punch
concussion on Botha.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many of his predecessors, Botha had not been
intimidated by Tyson's glowering presence, a fact that actually
cost him the victory when he grew overconfident and carelessly ran
into a shot to the chin.
</P>
<P>
   Of that night Tyson recalled two things _ his fear and one
fierce punch that, as so many others had in a life of tumult, saved
him from himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first fight in 2 1/2 years and I was pretty much
nervous and scared to death at the same time,'' Tyson said. ``I was
feeling myself out. I was somewhat lethargic. I needed to get one
under the wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been off four years,'' after a rape conviction sent him to
an Indiana prison, ``then I was suspended a year'' for biting
Evander Holyfield's ears during a match. ``Then I came back and
beat Botha and I've been off nine months. That's a lot of
inactivity. They did a pretty good number on me but I'm still going
to win the title again. If anybody makes a mistake, they're going
to take a dirt nap. That's what I get paid to do. Win and win
spectacularly.''
</P>
<P>
   And win he is likely to do against the undersized Norris, a
former cruiserweight champion who holds victories over four former
heavyweight champions but none of note. Tony Tubbs, Tony Tucker,
Greg Page, and Oliver McCall are no preparation for even a Tyson
who is a shadow of the fighter he once was. But this fight is not
about Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Few Tyson fights are about anyone but Tyson and so it is again.
But his latest return is about more than boxing. It is about the
dissolution of what might have been, a fact Tyson seems to
understand but has problems facing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave the fans what I am,'' he said when asked if he felt
he'd let his followers down in recent years. ``I am a human being.
Being a human being, you make mistakes in life. The difference with
me is I'm under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have issues we're dealing with. Why are some reporters
dysfunctional alcholics? Why are some people pedophiles? I'm not as
bad as some. But this is not about rewriting the book.''
</P>
<P>
   What it is about, frankly, is writing a few checks, which is
what it's always been about for Tyson and everyone around him. His
purses have been well in excess of $200 million in his career and
he will earn $10 million more when he faces Norris. Yet in the end
they have left him deeply in debt and forced to continue fighting
at a time when he seems to be spent from his prior battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, I owe Showtime my life,'' Tyson said of the cable channel
that has fronted him millions. ``I got kids, man. I gotta keep
fighting just to pay my bills. I'm just trying to get out of this
debt Don King got me involved with. I still love to fight, but
there comes a time when the monotonousness is very difficult.
There's people telling you what to do when you're a grown man.''
</P>
<P>
   So here he was Thursday, a broke millionaire of 33 who has twice
been to state prison being asked to explain how he got into this
mess. His answer said more about him than his fists ever did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politically correct to put me in prison,'' Tyson said.
``If Mike Tyson comes to your courtroom and you don't put him away,
you have a judicial malfunction in your courtroom. But listen, man,
I have no one to blame but myself. Others contributed to it, but I
gotta carry the weight for a fool alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-16 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTY' AND THE BEHOLDER'S EYE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   People magazine says  &UR; Annette Bening &LR;  could be nominated for an
Oscar for ``American Beauty,'' and applause broke out at a San
Francisco screening the other night, but a few feminists in the
audience weren't giving thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were appalled at the character played by Bening,
a vindictive and frigid suburban real estate saleswoman who's
horrid to her daughter, mean to her husband and fawning to her
competitor. The role, they said, is a woman-hating stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Bening had been scheduled to be at the screening but canceled
all publicity appearances because of her pregnancy. She told People
magazine, ``When I read this character, I felt that I had met her.
I grew up in the suburbs in those houses where it looks one way and
it's another.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the naysayers was equally bothered by the movie's
portrayal of the suburbs. ``This is supposed to be a hip,
avant-garde film, but in a way, it's a very retro film,'' she said.
``It's asking, `Aren't we superior to these weird dysfunctional
people in the suburbs?' And I thought, `Who are we to be so
arrogant about it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd we wind up here? We were going to live in Barcelona,
Maui, on a mountaintop in Nepal. We were going to be a novelist, a
painter, a Mother Teresa, a Malcolm X, a Jim Morrison but with more
girls, more drugs and a 30th birthday. At the very least we were
going to be the mook running for president of the United States
using the disappointments, failures and vexations of loser
suburbanites as the main plank in our campaign platform. And what's
really infuriating is who's to blame. We bought these FedEx
Federalist and Boomer Tudor houses, these Phony Colonials and Taras
for Teletubbies. We go balls-to-the-malls every Saturday and
Sunday. We shop at the Super Stupid Markets. We hit ourselves over
the head with the Price Club. ... We're guilty as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   _ P.J. O'Rourke on suburbia, in Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THERE GO THE URBAN NEIGHBORHOODS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rt,10p10  &UR; John Perry &LR; 's suggestion for BeLola, a new name for
the upwardly mobile segment of Mission Street, has spurred some
amendments and additions:
</P>
<P>
   BeLola's a good name, writes  &UR; Tom Valtin &LR; , but the area, which
lies between the Inner and Outer Mission, ``has had its own moniker
for some time now: Intermission.'' In reciting the boundaries of
this neighborhood, Valtin takes care to include Mitchell's ice
cream on San Jose.  &UR; Terry Walsh &LR; , a guy with a narrow field of
vision, insists that ``the city really only has two neighborhoods:
North of Lombard (NoLo) and South of Lombard (SoLo).''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andrea Lucas &LR; , who lives near the Alemany Farmers Market in ``a
lumpy rectangle bounded by Bayshore, Alemany, Mission and
Cortland,'' calls it Bernal Depths. And what about Upper DMV, the
territory between the Panhandle and Buena Vista Park?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Nick Nolte &LR;  told Esquire magazine that he's a devotee of all
manner of vitamins and supplements, injects his stomach every night
with human growth hormone and has oxygen cylinders bolted to the
wall of every room in his house, for instant pick-me-ups. Nolte has
told other magazine interviewers that he enjoys telling lies in
magazine interviews, but in this case, the writer watched while his
subject injected himself.
</P>
<P>
   Having read the Esquire interview,  &UR; Rama Lama &LR; , who played
basketball with Nolte when they attended high school together in
1957, observes: ``He was a man, the rest of us were still boys. We
had fistfights with each other. Nick had fistfights with the
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steffi Graf &LR;  and her boyfriend have split;  &UR; Andre Agassi &LR;  has
split from  &UR; Brooke Shields &LR; . And the New York tabloids are
reporting that Graf and Agassi, who were seen dining together
during the U.S. Open, are an item.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you can prove that you've bought 2 pounds of pork, you
qualify for a free family portrait at a JCPenney studio. This
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity, sponsored by the National Pork
Producers Council and the store, requires proof of pork purchase
and a family portrait certificate available from Parade this
weekend or at www.porkoffer.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ The bidding was up Thursday to almost $5,000, but the reserve
price has not yet been met on  &UR; Joey Buttafuoco &LR; 's Lincoln, being
auctioned on eBay until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; James Carville &LR;  and  &UR; Mary Matalin &LR; , revered political
pundits, earned $10,000 by officiating last Saturday at the opening
of a Maryland store that sells spas, grills and fireplaces,
reported the Washington Post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
