<P>
   (NYT23) GOLAN HEIGHTS, Israel -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., SEPT. 19 -- ISRAEL-GOLAN-2-COX, 09-16 -- Golan Dadon, his
wife, Rivka, and their daughter, Adi, 4, on top of a military
bunker overlooking Syria. The Dadons live in Kibbutz Mezar on the
Golan Heights. ``They'll get me out over my dead body,'' Golan
says. ``We fought on this land too much and lost too many soldiers
to leave this place.'' (Sharon Abbady/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) GOLAN HEIGHTS, Israel -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., SEPT. 19 -- ISRAEL-GOLAN-1-COX, 09-16 -- ``I consider myself
first an Israeli and second a Golan resident,'' says Yoav Tsur, who
came here 20 years ago and helps run electric-generating wind
turbines. ``I have to do what is best for my country.'' With a bomb
shelter between the windmill and himself, Tsur says ``It is very
clear that making peace and staying in the Golan is just not
practical.'' (Sharon Abbady/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) STANSTED, England -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 19 -- BIZ-PROFILE-CASSANI, 09-16 -- Barbara Cassani, chief
executive of Go, a low-cost airline, views it as more as a start-up
than as a unit of British Airways, with the same foibles and
hiccups that companies have when very young. ``I buy my sandwich
out of that really elegant machine over there,'' she says with a
laugh, apologizing for ``probably smelling a bit tuna-y from
lunch.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- FLAMME-DANCE-REVIEW, 09-16
-- In ``Vers la Flamme,'' the choreographer Martha Clarke has
focused her familiar brand of imagistic dance theater on sexual
encounters and marital unhappiness. Ms. Clarke has been doing this
kind of thing since she joined Pilobolus Dance Theater shortly
after it was founded in the early 1970s. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) CHENGDU, China -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
19 -- CHINA-PANDAS-1-COX, 09-16 -- The Zoo Atlanta hopes to receive
panda cubs Lun Lun and Yang Yang on Oct. 7 under the 10-year
agreement of ``intentions'' signed by officials of the zoo and of
the China Association of Zoological Gardens. ``Also maybe we can
get money from Atlanta to help us get more equipment here for
research of diseases and for reproductive and genetic research,''
says Yu Jianqiiu, deputy director of the Chengdu research base.
(Joseph P. Albright/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SANTA FE, N.M. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- APPLES-SANTA-FE-3,
09-16 -- Objects in the Museum of International Folk Art's
Alexander Girard collection. With only 67,000 people, the city has
a cultural life worthy of a European metropolis. (Steve Northup/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SANTA FE, N.M. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- APPLES-SANTA-FE-2,
09-16 -- The Museum of Fine Arts in Santa Fe. Perched 7,000 feet
above sea level on an alluringly undulating plateau, dry but not
arid, Santa Fe is a leafy faux-adobe city built around a core of
old adobe buildings. (Steve Northup/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SANTA FE, N.M. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- APPLES-SANTA-FE-1,
09-16 -- An exhibit in the Spanish Heritage Wing of the Museum of
International Folk Art. The City Different,'' they like to call it,
and that it is, a heady blend of Hispanic, Native American and
Anglo cultures, with a brisk topping up, these last few decades, of
new money, big money, from Texas, California and New York. (Steve
Northup/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- OFTEN-THEATER-REVIEW,
09-16 -- Hamish McColl, left, and Sean Foley in ``Do You Come Here
Often?'' Directed by Jozef Houben, ``Often'' provides winning
confirmation that when it comes to doing pure silliness, nobody
beats the British. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 09-16 --
The actress Mary-Louise Parker has committed to Craig Lucas' latest
play, ``Stranger,'' even though the Vineyard theater, to which the
play was offered, lacks a place to show it because the season's
schedule at Vineyard's theater is full. The plan is to rehearse in
December for a January opening in a house that seats 99 to 199
people. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN, 09-16 --
A17th-century Chinese folding, reclining armchair of prized
hardwood is one of the items on display at the Arts of Pacific Asia
Show. 70 exhibitors from the United States, Europe, Asia and
Australia are selling antiques at the show, which runs through
tomorrow at the 69th Regiment Armory in Manhattan. (Christie's
Images/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CARACAS, Venezuela -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN,
SEPT. 19 -- VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ-COX-2, 09-16 -- Vicente Britos,
president of Fedecamaras, the national association of Venezuelan
Chambers of Commerce, during an interview. Speaking about the
policies of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez, Britos said that the
goverment had the responsibility to ensure that a considerable
amount of the nation's riches were transferred to the people.''
(Mike Williams/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CARACAS, Venezuela -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN,
SEPT. 19 -- VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ-COX-1, 09-16 -- A street protest,
organized by the association of mayors and governors of Venezuela's
states, was one of the largest demonstrations against President
Hugo Chavez of Venezuela to be held in Caracas.Visionary social
reformer or would-be dictator: both labels have flown around
Venezuela's breathless new president. (Mike Williams/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHENGDU, China -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
19 -- CHINA-PANDAS-2-COX, 09-16 -- Male panda Yang Yang, left,
gives an upside-down look to female Lun Lun, who makes her way up
the jungle gym in the exercise yard of the Sub-Adult House of the
Chengdu Research Base of Giant Panda Breeding. The Zoo Atlanta
hopes to receive panda cubs on Oct. 7 under the 10-year agreement
of ``intentions'' signed by officials of the zoo and of the China
Association of Zoological Gardens. (Joseph P. Albright/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MAJDAL SHAMS, Golan Heights -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., SEPT. 19 -- GOLAN-ARABS-COX, 09-16 -- Afif Mahmoud stands
under photos of Syrian President Hafez Assad and the late Egyptian
President Gamel Abdel Nasser in his barber shop. ``These are our
leaders,'' says Mahmoud, 60. ``Everybody here feels Syrian, not
just me.'' While Israelis consider whether to include the Golan
Heights in a peace offering to Syria, Mahmoud is among thousands of
Golan Arabs who are anxious for the day when Syria will again be in
charge. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MARSH HARBOR, Bahamas -- Sept. 16, 1999 --
FLOYD-BAHAMAS-2-COX, 09-16 -- A 60-foot lobster trawler was just
one of the many casualties of Hurricane Floyd on the island of
Abacos. On Wednesday, 24 hours after the storm's eye passed over
this island, 170 miles east of Palm Beach, officials said damages
would run in the millions of dollars. It looked to be the hardest
hit of all the islands, according to the U.S. Coast Guard, which
sent a Falcon jet to survey the islands. (Richard Graulich/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MARSH HARBOR, Bahamas -- Sept. 16, 1999 --
FLOYD-BAHAMAS-1-COX, 09-16 -- Julian Williams, 13, retrieves the
base of a table he found in the water near his father's damaged
restaurant. On Wednesday, 24 hours after Hurricane Floyd's eye
passed over Abacos, officials said damages would run in the
millions of dollars. It looked to be the hardest hit of all the
islands, according to the U.S. Coast Guard. (Richard Graulich/Cox
News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-2, 09-16 --
Jennifer and Safraz Seerattan, try to make their way home along
Ocean Promenade at Rockaway Beach after visiting friends on
Thursday. Bowing early to the whipping winds of Hurricane Floyd,
New Yorkers had to keep their children home from school Thursday
and ducked out of work by mid-afternoon in preparation for the
punishing storm. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WEYMOUTH, Mass. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- PIGEON-FLAP-BOS,
09-16 -- Jim Gallagher with one of his 100 pigeons he keeps in
plywood ``condominiums'' in his mother's backyard. On weekends, he
and other pigeon enthusiasts at the Weymouth Sportsmen's Club race
their birds against a dozen other pigeon clubs in the Boston area.
Armed with a health edict, the executive board of the club decided
last month to oust the birds and their owners, some of whom have
been members for 25 years. (Bill Brett/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- PAPERLESS-RESEARCH-BOS, 09-16
-- James Becker, right, and Stephen Raymond, co-founders of the PHT
Corp., use a PlexxNet Patient LogPad at their office earlier this
week. As part of its ordeal to get permission to market its drug to
treat rheumatoid arthritis, Celebrex, G.D. Searle at one point sent
an 18-wheel truck to the US Food and Drug Administration, loaded
with pallets of paper records on 14,000 people who had participated
in 61 clinical trials over a five-year period. The logpad enables
patients to enter their data electronically eliminating the
paperwork. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 16, 1999 --
COMPUTERS-BUYING-BOS, 09-16 -- Aliya and Ahsen Khan shop for their
first computer at Best Buy earlier this week. The Khans have
established a $700 budget to purchase their first computer,
monitor, and printer. As recent college graduates on a limited
buget, they need every price break they can get and the low
computer prices now availalble allow them to consider some extras,
such as a fax machine. (Evan Richman/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- HISPANICS-MRSCLINTON-B&AMP;W,
09-16 -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton improvises a photo
opportunity with some supporters at the Congressional Hispanic
Caucus Institute's 22nd annual gala on Wednesday evening. Mrs
Clinton, a probable candidate for the U.S. Senate seat from New
York, angered many hispanics in the state when she announced her
opposition to clemency granted by President Clinton to a group of
FALN activists. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ROXBURY, Mass. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-1,
09-16 -- Participants in the Boston to New York AIDS fund-raising
bike ride wait to load their bikes onto trucks in a parking lot at
Northeastern University. The first leg of the ride was cancelled
due to weather associated with Hurricane Floyd. Bikes and riders
will be transported to Connecticut where they hope resume their
ride Friday morning. (George Rizer/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
