<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 09/16/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) FORT WORTH, Texas -- Sept. 16, 1999 --
TEXAS-SHOOTING-SCENE, 09-16 -- The day after a gunman killed seven
people at the Wedgwood Baptist Church, one mourner, Joy Ray, prays
at a fence near the church after placing flowers there. In
Washington, President Clinton decried the attack and offered the
nation's sympathy to the victims, their families and the people of
Fort Worth. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 19 --
INVEST-STOCK-EXCHANGE, 09-16 -- The American Stock Exchange might
list more types of mutual funds. ``We're satisfied that it can be
done but we have a lot of work to do,'' says Gary Gastineau, senior
vice-president of new products for the American Stock Exchange,
adding that the system by which actively-managed mutual funds can
be traded will not be available for at least 18 months. (Frances
Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- NBC-PAXON,
09-16 -- W. Lowell (Bud) Paxson, the chairman of Paxson
Communications, in the control room of his television network. NBC
completed its expected acquisition of a 32 per cent stake in Paxson
Communications on Thursday, enabling NBC to achieve a long-sought
goal: a second national television channel for entertainment
programming. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 19 --
ABOUT-CARS-LINCOLN, 09-16 -- The Lincoln LS, which went on sale
during the summer, is aimed at the increasingly affluent baby
boomers who buy luxury cars mainly from Europe and Japan. This is a
smaller, sportier high-end sedan than Detroit has traditionally
offered, with responsive handling and a less pillow-like ride.
(Ford Motor Co./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MIDWEST, Wyo. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
19 -- INVEST-OIL, 09-16 -- Shares of oil services companies and
some independent oil concerns have surged recently as crude oil
prices have climbed. Even so, analysts say, some bargains remain.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 09-16 --
Sen. Larry Craig of Idaho, R-Id., turns to his staff, during a
Senate Appropriations Committee meeting on Thursday. Congress on
Thursday passed and sent to president Clinton a spending bill that
will increase its members' salaries, as well as those of Federal
workers and the next president. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- SCI-JUPITER-MOON-B&AMP;W, 09-16
-- The fracture lines in the frozen surface of Jupiter's moon
Europa as photographed by the Galileo spacecraft. An analysis of
the striking scalloped lines has yielded the strongest evidence yet
that a global ocean of liquid water once lay beneath the thick
crust of ice, and may still be there. (NASA/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-2, 09-16 --
Thursday's Bill Blass show was supposedly his swan song, though he
hasn't officially announced the sale of his business. From left, an
easy sportswear look by Blass features an unstructured hooded
jacket; handknit cashmere and beaded lace by Michael Kors; a
chiffon dress by Blass is one of many floral prints in his spring
line. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) DORCHESTER, Mass. -- Sept. 16, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-5, 09-16 -- A sailboat is washed up along a
boulevard adjacent to Dorchester Bay on Thursday as Hurricane Floyd
began to hit the area. Rainfall moved into state Thursday morning
and the storm was expected to bring surging tides and heavier rain
Thursday night and Friday morning to the eastern two-thirds of the
state. Hurricane warnings have been posted as far north as
Plymouth. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-1, 09-16 --
Lawrence Steele is American in Milan whose sensibility is
definitely European. And after several seasons of showing in Italy,
Victor Alfaro brought his spring collection back to New York.
Daringly cut dress is by Steele, left; leather vest with laser-cut
design by Alfaro. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) SEATTLE -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- GATES-SCHOLARSHIP, 09-16 --
Microsoft Corp. Chairman Bill Gates, second from left, and his wife
Melinda, after they were introduced by William H. Gray, III, left,
head of the United Negro College Fund, during a news conference on
Thursday. The Gates formerly announced their donation of $1 billion
over the next 20 years to finance college scholarships for minority
students. (Paul Joseph Brown/Seattle Post-Intelligencer) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) YORKTOWN, N.Y. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-4,
09-16 -- Students at the Mildred E. Strang Middle School leave just
after noon on Thursday after school officials closed the facility
because of the approach of Hurricane Floyd. Gov. George Pataki of
New York declared a state of emergency this afternoon for New York
City and Long Island in anticipation that a hurricane could strike
the region for the first time in eight years. (Suzanne DeChillo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WILMINGTON, N.C. -- Sept. 16, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-3,
09-16 -- Tom Glaviano surveys the damage to his car on Thursday
after Hurricane Floyd passed throught the area. Floyd came ashore
near Wilmington early Thursday with winds gusting to 110 mph. More
than 15 inches of rain fell in some areas, flooding Wilmington
streets and coastal areas. (Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
