<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5020 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-CHIP-T     09-16 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-CHIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICER FELT WORLDS COLLIDE AT SHOOTING SCENE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Chip Gillette found his worlds colliding
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette rushed to a church that would become the site of the
worst mass shooting in Fort Worth history as a police officer, a
family man, a deacon and minister. They all came together in
several horrifying minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church were a gunman, Gillette's wife and 15-year-old
daughter and a congregation of friends he had worshipped with since
moving to Fort Worth 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I saw it all, until I saw people in my church dying
and I was walking over corpses,'' said Gillette, 45. ``It was just
gruesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 7 p.m., Gillette settled on the couch for a quick
nap before leaving for his midnight shift as a police Weed and Seed
officer in east Fort Worth. Then, his dog began to bark.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that someone was at the door, Gillette said, he walked
to the front room and found the family's 4-year-old yellow
Labrador, Jake, staring out the window and ``barking like crazy''
atop a hope chest. The dog's gaze focused on Wedgwood Baptist
Church across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hair from the tip of his nose down his back was sticking
straight up like a razorback hog,'' Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette looked out to see dazed adults walking out from the
west door of the church. He would later learn that the adults had
mistakenly believed that the shots were coming from outside.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said he headed to the church to investigate wearing a
shirt, shorts and no shoes. He spotted a friend who yelled at
Gillette to get the department's SWAT team because ``someone was
inside shooting and killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone opened the church's glass door to flee, and popping
sounds became audible to Gillette. He turned to see a person down
just inside the church's glass door and immediately ran home for
his bulletproof vest, gun and uniform shirt. He radioed for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could think about was I had my family over there and
other kids I know,'' Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Gillette had just ducked into the church office to inform
a youth pastor that his wife had been involved in a car wreck when
the shooting started. Daughter Kimberly was inside the sanctuary
attending the youth rally. Debbie Gillette helped rush teens out of
the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her husband had returned to the church. He and
another officer arrived and entered the church's south side.
Gillette said he heard one last gunshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last pop was him shooting himself,'' Gillette said. ``I
made entry immediately afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, a 13-year veteran of the Police Department, declined
to discuss what he saw inside the church, pending the
investigation. He said he did not recognize the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never been here before. He's never been to a worship
service. His tie to the church is completely arbitrary at this
point,'' Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   After things had calmed down, Gillette searched under the pews
and around the sanctuary for his daughter and wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know who was up or down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He later found them safe. Other friends weren't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unreal. People I love and worship and pray with are going
to be affected forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting, Gillette said, he has been inside the church
two or three times with investigators sharing his recollections.
Despite the traumatic experience, Gillette said, he planned to work
Thursday night unless his supervisors objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' Gillette said. ``There are other friends we know
who have lost lives and lost family members. They're the ones I'm
concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, a church deacon and minister who occasionally performs
weddings, said he worries that Wedgwood Baptist Church will be
remembered only as one of many mass shooting sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like that stigma: Wedgwood just being a blip in
history, one in many,'' Gillette said. ``That's not what Wedgwood
is all about. This one incident doesn't make Wedgwood, it doesn't
destroy Wedgwood, and it doesn't change anything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Rebeca Rodriguez contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
