<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-SEMINARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTINGS ROCK FORT WORTH BAPTIST SEMINARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ ``Precious people, precious people _ they
all were precious people,'' the Rev. Al Meredith said through his
tears Thursday, grieving with a shocked Baptist seminary after
several current and former students were gunned down in his church
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   During an emotional chapel service at Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary, Meredith joined about 2,000 students and
faculty members in prayers for the victims of the Wednesday night
shootings at Wedgwood Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Two seminary students, Shawn Brown and Susan Kimberly Jones,
both 23, were among the dead. So was Sydney Browning, 36, who
graduated from the Fort Worth seminary two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Two other seminarians _ Jeff Laster, and Kevin Galey, who was a
teaching fellow at the graduate training institution, were wounded
when a gunman burst into the church during a ``See You at the
Pole'' youth rally. Larry Gene Ashbrook, 47, fatally shot seven
people and wounded seven others before committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Seminary President Ken Hemphill, his voice breaking with
emotion, said the seminary is offering all the help it can to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things we don't understand,'' Hemphill said.
``But we do know that God is still on his throne and is our
strength and a very present help in time of trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith knelt on stage and several seminary students and
professors knelt with him, the closest putting their arms around
his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Groggy from lack of sleep, Meredith paused for a moment to gain
his composure when he first started to speak. But the students
encouraged him with their applause.
</P>
<P>
   Many seminary faculty members and students had been up all
night, counseling and helping victims' families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Dickens, associate professor of pastoral ministries, stayed
up all night counseling his family and others after being
personally touched by the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Kristin, 15, was at the rally and saw one of her
best friends killed.
</P>
<P>
   Seminary student Vickie Stewart, who lives in the same campus
dormitory as Jones, said many dorm residents were up late Wednesday
night crying and praying when they learned that Jones was among the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock,'' said Stewart, 36. She said many students
knew that Jones and about four other students had gone to the
Wedgwood church for the Wednesday night prayer service and began to
worry as they watched the news on television.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Jones' room was a Bible verse she had copied on a small
message board: ``Love must be sincere. Hate what is evil. Cling to
what is good. Be devoted to one another in brotherly love. Romans
12:9-10.''
</P>
<P>
   After the prayer service, Meredith said grief-stricken members
of his church will recover from the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Satan means for evil, God means for good,'' he said. ``It
will grieve us and sadden us, but it is not going to stop us. Out
of all this misery of darkness, we will come out stronger.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Renee Lee contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
