<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUITING A REFERENCE  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What can a job seeker do when a past employers won't give any
information to a potential new one _ beyond, of course, your job
title and dates of employment? I have run into this problem with
the preschool where I previously worked. The board decided to no
longer let the director give references, which would be valuable to
me in applying to a school system. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Take heart. Your job-hunting problem has become so common
that it almost fails to qualify as a handicap any more. Fearing
lawsuits, many companies are now reluctant to give an official
reference beyond name, rank and serial number, said Sheila Pianin,
a job search consultant in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you can slide by without having someone vouch
for your abilities. ``You just have to get a little more
resourceful about who you ask,'' said Robin Ryan, a career
counselor in Seattle and the author of ``24 Hours to Your Next Job,
Raise, or Promotion'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Company policy notwithstanding, a peer or supervisor may be
willing to provide an unofficial reference, the experts said. Ms.
Ryan suggested one path: ``Go to a boss or former boss who's
sympathetic to the fact that you're trying to move on and say, `I
know the company's not supposed to do anything formally, but would
you be a reference if someone called you at home?'''
</P>
<P>
   Or you could ask someone to write you a letter of
recommendation, Ms. Pianin said. Individual letters noting your
qualifications for specific jobs are best, but even a generic
letter is better than nothing. At the very least, you may be able
to find copies of old job evaluations or letters of praise from a
supervisor, Ms. Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   If colleagues fear that giving even an informal reference will
get them in trouble, look outside. At a school, you may find ``a
parent who worked on a committee or who was a volunteer there and
saw you in action on a daily basis,'' Ms. Ryan said. People in the
corporate world can recruit clients, vendors and consultants to
sing their praises. Former co-workers who have moved on to other
companies can also prove invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother with personal references, Ms. Ryan said. Unless you
are asked specifically for character references unrelated to a job,
having a potential employer call your friends (even important,
successful ones) is essentially worthless. ``The person must be
familiar with your work and your ability to do the job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Keep searching until you have a list of at least three people
willing to testify to your professional greatness, Ms. Ryan said.
When references become an issue in the interview process, offer the
hiring manager the list. Explain to her that, when calling your
most recent employer for an official reference, she can expect to
be shuffled off to the human resources department and given only
basic information.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies will understand your position, Ms. Pianin said.
In fact, she noted, ``the hiring employer is usually following the
same practice.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd Street, New York, N.Y.
10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
