<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CLEMENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANGERS GOP LAWMAKERS BY INVOKING EXECUTIVE PRIVILEGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Asserting executive privilege, President Clinton on
Thursday rebuffed a congressional request for information about his
controversial decision to grant clemency to members of a violent
Puerto Rican nationalist group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's refusal to fully cooperate angered Republican
lawmakers who are pushing investigations into whether the clemency
offer was designed to help first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's
anticipated bid for the Senate in New York, home to about 1.3
million Puerto Rican expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to invoke executive privilege was the fourth time
since early 1996 that Clinton has refused to provide information to
a congressional committee. He also used the privilege during two
grand jury investigations of the Monica Lewinsky affair and former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's authority to grant clemency is not subject to
legislative oversight,'' White House deputy counsel Cheryl Mills
said in a letter to Rep. Dan Burton. The House Government Reform
Committee, chaired by Burton, last week subpoenaed administration
records and White House Counsel Beth Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   Mills pointed out in her letter that some documents were being
provided, but they ``are not directly related'' to the president's
clemency power or to communication with aides and other
administration officials who provided advice before Clinton made
the clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said Nolan would not be appearing before Burton's
committee.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said more than 10,000 pages of documents
related to the decision were being forwarded to Burton's committee.
Included are thousands of letters urging Clinton to show leniency
toward the prisoners, most of whom are members of FLAN, a Puerto
Rican separatist group.
</P>
<P>
   The group, formally known as the Armed Forces of National
Liberation, is blamed for 130 bombings in the Chicago and New York
areas from 1974 to 1983. Six people were killed in the attacks and
dozens were injured. None of the 16 offered clemency were convicted
of killing or wounding anyone, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and other Republicans, sidestepping the constitutional
issues raised by Mills, instead accused Clinton of misusing
executive privilege to hide information from Congress and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``By claiming executive privilege he is, in essence, telling the
American people that it's none of their business,'' Burton said.
``The president has a moral obligation ... to explain why he let
terrorists out of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vito Fossella, a New York Republican, said, ``If the
president genuinely believes his clemency deal was justified, I
find it curious that he would choose to stonewall Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossella last week steered through the House a resolution,
adopted 311-41, condemning Clinton's decision to release the Puerto
Ricans after they renounced violence. A similar resolution critical
of the president's action was approved Tuesday by the Senate, 95-2.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Mills' letter arrived on Capitol Hill, the Senate
Judiciary Committee, chaired by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, postponed
until next week a vote on whether to subpoena documents and
testimony from the White House officials regarding Clinton's
clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is whether or not we're going to let the committee
be stiffed,'' said Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the call for Clinton to drop his executive privilege
claim was Sen. Robert Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat and member
of the Judiciary Committee who has criticized the president's
clemency decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the committee will learn more about his motivations and
the process so that it's never repeated,'' Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno argued that Clinton was on strong
legal ground, citing Article II, Section 2 of the Constitution. It
lists pardoning prisoners as one of the few specific powers granted
exclusively to the president. In addition, Reno said, the courts
have consistently said within certain limits the president is
entitled to confidential communication with aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House staff and the Department of Justice act as
confidential advisers to the president as part of the clemency
review process,'' Reno said in a six-page letter to Clinton.
``Executive privilege has long been understood to protect
confidential advice generated during that process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's clemency decision, which relied heavily on research
and advice by former White House Counsel Charles Ruff, has drawn
criticism since it was announced last month. Republicans and
several law enforcement officers, including some who were
disfigured and disabled by the FLAN bombings, accused the president
of trying to help Hillary Clinton's impending Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   As the firestorm grew, Hillary Clinton joined in criticizing the
clemency offer, which angered Puerto Rican leaders in New York.
Last week, she explained that she should have consulted Latino
leaders before taking a side on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart on Thursday repeated earlier
White House denials that the New York Senate race was considered
when Clinton decided to offer clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say it absolutely and unequivocally that this case was
based on the merits as presented by the former (White House)
counsel Chuck Ruff, and the politics of New York or anywhere did
not come into play,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
