u e BC-FILM-HONOR-SPI &LR;      09-16 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HONOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RETURN WITH HONOR' IS AN EXTRAORDINARY EPIC SAGA OF PRISON
SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No single issue or event of the Vietnam War was more emotional,
more politicized or more quickly turned into the fodder of bad
Hollywood action movies than the long ordeal of the American POWs
in Hanoi. Their real and human story has never been told, at least
on film.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Return With Honor,'' an absorbing, sobering documentary
that begins a theatrical engagement on Friday, does just that. It
allows the POWs to calmly tell their own story in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter where you may stand on the still-controversial
war, the results make an extraordinary epic saga of prison
survival, in its own way as gripping, horrifying and inspiring as
such classics of the genre as ``Papillon'' and ``Birdman of
Alcatraz.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has an eerie veracity made possible by the Vietnamese
government's decision to release, after all these years, its own
film of the POW experience, including some dramatic footage of the
actual capture of downed pilots, initial debriefings and the
day-to-day routine at the Hanoi Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   So, as the middle-aged ex-prisoners _ some two dozen in all,
some imprisoned as long as eight and a half years _ sit before a
black background and give their personal reminiscences, the
testimony is frequently intercut with the actual Vietnam prison
footage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these faces are famous, and some of the scenes are
emotional and intimate. For instance, there's Arizona senator and
presidential hopeful John McCain being paraded through the streets,
lying wounded on a cot, wincing with pain, and telling his captors'
camera he loves his wife.
</P>
<P>
   And Commander James Stockdale, who retired an admiral and ran as
Ross Perot's running mate in 1992, driven to such despair by the
isolation and torture that he admits to attempting suicide.
(Stockdale has reportedly since criticized the film for being
``superficial.'')
</P>
<P>
   The stories themselves are amazingly free of self-serving
bluster, and deal less with chest-beating heroism in the face of
torture as with the innovative ways the prisoners found to stay in
communication with each other, developing complicated systems of
code their captors never did crack.
</P>
<P>
   As directed and written by the husband-wife team of Freida Lee
Mock and Terry Sanders (who won an Oscar for ``Maya Lin: A Strong
Clear Vision''), the film honors the ex-prisoners and subtly
celebrates their steadfastness, but never tries to paint them as
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally, the film forces us to step inside the POWs' shoes
and see the war and the homefront tumult from their point of view,
and understand how they came to feel that the best they could hope
to get out of their impossible situation was survival with some
semblance of their honor intact.
</P>
<P>
   Return With Honor. Directed and produced by Freida Lee Mock and
Terry Sanders. Screenplay by Freida Lee Mock, Terry Sanders and
Christine Z. Wiser. Documentary. Banner Entertainment. 102 minutes.
Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
