<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-RETURN17-COX     09-16 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-RETURN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traffic nightmare greets evacuees returning to Georgia homes
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade, Steve Visser and Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ga. _ In a few weeks, the tales of the great Hurricane
Floyd evacuation will become chatter at cocktail parties, on golf
course tees and between halves of high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Thursday's bright sun and cloudless blue sky over
Middle and east Georgia was changing dispositions _ and perhaps,
recollections _ of how more than 2 million people fled coastal
Georgia earlier this week as Floyd threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 16 _ which became the main evacuation route from
Savannah on Tuesday when all lanes were made westbound _ was moving
eastbound slowly but consistently on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy traffic was on I-75 south. Starting about 20 miles
south of Atlanta, I-75 was clogged with evacuees driving home.
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Transportation spokeswoman Karen Mashburn
said southeast Georgia highways were ``saturated'' by 10 a.m., two
hours after the state officially reopened major highways. Even amid
the rush to get to their coastal homes, Georgians were showing
their senses of humor.
</P>
<P>
   In gridlocked traffic on U.S. 82 between Brunswick and Nahunta,
car radios blasted as drivers got out on the roadside and boogied
down. Some opened well-stocked coolers, prompting other thirsty
refugees to hold up hand-lettered signs saying, ``Will work for
beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Moochie Nicholson, who stopped briefly in this Middle Georgia
town during her trip from her relatives' home in Snellville to
Ellabell, was returning with a bounty: a couch and chair
Nicholson's sister had given her during the two-day stay. ``Well,
it was worth my trip,'' said Nicholson, during a coffee stop at
Burger King in this Middle Georgia town. ``We got something out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, 52, her husband and her daughter's family were
traveling in a two-truck, one car caravan. Given that Nicholson had
fled her Savannah area home with a gun, a pet bird, a pull golf
cart and pictures of her grandchildren, she needed the extra
vehicles for the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Howard traveled from Atlanta to Savannah in a three-car
caravan with her family. The 49-year-old Savannah native has been
through other storms, but never evacuated before.
</P>
<P>
   She said you find out what's important to people by what they
place in the back of their car or truck when doom is near. ``We've
seen people haul boats, motorcycles, tractors,'' Howard said.
``It's amazing to see how important pets are to people. I saw one
lady with a snake, bird, dogs, even kittens.''
</P>
<P>
   Near here, along I-16, which was a virtual parking lot when the
evacuation hit full stride Tuesday, there were remnants of that
frustrating, crawling exodus. Broken-down cars pointed east sat on
the interstate shoulders in both directions _ a reminder of the
road's part in the largest peacetime movement of people in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite stalled cars, hungry children, sick babies and
complaints about unscrupulous innkeepers who overcharged or sold
rooms more than once, many who fled Floyd said they would do it all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   They would just plan better by making sure they had food,
blankets and motel reservations closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Hiers and her daughter, 21-year-old Laura Cowart, said
they have no desire to test whether the government is right when it
orders a mandatory evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a Category 3 hurricane and it was a voluntary
evacuation, we wouldn't leave,'' said the 44-year-old Hiers. ``But
if it was a storm like this, we'd leave again. We live on Tybee
Island, and we'd have been wiped out if it had hit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our house would have been under water,'' Cowart said. ``But I
wouldn't go as far as I did. I would go to Statesboro, not
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Lauren Lattany of Brunswick said her family had
to drive all the way to Athens, Tenn., to find a hotel room because
none were available as far north as Rome and Dalton. They returned
home late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in Brunswick was the same except nobody was
there,'' she said. ``The power was on and everything. It was an
extreme relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management directors in the coastal counties echoed
that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Abel, director of the Brunswick-Glynn County Emergency
Management Agency, said Floyd left behind only a few power outages
and minor beach erosion. He said he heard of only one tree crashing
into a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people coming back today don't even think anything
happened here,'' Abel said.
</P>
<P>
   But emergency management officials were careful not to suggest
that future evacuation orders should be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-member family from Brunswick who traveled to Atlanta in
two cars said it was crazy to stay and risk the destruction
threatened by Floyd. They were worried more about the possibility
their homes and trailers had been looted _ figuring folks who
ignored a mandatory evacuation might be the type to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They capitalize on your misery,'' said Phyllis Sams, 33.
``They wait back and steal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricane skipped Savannah. And that put some of the
returnees in a sour mood.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Williamson, 26, of Savannah spent 12 hours Tuesday on the
road to Charlotte, N.C., normally a four-hour trip for her. If
another hurricane threatens, count Williamson out of the traffic
mess on I-16. ``Putting 3 million people on the same road at the
same time is ridiculous,'' said Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   Many were simply happy to be going home. And already, the
evacuation stories were getting grander with each telling.
</P>
<P>
   The Savannah-to-Atlanta trip in gridlocked traffic took 12
hours, 14, or 18 hours, depending on the telling. But why try to
quantify the trip when a succinct description was available?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one word to sum it up: hell,'' said Jameela Lewis, who
was getting take-out from the Huddle House at Exit 26. ``I hate to
say it like that. But that's the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   There also were tales about the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Bukowski, his wife and her parents were stuck in traffic
on the way to Macon on Tuesday when 7-month-old Donovan began
crying and their doubts about getting to Macon got stronger.
Bukowski looked up to see the minister of Irwinton Baptist Church
putting up a shelter sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people were the nicest people I've ever met,'' Bukowski
said of the congregation. ``If I could send them a Medal of Honor,
I would.''
</P>
<P>
   At Clary's, a cafe near Savannah's historic district, Mayor
Floyd Adams Jr. consoled constituents during Thursday's lunch hour.
Adams pledged that the city would find more sensible hurricane
escape methods next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few glitches,'' said Adams. ``But we learned a
great deal. We just have to apply that knowledge to future
endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Center, sitting nearby, said government officials and the
news media alarmed the public without much justification.
</P>
<P>
   Back at a Subway restaurant here, where Shelia Wisener, her
three kids and mother in-law had stopped for lunch, Wisener's Chevy
Suburban was packed to the roof with blankets, her china, photos,
important papers and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she would unpack when she got home to Savannah,
she paused, perhaps thinking about Hurricane Gert, which is far out
to sea and expected to curve east of Bermuda and stay away from the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think until the season's over, I'll leave some of it
packed,'' Wisener said. ``I don't want to pack it all again.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Fran Gilpin and the Associated Press contributed to
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
