<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HUGE-HNS &LR;      09-16 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUGE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The upsizing of America is a fact of the 1990s. We like to wash
down double cheeseburgers and super-size french fries with a
64-ounce soda while driving a sport utility vehicle.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Size matters.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly does on the football field, where offensive linemen
continue to grow bigger, heavier and stronger. Thirty years ago,
the 1969 Texas Longhorns team that won the national championship
had an offensive line that averaged 213 pounds. This year, the
Texas line averages 317 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirteen?'' said Texas A&AMP;M guard Chris Valletta, a
relative lightweight at 295 pounds. ``That's what defensive backs
weigh now. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   At big-time college programs, 300 pounds has become the norm for
offensive linemen. In the Big 12 Conference, only Kansas State does
not have at least one lineman who weighs 300 or more. At Colorado
and Texas, all five starting linemen come in at more than three
bills.
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado opened the season against Colorado State, the
offensive lines on both teams were heavier than the line for the
Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos. (Colorado averaged 311,
Colorado State 300 and Denver 287.) Granted, the Broncos' line is
one of the smallest in the NFL, but the size of collegiate linemen
is increasing with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Intense weight training, supplements such as creatine that add
bulk, and a larger average size in general are the main reasons for
the explosion of size in linemen. (The NCAA does not allow the use
of anabolic steroids or androstenedione, the substance used last
season by St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire. According to
NCAA literature, the organization conducts drug tests before bowls
and administers spot drug testing year-round.)
</P>
<P>
   Using the Longhorns as an example, the growth has been
eye-popping. From 213 pounds in 1969, the average weight of linemen
jumped to 248 in 1979 to 274 in 1989 to this year's 317.
</P>
<P>
   How large can you go? Texas left tackle Leonard Davis is 6-6,
360 pounds, and he sees bigger, stronger, younger players coming
along behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like (6-6, 339-pound sophomore) Mike Williams and (6-6,
335-pound freshman) Derrick Dockery, those are big guys,'' Davis
said. ``I always thought I would be the biggest guy here, but I'm
not so sure now. I'm a little leery of the big new guys coming in
every year. I have to stay on top of my game and work hard to keep
a spot. You can't earn a spot on size.''
</P>
<P>
   But as 6-5, 315-pound Texas guard Roger Roesler says, the bigger
the better _ as long as the bulk doesn't get in the way of a
player's quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get a 300-pounder, but you have to make sure you get
speed and agility with it,'' Roesler said. ``Coaches look for
somebody who has speed and agility, so they'll take a 280-pounder
if he is better than a 300-pounder. But if they have the same speed
and agility, then without a doubt I would favor the heavier guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I would lean toward the heavier guys because I'm
right up there with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are cases where a player is too big _ even to play the
offensive line. Texas Tech left tackle Jonathan Gray, considered
one of the top players at his position in the nation, once weighed
nearly 400 pounds during his redshirt 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Gray has lost weight each year and is down to 357 in his junior
season. He is still called ``The House,'' the nickname hung on him
when he was flirting with 400 pounds, but he's no longer an
apartment complex, merely a nice, four-bedroom split-level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a practice dummy then,'' Gray said of his redshirt
season. ``That was when I was able to assess myself and realize I
needed to change a lot of the things I was doing to be able to move
to the next level. I had to make some alterations in my physique.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the smaller guys that have the speed to work against me,
I knew I needed to get a little bit faster to be able to pass-block
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's role model is St. Louis Rams tackle Orlando Pace, who was
one of the first megasized college linemen while at Ohio State in
the mid-1990s. What set Pace apart was the speed he possessed
despite weighing more than 325 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paved the way for really big offensive linemen,'' Gray
said. ``But you have to be fast and big like he is, not just big
like he is. I don't see bigger automatically being better. It
really doesn't pay to be big and not be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the biggest difference in the last decade. Nearly every
one of the 300-pound-plus linemen has the quickness and agility to
handle the defensive player across from him. In the past, huge
linemen merely leaned on their opponent, making them strong run
blockers put suspect pass blockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you'd get a 260-pound guy and people would say
he's kind of on the light side but he's super-fast,'' Valletta
said. ``Now it's like, well, he's 315 pounds but he's super-fast.
It's just getting bigger and quicker, so you have to do the same
thing in order to survive. As long as you can stay quick and get
your pads under theirs, the more size you have, the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have size, but you have to be able to move and be
athletic and get under people. Leverage is the key. If you're lower
than the other guy, you're going to win; it doesn't matter if
you're 260 or 360. And that's what you're seeing, guys who are
300-plus who can really move and really play.''
</P>
<P>
   Valletta, a junior from Plano, gained 10 pounds during the
summer, taking him from 285 to 295. He spent two hours a day, five
days a week, in the weight room, pushing hard when it might have
been easier to bulk up by having a couple of extra helpings of
mashed potatoes or another chocolate malt. It doesn't work that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're so tired, you don't want to finish,''
Valletta said. ``What makes you want to finish is that you know the
guys at Texas are doing the same thing, and they're going to
finish. So we might as well finish and finish harder. That's the
attitude you have to have. That's what gets you through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at 295, Valletta is one of the smaller offensive linemen at
A&AMP;M. The Aggies have Andy Vincent (304) and Shea Holder (304) at
tackles, Valletta and Semisi Heimuli (309) at guards and center
Seth McKinney (293) on the offensive line, which averages 301
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Valletta wonders what linemen will look like in the future. Will
400 pounds be the norm 30 years from now? That might seem
incomprehensible, but certainly no one in 1969 thought so many
300-pound linemen would be stomping around football fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like 300 pounds does seem to be the norm now,''
Valletta said. ``It makes you think what they're going to look like
20 years from now. It's crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think there has to be a limit. There has to be a
point down the road where guys just get too big to be agile. But
that's what everyone thought before. I've seen guys who are 6-3 and
weigh 340, 350 and can really move. I'm 6-3, and I don't think I'd
be able to walk across the street if I was 340.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside to the upsizing of lines is by the fourth quarter,
defenses are worn down. Davis and Texas Tech's Curtis Lowery, a
6-5, 327-pound guard, say they've noticed opponents shrinking away
as the game progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe,'' Davis said. ``You've worked hard to
get to this point, then you have this guy who is literally ready to
walk off the field. You feel good about yourself. That's the goal _
to make a guy not want any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lowery: ``In the fourth quarter, when we've been pushing on
them the whole game, they just can't fight against how big we are.
They try and try, but eventually we're going to wear them down.''
</P>
<P>
   The dream of every starting lineman who has worked to bulk up to
the 300-pound-plus range is to advance to the NFL. Davis, a junior
from Wortham, says he believes he is at his ideal weight and
doesn't anticipate having to get any bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be none of that 380 or 390 stuff,'' Davis said.
``My back would start hurting. I can only carry so much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
