<HEADER>
A5046 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NASA-GORE-HNS &LR;      09-16 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT KNOCKS HOLE IN PROPOSED TRIANA PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore's plan to have NASA provide
continuous, satellite-generated images of the Earth for posting on
the Internet is not worth its $220 million cost, the space agency's
internal auditor says.
</P>
<P>
   In a new report, inspector general Roberta Gross said it would
be ill-advised for the financially strapped agency to fund a new
system to collect pictures of Earth when many images already are
available. In addition, Gross said Gore's proposed Triana project
would cost more than four times the vice president's $50 million
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, speaking through his spokesman Chris Lehane, defended
his proposed round-the-clock Earth pictures Thursday as a ``good
idea and good science.''
</P>
<P>
   The planetary views would increase scientific understanding of
environmental changes affecting the ozone layer and wind patterns,
Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Triana project would help us get important information
regarding weather patterns,'' he added, citing the havoc Tropical
Storm Floyd was wreaking Thursday on the East Coast. ``Weather
patterns have a dramatic impact on our nation's safety and
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA has spent nearly $41 million on the controversial project,
which has not received congressional endorsement. Republican
lawmakers in the House have voiced objections to Gore's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, in a letter to NASA Administrator Dan Goldin last week,
was critical of the agency's plan to spend much of its scarce
federal funds on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has yet to set NASA's budget for next year, but Texas
lawmakers on Capitol Hill expect the final figure to be about $13.6
billion, roughly the same as this year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the context of NASA's constrained budget and the widespread
availability of satellite pictures of the Earth, we are concerned
about the cost and changing goals of the Triana mission,'' Gross
wrote on behalf of the inspector general's office. ``We are
concerned that Triana's added science may not represent the best
expenditures of NASA's limited funding.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Triana critic Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr.,
R-Wis. and chairman of the House panel that oversees NASA, seized
on Gross' comments to reiterate his call for Gore to abandon the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope NASA will take the IG's reassessment recommendation to
heart and let science _ not politics _ decide how to spend NASA's
scarce budget dollars,'' said Sensenbrenner. ``By terminating the
Triana mission sooner, rather than later, we will free up well over
$100 million for higher NASA priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by Gore, the satellite would be stationed halfway
to the sun and beam high-resolution images of Earth to anyone with
access to the Internet. The project is named for Rodrigo de Triana,
the sailor who first spotted North America on Christopher Columbus'
voyage in 1492.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite is scheduled for launch aboard a space shuttle in
December 2000. By next month, NASA will have spent $41 million
developing the satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, in her Sept. 10 inspector-general report, criticized the
space agency for pressing forward with the Triana project without
fully assessing the scientific value of photographing the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA has described the Triana mission as the product of a
rigorous peer-review process,'' Gross wrote. ``(But) neither
internal nor external advisory groups reviewed whether a spacecraft
beaming back pictures of the Earth on the Internet was the most
effective way to educate and inspire the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross added that NASA could keep down costs and still provide
live pictures of Earth by conducting a ``virtual Triana'' a project
that would rely on U.S. spacecraft already transmitting images of
the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual Triana is the least costly option, and the one most
likely to meet the program's educational and inspiration goals
faster, better and cheaper, but it would gather no new scientific
data,'' the inspector general wrote.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Ghassem Asrar, associate administrator for Earth science,
assailed Gross' report for mischaracterizing the extent of
scientific discussion and work that went into the agency's
consideration into launching Triana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report's recommendation would have us revisit the
fundamental design of a project that is far along in its
development and is meeting the objectives set for it within the
cost and schedule constraints,'' Asrar said.
</P>
<P>
   Gross voiced her concerns about the Triana project as Senate and
House members prepare to debate how much money NASA should receive
next year.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate Appropriations subcommittee this month voted to fund
the space agency at $13.6 billion next year, about $900 million
more than the House has approved for the agency. Texas Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, a Republican, and House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, said they expect the higher Senate figure to clear
Congress and be signed into law by President Clinton within the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
