<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-BAHAMAS17-COX     09-16 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-BAHAMAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Respect for ocean means strong houses, less damage in Bahamas
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPE TOWN, Bahamas _ Sixty-year-old Peggy Gates has lived on
rocky Elbow Key all her life and has never seen a storm with the
awesome power of Hurricane Floyd. With reported winds off 155 mph
and waves surging to 20 feet, Floyd chewed away towering sand
dunes, toppled some houses and even cut this narrow island clean in
half for a short time.
</P>
<P>
   But as badly as Floyd roughed up Hope Town, Cherokee, Sandy
Point, Marsh Harbour and the other towns of Great Abaco, the
destruction in most places didn't appear catastrophic, at least
compared to the utter devastation that Hurricane Andrew _ a
smaller, less-powerful storm _ left in South Florida in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   While there was serious destruction on Abaco and there will be
weeks of misery with no power or telephones, residents think they
know why so many homes survived largely intact. Born and raised
with the ocean as an ever-present neighbor, they have a healthy
respect for its power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We build our houses strong and we build them where they should
be,'' said Gates, whose home survived Floyd's fury with hardly a
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, she pointed to a stretch of beach where foreign
residents recently built vacation homes atop a sand dune. Floyd
leveled seven of the homes, swatting them into heaps of splintered
lumber now floating in the nearby bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourists want to be on the water, and that's fine when the
weather is good,'' she said, shaking her head at the piles of
debris. ``But there is nothing like the power of the ocean. Some of
the locals' houses overlook the ocean, but they build on rock, not
on a sand dune.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the destruction left by Floyd isn't serious.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of homes and businesses have ripped-up roofs, and
hundreds more are missing shingles, but there are still roofs in
place on most buildings. There are twisted signs and torn awnings,
snapped trees and power lines dangling from some poles, but within
24 hours after Floyd had passed, residents had cleared most
streets, traffic was moving and life was slowly headed back to a
semblance of normal.
</P>
<P>
   After Andrew, large swaths of south Dade County looked as if
they had been bombed. Visitors driving across elevated freeway
bridges saw a vast panorama of destruction, with thousands of homes
completely roofless or with caved-in walls, and thousands more
roofs stripped bare of every single shingle.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, of course, devastated a much more densely-populated
area. It took south Dade weeks to clear the roads of downed trees,
and months to restore basic services such as power and telephones.
</P>
<P>
   And Abaco will take months to recover completely.
</P>
<P>
   But while the island's sparse population means fewer homes and
buildings are in harm's way, it is clear even to a casual eye that
most of the buildings in the Bahamas fared far better in Floyd's
winds than many south Dade structures fared during Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   There was an outcry after Andrew about shoddy building practices
and inspections, and the county adopted what is considered one of
the toughest building codes in the country. The standard is to make
most buildings withstand hurricanes with winds up to 125 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Gate's son, Bill, who has built houses in Florida and on Elbow
Key, feels builders here face a much tougher _ if unofficial _ code
than in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here knows everybody and they know which carpenter
built which house,'' he said. ``A code to 125 mph is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Gates was familiar with crews that might build homes
in six weeks or less, throwing up one after another in sprawling
suburban developments where the emphasis is on speed and sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bahamas, he takes six months to build a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use press-board or nail guns,'' he said, referring to
labor-saving devices and materials popular with American
construction crews. ``Every individual stud is strapped at the top
and bottom and every rafter is bolted through the double top plate
with a half-inch bolt. You do that and you know that house will be
standing after the hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Cash, another Hope Town resident who manages dozens of
rental vacation homes, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always got in mind what we're building for, and that's
hurricanes,'' he said. ``All our hardware is stainless steel, all
our concrete is hand-mixed. Here, reputation is everything. We
don't have inspectors, but the community is so small that you can't
get away with cutting any corners.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Gates says Bahamians simply don't know any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have an ordinary hurricane here and it hardly does any
damage, but when it hits the States, everything is flattened,'' she
said. ``People here respect the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
