<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-WARNING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN WARNED OTHERS AS GUNMAN BEGAN HIS RAMPAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If instinct told Mary Beth Talley to run
away from a man mumbling and firing his way through a church foyer
Wednesday night, she didn't heed it.
</P>
<P>
   Talley, 17, dropped the programs she was handing out and ran
into the sanctuary of Wedgwood Baptist Church, yelling over the
sounds of a Christian rock band, ``There's a man shooting
outside!''
</P>
<P>
   She ran to the mother of a lifelong friend. The woman was
struggling to force her disabled daughter out of the pew and onto
the floor. Shielding part of Heather MacDonald with her body as
gunman Larry Gene Ashbrook walked back and forth shooting, Talley
knew she provided an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   ``My full body was in view of him. I heard a shot, and then I
felt it,'' she said Thursday from a recliner in her far southwest
Fort Worth home. ``I thought, was I just shot? I felt a sting. I
thought it would hurt a lot, but it really didn't. I guess I was
numb. I was just thinking, `Don't freak out' or Heather would start
freaking out and he would notice her, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The last shot rang out and people started yelling: ``He's dead.
He's dead,'' she said. Talley half-ran, half-staggered outside to
the church lawn and laid down. She tried to use programs to stanch
the blood soaking one of her favorite shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `God, please don't let me die. I'm ready if
you want to take me, but I'm not ready,' '' she recalled. ``I
haven't seen my mom all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura MacDonald described Talley as a ``precious girl. But I
thought that before that night'' when Talley held on to MacDonald's
daughter even after Talley was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had her hand on one side of her neck and I had the other
side, and we were trying to keep Heather down,'' MacDonald said.
``She had her body up over my daughter's shoulder. We felt so
exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Talley, who has taken her daughter to Wedgwood Baptist
Church since she was a toddler, tried all day Thursday to get her
daughter to rest, to calm down and eat something. But her
daughter's actions Wednesday night hardly came as a surprise, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised her not to just think about herself, but to think
about other people first,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Talley, an honor student at Southwest High School,
knew by the time she got to the hospital that she would be all
right. The paramedics and doctors were being so rough with her, she
figured that it must be a good sign, she said. By 3 a.m., she was
headed home.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet penetrated her right shoulder, creating a
quarter-size hole, and traveled into her lower back, where it
remains embedded in muscle and tissue. Doctors will remove the
bullet in a few weeks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, Talley seemed more concerned about papers
and schoolwork, her flute practice with the marching band and all
the other pursuits of a teen-age girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't luck,'' she said. ``It was an act of God.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
