<SLUG> BC-IRS-PENSIONS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH-BALANCE PENSION PLANS UNDER SCRUTINY BY IRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Facing mounting pressure from Congress, the Internal Revenue
Service has effectively put off approval of so-called cash-balance
pension plans, which critics say discriminate against older workers
while saving many employers millions of dollars every year.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face by the agency comes as its chief counsel prepares
to testify before a Senate committee on Tuesday, and some lawmakers
seek to rein in what they now call an abusive practice that can
reduce middle-age employees' pensions by as much as a third to a
half.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of companies have already converted from traditional
pension plans to cash-balance pensions. Unlike old-fashioned plans,
in which employees earn most of their retirement benefits toward
the end of their careers, under cash-balance plans, employers set
aside the same percentage of an employee's pay every year. As a
result, pensions of younger workers grow faster, but older workers
can, and in some cases do, lose hundreds of thousands of dollars in
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Conversions at some companies have prompted protests from both
blue-collar and white-collar employees, most notably those at IBM,
where a number of workers have sought to unionize over the issue.
The chairwoman of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, Ida
L. Castro, has also said that her agency is investigating whether
the plans unlawfully discriminate against older workers.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo on Wednesday, Carol Gold, the IRS director of employee
plans, told regional IRS officials that ``a number of important
issues may be raised'' when a company converts to a cash-balance
plan, and she ordered them to obtain technical advice from
officials in Washington before taking action on conversions.
Previously, regional IRS offices had the authority to approve
conversions without a go-ahead from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The memo does not affect any pension plans that have already
obtained approval to convert to cash-balance plans. But critics of
cash-balance plans said the memo from Ms. Gold was certain to halt,
at least for some time, approvals of new plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, this is a freeze,'' said William
Carr, a Denver lawyer who represents employees in litigation
involving cash-balance plans.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ferguson, director of the Pension Rights Center in
Washington, said: ``This suggests that, finally, the IRS is taking
a hard look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to characterize the effect of the memo, Don Roberts, an
IRS spokesman, declined, saying the document spoke for itself.
Roberts said he did not know how many companies had already
received or were awaiting approval. Since the IRS has so far not
raised major objections to cash-balance conversions, a number of
employers have converted their pensions without first receiving
approval.
</P>
<P>
   But companies that fail to eventually obtain approval are at
risk of having their plans' tax-exempt status stripped. In fact, in
a case involving Onan Corp., a division of Cummins Engine Co., the
IRS took the position in a lawsuit last month that Onan's plan
should be stripped of its tax-exempt status because of the way it
converted to a cash-balance plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly hope any slowdown or any stalling is not the
result of any political pressure'' applied to the IRS, said James
Delaplane, vice president for retirement policy at the Association
of Private Pension and Welfare Plans, which represents large
employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would certainly not be reasonable for the service to shift
course from their existing guidance'' that cash-balance plans are
``appropriate and legal,'' Delaplane said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Charles O. Rossotti, the commissioner of the IRS, said in an
interview on Wednesday that the service was reviewing its policy to
determine whether conversions to cash-balance plans may unlawfully
discriminate against some workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very complex issue, and very fact-specific to each
plan and how the conversion is done. Some conversions may be very,
very reasonable, and others may not be,'' Rossotti said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on what direction IRS policy might take.
``We are working on it. It has to be worked through,'' he said,
referring other questions to Stuart Brown, the IRS chief counsel,
who is expected to testify on Tuesday before the Senate Committee
on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions. Brown declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bernard Sanders, I-Vt., a critic of cash-balance plans,
said the IRS action might ``provide breathing space for the IRS,
giving them the opportunity to thoroughly review whether these
plans violate federal age-discrimination laws.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
