<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW REBOUNDS FROM EARLY SLIDE BUT STILL CLOSES 63.96 LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices pulled out of an early sinking spell
Thursday to close with modest losses for two of the major gauges,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index eked out a slender
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the forces buffeting the market were warnings of corporate
profit shortfalls, a rebound by the dollar from a 44-month low
against the yen, a stronger-than-expected report on industrial
output in August, a rise in a barometer of Philadelphia-area
manufacturing and the approach of Friday's triple-witching session
when options and futures contracts expire.
</P>
<P>
   Many traders heeded official advice to leave early to beat the
full effects of Hurricane Floyd, in some cases covering short
positions _ that is, buying securities to repay borrowed securities
they have already sold _ and that helped fuel the comeback that
began about mid-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that traders closed out positions they'd normally
close out tomorrow,'' said Warren Epstein, head trader at Richard
A. Rosenblatt &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange kept normal hours and said it would
do so again Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which at one stage was down
nearly 175 points, finished with a loss of 63.96 points, or 0.6
percent. At 10,737.46, the Dow is 5.2 percent off its Aug. 25 peak
but is still 17 percent higher for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ market fell 7.45 points, or a quarter of 1 percent,
to close at 2,806.72. The S&AMP;P 500 edged up 0.51 of a point, to
1,318.48.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates eased, apparently reflecting diminished concern
about the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell 4 9/16 to 103 15/16 to account for more
than a third of the decline in the blue-chip Dow, where 21 stocks
fell and only eight gained.
</P>
<P>
   The session's most active issue was Quintiles Transnational, a
North Carolina company that is the biggest conductor of clinical
trials for drug makers. Quintiles skidded 14} a share, to 20, after
it said profits would be shy of expectations this year and next.
More than 39.5 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   FDX, parent of Federal Express, and Eastman Chemical also warned
of lower profits; FDX fell 5 7/16 a share, to 38\, while Eastman
lost 2], to 43 15/16. Xerox, which shuffled its sales force again,
slumped 4 5/16, to 42}.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products gained 3{, to 46}, on word that it may be
near settling injury claims by users of its diet drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the NASDAQ set a closing high in September, the Dow
industrials in August and the S&AMP;P 500 in July, the general market
has lagged well behind. According to an analysis by Alfred Goldman
of A.G. Edwards, 51 percent of S&AMP;P companies closed Tuesday 20
percent or more below their 52-week highs prior to mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Modigliani, an equity strategist at Morgan Stanley, called
the market ``overvalued,'' but said it still offered values in
basic materials, energy and some cyclical stocks. ``We think a
global recovery is under way,'' she said, predicting that the
Federal Reserve would avoid raising short-term interest rates at
its Oct. 5 policy meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Declining stocks outnumbered advancing ones 2,063 to 916 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 220 making new lows and only 18 new
highs.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell overseas, the biggest losses being 2.7 percent in
Tokyo, 1.5 percent in Germany and 1.5 percent in Sao Paulo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
