<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, RENO PUSH EFFORTS TO REDUCE GUN VIOLENCE IN WAKE OF TEXAS
TRAGEDY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW BROMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Spurred by the shooting deaths of seven people in a
Texas church, President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno
urged the country Thursday to redouble efforts to reduce
gun-related violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to act as if it were our own children being
targeted by gun violence,'' Clinton said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there is nothing we can do to assure that this
will never happen,'' the president said. ``But there is a lot we
can do to assure that it will happen more rarely. And I can only
hope that the shock of this event will spur that kind of action.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the Fort Worth tragedy served as yet another wake-up
call to America to better understand why such violent acts occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to require the commitment of all Americans to look
at the issue of how we handle guns, of how we deal with mental
illness, of how we deal with hate,'' Reno said during her weekly
press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to several recent high profile shootings, she said,
``...these events cry out for America to come together and to
address them in an effective, permanent manner.''
</P>
<P>
   A gunman identified as Larry Gene Ashbrook opened fire at the
Fort Worth church during a prayer rally Wednesday, then fatally
shot himself. He killed seven people and wounded seven.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, like the Columbine High School slayings in Colorado
or the shootings at the Jewish Community Center shootings in
California, is expected to renew calls to strengthen federal
gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Senate passed a bill that would impose
background checks on gun show sales, outlaw importation of
large-capacity ammunition clips and require the sale of safety
locks with firearms. But the House removed some restrictions
approved by the Senate and voted to roll back restrictions on gun
show sales. The bill is now in conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Wednesday's
shooting should pressure the conference committee members to
reconcile their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to act on protecting children; it's time to act on
passing sensible gun control, and the time to wait and to posture
is over,'' he said. ``I think that given enough time, the
leadership will send the conferees (word to), tell them to get to
work, and this legislation will pass.''
</P>
<P>
   House members from Texas sought to avoid tying the ongoing gun
control debate with the incident in Fort Worth, instead urging
Americans not to jump to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words cannot express my sense of shock and sadness at the
tragedy that took place at the Wedgwood Baptist Church. For a few
brief yet interminable moments, this house of worship became a
place of fear and terror,'' said Rep. Kay Granger, a Texas
Republican whose district includes the church. ``At this moment,
there are more questions than answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas, called the shooting a ``tragedy for
our entire community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This horrible act again makes clear that violent tragedies can
happen everywhere, even though we all hoped it wouldn't in our
community,'' said Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children deserve, at a minimum, a sense of security in a
house of worship or when attending school,'' Frost said. ``We
should not let the act of a deranged man further chip away at our
children's dwindling sense of security.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said, ``Clearly the
man responsible for this tragedy hated life. He hated all that was
good. And so long as there are people who have no regard for the
sanctity of life, we will never be safe. Not even in God's house.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
