<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-LAIRD-     09-16 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-LAIRD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN IS LEFT PARALYZED AS HIS BIRTHDAY TURNS FROM JOY TO TERROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR., CHRIS VAUGHN 
and MARISA TAYLOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ First came the simple pleasures of being a
kid:
</P>
<P>
   The revelry of a 16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership, finally, of a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   And the anticipation of suiting up for another high school
football game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the shooting erupted Wednesday night at Wedgwood
Baptist Church, the simple pleasures vanished: Justin Laird was
paralyzed from a bullet fired by a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, it has been a roller coaster of optimism and despair
for Justin: first, being told he was getting better, inspiring hope
that he might soon play football again; then, the sobering report
from a doctor that he may never
</P>
<P>
   walk again.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, friends and relatives said, Justin's will to
recover has been unwavering, giving strength to the people around
him.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours after the church massacre Wednesday night,
Justin's friends, relatives and teammates at Brewer High School
began to breath a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-pound offensive lineman for the Brewer Bears would live,
doctors told them.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the lucky ones at the church where Larry Gene
Ashbrook, 47, casually walked into a prayer meeting and concert
with a cigarette in his mouth and a gun in his hand. Ashbrook
fatally shot seven people and wounded Laird and six others before
killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was Justin's birthday _ a good day early on, when he got his
driver's license. ``He was very excited about that,'' a family
member said.
</P>
<P>
   The church had planned a surprise party for Justin after the
prayer meeting. Instead, Ashbrook walked in.
</P>
<P>
   Justin was sitting near his mother and father. They rushed to
his side when the gunfire began.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father discovered that he had been shot, and he was the
one who dragged him out of the building,'' said Jim Gatliff, the
family pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, in the intensive care unit at John Peter Smith
Hospital in Fort Worth, Justin was not talking about the shooting.
His mind was on football.
</P>
<P>
   He dispatched a message to Coby Kirkpatrick, athletic trainer
for the Brewer Bears, saying he wanted his play book for the game
scheduled for last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told his grandpa that I had to tape him up so he could play
tonight,'' Kirkpatrick said. ``So I brought a roll of tape and left
it in his room,'' the trainer said as he waited with dozens of
others to give blood for those wounded at Wedgwood Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Justin's doctor walked into his hospital
room. Once again, optimism and relief turned to gloom.
</P>
<P>
   The news was not good.
</P>
<P>
   Justin was told that the large-caliber bullet had damaged his
spinal cord and was still in his body, causing paralysis from the
chest down, said his grandfather, Don Laird. A neurosurgeon had
been summoned to determine the risks of trying to remove the
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, there will be no more football, and ``it would
take a miracle'' for Justin to walk again, Don Laird said the
doctor told them.
</P>
<P>
   If the prognosis frightened Justin, he did not show it, his
grandfather said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Don Laird said, the teen attempted to prop up his
shaken family. ``He's taking it really good. He took it better than
I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatliff added: ``He wasn't even angry or upset. He was humbled
by the support from his family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hospital waiting room, Justin's friends, classmates
and teammates cried and hugged as they received word of the
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   The grandfather went into a small office to make telephone
calls. He clutched in his hand a message from Dennis Franchione,
head football coach for Texas Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs want to join the Brewer Bears at the hospital to show
their support for Justin. It will mean a lot for the wounded boy,
Don Laird said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's lived and breathed football since he was 3 years old,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears' game was canceled last night. Several players said
that if Justin could not play, neither would they.
</P>
<P>
   Justin and his parents, John and Lori Laird, will rebound from
the tragedy, said an aunt, Judy Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very devoted to family; they are always there for
each other,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   She said of John and Lori Laird: ``They both worship that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
