<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NBC-PAXSON-ART-NYT &LR;      09-16 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-PAXSON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC COMPLETES ACQUISITION OF 32 PERCENT STAKE IN PAXSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BILL CARTER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC completed its acquisition of a 32 percent stake in Paxson
Communications Corp. on Thursday, enabling NBC to achieve a
long-sought goal: a second national television channel for
entertainment programs.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, for $415 million in new Paxson convertible stock,
includes the right for NBC to acquire 49 percent in Paxson in
February 2002 for another $800 million should changes in federal
regulations make it possible for NBC to expand its ownership of
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   NBC president Robert Wright called the deal ``a very good
investment for us,'' adding that in what has become an intensely
crowded media environment, ``you need as much voice as you can
get.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that recent deals involving ``highly integrated
competitors'' _ the planned acquisition of CBS Corp. by Viacom Inc.
_ ``pushed us to put ourselves in a position to expand our
services.''
</P>
<P>
   If NBC, a unit of General Electric Co., were to convert its new
securities, its holdings would translate into $13.01 a common
share. Shares of Paxson fell $1.0625 Thursday, to $14; those of GE
rose $1.25, to $117.25.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Dixon, an analyst with Paine Webber, said that the
deal was positive for both companies because it gave Paxson the
revenue needed to finish buying stations and to cover program
costs. It also ``gives NBC very real flexibility as they go
forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson Communications chairman W. Lowell Paxson said he had
negotiated with several potential investors but that ``NBC stood
out as the best partner.'' Paxson assembled a lineup of 72
television stations covering about 76 percent of the country for
his Pax TV network, which he built around what he called ``family
friendly'' programming, which consisted mostly of repeats of
programs like ``Touched By an Angel,'' ``Highway to Heaven'' and
``Bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright noted that NBC's affiliates, which have opposed many of
NBC's investments in cable, had reason to embrace this move because
it allows them to form partnerships with Paxson stations that could
result in programs like newscasts receiving additional coverage on
the Paxson stations, thus generating more revenue for the
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Wright also cited the additional opportunity NBC will have to
expand its channel capacity when broadcasters go to a digital
system that will make it possible to turn a single broadcast
channel into four or five.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters have wrestled with the decision of whether to use
the digital spectrum to create a single high-definition channel or
multiple channels. NBC Cable president Thomas Rogers, one of the
architects of the Paxson investment, said this deal would enable
NBC to do both.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we acquire controlling interest in Paxson,'' he said, ``we
may be able to use one channel in a market for high definition and
the other for multiplex channel options.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what specific NBC programming may turn up on the Paxson
channels, Pax TV president and chief programmer Jeff Sagansky said
he would work closely with the two executives in charge of NBC
entertainment, Scott Sassa and Garth Ancier, to decide which NBC
programs receive additional exposure on the Paxson stations.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
