<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE A CITY IN NEED OF MILK, AND A LITTLE PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ At 6:30 a.m., the lines have already
formed outside two food stores in New Belgrade, a district that
houses hundreds of thousands of the Serbian capital's 1.5 million
people. Residents are lining up for milk, which in recent weeks has
been scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two days now I have been standing in the lines for milk,''
said Jozefa Markovic, a pensioner, later in the day. ``And this is
the most basic foodstuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not only milk that is in short supply. Gasoline, whether
in state-run gas stations or on the black market, is also hard to
find and has doubled in price in the last two weeks. The currency,
the Yugoslav dinar, has slipped further in the past weeks, trading
on the black market at 13 to the German mark, from 12 just a week
ago, more than double the official rate.
</P>
<P>
   Branka Stojanovic, a mother of three, returned home from
Thursday's shopping expedition with no meat and only a carton of
chocolate milk. ``Prices are going up steadily,'' she said. Mrs.
Stojanovic, an artist who teaches high school, only last week
received her April pay packet. ``Two of my children are sick,'' she
said. ``All in all, the situation is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   After decades of mismanagement by Communists and their
successors, after eight years of war and international sanctions
and then a springtime of NATO bombing, Serbia's economy is in a
perilous state. Now, as winter approaches, there are even more
signs of distress, as Serbs buy up what they can and batten down
the hatches.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities also seem to be organizing themselves to at
least try to meet basic needs and thus avert widespread public
discontent. The Serbian prime minister, Mirko Marjanovic, traveled
to Moscow last week and apparently sealed a deal for Russian gas
supplies for the winter. His trip followed a visit to Belgrade by
Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Avdeyev, the first
high-level contact between the two countries since the war over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how Belgrade, already indebted to Moscow, will
manage to pay for the gas, or why the Russians continue to supply
it. Foreign currency reserves here are low, unofficially estimated
at less than $150 million. Opposition economists say the government
is printing money freely, which may have caused the fall in the
dinar, and talk darkly of a return of the hyperinflation of 1993,
when prices rose by the hour and notes nominally worth billions of
dinars barely paid for a loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Pensioners, meanwhile, have been told they will receive coupons
for electricity for the next few months instead of cash. Like all
citizens, they have had a tax for reconstruction of the country
deducted from their monthly income. Throughout the summer,
pensioners held protests against Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, but most are preoccupied, like other Serbs, with their
own survival.
</P>
<P>
   With economic troubles looming, the country is holding its
breath. The whole of society seems to be suspended in a sort of
limbo, paralyzed by inertia, even fear.
</P>
<P>
   This has helped produce an uneasy undeclared truce on the
political scene. Opposition parties have taken a breather from
their summer demonstrations, apparently hoping to gather strength
ahead of a new round of rallies scheduled to start Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's government, after floating ideas of a shuffle or
even early elections, has gone quiet, as if waiting to see what
strength the opposition can muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is brave enough or strong enough to make a change,''
said Bratislav Grubacic, editor of the independent news agency VIP.
He was talking not only about the opposition but also about some
members of Milosevic's own Socialist Party and its coalition
partner, his wife's United Yugoslav Left party, who are rumored to
be disaffected but too nervous to act.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions among the democratic opposition, and specifically
the rivalry between Vuk Draskovic, leader of the largest opposition
party, the Serbian Renewal Movement, and Zoran Djindjic, leader of
the Democratic Party, are solidifying.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic will be at the forefront of a nationwide campaign of
protests to be organized this fall by the Alliance for Change
coalition. Draskovic will not attend the opening rally in Belgrade,
one of his advisers, Predrag Simic, said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although that announcement may yet be reversed _ Draskovic
announced dramatically two days ahead of a big Belgrade rally in
August that he would not take part, only to take the stage when the
night came _ Simic argued that to try to remove Milosevic from
power through street protests is naive. Yet the Serbian Renewal
Movement appears to have no other strategy. They want elections,
and since they hold only a minority of the seats in Parliament,
they would have to resort to public pressure to secure any early
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Simic welcomed a European Union plan approved earlier this week
to provide oil to towns and cities in Serbia that are run by
democrats who won power in the 1996 municipal elections. The
Union's scheme, called Energy for Democracy, is a good example of
how to apply international pressure on Milosevic, Simic said. ``The
E.U. sent the right message,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Simic said that the divisions in the opposition would do no harm
as long as the movements maintain a common goal. A future coalition
is possible, he said. Analysts see trouble ahead, though.
``Draskovic is waiting to see Djindjic fail,'' Grubacic said, so he
can step in and take up the mantle of undisputed leader of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the public will respond and turn out for more
demonstrations is not at all clear. Srecko Mihajlovic, an associate
of the Institute of Social Studies in Belgrade, has announced poll
results showing that most of the people living in Serbia want
change, Beta News agency reported this week. How far people will go
to bring about change is less sure.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, tired and worried about the winter, the last
thing they want is unrest. Many of them took to the streets every
night for three months in the winter of 1996-97 to persuade
Milosevic to install the democratic municipal governments that had
won the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he relented, and the opposition _ while functioning
in some cities, notably many of those worst damaged by NATO's bombs
this spring _ disintegrated, not least because of the feud between
Draskovic and Djindjic.
</P>
<P>
   Few Belgraders, at least for now, seem interested in tramping
the streets again in such numbers, for such opposition leaders.
``This is only a story in the media,'' said Ms. Petrovic, a
freelance journalist. ``Ordinary people are not talking about it.
They are concerned first about their children, then their jobs and
then prices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
