<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE17-COX     09-16 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fastest not always first
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Jarrett and Mark Martin are 1-2 in the Winston
Cup points standings, but they are tied for last in pole positions.
</P>
<P>
   Neither one of the top two drivers in NASCAR's top circuit has
won a pole through 25 races this season. Neither Jarrett nor Martin
appears concerned about the lack of No. 1 starts.
</P>
<P>
   They say the race for pole positions is overrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main focus is taking cars to the racetrack that we know
are going to race good on Sunday,'' Jarrett said. ``A lot of times,
you give up something in qualifying (for the race).''
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't seen a lot of pole-winners win races this year,''
he said. ``We're a little more in the racing mode rather than
(chasing after the) pole.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, pole-sitters have won only four races, with the
last being Jeff Gordon at Sears Point on June 27. Gordon leads the
Cup with seven poles and is tied with Jeff Burton for most
victories with five. However, Gordon registered only two of his
wins from the pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fastest car doesn't always win the race,'' Sterling Marlin
said. ``Once the race starts, the pole-winner isn't always the
fastest car, either. Winning a pole means for one lap and one
particular time of day you were the best thing out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton said, ``A lot of teams put an extra emphasis on
qualifying. You can usually tell who does because they qualify
pretty good, but they fade away once the race starts.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, starting a race first has had a minimal effect
on finishing a race first. Seven pole-sitters took the checkered
flag last year; but in each of the three previous seasons, 1995-97,
only four drivers won from the pole.
</P>
<P>
   At New Hampshire International Speedway, site of Sunday's
Dura-Lube/Kmart 300, earning the pole position has proved to be
almost meaningless in the final results. In nine Cup races at the
track, the No. 1 starter has been the first to cross the finish
line only once _ Gordon last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing about winning the pole is it's the first
thing you compete for,'' Steve Grissom said. ``If they threw
birdseed on the ground and told you the guy who picked up the most
pieces was the winner, every one of us would be on our hands and
knees, elbowing the other guy out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who has a 270-point advantage over Martin with nine
races left, has been close to winning the pole a couple of times.
He started in the No. 2 position at the California and Dover races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe for some sponsors, it's a big deal for your driver to
get into the Bud Shootout,'' the preseason exhibition race for
pole-winners only, Jarrett said. ``We're more thinking about races
and the Winston Cup championship. I think it depends on the team
and what they are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guys, of course, want to qualify well. But I don't know if
they have ever been mad that I didn't get a pole. We just always
want to start up as far as we can up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who has captured a pole every season for more than a
decade, expressed surprise when asked about his lack of No. 1
starts. He has started second or third in eight races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that we haven't won a pole yet this year,''
Martin said. ``If we don't win one, it will be the first time since
1988, but the year is not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've qualified well in nearly every race this year and
probably have a better starting average than last year, despite not
having won any poles. It's not awkward, we're still trying to do
it, and we still have (nine) chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
