<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-TRASHTALK17-COX     09-16 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TRASHTALK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols, Gators talking that talk
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Steve Spurrier originally planned to keep
his Gators' trash talk to a minimum before Saturday's game between
No. 4 Florida and No. 2 Tennessee. After last year's loss in
Knoxville, the head Gator figured it might be best.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee didn't play last week and used its free time to
demonstrate that it can talk smack with the best of them. Their
confidence bolstered by a 14-game winning streak, two SEC
championships in a row and last season's national championship, the
Volunteers aren't bashful anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this is Tennessee guard Cosey Coleman on Florida's
defense, which had to replace 10 starters: ``I don't think they'll
be as good as they were last year up front. Most of the guys that
are starting now were in the rotation last year, but they weren't
as good as the guys starting. So you're looking at the second
string.''
</P>
<P>
   And this from receiver Cedrick Wilson, who was asked about
playing at Florida's Swamp, where Tennessee has lost six
consecutive games and the Gators have won 29 in a row: ``Playing
Florida in the Swamp doesn't mean any more to me than playing
Kentucky in Lexington. It doesn't mean anything to me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   So Spurrier took the muzzle off. ``I just told (the Gators) to
try and temper what they said. I hope we don't say more than we can
back up,'' he said. ``I think both teams have learned over the
years that all of this doesn't amount to (anything). But I read in
the paper that we're favored to win by two points, so how are we
supposed to act?''
</P>
<P>
   It has become an all-time week for bulletin-board material at
both schools. And the comments illustrate better than anything how
the Florida-Tennessee rivalry quickly is closing on Alabama-Auburn
as the nastiest in college football.
</P>
<P>
   Given the green light, several Gators were more than willing to
sling trash back. The consensus: Tennessee beat Florida in overtime
last year primarily because the Gators committed five turnovers.
And the Vols think they've earned the right to talk?
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us one year, off our mistakes, and they're suddenly
the team on top of everything,'' running back Robert Gillespie
said. ``I don't know what they feel like they've done, but we just
have to go out and beat them and prove they came up lucky last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They won the national title last year, so I guess they have a
little rap right now,'' safety Marquand Manuel said. ``They can rap
as much as they want. But they have to fly down on Saturday and
prove their point. We're going to prove ours, too.''
</P>
<P>
   End Thaddeus Bullard said: ``They better come down here for a
60-minute fight, or they'll be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   These attitudes, however, are new. Starting in 1916, Tennessee
and Florida met 19 times before 1990. Tennessee's biggest rival was
Alabama. Florida's rivals were Florida State and Georgia. But the
Vols and Gators have met every year starting in since 1990, which
coincidentally is the year Spurrier became coach at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Since then:
</P>
<P>
   _After Tennessee trounced Spurrier's first Florida team 45-3,
Spurrier and Volunteers coach Johnny Majors almost came to blows at
a social function in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1991, Vicky Fulmer, wife of then-assistant Phillip Fulmer,
was abused physically as she walked to her seat in Gainesville. She
vowed never to return to Florida without an escort.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1997, Florida tackle Mo Collins said Tennessee quarterback
Peyton Manning was ``overrated,'' drawing the ire of Volunteers
everywhere. Florida won 33-20 after Tony George returned a Manning
interception 89 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   _Last year Florida players said they and their families were
roughed up in the aftermath of the Tennessee win.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line for the Gators: There is a reason they have won 29
straight in the Swamp. One win by Tennessee, they say, has not
turned this rivalry around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come in here, I expect the streak to get to 30,''
defensive end Alex Brown said. ``They don't have room to talk. We
slipped up last year. They won in overtime, and they won the
national championship with an undefeated year. Great. Do it again.
Beat us here and then you can get all the respect you want. We
don't lose here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
