<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler barely better, so Graziani expecting to start
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The strained right hamstring of Falcons quarterback
Chris Chandler barely improved Thursday, and it appears third-year
pro Tony Graziani will get his third career start Monday at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler aggravated the hamstring injury in a 17-14 loss to the
Vikings and hasn't practiced since. He jogged slowly Thursday, and
coach Dan Reeves said, ``I think it would take a miracle'' for the
12-year veteran to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can run for longer distances, but I still can't run very
fast,'' Chandler said. ``It's better than it was, and hopefully by
(today) I'll be able to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   That appears doubtful, like Chandler's official status, although
Reeves said he might wait until just before Monday's 9 p.m. game to
make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani's first two starts, also on the road, were last Nov. 29
at St. Louis, and as a rookie, Oct. 26, 1997, at Carolina.
Graziani, a seventh-round draft choice from Oregon in '97, was
replaced at halftime in both games. Atlanta beat the Rams last
year, and lost to the Panthers in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, Reeves and others refer to Graziani's increased
awareness, although it was hard to detect in the preseason when he
amassed a 53.9 passer rating in just two quarters. The left-handed
passer was slowed in the preseason after getting poked in the eye
in one game and spraining a knee in another.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he beat out Danny Kanell, who had a 44.1 rating and seven
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can get the job done with Tony,'' running back
Jamal Anderson said. ``He's more comfortable in the offense, and
we're more comfortable with him.'' ``Every kid's dream growing up
is to play on Monday Night Football,'' Graziani said. ``Last year,
I got a real nervous energy from everyone (before starting at St.
Louis), and this year everyone is real relaxed, happy I'm the
backup.'' After going 0-6 in '97 in games Chandler missed or left
with an injury, the team was 4-1 in games like that last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our preparation is that Chris is not going to be there,''
Reeves said, ``and if he is, that's a plus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
