<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ferraro has goal on ice
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ``Hockey Club of the South'' type of surroundings
Thursday served as a nice backdrop for Ray Ferraro's skate down
memory lane. Fifteen seasons, 1,020 games, 346 goals _ these eyes
have seen a few things that some of the younger ones at nearby
lockers never will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of two showers and two light bulbs at the Boston
Garden are long gone,'' the Thrashers center said after his first
skate in Philips Arena. ``Rats were everywhere, but they had to
live someplace, too. I wonder where they went when they knocked
that place down?''
</P>
<P>
   And The Aud in Buffalo. ``A dump,'' Ferraro said, as he runs
down the list of former hockey venues. ``It's a storage facility
now. That's what it should have been all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro would like to believe his new home is more than
temporary quarters. At 35, he is the Thrashers' oldest player, No.
1 center and most likely player to score 20 goals this season _
which means that the team is as desperate as he is eager to prove
that he belongs here.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the signs have been positive, except for the mandatory
ice bags after games. Ferraro still skates hard. He scored a goal
the other night in St. Louis. His surgically repaired knees are
fine, and he wishes everybody would stop asking and holding their
breath every times he falls or rams the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My health is not an issue,'' he said. ``I feel better than I
have in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   He will not try to convince you that he is as mobile as he was
at 20, when he skated into the Montreal Forum for the first time,
in his second pro game, an obscure former fifth-round draft pick of
the Hartford Whalers trying to prove his worth in historic
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched that place on Hockey Night in Canada (telecasts) as
a little kid,'' Ferraro said. ``I remember skating onto the ice _ I
was in awe. Stanley Cup banners were hanging from corner to corner.
That was a big night for me. We got clobbered, 10-5, but I got my
first goal and three assists.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about having a hand in four out of five Hartford
goals, Ferraro said, ``Yeah, but I think I had a hand in a few of
their 10, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had 11 seasons of 20 or more goals, three 30 or more, two
40 or more. But the numbers that follow him into this year are 19
and 42 _ his total goals and games missed because of injury,
respectively, in the past two seasons. He has had cartilage removed
from his left knee twice and his right knee once.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which was the bad knee, Ferraro smiled and said, ``I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said, ``I wear the brace on the left one, if that means
anything. That one's a little more challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenged. He had a challenge last year in Los Angeles, and
Ferraro didn't think he was up to it. He went into the season
believing it was his last. His knees ached and, in part because of
Kings coach Larry Robinson's conservative system, the sport ceased
being enjoyable. Ferraro scored two goals in the first half of the
season. But in the second half, his knees started feeling better,
frustrations melted away, and he scored 11 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out the rest of the year how much I still loved the
game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro doesn't have a negative word to say about Robinson, but
he said, ``I don't think I was put in a situation where I could
perform well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro hasn't saved a lot of memorabilia through the years. But
he did keep a few items from his 1,000th career game last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 136 guys have done it, so it must mean something,'' he
said. ``Hopefully, I'll be durable enough for a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
