<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves: Injured wrist has slowed Jordan's roll
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three nights ago, Brian Jordan drove in two runs in
one game, an event once so ordinary that he did it four times in
five days during his first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The moment described where the Braves' most productive hitter
started and the strange place he has landed now. If April
determined that Jordan indeed could replace Andres Galarraga as
Atlanta's cleanup hitter, September wonders how Jordan can continue
performing as half of himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' final drive, which begins tonight with a home
weekend series against Montreal, is crammed with uncertainties,
ranging from the onrushing New York Mets to the alignment of
manager Bobby Cox's October rotation. But in a larger way, with
club scoring having slipped to 16th in the major leagues at 5.2
runs a game, Jordan is the focal point.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether a team with championship aspirations can
get along with a cleanup hitter who, while coping with a serious
wrist problem, has become one of the least effective in the game.
The Braves might be better suited by change.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cox) doesn't do that, which is good,'' hitting coach Don
Baylor said. ``Without Brian Jordan for the first three-quarters of
the year picking up the slack in the four-spot ... Every time we
needed an RBI with two out, he got it. He's earned that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's season reads like one giant downward gradient. When
Montreal's Mike Thurman, who starts for the Expos tonight, struck
Jordan on the outside base of his right hand at Turner Field on
June 22, Jordan was averaging an RBI every 4.7 at-bats. Since Aug.
1, as the condition has worsened with the discovery of a bone spur,
that rate has dropped to one every 6.4 at-bats. Since receiving
three cortisone injections in both wrists Aug. 25, Jordan has
driven in a run every 11.2 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   His batting average, weighted by an 8-for-50 September, is down
to a season-low .285. His average with runners in scoring position,
which stood at .341 six weeks ago, has been .250 (10-for-40) since.
He hasn't hit a home run in 92 at-bats, dating back to Aug. 16. He
admits that he is scared to swing, unable to overcome the pain that
has converted him into a singles hitter, an awful decline for a
player highly regarded for handling the fastball.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more despondent about the situation than Jordan, who
has fought injury most of his career. Playing his first full season
without incident in 1998, he posted career highs in eight offensive
categories and was well on his way to outperforming himself this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would accept moving out of the clean-up slot, he
replied, ``If he wants to put someone else in there, it makes no
difference to me. As long as I'm in the lineup, I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
