   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ENCRYPT &LR;  _ Silicon Valley scored another big win in Washington
yesterday, as the Clinton administration, reversing a decades-old
policy, said it will allow U.S. firms to export powerful computer
technology that scrambles data to keep it private. By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUC  &LR; _ Consumers fed up with changing area codes every few
months and angered at the prospect of having to dial 11 digits to
make a local call scored a victory yesterday when California
regulators scrapped the state's existing overlay and set the stage
for the elimination of overlays and splits across the state. A
decision late Wednesday by the Federal Communications Commission
that gives California more leeway in how it assigns area codes
prompted the state Public Utilities Commission to end the 310 area
code overlay and begin a process that will halt the seemingly
endless stream of area code changes in California. The ruling is
good news for Bay Area residents, who are facing at least five
overlays over the next few years. While yesterday's decision
doesn't directly impact any area code overlay other than the one in
310, it sets forth a process that will help stop the depletion of
available area codes. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
