<P>
   &UR; WINE  &LR; _ If you had to but a label on this year's wine grape
harvest, a good choice might be dichotomy. Cabernet Sauvignon and
other favored grapes in coastal counties remain in fairly tight
supply and their prices remain firm as demand stays strong for
pricey premium wines. On the other hand, a glut of wine grapes
exists in the southern portion of California's Central Valley.
There, prices have dropped up to 45 percent from last year. As a
result, consumers should see some big bargains in the
$3-to-$7-per-bottle category. By Peter Sinton
