 _ SF CHRON  
 Encryption Exports OKd by White House
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Henry Norr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Silicon Valley scored another big win in Washington yesterday, as
the Clinton administration, reversing a decades-old policy, said it
will allow U.S. firms to export powerful computer technology that
scrambles data to keep it private.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it will draft new regulations permitting
high-tech companies to sell even their most powerful encryption
technologies ``in retail form'' to any overseas customers,
including most governments.
</P>
<P>
   The decision shows politicians' increasing desire to court
Silicon Valley, even over the objections of law enforcement and
national security experts, who have long argued that strong
encryption makes it harder for them to fight terrorists and other
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge,'' said Rep. Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., who along with
Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-San Jose, whose district includes &LR;  Silicon
Valley,  &LR; has been championing legislation to eliminate the
encryption export controls.
</P>
<P>
   Technology-industry officials, who have fought for years for
liberalization of encryption exports, said the administration's
move met most of their demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they actually implement everything they've announced, then
this is a major breakthrough,'' said Jim cq &LR; Bidzos, vice chairman
of RSA Security, a leading vendor of security and encryption
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased _ we got 80 percent of what we wanted,''
said Roszel cq &LR; Thomsen, counsel for the Alliance for Network
Security, a year-old lobbying group that includes such high-tech
heavyweights as 3Com, Cisco, Hewlett-Packard, Intel, Lucent,
Microsoft, Network Associates, Nortel Networks, Novell and Sun
Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Technology industry officials warned, however, that many
critical details remain to be ironed out. One of the key issues,
they said, will be the definition of retail sales, since more
restrictions will remain for products the government will classify
as nonretail. Yesterday's announcements also appeared to focus
exclusively on finished goods, leaving tech officials wondering
about the status of component products such as encryption chips and
software tool kits.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. vendors will have to submit products for a one-time
government review, but they will not have to go through the complex
licensing process under which such sales were often prohibited in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   The only countries where exports of U.S. encryption products are
still banned are those the government considers terrorist nations:
Iran, Iraq, Libya, Syria, Sudan, North Korea and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates, who have generally joined with the high-tech
industry to demand freer exports of data-scrambling products,
welcomed the new announcements, but expressed more skepticism about
the detailed regulations, which are due December 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our filing cabinets are littered with White House press
releases claiming major policy changes in the past, and ultimately
they turned out not to be,'' said Alan Davidson, an attorney at the
Center for Democracy and Technologies, a privacy and civil
liberties advocacy group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He added, though, ``There's a level of specificity here that
will make it very difficult for them to back away.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Worries Over Secret Codes
</P>
<P>
   Davidson and other civil libertarians said they are especially
concerned about other initiatives the White House announced
yesterday, including legislation that might make it easier under
some circumstances for law-enforcement officials to obtain ``keys''
_ secret codes _ that would enable them to read data U.S. citizens
have tried to secure by encryption.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno also said the government will fund a
new ``technical support center'' at the FBI to help law-enforcement
authorities respond to the increased use of encryption by
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Washington observers cited a number of factors coming together
to explain why the White House has now  &LR; changed its tune on
encryption exports.
</P>
<P>
   One, of course, is the upcoming election, for which both parties
are courting Silicon Valley donations and support from &LR;  Silicon
Valley &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the U.S. House  &LR; House of Representatives is moving
toward consideration of legislation that would have &LR;   &LR; completely
eliminated &LR;  export controls on encryption products. More than half
the members of the House have signed on as co-sponsors of the bill,
known as the Security and Freedom through Encryption (SAFE) Act,
written by Virginia's Goodlatte.
</P>
<P>
   Still another factor, observers said, was a growing move to ease
restrictions on export of similar products from European countries.
Just this month, Germany announced substantial liberalization of
its policies, and several other countries, as well as the European
Union as a whole, have been taking steps in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. vendors have long argued that the only real effect of the
country's restrictive policies was to keep them out of foreign
markets, without preventing users abroad from obtaining encryption
products elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties are desperate to woo Silicon Valley,'' said RSA
Security's Bidzos. ``This is where the growth in the economy is,
this is where the money is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidzos, for example, said foreign competitors have been
increasingly ``winning business we can't even go after because our
hands are tied behind our backs by our very own government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Software and Information Industry Association, another
high-tech trade group, projects that global sales of encryption
products could reach $20 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
