r f BC-MYSIMON-MYSIMON_SFCHR     09-16 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSIMON-MYSIMON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MySimon.com Says Startup Stole Ideas
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By David Lazarus &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Santa Clara's MySimon.com, which offers an online price-comparison
service, has filed a complaint in U.S. District Court against a
startup firm in Texas for allegedly pilfering both its technology
and content.
</P>
<P>
   Priceman.com, based in Houston, is nothing more than a copy of
MySimon that uses MySimon's own search engine for its price
listings, the complaint charges.
</P>
<P>
   It also alleges that text on Priceman's site duplicated that of
MySimon's site.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Priceman posted a message to visitors yesterday
explaining that it is a ``meta-search'' engine that scours listings
on other sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Priceman.com is the currently ... the  &LR; first and only site to
do a meta search on Price Engines (or as some call them `Shopping
Comparison engines'),'' the message states. ``We pass on your
search string to numerous other Price Engines, get the product
pricing information from them, compile all this information, and
present it to the user.''
</P>
<P>
   The message says Priceman is trying to address MySimon's
complaint, but ``we believe that our meta-search capabilities do
not violate any existing infringement laws and have therefore not
done anything wrong since there are numerous meta-search engines on
the market that do the same thing we do.''
</P>
<P>
   It also chides MySimon for pursuing legal action instead of
trying to ``settle their problem in an amicable fashion.'' It
accuses the larger firm of trying to drive it out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, countered Josh Goldman, CEO of MySimon. ``We would have
been happy to discuss it with them if they wanted to pursue a
business relationship,'' he said. ``But they just repurposed our
content for their site.''
</P>
<P>
   The most ``flagrant'' example, Goldman said, was Priceman
allegedly taking MySimon's extensive online shopping guide and
substituting all references to ``MySimon'' with ``Priceman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There it was, page for page, word for word,'' he said. ``The
smoking gun was a page where they forgot to change `MySimon' to
`Priceman.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Priceman shut down its service after the complaint was
filed Wednesday, Goldman said his company's lawyers have the
supposedly incriminating evidence archived for possible legal use.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that MySimon maintains relationships with about a dozen
other price-comparison services and said he would have been open to
a similar arrangement with Priceman.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they clearly took our design and original content without
crediting us,'' he said. ``That's not the proper way to do a
meta-search engine.''
</P>
<P>
   James Paul, a Priceman spokesman, said MySimon simply is
engaging in hardball tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously see us as some kind of threat,'' he said.
``It's obviously a cheap way for them to get publicity for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Priceman, which bills itself as ``Earth's biggest shopping
comparison engine,'' was launched in December. Its eight employees
all have day jobs elsewhere, and to date, the free service has run
no advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no revenues at all,'' Paul said. ``We don't have any
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But they do have pluck. Priceman tried last week to auction off
nearly half its equity on eBay for at least $10 million. EBay,
questioning the legality of auctioning stocks online, pulled the
plug on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Paul said it's uncertain when, or if, Priceman will resume
operations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
