<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SHOOTING-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING TO THE FLAGPOLE, THIS TIME TO MOURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TEXAS-SHOOTING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON with GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Plenty of teen-agers would rather watch
television or haunt the malls. But for young people like Justin
Laird and Kristi Beckel, Wednesday nights were meant for hanging
out at the Wedgwood Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   And this Wednesday night was meant for celebration _ rocking and
rolling and praying. Instead, there were screams.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Beckel, 14, was one of the seven people shot to death
inside the red brick church on Whitman Street on Wednesday. Laird,
a 16-year-old football player, was also shot. He lay paralyzed in a
Fort Worth hospital Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wednesday nights are special to a lot of kids'' said Adrienne
Moore, 20, who works at a Christian bookstore here. ``A lot of
teen-agers don't even belong to a church because their parents
don't go. So the Wednesday night services are all they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for being hipper and looser than the usual Sunday worship
style, the Wednesday youth services are casual, sometimes
boisterous.
</P>
<P>
   A Christian rock band, The Forty Days, was performing at
Wedgwood on Wednesday night. They were playing a song called
``Alle, Allelulia,'' when the first shots rang out.
</P>
<P>
   The day had started with prayer for many students here and
around the nation. Students pray and hold hands as they encircle
flag poles at their schools in what has come to be known as ``See
You at the Pole Day.'' It is a way to embolden evangelical students
who might otherwise feel uneasy about praying in public.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Texas, a place where the Bible finds its way into
everyday talk, being seen as religious and a straight-arrow can be
difficult for a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the mumbled profanities,'' Miss Moore said. ``People
call you a Jesus freak.''
</P>
<P>
   But for young people like Stefanie Robertson, 14, who belongs to
Wedgwood Baptist, the support of friends make any snickers seem
silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is really a kind of a cool place when all the kids
are there on Wednesday nights,'' Ms. Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Fort Worth were given over to mourning Thursday.
``The teachers didn't even ask us to try to do any work,'' said
Nycole Dutton, 13, who knew some of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``You looked around at school,'' Miss Dutton said, ``and all you
saw was people crying.''
</P>
<P>
   At North Crowley High School, a football player named Brett
Parker led a huge clump of students out to the flagpole Thursday
morning where they prayed for a schoolmate, Cassandra Griffin, who
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   A youth minister, Johnny Derouen, spent the day talking to
grieving students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them what they told themselves, that you can't stop it
from happening but you can prepare for it,'' he said. ``We talked
about how if there are other students in our school who are lonely,
who are hurting, if we were more kind to them, it might stop them
from taking out their feelings on us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a sad day at Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary, where two of its students, Susan Jones, 23, and Shawn
Brown, 23, were remembered. Miss Jones, who was called Kim and who
was working with the children at the Baptist church, was one of
those who was shot to death. Brown, who also enjoyed working with
children, was also killed.
</P>
<P>
   Another of those slain was Sydney Browning, 36, a Southwestern
seminary graduate who was a teacher who worked with troubled
teen-agers. She served as children's choir director at Wedgwood
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Meredith, the daughter of the Rev. Al Meredith, said she
considered Ms. Browning a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Laird, who celebrated his 16th birthday Wednesday, had
taken a driving test in his father's Chevrolet Blazer. That night
he lay on the floor bleeding, as his father, John Laird, pleaded
with his son to get up and flee the gunman, said Ben Davis, the
athletic director at Brewer High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father told me that when he saw him down on the floor,
bleeding, he said, `We've got to get out of here,' but Justin said
he couldn't move,'' Davis said. ``His dad dragged him out of there.
You'd think that if you sent your kid to church or school, he's in
good hands, he's safe. Its a tremendous shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of the gunman's victims, Joseph Ennis, was recalled
Thursday as a gregarious, upbeat, 14-year-old who spent every
moment he could on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Beckel, was a ``very sweet girl'' who liked to play
volleyball, said her former Sunday school teacher, Missy McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Another victim was Justin Ray, 17, who was known for his
cheerfulness and his kind manner. ``You couldn't not like him,''
Miss Dutton said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman, Larry Gene Ashbrook, 47, remained a mystery to the
people of Fort Worth. But some people said they included him in
their prayers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``God died for the man who pulled the trigger, too,'' said Dan
Gill, the manager of a Christian bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Posted on the Baptist church's web page Thursday were messages
of grief. ``Father, give us peace, even when we don't understand,''
one read in part.
</P>
<P>
   At the three Texas high schools that victims had attended,
special rooms were set aside for grieving students. And school
administrators said there was special concern for the trauma of the
dozens of students who had witnessed the shootings at the church,
and the hundreds more that were friends with the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some moms who said they wanted to take their children
out early and of course we said yes,'' said David Walker, principal
of North Crowley High School. The only positive is this is bringing
the kids closer together. You see them pulling together. But I
don't know how anyone makes sense of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
