<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIELD-FIELD </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Californians Pleased by Economy, Poll Finds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Californians are more upbeat about the state's economy than they
have been at any time in the past two decades, a new opinion poll
shows.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual survey on the state's ``Economic Well-Being,'' the
Field Institute of San Francisco found that 70 percent of
Californians think the economy is going through `'good times.''
</P>
<P>
   That is nine percentage points higher than a year ago, and by
far the strongest positive response since Field began asking the
question in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1994, with the state still mired in a long
recession, only 4 percent of the Field Poll respondents considered
the economy ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very positive report card for the economy,'' said
Mark DiCamillo, director of the Field Institute. ``It's also good
news for the economy, because these are consumers, and consumer
dollars move the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, while the bulk of the respondents in this year's poll
were upbeat about the present, they weren't necessarily optimistic
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Field found that only 27 percent of Californians expect the
economy to ``get better'' during the next 12 months. That is down
from 34 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 52 percent said they expect `'periods of serious
economic downturn'' during the next five years. Last year, only 41
percent felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Gibson, chief economist with the state Department of
Finance, said reduced optimism is natural ``when things are going
well.'' He noted that in a strong economy people get nervous and
tend to wonder ``how long can this last?''
</P>
<P>
   Field conducted the poll from August 16 through 22, telephoning
1,010 adult Californians, including 230 from the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Fifty-two percent of those polled felt that their ``personal
financial well-being'' _ as distinguished from the condition of the
economy as a whole _ was better than it was a year ago. In the
previous poll, 55 percent felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect, people with relatively high household
incomes seemed the most satisfied with their economic status.
Sixty-eight percent of those with incomes of $80,000 or higher said
they were better off than a year ago, while just 36 percent with
incomes of less than $20,000 said they were better off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Forty-four percent of the respondents said they expect to be
better off next year. That is down from 49 percent in the previous
survey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Twenty-eight percent think the stock market will move higher
next year, while 18 percent expect it to go lower and 44 percent
think it will remain about the same. Ten percent had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous survey, 32 percent of the respondents expected
the market to rise, 18 percent expected a downturn, 39 expected
essentially no change and 11 percent had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The opinions of people from the Bay Area were generally in line
with those expressed by people living elsewhere in the state, said
Mark DiCamillo, director of the Field Institute.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bay Area residents tended to be more satisfied with
their personal economic status. Fifty-six percent said they were
better off than they were a year ago _ four percentage points
higher than the response for all California residents.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, only 39 percent of Bay Area residents thought
they would be better off a year from now _ five percentage points
less than for the state as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might interpret that as the Bay Area being a little ahead
of the curve,'' DiCamillo said. ``The Bay Area has been leading the
state's economic recovery, while Los Angeles has been trailing.
Now, more residents of L.A. are expecting better things, because
they are just beginning to feel the change for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the people polled this year, 57 percent said they were
homeowners, while 43 percent were renters.
</P>
<P>
   Field found that slightly less than half the renters had
considered buying homes during the past year. Of those who
considered buying, 3 out of 5 cited high prices as the reason for
not doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bay Area residents, 48 percent said they were renters.
Somewhat less than half considered buying homes during the past
year, and of that group, nearly two-thirds cited price as the
reason for backing down.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters also posed a couple of questions that ranged
beyond economic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The respondents were asked to give their opinions about the
``overall direction'' in which California and the United States are
heading.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-two percent thought California was heading in the
`'right'' direction, compared with 53 percent a year earlier.
Fifty-three percent felt the United States was heading in the right
direction _ down from 67 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sensitive measure,'' DiCamillo said. ``It can
help in predicting elections, because it indicates whether there is
a mood for political change or for staying the course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
