r f BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      09-16 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Rulings May Slow Spiraling Growth of Area Codes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two key rulings by government agencies this week could pull the
plug on four new area codes planned for the Bay Area that would
require callers to dial 11-digits, even when phoning their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The first ruling came Wednesday night, when the Federal
Communications Commission gave California permission Wednesday &LR; 
night &LR;  to hand out new phone numbers in blocks of 1,000 instead of
10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The current system _ which gives phone companies numbers in
blocks of 10,000, no matter how many customers they have _ has
rapidly depleted the pool of available phone numbers and has
contributed to the spiraling need for more area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the FCC's decision, which is expected to free up
additional telephone numbers, the state Public Utilities Commission
yesterday rescinded a controversial ``overlay'' plan for the 310
area code in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of dividing a region geographically and giving customers
in one half a new area code, an overlay lets existing customers
keep their area code and assigns a new area code to new phone
lines. The downside is that everyone in the overlay area must dial
11 digits _ 1 plus the area code plus the phone number _ on every
call, even when making calls to their own area code.
</P>
<P>
   Although the PUC's 3-to-2 ruling applied only to the 310 area
code, it could squelch plans for overlays in at least four area
codes in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this is going to mean we do not have to resort to
overlays anyplace in the state,'' said Commissioner Joel Hyatt, who
recommended yesterday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also told California regulators that it could force
phone companies such as Pacific Bell to disclose how many phone
numbers are actually in use and require them to release all unused
numbers, so they could be reassigned to other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 180 million numbers assigned to California phone
companies, the PUC estimates that only 35 million are actually in
use.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell says that 86 percent of the numbers it has been
assigned are in use.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are about 150 phone companies in the state, and
many of them have few customers but at least 10,000 numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Freeing up unused numbers will prolong the life of each area
code, Hyatt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC order is going to make it considerably easier for us
to do something serious about trying to slow down the rate at which
area codes are created in California,'' said Helen Mickiewicz, an
attorney with the PUC. ``And that means in turn we can reduce the
enormous amount of hardship the public has had to endure as we keep
opening up new area codes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, the 415, 510, 650 and 408 area codes are
scheduled to get overlays in the next two years. The PUC decision
will require phone companies to prove that the number supply in
those area codes is actually exhausted. If they cannot, the PUC
could issue a new order stopping the overlays.
</P>
<P>
   The first Bay Area overlay is scheduled to go into effect in the
408 region on October 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened in the 310 overlay would certainly raise
questions about other overlays that the commission has ordered,''
said Natalie Billingsley, a telecommunications expert with the PUC.
``As for 408, it would not be unreasonable for the commission to
reassess the decision it's already made in light of the extended
authority the FCC granted to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the PUC on Wednesday, Gov. Gray Davis urged
regulators to halt plans for overlays in 310 and 408.
</P>
<P>
   The 310 region of West Los Angeles was the first in the state to
get 11-digit dialing, and it has not gone smoothly. Customers had
trouble getting through to some numbers, some security systems do
not work with the overlay and people have been confused by the
change.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have flooded the PUC with complaints, and several
state legislators proposed a bill to end 11-digit dialing.
Customers in 310 began dialing 11 digits in April, and a new area
code, 424, was supposed to go into effect in July. However, the PUC
temporarily suspended implementation of 424.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the commissioners said yesterday that the overlay is
creating a hardship for customers and should be scrapped. Only one
other major city, Houston, has rescinded an overlay after it took
effect.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes will not happen quickly. The 310 area should
revert back to seven-digit dialing in about 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, the PUC will collect data from phone
companies to determine how many numbers are available in existing
area codes and will solicit bids from companies that want to assign
phone numbers in blocks of 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some months,'' Mickiewicz said. ``It
depends on a number of factors, including how cooperative the
(telecommunications) industry is. If the industry decides to fight
us at every turn, it's going to slow things down a lot. Hopefully,
we can get cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   John Britton, a spokesman for Pacific Bell, said the company is
willing to work with the PUC and to provide the data it requested.
PUC President Richard Bilas said he has been told by others in the
industry that they plan to cooperate as well.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners Bilas, Hyatt and Carl Wood voted for the plan to
rescind the overlay, while Josiah Neeper and Henry Duque voted
against the plan. Duque, who plans to write a dissenting opinion,
said he wanted more time to study the FCC decision before halting
the overlay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
