<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorneys fail in bid to have judge removed from role in
Davidian lawsuit
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon and Mark England
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Attorneys for some relatives of Branch Davidians
killed in the fire at Mount Carmel have failed in a second attempt
to have U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. removed from
presiding over their civil lawsuit against the government.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans rejected a
petition filed by attorneys for David Koresh's grandmother to have
Smith removed from the case and from attorneys for 44 plaintiffs
who were thrown out of the case by a July 1 ruling by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appellate court also denied a request from the
ousted plaintiffs to be reinstated in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The petition for writ of mandamus, which asked the higher court
to remove Smith from the case, claimed that because Smith had not
issued a ruling on the plaintiffs' request to postpone the trial,
which was scheduled at that time for Oct. 18, it showed he was
biased against the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ruled Wednesday that the trial will be postponed to
accommodate the transfer of evidence from governmental entities to
the clerk of his court. He did not set another trial date.
</P>
<P>
   A motion to have Smith recused that was filed by all plaintiffs
in the massive wrongful-death lawsuit two years ago also was
rejected. Not all plaintiffs' attorneys joined in the most recent
motion, which was filed two weeks ago with the 5th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the judge cannot sit as a fair and impartial
juror in the factual part of the wrongful-death case,'' said
Houston attorney Jim Brannon, who represents Jean Holub, Koresh's
grandmother. ``He has already made up his mind on key issues and I
think this ruling reflects that. With all the stuff that is coming
out now, we believe he made up his mind on tainted evidence. The
FBI evidence is just wholly not credible.''
</P>
<P>
   New York attorney Ramsey Clark, who asked that his clients be
restored as plaintiffs in the case, did not return phone messages
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit ruling was filed on Sept. 10, but a copy of the
ruling was not filed in Smith's court in Waco until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Mike Caddell, who represents about 90 percent
of the plaintiffs remaining in the lawsuit, said he declined to
join Brannon and Clark in seeking Smith's removal again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel just the opposite to some extent,'' Caddell said. ``I
think what Judge Smith has done over the last few months is
demonstrate his desire to be fair to both sides in the civil trial,
his desire to have the evidence made available and his desire to
get at the truth about what happened at Mount Carmel six years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he had concerns about the judge presiding over the
civil case because Smith was judge at the 1994 criminal trial of 11
Branch Davidians charged with killing four Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms agents during a gunfight Feb. 28, 1993, when
agents arrived to arrest Koresh on weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult for him or anyone to divorce what was
learned and what happened in the criminal trial from what the
evidence will be in the civil case,'' Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   In his July 1 ruling, Smith granted a majority of the
government's motions to dismiss elements of the lawsuit and a
number of plaintiffs. However, he said the issues of whether the
ATF used excessive force during the raid that started the 51-day
siege at Mount Carmel and whether the FBI used excessive force
during the tear gas assault that ended it must be decided at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Smith dismissed all but one of the individual defendants,
including U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and former Texas Gov.
Ann Richards. FBI assistant special agent in charge Lon T. Horiuchi
remains as the lone individual defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Smith based his ruling on Horiuchi on the statements of an FBI
agent who said he heard gunshots coming from a sniper position
manned by Horiuchi on the day of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
