<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WINE-WINE_SFCHRON &LR;      09-16 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-WINE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wine Grape Harvest Has Distinct Dichotomy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
If you had to but a label on this year's wine grape harvest, a good
choice might be dichotomy.
</P>
<P>
   Cabernet Sauvignon and other favored grapes in coastal counties
remain in fairly tight supply and their prices remain firm as
demand stays strong for pricey premium wines.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a glut of wine grapes exists in the southern
portion of California's Central Valley. There, prices have dropped
up to 45 percent from last year. As a result, consumers should see
some big bargains in the $3-to-$7-per-bottle category.
</P>
<P>
   That was the assessment of grape growers and winery owners who
attended the annual Wine Industry Symposium at the Silverado Resort
in Napa yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   After an unseasonally cool summer, the wine grape harvest began
in late August, about the same as last year. And like the 1998
crop, which was hurt by spring rains, one would expect overall
tonnage to fall below the record 2.9 million tons harvested in
1997. But it actually will be up because of new plantings.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, about 40,000 acres of recently planted vineyards in
California start bearing fruit. That's close to 10 percent of the
state's 385,000 acres of land devoted to grape production.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is a glut of grapes in the Central Valley,
especially from Madera County south, because many farmers are
switching to high-end grapes from other crops such as cotton and
table grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters even worse, each acre of hot Central Valley
vineyard land might produce two to three times the 5 tons produced
on one acre along the North Coast.
</P>
<P>
   New watered-down wine products also are contributing to the
Central Valley's wine woes, according to Allied Grape Growers
President Barry Bedwell and others.
</P>
<P>
   Canandaigua, a wine producer, pioneered the 5-liter bag-in-box
Chardonnay, Merlot and other wines ``with natural flavors'' and
E.&AMP;J. Gallo and the Wine Group followed suit. The actual percentage
of wine in these products is not disclosed, but Bedwell said it
ranges from 65 percent to less than 10 percent. Both of these
products could be drawing consumers away from products made
entirely from grapes.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of flavored wine coolers in 750-milliliter
bottles with names such as Blackberry Merlot, Strawberry Zinfandel
and Wild Vines also could be hurting wine sales.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all this, there is a surplus of wines _ from Australia
to Chile to Southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of all these factors, grape prices in the lower
Central Valley have been crushed. Cabernet Sauvignon, which sold
for $650 to $1,000 a ton a year ago, now fetches $400 to $600.
Chardonnay that went for $500 to $800 a ton is down to $350 to
$500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that big producers like Gallo and Canandaigua
have been cutting the prices they pay for grapes by about 30
percent,'' said David Freed, Chairman of UCC Group, which owns both
coastal and Central Valley vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   When farmers ask him about what variety to plant, Allied Grape
Growers' Bedwell said he is starting to respond, ``Pumpkins.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulk Wine broker Joe Ciatti labeled the Central Valley market
``depressed'' but called Napa, Sonoma and other coastal counties
``a different world.'' While overall California wine shipments were
flat through the first six months of this year compared to the same
period last year, sales of premium wines were up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As an indication of higher demand for greater grapes, Cabernet
Sauvignon grapes from Napa are now fetching about $2,450 a ton
compared with $2,200 a year ago. But not all prices are up.
Chardonnay has slipped from around $1,850 a ton to about $1,650.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who like cheaper wines should benefit from the current
market conditions. ``We haven't seen a decline in prices from
coastal producers,'' said wine industry consultant Eileen
Fredrikson of Gomberg Fredrikson &AMP; Associates. ``But there are some
wonderful buys in the $3-to-$7 wine category. Some prices have come
down about 15 percent in the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, the wine industry, which is facing a wine
glut, is anxious to get Americans to change their wine perceptions
and drinking habits.
</P>
<P>
   The average American adult drinks 2.38 gallons of wine a year,
which is up from 1.96 gallons in 1991 but down from 2.58 gallons
way back in 1982. In France and Italy, adults drink about eight
times as much wine. Moreover, only a sliver of the U.S. population
drinks wine. According to industry data, 11 percent of American
adults drink 88 percent of the wine, and 18 percent consume the
other 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In recent test marketing in Albany, N.Y., and Austin, Texas, the
Wine Market Council spent $1.2 million on ads to see if Americans
could be persuaded to abandon the generally held belief that wine
is for special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Council President John Gillespie said that the ``Wine. What are
you saving it for?'' campaign helped boost wine sales in those two
markets by about 2.3 percent. That may not sound like a lot, but it
matches the total growth in U.S. wine consumption last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Market Council hopes to spend about $4 million on a
national wine promotion next year. But some critics question how
effective such a campaign might be.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing an analogy to the toothpaste market, Stimson Lane
Vineyards &AMP; Estates President Allen Shoup said, ``You might be able
to get people to shift from Crest to Colgate (with advertising),
but I'm not sure you'll get them to brush their teeth more often.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
