<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RUSSIA-BOMBS-TERROR-N     09-16 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBS-TERROR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 RUSSIA'S TRAGIC LACK of LEADERSHIP ONLY ADDS TO THE PANIC  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By PAVEL PALAZCHENKO  
 c.1999 Metro International, Helsinki  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Almost as tragic as the nearly 280 deaths in five bombings in
Russia in less than three weeks is the mixture of fear,
defenselessness, frustration and cynicism with which most Russians
have reacted to them.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin has said all the right words. It is
certainly true, as he said after the second blast in Moscow, that
`` this enemy does not have a conscience, shows no sorrow and is
without honor. It has no face ... no nationality or belief. ...
Federal and regional bodies should work (to capture the
perpetrators) as a united body.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also quite true that, as he said, citizens must stay calm;
law enforcement should prevail.
</P>
<P>
   But why is it that so many people are ready to believe that the
highest Russian authorities had a hand in, or at least may benefit
from, the explosions?
</P>
<P>
   Wild accusations and conspiracy theories that appeal to the
man-in-the-street are being uttered all over the country _ that the
West is somehow to blame, that all people from the Caucuses are
suspect and should be deported from Moscow, that politicians are
behind the terror so elections can be put off, that Moscow should
bomb Chechnya! Now these absurdities are also being repeated by
some members of the Russian parliament. Other politicians and some
journalists are playing the blame game too.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly the wrong way to react to a campaign of terror.
The fear felt today by many Russians, in Moscow and in the
heartland, is tragically being intensified by the lack of
leadership. Frustration is almost a permanent state of mind for
many Russians, but popular cynicism toward the entire political
establishment is seeping into the general panic at the horrible
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Is anyone on the Russian political scene capable of instilling
faith and providing the powerful leadership so desperately needed
now?
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Luzhkov, the mayor of Moscow, was the first to call the
explosions a terrorist act and to point to the ``Chechen
connection.'' Leaders of the Islamic insurgency in Chechnya, who
weeks ago crossed into the southern province of Dagestan to wage
war, were exacting revenge, he said. But was it a good idea to do
so while police and Federal Security Service experts and
investigators were still probing the evidence?
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov's position is ambiguous. He has called the terrorists
``beasts'' and said they all ``need to be shot.'' He has been
criticized for statements that smack of racial intolerance, while
others are accusing him of allowing ``men from the Caucasus'' _
i.e., gangsters _ to control businesses in Moscow. Such accusations
turn the misgivings back on him.
</P>
<P>
   How about the president? Frankly, few people expect that Yeltsin
can provide the badly needed leadership. Over the past few years he
has failed the test on practically all the issues now challenging
Russia. His self-serving, abrupt game of reshuffling prime
ministers and Cabinet members has given Russia the heightened look
of an unpredictable and vulnerable place.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Lebed? This former paratroop general, who became
governor of the Siberian region of Krasnoyarsk, has a reputation
for being a strong law-and-order man. Yet he was sinking into
oblivion. Now, in an atmosphere of deepening crisis, Lebed's name
has, not surprisingly, come up again. So far, his reaction has
amounted to cryptic remarks and gestures that are at best confusing
and could well seal his political decline.
</P>
<P>
   Two former prime ministers _ Victor Chernomyrdin and Sergei
Stepashin _ have said little, and no wonder. Both were involved in
Yeltsin's disastrous military campaign in Chechnya in 1995-1996,
which helped to fuel the rise of militant Islamicism there _
regardless what doubts about the war they may have had at the time.
For them, this whole issue is a political minefield.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Putin? The present prime minister and Yeltsin's
anointed successor _ made the mistake of leaving the country after
the first explosion to go to a conference of Asian-Pacific leaders
in New Zealand. Returning hastily to Moscow after the second blast,
he railed at the ``rabid animals'' who perpetrated the destruction.
Then Putin proposed a serious of ``tough steps'' to the State Duma,
but actually these fail to constitute much of a coherent program of
action.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Yevgeni Primakov. The former prime minister, who may
run for the presidency in July 2000, is the most popular and
respected politician in Russia today. But his legendary caution may
have prevented him from making the kind of statement that would be
expected of a national leader in a situation like this.
</P>
<P>
   He has stated the obvious _ that imposing a state of emergency
to deal with the terrorism is the wrong path. But if Primakov is to
retain his standing _ not just ahead of the pack but above it
intellectually and politically _ he should speak out soon.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Russia's political class comes up with a proper reaction
to the new terrorist challenge, the cynical, embittered populace
could surprise them _ and all of us _ in December by voting for
those who now stand on the margins of Russian politics. The
radical, lunatic fringe is always there, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pavel Palazchenko is the author of ``My Years With Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze: The Memoir of a Soviet Interpreter'' (1997). He
teaches Russian language and contemporary politics at Colgate
University; he has also taught at Moscow Linguistic University.
From 1980 to 1991 he served in the Russian Foreign Ministry, before
which he was an interpreter with the United Nations in New York.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------- &QC;
</P>
