<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-CANCER-FOLKMAN-2T     09-16 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-FOLKMAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GAINS CITED IN CANCER THERAPY, BUT SOME RESEARCHERS HAVE
QUESTIONS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill.)  (mk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Judah Folkman, the Harvard researcher who has pioneered the
idea of starving tumors with factors that cut off their blood
supply, will announce Friday that he has discovered a third such
agent. But the report comes at a time when the first two factors he
identified, known as angiostatin and endostatin, have encountered
setbacks and prominent scientists have begun to criticize publicly
the quality of the work done in his laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the National Cancer Institute, which set out
independently to reproduce Folkman's work on endostatin, said in an
interview this week that the agency was making no new efforts to do
so. Its scientists have replicated Folkman's results while working
in his laboratory, but have failed to get the same results in their
own. Folkman, who works at Children's Hospital in Boston and at
Harvard Medical School, says the reason is that the endostatin
samples he sent were damaged by the dry ice in which they were
packed.
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, a scientist who worked at Bristol Myers Squibb
to bring angiostatin to market, provided new details about the
extensive efforts the company made to validate Folkman's results
and the scientific roadblocks that led them to drop the project.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior critic suggested that the substances isolated in
Folkman's laboratory could be artifacts resulting from erroneous
laboratory procedure and not true tumor-starving factors. He also
criticized the National Cancer Institute for its plan to test
endostatin in patients without first obtaining credible evidence of
its efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   These may well be minor glitches in the still promising field of
angiogenesis, the name for the body's process of generating small
blood vessels. Tumors must induce the body to form a blood supply
to them. Through many years of pioneering research, Folkman
discovered that tumors produce substances that induce angiogenesis,
and, more surprisingly, substances that suppress the process.
Because blood vessel cells, unlike tumor cells, cannot develop
resistance to drugs, they offer in principle a far better target
for anti-cancer therapy. Folkman reported in 1997 that in tests in
his laboratory, endostatin had caused tumors in mice to regress to
microscopic size, a spectacular result.
</P>
<P>
   The new anti-tumor factor Folkman has described in Friday's
issue of Science is a fragment of anti-thrombin, one of the many
proteins involved in the blood clotting systems. The fragment is
potent in reducing blood vessel formation and in shrinking tumors,
he and colleagues state in their article.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to follow up Folkman's work on the first two
angiogenesis inhibitors, some researchers have succeeded and others
have not. Dr. Gerald Soff of Northwestern University Medical School
has made his own angiostatin, independently of Folkman. Dr. Noel
Bouck, also at Northwestern, said she had tested it side by side
with angiostatin made by Dr. Michael O'Reilly, the leading
angiogenesis researcher in Folkman's laboratory. Both substances
were highly active at very small doses, Dr. Bouck said, although
she tested it mostly on cultures of cells and not on tumors in
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers testing endostatin have met with a similar spectrum
of success. ``There is a great deal of variability,'' said Dr.
Edward Sausville, the National Cancer Institute official
responsible for overseeing tests of endostatin. ``Some get results
and others, which are not published, did not get activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Folkman's response to the mixed success of other groups in
repeating his results is to note the extreme difficulty of the
experiments that O'Reilly and others carried out under his
supervision. ``Each of our papers takes about four years of work,
so you have a long learning curve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other laboratories may have had trouble repeating his work
because of the many exacting small points of experimental detail
that must be mastered. Even so, ``Five laboratories have made their
own endostatin and published their finding of anti-tumor
activity,'' Folkman said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute has not tried to make its own
endostatin ``because it's not our position to make things that
might undermine other manufacturers,'' Sausville said. It has also
not tried to select the most effective of the endostatins made by
other laboratories because a ``national bake-off of the best
endostatin preparation would get very complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the public interest surrounding Folkman's work, much
of it publicity that Folkman did not seek, the institute seems
interested in testing only the endostatin prepared by Folkman's lab
and by EntreMed, the small biotechnology company that has licensed
the product. Despite having been unable to repeat Folkman's animal
results independently, the agency is proceeding with tests in
humans, a procedure whose ethical basis was questioned in an
article this week in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Yancopoulos, an angiogenesis expert who is the chief
scientific officer at Regeneron Pharmaceuticals in Tarrytown, N.Y.,
has now come forward with his own criticism of the agency and of
Folkman's work. Although an academic and commercial competitor of
Folkman, Yancopoulos is also one of the most highly cited
biologists in the scientific literature. In an interview, he said
of the NCI, ``Subjecting patients to unknown risk and providing
illusionary or false hope in the absence of credible evidence for
potential benefit certainly raises ethical issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Sausville said that agency's rationale is that both Folkman and
EntreMed have now tested the human version of endostatin and shown
it has some efficacy against mouse tumors. (Previous tests used the
mouse version of endostatin.) Also, Sausville said, human
endostatin is ``completely and utterly safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal tests often do not accurately predict how well a drug
will perform in humans, and the Food and Drug Administration does
not require proof of a drug's efficacy in animals before going to
human trials. Given the safety of endostatin, it will be quickest
to test endostatin in people rather than try to clarify the
questions in animals, Sausville said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In pursuing this policy, the National Cancer Institute is
leapfrogging the obstacle at which Bristol-Myers Squibb fell, that
of successfully repeating the animal tests. Although the company
said at the time that it was dropping angiostatin because it
doubted it could produce enough, Dr. Mariano Barbacid, then the
company's vice president for oncology drug discovery and the
official responsible for developing angiostatin, said in an e-mail
Thursday: ``We could never reproduce the results published by
Folkman in vivo,'' meaning in animals, when using either O'Reilly's
preparation or angiostatin produced by EntreMed.
</P>
<P>
   Even then the company did not give up its efforts, Barbacid
said. Another of its laboratories prepared angiostatin in three
different ways, but ``to the best of my recollection, none of these
preparations had any biological activity'' in the standard mouse
tumor test, said Barbacid, who is now director of the Spanish
National Cancer Center in Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Barbacid then decided to make angiostatin in his own laboratory
at Bristol Myers and asked Folkman's laboratory for a virus
containing the angiostatin gene. ``To our surprise, this construct
did not yield the expected size products,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the angiostatin gene contained a grave
production flaw _ a genetic error known as a stop codon that halted
production of angiostatin before it was complete.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbacid noted that the virus method of making angiostatin
``was not the system of choice for the production of the
angiostatin molecules used in Folkman's publications.'' Folkman
said the virus did make a shorter version of angiostatin but that
it was effective too.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp disagreement has broken out over the nature of the
substances Folkman has isolated. All are fragments of larger, well
known proteins. Folkman believes the fragments become
anti-angiogenic after being cleaved in the body from their parent
proteins. But another leading angiogenesis researcher believes
Folkman's co-workers have made a common laboratory error, that of
isolating abundant protein fragments and erroneously attributing
some activity to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the first things you isolate as contaminants,''
Yancopoulos said. ``You work through them and get to the much less
abundant proteins that are really contributing to an activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are trained to be skeptical of their own and each
other's work, and Barbacid, in light of his experience of
angiostatin, has reservations about some of the results from
Folkman's laboratory. He said Folkman had given him little help in
trying to reproduce the angiostatin work. ``It was a very bizarre
situation, very frustrating to have a molecule that supposedly was
doing these marvelous things and not being able to get help from
the person who discovered it,'' Barbacid said.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman said it was totally inaccurate to say he had not been
helpful to Barbacid.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific progress rarely proceeds in a straight line and it
seems too early to tell whether, within the general promise of the
field, Folkman's particular factors are at a temporary roadblock or
some more serious obstacle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
