<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS TYSON MATURING? SLOWLY, MAYBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson, four months out of prison and preparing
for his comeback fight against Orlin Norris here on Oct. 23,
spreads around the blame for his troubles. Among the culprits: the
justice system, the media, his colleagues _ himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the former heavyweight champion remains bitter.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized the courts, claiming he has never been treated
fairly. He landed a jab on the chin of the media, referring to
sportswriters at a news conference on Thursday as ``dysfunctional
alcoholic reporters.'' And he said the fact he lives under a
microscope has distorted reality.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, in a reflective moment with a few of those
dysfunctional reporters, he looked inward to explain two prison
sentences, his suspension from boxing for biting the ear of Evander
Holyfield and other setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reflect on my life,'' he said. ``I'm only 33, so young, but
I seem so old. I've seen so many things. All the crap, how did it
come upon me?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad influences ... and I wasn't mature enough to understand
it. My problems came from my immaturity, I wasn't mature enough to
handle it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I grew up too fast. All the drama hit me and I wasn't
ready for it. So I went cold, I shut off my emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   And now? Has he turned the emotions back on? Has he gained any
maturity?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``It's one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that could be construed as hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   One involves his grade-school-age children, who live with their
mother in Maryland while he lives and trains in Las Vegas. They
watch TV, he said. Their friends watch TV and then make comments.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to behave in front of this audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing that's different now,'' he said. ``The other
kids talk to my kids so I'm real careful what I say. I definitely
don't want to use foul language.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, Tyson wants to make something clear:
He's a human being.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he's not much different from the rest of us. It's
just that everything he says and does comes under tremendous
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under a microscope,'' he said. ``In this room, and I'm not
saying just reporters, there might be perverts, pedofile, freaks,
horrible fathers. We all have issues we're dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides me being worldwide, I'm not as bad as some people. I
have some decency, some morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson could remain under that microscope for some time.
</P>
<P>
   His fight with Norris, a former cruiserweight champion about
Tyson's size, will mark the start of his third comeback.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, more than ever, he seems to be in it for the
money: He remains millions of dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately he hopes he'll once again fight for the world
championship he has twice lost _ and reap the ungodly financial
rewards that come with it. However, for now, he's not inclined to
focus beyond Norris.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't fought since he knocked out Francois Botha in January
because he was convicted of assault and spent three months in
prison, where he ballooned to 280 pounds. Now, after months of
training, he's trimmed down to about 235 but has a lot of work
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to work to get into shape to fight the top
contenders,'' he said. Again, one step at a time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
