<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-VICTIMS-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS ARE REMEMBERED, MOURNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ High school students. A youth minister. A
seminary student. A choir director who sang at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   All were united in their love of God, and all took time to pray,
sing and rejoice together Wednesday night at Wedgwood Baptist
Church in southwest Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   And all were tragically linked forever in an instant as they
were fatally shot by a man they did not know.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gene Ashbrook, 47, blasted their religion as he blasted
round after round of gunfire at them, and then took his own life.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spree is believed to be the deadliest in Fort Worth
history, wounding seven and killing seven before Ashbrook committed
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The dead: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KRISTI BECKEL
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of death, life.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Kristi Beckel has decided to use the loss of their
daughter to help save others desperately awaiting an organ
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Fort Worth family made the painful decision to
take Kristi off life support and have her organs and tissue
harvested, said Ron Ehrle, managing director for LifeGift Organ
Donation Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thoughts and prayers are with all the families affected by
this tragedy,'' Ehrle said. ``We hope that Kristi Beckel's family
decision to donate her organs and tissue will provide some comfort
in the months and years ahead. We are truly grateful for this
family's unselfish act to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristi, 14, died shortly after midnight Thursday at John Peter
Smith Hospital. She had been shot in the head during the killing
spree.
</P>
<P>
   No one in her family could be reached for comment. Neighbors
declined to talk about Beckel or the crime.
</P>
<P>
   LifeGift representatives and John Peter Smith officials met with
the Beckel family to discuss the organs and tissue donation.
</P>
<P>
   The family told LifeGift members that they want the girl's
organs donated so other lives may live. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN BROWN
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Brown was a man on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old student at Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary was pursuing a master's degree in educational ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very responsible, very attentive person, and he had a
particular heart for today's youth and in helping them,'' said Mary
Ellen Edwards, an advanced clinical practictioner at New Horizons,
a mental health facility that provides support to people suffering
severe grief and loss and other mental health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Brown worked part-time at New Horizons _ ``sometimes that meant
40 hours a week,'' Edwards said _ to support his education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have an overwhelming, incredible sadness and loss,''
said Edwards, his supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   As a mental health program assistant, Brown often transported
clients to and from group sessions, helped them with personal
hygiene and generally facilitated their stay at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and his wife, Kathy Jo, had been married about two years
and had no children. Edwards said Kathy Jo Brown requested privacy
and did not want to comment on the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children who died at Columbine now have a wonderful youth
minister in heaven,'' said Becky Roland, a friend and neighbor of
the Browns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY BROWNING
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Browning was ``one of those people who had boundless
energy and enthusiasm and this cutting edge humor,'' said Renee
Karriem, the principal at the school where Browning taught. ``I
just feel blessed to have her in my life. We loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Browning taught at Success High School, a night school on the
Trimble Tech campus. Thursday, students and faculty members wore
black lapel ribbons to mourn her.
</P>
<P>
   Browning, 36, was single and the children's choir director at
Wedgwood Baptist Church. She loved youngsters, her colleagues said.
She was involved in the lives of her students, many of whom were
high school dropouts, and always encouraged their success.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the kind of teacher who greeted every child,'' Karriem
said. ``She'd go to the ends of the Earth to help them make it. She
was the kind of teacher who liked to send `good news' notes home.''
</P>
<P>
   Browning had been a teacher for the Fort Worth school district
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Principal Sheryl Hopper was near tears as she
reminisced about Browning, who she said made Christian music
recordings and sang at weddings and funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all going to miss her'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Browning had a master's degree from Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary and was close to her family in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   One of Browning's students, Joe Alex Pulido , 19, said that he
and fellow students are in shock at losing their teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was humble, I guess. Outgoing and funny,'' he said. ``It's
still kind of hard to believe she's gone.'' &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
