<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      09-16 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S INTERNET PROVIDERS REMAIN BOWED, NOT BROKEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In private they are puzzled and angry, but in public,
China's fledgling Internet companies have pasted on brave faces the
last two days, ever since an important government minister said
that foreign shares in companies providing Internet content or
services were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   No one quite believes that Wu Jichuan, the minister of
information industries, intends to force dissolution of the dozens
of young, frontier companies that have attracted foreign funds from
giants like Intel as well as from individuals and venture capital
groups. Many of these companies also hope to make public stock
offerings in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign ownership has never been allowed in Internet service
providers, which connect users with the state-run gateways to the
global Internet. But on the assumption that fortunes will follow
the exponential growth of computer use here, tens of millions of
dollars in outside money has rushed to companies developing
Chinese-language electronic commerce and portals, or Web sites like
Yahoo.com and Excite.com that serve as the front doors for users'
Internet journeys. By government estimates, widely considered to be
low, China had more than 4 million Internet users as of June, with
the numbers rising fast.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best known portals here are SINA.com and Sohu.com, and
both have substantial foreign investment. Another pioneer, Sparkice
I-Com, which runs Internet Cafis, an Internet access provider, has
outside investors, too.
</P>
<P>
   The players in this risky field say they have cooperated with
government agencies to get where they are and profess surprise at
what appears to be a sudden turn. Most of the affected companies
said that the supposed ban on investment surely would not stick
and, indeed, one ministry official hinted Thursday that the rules
might be eased in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Zhang, the president of Sohu.com, which has investments
from Intel, Dow Jones and other foreign companies as well as three
professors at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said
Thursday that in building his company over the last three years he
has worked closely with several government agencies, including the
Information Industries Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang declined to comment directly on the minister's remarks,
only saying, ``I think that venture-capital investment to develop
high-tech industries is the path China is taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang held a previously scheduled news conference in Beijing on
Thursday to announce his company's entry into e-commerce, a genuine
frontier in a country where credit and debit cards are only
starting to catch on. Appearing with him were officials of Intel
China, which has provided capital for the project as well as the
computer chips; Microsoft China, which provides the software, and
Compaq Computer, which provides the hardware. But the sudden
questions about legality hung over the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Intel China president James Jarrett said
his company had invested in several Chinese Internet companies. He
said he felt that, in the end, officials would realize that such
investments contributed to China's progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left unclarified,'' Jarrett said of the minister's statement,
``this clearly would have a dampening effect on foreign investment
in these sectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of other investing companies went further in
private, saying that a ban on foreign investment would be
self-defeating for China because it would drive the same capital
and energy to places like Taiwan and Hong Kong _ where companies
could serve Chinese consumers from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Dow Jones Newswires on Thursday, an
official of the Information Industries Ministry restated that
outside investments in Internet companies were illegal. The
ministry's position is that Internet content and services are
covered by rules barring foreign ownership of telecommunications
services _ rules that were written in 1993 and 1995, before the
Internet was widely available in China.
</P>
<P>
   But the official, Wang Lijian, vice director of the ministry's
news office, also said that the telecommunications rules would be
revised later this year in a manner ``beneficial for investment and
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign entry into telecommunications services has been a prime
topic in the Chinese-U.S. negotiations over China's entry to the
World Trade Organization. If those talks succeed, then outside
investments in computer services are likely to be legalized in any
case.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese and foreign businessmen here are speculating about Wu's
reasons for raising the issue, which he first did in an interview
Tuesday with the Financial Times. Some think it is a ploy to warn
the United States what could happen if China is denied entry to the
World Trade Organization. Others think it is part of Wu's effort to
solidify the powers of his recently formed super-ministry over the
growing Internet sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TEXAS-SHOOTING-BUSH-3     09-16 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SHOOTING-BUSH-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BLAMES `WAVE OF EVIL' FOR SHOOTINGS ACROSS NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also sent with `a' code) 
(See also TEXAS-SHOOTING, TEXAS-SHOOTING-SCENE) 
 (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush cut short a busy
presidential campaign swing through Michigan and beat a hasty,
somber path back to Texas on Thursday, expressing outrage at what
he called ``a wave of evil passing through America'' but asserting
that gun control was not the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew the law to make people love one another,'' Bush
said Thursday afternoon as he left a hospital here, where he had
met with some of the people who had been injured Wednesday when a
gunman opened fire at a prayer service, killing seven of the
churchgoers and himself.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, reached out to the grieving, he was entering and
navigating delicate political straits.
</P>
<P>
   The church shootings joined other incidents of horrific gun
violence this year that have created new pressure for additional
restrictions on firearms. But Bush has not been a strong advocate
for gun control, and if he wins the Republican nomination, his
Democratic opponent is sure to shine a spotlight on that fact.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Michigan on Thursday, Bush made clear that he
retained the belief that the primary explanation for gun violence
was in people's hearts, not in the number and nature of firearms
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of a law _ a governmental law _ that will put
love in people's hearts,'' Bush said at a news conference in Grand
Rapids, Mich. ``There seems to be a wave of evil passing through
America now, and we as a society can pass laws and hold people
accountable for the decisions they make, but our hopes and prayers
have got to be that there is more love in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the shooter, Bush said, ``I'd like to make sure
people like him don't have guns.'' But he added that the man
``obviously was acting as a result of evil in his heart'' and that
Americans should ``pray for love in people's hearts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush clearly understands the potency of gun control as an issue
in the 2000 elections. His stump speech includes a section on gun
control. But what he says in that section is that gun laws must be
more vigorously and consistently enforced, and that people who
sell, obtain or use guns illegally must pay a harsh price. He does
not call for new laws.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has signaled his approval of some of the modest new gun
control measures that enjoy bipartisan support in Congress, like a
ban on the import of high-capacity ammunition clips. He has even
said he favors raising the age for the legal purchase of a handgun
to 21 from 18, which is not among the restrictions being considered
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Walker, president of Handgun Control, an advocacy group
in Washington, said that the moderation he had been hearing lately
in Bush's voice was less convincing than his record as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When push comes to shove, Bush has always been on the side of
the gun lobby,'' Walker said in a telephone interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Walker drew attention to two of Bush's decisions. In 1995,
shortly after he took office, Bush signed into law a measure
permitting Texans to carry concealed guns, providing the gun owner
first received proper training and certification.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush, said Thursday, ``A lot of
Texans feel safer because of that law _ women in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Walker noted, Bush signed into law a measure
prohibiting Texas cities and counties from filing lawsuits against
gun manufacturers. Under the law, the Texas attorney general must
approve of the lawsuit and file on the city's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said Bush, who has long made tort reform one of his
primary crusades, wanted to curb frivolous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan also drew attention to actions Bush has taken as
governor that toughened firearms regulations. He signed a bill
making adults criminally responsible if their guns ended up in
children's hands and caused injury; he has also stiffened penalties
for adults who sell or give guns to under-age children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in Grand Rapids that the Fort Worth gunman apparently
did not have a concealed-weapons permit, so was not in compliance
with the 1995 Texas law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know his background,'' Bush said, ``but it sounds to
me like he's mentally deranged.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush focused on the aberrant emotions and impulses behind
these incidents of violence, Vice President Al Gore, the front
runner for the Democratic presidential nomination, called on
Congress to pass an array of gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to respond to the flood of guns,'' Gore said in a
campaign stop Thursday in San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-SHOOTING-BUSH-3     09-16 0822
