<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-FIGHT-SCENE17-COX     09-16 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-SCENE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These are hairy days for Tyson
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ On the brash and gaudy Vegas Strip, where you find
one wondrous sight after another _ where the Statue of Liberty, the
Eiffel Tower, a spewing volcano, a massive pyramid and a medieval
castle stand alongside ancient Rome, a full-fledged sea battle and
100-story tower with a roller coaster on top _ he dwarfed
everything.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, Mike Tyson was billed as ``The Baddest Man
on the Planet.'' The Strip was where he became the youngest
heavyweight champ in history, where he became the game's most
savage knockout artist, where his menacing shadow eclipsed all of
the blazing neon and big marquee names. For one night's work, Tyson
could command more money than any athlete in the history of sports.
His bouts filled arenas and casinos with the kind of free spending
gamblers, celebrities and international fans that no other figure
could draw. Early this year Sports Illustrated was still calling
him ``the most galvanizing performer in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday he wasn't even the biggest boxer in this town. That
title is held by Oscar De La Hoya _ the Golden Boy _ the unbeaten
welterweight who is the most marketable face this sport has ever
known. And Saturday night _ in a showdown of welterweight champs
billed as ``The Fight of the Millennium,'' a bout that matches two
of the top three pound-for-pound boxers in the game _ both De La
Hoya ($16 million) and Felix Trinidad ($10 million) will pocket
more than Tyson will make next month when fights hand-picked Orlin
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   The Baddest Man is no more. That's given way to everything from
the fattest man to one of the most broke and certainly, most
confused.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old heavyweight showed up at the MGM Grand hotel and
casino _ where he'll fight Norris, a past-his-prime cruiserweight
who's added some pounds _ to talk about yet another comeback after
yet another forced exile from the ring.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked in, it was hard to recognize him. Dressed in
white pants and vest with a billowy, open necked shirt, he looked
like a disco regular from Danny Terio's ``Dance Fever.'' Recently
weighing 280 pounds, he was down to a still-chunky 235 pounds on
his 5-foot-10 frame. As for that menacing shaved dome, it now came
with a full head of hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going through so much right now,'' he said, ``I just don't
have time to cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, he'll soon will be wearing a Sly Stone Afro.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he was jailed for 3 1/2 months in Rockville,
Md., for assaulting two motorists after a minor traffic accident
last October. Before that had come the Nevada State Athletic
Commission's 15-month fight game banishment after Tyson twice bit
Evander Holyfield's ears in their June 1997 bout. And preceding
that was his three-year prison term in Indiana after being
convicted of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Add in a $13 million bill from the IRS, substantial debts to
Showtime, the MGM and promoter Dan Goosen _ all of whom loaned him
money _ a $100 lawsuit with former promoter Don King, other legal
problems, the lingering wounds from a highly publicized divorce
some years ago and enough social and psychological baggage to weigh
down the Goodyear blimp, and it's a wonder Tyson ever fought.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he rarely has. In the past eight years, he's had just
seven bouts. Most were against nobodies. The two of note were both
devastating losses to Holyfield. Even Tyson's last fight _ a
fifth-round stoppage over lackluster Frans Botha in January _ was
close to a fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   He had lost every round on every judges card until he landed the
right hand that stopped a suddenly careless Botha. ``I wasn't
psychologically ready for that fight,'' he said. ``Actually I was
nervous. I was scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   And because of that, Goosen _ like King before him _ now must
baby the once-bad man to be sure he has someone he can beat. The
promoter sifted through a list of lesser heavyweights and finally
came up with Norris, who fought for him a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson will get $10 million for the fight, but it's reported he
owes Showtime $33 million. For the Botha fight he was paid $25
million. His $13 million tax bill took half the check and the $12.5
million he owed in taxes from that purse, actually left him
$500,000 in the hole at the end of the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe Showtime my life,'' he said with disdain. ``I've got to
keep fighting to pay my bills. I'm just trying to get out of
debt.''
</P>
<P>
   His predicament angers him and no matter how much he tries to
praise Allah or talks about his kids, the venom and self-pity are
never far from the surface. Thursday he groused about training _
``People telling you what to do and you're a grown man,'' _ and
questions on his weight.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he let himself mushroom to 280 in ``the joint,'' as he
calls it, he shot back: ``Have you ever been incarcerated? Go out
and hit someone with your car and get incarcerated and see how fat
you get when you come out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his jail time, he said: ``It's politically correct to put
me in jail. It becomes so pervasive. If Mike Tyson is in your
courtroom, there's got to be a malfunction in the court system if
he doesn't get jail time ... They screwed me up pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on whether he shoulders the blame, he shot back:
``Listen man, I have no one to blame but myself. Others contributed
to it, but I've got to carry the weight of the fool alone.''
</P>
<P>
   His mood darkened when asked if he ever wonders what could have
been: ``Whoever created the word coulda or woulda, it's ridiculous.
There shouldn't be racism. There shouldn't be dysfunctional
alcoholics that are reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, by himself, he was more subdued for a while. ``I'm
33-years-old. I'm so young, but I seem so old.'' In the ring, he
said that translates into ``developing his skills again'' and
fighting maybe every two months: ``And if anybody makes a mistake,
they're gonna take a dirt nap. That what I get paid to do _ knock
people out and win spectacularly ... I'm still gonna win the title
again.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested he he had let his fans down, he soured
again: ``It's just that I'm under a microscope ... Look around the
room. If I know some guys in here, (they) are probably perverts,
pedophiles and freaks and horrible fathers. I'm not pretty. But I'm
not as bad as most people. I have some decency and morals.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I'm just not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he walked out, leaving that last line lingering in the air.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem. In the ring, the Baddest Man on the
Planet is just not that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
