</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM PROVES LESS DEVASTATING IN REALITY THAN MANY HAD FEARED
</HEADLINE>
   (See also HURRICANE-RDP, HURRICAN-NY-SCENE) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hurricane Floyd sent its fierce winds and torrents of
rain Thursday night into a New York region that was waiting and
well-prepared, and while the storm closed schools and businesses,
pounded beaches and flooded highways, it failed to inflict the
devastating damage many had feared.
</P>
<P>
   By early Thursday night, the storm was stoking winds of up to 62
mph and was expected to dump up to 10 inches of rain in some areas.
The brunt of the storm was set to hit Long Island by Thursday
night; the tail of the storm, meteorologists said, was expected to
leave the area by early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Downgraded, Tropical Storm Floyd _ and the fear of Floyd _
generated a host of disruptions that altered life in the New York
region. Thursday night, transit officials _ fearful of flooded
tracks _ shut down Metro-North, but restored ``extremely limited''
service an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey and New York City, schools were closed Thursday.
On Long Island, officials ordered that residents evacuate Fire
Island and the village of West Hampton Dunes. And in Vineland,
N.J., water was coursing so rambunctiously through the sewer system
that it uncorked manhole covers.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the reality of the storm turned out to be a little less
devastating, perhaps, than people had anticipated. As of late
Thursday night, there were no reported deaths related to the storm
in the New York region. No reported injuries. No interruptions to
subway service.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the region appeared to have been less
discombobulated by the obsessively watched, Weather
Channel-friendly trajectory of Floyd than it was three weeks ago
when a surprising three-inch flash flood crippled the region's
transportation network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the storm is about as we expected, maybe even a little
less,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday afternoon at a news
conference at the city's emergency crisis center.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman echoed those sentiments at a
news conference in Trenton, saying: ``We're going to get lucky it
appears. It won't be as bad as it could have been for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials breathed a collective sigh of relief after
girding for a storm, which, as a hurricane, had pounded the
Carolinas on Wednesday night and forced the biggest evacuation in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   According to meteorologists, the storm _ which at one point
covered as much area as the size of Texas _ licked coastal areas
Thursday as it churned quickly, and faster than expected, up the
East Coast, losing strength along the way.
</P>
<P>
   By early Thursday night, the storm, which was moving at 30 mph,
was passing through Long Island en route to Connecticut, the
National Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the New York region Thursday , officials stayed glued to
their cellular phones, radio equipment and televisions in preparing
for the storm, the first hurricane to touch the region since
Hurricane Bob skirted eastern Long Island in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   There were many unilateral acts of precaution. Whitman declared
a state of emergency for all of New Jersey on Wednesday; New York
Gov. George Pataki followed suit Thursday for New York City and
Nassau and Suffolk Counties, deploying 1,500 members of the
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   State and local officials ordered so-called nonessential
employees to leave work early, in order to alleviate any possible
rush hour crush. They encouraged private businesses and other
institutions to do the same _ and many, apparently, heeded that
advice, including the United Nations, which closed at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, there was wall-to-wall news coverage via
television, radio and the Internet, containing the latest warnings,
offering storm-safety tips and flashing various emergency phone
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a well-broadcast storm that people _ or smart
people anyhow _ got off the water,'' said Petty Officer Brent Erb
of the Coast Guard, adding that there were no reports of people or
vessels in danger on the seas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
