<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-LEMANS-QUALIFYING     09-16 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEMANS-QUALIFYING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Records set during qualifying
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Panoz LMPR Roadster S, Dodge Viper and Porsche all
set American Le Mans Series course records in the first session of
qualifying Thursday to take provisional pole positions for
Saturday's Petit Le Mans at Road Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Panoz, driven by David Brabham, Eric Bernard and Andy
Wallace, charged around the course in 1:10.873/129.01 mph to break
the record for prototypes, set in April by Wallace in a Riley &AMP;
Scott MKIII Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Second and third in a tight pack were the BMW V12 LMRs that won
Le Mans. J.J. Lehto and Jorg Muller, at 1:12.058/126.89, edged
teammates Steve Soper, Bill Auberlen and Joachim Winkelhock, who
clocked 1:12.104/ 126.81. The No. 2 Panoz, driven by Jan Magnussen,
Johnny O'Connell and Memo Gibley, was fourth with a lap of
1:12.364/126.36.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia Beretta, Karl Wendlinger and Mark Duez had to push their
Dodge Viper to an ALMS course record 1:19.525/114.98 to edge
teammates David Donohue, Tommy Archer and Jean-Philippe Belloc
(1:20.012 /114.28) in the GTS class. In the Porsche-dominated GT
field, Cort Wagner, Dirk Muller and Sascha Maassen took their
Porsche 911 GT3R around in 1:25.617/106.80 to edge the
1:25.814/106.55 of Luca Riccitelli, Patrick Huisma and Hans Jorg
Hofer, also in a Porsche 911 GT3R.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying resumes at 2 p.m. today. There are 51 entries
battling for 50 starting positions.
</P>
<P>
   Going global
</P>
<P>
   The American, European and Asian Le Mans Series are preparing
schedules to run in 2000 under terms of the license agreement
between Panoz Motorsports and the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO),
organizers of the 24 Hours of Le Mans. The agreement runs through
the 2008 season, and the 2000 ALMS schedule is expected to be
announced today. The 1999 ALMS has been viewed as a transition
season for participating teams to bring their equipment up to ACO
technical guidelines. For 2000, teams must be in full accordance.
</P>
<P>
   They said it
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Jr. returns to the ALMS for the first time since
Sebring, driving a Corvette. ``It's exciting to be back road
racing,'' Paul said. ``This is my first time back at Road Atlanta
since they changed the track. Everything that's happened to the
track is awesome. I've always been in love with this place, but
it's nice to see her get a face lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
