<HEADER>
A5167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-TIMELI     09-16 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-TIMELINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT BEGAN LIKE ANY OTHER CHOIR PRACTICE. THEN THE WORLD CHANGED
FOREVER.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For Jaynanne Brown, it started like any
other night of choir practice at Wedgwood Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Then about 6:45 p.m. Wednesday, she saw Larry Ashbrook walking
toward the church, smoking a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, Ashbrook pulled a pistol from inside his belt
and fired a shot that grazed her head with its searing heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my hand up and thought, `Dear Lord, is this how it feels
to die?' '' Brown said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The rampage that began at the main entrance of the church would
build to a terrifying climax over the next several minutes,
according to witnesses, victims and police. Ashbrook would shoot 14
people, killing seven, before turning the gun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Ashbrook gave the outside world little
warning of the terror to come. One neighbor passed Ashbrook's home
in Forest Hill, a Fort Worth suburb, about 3 p.m., and saw him
sitting on the front porch, watching cars and people pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked kind of sad ... maybe a little angry,'' Patricia
Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, Ashbrook was working on his well-maintained
lawn, attending to his pear trees and potted plants. That contrasts
sharply with his earlier behavior: Investigators said he trashed
the inside of his home and tore the family Bible to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Around 6:30, investigators said, Ashbrook walked out of his home
for the last time. He was dressed in a short, dark green jacket,
blue jeans and tennis shoes. A white baseball cap was pulled down
near his eyes, and he wore sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few miles to the west, more than 100 teens were starting
a religious rally at Wedgwood. The church had recruited a Christian
band, prepared skits and publicized the gathering to other
churches.
</P>
<P>
   The band was about to start playing as Ashbrook's car arrived.
He approached a few adults, asking about the prayer meeting. As
Ashbrook neared the entrance, Brown and some friends worried aloud
about him smoking in the church.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Laster, a maintenance worker, approached him and asked him
to put out the cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Ashbrook reached inside his jacket and pulled out a
gun that police later identified as a Ruger 9mm semiautomatic. He
fired into Laster's abdomen, badly wounding him. He then turned to
the couch and fired one bullet into the head of Sydney Browning,
killing the 36-year-old director of the children's choir.
</P>
<P>
   He then fired at Brown, who slumped to the couch. As Ashbrook
moved on, Brown realized that she was not badly hurt and scampered
out.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook, heading toward the sanctuary, encountered Shawn Brown
beside a rack of CDs and shot him. The 23-year-old seminary student
ran several yards before dying in the hallway, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook fired a few bullets through a window into the
sanctuary, but people inside said they didn't realize anything was
amiss. Even as he entered the room and began yelling, many assumed
that he was part of a skit and that the shots were blanks.
</P>
<P>
   But as victims began to fall, teens started diving to the floor.
A few scrambled to help others. Mary Beth Talley, 17, ran to the
sanctuary to warn others and was struck by a bullet as she helped a
small friend.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook sprayed the sanctuary, emptying three magazines of
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Griffin, Joseph Ennis, Susan Kimberly Jones and Justin
Ray would die at the scene. Kristi Beckel would die shortly after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Five more would be injured.
</P>
<P>
   As Ashbrook cursed and paced, he moved to the right side of the
sanctuary and tossed a pipe bomb near the stage. It exploded but
injured no one seriously.
</P>
<P>
   By then, police were on their way. Chip Gillette, who had been
off duty, was alerted to trouble about 6:50 p.m., when his dog
began barking toward the church across the street.
</P>
<P>
   When Gillette went outside, he ran into people screaming and
fleeing. Gillette ran home, called police on his radio, grabbed a
gun and bulletproof vest, and ran back to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:55, the police received three 911 calls. Three more came a
minute later. Four more at 6:57.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said he and another officer entered the church. He
immediately saw his friend, Browning, dead on the couch, and his
fear grew as he moved down the hall, knowing that his wife and
daughter were at the church.
</P>
<P>
   He heard several more gunshots, then it turned strangely quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a few moments, it seemed unreal because it was so
silent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 10 feet from the sanctuary door, he heard one more
shot _ what turned out to be the bullet that Ashbrook put into his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the doors opened up and kids just poured out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (This report contains material from Deanna Boyd, Yvette Craig,
Gabrielle Crist, Jan Jarvis, Rebeca Rodriguez and Kathy Sanders.)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
