<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-16 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LIKE BIRD, PARCELLS MAY DECIDE TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HARVEY ARATON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird does not plan to coach after next season, and this
should surprise no one who saw the resignation in his face as his
Indiana Pacers surrendered their championship dream, like the
victim of a holdup on a dark New York street.
</P>
<P>
   With two of the most focused, penetrating eyes basketball has
known, Bird took a hard look at the soul of his team last spring
and clearly saw that it lacked what it takes. If he evaluated
himself just as honestly, then he has also by now acknowledged
that, in the chess match of coaches, the New York Knicks' Jeff Van
Gundy was bishop to Bird, the rook.
</P>
<P>
   When Bird didn't obstruct the Pacers' trading of Antonio Davis,
their best big man, for a high school prospect in the National
Basketball Association draft last June, that was the clue. In
promoting a recently published book the other day, Bird said he
would coach the remaining year of his contract, and no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was actually a little surprised that he got back into the
fray in the first place,'' Nets coach Don Casey, a former Boston
Celtics assistant, said Thursday. ``We used to talk about life some
when he was at the end of his career. His mother died of the same
thing mine did, Lou Gehrig Disease. I always got the feeling Larry
wanted to walk away and view the game from a distance. But Indiana
had a shot, it was his home state and I guess it was within his
competitive nature to try and get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   At the height of opportunity, the Pacers wilted, their veteran
core defining itself as, at best, a quality conference final
opponent. Donnie Walsh, the team's president, began the inevitable
overhaul, but people who are used to playing or coaching for the
ring don't wait around for teen-agers to become men. Larry Bird
doesn't need the money, and apparently has good reason to not risk
the stress.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, Bird reveals that he has for years been dealing
with an irregular heartbeat, which once almost caused him to pass
out while coaching a game. The health and stress factor has,
likewise, been a factor for Bill Parcells, since he had heart
surgery following his time with the New York Giants. No one will
ever confuse Bird the coach with Parcells the genius, but in the
terms of what they demand, of others and themselves, these proud
men are more than similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' the Tuna defiantly snapped earlier this week
when asked if the calamities that have befallen his team so soon
this season might affect his decision to coach on next year.
</P>
<P>
   This was contrary to what Parcells told HBO's ``Real Sports'' a
few weeks ago, when Vinny Testaverde's feet were intact, when the
Super Bowl was more than a plausible goal. In a show that aired
this week, the 58-year-old Parcells was asked if this season could
be his last. ``I think there's a chance it could,'' he said. ``I
always felt I wasn't going to coach when I was 60.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells went on to reveal that he couldn't relax after last
season, couldn't let go. ``It was scary,'' he said, and he also
admitted being spooked by the cancer that recently took the life of
Seattle assistant coach Fritz Shurmur, a friend and peer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have a little time, do a couple of things,''
Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   While a sound argument could be made that the rash of New York
Jets injuries would insure the coach's return next season, Parcells
must still determine from the rest of this season whether a
championship run was canceled by bad luck, or merely postponed. He
built this veteran team quickly, to correspond to his own
professional agenda, and to the octogenarian wishes of the late
owner, Leon Hess. Now Hess is gone and new ownership is imminent.
Parcells, never that easy to work with, may not be so enamored of
the next boss.
</P>
<P>
   Footballs sometimes take the strangest, most fateful bounces.
Who knows when Testaverde, if ever, will come all the way back?
Parcells is not likely to spend much time chasing a last
championship with Rick Mirer, or with any other quarterbacks he
can't trust. He certainly isn't interested in presiding over a team
not reaching for the top, any more than Bird, who clarified his
position this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years is enough for a coach in any one place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Early last spring, it seemed the Celtics' legend was the calm,
stoic leader of the logical heir to Jordan's Chicago Bulls. The
next minute, out of nowhere, Marcus Camby and the Knicks were
rejecting the thought, suspending belief.
</P>
<P>
   Jets fans beware: Bird's planned flight could be a preview of
the path that Parcells soon chooses for himself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
