<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, DON: THIS ONE SELLS ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Calling it ``The Fight of the Millennium'' is Don
King's job, not Jim Lampley's.
</P>
<P>
   Semantics aside, Lampley won't have to show much restraint when
he does the blow-by-blow Saturday night of the Oscar De La
Hoya-Felix Trinidad fight. It is being touted as the greatest
attraction for a non-heavyweight fight in pay-per-view history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a phrase you'd hear me tossing out without some
context,'' Lampley said Thursday morning, stuck near the Lincoln
Tunnel as he tried to get a flight out of rain-drenched New York,
hoping to make it to Las Vegas by Saturday to change into a tux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, no fight was bigger than Ali-Frazier I. This isn't
bigger than that. And most who call it `fight of the millennium'
don't even know when the millennium changes. They'll have another
year to work up another `fight of the millennium' and they don't
even know it yet. Once they do, they'll surely try to take
advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (For the record, the new millennium doesn't begin in 2000. The
20th century ends and 21st century begins in 2001. We don't make up
the rules. We just report them).
</P>
<P>
   As if De La Hoya-Trinidad needs one of those ridiculous
promotional titles. Here's a rare instance when a pay-per-view bout
doesn't have to bog itself down in predictions of home sales
figures and dollar amounts. But because of the legacy it has
created in the past decade _ that's a 10-year period, by the way _
promoters of the final fight of the '90s indulge in a screaming
match that doesn't even make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because TV viewers already get the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature abhors a vacuum,'' said Lampley. ``Don't let the facts
get in the way. Trying to convince Don King this fight needs no
promotion is like telling him don't bother waking up tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, De La Hoya-Trinidad will attract a predicted
800,000 to one million home buys at $49.95 a whack. The current PPV
leader in a non-heavyweight bout is De La Hoya-Pernell Whitaker,
which did more than 800,000 in April, '97 and went for $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   The difference now is there are about 42 million homes with
addressable cable or satellite dishes, which will produce millions
of dollars more. So when someone like TVKO executive Mark Taffet
says, ``this will be one of the greatest events in pay-per-view
history,'' he's talking volume.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's last pay fight, in February against Ike Quartey,
had about 600,000 buys. That's about in line with his bouts against
Hector Camacho (Sept. '97) and Julio Caesar Chavez (Sept. '98). In
seven pay fights during his career _ those on TVKO, not just HBO _
De La Hoya has attracted 3.5 million buys that have resulted in
$150 million.
</P>
<P>
   But enough of the numbers, says HBO executive producer Ross
Greenburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to look at this as more an historical fight than a
cash machine,'' said Greenburg, whose boxing experiences at the
network go even further back back than its closed-circuit telecast
of the 1981 Sugar Ray Leonard-Thomas Hearns classic, which is being
compared to this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 12th round, when De La Hoya is digging deep, he isn't
wondering how many buys the fight has,'' said Greenburg. ``These
two enjoy cashing checks, of course, but that's not why they're
here or why we're going to watch. It's unfortunate that boxing
takes on this business sense with these pay-per-view bouts. We need
a return to the dramatic heroics and stop looking at the cash
register.''
</P>
<P>
   That'll happen soon enough. Within two months after this fight,
King has the honor of pimping Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis II, a
pay-per-view gold mine set up because of their controversial draw
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   King already predicts an unheard of two-million home buys for
that Nov. 13 fight, saying: ``The rematch will do more pay-per-view
than any fight has done because of the alleged scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   So enjoy the purism of De La Hoya-Trinidad while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sport is plagued by fighters protected by their managers
who look for the big pay-per-view payoff, and for these two, it's a
rarity,'' Lampley said. ``Everyone has waited for this for five
years. This should be an example to other fighters to meet the best
guy available. I hope other fighters notice, and I hope the fans
don't let the other one (De La Hoya or Trinidad) drop off the map
just because they lose, because neither deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in cyberland: The mandatory Internet link to this
bigger-than-life event takes place at a site developed by Excite
(www.excite.com/oscarfelix). It did a Webcast of Wednesday's press
conference with the two fighters and has had live chats each day.
</P>
<P>
   Today's weigh-in can be seen there at 6 p.m., which follows a
live chat with Don King at 5 p.m. There's also an auction for the
Oscar De La Hoya Foundation with bidding on autographed gloves and
a fight post from the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Other info and trinkets for sale can be found at the sites for
Top Rank (www.toprank.com), TVKO (www.tvko.com) and De La Hoya
(www.oscardelahoya.com).
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, it also should be noted, is a recent enshrinee at
the Male Celebrity Navel Academy, which, in essence, is the Web's
Belly Button Hall of Fame (www.tigerx.com/bbs/men/index.htm). He is
one of 24 men and a few hundred women so honored. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
_Our Monday afternoon ex-quarterback, Terry Bradshaw, whose
hour-long, noon-to-1 p.m. show on KXTA-AM (1150) wasn't embraced
here with open ears, proved his worth the day after the NFL season
opener. With all the stuff the former Pittsburgh Steelers QB and
Fox NFL analyst had to discuss, the show could have gone four hours
_ but unfortunately didn't. At last, the benefits of having
Bradshaw on the radio outweigh the promotional value he brings to
the station. It's a complete reversal of what happened with the
Karl Malone hiring during the NBA strike. Now, if we can just
eliminate the callers and all those commercial spots that have to
be there to pay the bills for Bradshaw's services. &QL; 
_Both Bradshaw and ESPN's Chris Mortensen have interviews with
Green Bay Packers quarterback Bret Favre for their respective
Sunday NFL pregame shows. &QL; 
!arrow!Fox Sports Net's ``NFL This Morning'' has added recently
retired Cleveland Browns linebacker Chris Spielman to the lineup
for the rest of the season. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
_The sailors say Brandi, you're a fine girl: A few months after her
black-and-white, pretty much bare-it-all photo in Gear magazine got
the relative unknown some great exposure, U.S. women's soccer
sensation Brandi Chastain reappears in the October issue _ in
color, and more revealing. Plus she's actually !ital!interviewed
this time. The cover headline tease: ``Sex, Soccer and Me: Brandi
Chastain Talks.'' This smells of an ongoing series that readers
will be forced to gear up for. Coming in November: ``Brandi
Chastain Does Stuff Like Other Human Beings _ Eats, Sleeps, Pays
Bills _ All With Her Clothes On!'' &QL; 
_What do John Elway, Tiger Woods, Nolan Ryan, Florence Griffith
Joyner, Karch Kiraly, Ken Griffey Jr., Mark McGwire, John McEnroe,
Gail Devers, Sugar Ray Leonard and Evander Holyfield have in
common? All were left off the ESPN SportsCentury Top 100 list. But
remember, three horses made it.
</P>
