s f BC-BIZ-HISPANIC-CHARITY-     09-16 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-HISPANIC-CHARITY-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HISPANIC PHILANTHROPY, THE PERSONAL TOUCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Calif., Fla.)   (af)  
 By LAURA CASTANEDA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the town of San Miguel Epejan in the Mexican state of
Michoacan needed a new road, former residents who had emigrated to
the Chicago suburb of Aurora, Ill., held raffles, sponsored dances
and knocked on hundreds of doors asking for donations.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two years, their local organization, Club de
Michoacan, raised more than $100,000 to help the Mexican government
complete the road, which opened a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my town in Mexico, you call people your `uncle' even if
they're not related to you,'' said Gonzalo Arroyo, a native of San
Miguel Epejan and president of the Michoacan Federation, which
oversees 25 such clubs in Illinois. ``It's like a large family, and
you rely on each other for lots of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the familiar, personal ways of Hispanic philanthropy in
the United States. And now, those mainstream philanthropic
organizations that have lamented their inability to reap Hispanic
donations are trying to better understand those ways.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, Hispanic people are starting their own
businesses at rapid rates and joining the middle class in
increasing numbers. The new efforts to strengthen Hispanic
nonprofit groups and to help mainstream philanthropies gain more
Latino donors include a five-year, $15 million program of Hispanics
in Philanthropy in Berkeley, Calif., a group of Hispanic people who
work at a wide range of grant-making institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The program will award its first grants next year to nonprofit
agencies that provide social services to Hispanic people.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, experts on Hispanic philanthropy provided
potentially influential guidance in a book called ``Nuevos
Senderos: Reflections on Hispanics and Philanthropy'' (Arte Publico
Press, 1999) and as part of a report called ``Cultures of Caring:
Philanthropy in Diverse American Communities'' by the Council on
Foundations, a Washington-based association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential of our community is terrific, and it needs to be
acknowledged,'' said Henry J. Ramos, of Mauer Kunst Consulting, who
contributed to ``Nuevos Senderos'' and wrote the Hispanic section
of the ``Cultures of Caring'' report. ``But this potential cannot
be capitalized on unless mainstream institutions do a better job of
understanding Latino culture and needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos's research shows that Hispanic people tend to give to
religious organizations, mutual aid societies like the Clubs de
Michoacan or directly to needy friends and family members in the
United States or their native countries instead of to mainstream
philanthropies. Donors often cite a sense of responsibility to
their communities _ in the United States and elsewhere _ and to
their extended families and social circles.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic donors also report that mainstream philanthropies make
few efforts to solicit their support.
</P>
<P>
   When the charities call on wealthy Hispanic people, they
sometimes make the mistake of dwelling on financial planning and
tax advantages. Experts say Hispanic donors are more interested in
exactly who the gifts will benefit and how; sometimes they even
want to meet the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The few quantitative studies on Hispanic people and philanthropy
confirm that donations are rising but that nonprofit groups are
slow to seek their gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to organized philanthropic groups by the average
Hispanic household jumped 55 percent from 1993 to 1995, to $547,
according to the most recent figures from Independent Sector, a
Washington-based coalition of charities. But, it said, just 44
percent of Hispanic households were ever approached by any
charitable organization in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainstream philanthropy assumes that if Latinos are poor, they
don't have money to give,'' said Diana Campoamor, the director of
Hispanics in Philanthropy. ``In fact, they give in proportion to
their income.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of informal giving by Hispanic people to those they
know personally is, of course, difficult to measure. But the amount
may be significant. Money sent from immigrants in the United States
to six Latin American countries _ Mexico, Colombia, the Dominican
Republic, El Salvador, Guatemala and Nicaragua _ amounted to almost
$8 billion in 1998, according to the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute
in Claremont, Calif., which based its estimates on research by the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the giving that happens in Latino communities is
never counted and not recorded,'' said Anna Gloria Rivas-Vazquez, a
fund-raiser for the Carrollton School of the Sacred Heart in Miami
who has done research on Latinos and philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Groups are finding that Hispanic donors are more likely than
others to support causes or organizations that have touched them
personally. Consider Bob Vila, the home renovation guru, whose
parents came to the United States from Cuba. He received good
grades in high school and wanted to go to college to study
architecture, but his guidance counselor offered little help. ``I
had to mine the territory myself just to get to Miami-Dade Junior
College,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So earlier this year, Vila, 53, established the Vila Family
Foundation with $400,000 to support several Miami programs that
help Hispanic students get into college. He also sends money to an
elderly relative in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never thought of it as `philanthropy,''' Vila said.
``I've just thought of it as part of my responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos A. Saladrigas, 51, chief executive of ADP Totalsource of
Miami, a payroll processor, has donated more than $1 million to
charity. He says he has always given to human rights groups,
because he recalls fleeing Cuba as a boy. After his youngest son
was diagnosed with diabetes, he also began giving to the Juvenile
Diabetes Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   As Saladrigas put it, ``The key to the Latino pocketbook lies in
the heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
