<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5175 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-CASSANI-A     09-16 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-CASSANI-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURTURING A NO-FRILLS AIRLINE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af) 
By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANSTED, England _ Like the proud mother of a newborn, Barbara
Cassani bounces into the reception area of Go, the no-frills,
low-cost European airline, showing off and pointing out every facet
of her company _ ``my baby,'' she says _ down to the dowdy details
of the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buy my sandwich out of that really elegant machine over
there,'' she said with a laugh, apologizing for ``probably smelling
a bit tuna-y from lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cassani (pronounced cas-SAN-i), at age 39 the chief
executive of Go Fly Ltd., shares responsibility for the company
with its true parent, British Airways PLC. Three years ago, Robert
J. Ayling, the president of British Airways, tapped Ms. Cassani, an
American, to write a business plan for a low-cost airline with the
promise that if she could show it could be profitable, she could
run it. It's not profitable just yet _ Go has been in business just
a little more than a year _ but Ms. Cassani said it would break
into the black by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In that first year, she has already had to deal with low-cost
competitors wielding words and lawsuits. Easyjet tried to ground Go
by filing a lawsuit contending that the airline's pricing was
anticompetitive. Richard Branson, who founded Virgin Express along
with Virgin Atlantic, his original rival to British Airways,
initially said, ``I think they are determined to get rid of
low-cost carriers and subsidize Go to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Branson and other competitors contended that Go was a pawn in a
larger plan by British Airways to eliminate the no-frills, low-cost
niche by undercutting everyone's prices.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her no-windows office at Stansted Airport outside
London, Ms. Cassani recalled that time. ``I think people love
conspiracy theories, she said. ``I just put my head down and got on
with it. It actually helped raise the profile of the company.'' The
lawsuits have since been dropped and, lately, most rivals have been
less outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cassani has had high ambitions since her middle-class
childhood in Boston and San Francisco. ``I've always been old for
my age, but it's catching up with me,'' she said. Growing up, she
cleaned houses and worked at a Burger King _ to pay for things like
the feeding and upkeep of her own horse. ``I've always wanted to do
things that required money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cassani went to Mount Holyoke College in South Hadley,
Mass., for her undergraduate degree and then to the Woodrow Wilson
School of Public and International Affairs at Princeton University
for a master's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't supposed to be a business person,'' she said. ``I was
supposed to grow up and move to Washington, D.C., or join an
international organization or go run a state somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she ended up joining Coopers &AMP; Lybrand in Washington as
a consultant in its international division. In 1986, Ms. Cassani
transferred to the company's London offices with her husband, Guy
Davis, ``a Brit,'' she explained. Now an investment banker in the
London office of Wasserstein Perella, he had met her while she was
at Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, after reading a newspaper advertisement, she found
a job in sales and marketing with British Airways. In short order,
she worked her way up, turning around Dan-Air, a small European
airline that British Airways had bought in 1992 and that was losing
money. She went to New York in 1993 as the general manager for
British Airways' United States operations.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, the call came to take a stab at starting an
airline. ``I've always been a maverick, but I've never been an
entrepreneur,'' she said. ``I think I had no idea what I was
getting into personally, because if I did I probably would have
been frightened by the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a $40 million investment from British Airways, Ms.
Cassani likes to view Go as a separate company, like a true
start-up with all of the same foibles and hiccups that all
companies have in their first months. When she started, the company
had two employees. Now it has 500. ``I used to know everyone's
name,'' she lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Since Go began in May 1998 with just two routes, it has expanded
to 13 from Stansted Airport, with Barcelona and Prague to be added
later this month. A typical round-trip fare to Rome is $187,
compared with $570 on British Airways. Like Southwest Airlines,
which Ms. Cassani studied, Go has few frills. Sandwiches and coffee
are available, but cost extra.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether Go is taking customers from its parent, Ms.
Cassani said bluntly: ``It's irrelevant. If I weren't cutting into
their sales, someone else would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that Ms. Cassani could be Ayling's heir
apparent at British Airways, though Ayling, at 52, has no plans to
retire anytime soon. Ms. Cassani expertly dismisses the
speculation. ``I'm a person of the moment,'' she said. ``I've never
sat down and said, `This is my path.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a country where executives like to be addressed as ``Mr.,''
she is always ``Barbara,'' casual, chatty and warm. She is the
mother of two children, aged 4 and 7, and drives a Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty strict mother,'' she said. ``Very little junk
food and no TV. I import tapes from the U.S. My dad tapes PBS and
sends them over.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being the only women to be chief executive of an airline,
even a corporate subsidiary, in the world, Ms. Cassani shrugs.
``Running a business here in the U.K., particularly being a woman,
is just far too big a deal,'' she said. ``The point at which some
woman starts up a business and nobody cares about it, that's when
we'll all we know we made it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
