<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-LINCOLN-AR     09-16 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-LINCOLN-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 LINCOLN LS: GERMAN COOKING AT CHEZ LINCOLN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ My friend scowled as she circled the black 2000
Lincoln LS. She turned up her nose as she peered inside. She sat
silently as we went for a drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it,'' she said apologetically when we returned,
sheepishly recalling my raves about the Lincoln. Her complaints:
The LS's body is too small and plain, its interior is too spare and
its ride is too firm.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln had done its job, I thought, as she lumbered away in her
large, plush Lincoln Continental. A professional woman in her 50s,
my friend had always driven American luxo-barges. She was seeking
her father's Lincoln, and the LS is certainly not that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The LS, which went on sale in the summer, is aimed at the
increasingly affluent baby boomers who buy luxury cars mainly from
Europe and Japan. These are smaller, sportier high-end sedans than
Detroit has usually offered, with responsive handling and a less
pillow-like ride. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until now, this was uncharted territory for Lincoln, which has
some of the oldest customers in the industry. Lincoln figured it
would take a lot of time to lure new, younger buyers, but the LS
has worked even better than they expected. Already, Lincoln has
sold more than 11,000 of the sedans, roughly a third of the
expected volume for the year.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising, Lincoln is nailing its target market. LS buyers
are younger than other Lincoln owners, at about 40, and have
household incomes of $100,000 a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I, too, figured Lincoln might struggle to convince young,
affluent buyers that the LS was worth putting on the shopping list
next to BMW or Lexus. But after multiple test drives, I concluded
that the LS is the first American car truly capable of competing
against the wave of midsize luxury imports.
</P>
<P>
   After they got the green light to develop a midsize ``entry
luxury'' car, Lincoln engineers checked their cupboard for a
chassis and found it bare. That proved to be a blessing. Another
Ford division, Jaguar, was also in dire need of a smaller car.
</P>
<P>
   The need for new iron, combined with the ability to spread costs
across two divisions, led Ford to start from scratch in developing
an all-new platform _ the basic architecture of a vehicle. So far,
this platform has spawned the LS and the Jaguar S-Type, with more
models _ including the 2001 Ford Thunderbird _ to come.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers and designers have done a masterly job of
distinguishing the Lincoln from the Jaguar. The S-Type, which
resembles its namesake of the 1960s, is smooth, powerful and
luxurious in the British tradition. The LS feels German, with the
hard-edged demeanor of a serious driver's car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Teutonic influence should not be surprising, given
that a German, Helmuth Schrader, Ford's corporate design director
for large and luxury cars, oversaw the styling. While the LS is
generally patterned after European and Japanese entry-luxury sedans
in size, proportion and rear-drive layout, it has BMW touches like
a low hood line, which provides good visibility, and wheels that
are pushed almost to the corners. It is no head turner like its
S-Type cousin, but the LS's simple, classic style should hold up
over time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only what I consider excessive use of chrome gives the LS an
American touch. The grille is similar to that of the Navigator
sport utility, though smaller. There is chrome around the license
plate and bright accents around the windows and bumpers. Order the
$1,000 sport package, however, and most of the chrome disappears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chrome carries into the interior, with accents around the
gear shifter and air vents. Otherwise, the interior is classic and
simple, outfitted in muted tones and matte finishes. The leather
seats are very comfortable and supportive. The back seat, which
splits and folds, is raised slightly, giving rear passengers better
visibility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cabin is more spacious than some competitors' because of the
car's rather long 114.5-inch wheelbase. The LS has significantly
more interior room than the more expensive BMW 5-Series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I had a few complaints: The windows, save for the driver's, lack
a one-touch control. The power adjustment for the outside mirrors,
at the left of the dashboard, is obscured by the steering wheel.
I'd prefer the hand brake, situated along the center console, to be
tucked under the dash. The wood trim is fake; the real thing would
be more fitting for a car with the LS's ambitions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the LS's forte is not its design, but its responsive
handling. If you took off the badges, a driver zipping around sharp
corners and sweeping curves would swear this car came from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Does the LS handle as well as the unflappable BMW 5-Series?
After comparing the cars on a slalom course, I thought not. Still,
the LS gives the 5-Series a run for the money _ for roughly $10,000
less. While older Lincoln owners like my friend may consider the
ride too firm, I found it quite pleasant in around-town motoring.
</P>
<P>
   The brakes also impress. Stomp on the pedal, and the car stops
quickly and stays level, rather than diving like a porpoise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The LS has essentially the same engines as the S-Type, though
they are slightly less powerful: The 3-liter V6 has 210 horsepower;
the 3.9-liter V8 has 252. Both have adequate, but not
extraordinary, power. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both engines are available with a new smooth-shifting five-speed
automatic. The V6 can be ordered with a manual transmission _ the
first in a Lincoln since 1951. Typically, I'd prefer the manual,
but the LS's stick shift felt sloppy, a trait that Ford executives
promise to fix. The automatic was as smooth as silk, but emitted a
tiny whine as the car accelerated from a stop, another problem
engineers are tending to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The V6 model, which is lighter and has a better front-rear
weight balance, feels more agile. Still, for just $4,000 more, I'd
pick the more potent V8. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buying an all-new car is always risky in the first year of
production. The quality in all three of the Lincolns I tested
appeared generally high.
</P>
<P>
   Further, I suspect that Lincoln will bend over backward to
please customers new to the brand. For the moment, the LS
represents one of the best deals around, with most items standard,
including side air bags up front, anti-lock brakes and power seats,
doors and windows. The V6 with the automatic starts at $31,450; the
manual version, which adds the sport package, starts at $32,250.
The V8 model starts at $35,225. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that the prices will go up. Indeed, Jacques A. Nasser,
Ford's chief executive, recently made the offhand comment that
``we're selling them too cheap.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: An American luxury car that speaks fluent German. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
