<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUESOME TESTIMONY CAPS DRAMATIC TESTIMONY IN DRAGGING DEATH TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ Before decapitation ended his torture, dragging
victim James Byrd Jr. ground his elbows, knees and heels to the
bone, shifting his weight in a futile attempt to relieve his
``devastating pain,'' a pathologist testified Thursday as
prosecutors wrapped up their capital murder case against a white
supremacist.
</P>
<P>
   The gruesome testimony from Dr. Tommy Brown drove two of Byrd's
sisters from the courtroom and left several jurors in tears.
</P>
<P>
   It capped a day of dramatic testimony and evidence, including
the reading of Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr.'s own writings in which
he boasted to co-defendant John William ``Bill'' King that they had
a 70 percent chance of getting away with the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our word against (co-defendant) Shawn Berry's,'' Brewer
wrote in a note intercepted by jailers at the Jasper County Jail
shortly after the three white men were arrested. ``Be for real.
What's the worst they can possibly do? Pull prints off a 20-foot
rusty ass log chain?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at O.J.,'' he added. ``He beat his case so nothing's
imposs (sic) my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they couldn't avoid conviction, Brewer indicated that he
and his fellow racist would die as martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A life sentence wood (sic) do us no justice,'' he wrote. ``I
say we fight to the very last breath of air and last drop of blood
left in us, Bro, for history's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes, Bro, the way I see it, I wood (sic) much better be
taken out like this than to be in some fatal accident (fire, wreck,
drown),'' he continued. ``The way I picture it is all it will be is
a little o' little sleepin' medicine to slowly cary (sic) us out of
this land of the free and home of the brave ... Plus we
accomplished more than most ever dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, prosecutors pulled a 25-foot logging chain across the
courtroom, dropping it loudly on the floor. As several of Byrd's
sisters wiped away tears, witnesses testified that they believed it
was the chain that was wound around Byrd's ankles before the
disabled black man was dragged behind a pickup more than three
miles down a rural Jasper County road June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI agent testified that Brewer's DNA was found on a Bud
Light bottle and a cigarette butt found at the crime scene, and
that Byrd's blood was found on Brewer's Nike tennis shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors rested their case and jurors were sent home for the
day after watching an 11-minute silent video following the trail of
Byrd's gruesome death. Jurors and spectators in the hushed
courtroom were riveted, as was Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Byrd's sisters and his ex-wife were crying as they
walked toward the parking lot with their arms around each other.
They left without talking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Byrd's sister, Betty Boatner, said that
seeing the chain and listening to the graphic testimony made it a
hard day for the family. Prosecutors had warned them that they
would show the chain Thursday morning, so Boatner took a seat at
the back of the courtroom instead of the front row where she has
been sitting with her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting there thinking, why would anyone hook someone up
to a chain like that?'' she said. ``It's unbelievable to me _ and
it's unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, Louis Berry, the 26-year-old brother of Shawn
Berry, testified that he had been turned off by King and Brewer
reliving their prison days, even going so far as to eat as they did
in prison even though they had access to a variety of food in the
free world.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was offended by King and Brewer's racist talk.
Asked whether his brother had also used racist words, Louis Berry
replied: ``No. We weren't brought up that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, asked by Assistant U.S. Attorney Johnny Stevens, who is
assisting Jasper County prosecutors, what kind of people would
chain Byrd to a pickup and drag him nearly three miles until his
head came off, Louis Berry answered: ``They're definitely racists.
I don't know any other way to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's defense attorney, Doug Barlow, then asked, ``Would that
include your brother, Shawn Berry?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he participated in it,'' Louis Berry said. ``If he went out
there with the intention of doing that and he actually did it, then
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Barlow and co-counsel Layne Walker, both of Beaumont, will have
the opportunity to address jurors Friday in an opening statement
and call witnesses if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   If Brewer is convicted, he would face life in prison or death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   King was convicted by a Jasper jury last February and sentenced
to death. Berry will be tried later this year in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
