<HEADLINE>
YOU SAY SPEND, I SAY SAVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After reading my column in the spring about how couples handle
money discussions during courtship, many people asked me how young
couples should cope with money matters once they are married or
otherwise solidly committed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good question, especially if you think, as Gertrude Stein
did, that ``whoever said money can't buy happiness didn't know
where to shop,'' while your beloved scrimps and saves for
retirement (or vice versa).
</P>
<P>
   Such dissonance, of course, can result in financial fisticuffs,
so serious discourse is needed.
</P>
<P>
   A few months before Scott Collins, a sales manager at Midwest
Publishing Inc. in Phoenix, got married, he and his fiancee,
Sharon, had a little heart to heart. She carried credit card debt,
which drove him nuts.
</P>
<P>
   He told her that aside from maintaining a mortgage, he never
wanted to be in debt _ that he had to pay bills in full every
month. ``My thinking is, if I can't afford it, then don't spend
it,'' Collins, 29, said. ``I'd much rather start saving money now
and retire younger. She'd rather live for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   She complied _ to a point. Ms. Collins, 27, a senior brand
specialist at Tosco, the gas station and convenience store company,
controls the household finances and pays the credit card bills on
time and in full. But she goes just a little over budget on
clothing and travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different from what I would do,'' Collins said. ``I panic
sometimes _ `What if we can't pay our mortgage?' _ but she works
just as much as I do, she makes money, and I'm not going to tell
her what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is one of the main things couples fight about. Part of the
problem may be the varying perceptions about money and work. For
some, it's all about security; for others, better immediate living.
Such differences help explain why, in many couples, one partner
thinks more about longer-term financial goals.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah and Wes McBride, moved from Los Angeles to Manhattan last
year. They had more than $10,000 in credit card debt and stayed
with a friend because they couldn't afford their own place. They
wanted to save enough to rent an apartment and eventually buy one.
</P>
<P>
   So they got Quicken, the financial planning software, and
painfully budgeted for everything _ even their daily tea excursions
to Starbucks. The goal was to pay off all debts and buy a home in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lay in bed and sobbed,'' said Ms. McBride, 25, an executive
assistant at an architectural firm and the couple's primary
breadwinner. ``No sushi for four years. I can't live like this.''
</P>
<P>
   So McBride, 30, a freelance set designer, revamped the budget,
this time allowing for the occasional movie or California roll.
``Sarah's very upset by restrictions,'' he said. ``She feels that
we're making money and we deserve to spend it. I agree with that to
an extent, but I also feel that you have to prepare for the
unknown. Sarah likes to go out to eat, and I think you can cook at
home. So we talk about it, yell, and then come to an agreement we
can both live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Feitelberg, a financial adviser with Chase Investment
Services in Manhattan, urges couples to accept their differences
and have several bank accounts: a joint one for household needs
and, if there's money left over, separate ones for individual
wants. But, she cautioned, both parties should know where all the
records are.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if something happens to one person and the other doesn't
know where the information is?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of procreation. Since a new child adds,
on average, about $8,500 to a couple's annual overhead, Ms.
Feitelberg said, the partners should begin putting money into a
mutual fund as soon as possible to help pay the added expenses.
</P>
<P>
   They should also coordinate their investments, making sure, for
example, that their 401(k)s, considered together, have appropriate
levels of risk, growth potential and diversification.
</P>
<P>
   But above all else, it's important to take time to relax and
enjoy things, as Collins is learning to do. ``Every time we go on a
trip, I think, `Why am I doing this? We can't afford it,''' he
said. ``But afterward I think, `I'm glad I went; I had a great
time.' At some point, you've just got to stop worrying and live.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin is a Manhattan writer. Her column on starting out in
the world of money appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
preludes(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
