<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-BARR-T     09-16 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-BARR-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
And MAX B. BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ |Running on two hours of sleep, Fort Worth
Mayor Kenneth Barr cut short a trip to Mexico on Thursday to
comfort a city shocked by violence and to tell children that it is
safe to go to church and school.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, the city's mayor since May 1996, sought advice from
another Fort Worth native, Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, and spent the
afternoon with Texas Gov. George W. Bush visiting survivors of the
city's worst mass shooting ever. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less than three hours after returning to Fort Worth from Toluca,
Mexico, Barr and his wife, Karen, faced more than 13 television
crews and a horde of national news reporters at 12:07 p.m. at the
police and fire training center near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Barr urged children not to be afraid in the wake of the
killings. Police administrators praised nearly 300 volunteers who
regularly patrol their southwest Fort Worth neighborood and
emphasized that reported crime has declined 53 percent since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let one senseless act of violence define
who we are as a city,'' Barr said. ``People really responded.
That's who we are. We are not that gunman.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr had been in Toluca, a Fort Worth sister city, for a
bicentennial celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Barr carried with him a legal pad with
advice from Owens, who had to deal with a similar shooting near
Littleton, Colo. The two leaders talked by phone in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the most critical thing was dealing with the community
once you get past the initial phase of getting the information
out,'' Barr said. ``He said, `You need to project calmness and the
perception that the community is coming together.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived by private jet at Fort Worth's Meacham Airport
about 1:45 p.m. from Michigan, where he was campaigning for the
Republican presidential nomination. The governor scrapped two
fundraisers and said he and his wife, Laura, plan to attend a city
memorial service Sunday ``on bended knee.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stopped at John Peter Smith Hospital to visit with victims,
Southwest High School to reach out to students, and the home of the
church's pastor.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly poignant moment came when Bush met with Justin
Laird, a young football player from White Settlement paralyzed in
the shooting. The governor fought back tears, and later cried at
the pastor's house, Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are looking at a 16-year-old football player who is
paralyzed, there is not much to say,'' Bush said. ``We saw a little
boy with a great football career ahead of him who now can't play.
It's hard to do anything but to say I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he, too, was humbled by the hospital visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to talk to people who have massive bandages
on their chests,'' the mayor said. ``I spoke to all of them, but
there's not a lot you can say. I told them, `You need to know there
are a lot of people out there praying for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush focused on compassion, not politics, his visit had
political overtones. Bush signed a 1995 law allowing Texans to
carry concealed weapons with a permit. Democrats question his
commitment to federal and state efforts to require background
checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are loopholes in the laws, let's close them. If there
are laws on the books, let's enforce them,'' Bush said. ``I wish I
knew the law to make people love one another. We'd pass it in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   At Southwest High School, Bush, Barr and U.S. Rep. Kay Granger,
R-Fort Worth, met with four students and about 20 teachers,
counselors and school administrators. One teen told Bush that she
had seen classmates once considered enemies clutching each other
and crying in the school hallway.
</P>
<P>
   School nurse Ann Tomme said the governor's visit helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them acknowledgment of what has happened,'' Tomme
said.
</P>
<P>
   By 4:25 p.m., Barr and Bush had joined a prayer group inside the
home of Al Meredith, pastor of Wedgwood Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pretty shaken up. One man I talked to said he dodged
five bullets and his wife was standing in front of him. He didn't
know how she survived,'' Barr recalled. ``That really drove it home
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bush: ``This is an example of where someone's heart became
so full of hatred and evil that he would walk into a church and
randomly kill people. This is a time for us to recognize that it
requires a higher authority to heal the hate that exists in some
people's hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
