<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CHURCH-BUSH-HNS &LR;      09-16 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CALLS TEXAS SHOOTINGS AN `EXAMPLE OF ONE SICK PERSON' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R..G. RATCLIFFE 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush cut short a presidential
campaign trip to Michigan on Thursday because of the shootings at a
Fort Worth church. But his position on gun control was largely
unchanged because he said ``there is no government law that will
eradicate hate and evil.``
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of one sick person,'' Bush said after
visiting with shooting victims and their families. ``This is an
example of where someone's heart became so full of hatred and evil
that he would walk into a church and randomly kill people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this instance, I don't know if government could have done
something to prevent this man from walking into a church,'' said
Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gene Ashbrook, 47, described as an eccentric loner, opened
fire inside Wedgewood Baptist Church on Wednesday during a service
for teen-agers, killing seven people and himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth shooting was the latest in a string of deadly
mass shootings this year. The random shootings _ occurring in
California, Colorado, Georgia, Kentucky and Louisiana _ have killed
dozens of people and wounded more than two dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had begun a campaign swing Wednesday in Michigan. The Texas
governor visited an elementary school in Grand Rapids as planned,
but then canceled several Michigan events, including two
fund-raisers and a state Republican get-together, to return to Fort
Worth. Bush was criticized recently for canceling an
elementary-school visit in Rhode Island because of bad weather, but
later attending a fund-raiser there.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also canceled plans to attend a motor car race in New
Hampshire on Sunday so he can attend church in Fort Worth. His
wife, Laura, also scrubbed her campaign schedule. Earlier this
week, Bush had to postpone a major speech on defense policy in
South Carolina because of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush stuck to his general anti-gun-control stance, he
told reporters in Grand Rapids, ``I really think we should make
sure people who are mentally deranged should not have guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added, however, that passing laws can only accomplish so
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a wave of evil passing through America
now,'' he said.``And as a society we can pass laws and hold people
accountable for decisions they make, but our hopes and prayers have
got to be that there is more love in our society.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush met first with relatives of Ashbrook's victims at John
Peter Smith Hospital before visiting Southwest High School, which
some victims had attended. Bush later met privately with Wedgewood
Baptist Church pastor Al Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters at the school that he returned to Fort Worth
to offer his condolences to the city, not gain political points in
his presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right thing for me to be here,'' Bush said. ``I can't
heal the wounds. But maybe I can comfort one person. Maybe I can
thank one teacher. This is a serious situation that is going to
affect this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr said if Bush had not rushed home
the question would be: ``Why isn't he here?''
</P>
<P>
   After his high school news conference, Bush met and joked with
many of the teen-agers gathered around him who had not been
involved in the shooting. He posed smiling for one picture when a
girl said it was for the high school yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   Before departing Michigan, and again in Texas, he was peppered
with questions about gun control, a hot-button issue that has
caused a headache for many Republicans who have been reluctant to
alienate their supporters while at the same time addressing this
year's shooting sprees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no law _ I wish we could pass it. I would sign it. _
that says people will love one another,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, another Republican presidential candidate who has
become the standard-bearer for social conservatives, suggested the
latest mass shooting revealed a pattern of crimes against religious
people and urged the Justice Department to study the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have criticized Bush for pushing through a law in
Texas that allowed licensed citizens to carry concealed weapons and
for his decision not to urge the Texas Legislature to close a
loophole that allows firearm purchases at gun shows without
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended Texas's concealed weapons law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a dangerous society, and if people want to protect
themselves, law-abiding citizens want to protect themselves, they
should be allowed to do so,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, the governor has largely echoed the
National Rifle Association position that the problem is not the
lack of tough gun control laws but the failure of authorities to
enforce the current regulation.
</P>
<P>
   He has endorsed a number of minor changes now before Congress,
including closing the loophole that allows guns to be purchased at
gun shows without a background check, and has said he supports the
ban on automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential
front-runner, however, pushed once again for more gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing this week's East Coast hurricane and the shooting,
Gore said, ``There are differences between these two tragedies. A
hurricane is something we can't do anything about. It's an act of
God. but the shooting is something that people do to people.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has after the nation's other recent mass shootings, Gore
lamented the easy access troubled people have to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know that the availability of assault weapons and deadly
weapons in the hands of people who shouldn't have them contribute
to ... having these things over and over again,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He called for requiring licenses for handgun purchases, closing
the gun-show loophole, re-establishing the three-day waiting period
for handgun purchases, requiring child-safety trigger locks,
raising the age of purchase and toughening the penalties for giving
guns to those who should not have them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush once again chided the Clinton administration for not
adequately funding gun-control enforcement programs. Bush also said
that he did not regret that he did not more strongly urge the Texas
Legislature this year to approve a measure requiring background
checks of those who buy handguns at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush initially said he supported the proposal, Texas
lawmakers said he did not lobby for its passage. It was killed by a
Texas House committee.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said a toughened state law would not do any good
until the federal government allows unlicensed dealers who work at
gun shows access to computerized background checks.
</P>
<P>
   While the governor acknowledged the need for some gun control
laws, he preferred to focus on the moral dimensions of the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can pass laws. But there needs to be a higher law and that
is love your neighbor like you love yourself,'' he said.``I
recognize that hate and evil lurk in people's heart and there is no
government law that will eradicate hate and evil. That is going to
require a higher authority, much higher than a humble governor.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
