<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-NEWREPORT17-COX     09-16 1666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NEWREPORT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corrupt Olympic bid system to blame for excessive gift-giving,
officials say
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Olympics officials took the offensive Thursday
in the Olympic vote-peddling scandal and portrayed themselves as
victims in a shady system fostered by the International Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Attorney General Griffin Bell and Atlanta Olympic
Chief Billy Payne characterized the effort to host the 1996 Summer
Games as good intentions awash in a wink-and-nod game that
encouraged favor-trading and frequent rule-bending.
</P>
<P>
   In a revised report to Congress, Bell portrayed the Atlanta bid
team members as being tangled in a pattern of excessive gift-giving
and offers of scholarships and job assistance, athletic training
and free health care for IOC members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Bell painted a picture of a perverted Olympic bid process that
exploits cities eager to land an enormous prize worth
``incalculable prestige and potentially billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   He cast the Atlanta Olympic bid team as innocent in an
adulterated courtship that ``encouraged a practice of lobbying IOC
members in which excess was inherent.''
</P>
<P>
   The stance represented a remarkable change of tone by Olympic
officials, who had previously labeled IOC members as friends to
whom they were simply extending Southern hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta group were neophytes,'' Bell said at a news
conference that coincided with the release of the report. ``They
had never been in a contest like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantans were enticed to play along because, although they
had the best technical bid among the six competing cities for the
1996 host role, that wasn't enough, Bell said. ``The votes were not
necessarily cast on the merits.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition, he said, took place in a ``system known to
welcome generous gifts and travel allowances, lavish hospitality
and personal accommodations.''
</P>
<P>
   Since a vote-buying scandal erupted in Salt Lake City in
November, Payne has maintained that the bid team was guilty of no
wrongdoing. Payne contended Thursday that his group ``never
believed for one minute any of our actions or conduct were
improper.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Payne offered an apology to Atlanta for any shame the
drawn-out investigation has caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in our enthusiastic pursuit of the Games, if by our
aggressive marketing, we have embarrassed any of the wonderful
volunteers and citizens of this community who have worked so hard
to make these Games so successful,'' he said, ``we apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a prominent attorney for the King &AMP; Spalding law firm that
represents the Atlanta Olympic group, offered no apology. Instead,
he blamed the IOC for encouraging the no-holds-barred competition
among bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite simply, the competition for the right to host these
Games was in large part about out-lobbying the competition,'' Bell
wrote in his revision of an earlier report to the U.S. House
Commerce Committee, which is investigating the Atlanta lobbying
campaign. ``The name of the game was to get the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   While the IOC had rules in place to limit gift-giving and
travel, Bell said they were ``often ignored, never enforced _ and
all the participants knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials could not be reached for comment Thursday. Earlier
this week, IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber deflected the
blame toward Atlanta bidders, saying they ``pushed those favors and
gifts onto the IOC members under the pretext of friendship.'' He
contended the delegates ``were not used to this systematic approach
to lobbying.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell acknowledged that an earlier report to Congress, signed by
Payne and former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, was inaccurate and
incomplete. The number of gifts that violated the $200 limit was
nearly double what was originally reported, Bell conceded.
</P>
<P>
   The former federal judge was called upon to amend the report
after federal investigators found numerous discrepancies between
Payne and Young's account and materials in 78 boxes of Olympic bid
documents. They estimated the bid group underreported its
expenditures on gifts for IOC members by $92,000 and omitted about
50 trips for members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's improprieties were not as excessive as Salt Lake
City's and probably did not come close to the extravagances of its
competition for the 1996 Games, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers in Salt Lake City plied IOC members with $1.2 million
in cash and scholarships in trying to land the 2002 Winter
Olympics, prompting an overhaul of the bid process and the
resignation or expulsion of 10 members of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Bell pointed out that Atlanta received only 19 of 86 IOC votes
on the first ballot for the '96 Games. One city was eliminated in
each round of voting, and Atlanta did not take the lead until the
final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either we're the world's worst salesmen or there was severe
competition going on from other cities,'' he said. ``We have no way
to investigate other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell neglected to note that most IOC members vote for the
candidate city in their own region in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Bell admitted the bid team provided many more unreported gifts
that cost more than a $403 camera and $124 in batteries for the
member from the Ivory Coast, a $273 sports jacket for the Russian
member and a $1,000 Georgia pine bowl given to the Swedish delegate
by his Atlanta hosts, Mack and Mary Rose Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Bell also acknowledged numerous shopping sprees conducted by
volunteer hostesses in which many gifts were purchased for members
and their wives at upscale stores.
</P>
<P>
   One such spree netted $1,493 in clothing, cosmetics and
toiletries for two visitors from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   When General Francis Nyangweso from Uganda lost his luggage, the
bid team spent $1,413 on clothing and a sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Pirjo Haggman of Finland, who brought her husband and two young
children with her to Atlanta, received $1,300 in clothing, makeup,
toys and books. The bid team also paid a magician $150 to entertain
her children while their mother toured Olympic venues.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell insisted the gifts and shopping sprees were customary
in the Olympic bid environment, despite written rules to the
contrary. ``We don't think the International Olympic Committee has
ever questioned anybody about the size of gifts or ever sanctioned
anyone or reprimanded anyone for any kind of gift,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Payne still contended the Atlantans ``believed we were
playing by the rules and regulations and guidelines as we
understood them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said the bid records revealed 10 instances where the bid
team gave cash, checks or wire payments to IOC members. While there
was no documentation indicating what these payments were for, Bell
said he believed they were reimbursement for first-class plane
tickets purchased by the IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Bell confirmed the bid team compiled profiles on IOC members
that indicated some could be wooed by ``extending sexual favors.''
But he said he found no evidence the team paid for or provided
sexual favors.
</P>
<P>
   Bell delivered the report Wednesday to Rep. Thomas Bliley
(R-Va.), chairman of the U.S. Commerce Committee, and Rep. Fred
Upton (R-Mich.), chairman of the subcommittee on oversight and
investigations, which is spearheading the inquiry into the Atlanta
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional committee is considering legislation to bring
the International Olympic Committee under the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act. The report on Atlanta's activities appears to fuel
that effort, they say.
</P>
<P>
   After reading Bell's report, Upton said Thursday, ``What has
emerged is a pattern of troubling and disturbing events in order to
secure these Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said he hoped lawmakers would examine the report and then
end the investigation, but that's not likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.), ranking Democrat on the Commerce
Committee, said Thursday the report would have to be reviewed ``by
the relevant law enforcement authorities to close out this sorry
chapter of Olympic history.''
</P>
<P>
   Some laws may have been broken, although the statute of
limitations may have passed. Bell conceded the bid team violated
federal trade embargoes in delivering some gifts. A carburetor kit
and brake pads were given to the IOC member from Libya, and a live
bulldog to an IOC member from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   A shotgun and case, which cost $400, were given to a national
Olympic committee official from Ghana, who couldn't legally
purchase the gun himself because he was a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   Two bid team members transported $15,500 in cash into the United
States at the request of the IOC member from Jamaica. Their action
may have violated a law that requires travelers to file a
declaration if they enter the country with at least $10,000 in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a legitimate reason the money was (delivered),'' Bell
said. ``It was not laundering money for drug pushers, that sort of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said the Olympic bid team would make available to the
public eight boxes of documents they have contended were personal
and had fiercely guarded from public inspection. The boxes contain
the more salacious dossiers compiled on the IOC members, as well as
notes written by Atlanta hostesses and drivers about their guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new disclosures are an important chapter in Atlanta
history in that the public will now have a chance to examine and
judge for themselves,'' said Peter Canfield, attorney for The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper and WSB-TV had sought a court ruling that the
Olympic records were subject to Georgia Open Records laws and
should be made accessible to the public. A judge has yet to rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in the boxes is in the report. It's all out now,'' Bell
said. ``Whatever is in there is in there. Whatever has happened has
happened. Whatever has been done is done. And this is the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
