A5205 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-GUNMAN     09-16 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-GUNMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORS, ACQUAINTANCES REMEMBER A STRANGE, ALOOF MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Conspiracy consumed Larry Gene Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   His brother called him a paranoid schizophrenic this summer and
took up a loaded 12-gauge shotgun to keep Ashbrook away from his
Wise County home.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook exploded in violent rages in his Forest Hill
neighborhood, railing against children, life and his now-deceased
father.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook's writings blame a vague, vast conspiracy _ which he
thought included the military's special forces and the CIA _ for
his inability to keep a job. The conspirators, he wrote, tried to
implicate him as a serial killer of women in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But as bizarre as his lifelong behavior was, few believed the
cigarette-smoking loner could have caused such devastating carnage
Wednesday at Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth. Ashbrook opened
fire at the church, fatally shooting seven people and wounding
seven others before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question in my mind is, why such a vicious attack on
such innocent people?'' homicide Detective Curt Brannan said. ``I
don't know if we will ever know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to those questions has eluded investigators, grieving
families and a city unaccustomed to such unbridled hate. Witnesses
said the man in sunglasses, a dark green jacket, jeans and white
hat spewed blasphemous words at the people inside the sanctuary,
belittling their belief in God, hymns and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   This from a man whose deeply religious father contributed up to
10 percent of his income to his church in Arlington, a Fort Worth
suburb. And who, hours before the mass slaying, ripped the family
Bible apart page by page, sliced family members out of photographs
and used a shovel to hack large family portraits, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook, 47, the youngest of four children of Jack Ashbrook and
Ethel Muriel Ashbrook, was born in Fort Worth and attended Forest
Oak Middle School, Polytechnic High School, O.D. Wyatt High School
and Tarrant County College.
</P>
<P>
   Some high school acquaintances recalled Ashbrook, an art club
member, as someone who hung out with a group of other teens at
Trinity Park.
</P>
<P>
   Adults said Ashbrook was a troubled child while growing up in
Forest Hill, a Fort Worth suburb. He even forced one small girl in
the neighborhood to eat bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived next door to the Ashbrooks. I remember his mom, and
he had a sister in a wheelchair,'' said Jane Lane, 38, of Burleson,
a Fort Worth suburb. ``He used to make my sister eat roly-polies.
He was always kind of a strange kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook was arrested in 1971 on suspicion of marijuana
possession, but charges were never filed, police records show.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Ashbrook moved to Jacksonville, Fla. in the
late 1970s to work for the Navy, military officials confirmed. He
never married or had children.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook moved back to Texas about 1994, four years or so after
his mother died. In July, his 85-year-old father died.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook seemed to decline into more bizarre and violent
behavior after his father died, acquaintances and police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook's older brother, Aaron Ashbrook, called the Wise County
Sheriff's Department on July 24, saying that his younger brother
``is a paranoid schizophrenic.''
</P>
<P>
   Homicide Detective Mike Carroll, the lead detective in the
church slayings, said Aaron Ashbrook told Fort Worth police
Thursday that he has no idea why his brother opened fire on
churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew nothing about any psychological disorder, nothing
about his hatred for religion,'' Carroll said. ``He talked about
the fact that his brother thought there was a conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County Mental Health/Mental Retardation has no history
of Ashbrook receiving treatment at any county or state facility,
said Shelley Buttgen, an MHMR spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   A former employer said he vaguely remembers Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was all mixed up,'' said W.I. Spitler, former owner of
Photo Etch in Fort Worth. ``As far as we were concerned, we
couldn't get rid of him quick enough''.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors said Ashbrook rarely spoke with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry would give me these looks that I can't explain,'' said
Venita Hord, who lives across the street. She recalled one incident
several years ago when Ashbrook became upset because he thought
people in the neighborhood were talking about him. She said he
exposed himself to her and shouted obscenities at her and other
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   He was meticulous with the yard around his home, even pruning
and tending to pear trees in his back yard three hours before his
rampage at Wedgwood Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed ironic to investigators searching his Forest Hill home
_ where his family had lived for more than 40 years _ that he took
the time to tend his yard after destroying the inside of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared as someone in that house was in a violent rage,''
Brannan said. ``This person destroyed and shredded what many people
would cherish: family photos, possessions of deceased loved ones,
the holy Scriptures.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
