<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-BAHAMAS-NYT     09-16 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BAHAMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING FLOYD'S IMPACT IN THE BAHAMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABACO ISLAND, the Bahamas _ William Morris Bain walked barefoot
and somberly Thursday through his house, where the tile floors were
slick and silty from the surge of sea water that swept inside when
Hurricane Floyd struck. Outside, piles of debris were all that
remained of his tool shop and storehouse. The rushing water had
also ripped through his two sons' homes next door, where their
wives now hanged damp clothes to dry on a fallen tree trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't going to be no drying,'' he said as he showed a
visitor a waterlogged mattress. ``We got to start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of his 65 years, Bain has worked the seas, hauling in
fish and lobster to feed restaurant diners and the family around
his dinner table. Was this some sort of watery payback, he
wondered. ``I don't know whose revenge it is,'' he said. ``But
whatever it is, it's serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The eye of the hurricane zipped through many of the towns along
this island, which is home to humble fishing villages and upscale
resorts. While physical injuries were almost unheard of, hundreds
of trees were uprooted, shingles and entire roofs were sheared off,
sections of roads were washed away, and power and phone lines went
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Several towns on Little Abaco Island appeared especially hard
hit. From Cedar Harbour to Foxtown, cars and boats were strewn
about, roads were covered with dirt and rocks, and several houses
were completely blown out. A radio tower lay crumbled near palm
trees that were bent sideways like pipe-cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Three helicopters sent by the United States ferried U.S. and
Bahamian officials to outlying islands that were in the eye of the
hurricane. While relieved at finding hardly any casualties, they
also realized that repairs to homes and public services would
present enough of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a country this size, it truly can be a financial
disaster,'' said U.S. Ambassador Arthur Schechter, who had also
visited several islands on Wednesday with Prime Minister Hubert
Ingraham. ``The damage to the infrastructure is so extensive, from
what I've seen, I would say it runs into the tens of millions of
dollars. In a country like this, that's devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Houses in some areas withstood the winds only to be swamped by
water. Bruce Lightbourne, a lobster fisherman who lives near the
narrow, southern part of Abaco, said the lower floor of his
split-level home was filled with water, and his car was still
submerged in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere, there is water damage, from sea to sea,'' he said.
``We're on a little peninsula, only two miles wide at most. The
wind came out of the northeast and blew the water into the swamp.
After that, it just took over.''
</P>
<P>
   On Moore's Island, about 20 miles west of Great Abaco, small
fishing boats were sent into front porches, and chunks of roadway
crumbled. Many wooden homes were reduced to pastel piles of planks
covered with musky sea grass, and about 50 families have been left
homeless and doubled up with friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the brunt of the storm,'' said Thomas Hugh, who lives
in the aptly named neighborhood of Hard Bargain. He spent part of
the storm driving people to shelter in his pickup truck. ``I was in
my apartment when the storm was coming, and something said, go,''
he said. ``I drove to my son's house and got him to leave. Ten
minutes later, the roof was gone from his house. We went to the
church for shelter, but even there, part of the roof came off.''
</P>
<P>
   In the resort community of Turtle Cay, residents were still
trying to hack their way through the trees that had blocked their
driveways and fallen on some homes.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Goddard, a businessman from San Diego, had come here to
replace the roof on his vacation home that had been destroyed by
Hurricane Dennis. He and his wife were stranded on the island when
the airport was closed Monday, though he had a plane waiting to
take them home. Instead, they took shelter at a friend's house,
which nonetheless proved frightening when the shutters were torn
off and four people struggled to prop themselves against a mattress
and box spring to blot out the withering winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roof was heaving like somebody was breathing on it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The question for many residents and business owners now is how
much and how fast can they rebuild. Some said they were hoping for
reduced duties on imported supplies and construction materials, and
easing of restrictions on foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be open for the millennium,'' said David Phillips, who
owns the Bluff House Beach Hotel. ``We have three months. We hope
the government will aid us. To get money to come in, we got to get
tourists to come. If we sit and wait six months, everybody will be
starving. Except the construction workers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
