</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE LOSING POWER AFTER GLANCING N.C. COASTLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 4th graf with updated fatalities; deletes
original 9th graf; inserts new 9th-11th grafs, bgng On St.
Michael's...)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ The heart of Hurricane Floyd raked across the
mainland here at Cape Fear Thursday morning, uprooting beach houses
and leaving widespread floods as it set a rapid but steadily
weakening course up the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   The vast storm, whose advent alarmed much of the Eastern
seaboard and widely disrupted air, rail and highway travel, was
clearly losing its power with the dawn Thursday as the hurricane's
eye danced across the coastline following a two-week buildup of the
forces of nature and the precautions of government.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday evening, as Floyd reached northeastward along the
New Jersey coast to New York City, its strength had further waned.
It was downgraded to a tropical storm that still delivered lashing
rain but that officials said presented no major threat to New York
or other population centers.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 deaths were attributed to Floyd. Seven people died
in traffic in the Carolinas and Virginia and two girls in Delaware
drowned after a storm-swollen creek swept them into a sewage pipe.
One man was presumed drowned in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   In the howling predawn of this coastal city, Floyd's power was
measured to be dropping from a Category 4 to a Category 2 hurricane
before dropping further to a tropical storm. While storm-drenched
hurricane veterans were delighted after all the ominous evacuation
warnings that it delivered far less physical injury and property
destruction than originally feared, Floyd nevertheless proved
relentlessly drenching, dropping as much as 19 inches of rain in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were blessed this time,'' Fire Chief Keith Studt said as he
roamed flooded streets and hacked away at fallen trees cluttering
the streets of nearby Winter Park. ``We were lucky this thing
suddenly ratcheted down before it hit town.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the flooding and house damage out on Oak Island and
other coastal barrier islands was considerable as the storm headed
unpredictably northward, causing further disruption across a wide
swath of the seaboard. Residents emerged uncertainly here from
emergency centers to blink at piles of suddenly sun-dappled debris.
By then Floyd was speeding up along the coast by Virginia,
Chesapeake Bay and the New Jersey shore.
</P>
<P>
   It lost further power but still spewed fresh damage along its
western flank as the storm was described as fading into a rough
course aimed toward eastern Long Island. But travel turmoil was
widespread during the day and quickly became bumper to bumper
around Washington, as a truck overturned on the storm-lashed
Chesapeake Bay Bridge and blocked one of the major regional
arteries.
</P>
<P>
   On St. Michael's, a resort and retirement village on an
elbowlike peninsula reaching into Chesapeake Bay, the day's rain
and winds started turning savage in midafternoon as the eye of the
storm approached.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Murphy is a netter, who fishes with nets attached to
poles. He left two, $10,000 polenets standing in the bay, where he
assumed they would be safe from a northeaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's coming from the northwest,'' Murphy said. He said his
nets had withstood 40-mph winds. ``But this was 60 or 70,'' he
said, figuring his rigs were lost. ``The netters are caught real
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm's eye loomed out of the Atlantic's 30-foot seas as a
somewhat tentative invader, avoiding a deep inland attack and
cutting across Cape Fear at 3:20 a.m. to begin a rapid ride up the
coastline. Open relief at the turning was the reaction from this
storm-hardened city, which has had to batten down for five
hurricanes in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was merciful that it didn't come through at the 155 mph
they were first talking about,'' said James Blanton, hitching his
pickup truck's chain to a tree fallen across the road to his
granddaughter's house. ``That's what saved us, even with all this
flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the storm registered sustained winds of 98 mph that
gusted up to 130, tearing up the roof of the Brunswick County
Hospital to the south. There was some roof damage as well to
Wilmington's historic Cotton Exchange building, which is now a
shopping mall centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   One unnerving accident was the draining of 2 million gallons
from a hog waste lagoon into the Northeast Cape Fear River, about
40 miles to the north.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise the storm caused minimal structural damage here,
as in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The old buildings of downtown Charleston shrugged off lashing
wind and rain, as many have there for two centuries. ``These old
houses have seen a lot worse,'' said Park Smith, wielding a saw to
create fresh firewood from a fallen tree near South Battery Street.
</P>
<P>
   Charleston suffered little more than $10 million in damage,
according to the county director of building services, Carl
Simmons. ``Very, very minor,'' he declared. Other residents said
Floyd would be remembered for the convoys of rain-slickered
television anchormen who hit the beaches more than for the actual
glancing blow the storm delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Down the coast in Myrtle Beach, S.C., wind damage was minimal
but flooding was severe along the coastal Grand Strand. Safety
workers had to deal with snakes fleeing to dry ground and drivers
determined to ford passages left obviously risky with coursing
flood water. National Guardsmen audibly cursed one driver who
ventured blithely ever deeper into a flooded crossing in his pickup
truck. Suddenly, the driver, his wife and daughter had to be
rescued when the truck was swept away.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he made the attempt, the driver, Ralph Elem,
personified the sense of happy adventure that seemed part of the
local post-hurricane mood. ``For the heck of it,'' Elem replied.
``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The main effect here from Floyd was a relentless 34-hour record
rainfall of 19.06 inches that spilled beyond drainage ditches,
flooded houses and blocked major crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen water like this,'' said Donald Squires as he
paddled in a rowboat down the road to his house, which he found
sitting high and mostly dry in outlying Delco. ``This sure ain't
another Hazel, not the way my father always talked,'' he said of
the 1954 hurricane that set this city's benchmark for death and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   As he roamed in the sunlight that followed the storm, Fire Chief
Studt was openly grateful that Floyd never lived up to the advance
billing. ''But, hey, we got another one coming next week,'' he
quickly added, his eye out for an evolving storm called Gert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-ANALYSIS17-COX     09-16 2060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ANALYSIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report acknowledges `many gifts'
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Griffin Bell's revised report to Congress attempts to
provide a more complete picture of the extreme means the Atlanta
Olympic bid team used to land the 1996 Centennial Games.
</P>
<P>
   He said the original report, signed by Atlanta bid chairman
Billy Payne and former Mayor Andrew Young, was incomplete because
they didn't have much time to pull it together.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said Thursday his report was not intended to be
comprehensive. ``It was a best effort by a lot of good folks in a
short period of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The revised report contains no evidence that Atlanta's bid
activity was as excessive as that of the Salt Lake City team. But,
in a letter to two congressional committees, he wrote, ``What the
evidence does show is that Atlanta volunteers gave many gifts and
were eager to accommodate IOC members.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a breakdown of Bell's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts and shopping
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic culture of gift-giving has raised more eyebrows and
received more criticism than any other aspect of the lobbying
process. It's a system former Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell labeled ``gift creep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell headed an ethics commission that investigated the Salt
Lake City scandal and came to the conclusion that the city's
misconduct was ``part of a broader culture of improper gift-giving
in which candidate cities provided things of value to IOC members
in an effort to buy their votes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from Bell's report that this culture was alive and
flourishing in Atlanta. And it was vastly underreported in Payne
and Young's initial account to Congress. In that report, they
identified 38 gifts valued at more than the $200 limit set by the
IOC.
</P>
<P>
   In his research, Bell found a total of 64, including a $948
carburetor kit for the Libyan member, $318 in antique surgical
instruments for the now-deceased IOC member from Cameroon and a
$365 antique compass for the member from Denmark. Steuben glass,
china and crystal sculptures were common gifts.
</P>
<P>
   These gifts were ``carefully selected to please the tastes of an
individual IOC member or that member's relatives or friends,'' Bell
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said two of the gifts may have been illegal. A live bulldog
and a carburetor to the IOC delegates from Cuba and Libya,
respectively, may have violated a U.S. embargo on both countries.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the report acknowledged for the first time the
shopping sprees in which IOC members and their wives were escorted
through the city's malls and upscale specialty stores to collect an
assortment of gifts _ paid for by their hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and Young denied knowledge of ``shopping sprees'' in their
original report to Congress, just as they denied them when such
rumors first emerged in the German press in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   One such shopping spree for Agustin Arroyo and his wife from
Ecuador netted $331 in trinkets such as a belt, makeup, sewing
supplies, drugstore items and toys. The Smirnovs of Russia took
home $861 in clothing, makeup, sporting goods and a sports jacket
after two visits to the city and two shopping trips, compliments of
the bid team. Pirjo Haggman of Finland received $1,300 in clothing,
makeup, toys and books in one visit with her husband and children.
And the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Other accommodations
</P>
<P>
   The bid team was nothing if not accommodating. It acknowledged
providing help to IOC members seeking business opportunities, visas
for entry into the country and used MARTA buses for one country.
</P>
<P>
   Two bid team members carried $15,500 in cash into the United
States from Jamaica at the behest of the IOC member from that
country. The members divided the cash between them to avoid having
to declare the money to U.S. Customs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody asked us to do a favor, we would do it,'' Bell
said. ``We were trying to get votes. That was what we were trying
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants
</P>
<P>
   Dick Angell, a member of the unsuccessful Anchorage bid team,
provided dossiers on the IOC members, which detailed their personal
likes and dislikes and strategies for winning their votes. His
profiles, paid for by the Atlanta bid team, provided the more
salacious material about the membership, including whose vote could
be bought with sexual favors.
</P>
<P>
   The bid group paid his firm $19,321 for his services but said it
never made use of the information on sex
</P>
<P>
   Health care
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic bid team offered medical services to IOC members and
their relatives at some of Atlanta's premier health care facilities
as a means of attracting them to the city, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, hospitals and doctors provided free services for
the foreign visitors. In other cases, the bid team picked up the
tab, although Bell's letter inexplicably said the group never
incurred any expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the services were not identified in the original report,
including $93.48 for medication for the IOC member from Swaziland.
David Sibandze, who was forced to resign from the IOC for favors
received from the Salt Lake City committee, also received free
emergency care after he suffered a heart attack during a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Another hospital treated without charge an infection for the son
of the IOC member from Algeria. And Payne's private physician twice
provided a medical examination for Vitaly Smirnov.
</P>
<P>
   The bid team offered much more, although the records indicated
no evidence the offers were accepted, according to Bell.
</P>
<P>
   It offered to fly the IOC member from Libya _ Bashir
Attarabulsi, who also has resigned _ to Atlanta for medical
treatment. There were offers of trips for treatment at the Emory
Medical Clinic for the now-deceased IOC member from Morocco and his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City team also came under fire for paying for
medical treatment and cosmetic surgery for various IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Employment opportunities
</P>
<P>
   Bell acknowledged that Payne's bid team was ``eager to
facilitate'' the job hunting efforts of the children of IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   The report details seven instances of providing letters of
recommendation, arranging interviews and offering referrals that
could lead to employment for offspring.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance ranged from securing a job offer from
then-Citizens &AMP; Southern bank for the son of Congolese delegate
Jean-Claude Ganga, who has been expelled, to arranging a job offer
at a Vail ski resort for Smirnov's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We helped people who wanted a job, but as far as we can tell
from the record, we never got anybody a job,'' Bell said. ``We
tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic training
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were most concerned in the wake of the original report
about athletic scholarships and training provided to three
teen-agers from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The bid team had acknowledged spending $9,145 for a swimmer from
Mauritius to live in Atlanta and train at the Dynamo Swim Club. It
also spent $14,583 to send two young tennis players from the Congo,
at Ganga's behest, to an exclusive camp in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the new report, the bid group acknowledged making additional
offers to assist foreign athletes, which apparently were declined.
It did help some athletes obtain financial assistance for training
from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a request by Ivan Dibos of Peru, the bidders
helped a team of cyclists and a shooter obtain entry into a U.S.
Olympic Committee training program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were athletes who needed training,'' Bell said. ``That's
one of the things Olympic bidders are encouraged to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports equipment
</P>
<P>
   The initial report described a gift of sports equipment for the
School and University Games in the Congo. The collection, which
included everything from soccer balls to T-shirts and shorts, cost
bidders $20,633.
</P>
<P>
   They also reported earlier of facilitating the donation of a
$10,000 scoreboard for the National Sports Stadium in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The new report added that 1,500 pairs of shoes were supplied to
participants in the Games. And the bid team discussed with Ganga
about donating track clothing to the Congo Sports Ministry and
providing sports equipment grants to ``all African national Olympic
committees.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers could find no evidence that the grants were made
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic assistance
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most controversial favors offered in the Olympic
scandal were scholarships and other college assistance. The
discovery of Salt Lake City's $400,000 college scholarship program
for the children of IOC members touched off the influence-peddling
scandal last November.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell said he found no evidence that scholarships were
provided to IOC members or their relatives in Atlanta, they were
certainly offered _ contrary to what bid team officials said
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The new report said bid team officials promised to secure
scholarships for some students and assisted others in gaining
admission to U.S. universities.
</P>
<P>
   Young pitched a scholarship to Georgia Tech to the daughter of
General Henry Edmund Adefope of Nigeria, and another bid team
member offered a tennis scholarship to the University of Georgia
for the daughter of Pal Schmitt of Hungary. Neither apparently
accepted the offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not give a scholarship,'' Bell said. ``But we offered
scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell acknowledged the bid team's effort in gaining admission to
Tech and setting up an apartment for the son of Ram Ruhee of
Mauritius, and assisting the son of Paul Wallwork of Western Samoa
gain admission to the University of Michigan to wrestle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two instances where we helped people get in Georgia
schools after the Olympics were awarded,'' Bell added.
</P>
<P>
   Travel
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably more abuses in travel than anywhere,'' said
Bell, ``but it was not the Atlanta group's abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell cited the IOC delegates' practice of requesting round-trip
tickets to Atlanta and to Toronto, another bid city, for visits
during the same time period. They would cash in one, take a
connecting flight between the cities and pocket the difference.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also found 10 instances where the bid group
reimbursed an IOC member who visited Atlanta for airfare with cash,
check or wire payment, but where no documentation could be found.
</P>
<P>
   While the IOC rules limited members to one visit to a candidate
city, Atlanta's strategy relied heavily on encouraging them to
visit the city and other locales. And, apparently, to visit often.
Many members made multiple trips and brought the family with them.
</P>
<P>
   Every member was invited to Disney World during the bid, and
many took Atlanta up on the offer. The exuberant bid team promoted
the potential for IOC families to visit attractions throughout the
South should Atlanta win the Games, although the program was never
implemented due to a money crunch. Nor was a plan to send all
athletes to Disney after their competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many IOC members played golf at the Augusta National Golf
Club, rested at The Cloister at Sea Island, cruised on Malcolm
Forbes' yacht in Savannah and attended University of Georgia
football games in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   They flew first class or in private corporate or state-owned
aircraft, stayed in luxury hotels and were chaffeured in private
cars. The bidders happily paid for visits to other cities once they
had the IOC members on the continent. Records show trips to Boston,
New York, Washington and Coral Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, the bid team paid for plane tickets for
the children of Ganga from the Congo. They flew his two daughters
from Atlanta to Montreal and his two sons on a three-stop junket
between Atlanta, Montreal and Toronto. They also picked up a $2,663
tab for the Ganga family's two-night stay in a New York City hotel.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the bid team spent $15,702 on hotels and airfare for
Ganga, the most egregious violater in the Salt Lake scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of these trips went unrecorded in the bid team's original
report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who co-signed the first report, said he believes the
revision is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope and believe the report Judge Bell has submitted to the
Commerce committee,'' Payne said, ``fully and finally represents
the record of the bid activities of the Atlanta campaign to win the
1996 Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
