<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-MEDIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MUCH COVERAGE IS ENOUGH, AND HOW MUCH IS TOO MUCH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ WFAA-TV/Channel 8 continued to sink its
teeth into the Wedgwood shooting story early Thursday, giving
updates and filing reports as its competitors yielded to regularly
scheduled programming.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 8 pre-empted ``Good Morning America'' and took advantage
of the hour reserved for the locally produced ``Good Morning
Texas,'' shelving the happy-face infotainment format in favor of a
somber-looking Carmen Aimsworth and Janette Smith anchoring from a
news desk.
</P>
<P>
   But as news organizations shifted to the second-day phase _
asking why a gunmen walked into a church and opened fire _ the
question for Channel 8 and its surprisingly average performance
was: Where was anchor John McCaa?
</P>
<P>
   On vacation in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   With Gloria Campos returning from a speaking engagement as the
story broke, morning and midday anchor Scott Sams was handed the
bulk of the anchor duties.
</P>
<P>
   Sams was somewhat flustered yet servicable. But there's
something uneasy about going into battle without the heaviest
artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 8 remains the most-watched station, with KXAS-TV/Channel
5 nipping at its heels. With former anchor Tracy Rowlett awaiting a
Jan. 1 on-camera start at KTVT/Channel 11 and Chip Moody still
recovering from illness, Sams has joined McCaa and Campos in the
station's traditional three-prong anchor attack.
</P>
<P>
   First-day coverage is where TV news usually trips over itself in
trying to get too much on the air too fast. Day Two is where it has
faced criticisms of crossing the line from getting the story to
exploiting it. (Channel 5 didn't hesitate to air the frantic 911
call, for instance.)
</P>
<P>
   Channels 8, 5 and 11, KDFW/Channel 4 and newcomer KDAF/Channel
33 dispatched reporters to various schools, hoping to get some kind
of reaction. Schools weren't letting them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us in the newsroom are parents,'' said Channel 8 News
Director David Duitch. ``And the golden rule is to insert your kid
as the victim and ask how would you feel as a parent. We want to be
careful. We don't want to cross that line. Does it happen
sometimes? Yes. But it's not intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the glory and the nemesis of TV news. Newspapers
basically operate on a once-a-day cycle. TV news, under routine
conditions, shortens that to roughly five hours, the times
separating their morning, noon and evening news programs.
</P>
<P>
   But on big stories, the reporting is continuous if need be with
each station looking for exclusive ``updates,'' even when no such
material exists.
</P>
<P>
   The result, as we've noticed in only two days of coverage, is
that old information is re-spun to seem new, raw information is
telecast before it has been pinned down, and stories are rushed on
the air without independent checking.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, CNN and MSNBC have been noticably more
measured and balanced on this fevered story _ but its laid-back
approach could point out a troubling sign.
</P>
<P>
   With a hurricane bearing down on the East Coast, the networks
and even CNN have made the Wedgwood shooting a lower priority. News
judgment is in itself a judgment call. Do you cover those already
dead or those who could die?
</P>
<P>
   Or are multiple killings now simply passe?
</P>
<P>
   kperkins\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
