u i BC-TIMOR-U.S.-NYT &LR;      09-16 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IS SENDING 200 TROOPS FOR EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second time in three months, President
Clinton announced that the United States would contribute soldiers
to a peacekeeping force in a troubled spot thousands of miles away,
dispatching 200 troops to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those in Kosovo, these troops will not be responsible
for combat, but for intelligence, logistics, communication and
transport.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the Roosevelt Room of the White House Thursday,
Clinton said the United States had political and moral interests at
stake in bringing peace and order to East Timor, even though an
overseas deployment will add to concerns in Congress and the
Pentagon that the armed forces were stretched too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia's future is important to us,'' Clinton said, ``not
only because of its resources and its sea lanes, but for its
potential as a leader in the region and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In consultations with Congress, the administration emphasized
that the countries of the region, rather than the United States,
would carry the main responsibility for the military operation and
that American forces would be small and restricted to noncombat
specialties.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will also consider enlarging the contingent
if Australia finds that it needs added help, a spokesman for the
Pentagon, Kenneth Bacon, said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the American role is small, especially compared to
the operation in Bosnia and Kosovo, it can still strain the
military, because each deployment requires so many additional
support and relief troops.
</P>
<P>
   The first Australian troops are expected to arrive in Dili by
the weekend, according to Vice Adm. Scott Fry of the Navy, a senior
official on the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Fry said although American soldiers would be ready to move in 48
hours, they did not expect their orders to deploy until the
Australians had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that effort, American aircraft will help the other
nations transport heavy equipment to Darwin, Australia, now the
staging base. Later, the Air Force could transport equipment in
C-5, C-17 and C-130 transports to Dili, the East Timor capital, and
if necessary, help fly in troops.
</P>
<P>
   When deployed, fewer than 100 American troops are to be
stationed on the ground in East Timor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
