<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-FLOODS-HNS &LR;      09-16 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FLOODS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF THOUSANDS SLOSH THEIR WAY HOME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note byline changes) 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
and STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Once a mighty hurricane, Tropical Storm Floyd
sloshed through the Northeast with heavy rains and gusty winds
Thursday after triggering widespread flooding, but relatively
little damage along the North Carolina coast where it rolled ashore
in the early morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of thousands who evacuated coastal communities from
Florida to Virginia started to return to their homes, those in the
path of the storm's northward march faced closed schools, shuttered
shops and canceled airline flights. Officials in Delaware,
Maryland, New Jersey, New York and Virginia declared states of
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 deaths were blamed on Floyd, seven from traffic
accidents in the Carolinas and Virginia. Two girls in Delaware
drowned after a storm-swollen creek swept them into a sewage pipe,
and one man was presumed drowned in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   But state and federal officials expressed relief that Floyd,
which at one point in its short life was one of the biggest
hurricanes ever to threaten the U.S. coast, appeared to pull its
punches just before landfall near Cape Fear, N.C., and caused
minimal damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're most fortunate,'' said George Lemons, a National Weather
Service forecaster in Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton freed more than $500 million Thursday for
victims of Hurricane Floyd and defended the mass evacuation of
coastal areas in the Southeast, calling it a ``terrific test.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than flooding, which was widespread throughout the state,
what damage Floyd caused to property appeared to be minimal and
limited to the coastal areas near where it came ashore. Power
outages affecting hundreds of thousands of people were endemic
throughout the areas affected by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   At its strongest Monday, Floyd was a Category 5 hurricane with
maximum winds of 155 mph. When it crossed the coast early Thursday,
it was a minimal, Category 2 storm with winds of 110 mph. After
picking up speed and racing northward, Floyd, with winds of around
65 mph, was downgraded to a tropical storm near Atlantic City,
N.J., in the early evening.
</P>
<P>
   After traversing North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, Delaware
and New Jersey on Thursday, then into New York's Long Island, the
considerably weakened storm is expected to glide off the continent
back into the Atlantic Ocean at Cape Cod in Massachusetts late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nudged along by a low pressure system, the storm's northeasterly
motion accelerated to nearly 30 miles per hour as it scaled the
mid-Atlantic Coast, lashing Washington, D. C., with heavy winds and
rain, and bearing down on New York City and Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The projected track of the storm is essentially off the East
Coast of Long Island, up off of Cape Cod and then to Novia
Scotia,'' said Frank Lepore, a spokesman for the National Hurricane
Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the higher latitudes, these storms tend to move across the
surface very quickly, so it becomes a rapidly deteriorating
event,'' said Lepore. ``It loses its nice cyclonic form. It just
becomes an amorphous blob of rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainfall amounts of 5 to 7 inches were predicted along the path
of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 2.6 million people from Florida to North Carolina
were ordered to leave their homes in what officials described as
the largest evacuation ever for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the path of destruction caused by Hurricane
Floyd along the state's southeastern coast was not the typical
house-smashing variety. Rather the storm deluged the state with
record amounts of rain, flooding major interstates and low-lying
areas as far inland as the Raleigh-Durham area.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were confirmed dead, including a Department of
Transportation worker who stopped to help a stranded motorist in
Trenton on Thursday. The worker, whose name was not released,
apparently stepped just a few inches off the road and was swept
away in rushing water. His body was recovered in 12-foot deep
water.
</P>
<P>
   Ten coastal counties were under dusk-to-dawn curfews Thursday
night. While authorities in most of the counties were issuing only
citations to violators, some were detaining them.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimated the flood damage would be just as
costly as it would be if Floyd had flattened the coast. Several
inland rivers were expected to crest Friday and Saturday, and were
expected to set new flooding records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flooding is going to do more damage,'' said Andy James, a
spokesman for the North Carolina Division of Emergency Management.
``Most people associate a hurricane with it coming in and blowing
down a house. We didn't have much of that. But we are flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   Assessment teams across the coastal area had not been able to
fully tally the damage late Thursday because flooded roads
prevented entry to most beaches from Surf City to the South
Carolina border.
</P>
<P>
   Besides some coastal roads, two major interstates were closed in
areas because of inland floodin. James said I-95 was closed in
both directions near Halifax and near Wilson. Interstate-40, the
main route for evacuees returning to Wilmington, was closed in both
directions at spots in New Hanover County and in Pender County.
</P>
<P>
   Officials ordered more than 500,000 people to leave the coastal
area before Floyd struck about 3 a.m. EST Thursday. About 37,000
were staying in shelters throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   By daybreak the storm had passed and many were trying to return
home. While some made it before the road closures, many were forced
to turn around or take routes that added several hours to their
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jams were reported along most of the alternate routes.
The back-ups were causing problems for power crews trying to get to
the coast where 600,000 remained without electricity Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see that number going down any time soon simply
because of the high water on the roads,'' James said. ``The repair
crews can't get to the areas.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen ``Push Packages,'' teams of six National Guardsmen
and three state forestry employees in two Humvees and a
two-and-a-half ton truck, were charged with scouring the area to
perform search and rescue missions as well as clear fallen trees
and debris from roadways.
</P>
<P>
   State emergency management spokesman Robert Carver said the
teams, formed recently in the state in the wake of past hurricanes,
were concentrating on clearing roadways so power and sewage crews
can repair broken lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is flooding everywhere,'' Carver said. ``We're going to
get out there as soon as we can. Our priority today is to get the
roads open and make sure critical facilities are operable.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one hospital was forced to close as the storm rushed
through, Carver said. An estimated 50,000 square feet of roof caved
in at the Brunswick County Hospital early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Most state and county roads leading to the beaches in Brunswick
County at the South Carolina border were covered with standing and
rushing water in various spots. While most of the areas were
passable, every road had at least one impassable spot where water
lapped across at six to eight feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who evacuated the day before lined the shoulders and
packed parking lots of closed convenience stores as they waited in
frustration for the water to subside so they could return home.
</P>
<P>
   On the beaches near Wilmington the sea surged about 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't dodge anything,'' said New Hanover County spokesman
Mark Boyer. ``We took a direct hit. Luckily it started to break up
before it hit land. The amount of damage is significantly less than
what a category four storm would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   At Topsail Island residents were turned away, many told their
homes may not be accessible until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated we couldn't get back,'' said Stan Sneeden who
was one of hundreds turned back all day Thursday. ``They said no
homes were lost so that's good news.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina on Thursday, Gov. Jim Hodges lifted the
emergency evacuation order for coastal areas of the state and about
46,000 evacuees from 146,000 shelters began to head home. In all,
800,000 people in the state had been ordered from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Both the east- and westbound lanes of Interstate 26 were opened
to eastbound traffic as people streamed back to their houses, many
of whom could expect to find no power when they arrived. Public
utility officials said more than 200,000 customers across the state
were without power early Thursday, but repair work already was
under way.
</P>
<P>
   In Myrtle Beach, where the hurricane dumped 15 inches of rain in
two days, flooding was severe, and area rivers were rising from the
runoff farther inland. Rising waters were expected to crest this
weekend, a state emergency official said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
