<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5250 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-VICTIM     09-16 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-VICTIMS-2000(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS ARE REMEMBERED, MOURNED
</HEADLINE>
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas: believe she's gone.''JOSEPH ENNIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He was my only child,'' Donna Ennis said. ``He was a very
special child and he respected and loved me,'' she said, choking
back tears Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Ennis said that her 14-year-old son had been talking about
getting baptized recently, and that she wanted him to learn what it
was all about. So he started attending the youth group at First
Baptist Church in White Settlement, a Fort Worth suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he attended the rally at Wedgwood Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to believe it, but I knew he had been shot in
the head,'' said Donna Ennis, who waited until 3 a.m. Thursday for
confirmation that her son was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in the shade of the trees at the church Ennis had just
joined, Hootie Woldai stood with his arms crossed, trying not to
cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey had his own way,'' Woldai said simply.
</P>
<P>
   All of Joey Ennis' friends and classmates, the ones he had grown
up with at West Elementary and in the close-knit environs of White
Settlement, the ones with their faces wet from tears, nodded their
heads at that description.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis, they said, was a basketball nut, a freckled boy with a
chili bowl haircut who hadn't started growing vertically but who
held out hope for his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be in the NBA,'' said Jennifer Cubillos, a
14-year-old classmate in the 9th grade at Brewer High School in
White Settlement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASSANDRA GRIFFIN
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Griffin was only 14 years old when Ashbrook entered
the church and took her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that stands out about Cassie is she was not your
typical teenager,'' said David Griffin, her father. ``She tried
very hard to please her mom and dad, and she had a very strong
faith in God.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Lockney, Texas, the North Crowley High School freshman
excelled at clarinet, which she had been playing since the sixth
grade. She also tinkered with the piano and the flute and liked to
sing.
</P>
<P>
   Her family moved to North Texas from West Texas two years ago,
and in that time, Cassie made many friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always happy-go-lucky, easygoing,'' David Griffin
said. ``She had a real concern for her friends. She would pray for
her friends, and she was disappointed when they would go out
drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cassie brought home some of her friends after
school; they had dinner and then went to the rally. Her mother,
Tralissa Griffin, was at the rally, sitting about seven rows behind
her daughter when the gunman entered and started shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The thought still shocks the Griffin family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to raise your children in the church, and you think of
all places, you'd be safe in church,'' David Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Cassie's brother, 11-year-old Chris, has been dealing with his
grief in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been sleeping a lot, trying to forget,'' David Griffin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Griffin family can never forget their only daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a beautiful girl.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN KIMBERLY JONES
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kimberly Jones sang in the Wedgwood church choir and had
enrolled at Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Seminary student Vickie Stewart, who lives in Barnard dorm where
Jones lived, said many dorm residents were up late Wednesday night
crying and praying when they learned that Jones was among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock,'' said Stewart, 36. She said many students
were aware that Jones and about four other students had gone to the
church for the Wednesday night prayer service and began to worry as
they watched the news on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 23, lived on the third floor of the dorm. Outside her
room, 345, visitors are greeted by a Bible scripture that Jones
wrote on a small message board: ``Love must be sincere. Hate what
is evil. Cling to what is good. Be devoted to one another in
brotherly love. Romans 12:9-10.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JUSTIN RAY
</P>
<P>
   Justin ``Steggie'' Ray, 17, was a good kid who was starting to
turn his life around after floundering for two years because a
former stepfather left his life, his former Scoutmaster said.
</P>
<P>
   Known to many by the last name Stegner (from a former
stepfather), Ray was a Boy Scout who was also a Cub Scout camp
counselor. He seemed lost at Southwest High School until production
teacher Tim Hood piqued his interest in film and record producing,
said Malcolm Hill, Ray's former Scout leader.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Ray transferred to Cassata High School, a
private alternative school. He hoped to graduate in December so he
could begin fulfilling his dream of owning his own production
company.
</P>
<P>
   At Cassata, Ray made friends like Chris Roddan and Travis
Laminack who were updating the school's promotional video as part
of Bobbie Su Nadal's video class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really goal-oriented. That's what I liked about him,''
Nadal said. ``He took on the leadership role in the video class.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadal and Hill said Ray used his production skills to run
audiovisual equipment at concerts and PTA meetings, Cub Scout
ceremonies and other events.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a genius with that stuff,'' Laminack said. ``Media
technology was his thing. He came over here (Cassata) but he kept
going back to Southwest. I think Mr. Hood was like a father figure
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Hood were running the band's sound equipment at Wedgwood
Baptist Church on Wednesday night when Ray was fatally shot,
Cassata counselor Brandon Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Cassata teacher Dawn Farmer said Ray was a quiet thinker who
died doing what he loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he went to church there, but it doesn't surprise
me,'' Farmer said. ``He was quiet but he was deep. I think if
anyone was ready to meet his maker, he was.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Yvette Craig, Martha Deller, Mary Doclar, Renee
Lee, Marisa Taylor and Chris Vaughn contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
