<HEADER>
A5257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-CAROLINA-HOUSES     09-16 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-CAROLINA-HOUSES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd rips apart houses atop island
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK ISLAND, N.C. _ At the mouth of the Cape Fear River,
Hurricane Floyd landed its biggest punch.
</P>
<P>
   Stilt houses once towering over the beach on this small resort
island of vacation rentals and Dairy Queens toppled to the surf.
Some simply vanished into pieces of timber. Beach Road disappeared
under sand, loose pilings, toilets, microwaves, washing machines
and all the other flotsam Floyd tossed aside as it crested on the
12.5-mile long island just west of where the river meets the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every hurricane that comes up goes up the mouth
of the Cape Fear. It's like a magnet,'' said Von West, 52, who
huddled in his house a block from the beach as the storm shook his
roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look out on this beach, you see a lot of people's hopes
and dreams. Then you see this,'' he said, pointing to a house that
will almost certainly be submerged at high tide.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who stayed say winds howled the worst about 2:30 a.m.
But water, more than wind, ravaged this island of 8,000 residents
that swells to 45,000 during summer tourist months. Debris formed a
line in the sand like sea weed. Steps that once led from the beach
to houses were swept across the street. One house lurched sideways
as the floor hung from below. Every few minutes, it groaned eerily.
</P>
<P>
   Town Councilman Jeff Emsminger, who has lived on the island for
14 years, spent the day walking from one end to another with a
clipboard, adding up the damage. With three blocks to go, he
guessed that 20 houses had been completely washed away. The damage,
he said, will amount to millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got houses missing here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emsminger also complained bitterly that the community, which
incorporated Yaupon Beach and Long Beach last year into one town,
has long fought for federal assistance to renourishes beaches and
protect the seaside houses with names like Sea Bee's Dream and Sea
King.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the federal government had cooperated with us the past few
years, you wouldn't see any of this,'' he said. ``I went through
Hugo and Hugo didn't do what this did.''
</P>
<P>
   The island has been inhabited since Colonial times, said
resident Randy Armstrong, 52. Fort Caswell sits on one end, with
its lighthouse that served during the American Revolution and
continued to guide ships until World War II. The island's first
industry was providing timber from the graceful oaks that grow
thickly on the island's interior to northern shipyards. Agriculture
eventually took over, then tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the houses lost were vacation rentals, which can cost as
little as $450 a week to rent to more than $3,000. Still, the
tourists here feel more like residents, with most returning
annually, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you noticed there's no motels? No condos?'' Armstrong, a
jeweler, asked. ``This is the kind of place you put your kid on a
bicycle and let him ride. This is a like a time warp.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the cozy feel stretches up and down the beach. Picket
fences surround some houses. The town's pride and joy was a
bathhouse and beach cabana where residents gathered in the
evenings, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   But Floyd grabbed hold of the cabana and splintered it, leaving
only steps to a railing that now surrounds nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, residents who stayed back from the beach during
the storm _ about 100 remained despite a mandatory evacuation,
Emsminger said _ heard none of the devastation occurring just a
block away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could only hear the wind and rain. We had the generator
going and I was watching movies but I'd step out every once in a
while,'' said Marvin Geddings, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say with so many storms and hurricanes under their
belts in the last few years _ Bonnie, Bertha, Fran and Dennis _
they were feeling pretty confident about their new address in
``Hurricane Alley'' _ until Floyd began churning up the coast with
150 mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through a lot of hurricanes and we've seen what
they can do,'' said Sally Skipper, 61, whose husband retired from
the Coast Guard in 1978 and just finished building their house
across from the beach two months ago. The couple fled inland, and
returned Thursday to find every shingle in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got christened well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were not so lucky. At one house where Floyd had ripped
off siding and splintered stairs, someone had posted a sign in the
front: Yard Sale.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
