<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 2 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert Jacksonville-Carolina game.)  (A Macintosh graphic of this text is being sent electronically to
NYT graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(lh) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (0-1) vs. Minnesota (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Raiders (409) _ yardage allowed Green Bay. Vikings (8
of 9) _ home openers won.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders led Green Bay late and then stood by helplessly as
the Packers kept driving for big yards and big points for a
last-second victory. Now Oakland hits the road again in its second
of three straight against the National Football Conference Central
division. What it will find in Minnesota is a team eager to
duplicate last season's offensive exploits, a team yearning to blow
its offense open en route. Oakland allowed 409 yards and 28 points
at Green Bay. Look for improvement, but not enough, in a testy
battle featuring big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Vikings, 26-20.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (1-0) vs. Carolina (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Jaguars (10.8) _ Reggie Barlow's punt return average.
Panthers (9-7) _ record vs. the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: These two recent expansion teams are heading in
opposite directions. The Jaguars are climbing; the Panthers are
sinking. Dom Capers used to coach the Panthers. He is now the
Jaguars' defense coordinator. Last week his group held San
Francisco to three points; Carolina doubles that but still sinks.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Jaguars 23-6.
</P>
<P>
   Washington (0-1) vs. Giants (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Redskins (3-6-1) _ Turner's record vs. Giants. Giants
(plus 5) _ turnover differential.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Mike Nolan, the Redskins' defensive coordinator, used
to hold that job with the Giants but now works under Norv Turner,
Washington's embattled head coach. When Nolan left three years ago,
many Giants thought they had lost one of the best defensive minds
around. But John Fox replaced him and has made Nolan a distant
memory. Fox leads a group that scored more points (14) last week
than many offenses did, including the Giants'. Washington's offense
streaked toward 504 yards and 35 points against Dallas last week,
and the Redskins still lost. It is a magical matchup _ the
Washington offense against the Giants' defense. Take the Giants'
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Giants, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (1-0) vs. Detroit (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Packers (4.3) _ Levens' average yards per run. Lions
(6.0) _ Rivers' average yards per run.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: So Ron Rivers is outrunning Dorsey Levens? Rivers, the
retired Barry Sanders' replacement, rushed 16 times for 96 yards in
Detroit's rousing 28-20 victory at Seattle. Charlie Batch threw
three touchdown passes, Robert Porcher made three sacks and the
Lions' defense held Mike Holmgren's ballyhooed offensive system and
players to 205 yards. Of course, doing that to Brett Favre and the
Packers will be more challenging. Look for Favre, again, to win it
late.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Packers, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (1-0) vs. New England (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Colts _ (1) '98 division victories. Patriots (14-4) _
in last 18 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Indianapolis won one American Football Conference East
division game last year. Having beaten Buffalo last week, it can
double that number for this season. It will attempt to do so
against a team that usually shakes the Colts silly. Patriots
quarterback Drew Bledsoe owns a career-most nine victories against
the Colts. In his last five games against them, he has thrown 11
touchdown passes and one interception and earned a 108.4
quarterback rating. The Patriots hope they have found a solid
running threat in the veteran Terry Allen. Their defensive stars
(Ty Law, Willie McGinnest, Lawyer Milloy, Chris Slade) made huge
plays at big times against the Jets. New England played confidently
against the Jets and will illustrate even more confidence here.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Patriots, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (1-0) vs. Baltimore (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Steelers (40) _ yards allowed vs. Browns. Ravens
(44.6) _ Mitchell quarterback rating.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Scott Mitchell, the Ravens' quarterback, needs a strong
showing. He got a second chance as a starter this year after things
blew up for him in Detroit last year. His start last week against
St. Louis _ 17-of-40 for 188 yards with a touchdown and two
interceptions in a 27-10 loss _ was lackluster. Nothing like what
Kordell Stewart did, attacking the Cleveland Browns on the ground
and in the air with a display of quickness and arm strength and
precision that made Steelers fans hopeful. Are they back? Why, yes,
for the moment, they are.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Steelers, 19-17.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (0-1) vs. Philadelphia (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Buccaneers (minus 5) _ turnover differential. Eagles
(103) _ Staley rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Duce Staley is a diminutive running back who is fun to
watch. He hits holes quickly and keeps chucking _ this Eagles back
has gained 100 or more yards from scrimmage in each of his last
seven games. He is one of the few bright spots for the Eagles,
losers again last week in painful fashion, 25-24, against Arizona.
Now come the Buccaneers and their stressed-out quarterback, Trent
Dilfer, who absolutely needs a big game, a victory. He is on the
verge of getting benched for good after just two '99 starts. His
last one was lousy (two interceptions returned for touchdowns)
against the Giants. This one is better.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Buccaneers, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (0-0) vs. Cincinnati (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: (0) _ 100-yard rushers allowed. Bengals (90) _ QB
Blake's rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: That's right, the Chargers did not allow a 100-yard
rusher in 1998. They didn't play last week, the only NFL team to
have be a bye on opening weekend. How strange for the Chargers to
be the only team at home watching the season unfold and pass them
by? There is time to catch up, right now. As a matter of fact, each
team in their division (AFC West) lost last week, so the Chargers
are in first place at 0-0. If only the Bengals could gain a bye
every week. They lost another game in sorry fashion, 36-35, at
Tennessee, wilting when it counted most. Both teams follow their
current suits.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Chargers, 27-21.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (1-0) vs. Miami (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Cardinals (4) _ winning streak. Dolphins (25-9) _
September record in '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Arizona had not won four consecutive regular-season
games since 1988. It is winning with quarterback Jake Plummer, who
owns 10 comeback victories in his 27 Cardinals games. What a
thrilling victory for the Cardinals at Philadelphia, but now they
are matched against a team riding high after dumping Denver on
Monday night. This is no time to let down, and the Dolphins won't.
Dan Marino has never lost to the Cardinals in three games and has
never thrown an interception against them compared with his seven
touchdowns. Miami has never lost to the Cardinals, going 7-0 all
time. Make it 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Dolphins, 30-20.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (0-1) vs. Chicago (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Seahawks (7,894) _ Watters' career rush yards. Bears
(16) _ passing first downs.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Chicago beat Kansas City and Seattle lost to Detroit
last week. Most expected those results to be opposite. Not the
Bears. Under Dick Jauron, their new coach, the Bears are refreshed
and optimistic. Playing at home for a second straight week is a
plus. But Seattle Coach Mike Holmgren has won 10 straight over the
Bears and is 6-1 in Soldier Field. He knows them. His quarterback,
Jon Kitna, earned a 107.9 quarterback rating last week against
Detroit. He did not earn enough big plays to win, but his
performance was solid. Another good showing from Kitna and more
running from Ricky Watters will make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Seahawks, 16-9.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (0-1) vs. Tennessee (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Browns (2) _ first downs vs. Pittsburgh. Titans (162)
_ Dyson's record yards.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: After a pitiful offensive showing against Pittsburgh,
Cleveland has chosen to move the heralded rookie Tim Couch into the
starting quarterback slot. Is Couch ready? Well, Ty Detmer
certainly wasn't. He struggled mightily as the starter against
Pittsburgh (6-of-12 for 52 yards, an interception and a quarterback
rating of 25.2). Tennessee struggled early against Cincinnati
before compiling 403 yards of offense, 162 of it by receiver Kevin
Dyson. Tennessee has won seven consecutive division games. Al Del
Greco has converted a club-record 19 consecutive field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Titans, 31-17.
</P>
<P>
   Denver (0-1) vs. Kansas City (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: (61) _ Davis' rushing yards. Chiefs (8.96) _ average
gain on first down.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: After Denver's debacle against Miami on Monday night,
the Dolphins felt sure that Terrell Davis was still hurting from a
shoulder injury. He rushed for only 61 yards and left for much of
the fourth quarter. His team exited for much of the game. The
Broncos hope to rebound in Arrowhead Stadium, where they won, 30-7,
last year in what was the signature game for the Chiefs' deplorable
season. It was the game in which the Chiefs unraveled, showing
their frustration with a bushel of ugly personal foul penalties.
Denver seeks improvement. Kansas City seeks retribution. Take the
angry team.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Chiefs, 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (1-0) vs. San Francisco (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Saints (12) _ sacks in last two games. 49ers (17) _
home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Big game for the Saints, a confidence builder against
the team that has dominated this division in the .90s. Big game for
the 49ers after last week's blowout loss (41-3) at Jacksonville.
Hands are wringing in San Francisco. Is this it? Are the good times
gone? Can quarterback Steve Young do it anymore? Young needs help,
especially from the running game. Charlie Garner and Lawrence
Phillips need to produce more at running back. If the 49ers get it,
they win easily. They do.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: 49ers, 36-17.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 8 P.M. GAME
</P>
<P>
   Jets (0-1) vs. Buffalo (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Jets (194) _ Johnson record yards. Bills (20) _
Flutie incompletions.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Both teams seek to avert not only an 0-2 start but also
an 0-2 division start. The Jets turn to Rick Mirer at quarterback
and hope that Keyshawn Johnson (eight catches, career-high 194
receiving yards against New England) can maintain his fast pace. It
is the Jets' first chance to show what they can do without the
injured Vinny Testaverde. Flutie was all over the place in his
team's loss at Indianapolis. Flutie completed only 22-of-42 passes
in the scrambling mode that is his game. The Jets will try to box
him, keep him contained and let the game boil down to Curtis Martin
vs. Antowain Smith at running back. Martin can win that battle.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Jets, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT GAME
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (0-1) vs. Dallas (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stats: Falcons (minus 3) _ turnover differential. Cowboys
(541) _ offensive yards.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Atlanta lost to Minnesota because the Falcons kept
dropping the ball. Dallas beat Washington in overtime because the
Cowboys kept getting the ball into the end zone. If those trends
continue, it will be a troublesome start for Atlanta. If Chris
Chandler (hamstring) plays, he has a chance to improve on his 20-9
record as the Falcons' starter. Expect Chandler to make it _ he has
not played in a Monday night game in 11 years. Dallas will win with
special-teams play and with the arm of Troy Aikman and hands and
fleet feet of Rocket Ismail in another pitch-and-catch deep-passing
display.
</P>
<P>
   Game Score: Cowboys, 23-21.
</P>
