<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-FLA-NC17-COX     09-16 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FLA-NC17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd's rain pummels N.C.
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin, Jenny Staletovich and Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Floyd, one of the most feared
storms of the 20th century, continued to create havoc throughout
the Carolinas, Virginia and the Northeast even at half its full
strength Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Floyd's center wheeled past the casinos of Atlantic
City, N.J., Thursday afternoon, it had whipped and wrung itself
down to a tropical storm _ but not before dropping up to 19 inches
of rain in the Carolinas, causing hundreds of airline flights to be
canceled, interrupting train and ferry service all along the East
Coast and throwing New York and New Jersey into states of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical storm warning for heavy rains and winds of more than
40 mph was in effect in northern New Jersey and New York City and
up to the Merrimack River in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd had been feared most for the intensity of its winds, which
had reached 155 mph over the South Atlantic and made it a
borderline Category 5 hurricane, the most destructive of all. But
after raking the Bahamas with winds of more than 100 mph, Floyd
collided with a cold front pushing a trough of low pressure and the
combination turned it into a super-wet storm when it hit the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It interacted with the cold front, and together they made more
(rain) than either one by itself,'' said Jim Lushine, storm warning
coordinator for the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane brought the largest peacetime evacuation in U.S.
history from Florida's east coast northward. It plowed into the
North Carolina coast just before dawn Thursday, triggering
widespread flooding and blacking out power to hundreds of thousands
of people.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. James Hunt said thousands of residents had
lost their homes and damage would be in the hundreds of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven deaths were blamed on Floyd, including four in
North Carolina from traffic accidents provoked by the storm. In
Maryland, one man died Wednesday of a heart attack while overseeing
a Red Cross shelter set up in his school building.
</P>
<P>
   Another man was swept away Tuesday by a raging storm tide in the
Bahamas, which bore the brunt of the hurricane's force before it
turned north into cooler waters and began to weaken. Floyd's storm
surge and wind gusts up to 190 mph swept an entire village out to
sea, flattened hundreds of homes and destroyed power and phone
lines throughout the islands.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, 65,000 Florida Power &AMP; Light customers were still
without electricity Thursday night, mostly in Volusia and Brevard
counties. FPL expects to have all power restored by tonight,
spokeswoman Betty Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm swept farther up the U.S. coast, winds and rain
caused 1.4 million utility customers from South Carolina to New
Jersey to lose power. Flooding and power failures combined to shut
down Portsmouth, Va.'s water supply system, which serves 110,000
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were closed for more than 2 million youngsters in
Washington, Baltimore, all of New Jersey, Philadelphia and New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach International Airport was open Thursday, but many
travelers were stranded. All flights to the Northeast were canceled
or delayed as Floyd affected airports from South Carolina to New
England. Flights to and from Boston, Hartford, New York and Newark
were canceled. Flights to Philadelphia, Raleigh/Durham, Baltimore
and Washington were expected to resume Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd roared ashore at 3 a.m. near Cape Fear, N.C., with 110 mph
winds, then quickly weakened after flooding the coasts of the
Carolinas and Virginia with more than a foot of rain and chasing
tens of thousands of people into shelters. It was downgraded to a
tropical storm as sustained winds fell to 65 mph, below the 74 mph
threshold for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Until Hurricane Floyd, thousands of people who live on the
twisting roads near the border of North and South Carolina thought
they were on high ground. But Floyd wasn't like other hurricanes _
it didn't smash windows, rip off roofs or snap acres of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it quietly filled nearby swamps and rivers, leaving
damage that continued to creep into homes well after the skies had
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of the North Carolina coast and the Myrtle Beach area of
South Carolina got up to 16 inches of rain, and a foot fell on
Virginia's Tidewater region. Wilmington got 13 inches. Water and
sand swept over Wrightsville Beach and other beach communities,
burying the ocean roads. Most remained closed for much of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmington's barrier islands and old city streets were largely
undamaged, but severe flooding closed part of Interstate 40. With
white caps forming in places, some people drove across the highway
median while the less lucky abandoned their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wilmington looked as if it sustained only a hard rain,
not a hurricane. While power was lost to most of the city for much
of the day, few lines were downed.
</P>
<P>
   Inland was a different story. Small towns to the north in Pender
County struggled with rising water from creeks washing over roads,
into yards and through front doors. At first light, the Castle
Hayne Volunteer Fire Department pulled one motorist from his car as
it stalled under a current of water.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to the Northeast Cape Fear River, water flooded the
entire hamlet of Burgaw Creek. Everywhere in the community of about
75 houses, neighbors stood on porches, some venturing out in
rowboats. Bill and Betty Lundsford stayed dry on their porch while
their son, his wife and two children waded up the driveway in 3
feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried three ways to get here,'' said Patrick Lundsford, 33.
</P>
<P>
   The Lundsfords moved to their house along Highway 53 after
Hurricane Fran destroyed their other house. They built the new
house about 4 feet off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put it as high as we could, but I guess it wasn't high
enough,'' Betty Lundsford said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say worse flooding in the area is yet to come as
rivers continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared a major disaster in North Carolina,
and released $528 million to the Federal Emergency Management
Agency to help hurricane victims.
</P>
<P>
   The wind set a Ferris wheel spinning on its own at Ocean City,
Md., and overturned an empty truck on the high Chesapeake Bay
Bridge. Virginia closed the 18-mile-long Chesapeake Bay
Bridge-Tunnel, and New York City shut down the exposed upper deck
of the Verrazano Narrows Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had urged more than 2.6 million people along the
southern Atlantic coast to clear out of Floyd's path, and more
people were urged to evacuate in parts of Virginia, Maryland, New
Jersey and Long Island, where the storm hit late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New York City sent nonessential municipal employees home early
and urged businesses to do the same because of the possibility of
widespread mass transit outages during the rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   For most of Florida, Floyd's damage was light and there were no
reports of deaths or serious injuries. Some North Floridians
returning from the state's massive evacuation were dismayed about
the sand and debris inside their homes and the cleanup ahead, but
most were relieved the damage wasn't worse.
</P>
<P>
   In Fernandina Beach, Terry Laughinghouse had boarded up her
two-story stilt house that backs up to the ocean and fled with
thousands of others as the storm approached. What should have been
a one-hour drive to Waycross, Ga., turned into a seven-hour
odyssey, as highways became impossibly clogged with evacuees
seeking shelter.
</P>
<P>
   When Laughinghouse came home Thursday, she found the force of
Floyd's storm surge had collapsed the back wall of the first-floor
garage, pushing tons of sand through and knocking out the doors.
Sand was 4 feet deep in the garage, but the main part of the house
had no major damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``God and plywood were on my side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Stephanie Desmon contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
