r a BC-FORBES-AZR &LR;      09-16 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES BACK IN STATE, HOPES FOR '96 RERUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON - Presidential hopeful Steve Forbes, hoping against long
odds for a repeat performance, returned Sept. 16 to the state that
four years ago crowned him as a serious contender for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who stunned political observers by winning Arizona's
primary in 1996, began a two-day campaign swing through the state
by re-issuing a challenge to the campaign's front-runner, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, for a series of debates. Bush has been
avoiding appearances with other GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also warned that the looming defection of Pat Bu chanan
to a third party should stand out as a ``dramatic wake-up call'' to
the GOP to not stray from its conservative roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of election cycles we have had mush,'' Forbes
said. ``You have either got that inspired message or eventually you
go the way of the Whigs.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Forbes won Arizona's Feb. 22 primary with 33 percent of
the vote, beating the eventual nominee Bob Dole, who placed second
with 30 percent. Buchanan placed third with 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Forbes has often pointed to his victory as proof
that he can get elected. At last month's Iowa Straw Poll, his
first-place finish in Arizona was featured prominently in a
campaign video that played inside the Iowa State University
Coliseum, paid for by Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who finished second to Bush in the straw poll, has been
prodding the front-runner to debate him, a match-up that continued
to elude Forbes after Bush on Sept. 15 decided to forgo a debate
that was scheduled to be televised nationally from Florida early
next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have issued a challenge for a series of debates - I don't
care where he wishes to hold them - between now and year-end so
people can hear for themselves what each candidate stands for,''
Forbes said before a fund-raiser at the Savoy Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to get a gauge - to get a feel - for whether a
candidate is serious about making real change in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also came close to accusing Bush of hypocrisy for posting
the names of each of his campaign contributors on his Internet Web
site while remaining mum on a number of issues facing the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very telling that he's willing to reveal the
source of his money, but he's not willing to reveal what his
positions are,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate has made it clear he will vigorously contend for
the GOP's favor again in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Forbes set up a sizable campaign office here
to nurture a fund-raising and organizational effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my favorite state, for obvious reasons,'' Forbes said
on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 17 Forbes will appear before the Arizona Chamber of
Commerce with New Mexico Gov. Gary Johnson, who has endorsed his
candidacy, and later will attend a town hall meeting at a
retirement community in Mesa, followed by a fund-raising dinner at
the Arizona Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his focus on the state, observers say Forbes has miles
to go before he can catch up to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll conducted by the Rocky Mountain Behavior
Research Associates, an Arizona group, placed Forbes fourth, with 9
percent of the vote. Bush garnered 37 percent, Arizona Sen. John
McCain got 21 percent and Elizabeth Dole 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Earl de Berge said Forbes is facing a much different
set of competitors and issues in this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the conditions are the same (as in 1996),
nor are the candidates the same. It's comparing apples and
oranges,'' de Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes steamed to victory in 1996 largely on the engine of his
flat-tax proposal. And while the candidate has broadened the scope
of his appeal, taking detailed stands on issues such as abortion
and education, he is still heavily identified with tax reduction, a
``cause celebre'' from another time, according to de Berge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think (voters) are fixated on taxes the way they
were in 96. Wrong issue, wrong time,'' de Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   During a radio call-in show in which he was asked, among other
things, whether he had ever ingested cocaine - a question that Bush
has largely declined to answer - Forbes said no.
</P>
<P>
   '`I drink Coca Cola, but I've never sniffed cocaine,'' he said,
adding that he thought such issues were peripheral to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in response to a question about the Endangered Species
Act, Forbes attempted to flash his conservative credentials by
relating a story about a protected species of fly in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There they wanted to close the highway for two months out of
the year so the flies could cross the road and not face windshield
hazard,'' he said without specifying which species of fly he was
speaking about. ``This is how bizarre it (the Act) has gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   About 500 Tucsonans paid $10 each to eat barbecue and hobnob
with Forbes. He stuck around long enough to hand out free signed
copies of his books to 350 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Several supporters said the candidate's message has retained its
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for him for the nomination four years ago, and I hope
he makes it as president this time,'' said Thomas Evans, a retired
financing agent living in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he does not buy into predictions that Bush has the
nomination sewed up, invoking the name of another unlikely
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My response is this: They said that about Jesse (Ventura),''
Evans said. ``If people will use their heads and use their
intelligence, I think he will be president.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
