r a BC-MISSAMERICA-COLUMN-AZ     09-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGEANT SWIRL HAS ARIZONA ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
 AMERICA-COLUMN-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - The controversy stalking Atlantic City may feel new,
thoroughly modern, but really the story is 50 years old. The debate
over Miss America's virtue, over her marital status and her womb,
begins not in New Jersey, but in a tiny chapel in Litchfield Park.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a tiny brunette, a Miss Ari zona named Jacque Mercer, and a
plain gold wedding band.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque's North High School sweetheart, Doug Cook, slipped this
band onto her finger on Dec. 27, 1949. The groom was 21, an art stu
dent; the bride 18, a Phoenix Col lege freshman and a school
principal's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Their union set off more than wedding bells. Of course, the
bride's was not just any ring finger.
</P>
<P>
   On the day she got married, Jac que Mercer was the reigning Miss
America 1949 _ three months into her year wearing the
diamond-dusted crown.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, the Mercer nup tials owned the front page of
that day's Republic _ ``Jacque, Doug Cook Are Wed'' ran the
headline in a point size usually reserved for wars. This drew
national press, which in turn sent the Miss America officials into
apoplexy.
</P>
<P>
   Pageant chairman Park W. Haver stick gave Jacque a statement for
a wedding gift: ``There is no prece dent in this,'' he said. ``It
is the first time a Miss America has married before completing the
obligations that go with the title.''
</P>
<P>
   It would also be the last: Though the pageant backed down days
later, letting Jacque keep her title, Haver stick and peers passed
a ``no wed ding, no pregnancy rule'' the very next year. It was the
repeal of that rule, 49 years later, that caused the hubbub in
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   After Haverstick's decision, the controversy faded, as did the
beauty queen who started it. Jacque Mercer died in California 17
years ago. Her obituary cites leukemia, but some who knew her well
call the disease more side effect than cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be around her, you'd think that she was at the height of
happi ness, but underneath that you won dered,'' says her
stepmother, Margaret Mercer, now 88 years old and living in a
nursing home on 16th Street. ``I'm very opposed to these beauty
contests and people be ing elevated to something of fame. They just
don't come down off of it. I think that was a great deal of her
trouble.'' &QL; 
High price of early fame &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Mercer wore trouble like a contestant's silk sash.
</P>
<P>
   Her wedding to Cook was the first of four. The union lasted into
1952. Jacque's second marriage, to a ``casual acquaintance,'' ended
after 11 days. A year later came her long relationship _ with
Richard Cur ran, a star running back at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   The two had a son and a daugh ter. Richard played for the Green
Bay Packers, then retired to found an advertising agency in town.
Jac que worked with him for years. Their divorce happened in 1974.
Then Richard got into the land busi ness with swindler par
excellence Ned Warren. Curran's conviction on 33 counts of land
fraud happened in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Around that same time came trouble for their son, Richard Jr.,
nicknamed ``Dandy.'' Old newspa per clips detail a drug bust in New
Mexico, a plea deal and a felony conviction. Other clips mention
the son's disappearance and permanent estrangement from his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about that,'' Mar garet Mercer says.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque, meanwhile, stayed single for a few years. She went into
real estate, coaxed her daughter, Shan non, to the title of Miss
Teenage Ar izona, and got reacquainted with another North High
grad, Dr. Mar vin Gillespie. They married in Cali fornia in January
1978.
</P>
<P>
   If they were happy for long, it dissolved in a liquor river.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to rehabilitate her in her alcoholism,'' Margaret
Mercer explains, ``but she'd come out and go right back at it
again. It just wasn't successful. Eventually, she was diagnosed as
having leukemia.'' &QL; 
The world's not a stage &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Jacque Mercer, life never got better than those few months
50 years ago, days when she alternated between wearing a tiara and
a crown. The old stories say she won Miss America on the strength
of a dramatic reading _ the suicide scene from Romeo and Juliet.
</P>
<P>
   First, she performed Shakespeare, then she lived it.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cook, Jacque's first hus band, went on to a career as a col
lege professor. He's still a Phoenix resident and he remained
friends with Jacque until her death. He can still recall giving her
the ring that sparked the rule that sparked a con troversy half a
century later.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never quite recaptured the excitement of the Miss America
achievement. She hit a bright point in her life and then . . .
there's not a heckuva lot else for a former Miss America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacque never found that some thing else.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at (602) 444-8515, or at
david.leibowitz &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
