<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-OBSESS-NYT &LR;      09-16 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-OBSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PUBLIC FIXATED ON THE WEATHER IS MESMERIZED BY FLOYD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Okla, N.D., Utah, Mass.)  (See also HURRICANE-RDP, HURRICANE-NY, HURRICANE-NY-SCENE) 
(rk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For days, Bob Chartuk, a spokesman for the National Weather
Service, had been answering an endless stream of phone calls from
reporters as Hurricane Floyd rumbled up the East Coast. Perhaps the
most unexpected call, he said, came from a radio station in North
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts of a midday talk show on KVMI, 96.7 FM, put him live
on the air in West Fargo, introducing his segment with a pounding
heavy-metal tune by Megadeth. ``The music was certainly
appropriate,'' said Chartuk, who works at an office in Bohemia on
Long Island but answers queries to the National Hurricane Center in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dangerous and hard driving, just like Floyd. But I couldn't
quite figure out why they were interested in our hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dakotans, like everyone else, seemed hypnotized by the
swirling, evil-eyed monster. From the West Coast to London, and
certainly from New Jersey through the five boroughs of New York
City and around New England, Floyd fixated millions of people
Thursday, staring at some from television screens with its
Cyclopian eye etched in synthetic orange swirls and blasting others
right in the face with potent, rainy gusts.
</P>
<P>
   The storm hit dead center on the nerve that seems to jangle in
more and more people these days any time the weather grows
dangerous or unusual. Part of the jangling might be that the
weather has seemed more intense lately: there was the scorching
drought that is a soggy memory now; there was the tornado that
shocked Salt Lake City, and of course the giant F5-strength tornado
that trampled Oklahoma City in May.
</P>
<P>
   But weather experts say that other factors have contributed to
the growing fascination. Some are obvious, such as the growth of
on-demand weather broadcasts, with the Weather Channel and even CNN
following storms nonstop. The Weather Channel broke its record for
viewers on Tuesday, with 2.5 million households tuning in.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the Internet, with the Web site for the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, www.noaa.gov, receiving
about three million visits a day earlier this week, according to
Chartuk. Dozens of other weather-related sites have sprung up in
the last few years. The Weather Channel's site, weather.com, hit a
record on Tuesday, a spokesman for the channel said, with more than
23 million visits as the storm passed Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But less obvious changes may also account for the increased
attention, said John W. Firor, a senior climatologist at the
National Center for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Far more people live in harm's way than ever before, he said.
Thickets of expensive beach-front houses sit where only marsh grass
grew a few decades ago, raising the stakes when a giant storm
sweeps a coast, and contributing to the record exodus of people
that paralyzed highways from Florida to the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   The news used to begin when a hurricane struck and end with the
cleanup. Now, he said, we watch for days ahead of time _ often from
the moment a wispy cluster of thunderstorms off the African coast
coalesces into a depression and then a tropical storm, and finally
a hurricane. Then it wanders and weaves, almost like some brooding
animal, until it picks a course and charges the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a drama to it,'' Firor said.
</P>
<P>
   Other weather experts said that maybe it is not so much that new
technologies are changing the way we think, but instead allowing us
to return to our roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be just one of those things that takes us back to our
elemental days when we were a lot more attuned to the weather than
we are now,'' said Doyle S. Rice, the managing editor of
Weatherwise, a 51-year-old journal about, yes, the weather.
``Weather is something that touches you at a level deeper than a
lot of other things,'' Rice said. ``I'm cold, I'm hot, I'm wet.
These are things that really get right back down to your gut.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike a sports event or movie, a big storm, although
entertaining, is uncluttered. ``It isn't `Hurricane Floyd,' brought
to you by the Weather Channel,''' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, hurricanes have brought celebrity status to a few,
including John Hope, the Weather Channel's mustachioed maestro, who
at the age of 80 has been trying to retire from his position for a
while, but keeps coming back every time a big storm brews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't seem to help myself,'' Hope said. He has become known
in some circles as the Walter Cronkite of weather. ``I haven't had
time to check my fan mail today,'' Hope said Thursday night, as he
arrived to announce Floyd's end game.
</P>
<P>
   His fans mainly are avid viewers that Weather Channel managers
refer to as people who are ``weather engaged.'' But some thank-you
notes come from people who were convinced to evacuate a shoreline
because of Hope's warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The ``weather engaged'' range from retirees to school children,
and, in fact, meteorology clubs have been popping up at many
schools. But no one need worry that meteorology is going through a
boom, said Dr. Keith L. Seitter, the deputy executive director of
the American Meteorological Society.
</P>
<P>
   He said that about 500 people receive bachelor's degrees in the
subject each year, about 200 get master's degrees, and 100 receive
a doctorate in meteorology, with the total growing about 3 percent
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, as the weakening storm swept toward New York City
and up into New England, at least a few people there welcomed its
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   In Gloucester, Mass., a film crew was making the adaptation of
``The Perfect Storm,'' the 1997 best seller about a deadly
Northeaster. Sebastian Junger, the author of the book, was there as
a spectator, watching as the crew sent the Hannah Boden, one of the
fishing boats in the story, out to sea to get some real-life storm
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Junger, who lives in Manhattan, said that most people secretly
desire the wild sense of danger in a big storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous experience,'' he said. ``We live in such a
safe society and people are a little bit thrilled by a situation
where you're not in control. Where all you can do is hunker down
and wait it out. A blizzard in New York is the same thing. As much
as they sort of swear at the inconvenience and mutter, it's also
satisfying to people that that can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
