<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T AND BRITISH TELECOM TO LINK WIRELESS OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications said they would expand their
global communications alliance by linking their wireless telephone
operations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and British Telecom are already trying to create a $10
billion joint venture to serve the international communications
needs of multinational corporations. While the new wireless
alliance would not technically be part of that venture, its
formation underscores the growing importance of wireless as part of
the comprehensive package of services that carriers are trying to
build.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN TO RETURN TO WALL STREET
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rubin, the former Treasury secretary, plans to return to
Wall Street, though he has not decided where he will work. Rubin
said he had been sifting through job offers. He has decided to
spend part of his time in community service as the new chairman of
Local Initiatives Support Corp.
</P>
<P>
   CABLEVISION TO BUY SONY EQUIPMENT
</P>
<P>
   Sony made its first big move into the U.S. cable television
market with the announcement that Cablevision Systems would buy
more than $1 billion worth of Sony equipment to deliver advanced
digital television services in the New York City area.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES TO SHARE AUCTION LISTINGS
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to catch up with Ebay, nearly 100 Internet sites
have agreed to share their auction listings so that an item put up
for sale on one site will be available on all other sites.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P RISES; DOW AND NASDAQ FALL
</P>
<P>
   Stock were mixed with the Dow Jones industrial average dropping
63.96 points, to 10,737.46. The NASDAQ composite index fell 7.45
points, to 2,806.72. The S&AMP;P 500-stock index edged up half a point,
to 1,318.48.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL STRATEGY BEFORE THE GAMES
</P>
<P>
   The studio programs that precede National Football League games
on Sundays are promoting themselves in TV ads that focus on
entertainment, expertise and the interaction between announcers. In
some spots, Fox has transformed its announcers, including Howie
Long, Terry Bradshaw and Chris Collinsworth, into animated
Claymation characters.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD CASE HIGHLIGHTS REGULATORS
</P>
<P>
   The sleuthing in Japan that uncovered the purported fraud of
Martin Armstrong, the chairman of Princeton Economics
International, is likely to help burnish the reputation of Japan's
fledgling financial regulators, who began operations a little more
than a year ago and have struggled under severe financial
constraints.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC Holdings said it was still awaiting a report from Republic
New York, which it is planning to acquire, on its investigation
into dealings with Martin Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   COKE DENIES SHREDDING ALLEGATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for four Coca-Cola employees who have filed a racial
discrimination lawsuit against the company said they had evidence
that company executives shredded documents that might be relevant.
A spokesman for Coke denied that any shredding took place.
</P>
<P>
   FDX SAYS IT MAY NOT MEET FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   FDX, the parent of Federal Express, said that rising fuel prices
hurt its first-quarter earnings and might keep it from meeting this
year's profit forecasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
