<SLUG> BC-GATES-SCHOLARSHIP-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES, `SPREADING THE WEALTH,' MAKES SCHOLARSHIP GIFT OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Making a commitment that the head of the United Negro
College Fund described as ``earth-shattering, landscape-changing,''
Bill Gates and his wife, Melinda, on Thursday formally announced a
$1 billion scholarship program for minority students that will
guarantee recipients full financing for college and advanced
degrees. It is one of the largest philanthropic gifts ever made.
</P>
<P>
   United Negro College Fund president William Gray predicted that
the scholarships, for at least 1,000 students a year over the next
20 years, would ultimately lead to noticeable growth in the numbers
of black, Hispanic and American Indian students who receive
doctorates.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, whose organization will administer the Gates Millennium
Scholarship program with help from the San Francisco-based Hispanic
Scholarship Fund and the Denver-based American Indian College Fund,
said he believed that the scholarships would lead to increases of
15 percent to 40 percent in the numbers of minority students who
receive doctorates in mathematics, the sciences, engineering and
education, the fields covered by the scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he was hailed by minority educators and said in an
interview that he was making ``nothing in the way of a political
statement,'' Gates, co-founder and chairman of Microsoft Corp.,
came under some criticism Thursday from opponents of affirmative
action programs. They did not question his legal right to donate
the money, but faulted him for not opening the program to white
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program will unquestionably do a lot of good, but it
raises a real concern,'' said John Carlson, the host of a local
talk-radio program and leader of a successful campaign last year
for passage of a ballot initiative that effectively ended
state-supported affirmative action programs in Washington state by
banning consideration of race in hiring, contracting and university
admissions. ``Shouldn't this apply to all kids from underprivileged
backgrounds, regardless of their skin color?''
</P>
<P>
   Gates defended the program's focus on minority students, saying
he considered it an obvious national problem that some minority
groups were woefully underrepresented in the high-tech industry and
on so many university campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that private philanthropy can be part of making sure
there is equal opportunity, I think you'd get virtually every
politician to feel like that's a very positive thing,'' Gates said
in an interview at the headquarters of the Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation, which with $17 billion in assets is the largest
philanthropic organization in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can deny that there is a huge gap, particularly in
these key areas, for minority students,'' said Gates, who dropped
out of Harvard University to found Microsoft, ``and the financial
barriers are a substantial element in that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gates and his wife have so far set global health issues and
education as their two top priorities for philanthropic giving,
though Thursday's commitment far surpasses any other gift they have
made. The foundation they have established is headed by Gates'
father, William H. Gates Jr., and by Patty Stonesifer, a former
Microsoft executive and longtime friend of the younger Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft chairman, whose vast holdings of Microsoft stock
make him the wealthiest person in the world, with a net worth of
about $90 billion, said that he was devoting 5 to 10 hours a week
to philanthropic matters and that he did not expect that to change
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I have a job,'' he explained Thursday. ``It doesn't
have any expiration date on it and certainly there's more than
enough challenges in that job.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes amid a national debate over affirmative
action, including the passage of measures banning it in California
and Washington and campaigns for similar laws in Michigan and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the freshman class here at the University of Washington,
officials are projecting that they will have about 40 percent fewer
black students, 30 percent fewer Hispanic students and 20 percent
fewer American Indians than were registered last fall, before the
initiative was approved by voters.
</P>
<P>
   While Gates' company took an official position against the
Washington measure and donated to the unsuccessful campaign to
block its passage, the Microsoft chairman seemed to go out of his
way Thursday to say that his gift was not motivated by the divisive
fight over the measure. ``I would be doing this gift in exactly
this way, independent of that or any other political questions
around the issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates has stoutly rejected calls to characterize himself as a
liberal or a conservative or something else, and true to form, he
also parried a question about his political affiliation. ``I
wouldn't say that I'm either clearly a Democrat or a Republican,''
he said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the Republican Party often does a good job of
looking at what kind of environment you have to have to encourage
wealth creation, and seems to have some good thinking in those
areas, whether it be free trade or whatever,'' he said. ``And the
Democratic Party often seems to be thinking more about once you
have the wealth, how you spread it around, and those are both
things I think are very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people attack the wealth-creation mechanisms, it seems to
push me in one direction,'' Gates said, smiling as he continued to
explain his nonaffiliation, ``and when they don't take spreading
the wealth seriously, well, that pushes me in the other
direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
