<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORT-WORTH-SHOOTING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relatives recall ordeal, shock of church shooting
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Laurie Ayn's voice, never loud, was a little
girl's voice, struggling to be strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, I just wanted you to know we were OK,'' she said.
``Daniel got out, but we don't think one of our friends did.''
Ten-thirty at night, and the network news had just become a very
real intruder in our family's life.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest daughter, 24 years old and a graduate student at
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, was
working in the nursery at Wedgwood Baptist Church when guns started
going off Wednesday night. She made one of the first 911 calls for
help.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Daniel Cox, 28, was standing in the rear of the
church sanctuary with their friend Shawn Brown, 23, when the gunman
began shooting at the two of them. ``He (Brown) died,'' Laurie Ayn
said Thursday morning, talking now in a speedy monotone. ``He and
his wife live right behind us. He's a student. He and Daniel taught
a fifth-grade class (at church). We taught Vacation Bible School
together.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Daniel strolled over to Shawn's side when he entered
the front door of the church. They slipped into the sanctuary
through a rear door and joined a regular Wednesday night song
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were standing in the back of the sanctuary singing when we
heard these loud bangs,'' Daniel said. Apparently that was the
moment when gunman Larry Gene Ashbrook killed two people at the
church's front door, then began moving toward another rear
sanctuary door, firing as he went. ``We looked out into the foyer
and it was really smoky. When we peeked down the hall, he started
shooting at us. It doesn't sound like it does on TV. As we ducked
back through the door, I saw the glass break. It was like in slow
motion.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no movie moment of locked eyes or recognition, just
adrenaline and shock. ``All I saw was a blur,'' he said. ``The door
kind of shielded us for a second. When I peeked around it, there
was just a dark form, shooting . . . at us, at people out in the
foyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Other friends and church members were killed and wounded as the
tragedy played itself out, leaving the young couple among those
wondering what happened and pondering the fact that they survived.
Like other parents in these unimaginable circumstances, I was
washed in guilt-scented relief, even as I tried to draw each of
them out enough for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the nursery and didn't hear anything,'' Laurie Ayn
said. ``I just saw all these people running out and crying and
telling me to call 911. The lady told me to get down on the floor
and I did. That's when Daniel came running in to check on me. He
said, `I'm OK but I'm going back to get the kids.' Then we started
getting our preschoolers out the side door and across the street
where they would be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   After the relief of finding his wife safe, Daniel realized that
his friend Shawn wasn't with him.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, my son-in-law was subdued, almost robotic as he tried
to absorb the reality of his friend's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a guy, you always think, `What would I do in this
situation?' '' Daniel said. ``Would I be able to stop the guy from
hurting people? But your first instinct is to run, and my thought
was, `What if there's somebody else in the part of the church where
Laurie is?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I think maybe there was something I could have done,
thrown a chair or something,'' Daniel said. And even though Shawn
Brown was found some distance away from where he and Daniel first
were shot at, there's the question of whether he could have done
more to help. ``I do wish I'd turned around and picked up Shawn and
gotten him out of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   It took several phone calls to track down Laurie Ayn and Daniel
on Thursday morning. They were in church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to chapel at the seminary to do some crying and
praying and start getting over the shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock. Last night was just numb,'' Laurie Ayn
said. ``I saw stuff during a tornado in college, but never anything
like this, people hurt and bleeding. There was one lady sitting
outside my door who was bleeding from her head. She was either shot
or hit by something when the bomb went off.''
</P>
<P>
   Wedgwood Baptist is an older church that draws its membership
from families in the neighborhood around it and students from the
nearby seminary. The quiet and solitude it once offered stand in
stark contrast to Wednesday night's mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just surreal that you were there,'' she said. ``You were
a part of it. That's you and your friends on television, but it's
not really happening. We all thought church was a safe place,
especially our church.''
</P>
<P>
   But the young couple plan to go back. ``We won't be able to get
back in the church for a while,'' Daniel said. ``But we'll meet
somewhere. That's where we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
