<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-HOYA-TRINIDAD-NYT     09-16 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOYA-TRINIDAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW STRATEGY: MORE BLUSTER BEFORE THE BLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Before his last big fight, against Ike Quartey,
Oscar De La Hoya spent a lot of time thinking about losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were talking about how strong a puncher he was,'' De La
Hoya said of that Feb. 13 fight. ``That got me nervous and made me
hesitant in the fight. But never will that happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, the World Boxing Council welterweight champion, was
knocked down in that fight, but finished with a ferocious flurry in
the 12th round and pulled out a split decision. Afterward he said
he had given Quartey, and many of his previous opponents, too much
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that was based on De La Hoya's not having an
understanding of just how good he really was. And much of that was
because his promoter, Bob Arum, had coddled him by tossing him in
with opponents who weren't his equal in talent and skill. The
tactic, and some deft marketing, made De La Hoya a wealthy boxing
celebrity but had allowed doubts to creep in.
</P>
<P>
   As De La Hoya (31-0), now 26, prepares to take on Felix Trinidad
Jr. (35-0), the International Boxing Federation champion in a major
welterweight showdown at the Mandalay Bay Casino on Saturday night,
he is taking a completely different tack than he did against
Quartey _ at least publicly. He isn't praising Trinidad. He is even
denigrating Trinidad's boxing skills, saying Trinidad can't move
laterally, has poor footwork, fights off-balance and doesn't have
good hand speed.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference on Wednesday, De La Hoya measured
himself against Trinidad and in his own estimation he came out
ahead of the Puerto Rican champion in all categories. He even rated
Quartey ahead of Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a solid fighter, an all-around good fighter,'' De La Hoya
said of Trinidad. ``I told Trinidad that I respect him as a
fighter. He's got all the tools necessary to become a good fighter.
But if you talk about the whole package, the footwork, the speed,
the power and the intelligence in the ring, Ike Quartey was a
stronger fighter, had the upper body movement and was smarter in
the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   But listen to De La Hoya long enough, and contradictions begin
to creep into his conversations about this fight. In one breath he
said he believes that Quartey was his career defining fight. But in
another he said that a victory against Trinidad would be a
monumental achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight is going to have a huge impact in my boxing
career,'' De La Hoya said. ``It's going to put me up there with the
greats.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he is not getting caught up in all the hype, but he
knows that it is an event of great magnitude. He is guaranteed $15
million for the bout, his largest paycheck to date, and Arum has
guaranteed him another $6 million based on other revenue from the
fight. It could be the highest grossing nonheavyweight bout in
history, attracting close to a million viewers on the TVKO pay per
view. De La Hoya gets a share of the revenue from all the
pay-per-view buys above 850,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, De La Hoya said he has let those types of things
interfere with his concentration for the fight. Before he fought
Quartey, he had entered into a partnership as a co-promoter with
Arum. He later dropped out of the arrangement, because it was a
mental strain and was affecting the way he boxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always well trained, always in good shape,'' De La Hoya
said. ``I'd never cheat my fans that way. But it's the mind. The
focus just wasn't there. When you're in the position I'm in and
with all the money that you're making, it's very tough. It's hard
to focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad might have caught De La Hoya's attention by predicting
that he will knock De La Hoya out in the sixth round of the fight.
De La Hoya said there is no personal animosity on his part toward
Trinidad, but De La Hoya certainly won't forget that prediction
when the fight rolls around. De La Hoya punished Julio Cesar Chavez
in their second fight, after he felt Chavez had not given him the
proper credit for beating Chavez in the first fight. Chavez said
that had the fight not been stopped on a cut, he would have beaten
De La Hoya. In the second fight De La Hoya forced Chavez, who was
cut and bleeding inside his mouth, to quit in his corner before the
eighth round.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has tuned out what the public says about
Trinidad's punching power or his boxing ability, De La Hoya is
apparently listening to his trainer Robert Alcazar and Gil Clancy.
They did film studies of Trinidad to help De La Hoya prepare. Then
they took De La Hoya to his training camp at Big Bear, Calif., for
three months to put everything into action. It was the longest
training camp of his career. He usually trains five weeks for a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see Oscar in his best shape ever,'' Alcazar said
when asked why De La Hoya was in camp for so long.
</P>
<P>
   The mantra of Alcazar and Clancy has been that De La Hoya is
faster and stronger than Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster hand speed, foot speed, better punching power, better
combinations, fighting better opponents and Oscar always comes
through in the clutch. He has all that going for him,'' Clancy
said.
</P>
<P>
   After three months of listening to the mantra, De La Hoya has
begun to repeat it, and he must believe it, because he talks about
nothing else in this fight. If it isn't the case, he could be in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For now, De La Hoya isn't worried about that. He is supremely
confident that he will beat Trinidad and the same doubts that
plagued him before he fought Quartey are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really wants this fight badly,'' Clancy said. ``He feels
this will be his crowning achievement as a welterweight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
