<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LESSONS IN THE SCHOOL TEST DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Sept. 17:
</P>
<P>
   There is an encouraging bright spot buried under all the
confusion and recriminations generated by New York City's
comic-opera attempts to end social promotions in the public
schools. It turns out, we are now told, that reading-test scores
for the city's schoolchildren went up sharply this spring instead
of remaining flat as originally reported.
</P>
<P>
   It would be dangerous to attach too much significance to such
comparisons in a year when the standardized tests have been
radically changed. But if these revised numbers mean anything, they
offer heartening proof that something is beginning to go right at
the classroom level in the beleaguered New York City school system.
</P>
<P>
   That does not absolve the school system, or its testing company,
CTB/McGraw-Hill, for the appalling fiascoes that have marred this
first year's attempt to hold back children who failed standardized
tests for promotion in the spring and then failed again in a second
attempt at summer school. True, the city's first mandatory summer
school _ for children who failed tests at the end of the third,
sixth and eighth grades _ was bound to be hectic, given that the
Board of Education rushed into it with little preparation under
political pressure from City Hall. But that is no excuse for
failing to keep accurate attendance records to determine whether
the right children actually showed up, nor does it justify an
apparent failure to communicate well with families about the need
for summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the most disturbing fiasco of all, comes word that a
mistake in scoring the pivotal spring tests led the school system
to order more than 8,600 students to attend summer school who had
actually passed those tests. Of these, some 3,500 were subsequently
held back for failing to show up at summer school or for flunking
the tests there even though they had passed them before. The chief
blame for this sad affair apparently lies with CTB/McGraw-Hill,
which miscalculated when it transformed students' raw scores into
an assessment of where they stood with respect to schoolchildren
nationally. The only positive note is that correcting the error
revealed a system-wide gain on the reading examination of nearly 5
percent compared with the year before.
</P>
<P>
   This page has supported tougher standards and higher
expectations for New York City's children. But the error by
CTB/McGraw-Hill has thrown a Klieg light on what happens when a
system bases momentous decisions on a single, standardized test.
This problem vindicates the Board of Education's recent decision to
move toward multiple criteria that include not only tests but also
grades, student portfolios and the teacher's sense of whether or
not the student has mastered the material.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems require more work to develop and maintain, but they
also minimize the system's vulnerability to statistical errors like
this one _ and protect children from judgments based on a single
bad day at school. But those children and parents also need to be
protected from sloppy management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
