<HEADER>
A5416 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NOTARO-COL-AZR &LR;      09-16 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROW DOWN YOUR HOT DOGS, JOIN GREAT AREA CODE REBELLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURIE NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Shhhh.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't tell anybody, but I just called my mom and got through
using the plain old, seven-digit number.
</P>
<P>
   I think the phone company forgot about me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping so, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I hate this new sys tem. I'm never
sur prised anymore when some face less Arizona Board of This, That
and The Other Thing makes some stupid _ actually, it's the kind of
stupid spelled with two Os, as in ``stoopid'' _ decision that con
cerns the common good of our city, but somehow never bothers to ask
the common good.
</P>
<P>
   You know what I mean, like when someone sneaks downtown one
morning with a bulldozer before the sun comes up to smash and
flatten a historic building so we can park some more cars in front
of the new morgue, despite the fact that dead folks typically
aren't big drivers. Or when someone else wants to build a sports
stadium, saddles you and me with the bill and then still has the
nerve to charge us FOUR WHOLE BUCKS for a hot dog that will turn
your intestines into stone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you hear on the nightly news someone decided to change
your phone number without asking you, only to find you're going to
be charged for it, too. Comes straight out of your pocket. Didn't
think that the state was gonna swallow that horse pill, did you?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. According to the USWest.com Web site, ``Because
the area code modification is the re sult of normal growth in
Arizona, if any costs are incurred for updating systems and
revising printed materi als, they are the responsibility of in
dividual telephone customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? Normal growth? Normal growth of what, a magic
beanstalk? If I ever saw anything in my yard or in my house that
grew as quickly as the size and popula tion of Phoenix, I'd kill
it. Out-and-out strike it dead. The only thing I know for sure
which ``nor mally'' grows that fast is cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But paying for the change is only part of the reason I'm mad,
aside from the fact that we didn't get any free hot dogs in this
transaction, ei ther, which is a testament to the stoopidity of our
elected leadership. The city could do anything it wanted as long as
it gave out free hot dogs. People love free hot dogs. They'll buy a
car from you if you give them a free hot dog. They'll come to the
grand opening of your store if you give them a free hot dog.
They'll forgive sin and vote for you for a free hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   You could change their phone numbers and then charge them for
it, and they wouldn't care. They're too busy smiling, chewing on
free hot dogs and asking for spicy mus tard. But here's my problem:
I don't want three more digits added to my phone number. Neither
does my mother, my sister, or anyone else I know. We can't handle
memorizing any more numbers. I can't do one more. There is no more
room. My RAM is full.
</P>
<P>
   I gave up my block of memory concerning birthdays, anniversaries
and special events to make room for the time it takes different
brands of microwave popcorn to cook. I relin quished my entire high
school expe rience to accommodate more than 2,000 versions of my
user IDs and passwords for eBay, Amazon.com and CDnow. Luckily in
college I drank a lot, so I was able to store other people's e-mail
addresses in that folder because there was an abundance of extra
blackout space. I gladly purged some Bad Boyfriend Flashbacks into
the trash to make way for the four numbers added to my ZIP code,
and I dumped what little retention I had of math in or der to
remember my debit card PIN number and which of the remote controls
go to the VCR, TV and ca ble box.
</P>
<P>
   Now they want me to remember three more numerical figures?
</P>
<P>
   I can't do it. I am dry. My sponge is full. I HAVE NOTHING LEFT
TO GIVE.
</P>
<P>
   Memory is not like hate. It doesn't just multiply! It's like pa
tience. You only get a certain allot ment when you're born, and
every year you watch more and more of it slip away.
</P>
<P>
   In the first place, I don't under stand how we could have just
``run out of numbers.'' To me, that just seems impossible. In fact,
I believe it's a lazy reason. I don't know any one with a 000- or a
666-prefix, do you? Maybe it's because I threw math away, but if
you mix up enough numbers, doesn't that just make _ I don't know _
infinity? Start using the star and the pound sign in prefixes for
all I care. Throw in a flash and a redial, but don't mess with what
I already know and have on file in my head.
</P>
<P>
   With three separate area codes, I sense other crises as well.
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, we're playing a dangerous game. Not only with
in formation overload, but with the very fabric of our community.
</P>
<P>
   Once you start assigning people categories and groups,
competition starts. Rivalries flare up. Elitism slips in and takes
a strong hold.
</P>
<P>
   Area codes and their border streets will become the new Berlin
walls.
</P>
<P>
   On the black market, 480 num bers with tony Scottsdale prefixes
will be selling like they were coo ing, pudgy, blue-eyed babies,
and will become the most prominent and prestigious status symbol
since calf implants and koi ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Families will be torn apart and divided, people will defect into
``The 480'' via hot air balloons and hang gliders launched from
Camel back Mountain, and will easily re nounce their 623 and 602
origins without a hint of hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   I think we'll see it in the singles ads first:
</P>
<P>
   ``You: Slothlike smoker with no general ambition other than
eating and shopping. Looks and hygiene not important, only inner
beauty. Me: Heir to Yoo-hoo and Funyon fortunes, have free samples
for life. Just a generous zillionaire looking for someone to share
my fantastic wealth with. 480s only. No others need apply. Require
proof with phone records.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a city-wide disaster waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   I'm watching, ready to witness this city tear itself apart from
the in side out because of three little num bers, to listen to
chaos and anger reign, to cry as a 623 brother arms himself against
his 602 brother.
</P>
<P>
   To hear the sounds of antipathy and loathing come to life,
echoing through the valleys of this city in a roar too deafening to
drown out, un til someone points to what is falling from the sky
and yells:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, look you guys! Free hot dogs!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send com ments about her
column to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by
e-mail to laurienotaro &LR; usa.net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
