<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON SAYS HE HAS LOST 45 OF 60 EXTRA POUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Having trimmed 45 of the 60 pounds that he gained
during a three-and-a-half month stay in a Maryland jail, Mike Tyson
said today that he was close to being ready for his Oct. 23
heavyweight bout against Orlin Norris at the MGM Grand Casino here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from 280 pounds to 235 pounds,'' Tyson said during a
news conference at the MGM Grand to announce the fight. ``By fight
time, I'll be right. I'm looking forward to it. It's not going to
be a walk in the park. But it's not going to be a walk in the park
for him either.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, 33, last fought on Jan. 16, knocking out Francois Botha
in the fifth round of a bout that Botha had dominated through the
first four rounds. Tyson was sentenced to one year in jail in
Montgomery County, Md., on Feb. 5 on assault charges stemming from
an altercation following a traffic accident on Aug. 31, 1998. He
was released May 24.
</P>
<P>
   He indicated Thursday that his big weight gain was a result of
his inactivity in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever been incarcerated?'' Tyson asked a reporter who
questioned him about the weight gain. ``Go out, hit somebody with a
car, get incarcerated and see how fat you'll get.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, 33, said it had taken him just two months to shed the
bulk of the weight by running five miles a day and sparring 10
rounds a day on the heavy bag. But he still wants to trim down to
221 pounds for the bout against Norris (50-5), a lightly regarded
heavyweight who is the brother of Terry Norris, a former junior
middleweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Orlin Norris, who will turn 34 on Oct. 4, said this was the
defining fight of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fighter looks at a marquee fight they can build upon,''
he said. ``Mike Tyson could be that fight for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who is 46-3, has welcomed Jay Bright, his former trainer,
back to his corner. Bright will be working with Tommy Brooks, who
joined Tyson for the Botha fight.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said he was not surprised that he was sentenced to jail
for the fight that followed the automobile accident. He had pleaded
to the misdemeanor assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politically correct to put me in prison,'' Tyson said.
``If go I go to any state, California or Nevada, if you don't put
me away there's a malfunction in your justice system. ''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said he had planned to fight three to four times this year
to clear up some debts. He owes several million dollars to Showtime
because the cable network paid off delinquent taxes and picked up
the federal tax liens that were placed on his homes in Connecticut
and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no one to blame but myself,'' Tyson said. ``Other
people may have contributed to my problems. But I have to carry the
weight of the fool.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
