<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EASY GLAMOR PERMEATES BLASS' SPRING COLLECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thursday's Bill Blass show was supposedly his swan
song, though he hasn't officially announced the sale of his
business.
</P>
<P>
   So, there was a frisson of excitement tinged with nostalgia
among the faithful waiting in the Bryant Park tent Thursday morning
for what might be his final fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   They had slogged through driving rain (or, in the case of his
``ladies,'' been chauffeur-driven), praying that the show would go
on. It did. So did the Jill Stuart show that followed, but Seventh
on Sixth canceled the rest of the afternoon's shows, rescheduling
them for Saturday, because of fears of what Hurricane Floyd's high
winds might do to the tent.
</P>
<P>
   The Blass spring 2000 show made everyone forget about the
pounding rain on the tent's roof, and the occasional leaks.
</P>
<P>
   From the first number _ a color-banded white dress _ to the last
_ a chiffon turtleneck and short silver skirt _ there was never any
doubt that a master was in control.
</P>
<P>
   Every outfit displayed the unmistakable Blass touch. Call it
perfectionism. Call it a vision of how he likes to see women
dressed.
</P>
<P>
   An easy glamour permeated the collection. Cropped sweaters were
paired with floral-beaded skirts or sequin-paved pants _ a look
Blass might have patented. Jackets were loose, unstructured affairs
with soft hoods. Chiffon and organza dresses burst into colorful
bloom, sometimes trailing asymmetric ruffles.
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-shoulder black lace topped a pale pink ball-gown skirt.
And to round out the picture there was a series of those short
black dresses in chiffon and lace that no Blass customer's closet
would be without.
</P>
<P>
   If Thursday's show indeed turns out to be Blass' last, it will
leave his ladies well taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors is the designer many people expect to inherit the
Blass mantle for dressing the social set. He had a winning show on
Tuesday, but, as might be expected, it was easily a generation
younger in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Kors called it ``sexy, indulgent, American sportswear,'' and it
lived up to the billing.
</P>
<P>
   There were microscopically short skirts, in leather that
mimicked guipure lace or in a muted blue and green floral print.
There were skin-tight jeans cropped above the ankle and worn with
sheer cashmere tops or glove-leather jackets.
</P>
<P>
   There were bikinis and cabana jackets, shown with towels wrapped
around the models' heads, as if they had just emerged from a cool
dip.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the clothes looked as if they were meant for a
summer at the beach. Just about the only city-ready styles were the
cable-stitched sweaters and the yummy glove leathers, particularly
a short-sleeved shirtdress. To make a shirtdress look sensuous
takes talent, and Kors has it in abundance.
</P>
<P>
   He used flattering colors like pink, lime, lemon, tangerine and
aqua, balanced against bold black-and-white zebra patterns and
leavened with a series of skin tones ranging from the palest pinky
beige to cocoa brown.
</P>
<P>
   For evening, there were the slinky beaded dresses he has made a
specialty and some beaded laces that were less original but just as
sexy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After several seasons of showing in Italy, Victor Alfaro brought
his spring collection back to New York. Like Kors, he expects his
customers to spend a lot of time at the beach. He showed swimsuits
that were deeply cut out at the sides and back, paired with snug
leather Capri pants, hip-slung skirts or shorts brief enough to
reveal two crescent moons in back.
</P>
<P>
   Leather punched out to resemble lace has become as common on
spring runways as bare midriffs and denim. And Alfaro had them all.
</P>
<P>
   He also had some lovely embroidered chiffons and lightly
sequined tulles in pale lilac or ivory that had the delicate touch
he has become known for.
</P>
<P>
   So, those thick leather belts with heavy gold rings and the
chain-link thongs were like false notes struck in a Chopin sonata.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Steele is another American in Milan, Italy, who
returned to his roots this season. But his sensibility is
definitely European. No classic American sportswear appears on his
runway. He uses raffia fringe to trim a sweater, cuts the back of a
blouse to shreds, uses zippers for decoration, and bares the sides
of dresses as daringly as he bares the backs.
</P>
<P>
   His collection seesaws from refined tailoring to studded
bondage, from handkerchief-hemmed chiffon to orange and black
paillettes.
</P>
<P>
   Fine strands of chain-link were draped into a halter top worn
with a raffia-feather skirt and an unlined skirt worn with a raffia
halter.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad Steele feels he has to try so hard to be
provocative, to make so many things for the woman with a tough
edge. But fashion can be mighty boring when everyone shows clothes
that are pretty and safe. Fashion, like a good meal, needs a little
spice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-16-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990916.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-WHITE-NYT &LR;      09-16 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WHITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN WHITE, 75, POLITICAL STRATEGIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Md.)   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John F. White Sr., a political strategist and organizer whose
leadership played a vital role in the election of black officials
in Philadelphia, died Sept. 15 at his home in Philadelphia. He was
75.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, White helped found the Black Political Forum, his
principal political arm.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years before the election of W. Wilson Goode as the
first African-American mayor of Philadelphia in 1983, White helped
blacks win election to 10 city offices or seats in the state
Legislature and a seat in the U.S. House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy Williams was the first of this group when he was elected
to the Pennsylvania House in 1970. Williams was followed to the
state Legislature by David Richardson, and then White's son, John
F. White Jr.
</P>
<P>
   William Gray was elected to the U.S. House and became the first
black House member to serve as the Democratic whip.
</P>
<P>
   White used the Black Political Forum to bring local
African-American leaders together, consider ways to maximize their
influence and establish goals and means of achieving them.
</P>
<P>
   In White's last public appearance this week, said David W.
Brown, a longtime friend and a spokesman for the family, ``he was
saying that African-Americans should look beyond race and party
affiliation in making endorsements. They should join their natural
allies, the liberal middle class, which includes both
African-Americans and non-African Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that White's preaching of political independence was
reflected this week when White's son, who finished third in the
Democratic mayoral primary behind John Street, announced that he
was endorsing Street's Republican opponent, Sam Katz.
</P>
<P>
   White retired in the early 1990s from his job as an assistant
managing director of the city of Philadelphia, an appointive post
with responsibilities that included overseeing the City Watch, a
community policing program that White had helped to establish.
</P>
<P>
   John Felix White was born on June 9, 1924, in Berlin, Md. He
received a bachelor's of science degree in 1944 from Bowie State
College.
</P>
<P>
   He received a certificate of Christian education at Cedar Crest
College and for many years served as deacon at Mount Carmel Baptist
Church in West Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   White's first wife, Sylvia Lewis, died in 1990. In addition to
his son, from the first marriage, White is survived by his wife,
Patricia Washington of Philadelphia; a brother, Otha White of
Maryland; four sisters, Anna Waters, Emma Jones, Eliza Brown and
Barbara Corbin, all of the Philadelphia area; nine grandchildren
and one great-grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
