<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-BUYERS-NYT &LR;      09-16 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BUYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRICE FOR EVERYTHING, EVEN TESTAVERDE'S HEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Vinny Testaverde collapsed to the Giants Stadium turf with
a season-ending torn Achilles' tendon last Sunday, did the New York
Jets' potential sale price plunge?
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets were a publicly traded stock, Testaverde's injury
would have sent shares reeling, just as if a company's earnings had
come in below projections or the sales of a ballyhooed product had
gone into the tank.
</P>
<P>
   Potential buyers seeking to acquire the Jets started to assemble
last month with the expectation that the team might play in the
Super Bowl. Such anticipation had to figure into the price one of
the suitors would pay. Now, with Testaverde out and Rick Mirer in,
the anticipation is considerably muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are emotional buys and factors like that can't be ruled
out,'' John Moag, the managing director of the sports industry
group at the investment banking firm Legg Mason, said of the impact
of Testaverde's injury. ``How a team is playing has a psychological
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Jets now worth $10 million less than they were before 2
p.m. last Sunday? Or did the value drop by $25 million? Or $50
million?
</P>
<P>
   Will the loss of each game lop $5 million from the price? Will
each of Rick Mirer's interceptions cause a $750,000 drop? Will
Wayne Chrebet's return from injury be worth $2.5 million more? Will
each first down be worth $10,000?
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 26 suitors who have signed confidentiality
agreements to examine the Hess estate's sale prospectus know,
however, that winning isn't the only consideration. The Washington
Redskins' 6-10 record last year did not scare Daniel Snyder away
from from buying them for $800 million, a price largely determined
by the cash horde coming from the team's two-year-old stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the Testaverde situation affecting the value, but
you can say for sure that if the Jets are out of the playoffs early
_ say they're 1-7 or 2-6 _ it takes some glamour off the team,''
said Michael Ozanian of Forbes magazine, which values the Jets at
$363 million in its current issue, slightly more than half the
Dallas Cowboys' value of $663 million.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ganis, the president of Sportscorp Ltd., a Chicago
consulting firm, added: ``Being without Testaverde shouldn't make a
difference. We're not talking about Peyton Manning or Tim Couch,
quarterbacks in their early 20's, but a guy who's in his 30s and at
the tail end of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern for the value of the Jets, said Ganis and
Ozanian, is the coaching future of Bill Parcells. If he leaves
after a disappointing 1999 season, it would be like Lee Iacocca
leaving Chrysler in the 1980s before the company's recovery was
completed. ``I see Parcells staying on as coach as being worth $10
million or $20 million,'' Ganis said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets sell for $500 million or more, it will be because of
the hope of getting a new stadium when the team's Giants Stadium
lease expires in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Jets' suitors are Cablevision's Charles Dolan; New
Jersey Devils owner John McMullen; builders Sam Grossman and Samuel
LeFrak; cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder; New York Mets co-owner Fred
Wilpon, and the tandem of developer Steve Ross and
developer/financier Bill Mack. For whomever wins the bidding, the
biggest challenge might be negotiating an expensive and difficult
buyout with the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority to get a
new stadium and sweetheart lease in place by 2003 or 2004.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets and the Devils planning arenas away from the
Meadowlands, the authority wouldn't want to make it easy for
another team to leave, especially one that had never squawked about
its lease when Leon Hess was alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
