<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-NYT &LR;      09-16 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS CARRY A QUIET SWAGGER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the road, the most popular player on the team
spends Sunday mornings in search of a Roman Catholic church. The
dazzling second baseman is a better shortstop and is named Pokey.
The bullpen is unknown and unbelievable. The manager is 68 years
old and the general manager is 38. The team plays games in a park
that is almost always half empty in a city that is ignoring a
frenetic pennant chase.
</P>
<P>
   The team is the Cincinnati Reds, who might be more of a threat
to the Mets' postseason aspirations than the Atlanta Braves are.
While the Mets have been pursuing the Braves in the National League
East and are one game out of first place, the Reds have been
futilely chasing the Houston Astros in the NL Central and have kept
a wary eye on the Mets in the wild-card tussle.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon, the relaxed manager who can secure senior citizen
discounts, tells the Reds there is no pressure on them because they
were not even supposed to be in contention. McKeon was in his
office at Cinergy Field by 10:30 a.m. for Thursday night's game
against the Chicago Cubs and had the television on, a newspaper in
his hands and a cigar dangling from his mouth. He sounded calm and
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a gut feeling that we're either going to win our
division or we're going to beat out the Mets for the wild card,''
McKeon said. ``It's a gut feeling. I've had that feeling for the
last month.''
</P>
<P>
   When McKeon was asked what made him feel so strongly about the
Reds' being able to overtake the Astros or the Mets, he did not
cite favorable schedules or glaring statistics. The manager simply
said he has a feeling. He said it would be unfair for the Braves,
Astros, Mets or Reds to insist they were better than the other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   But McKeon, whose team trails Houston by 3 1-2 games and the
Mets by three games repeated his strong sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is going to be tough, but we play them twice at the
end of the month, so we could sneak by them,'' McKeon said. ``If
that doesn't happen, I think Atlanta will take care of the Mets and
we'll slip by them and get the wild card. That's how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds won 11 of 13 games before Thursday night's loss to the
Cubs, but in that time they lost a half game in the standings to
Houston because the Astros won 12 of 13 in the same period.
Houston's blitz is one reason the Reds see the Mets as the team
they might be closing in on soon. The Mets have to play the Braves
six more times, while the Reds have only two more games with teams
over the .500 mark, against Houston on Sept. 28-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're going to make the playoffs,'' said Sean Casey,
the player who finds a church almost every Sunday. ``It's a special
team. We feel like we're going to win every night.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate that the city of Cincinnati has not really
embraced the Reds, a $33 million creation of Jim Bowden, the young
general manager, and a team that has been patiently nurtured by
McKeon. The Reds are averaging 24,146 fans a game, which is 11th in
the league, and Casey lamented how thousands have bolted from
Cinergy on nights when Cincinnati later rallied to win.
</P>
<P>
   When Sammy Sosa batted with a runner on first and the Reds
leading, 5-3, in the ninth inning on Wednesday, fans chanted
``Sam-my, Sam-my'' in anticipation of his 60th homer, a milestone
never before achieved in two seasons. Danny Graves, who surrendered
a run-scoring single to Sosa before saving a 5-4 victory, was
incensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to win a pennant race, not get Sammy Sosa in the
record book,'' Graves told The Cincinnati Post. ``Who are they
rooting for, Sammy or us?''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds should be easy to root for because they are underdogs
and they have exciting young players. Casey is hitting .338 and has
one of the sweetest swings in baseball. Pokey Reese, who McKeon
says could win a Gold Glove at three infield positions, will
eventually replace 10-time All-Star Barry Larkin at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Boone was demoted to Triple-A Indianapolis in May, but the
third baseman has rebounded with 14 homers and 70 runs batted in
while hitting .293. Mike Cameron has given the Reds the sort of
defense in center field that they have lacked for several years.
Scott Williamson, a rookie who is 11-6 with 18 saves and a 1.87
earned run average, combines with Graves (8-6, 24 saves, 3.03 ERA)
to spearhead a bullpen that leads the majors with 31 victories and
a 3.24 ERA and has 49 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden acquired Greg Vaughn for Reggie Sanders from San Diego
before the season, and Vaughn, a left fielder, is close to becoming
the first Reds player to slug 40 homers since George Foster in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Reds needed another starter to complement
Pete Harnisch (14-9) and Steve Parris (9-2), so Bowden gambled in
obtaining Juan Guzman from the Baltimore Orioles. Guzman, 35, has
revived his career while going 6-2. Larkin is no longer the only
Red worth watching as Guzman is another integral piece to this
surprising team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting because no one expected us to do anything,''
Casey said. ``We believe in ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
