<SLUG> BC-SOC-NORTHCAROLINA-220&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP SUCCESS LIFTS UNIVERSITY OF NORTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the University of North Carolina is any barometer, as it has
always been, women's soccer at the college level is starting to
feel the benefits of the triumph by the U.S, national team in the
Women's World Cup this past summer. While the women's game has
become more competitive in recent years with Notre Dame and Florida
winning national titles and ending the dynasty at North Carolina,
attendance at women's games so far this season has shown a huge
increase.
</P>
<P>
   As the dominant team with 15 national titles, North Carolina's
average attendance of 3,046 last year was the largest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of this size used to be reserved for games of paramount
importance or for heated rivalries. But in the Tar Heels' first
game of the season at home Sept. 1 against Tennessee, a rather weak
team with no soccer history, the size of the crowd surprised even
Anson Dorrance, the North Carolina coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe my eyes,'' Dorrance said from his office in
Chapel Hill, N.C., about the crowd of 4,655 for a midweek match to
watch the Tar Heels' easy 3-0 victory over the Lady Vols. ``I was
skeptical about the overflow of the World Cup. I was wondering if
the World Cup would have an impact. Maybe I underestimated the
impact the World Cup would have on the women's game in just about
every level.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American success in the Women's World Cup has given
additional incentives for colleges and universities to pour money
into women's programs.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking balance in collegiate sports programs, it appears that
women's soccer may benefit the most in the battle for gender
equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some schools are dying to find the Title IX equivalent to
football and they have found it with women's soccer,'' Dorrance
said. ``The thing we have to do is become a revenue-producing sport
to have a real impact on NCAA decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's soccer programs found out the hard way in August how much
emphasis the National Collegiate Athletic Association puts on
revenues, and expenses for its major tournament. The NCAA reversed
an earlier decision to increase the number of teams for the men's
Division I tournament from 32 to to 48, and stuck with 32. The
reason was strictly financial, said Tom Jacobs, the NCAA
administrator in charge of men's soccer. The size of the women's
tournament, however, has been increased to 48 teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to most of us,'' coach Jerry Yeagley of Indiana
University, the defending champion, said of the NCAA's refusal to
expand the tournament to match the size of the women's event. ``We
thought the decision had been made to go to 48. We thought it was a
rubber-stamping thing, but it stonewalled.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's programs have been given priority over the men for the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of Division I men's programs has remained about
the same for almost a decade, the number of women's programs in
Division I has increased steadily. There will be about 260, while
the men have fluctuated between 190 and 200 for most of the past
decade, with 196 expected for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's victory in the national title game last year after
only four seasons with a women's program has encouraged schools
such as Texas, Penn State, Notre Dame and Nebraska, to name a few,
to invest in women's soccer. Texas lured away Notre Dame coach
Chris Petrucelli this season.
</P>
<P>
   Petrucelli enjoyed support at Notre Dame, which hired Randy
Waldrum of Baylor to replace him, but Texas apparently made a
lucrative offer. Petrucelli said it was also difficult to look away
from Texas' commitment to invest $28 million in a soccer facility.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the pretty picture is that coaches in women's
programs are now under pressure to produce on the field after their
schools committed more resources to the programs. As a result,
there has been a large turnover in jobs, with almost one in five
schools with Division I women's programs changing coaches for this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Petrucelli views Santa Clara, Portland, Notre Dame and Penn
State as the toughest challengers to North Carolina and Florida for
the national title this season. ``They're a lot of teams on the
verge of becoming really good and I look for a lot of upsets this
season,'' Petrucelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State registered perhaps the biggest upset thus far,
shocking North Carolina last Sunday with a 3-2 triumph, which came
only two days after the Lady Lions had lost to Duke in the
Nike/Carolina Classic at Chapel Hill, before a crowd of 4,213.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four of the 48 teams will receive automatic bids for the
women's tournament, which will end the first weekend in December at
San Diego State with the newly named Women's College Cup. Clemson,
Nebraska, Duke, Wisconsin, Texas A&AMP;M and Hartford could also
challenge for the title. It may take more than a year or two for
Petrucelli to lift Texas into contention.
</P>
<P>
   The men's tournament will award automatic bids to 16 of the 32
teams, and the champion will be crowned a week after the women in
Charlotte, N.C. The NCAA has upgraded the men's Final Four by
moving the event to Charlotte, after four years in Richmond, where
the facility is half the size of Ericsson Stadium, the home of the
Carolina Panthers of the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana is the favorite to repeat, the way it did in 1982-83.
The Hoosiers have lost one key player from last year's team, Dema
Kovalenko, now in Major League Soccer with the Chicago Fire. Their
strongest challenge is expected to come from UCLA and Maryland, two
schools with several youth national team players on their rosters.
Creighton, Clemson, St. Louis, Stanford, Santa Clara, Virginia, St.
John's, Connecticut, Duke, California State-Fullerton and
Washington could also contend for the Men's College Cup. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
