u a BC-GATES-GIFT-SPI &LR;      09-16 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-GIFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1 BILLION GOES TO MINORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT and KRISTIN DIZON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Rick Williams remembers how his grandmother would save
buffalo nickels from the $50 a month his family lived on. They were
for his college education, she would say.
</P>
<P>
   That was long before Williams, a member of the Oglala Sioux
Tribe in Nebraska, became the executive director of the American
Indian College Fund _ a fund that doubled in size Thursday when the
Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation announced a $1 billion
scholarship program to help high-achieving minority students
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting Bull once said, `Let us put our minds together and see
what kind of future we can bring for our children,''' Williams said
at Thursday's press conference to announce the Gates Millennium
Scholarship program. ``That's what we're doing here today.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion scholarship, to be administered by the United
Negro College Fund, in collaboration with the American Indian
College Fund and Hispanic Scholarship Fund, creates a reservoir of
money on a scale the organizations have never seen.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic Scholarship Fund will be able to award at least
twice the number of scholarships it awarded this year, and the
United Negro College Fund's revenues for the year jumped by nearly
one-third.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a historic day, this is a wonderful moment,''
said William H. Gray, III, president of the UNCF.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many young people don't get an opportunity in the minority
community to reach their potential and to go to college because of
the barrier of finance,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Gates Millennium Scholars Program'' will provide $50
million a year for 20 years primarily to black, Hispanic and
American Indian students, although the program will be open to
other minority students as well. The first scholarships will be
awarded in the fall of 2000, based primarily on academic
achievement and financial need.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship is designed to support what will be about 20,000
minority students as they move through their undergraduate degrees
and onto graduate schools in math, science, engineering, education
or library science.
</P>
<P>
   The number of minorities who earn doctoral degrees in these
fields is extremely low. In 1996, only one Native American earned a
Ph.D. in mathematics, according to the National Center for
Education Statistics. Only 1 percent of all engineering doctorates
went to blacks that year and Hispanics earned 3 percent of
education Ph.D.s.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking about a program that will double and triple
those numbers over the next two decades, and that means changing
the landscape of American education, but also the landscape of
America itself,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarships will provide financial assistance to about
1,000 new students a year, with an annual investment of $50
million. In any given year, a total of 4,000 students could be
working their way toward a degree as Millennium Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for assistance, students must have a 3.3 high school
grade-point average, be nominated by a teacher or the school's
principal and must also write an essay. Awards will be renewed
annually and participants will be expected to maintain a cumulative
G.P.A. of 3.0 or better.
</P>
<P>
   The grants _ which cover tuition, room and board and expenses _
will be large enough so that students will not have to work or take
out loans. The idea is to give minority students from impoverished
backgrounds the chance to go onto college without the burdens of
debt or work commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest thing you can do is provide somebody with a
wonderful education,'' Gates said Thursday. ``And we'd like to do
that in a way that they can really focus on their studies, that
they don't have to be having too many jobs on the side or be
thinking about the size of the loans that they're building up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a word was uttered by Foundation co-chair Patty
Stonesifer, the audience of politicians, educators and foundation
employees at Thursday's press conference gave a standing ovation to
the Gateses. The announcement was made at the new headquarters of
the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, a crisp, modern two story
building east side of Lake Union, just north of downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the program spread, even President Clinton took time
out to recognize the substantial initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud the foundation for its leadership and foresight,''
Clinton said in a statement. ``These landmark scholarships will
help address important needs.''
</P>
<P>
   During the press conference, Bill Gates called the close of the
millennium a period of ``breathtaking'' advances in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we look inside that picture and say, `is everybody
getting a chance to benefit from this,' the answer's really no,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling her own upbringing and the couple's approach in
raising their own two young children, Melinda Gates spoke of
helping youngsters to see opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet when we look out today, there are many students,
including many minority students, who don't have that horizon,''
she said. ``Their parents aren't telling them, `You can go to
college. You can go to any college you can get into.' Because their
parents literally can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Education is primary focus of the philanthropic Gates
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Gates dropped out of Harvard to found Microsoft with high-school
friend Paul Allen, a move that ultimately made him the world's
richest man. Microsoft is the world's largest producer of computer
software, and has helped Gates reach a net worth of more than $90
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Gates is a graduate and trustee of Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   The Gateses' enormous gift comes less than a year after
Washington voters approved Initiative 200, banning
government-backed affirmative action programs and removing race
from university admissions decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the press conference were quick to say that
these scholarships have nothing to do with college admissions, but
give financial support to qualified high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke, however, said the Gateses gift can help fill
the vacuum of opportunity in the wake of I-200's ban on affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advocates of Initiative 200 said government can't do it;
they never said that the private sector can't do it,'' said Locke,
the nation's first Chinese American governor and the son of
working-class immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Gates Jr., the Microsoft chairman's father and a
co-chair of the Gates Foundation, said that I-200 had little effect
on the shape of the scholarship initiative, which had been in the
works for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Gates Millennium Scholarship Program sends an
encouraging message to potential minority students, ``it's a real
plus,'' said Gates, who is also a UW Regent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Thursday's enthusiasm for the Gateses' benevolence,
however, some in the minority community believe that the chairman
of Microsoft is in a position to do much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that he gave the money, and I'm glad that it's
earmarked for minority education,'' said Robert Jackson, a Quinalt
Indian who served on an advisory committee on minority issues at
the University of California Riverside. ``But I would also like to
see training programs and taxation of the software industry to
benefit minorities as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
