<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-COUNSEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNSELORS, PSYCHOLOGISTS OFFER STUDENTS HOPE, ASSURANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY DOCLAR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Some drew pictures and wrote cards. Others
cried and needed comfort. Most simply wanted to vent about the
brutal crime that had shaken their world.
</P>
<P>
   For counselors, psychologists and other mental health
professionals who fanned out across Fort Worth on Thursday to
encounter those emotions and help those touched by Wednesday's mass
shooting at Wedgwood Baptist Church, the mission was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are frightened,'' said Ann Baker, a psychologist
with the Fort Worth school district. ``For many of them, this is
their first encounter with death, and it's very sobering for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agencies offered psychological services, including the Fort
Worth and White Settlement school districts and a nonprofit
alternative school where one
</P>
<P>
   shooting victim attended classes. Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary, where several victims were current or former
students, also provided services.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth schools used campus counselors and 25 school
psychologists to help students cope with their grief, said Dr.
Michael Dixon, director of psychological services. Several other
school districts, including Birdville and Northwest, also offered
their help, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real concern kids were expressing was that this happened
in a sanctuary,'' Dixon said. ``This was such a violation of their
sense of propriety. This is a sacred place.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who provided counseling at the church Wednesday night and
went to three schools near the church Thursday, said she tried to
comfort children without promising them that such a tragedy would
never happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to get them to recognize that these things happen;
people get hurt and the way you get through it is by holding hands
with others,'' she said. `` ``You try not to say to them it's never
going to happen because it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the elementary children drew pictures as a means of
coping and middle-school students wrote letters, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Deryl Logan, another Fort Worth school district psychologist,
said the most difficult question was the one he couldn't answer:
Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a good number of students that are still in
the shock phase,'' he said. ``A lot of them, it's already hit them
emotionally and they're very upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is asking `Why, why, why?' and there's never a good
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the students he met with didn't witness the shooting,
some voiced fears about future violence, Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them were just apprehensive,'' he said. ``One student
that I talked with even asked me, `Why's the police here? Is
something going to happen?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Both psychologists said that students didn't show any signs of
callousness to such violence despite mass shootings becoming more
frequent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find very few kids who don't have normal human sensitivities
to these situations,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   At Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary, counseling was
offered to seminary students and others affected by the shooting. A
dozen counselors were sent to public and private schools to offer
assistance, said Dr. Ian Jones, director of the seminary's
counseling center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show how God's healing hands can work to help in
the midst of pain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cassata High School, a nonprofit alternative school that serves
about 200 students, called in eight outside counselors to help
their two counselors meet with students grieving over slain
classmate Justin Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we couldn't deal with it alone,'' said Cassata
counselor Brandon Pope. &QL; 
Staff writers Jim Jones and Martha Deller contributed to this
report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
